<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     11-17 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIKE Hampton might have lost the Cy Young Award, but he's about to
win the lottery. Hampy's blue mood soon will fade to green.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros couldn't afford to keep Randy Johnson last autumn,
and so the Big Unit did a Horace Greeley and headed west, where,
yes, he claimed the Cy Young for Arizona that Hampton tried to get
as an Astro. No regrets there, though, even if Johnson's continued
presence in the Astros' rotation would have given the locals the
best starting foursome in baseball, Atlanta or no Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But could said fact have guaranteed the Astros a World Series
berth? Not the way they hit, or didn't, in the postseason. Johnson
wouldn't have bolstered their cause against the Braves any more
than he did the Diamondbacks in their ill-fated series against the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   For the Astros, Johnson's price tag _ $13.1 million average for
1999-02 _ was cost-prohibitive, no matter how amazingly durable his
straw-shaped 36-year-old body proved to be, hardly a given going in
considering his history of back problems.
</P>
<P>
   And the Astros managed smashingly without him, in no small part
because of Hampton's 22 victories against only four defeats.
Johnson might have been the National League's most overpowering
lefthander, but Hampy was easily its most effective in terms of
tangible results.
</P>
<P>
   And cost-effectiveness, too. Cripes, the Astros lost only five
of the 34 games he started.
</P>
<P>
   Now reality bites. Although Hampton is under contract through
the 2000 season thanks to a three-year, $12 million deal he signed
in early 1998, the Astros have little choice except to award him a
bountiful extension before spring training. It was about this time
last fall when they did the same for Shane Reynolds, who received
three additional years and lots of additional clams.
</P>
<P>
   Precedent has thus been set in concrete, even though Reynolds
delivered something of a down year after receiving his relatively
modest windfall. It's not an if for Hampton, rather a how long and
a how much.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the former, he figures to be offered the same extra
three years, locking him up through 2003, when he'll be 31, barely
entering his pitcher's prime. As for the latter, well, general
manager Gerry Hunsicker had been sighing about that mystery number
since last spring, before Hampy's near-Cy season. He was aware of
the pitcher's upside potential and was ``worried'' it would be
realized too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it has come to in baseball, with its silly-money
economics. If your responsibilities include the fiscal ones, as do
Hunsicker's, you find yourself in the bizarre position of almost
rooting against your players having exceptional seasons because of
the extreme financial consequences thereof.
</P>
<P>
   In the NL's Cy Young voting, Hampton wound up between Johnson
and Kevin Brown, whose $15 million average salary is the sport's
ultimate excess for the moment, until Ken Griffey Jr. negotiates a
Third World nation GDP-sized deal with his new team.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Brown and Johnson have walked the walk longer than
Hampton, who has just five full seasons behind him. To suggest he
receive something in the range of $13 million to $15 million as
well would be ludicrous. But does $8 million to $10 million per for
the next four seasons seem grossly out of line? No, sir.
</P>
<P>
   Should Hampy deliver a 2000 comparable to his formidable '99,
he'll be worth at least that on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' payroll has risen from $33.6 million in 1995 to
$56.4 million last summer, a 68-percent increase. Yet the latter
figure remains a veritable bargain _ the bloated Rangers bowed out
of the playoffs just as quickly for $80.8 million _ and can be
justified with the significant new revenues Enron Park will
generate.
</P>
<P>
   But at the current pace of inflation, the Enron factor will run
out of gas, so to speak, long before the Astros' 30-year lease
expires. The $92 million the Yankees spent for their World Series
championship in '99 might surpass what the Astros will ever be able
to budget if Drayton McLane Jr. intends to remotely break even on
what remains his worst business decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' most recent payroll was still $2 million less than
what the Yankees forked over in '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tough part,'' Hunsicker has said, ``is knowing you can
never catch up. Somebody out there will always be raising the bar,
spending more than it's possible for you to consider spending.''
</P>
<P>
   And while dollars dispensed with don't necessarily equate to W's
accumulated _ note the Dodgers ($76.6 million) and the Orioles
($75.4 million) _ the record shows only the fattest of cats have
finished on top each season since Minnesota's seven-game triumph
over the Braves in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Hampy, congratulations. Despite Monday's disappointment,
there will be a hefty pot of gold at the end of your rainbow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
