<HEADER>
A2172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC--BLISS-HNS &LR;      11-17 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC--BLISS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ Dave Bliss could have stayed in the comfort zone at New
Mexico, continuing to coach a winning basketball program in front
of sold-out crowds, then retiring a few years down the road.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sounds like the way to go, doesn't it? A successful man in a
high-profile position who was offered a six-year contract at age 56
to keep doing what he was doing. What corporate executive wouldn't
jump to reach for a pen and put the ink to that deal?
</P>
<P>
   Most of us would take the smooth road and coast home to our
golden years, but Bliss chose a different path. He left the cushy
job to come to Baylor and take over a team that was winless in
conference play last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what people say,'' Bliss said. ``They ask me, `Why
would you try this type of a challenge this late in your career?'''
</P>
<P>
   For Bliss, the answer to that question is a simple one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a coach,'' Bliss said. ``If you really love coaching, this
is coaching. You're not dealing with a pat hand. You're working
uphill and exploring new avenues. It's a tremendous challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, coaching is an adventure. We had 11 wonderful years at
New Mexico, but there comes a time in everyone's life when you want
to do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   When Baylor opens the regular season Saturday against Eastern
Washington, Bliss will walk onto the court at the Ferrell Center as
the most recognizable coaching hire in school history. Former
football coach Grant Teaff left Baylor as a big name, but he
arrived in obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   So expectations are high for a man who takes over a basketball
team that is about as low as it can get after the Bears lost their
final 17 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor fans are desperate for a sign of hope. With the football
team experiencing one of its worst seasons in history, Bliss is
seen as the one person who can bring something positive to the
revenue-generating sports. But he knows he has a daunting task
ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt football has struggled, and we probably will
struggle for many of the same reasons. I know people don't want to
hear that, but we probably were worse off than the football team.
We have our work cut out for us, and we have a tough climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is true about any bankrupt company, which we are. We have
to regain self-esteem, but know that it comes without a pity party.
It only comes through hard work. That lesson will help these
players far after their basketball days are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss has been teaching that lesson for 25 years. His head
coaching career started at Oklahoma, where he was the Big Eight
Coach of the Year in 1976 and 1978. His first NCAA Tournament bid
as a coach came at OU in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my first year at OU we weren't doing very well,''
Bliss said. ``I was really down, and I thought I would be out of
there the next year and out of coaching, but I guess we're
survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss moved on to SMU to take on a major rebuilding task. He led
the Mustangs to a Southwest Conference title, three NCAA
appearances and one NIT bid in eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``SMU was down,'' Bliss said. ``But we took it further down
before we got it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss moved on to New Mexico and guided the Lobos to seven NCAA
Tournament appearances in 11 seasons, but his record the last four
years really tells the story. New Mexico won at least 24 games and
reached the second round of the NCAAs in each of those seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave is his own person with his own style,'' said New Mexico
athletic director Rudy Davalos. ``But you can't fault him on
anything he did here.''
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up, and Bliss' teams have made 11 NCAA Tournament
appearances in his 24 seasons as a head coach. If you ask him to
name one person who is most responsible for his coaching success,
Bliss doesn't hesitate. That man is Indiana coach Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss started his coaching career as an assistant under Knight
at Army in 1967. He coached under Knight for four seasons at
Indiana before taking the head coaching job at OU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave is a very bright guy,'' Knight said. ``But what sets him
apart is his ability to see things differently. He understands that
different players have different needs. He is able to evaluate
people quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss said he has never heard Knight say those things about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, all I heard usually was him yelling at me,'' Bliss said.
``I'm kidding, but really he's like an older brother to me. I
talked to him on the phone last week, and he asked me how we were
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is I wouldn't be in coaching and I wouldn't be a lot
of things if it hadn't been for Bob Knight. Because of him, I've
been able to make a life out of a game. Outside of my parents, he
probably has had more to do with helping me than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Personality-wise, Bliss and Knight are quite different. Bliss
doesn't throw chairs, doesn't have a fiery disdain for the media
and doesn't have the cantankerous demeanor of his mentor. But Bliss
said he does have some fundamental beliefs that came from Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us who have worked under him learned a respect for
certain things,'' Bliss said. ``You learn about things important in
all walks of life, like hard work, organization and priorities. And
in basketball you learn about shot selection, not beating yourself,
maximum effort and preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss is trying to teach those things to a Baylor team that shot
only 35.8 percent and averaged 17 turnovers in Big 12 play last
season. But the players feel Bliss can put them on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a special chemistry that coach Bliss has brought to
the team,'' said guard Tevis Stukes. ``Everyone can see it, so
we're all accepting our roles in his system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Bliss is a winner,'' said guard DeMarcus Minor. ``He's
won everywhere he's been. Shoot, if you can win at SMU, you can win
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss has not had a losing season since 1982 at SMU. It would
take a miraculous turnaround to avoid a losing season this year at
Baylor with a team that was 6-24 last year and has only nine
scholarship players. It could be a tough transition, but Bliss is
optimistic about the future of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big 12 is a terrific conference,'' Bliss said. ``Granted,
we're at the bottom right now, but Texas is a can-do place. The
spirit of this state is a philosophy that all things are possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has good players. Last year at New Mexico, four of our
five starters were from Texas and seven of our 12 players were
Texans. When I was at Oklahoma, Barry Switzer taught me to go to
Texas for players, and I never forgot it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss had a chance to return to Texas in the spring of 1998 when
he talked to Texas A&AMP;M officials about the Aggies' job, but he
opted to stay at New Mexico when forward Kenny Thomas told Bliss he
would return for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss was tendered a new six-year deal at New Mexico before the
start of last season, but he never signed the contract. He had
decided he was ready for a new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a Baptist, I thought that I might end my career coaching
at a small church school,'' Bliss said. ``I just happened to pick
the largest Baptist university in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
