<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN DOES A MISTAKE MUTATE INTO A GAFFE?
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has now joined a long list of
politicians who must cope with nagging bloopers. Asked recently by
a television journalist to name the leaders of Taiwan, Chechnya,
India and Pakistan, Bush managed only one.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two weeks after that embarrassing exchange, Bush finds
questions about his foreign policy expertise lingering on as fodder
for Letterman and Leno. In his latest explanation, Bush told Matt
Lauer on NBC's ``Today'' show on Tuesday that he should have
handled the picky questions the way Bill Bradley, the Democratic
presidential candidate, did. That is, he should have responded that
he was ``not going to play pop quizzes'' and talked instead about
``how I intend to keep the peace.'' He used these phrases twice,
almost word for word, in the same interview, showing that he now
has a well-rehearsed answer to a question that he will hear from
time to time for the rest of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that most Americans would not do well naming
foreign leaders, the flunking of his mini-exam plays into the
concern that as a governor, Bush is under-informed about global
issues. ``A blooper sticks around if it reinforces a pretty solid
perception,'' said Robert Neuman, a Democratic media consultant.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be fair, but it is a hazard faced by most
first-time presidential candidates. Some of them discover,
painfully, that for all the long hours and hard work on any
campaign, a wounding gaffe can take place in a few unguarded
seconds. Fans and supporters often quickly forgive their
candidate's human failings. But for the media and the distant
public, an important _ or merely memorable _ mistake dangles from a
candidate's image like a noisy tin can, adding its dissonant clank
no matter what political music is being orchestrated.
</P>
<P>
   Take the word ``potato,'' which has trailed former Vice
President Dan Quayle ever since he corrected a New Jersey student
in 1992 by adding an ``e'' at the end. Nothing short of a Nobel
Prize or a membership in Mensa would have erased that scarlet ``e''
from Quayle's record. The reason was that the public already had a
faint suspicion that the Indiana Republican was light in the
substance area. Similarly, the worry that the 1996 Republican
presidential nominee Bob Dole was too old at 73 expanded full-blown
into public debate when Dole mentioned the Brooklyn Dodgers, 39
years after the team had moved to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Some gaffes last because they confirm our worst suspicions.
Others linger because they suggest something totally unsuspected.
When Jimmy Carter, a born-again Christian, admitted in Playboy
magazine in 1976 that he had ``committed adultery in my heart many
times,'' the verbal picture occupied cartoonists and gag writers
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Visual blunders can also be durable, especially when they come
at a photo opportunity arranged by the campaign. The Democratic
candidate Michael Dukakis went into the gaffers' hall of fame in
1988 when he donned a helmet and rode in an Army tank to boost his
image with the military. Unfortunately, the effect was less George
Patton than George Will.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, the slips are verbal. In its latest issue,
George magazine has come up with its top 10 doozies, including one
from Thomas Dewey's whistle-stop tour in 1948. His train suddenly
started moving before the New York Republican, standing on the rear
platform, had finished his speech. Dewey could be heard shouting:
``What's the matter with that lunatic engineer? The man should be
shot at sunrise.'' Unfortunately, the candidate was speaking to an
audience of railroad workers. Similarly, in 1964 the Republican
nominee, Barry Goldwater, said at one point during his campaign
that ``This country would be better off if we could saw off the
Eastern Seaboard and let it float out to sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Some mistakes, like Gerald Ford's 1976 declaration that ``there
is no Soviet domination of Eastern Europe,'' land heavily on a
campaign. But some candidates get lucky. Sen. John McCain of
Arizona cracked a very tasteless joke recently about Chelsea
Clinton that might have blighted his reputation with women. But
McCain's contrarian image seems to be working, for the moment at
least, as a protective shield. Others carefully offend the right
audiences. When Richard Nixon's running mate Spiro Agnew said, ``if
you've seen one city slum, you've seen them all,'' he horrified
voters around the country. Most, however, were Democrats who were
never going to vote for him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Even political pros are not always sure what makes a mistake
into a gaffe that never goes away. The half-life of a blooper
``depends on how many people are out there to getcha,'' says Jody
Powell, who was Carter's press secretary. Ronald Reagan's former
political adviser Lyn Nofziger adds that it also depends on how
long it takes to admit you got it wrong. ``President Reagan made
some awful bloopers, but he got away with it because it's all in
the way you handle it. If you don't try to duck and dodge and just
say I screwed up, people accept that,'' Nofziger says.
</P>
<P>
   If self-deprecation heals a self-inflicted wound, Bush is good
at such humor. He has been joking about the test ever since he
failed it, telling Lauer that he scored a 25. But the Texas
governor was also ready with answers on Russia, China, the World
Trade Organization and NATO. Maybe he failed the first foreign
policy pop quiz, but Bush clearly seems to have been studying for
the next one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
