<SLUG> BC-ART-AUCTION-760&AMP;ADD--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTION SETS RECORDS FOR 18 CONTEMPORARY ARTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices for artworks made in the last 30 years were so
high at Christie's Tuesday night that it seemed as if a bubble were
getting ready to burst. Bidders acted like spoiled children,
consistently ignoring the estimates and paying whatever it took to
outpace the competition, even though many works had been up for
auction in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of contemporary art totaled $13.2 million, above
Christie's high estimate of $12.8 million. Of the 60 lots offered,
56 found buyers. Records were set for 18 artists, ranging from Jeff
Koons to Chuck Close to Damien Hirst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of an unhealthy market,'' said Edward
Nahem, a Manhattan dealer. ``There's just too much money around.''
</P>
<P>
   The cover of the evening's catalog featured Jeff Koons' ``Pink
Panther,'' a porcelain sculpture of a semi-nude blonde hugging the
cartoon character. Five bidders sought the work, which finally sold
to an unidentified telephone bidder for $1.8 million, more than
twice its high estimate of $800,000. The seller was believed to be
Kent Logan, the San Francisco collector.
</P>
<P>
   Another telephone bidder bought Chuck Close's ``Cindy II''
(1988), a portrait of the photographer Cindy Sherman. Estimated at
$600,000 to $800,000, it sold for $1.2 million after five bidders
vied for it. The painting had sold for $231,000 at Sotheby's in
1992. Tuesday night's price was a record for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   All eyes were on the results of the work of two British artists,
Rachel Whiteread and Hirst, who are currently represented in the
Brooklyn Museum's ``Sensation'' exhibition. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
who deemed the show offensive, tried to cut off city support to the
museum and threatened to evict it from its city-owned building. He
also questioned the financial interest behind the show, since
Christie's had donated $50,000 toward the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Did Christie's investment paid off? It's hard to say. Ms.
Whiteread had one piece in Tuesday night's sale: ``Untitled (Three
Tables),'' a 1996 plaster floor piece being sold by Gerald
Fagginato, the London dealer. Estimated at $100,000 to $150,000, it
went to an unidentified telephone bidder for $112,500.
</P>
<P>
   The sale included five works by Hirst, known for submerging dead
animals in formaldehyde. They performed well, but not so
spectacularly as many other works Tuesday night. The five are all
from different periods in his career. Three had been on the market
within the last 18 months, but that didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Way'' (1990-91) _ one of the artist's well-known
pharmaceutical works, actually a medicine cabinet filled with old
drug bottles _ set a record for the artist. Estimated at $250,000
to $350,000, it sold to an unidentified bidder for $354,500. Just
last year, it was sold at Sotheby's for $262,900.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loss of Memory Is Worse than Death,'' a 1994 piece consisting
of a steel cage filled with formaldehyde containers, masks, gloves
and a syringe, was estimated at $120,000 to $180,000. Simon de
Pury, the former chairman of Sotheby's in Europe who is now a
private dealer in Geneva, bought the work for $178,500 _ quite a
handsome price, considering that it failed to sell at Christie's in
London in October 1998, when the estimate was $140,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hirst that didn't sell last year but soared above its
high estimate Tuesday night was ``Alone Yet Together,'' a 1993 wall
piece consisting of 100 dead fish floating in individual glass
blocks filled with formaldehyde. Estimated at $180,000 to $250,000,
it sold to de Pury for $277,500. Last year in London, it carried an
estimate of $170,000 to $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Dead Head,'' a photographic self-portrait of Hirst at age
16 posing with a severed human head, was estimated at $25,000 to
$35,000. It sold to a telephone bidder for $74,000.
``N-(9-Acridinyl) Maleimide,'' from 1992, one of the artist's dot
paintings, was expected to bring $150,000 to $200,000; a telephone
bidder paid $173,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most exciting moment in the sale came when Martin
Kippenberger's ``Untitled'' (1998) went on the block. The painting,
showing a man dressed only in boxer shorts looking at himself in a
bubble-like mirror, was estimated at $40,000 to $60,000. Seven
bidders wanted it badly. When the bidding reached $500,000, the
audience began laughing in disbelief. It finally went to an
unidentified telephone bidder for $717,500, a record for the
artist.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another huge price was paid for a 1986 ``Last Supper'' from Andy
Warhol's famous series of reflections on Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last
Supper'' (1495-97), based on reproductions of that famous image
rather than the image itself. Estimated at $400,000 to $600,000, it
sold to another telephone bidder for $772,500.
</P>
<P>
   The sale included property from several collections, among them
the O.R.S., Doron Sebbag Art Collection, owned by Tel Aviv art
patrons who support the Israel Museum. The first 12 lots in the
sale came from this collection, emphasizing both portraiture and
photography.
</P>
<P>
   The first lot was Thomas Struth's ``Musee du Louvre 4, Paris,
1989,'' a photograph of visitors to the Louvre stopping in front of
Gericault's ``Raft of the Medusa.'' Estimated at $30,000 to
$40,000, it sold for $178,500, a record for the artist, to Perry
Rubenstein, a Manhattan dealer. In May 1997, Sotheby's sold the
work for $39,100 in an auction of works from the Boston Children's
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The O.R.S., Doron Sebbag Collection also included works of
German artists like Gerhard Richter and Georg Baselitz. Richter's
``Gilbert, George (381-1,2),'' from 1975, a pair of blurred
paintings taken from photographs of the artist team Gilbert and
George, was estimated at $300,000 to $400,000; it sold to Anthony
d'Offay, a London dealer, for $431,500. In 1996, Christie's in
London had sold the work for $175,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of the evening's few casualties was Bruce Nauman's ``First
Hologram Series: Making Faces (F,G)'' and ``Second Hologram Series:
Full Figures Poses (B).'' These three holographic images on glass,
from 1968-69, were expected to bring $200,000 to $300,000, but
nobody was interested and bidding stopped at $170,000.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, prices were stronger than many
dealers would have liked. A Charles Ray drawing, ``Untitled,'' of
an enraged Superman purposely rendered in the comic-book style of
Roy Lichtenstein, sold for $189,500, more than four times its high
estimate of $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemarie Trockel, the German-born artist whose work was
represented in this year's Venice Biennale, was included in Tuesday
night's sale. Her sculpture of a bronze deer lying on its side,
expected to bring $50,000 to $70,000, was sold to de Pury for
$85,000, a record for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were paying a lot of money for talent that hasn't been
proven, while the classics are often being overlooked,'' said Marc
Selwyn, a Los Angeles dealer, leaving the sale Tuesday night. ``It
all seemed out of kilter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
