<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NUGGETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL LEADS KNICKS TO 102-95 VICTORY OVER NUGGETS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Latrell Sprewell shook off his shooting slump on
Tuesday night and stepped into a mesmerizing zone that helped pull
the New York Knicks out of a dire situation. With his fists pumping
and his teeth gritted, Sprewell's burst of energy and 26 points
helped the Knicks break a three-game losing streak with a 102-95
victory over the Denver Nuggets at the Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling for a week with his shot, Sprewell shrugged off
a 1-for-4 start and came out invigorated in the second half. It was
almost a flashback to the game against Chicago in the first week of
the season. With his team lagging, Sprewell scored 16 points in the
third quarter and sustained his energy in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Sprewell supplied his team with oxygen. Suddenly,
everyone was alive and ready to hold off Denver's late surge. There
was Allan Houston putting down a key 3-pointer and the limping
Marcus Camby converting a 3-point play in the closing minutes of a
tight game.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell also had a couple of timely steals and nifty passes to
complete a dominant performance.
</P>
<P>
   His exuberance nearly got the best of him in the fourth quarter.
He had four fouls when a turnover was converted into a fast-break
dunk by Ron Mercer. As Sprewell ran with Mercer stride for stride,
he could not help fouling Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-point play not only left Sprewell with his fifth foul, but
it also gave life to a Nuggets team that seemed destined for a
double-digit loss, down by 89-80 before the play.
</P>
<P>
   After the Nuggets pulled within 5, Sprewell atoned with
back-to-back jumpers to give the Knicks (5-4) breathing room.
Houston added 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets were not considered a threat, but that did not
prevent Coach Jeff Van Gundy from calling an impromptu practice on
Monday, the Knicks' travel day. This was not about Denver, but more
a manifestation of Van Gundy's growing concern with a team that
started the season 3-0, but had dropped four of five games before
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well in the fourth quarter in Minnesota,'' he
said. ``And in Boston, we didn't play great. But we had a
commitment to winning. Against Miami, we didn't show a commitment
to winning, and that's what has disappointed all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the loss to the Heat on Sunday would wake up the Knicks.
If so, it wasn't apparent early against the Nuggets on Tuesday
night as the Knicks trailed at the half, 48-46. It took Sprewell,
snapping out of his recent shooting slump, to inject some energy
into the team with a third-quarter scoring binge. Similar to the
pick-me-up he gave the Knicks in the second game of the season in
Chicago, Sprewell was unstoppable as he slashed to the basket and
pulled up for his off-kilter jumpers, hitting five of his first six
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's 16-point third-quarter effort helped the Knicks forge
a 74-70 lead after three periods. But this was a resilient Denver
team; young and athletic, the Nuggets were fresher and livelier in
their pursuit of every loose ball in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   On one sequence in the second quarter, Mercer put up a jumper
over Houston that missed. The ball was batted back out by Antonio
McDyess and bounced around the floor in front of three Knicks
before George McCloud swept in and picked up the loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   He fired a pass to Raef LaFrentz, who dunked and drew a third
foul on Chris Childs. This hustle play gave the Nuggets, who had
trailed by 9 points in the second quarter, a 41-39 lead with 2:51
left before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Denver maintained that edge until the intermission. Although the
Knicks hit 54 percent of their shots against a team that lives near
the bottom of the league in defense, they were outrebounded, 23-17,
turned the ball over nine times and made just 6 of 11 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets were shooting poorly from the field at 40 percent,
but went to the free-throw line 21 times, leaving the Knicks in
foul trouble up and down their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   About the only player clicking for the Knicks was John Wallace,
who had 12 first-half points. The rest were still struggling with
the issues that had haunted them over the last week, like
Sprewell's shooting problems.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous four games, Sprewell had shot 32 percent. On
Tuesday night, he began 1 for 4. He was missing everything,
including his pull-up jumper that kept rattling off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get discouraged,'' Sprewell said before the game.
``Just got to keep trying.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he did. With the Knicks trailing by 8 early in the second
half, Sprewell went on a tear. On his way to hitting five of his
first six shots, he had two steals to help the Knicks go take a
66-65 lead with three minutes left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell picked a good time to go on a roll. As much of a team
player as Sprewell has been, the Knicks need him to score with so
many of their other options ailing. Larry Johnson has not been
effective since back spasms put him on the bench last week. And
Camby spent most of tonight limping and grimacing from the
tendinitis in his left knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
