<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND APPLE CUP HYPE LURKS AT LEAST ONE PRAGMATIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The sentimentality of Apple Cup week always evokes
some slop about final runs down stadium tunnels, senior-class
salutes and reflections about grand victories and agonizing losses.
</P>
<P>
   That works for a lot of fans and some former players. But there
are some in purple, such as Lester Towns, for whom the career
climax Saturday is unlikely to evoke industrial-grade wistfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' the Huskies senior linebacker and
tri-captain said. ``After the game, I'll be more emotional if Cal
beats Stanford. But you know, I've been here long enough. I got a
degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I'm ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Towns is a pragmatic, even melancholy, fellow not easily given
to gee-whiz soliloquies about Old Siwash. Nor is he likely to wax
rhapsodic to any reporter looking for tender anecdotes about his
tiny sanctions-compromised class, among whom there are just seven
others who will start Saturday against Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as close as you might think _ not any closer than a
big class,'' he said. Then he laughed. ``We don't sit around and
drink tea and talk about things that happened our freshman year.''
</P>
<P>
   As a class limited to a maximum 15 scholarship athletes by the
1993 Pac-10 sanctions, Towns and his remaining peers know their
station in the cold business of big-time college sports.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, the business also included a head-coaching change
that outsiders have readily accepted as necessary and beneficial.
For insiders such as Towns, something was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to finish with the same coach,'' he said, without
rancor. ``He knows you. You get a new coach in here who doesn't
know you, and you don't really get to know him until halfway
through the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Towns misses his old linebackers coach, the garrulous Dick
Baird, a longtime player favorite under the tenures of Don James
and Jim Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know my position coach (Tim Hundley) half as well as I
knew Coach Baird, who I had for four years,'' said Towns, one of 10
starters on the defense from California. ``I think (a close
relationship) helps, especially coming from out of state. Without
family here, the transition is kind of hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The position coach is someone you talk to every day. The head
coach, you hardly ever talk to. The position coach is more involved
with your life, helping you out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard to do with new coaches coming in. I think they
should take time to get to know players.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Towns and other loyalists, Lambright's
post-bowl firing and Neuheisel's hasty hiring left little time for
pleasantries. If the coaches didn't even bother to read the NCAA
rulebook, a gaffe that brought about minor sanctions, the works of
Miss Manners received no attention.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching change also brought change to the player hierarchy
favored by Lambright, who valued loyalty and seniority above all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors have always been captains here, but now we have
sophomores and freshmen standing up at meetings,'' he said. ``You
look at them and say, `Who are you? You haven't been here long
enough.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our seniors deserve to play more. If you're not
playing as a senior, that's sad. At least, special teams or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult change for Towns has been himself. After a
much-chronicled foot injury following his impressive sophomore
year, he hasn't been the same player. At 6-foot-3 and 240 pounds,
he's still the strongest Husky in uniform, one of the strongest
ever at Washington, but the speed and quickness that distinguished
him have diminished. Instead, there is sometimes a limp.
</P>
<P>
   The agents who inquired two years ago when he was going to turn
pro have stopped calling.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had evaluated his pro potential, a chagrined
Towns said, ``I don't know. I'm kind of scared to. Last year being
injured, this year not having a great year ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how my injuries hold up. I try not to get
injured. Once I do get a chance, I think everything will be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The glorious career that was mapped out in Towns' mind never
quite materialized. But he knows college football dreams don't come
with guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   And for the grunts of the industry, the players, it sometimes
doesn't come with a lot of sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how I'm going to feel when I get dressed and
they call my name the last time,'' he said, smiling. ``It's been
fun, and I might think I'll miss it. But who knows, I might get
drafted by the Seahawks and end up back here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fun, some fame and a college degree _ not to mention an
education. Towns learned when to move on and how to be OK with it.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
