<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD IN ALL CAPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXT STARTS RIGHT HERE  &UR; KC-Heaster-Column _ Business  &UR; Aspiring
Royals owner Miles Prentice deserves respect
</P>
<P>
   By JERRY HEASTER
</P>
<P>
   Knight-Ridder Newspapers KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Is aspiring Royals
owner Miles Prentice going against the folk wisdom of the song that
admonishes gamblers to ``know when to hold 'em, know when to fold
'em, know when to walk away''?
</P>
<P>
   If so, is his apparently quixotic effort to keep his purchase
bid alive jeopardizing Kansas City's big-league baseball status and
its future economic potential in the bargain?
</P>
<P>
   The early reaction of some pundits hereabouts seems to be yes to
both questions. No sooner had Prentice vowed not to be deterred by
his rebuff at the hands of baseball's reigning moguls than some
fellow opinionmeisters began a spirited campaign to banish Prentice
to outside the pale.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a couple of years makes. It seems like
yesterday when the amiable New York lawyer arrived to begin his
one-man crusade to form a local ownership group to purchase the
Royals. He quickly won the hearts of Kansas City, and against long
odds recruited a platoon of affluent Kansas Citians willing to pony
up enough cash to bid for the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice worked hard, played by the rules and showed the
patience of Job at every exasperating turn. His efforts were
rewarded by a boorish kiss-off from Major League Baseball's owners,
who rejected him without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone expected Prentice and his prospective ownership team to
capitulate, but they aren't going down without a fight. All of
which raises the question of whether their hard-nosed reaction
jeopardizes the future of big-league baseball in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to see how it could. If Prentice is willing to go
through the agony of resubmitting his bid, this shouldn't
discourage others from bidding. David Glass has emerged as the
seeming consensus candidate to save the hometown nine, and his
entry to the lists would be welcomed by many.
</P>
<P>
   It's his call, though, and if Glass wants to go for it,
Prentice's group shouldn't be viewed as anything more than a
competitive factor. It's as simple as Glass removing himself as a
Royals transition steward and initiating his own bid. He surely
must know by now that those who misjudged him before will never
again question his motives.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Kansas City should show some class when it comes to
the way it treats Prentice and his group. Prentice performed a
valuable community service, not only by putting together a local
team of prospective buyers, but also by helping rally the community
around the Royals when a valid rallying point was badly needed.
</P>
<P>
   The ``dump Miles'' and ``hug David'' approach is unfair to both
Prentice and the area residents who threw their support behind his
effort to sustain the team's status as community property. In being
too quick to dismiss Prentice and his local partners, we risk
sullying our image in much the same way baseball owners did theirs
in the classless way they blew off the Prentice partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever develops, though, the critical consideration is
ensuring the Royals' continued presence in Kansas City. There is a
body of scholarship claiming to prove big-league sports aren't
meaningful contributors to a community's economic dynamism. Anyone
who believes this, however, fails to appreciate what differentiates
Kansas City from, say, Omaha or Des Moines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
