r f BC-ECONOMY-CALIFORNIA-LA     11-17 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-CALIFORNIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC GOOD TIMES EXPECTED TO LAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Chris Sieroty 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern California's economic good times should continue over
the next two years but at a slightly slower growth rate than the
region has enjoyed since the mid-1990s, a survey to be released
today predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, commissioned by the Southern California Association
of Governments, also predicts the regional economy will outperform
the nation's economy over the next two years as measured by job
creation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the area -- comprising Imperial, Los
Angeles, Orange, Riverside, San Bernardino and Ventura counties --
will add jobs at a rate of 2.8 percent this year, followed by 2.6
percent in 2000, and 2.3 percent in 2001. The study is the first
comprehensive attempt by the regional planning agency to conduct a
two-year forecast for the six-county area.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that construction, services, state and
local government and wholesale trade sectors are all expected to
continue to experience growth during the next two years but at a
slightly slower rate than in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The service sector, for example, is expected to slow down over
the next two years, but growth is forecast to remain impressive
with increases of 3.5 percent in 2000 and 3.1 percent in 2001,
after rising 3.7 percent this year. In Riverside and San Bernardino
counties, the growth in service jobs will outpace the region's with
4 percent this year, another 4 percent in 2000 and 3.7 percent in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The report underscores the impressive rebound that Southern
California has achieved from the severe recession in the early part
of this decade. The region's economic recovery began in late 1994
and SCAG's figures show that after several years of moderate
growth, the regional economy began to grow outpace the nation in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The survey attempts to gauge the economic picture of the
region to help businesses who are contemplating moving to Southern
California or expressing a desire to leave the area,'' said Bruce
F. DeVine, chief economist with SCAG.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed employment in state and local government
will continue to increase because of improving financial conditions
and continued hiring by local school districts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Inland Empire, for example, state and local government
employment is expected to grow by 4.3 percent next year and 3.8
percent by 2001. By comparison, similar jobs in Los Angeles County
will grow by only 2.3 percent in 2000 and 2.4 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report shows that times are good but we need to plan for
the future to deal with the problems of transportation, housing
affordability and availability,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist
with the Los Angeles County Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser also said local governments and businesses need to
re-examine their planning despite the inclination of many people to
avoid thinking about the future when times are good.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that for the second consecutive year,
construction was the fastest-growing sector in the six-county
region with 20,000 new jobs added during the first two quarters of
1999. The survey attributed the increase in construction employment
to an exceptionally strong housing market, driven by low mortgage
rates, continued asset growth and healthy gains in employment and
income.
</P>
<P>
   The survey predicts that regional payroll will grow at an
average rate of 2.1 percent over the next five years. Total payroll
in Ventura County is expected to increase by 1.7 percent next year,
while payroll growth in Los Angeles will slide from 1.9 percent
this year to 1.4 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Imperial County payroll employment is expected to increase 1.4
percent next year, while Orange County's payroll employment is
expected to grow at a 2.8 percent rate in 2000 and 2.6 percent the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   The gains in payroll will translate into relatively low
unemployment figures for the region. The average jobless rate in
Southern California is expected to be 5.5 percent in 1999 and 6.1
percent next year and 5.9 percent in 2001, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Orange County, which accounted for half of the 182,000 jobs
added to the Southern California region so far this year, is
projected to have an average unemployment rate of 2.8 percent in
1999 and 3 percent next year. The low figures mean a continued
tight labor market for the county, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``2000-2001 Regional Economic Forecast for Southern
California,'' is a combination of two regional forecasts from
California State Universities Long Beach and Fullerton, DeVine
said. He added that SCAG commissioned the survey to promote the
idea of a regional economy which includes all six counties. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
