<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-PAYTON-SPI </SLUG>
  
 McMILLAN SAYS PAYTON'S TIME HERE AT LAST  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was perhaps the perfect symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Gary Payton became the Sonics' all-time assists
leader, Sonics assistant coach Nate McMillan interrupted his Payton
tribute to show off the watch on his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Rolex. A $30,000 time piece. The gift Payton presented
McMillan last season in honor of his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this. It's love there,'' McMillan said, genuinely
delighted Monday night at New Jersey when Payton passed him to move
atop the Sonics' assists list. Payton enters the Sonics' game
Wednesday night against Golden State having become the team's
career leader in a fourth statistical category.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Payton also will enter KeyArena with a torch handed
down by an icon.
</P>
<P>
   As far as McMillan is concerned, Payton's time has truly come.
</P>
<P>
   The all-star point guard is finally in his proper place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being the leader that I always hoped to try and mold him
(into). Finally, he's become that guy,'' McMillan said. ``For once,
numbers don't mean anything to him. The only numbers that mean
anything to him is wins or losses. He's always been a guy who
pretty much kept up with his statistics. But now he's being the
leader that he needs to become for this team to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Proof of McMillan's testimony is how Payton handled grabbing the
assists record.
</P>
<P>
   Payton actually did not know he had achieved the mark at the
time. It wasn't until after the game against the Nets that Payton
was told about the achievement and congratulated.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing McMillan's compliments was high praise to Payton.
</P>
<P>
   They are only four years apart. Payton, 31, always has described
a brotherly relationship with his former teammate. But McMillan,
35, watches Payton with a look in his eyes normally reserved for
proud fathers.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan was already wearing Seattle green when the Sonics
drafted Payton to succeed him in 1990. As the oft-told story goes,
McMillan took a volatile Payton under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   Now McMillan sees a mature Payton _ a point guard for the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Payton is on top of his game, averaging 21.9 points, 10 assists
and 7.1 rebounds in the flow of the team's schemes. He still is
wiry and strong. His defense is hard-nosed. And his mouth still
runs in overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand his ways and how competitive he is,'' McMillan
said. ``I've seen him grow throughout his career, and so far this
is his best year. Anytime someone needs to speak, he's speaking
up.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan concedes that one reason Payton no longer suppresses
his leadership skills is because the old regime is gone. McMillan,
Detlef Schrempf, Sam Perkins and Hersey Hawkins were veteran Sonics
players who also accepted responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the fact that I was part of that group,'' McMillan
said, ``I was a guy who was leading him. ... (But Gary's) happy
with the guys we signed this year. He feels these are the guys he
can lead.''
</P>
<P>
   It gives McMillan a warm feeling. He can afford to follow the
inscription, ``Take it easy,'' that Payton put on the bottom of
McMillan's watch.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
