r n BC- &LR; GRIDLOCK-STUDY &UR; -LADN     11-17 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHLAND TRAFFIC WORST IN NATION 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- GRIDLOCK-STUDY -LADN  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Steve Carney and Harrison Sheppard 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a finding that won't surprise angry commuters stuck on the
101 Freeway, Los Angeles ranked first in the nation for traffic
congestion for the 16th year in a row, according to a study
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And with six million more people expected to move to the region
by 2020, transportation experts said the Southland likely will
retain its inglorious heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very large population, a very wide area, and because of
that there are just very few ways to get from one side to the
other. Except for cars,'' said David Schrank, co-author of the
study from the Texas Transportation Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most important thing to realize is there's no one
or two silver bullets,'' said Dan Beal, transportation policy
manager for the Automobile Club of Southern California. ``What we
have is a need to apply a lot of different solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The gridlock study, compiled annually by the Texas
Transportation Institute, ranked 68 of the nation's largest urban
areas, and listed L.A. at the top of all congestion categories.
</P>
<P>
   A rush-hour trip in Los Angeles takes 51 percent longer than a
drive during off-peak times, according to the study. That's up from
31 percent in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   In Brownsville, Texas, the study found that motorists lose about
three hours a year to congestion. A Los Angeles driver can rack
that up in one trip, if caught in a nasty SigAlert. By comparison,
over the course of a year the average L.A. driver spends about 82
hours caught in traffic, topping second-place Washington D.C. at 76
hours.
</P>
<P>
   And that gridlock costs L.A. drivers about $1,370 per year in
wasted fuel and travel time, according to the study's 1997 figures,
the most recent available.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation experts say the answers to gridlock can be found
in five main areas:
</P>
<P>
   Add freeway lanes or build new freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the number of vehicles on the road by persuading people to
carpool, ride buses or trains, bicycle, walk or work from home.
</P>
<P>
   Convince people to avoid driving at peak times by adding freeway
tolls that rise during rush hour, or having employers shift work
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Increase road efficiency by improving ramp metering,
synchronizing traffic signals on surface streets and quickly
clearing the freeways of disabled vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Manage population growth to slow the number of new vehicles on
the roads and build communities so people don't need to drive as
far to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the problem is sprawl, and that is something Southern
California has to come to grips with,'' said Gloria Ohland,
spokeswoman for the Surface Transportation Policy Project, a
nonprofit coalition of 200 groups that reviews transportation
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to create more compact, mixed-use communities,'' she
said, ``so you don't have to go very far to get groceries, to go to
the dry cleaners, to take your kid to soccer practice.''
</P>
<P>
   She said cities such as Burbank, Santa Monica, West Hollywood
and Glendale, to a certain extent, all offer such lifestyles. In
traditional suburban communities like Northridge or Santa Clarita,
``you really need to get into the car to do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said it is too late to regulate growth in Los Angeles. A
key is to provide attractive alternatives for motorists, such as
trains, car pools or Smart Shuttle vans, which are dispatched on
demand like airport shuttles.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said it will be hard to get drivers out of their cars,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't going to change their lifestyles,'' said Mark
Pisano, executive director of the Southern California Association
of Governments. ``How can we create systems that give the same
service as your automobile?''
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans spokeswoman Margie Tiritilli said the answer is not to
add freeways.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be any more freeways. We're looking at
maximizing our existing system,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans is adding 300 miles of new high-occupancy vehicle lanes
to every freeway countywide, except the Pasadena Freeway and those
that lead into downtown, Tiritilli said.
</P>
<P>
   Some contend HOV lanes are wasted space.
</P>
<P>
   The Reason Public Policy Institute, a Los Angeles-based
nonprofit foundation, advocates turning some HOV lanes into
quasi-toll lanes, so solo drivers could pay to join car poolers.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Transportation Authority plans to begin a rapid
bus system next year. It would run on surface streets and allow
buses to turn traffic lights green as they approach, said MTA
regional planning director Brad McAllester.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA is testing the project with three lines, including one
along Ventura Boulevard from Warner Center to Universal City that
will start running in June.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the rapid bus system would expand, removing the
equivalent of nine freeway lanes full of rush hour traffic,
McAllester said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Green, director of the environmental program at Reason,
said policy makers and motorists alike will not easily embrace big
solutions such as freeway double-decking or massive transit
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem will undoubtedly eventually solve itself,'' Green
said, adding that people tend to limit their commutes to an average
of 20 minutes. ``They do what's necessary to try to maintain that.
They will find other jobs, or live other places or work at home.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
