<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURONET-KAN </SLUG>
  
 SERVICES OPERATE ATMs THAT DISPENSE MORE THAN CASH  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MARK DAVIS
</P>
<P>
   Knight-Ridder Newspapers KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Americans, believe
it or not, are behind the curve when it comes to using automated
teller machines. The Poles, Hungarians and Czechs are way ahead of
us, thanks to a Leawood, Kan., company.
</P>
<P>
   Euronet Services Inc., at 4601 College Blvd., operates a network
of nearly 1,800 ATMs across Europe at which former communist bloc
shoppers can conduct a flurry of business.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the machines dispense cash like their counterparts in
the United States. But they also flash advertisements to users and
spit out coupons. Users in Poland also can pay their utility bills
at the ATMs. Users in Poland and Hungary can buy vouchers for
mobile phone minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll start to see the same things here,'' said
Michael Brown, chief executive officer and chairman of Euronet. ``
It just hasn't started here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such services might make their debut in America through 334 Dash
network ATMs that Euronet's software operates in Dillard's stores,
including those in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're probably going to see all of that in Dillard's stores
in the future,'' said David Helm, assistant treasurer of the Little
Rock, Ark.-based department store chain.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements probably will be the first feature to show up on
the Dillard's ATMs, the last of which went in this month. Helm said
a cosmetics company's ad might flash on the machine's small screen
during the 30 or 45 seconds it takes to process a cash transaction
or account balance inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, Euronet's software can select an ad geared to
the person standing at the machine. The cosmetics ad might pop up
if the card activating the machine belongs to a woman; a menswear
ad might pop up if it's a man's card.
</P>
<P>
   Helm said Dillard's decided to put ATMs in all its stores
because customers are using checks less often and debit cards more
often. A debit card looks like a credit card but automatically
deducts the purchase price from the user's bank account, rather
than bill the customer later.
</P>
<P>
   Helm said having an ATM in the store also allowed shoppers,
especially this holiday season, to double-check their balances and
avoid an embarrassment at the register.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the department store will look into the other
features Euronet can provide through ATMs, Helm said. That's why
Dillard's went to Euronet to operate the machines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed to be way ahead of everyone with ATMs and how
they're proceeding,'' Helm said.
</P>
<P>
   Euronet got that experience in Europe, principally in former
communist bloc countries.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Henry, chief operating officer at Euronet, spent five
years scouting locations and setting up the network, starting in
Hungary and expanding outward. Consumers in these recently opened
economies were good candidates to use the added features of the
machines because they had been in such a primitive economy.
</P>
<P>
   No one had checking accounts before the Soviet bloc fell apart.
Consumers simply lined up with wads of cash to pay their utilities
in person. Post offices allowed consumers to pay the bills in one
place, but it was still a cash-only deal.
</P>
<P>
   Each Euronet ATM is hooked up to let consumers pay utilities
electronically. It's also quicker than getting in five separate
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers in these former Soviet-dominated economies also don't
have established credit histories to get mobile telephone service,
Brown said. Consumer credit, like checking accounts, simply didn't
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, individuals who want mobile phone service buy vouchers
worth so many minutes of use. Brown said the vouchers were
something like calling cards, but involve accessing a code to fill
your phone with usable minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Euronet ATMs sell these vouchers. The ATM offers an advantage in
that the machines operate 24 hours a day. Brown said retail stores
that sell the vouchers were open only a few hours on weekends and
far fewer hours during the week than U.S. retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Although Euronet's machines regularly pay off consumers,
investors haven't fared so well. Euronet sold stock publicly in
March 1997. Its initial public offering came out at 131/2, and
shares traded as high as 161/4 that first day.
</P>
<P>
   This week, shares are bumping around 3 and briefly fell below 2
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Building the network in Europe has been expensive, and machines
generally don't reach average transaction volumes for three to 12
months, the company's reports said. Brown said that machines in
Poland had taken even longer to gain volume but that monthly
transaction totals had doubled this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 8 percent of the (Polish) population has a card, which I
love, (because) we're already hitting break-even,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the firm's entire ATM network was likely to be
operating at a profit by year-end. But that's on an operating
basis, before the firm covers its interest expenses, taxes,
depreciation and amortization costs.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has reeled in its capital expenditures to get there,
partly by selling its ATMs in Croatia to a bank, though it
continues to operate the network.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Gyulafia, the firm's director of marketing
communications, said the firm could expand into other areas, such
as helping banks in Europe set up credit card operations.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he saw Euronet's ATMs getting into the e-commerce
field even more, offering, for example, concert tickets,
particularly in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got connections to people's money,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
