<SLUG> BC-NETZERO-AIMTV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETZERO SWAPS STOCK FOR VIDEO AD CARRIER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Z. Cohen 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE -- Internet service provider NetZero began
spending the spoils of its initial public offering Tuesday by
buying AimTV, a carrier of video advertising on the Web, for $25.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for NetZero to give AimTV shareholders 1 million
shares of NetZero stock for the company. The deal is expected to be
completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   NetZero went public Sept. 24, issuing 10 million shares and
raising $160 million through the stock sale.
</P>
<P>
   Now, NetZero users will have no choice but to watch video
commercials as well as still banners on their screen in exchange
for the free Internet access the company offers.
</P>
<P>
   NetZero Chief Executive Mark Goldston said the addition of AimTV
gives NetZero another outlet for advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, AimTV's product will be integrated into the NetZero
browser in the form of a service called GroundZero. When users log
on, they will view television-quality advertising while their modem
is dialing and connecting, Goldston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time it is our intention to try and integrate the AimTV
technology so that during part of your log-on we'll show you
regular banner advertising, and part will be television-quality
commercials,'' Goldston said.
</P>
<P>
   The product AimTV has developed employs a thin file to transmit
the video to targeted users identified by the profile information
they give the company as part of the registration process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not streaming video, and it's something that can work
on narrow-band access (such as a telephone connection),'' Goldston
said.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst began coverage of NetZero on Tuesday with a hold
rating, saying the company looks strong, but the business model is
unproven. ING Barings analyst Youssef Squali initiated the coverage
of the company along with several other Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Goldston said his company has not yet been able to go after
advertisers, but he believes the service will be well-received.
</P>
<P>
   NetZero's stock ended trading Tuesday 75 cents higher, at $25.25
per share. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
