<SLUG> BC-CENTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOVATED APARTMENT COMPLEX OFFERS SAFE PLACE TO LIVE, LEARN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHANI A. BROWN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By SHANI A. BROWN Knight Ridder Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Residents of Olive Park Village now have a
safe place to live and interact with one another, thanks to a $3.2
million partnership between a bank and a local nonprofit community
development group.
</P>
<P>
   The complex also includes the ``Make a Difference Center,''
which opened Monday. The project is the result of a partnership
between Bank of America Community Development Corp. and Old
Northeast Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Housing Development Commission also provided $1.4
million in rehabilitation loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am speechless about what has happened here'' said Mary
Therese Carroll, chairman of the Old Northeast board. ``It really
has become a wonderful place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   The Make a Difference Center at Ninth and Olive streets consists
of a computer lab connected to the Internet, a library and a
tutorial area. It will provide activities at no charge for children
and adults who live in the complex. Children also can frolic on the
playground outside.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America CDC and Old Northeast worked together to buy and
renovate the 137-unit complex about a year ago, said William
Nelson, president of Bank of America Kansas City Region.
</P>
<P>
   About 85 percent of the apartments have been renovated.
Completion of the others is scheduled by the end of December. The
property is mixed-income housing, with 52 of the units available
for rent subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   The Make a Difference Center is the first to open in the
Midwest, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center will provide residents, especially school-age
children, with a safe, community-based place to play and learn,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The center's program was created by Bank of America to provide
services to residents of multifamily rental properties developed by
the Bank of America CDC. A total of 25 centers are planned across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In only 11 months, Olive Park Village was transformed into a
community where people feel safe, said Paul Livingston, senior vice
president of Yarco Cos., which renovated the complex and will
manage it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the better developments in this area,''
Livingston said. ``And the center is probably the most premium
community center in this area because of all the services it
offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the books and computers have not yet arrived, 13-year-old
Ryan Johnson was excited to use the center Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to eat, take a nap and do my homework after school,''
Ryan said. ``Now I can come here and use the computers. I will
probably come everyday. I guess I will have to cut out my nap
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
