<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2198 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-KAN &LR;      11-17 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION HEATS UP AS SPRINT, MCIWORLDCOM FILE MERGER
APPLICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By TED SICKINGER
</P>
<P>
   Knight-Ridder Newspapers KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As Sprint Corp. and
MCI WorldCom Inc. file their formal merger application today with
the Federal Communications Commission, the voices of opposition to
the marriage are gathering strength.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and regulators already are blustering about ``the
dangers of market concentration'' and ``taking a hard look at this
deal,'' though Congress has little direct power to block a huge
telecommunications merger, and regulators have never done so.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates, frustrated by the parade of megamergers and
seeming inaction in Washington, are back at the ramparts, howling
about hidden increases in consumer long-distance prices and a
telecommunications system set up to serve Wall Street and corporate
America.
</P>
<P>
   Yet corporate America sees little in the deal for itself, save
one less rival to compete for its business.
</P>
<P>
   And competitors, predictably, think the deal would stifle
competition and should face onerous conditions if allowed at all.
</P>
<P>
   The naysayers' zeal doesn't surprise officials at Sprint and MCI
WorldCom, who will be trying to rush their deal past roadblocks as
quickly as possible while making as few concessions as possible to
appease various opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say they hope to complete the deal by
mid-2000, an optimistic schedule given the two-year regulatory slog
that past telecom mergers have been subjected to.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a merger of this size, it's understandable that a variety
of interests would express concern,'' said Peter Lucht, a spokesman
for MCI WorldCom. ``But we're confident that we're going to be able
to show that this merger is pro-consumer and in the public
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Benjamin Wolff, a partner with the law firm of
Davis, Tremain and Wright who specializes in antitrust issues,
``That's going to be a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   ``On its face, this appears to be something that decreases
competition. They're going to make the pitch that everything's in
flux in the industry, but regulators aren't in the business of
predicting future trends. Under the law, they have to make the
determination under today's competitive landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   It's almost certain that if regulators allow the deal, they will
force the combined company to divest Sprint or MCI WorldCom's
Internet backbone, the large national and global networks that
carry Internet traffic between smaller networks and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   When WorldCom bought MCI Communications in 1998, regulators
forced MCI to sell its Internet backbone. With that precedent and
their urgency to get the deal done, it's unlikely that MCI WorldCom
and Sprint would waste time arguing against such a divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   The open questions are whether the companies' combined share of
the long-distance market will be cause for strong concern, and
what, if anything, regulators will do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Together, MCI WorldCom, Sprint and AT&AMP;T control 80 percent of
the long-distance market, easily enough concentration to raise
antitrust concerns at the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The department has already asked MCI WorldCom and Sprint for
additional information after their initial merger filing in
October. The request is not out of the ordinary, but it indicates
that the department intends to examine the merger in detail, rather
than approve it immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies declined to comment on the process at Justice,
which is not public.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC review, however, is a public process. And the companies'
filings today will provide the best view of their strategy with
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The betrothed are likely to offer a two-pronged rationale for
their union.
</P>
<P>
   First, they will argue that long-distance is already a commodity
business, with more than 600 providers overall. Moreover, they will
argue that a growing number of smaller carriers now have their own
fiber networks and can compete directly against the big three, even
for the sophisticated voice and data services that corporations
use.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, regulators are likely to permit at least one of the
regional Bell operating companies _ Bell Atlantic or Southwestern
Bell _ to begin offering long-distance service to its customers,
adding competitive vigor to the residential market, where the Bells
are expected to be most active.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you put aside the notion that the market is evolving
and the Bell companies will be entering, we still maintain that
this merger would not harm competition in the long-distance market
because that market is so robustly competitive already,'' Lucht
said.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the companies will argue that long-distance as we know
it is disappearing and will soon be replaced by all-distance
pricing as consumers buy flat-rate bundles of local, long-distance,
wireless and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the Senate Judiciary and Commerce
committees, company officials have tried to portray the new
WorldCom as the best hope for a strong alternative to the
``mega-Bells,'' with their stranglehold over local telephone
markets, and the ``emerging AT&AMP;T cable monopoly,'' which that
company has assembled by buying national cable providers during the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a merger of monopoly providers,'' said John
Sidgmore, vice chairman of MCI WorldCom. ``This merger is being
done so we can become large enough to compete with the monopoly
powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups say that rationale is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``In theory, they'll face real competition in the future, but
they don't have it now,'' said James Love, director of the Consumer
Project on Technology. ``The current (long-distance) market share
of the Baby Bells is zippo, and they're the best hope against that
awesome competitive threat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should people trade in real competition today for a theory
about how there might be competition down the road? This is about
as plain and straight an example of a harmful merger that consumers
can imagine. It should be stopped. That's why we have antitrust
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Business users also take issue with almost every point the
companies offer. They say the vast bulk of long-distance carriers
are niche players, and the market is already an oligopoly, with
most carriers taking their pricing cues from the big three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the arguments that this is going to be good for
competition, and I think they're fairly specious,'' said Bruce
Thatcher of TelCon Associates, a Kansas City company that audits
telephone bills for companies and helps them negotiate contracts
with carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to get lower-priced service because of this. I
have not talked to a single telecom user who thinks this is a good
deal for them, and I've heard a lot of people cast doom and
gloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that trepidation, Thatcher said, is due to direct
experience with customer service problems after WorldCom's purchase
of MCI. Just as they surmount some of those problems, the combined
MCI WorldCom and Sprint will try to meld two vastly different
cultures and have a multiyear repetition of those issues, Thatcher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Big corporations also tend to divide their businesses among the
top two or three carriers. The disappearance of one of those
players will mean higher rates and less innovation in services,
businesses say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint has been quite innovative in introducing new pricing
plans,'' said Ruth Michalecki, director of telecommunications and
information services at the University of Nebraska and chairman of
the International Communications Association, which represents
business users.
</P>
<P>
   After the merger, she said, ``I don't think that consumers or
big users will have the opportunity to negotiate rates.''
</P>
<P>
   They also discount the notion that emerging carriers such as
Qwest Communications and Level 3 Communications can offer real
competition to AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the big three have the networks that can serve anybody,
anything, anywhere,'' Michalecki said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jeff Hafer, manager of telecommunications for GPU Energy in
Redding, Pa.: ``Not many Fortune 500 or Fortune 1000 companies take
the third-tier carriers seriously. Telecommunications is mission
critical. We're not willing to risk it to save a few dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the sole voices of support for the merger so far _
besides Wall Street _ comes from Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri, a
member of two key Senate committees, Judiciary and Commerce, that
will examine the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint happens to be the second-largest contributor to
Ashcroft's 2000 re-election campaign, having donated $22,000 by the
end of June, according to the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Senate Judiciary Committee held its hearings to
discuss the merger, Ashcroft announced that he had met with MCI
WorldCom Chief Executive Bernard Ebbers and was ``strongly inclined
to support the proposed merger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the most important question raised by the merger is
its impact now and in the future on Missouri and on Kansas City,''
Ashcroft said. ``In his discussion with me, Mr. Ebbers made it
clear that MCI WorldCom expects to deliver a substantial number of
new jobs to Kansas City over the next few years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
