<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-FBC-UW-1969-SPI &LR;      11-17 2084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UW-1969-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1969: HUSKIES YEAR OF TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Should first-year coach Rick Neuheisel ever feel the
pressures of the great University of Washington football monolith
gnawing at him, it would serve him well to consider the plight of
the 1969 Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Worlds collided, and everything was knocked off center.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, a ridiculous schedule was met with an
undesirable offense, exposing a glaring lack of talent for the
Huskies. As loss after loss piled up, a rigid coach clashed with
mildly rebellious players, leading to suspensions, protests,
boycotts, even death threats. Toss in a shredded ankle for the
team's All-America running back candidate, and one of the most
turbulent seasons of college football for Seattle emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Capping it off was the most miserable Apple Cup matchup on
record: 0-9 Washington hosting 1-8 Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those times were tough,'' said Lee Brock, a Huskies defensive
tackle and co-captain in '69. ``Everybody was getting killed back
then, Vietnam, Martin Luther King Jr., Bobby Kennedy. I don't think
a whole lot of people were focused on football, at least not like
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of blame and mistrust, a lot of
finger-pointing. People didn't like each other.''
</P>
<P>
   STARS
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Alex, Ralph Bayard, Harvey Blanks and Lamar Mills were the
objects of much hate and vile bile. Their names and mugshots would
be plastered across the front pages of Seattle's newspapers. They
were the Four Hoarse Men of Washington _ they spoke out and paid
dearly for it.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 30, 1969, these players were banished from the UW
program by longtime coach Jim Owens. Their crime? Failure to give
``100 percent commitment'' to Owens during hastily called
one-on-one meetings with the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question that was asked of me was, `Can you give loyalty
to me as an individual?' '' Bayard recalls. ``My response was that
`I was taught that that was something you have to earn and I've
seen some things I don't necessarily agree with.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fallout was certain after a 22-7 loss at Oregon, dropping
Washington to 0-6 for the first time in school history. Coaches
were looking to give players a jolt. Fullback Landy Harrell was
singled out, ordered to run stadium steps for fumbling twice
against the Ducks. Other players had coughed up the ball in that
game. Only Harrell, who was black, was punished.
</P>
<P>
   Players practiced and Harrell ran. Players went to dinner and
realized Harrell was not among them. He was still running steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in and changed (clothes) and, very honestly, we never
saw Landy again,'' Alex said of Harell, who would transfer to
Montana State.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's African American players, 13 strong among a squad
of 80, were so disturbed by the obvious sacrifice of Harrell that
they met privately and asked through an assistant coach to see
Owens.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of racism claims from the year before, Owens faced his
entire team the next day. He asked that anyone not committed to the
program stay in the locker room. Everyone stood up and went to
practice. Not satisfied, Owens demanded to meet with each player
out on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two long lines, like going into a movie,'' said
Brock, who is black. ``Everybody in line was asked if they were
loyal to the program. I said, `How could I not be, I'm captain of
this (bleep-bleep) team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mills, ``In those days, the coach was everything and the
athletes just blindly followed him. I thought that was stupid. I
said what I felt. I wasn't going to lie. Some of those guys lied.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens' demeanor never changed during the inquisition. But it was
clear four answers didn't sit right with him.
</P>
<P>
   The suspensions were relayed to reporters that afternoon. Bayard
heard about it from another student while walking across the
skybridge that connects the upper campus to Hec Edmundson Pavilion;
the others were in a car, headed for upper campus, listening to KJR
radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had come to get an education and play football,'' the
normally soft-spoken Bayard said. ``The last thing on my mind was
to get involved in anything controversial. We were all stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayard was a starting split end from San Francisco. Mills was a
reserve running back from Los Angeles. Alex was a defensive back
from Seattle, sidelined after suffering a concussion against
Michigan in the second game. Blanks was a breakaway runner from
Chicago, out since spring ball with a broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Their ouster stirred an already volatile atmosphere in town. If
debate over the Vietnam War, race relations and drug use weren't
enough, the normally stable yet now-divided UW football program had
everyone in a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, it seemed as if the 1969 Huskies had a death
wish hanging over them. They opened against Michigan State,
Michigan and Ohio State _ respectively the nation's sixth-ranked
team in preseason, the eventual Rose Bowl entry and the nation's
No. 1 club in the first polls. Washington was outscored 113-32 by
this trio.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies also tried to use the run-oriented wishbone offense,
not a fan or player favorite. It was a disaster. Washington didn't
score more than 14 points until the Apple Cup.
</P>
<P>
   All of it became secondary once the suspensions were meted out.
The next day, 200 protesters, black and white, blocked the path of
the Huskies charter bus bound for the airport, demanding that no
African American players accompany the team to UCLA. None did. In
Los Angeles, Owens suffered his worst defeat as UW coach at that
time, 57-14 to the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings were held. Lawyers were hired. UW faculty members
considered their own protest. The Huskies' lone African American
assistant coach, Carver Gayton, quit. Fights between black and
white students broke out during the next two games in Husky
Stadium. Owens' oldest daughter, Kathy, was stopped in her car by
four men, two black and two white, and had her hair pulled and was
slapped in the face. Owens' removal was demanded.
</P>
<P>
   The suspended players were not immune from community backlash,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents got threatening phone calls that said, `Your son
will be killed if he steps back on the field,' '' Alex recalled.
``I got a postcard in the athletic department from a guy who said
he had a high-powered rifle and if I stepped back into Husky
Stadium he would blow my head off. I'm trying to remember how he
signed it; maybe `a loyal Husky fan'?''
</P>
<P>
   A racist label was stuck on Owens, amid claims he either stacked
players at positions by race or didn't let blacks hold leadership
roles.
</P>
<P>
   Others argued that Owens, a former University of Oklahoma
All-American end, simply was too unbending to deal with the new
breed of athlete, that his militaristic coaching style, which had
been responsible for Rose Bowl victories in 1960 and '61 and for
returning UW football to prominence, had become outdated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any evidence of (racism) with me,'' Brock
said. ``But being originally from Oklahoma myself, Owens was the
way Okies are. They never had been exposed to black people like us.
He'd never seen a Harvey Blanks who was from Chicago and would step
into your face and say what he liked. I'm certain there were some
insensitivities on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gary Gayton, brother of Carver Gayton and an attorney who
represented some of the suspended players, ``I think Jim sincerely
thought he was doing the right thing, but times were changing. The
only thing I said is, `You're recruiting these kids from the ghetto
and you can't treat them the same as the others, like kids out of
Puyallup.' That was hard for Jim.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently about this tumultuous time, Owens spoke softly
and in measured tones. It was clear that he still believed what he
did with those players 30 years ago was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would hurt anyone to be misunderstood and not be able to
convey what we were trying to do to all the athletes on that
club,'' said Owens, now retired and living in Bigfork, Mont. ``Some
seemed to agree, some didn't. We were constantly trying to meet
somewhere in the middle and have some kind of accord, which we did
after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Compromise was reached before the Apple Cup. UW president
Charles Odegaard got involved and promised that football discipline
would be overhauled. There would be no more loyalty oaths at
practice. Any punishment would be subject to upper-campus review.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four suspended players were reinstated. Blanks was
not.
</P>
<P>
   According to teammates, the often-animated running back wouldn't
give in on someone else's terms. Instead, he made matters worse.
Blanks allegedly swore at Owens and challenged him to fight in
front of the team, committing insubordination that wouldn't be
overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted Owens to apologize publicly to him and the coach
wasn't going to do it,'' said Mark Hannah, a defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Others blamed Blanks' debilitating pain for getting in the way
of common sense. He had been a pro prospect, an honors candidate, a
showcase player. When his ankle snapped under the weight of a hard
tackle during spring ball, dreams were shattered as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he could have been as good anybody who ran the ball
out there, including Napoleon Kaufman,'' Brock said. ``The injury
was so devastating to Harvey it destroyed his soul. I'm sure that
was part of Harvey's frustration _ that he wouldn't ever be the
same again.''
</P>
<P>
   STARS
</P>
<P>
   In the '69 Apple Cup, the Huskies beat Washington State, 30-21,
with Bayard catching touchdown passes covering 62 and 11 yards.
Demonstrating how bad these teams were, they combined for just one
victory before their fearsome meeting _ the Cougars earning a 19-18
decision in their season opener over an Illinois team that would
finish 0-10. At no other time in the past 50 years have the state's
Pac-10 rivals combined for fewer than five victories entering a
season-ending game.
</P>
<P>
   As the Huskies and Cougars prepare for their 37th Apple Cup and
91st meeting overall on Saturday, Bayard ironically is right in the
middle of it. For the past seven years, he has served as the UW's
senior associate director for compliance. If there were suspensions
today similar to his, he might have a hand in the decision-making
process.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, there was opposition to Bayard's hiring among UW
alumni who still hadn't forgiven him for speaking up. He got the
job anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bayard has no regrets over what happened in 1969. If anything,
his actions helped integrate the football team and athletic
department to more acceptable levels, as well as humanize
coach-player relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being honest up front is going to get you in trouble, but I'll
stick with being honest and straightforward,'' Bayard said. ``If I
had to do it all over again. I'd do it the same way. Right is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayard and the three other players remain close today. Alex is a
Seattle minister and director of the Matt Talbott Center for the
Homeless. Mills is a Seattle attorney and deputy director of the
Northwest Defenders Association and is married to a judge. Blanks
played briefly in the now-defunct World Football League for a
Chicago team coached by Steve Spurrier, then turned to acting and
directing. He has appeared in movies, TV and most notably
Shakespearean theater, and bounces between Los Angeles and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only one who is down on the streets, where folks
probably thought all of us would end up,'' Alex said jokingly. ``We
were painted as being ungrateful and evil. We were the blight on
the purple fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Owens, ``I'm tickled to death all of the fellows are doing
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayard was the only one who played again for Owens, enjoying the
Huskies resurgence brought on the very next season by the Sonny
Sixkiller era. Years later, Alex sat and chatted easily with Owens
as they rode a bus to a UW Alumni-Varsity football game in the
Kingdome. Alex said he prayed for Owens when he heard he had
undergone surgery for a brain aneurysm in recent years. Word has it
that even Blanks and Owens eventually shook hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is tough and it's expensive,'' Alex said. ``If the
price wasn't exacted, I would hate to see where the program would
be today. It cost us something. We all know we'll never be in the
Husky Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
