<SLUG> BC-IMPACT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY LEADERS WANT TO IMPOSE IMPACT FEE ON NORTHLAND
DEVELOPERS TO PAY FOR ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE RICE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MIKE RICE Knight Ridder Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City leaders want to impose an impact
fee on Northland developers to help pay for new roads in the city's
fastest-growing sector.
</P>
<P>
   The fee, a popular funding mechanism in the West and in Florida,
would be levied on all new development to help pay for the capital
improvements needed to serve that development. The fee would vary
according to how much traffic a development generated.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council is expected to vote on the proposal shortly
after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents believe the fee could generate about $4 million
annually toward needed road construction and upgrades, estimated to
cost as much as $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Kansas City's growth is occurring north of the Missouri
River, but the road system is regarded by many to be inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The city has tried to address those road needs with sales tax
money and tax increment financing projects, but city leaders
believe developers need to pay more of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, developers with frontage on arterial streets must
construct the portion of the roadway adjacent to their project.
This policy has led some developers, who do not want to pay for
those costs, to leave their frontage undeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   The policy also has created a patchwork of improved and
unimproved street segments.
</P>
<P>
   Developers have attended meetings on the proposal, which has
been in the discussion stage since spring. The fee, they said, is
too high and could be cost-prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   But they are working with the city at modifying the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The fee would be based on the amount of peak-hour traffic that a
new development generated. Using a formula established by the
Institute of Traffic Engineers, the highest rates would be imposed
on banks with drive-through facilities, video-rental stores,
convenience stores that sell gasoline and fast-food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The rates for residential, office and industrial developments
would be less.
</P>
<P>
   The full fee would not be assessed until four years after the
fee's adoption. It would be assessed at 50 percent of the
designated amount the first year, 62.5 percent the second year, 75
percent the third year and 87.5 percent the fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   Developers would qualify for credits if they paid for or built
any arterial streets in the city 10 years before the fee's
adoption. And any developer would receive a refund if the city did
not spend the fee after seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Several cities in the metropolitan area have a development fee
in place. Overland Park, Kan., for instance, levies a
14.5-cent-per-square-foot excise tax _ about $6,300 an acre _ to
pay for thoroughfares whenever land is platted.
</P>
<P>
   Impact fees have been popular in suburban areas in states like
California, Florida and Arizona, where growth has been rapid and
taxpayer resistance to paying for infrastructure is common, said
James Duncan, an Austin, Texas-based consultant who is assisting
Kansas City on drawing up its fee proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what some might think, Duncan said, impact fees
stimulate growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one likes to shell out money,'' Duncan said, but he noted
that growth is not free. ``Cities have to pay for it somehow. The
federal and state grants that used to pay for these kinds of things
are not out there anymore. When Uncle Sam stops spoon-feeding you,
you have to stand on your own two feet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
