<SLUG> BC-ROADS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY TRAFFIC HEADING NOWHERE, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   City dwellers across the United States are increasingly stuck in
traffic, and it's costing them hundreds of dollars in extra travel
time and fuel, a study released Tuesday says.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Phoenix, land of the car and home of the perpetual
freeway-construction project, is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to increased time spent going nowhere, the
Valley of the Sun rates better than most, finishing 53rd out of 68
urban areas studied by the Texas Transportation Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Over a 15-year period, the time lost to road congestion in metro
Phoenix jumped 133 percent, the institute found in its annual
mobility report. That's a big increase, but a far cry from the
1,000 percent increase in Indianapolis or the 633 percent jump in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The report's release sparked a flurry of dueling news releases
by groups interested either in promoting or discouraging road
building.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Policy Project, which argues that the
nation can't build its way out of congestion, analyzed the
institute's figures and concluded that urban sprawl is what's
locking motorists in traffic. Sprawl makes people drive more, so a
nearly 1 million gain in population over the past 15 years actually
feels like 1.9 million new drivers, travelwise.
</P>
<P>
   The American Road &AMP; Transportation Builders Association had a
different spin on the study: Lack of road building is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyist group said that although the number of vehicle
miles traveled has increased 130 percent in 30 years, and
population and vehicle registrations have jumped by double digits,
new highway capacity has inched up only 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in between _ and behind the steering wheel _ are Valley
motorists such as Eliot Suied and Dave Matthews. Their views show
how traffic woes can be relative.
</P>
<P>
   To Suied, a three-year transplant from Orange County, Calif.,
who has plied the roads of Los Angeles; Washington, D.C.; and
Miami, ``traffic'' and ``congestion'' hardly belong in the same
sentence in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no comparison,'' Suied said. ``It's like
saying, `That third-grader hit me real hard,' vs. `Mike Tyson
smacked me in the mouth.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Matthews, who daily commutes 50 miles from Ahwatukee to
Central Avenue and Camelback Road and back, calls rush-hour traffic
``abysmal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the problem: too many cars for not enough road,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A while back, Matthews said, he would have prescribed more roads
as the solution. But no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic engineers say we open lane after lane and they
fill up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report added more gasoline to the fire raging over how
to reduce congestion. Researchers at the Texas Transportation
Institute say the road builders and the pro-transit crowd are both
right _ and both wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There is no single answer, study authors David Schrank and Tim
Lomax said. Rather, American cities need to build more roads,
encourage carpooling and boost transit.
</P>
<P>
   If road building alone were the answer, the cities they studied
would need to add 37 more lanes of roads and freeways just to keep
up with one year of higher traffic demand, the study's authors
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If carpooling were the only answer, the average city would
have to increase its annual number of carpool trips by at least
100,000 every year,'' they stated.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas study indicated that the average Phoenix driver in
1997 lost 35 hours a year stuck in traffic. That works out to about
45 minutes a workday.
</P>
<P>
   And traffic delays cost them $580 each in 1997, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers landed Phoenix in the middle of the pack. At the
top of the heap, the typical Los Angeles driver spent 82 hours
sitting in traffic in 1997, at a cost of $1,370 in wasted fuel and
extra travel time. &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at (602) 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
