<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-BLACKHAWKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HOLD ON TO BEAT BLACKHAWKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Andy Murray's mom called the other day and told
him just how good a job he was doing with the Los Angeles Kings.
Murray, the quintessential downplayer of great coaching jobs, shot
back with a quick retort.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom said, `Maybe you'll be Coach of the Year,''' Murray
said. ``I told her I just want to be coach for !ital!for!off! a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Murray's mom had a premonition. It's early, as Murray
reminds anyone who will listen, but in his first year with the
Kings, he's doing something no one thought possible: He's winning.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Jamie Storr's 36 saves, the Kings won their third
straight, holding on to beat the Chicago Blackhawks 3-2 in front of
12,980 Tuesday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   A win over the hapless Blackhawks isn't much to celebrate, but
it does show something. Past Kings teams lost to these teams.
Though this wasn't pretty, the Kings did win and are again atop the
NHL with the most points. Los Angeles, Detroit, Ottawa and Toronto
had 26 points entering the night, but only the Kings played, and
they have 28.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite looking at a 12-4-4 mark, which includes the
8-1-2 record in their last 11 games, Murray remains the worrywart
who fears the loss that can come at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid to lose, every game,'' Murray said. ``We have to
win these games. I don't know what the attitude was last year. All
I know is the players, to this point of the season, have
acknowledged how important each game is on each night.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the third-period collapse against Phoenix nearly a
month ago, when everyone bemoaned it being the same old club, the
Kings have been the suprise of the league. It's also that game the
Kings remember and which drives them on nights in which they play
teams like the Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   With a rematch with Phoenix up next and a season low in
attendance, the Kings jumped on Chicago early and didn't let up.
They took control with a pair of goals 38 seconds apart in the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings went ahead 1-0 when Vladimir Tsyplakov chipped the
rebound of Rob Blake's shot from the point past Chicago goalie
Steve Passmore at the 7:05 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles added to its lead on a pretty pass from Glen Murray
to Brian Smolinski. Murray had the puck along the left wing boards
and flipped to Smolinksi, who tipped it past Passmore for a 2-0
Kings lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings increased their lead to 3-0 midway through the second
period on Donald Audette's eighth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kings goalie Jamie Storr shut down the Blackhawks
offense until the 10:36 mark of the third period. Storr, looking
for the Kings' first shutout since opening night, stopped the first
27 shots he faced.
</P>
<P>
   However, that ended when Eric Daze corralled a loose puck at the
top of the crease, and despite partially fanning on the shot,
managed to squeak the puck through Storr's pads to pull Chicago to
within 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks made it 3-2 when Tony Amonte scored on the power
play with 58.8 seconds left. Amonte took a pass from Michael
Nylander at the left side of the net and banked in a shot off
Storr's back. It made the Blackhawks 1 for 8 on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Kings are 3-0-1 since first-stringer Stephane Fiset
was injured before the Edmonton game last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goaltending has been a strong point for our team all year,''
Murray said. ``It doesn't matter who's in there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
