<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAVS-HNS &LR;      11-17 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAVS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ The surprise was that when Steve Francis grabbed Dirk
Nowitzki and threw him to the floor, he hit it. It was the only
significant shot the Rockets connected on all night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francis earned a quick ejection and apparently took the Rockets'
defense and shooting touch with him. If the 0-5 start to the season
was frustrating, this might have been worse. At least then, the
Rockets were close.
</P>
<P>
   They fell to 2-7 by getting routed 114-95 by the Dallas
Mavericks on Tuesday night at Reunion Arena. And the Rockets could
be without Francis when they face the high-speed Sacramento Kings
on Thursday, still seeking their first win at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Francis would not comment on the incident, which occurred with
2:57 left in the second quarter. Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said he would leave it up to the league but added that nothing
Francis did should merit a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Official Don Vaden, however, indicated he saw a punch thrown,
which would bring an automatic suspension. Mavs officials said that
after reviewing tape, officials e-mailed a description of a punch
to Rod Thorn, NBA senior vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contact was unnecessary and excessive, which constitutes
the flagrant two,'' Vaden said. ``That first contact (when Francis
hammered Nowitzki on the arm on a breakaway) was unnecessary, and
the second one (tossing Nowitzki to the floor) was excessive. The
punch had nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said: ``I expect to have him, definitely. There was
no behavior that warrants a suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Rockets lost Francis for the remainder of
Tuesday's game, they were already in trouble, unable to slow the
Mavericks' break or to make the sort of shots they would like to
find every night.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a team that had beaten only the Magic and Warriors
(twice), the Rockets collected worsts like an 11-year-old hoarding
Pokemon cards.
</P>
<P>
   Against a Mavericks team that has been the fourth-worst in the
NBA in field-goal defense, the Rockets made just 34 of 92 shots (37
percent), their worst shooting night of the season. They matched
that with their worst free-throw shooting night, making just 22 of
35 free throws (62.9 percent).
</P>
<P>
   And they allowed more fast-break points than in any game this
season (37).
</P>
<P>
   ``You give up 37 points on fast breaks and can't make layups and
wide-open shots and free throws, that's what you get,'' Tomjanovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Rockets got the sort of shots they wanted,
Tomjanovich said: ``Layups. We were right on top of the basket. And
free throws. They must charge for them here in Dallas. We didn't
take advantage of the free ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley made just one of seven shots and was held to
seven points. After making his first five shots, Hakeem Olajuwon
made just one of his next five and had 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Drew, who played the rest of the night after Francis'
ejection, made just five of 18 shots to lead the team with 15
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just shot the ball horribly,'' Drew said. ``They all felt
good. They just didn't go in. I've never gotten better looks than
that. So many jumpers, pull-ups, things I normally make. Everything
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets' offense might not have been their greatest
problem. The Mavs beat them down the court from the outset. Michael
Finley and Cedric Ceballos repeatedly set up with good position in
transition.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Mavericks did not beat the Rockets on the break,
Robert Pack darted around screens to get in the lane or burn the
Rockets' rotations with passes.
</P>
<P>
   Finley had 28 points on 12-of-17 shooting to go with season
highs for rebounds (13) and assists (seven). Ceballos had 19 off
the bench. Pack had 10 of the Mavericks' season-best 29 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing playground ball,'' Barkley said. ``They
didn't want us to set up in the half-court set. They were just
getting it and running it down our throats. They were playing like
they were playing in a rec league. They were just running and
gunning tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to win for them that often. It worked against
us. But it worked better because Steve was out of the game. As well
as they played, they were only up six or seven points late in the
third quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, the Rockets began to fall apart in the third quarter,
almost duplicating the fourth-quarter collapse of the night before.
Trailing 64-58, the Rockets missed consecutive free throws, as they
had Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They then began clanging outside shots, as they had Monday. Drew
missed consecutive wide-open 3s. Barkley missed a jumper. Walt
Williams missed a layup.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Rockets moved on to turnovers, losing the ball
on three consecutive trips down the court.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs' Sean Rooks had a three-point play and Finley hit a
jumper to push the lead to 69-58. By the end of the quarter, the
Mavericks led by 13, had outscored the Rockets 34-2 on fast breaks
and were getting inside with ease. And all this was before the
nightly fourth-quarter offensive meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   That came quickly and predictably. The Rockets made just one of
their first nine shots and had two turnovers to begin the quarter.
By the time Barkley and Olajuwon got up to return to the game, the
Rockets were down by 20.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Thomas Hamilton drove for a lefthanded layup and the
first Rockets basket of the quarter, the Mavericks had pushed their
lead to 26 and Olajuwon and Barkley were back on the bench resting
for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And if Tomjanovich had not quite seen it all in nine games, he
knew he had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of things already in this short season. It's
enough already,'' he said with a chuckle. ``That's not the laugh of
something funny. That's a guy ready to be fitted for a
straitjacket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
