<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS COULD SEND VALDES TO BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers already pulled off the blockbuster
trade of the offseason, sending disgruntled outfielder Raul Mondesi
to Toronto for Shawn Green.
</P>
<P>
   They have now laid the groundwork for another high-profile deal
involving right-hander Ismael Valdes. Sources said the Dodgers and
Boston Red Sox are working on a deal to send Valdes to Boston for
pitcher Jin Ho Cho and infield prospect Adam Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Valdes' immense potential, the new Dodgers regime
believes the past rap on the 26-year-old. Valdes went 9-14 with a
3.98 ERA, but was criticized harshly by pitching coach Claude
Osteen for not being tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what a lot of teams are doing is just getting into
position for the winter meetings,'' said Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone, who won't talk about specific trades. ``I don't think
you'll see much until then.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the St. Louis Cardinals and Colorado Rockies pulled
off a seven-player deal that included two of the pitchers the
Dodgers eyed from the Cardinals, a deal that would include Dodgers
second baseman Eric Young is still possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals and Dodgers talked about either Manny Aybar or
Jose Jimenez in a deal for Young, but both were sent to Colorado as
part of a seven-player trade Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But sources said the Dodgers also would trade Young for one-time
Philadelphia closer Ricky Bottalico. He would fill one of the
Dodgers' top needs, a power pitcher in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had shown interest in making a multi-player trade
with the Dodgers that would also include Valdes, but after trading
for Pat Hentgen and now Darryl Kile, the Cardinals no longer are
actively pursuing starters, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers can move Young and Valdes, both considered
offseason priorities, they would cut nearly $11 million of payroll
for next season. Young is set to make $4.5 million in each of the
next two years, and Valdes is eligible for arbitration and likely
to make approximately $6 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It would drop the Dodgers' payroll to near the mid-$80 million
range.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it leaves them in an awkward situation if they lose third
baseman Adrian Beltre, whose agent, Scott Boras, petitioned the
commissioner's office to have Beltre declared a free agent. Boras
said the Dodgers signed Beltre when he was 15, a breach of Major
League Baseball rules.
</P>
<P>
   If Beltre is given free-agent status, it could leave a gaping
hole the Dodgers may be unable to fill. The commissioner's office
could also keep the Dodgers from negotiating with Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet you there's 50 ballplayers in the major leagues that
have signed illegally,'' Lasorda said during a news conference
honoring one of his former players, New York Mets manager Bobby
Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was done illegally, they gave the birth certificate to
us, which simply means that they knew that he wasn't the right
age,'' Lasorda said. ``Why should he be able to go out into the
world and make millions of dollars?''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing they may lose Beltre, the Dodgers have turned to free
agent and former Dodger Todd Zeile. Sources said Zeile's agent,
Seth Levinson, spoke with Malone and Dodgers chairman and CEO Bob
Daly numerous times Tuesday. But time and money is working against
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers can't afford to pay a huge contract, but Zeile is in
the market for one. The Van Nuys native and Thousand Oaks resident
is 34, and this could be his last big payday. After driving in more
than 90 runs in each of the past four seasons, and coming off a
year in which he hit .293 with 25 homers and 95 RBI for the Texas
Rangers and was paid $3.2 million, sources said it's unlikely he'll
sign for anything less $5 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   The same sources say Zeile is close to re-signing with the
Rangers, which could happen as early as today. It is believed to be
at least a three-year deal with an option for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: While most of the elite organizations eye Japanese closer
Kazuhiro Sasaki, the Dodgers can do nothing but scout him. As a
penalty for illegally signing two Cuban players, the Dodgers can't
sign a foreign player until January. But Sasaki may wait until the
New Year to sign.... With Dodger Stadium undergoing extensive
renovations, the club will soon announce its annual winter workouts
will be held at USC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
