<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC GIVES TOLEDO MORE AMMUNITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's rivalry week, and right on schedule, the war
of words has begun.
</P>
<P>
   USC free safety David Gibson, when asked about UCLA's eight-game
winning streak in the crosstown series, provided Bruins coach Bob
Toledo with one of his favorite pastimes: collecting bulletin board
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hate seeing Bob Toledo on the sideline with his arms
raised in the air,'' Gibson said. ``When I see UCLA, there's a
silent, cocky demeanor. I don't think they've had much class about
the streak. I have a strong dislike for UCLA. The
self-righteousness on that sideline gets to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can live with myself if I can't say I beat
UCLA, and it's a ninth loss in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also some disagreement between Toledo and USC coach
Paul Hackett regarding which team had more pressure on it going
into Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot more pressure on them than us. They have
got to stop the streak. We've had the streak,'' Toledo said. ``I
think there's so much pressure to `Stop the streak, Stop the
streak.' We'll just go out, have fun and try to keep the streak
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett seemed taken aback by the comments when informed of them
during Tuesday's press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? He doesn't mind being 4-7? That's a bunch of B.S.,''
Hackett said. ``I wonder if you polled the seniors if they felt the
same way. USC-UCLA is always pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to be the team that kept the streak going? Do you
want to be the team that couldn't keep streak going? Maybe there is
a little more pressure on the team that has to break the streak.
This is big. We've been waiting for this for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, Hackett added to his feelings on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob says it's all on us, great. This is not about Bob Toledo,
it's about USC and the senior class. We've been talking about it
for a year. It's a huge deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson on fans: Gibson also had some terse comments for USC's
fans, stating that the Trojans would be better than 4-6 this season
if there were larger crowds at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   USC's largest crowd this season has been 57,494, with a low of
43,795.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee this team would play better if we'd gotten
more support,'' Gibson said. ``It brings energy to have that
support. They're front-runners. When we're doing well, they'll be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knows the importance of this Saturday's game with the
above-mentioned fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating UCLA, as far as the alumni's standpoint would make
everything all right,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dumb question: Hackett should be applauded for keeping a
straight face when a reporter asked him if injured quarterback
Carson Palmer would redshirt this season. Or if he would play
against Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer had already been declared out for the season Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Football alumni banquet: The Trojan Football Alumni Club is
holding its 44th annual pre-UCLA fall banquet Thursday at the Grace
Simon Lodge in Elysian Park. Festivities begin at 6 p.m. and all
former football players are invited. Information: (310) 831-1255.
</P>
<P>
   Grain out: Offensive guard Jason Grain, who is recovering from
knee surgery, will not be available. Wide receiver R. Jay Soward
and tight end Antoine Harris, who have strained hamstrings, are
expected to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
