<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINN FINALLY SLIPS INTO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly five months after signing with the Kings,
Finnish defenseman Jere Karalahti arrived in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the question is when the 24-year-old will join the Kings.
Karalahti says he'd like to during the three-game homestand that
ends Saturday. Kings coach Andy Murray says there is no timetable.
General manager Dave Taylor said Karalahti will be with the Kings
beginning Thursday, but when he debuts is up to Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti plans to be on the ice with the Kings for the first
time during Thursday's morning skate. Whether he plays that night
against Phoenix is another issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to me,'' Karalahti said. ``If I play at my level and
play like I can play, I have a good chance to make the team. I'm
ready to play. It's a different hockey game here, but I don't think
it's going to be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever may be the case, the answer will begin to work itself
out today when Karalahti plays for the Kings' International League
affiliate in Long Beach. Murray and Taylor are expected to be in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for a player to get into the lineup,'' Murray said.
``He's a great European player. We have to see how he plays here.
It all depends on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti, a 6-foot-2, 210-pounder, spent parts of the last
seven seasons with IFK Helsinki of the Finnish Elite League. He
said he's in fine shape after playing this past weekend, though
fatigued after a 20-hour journey to the States.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, however, brought an end to a frustrating battle of red
tape. A few years ago, he was arrested for possession of drugs and
admitted to using. It made it difficult for him to obtain a work
visa, which he recently secured.
</P>
<P>
   But breaking into the Kings' lineup, considering how well
they've played, could be tough. Murray doesn't like to shake things
up, but when Karalahti plays, he's expected to add a physical
presence to the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a pretty good all-around game,'' Taylor said. ``He's
good on the power play, has a big shot. He's best described as
steady. He has a little bit of a physical edge, plays with a bit of
a bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset, Robitaille not close: Not that it matters as much since
Jamie Storr is playing so well, but goalie Stephane Fiset (right
hand contusion) may not be ready to return to the Kings until they
play in Colorado next Tuesday, if then.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Fiset was ``at least a week away, maybe longer,''
which could keep him out of the next four games. The Kings play
Colorado and Dallas on back-to-back nights before returning home to
play San Jose on Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, injured left winger Luc Robitaille (fractured left
foot) could still be three weeks away from returning despite being
off crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be the full six weeks,'' Murray said. ``I know
Luc was optimistic about it, but he's still three weeks away.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille's injury was detected Nov. 6, the same day it was
discovered center Jozef Stumpel (hernia) would miss two to three
months. Stumpel is slated to begin working out later this week, but
his return date remains the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
