A2231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-1STLD     11-17 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN ON MIDTOWN STREET IS HIT BY MAN WITH A BRICK
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout; adds byline)  
(sw) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 27-year-old woman returning from an office errand
was smashed in the head with a brick and left critically injured on
a bustling midtown sidewalk on Tuesday afternoon by a man who then
ran off, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Nicole Barrett of Queens, underwent two brain
surgeries at Bellevue Hospital Center on Tuesday night and was
expected to survive, one of her neurosurgeons said. A CAT scan of
Ms. Barrett's brain ``looked pretty good,'' said the surgeon, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they had no suspects in the attack, an
apparently random act that took place in front of a street full of
horrified witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett, a temporary worker on the last day of a job
assignment at Taylor Gray employment agency on East 42nd Street,
was walking at the corner of East 42nd and Madison Avenue about
3:10 p.m. when a man in his 40s walked up behind her, a law
enforcement official said.
</P>
<P>
   Without a word, the man brought a large gray paving stone down
on the back of her head, then ran north up Madison Avenue as Ms.
Barrett slumped to the ground unconscious, witnesses told the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who was black, about 5 feet 4 inches tall, with a white
beard and close-cropped hair, wearing a dark jacket and blue jeans,
turned west on 43rd Street and disappeared into the crowd,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett, a native of Athens, Texas, a town of about 15,000
an hour's drive southeast of Dallas, moved to New York City a year
and a half ago, a law enforcement official said.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor of her parents in Athens said that they planned to
catch a 6 a.m. flight from Dallas on Wednesday morning to be with
their daughter. The neighbor, Joyce Barrett, who is not related to
Nicole's family, said that Nicole's mother, Sharon, was concerned
but hopeful. ``She was upset, but she was pretty calm,'' Joyce
Barrett said. ``She's kind of nervous and wringing her hands. I'm
surprised she's even functioning at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack against Nicole Barrett was a reminder of just how
senselessly violent life in New York City can still be despite a
decrease in crime in recent years. It brought to mind other attacks
in public places like the death earlier this year of Kendra
Webdale, who was standing on a subway platform when a mentally ill
man pushed her in front of a train.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rhyme or reason to this,'' said a man who described
himself as Ms. Barrett's boyfriend, but would not identify himself.
He and several friends visited her at the hospital for several
hours on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear last night if anyone on the street had tried to
stop Ms. Barrett's attacker. A man working in a newsstand a few
feet away said he heard a commotion and ambulances but did not
leave his perch to see what was the matter. ``We don't look out
from here,'' said the man, who would not give his name. ``The
moment we look out, people start taking things. Our business is in
here. Not out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
