<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-HERMOSILLO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERMOSILLO HAS DECISIONS TO MAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Carlos Hermosillo has been all smiles this
week. He's shaking hands, posing for pictures and is usually the
last to leave training.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's savoring every minute before Sunday's Major League
Soccer championship match against D.C. United in Foxboro, Mass.,
because he's ready to leave the Los Angeles Galaxy and finish his
career in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo is only 34 goals shy of becoming Mexico's scoring
champion and, at age 35, playing in two leagues could hurt his
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are various aspects going into my decision,'' Hermosillo
said. ``My train of thought is that I'll never stop wanting to play
here. But obviously, I have to make a decision with my goals in
Mexico and breaking the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now is not the time to talk about it. We're trying to win
a championship. After the game, I'll start thinking about my
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be another factor to explain Hermosillo's relaxed
demeanor. He is peaking. After going through a period in which he
scored just two goals in 10 games, Hermosillo scored three in the
Western Conference finals against Dallas to become the Galaxy's
playoff scoring leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``His confidence is certainly back because he's getting goals,''
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said. ``The thing he's really done so
superbly over the last few games is just his work rate. That's
where the goals are coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also helped us defend and, as a result of that, he puts
our team in a better position when we're regaining the ball, which
is going to make it easier for him to score goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also been invaluable because of his big-game experience.
He's been in these kind of battles and championship games.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo admitted that his confidence was rattled heading into
the playoffs. But now, that problem has been solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lost confidence in myself and the league, being the top
goal scorer in Mexico but having trouble here,'' Hermosillo said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, Hermosillo is respected much like Michael Jordan or
John Elway were here. But in MLS, he had been in a rut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only human,'' Hermosillo said. ``It's nice to have that
human contact, to have someone saying you're doing a great job
again. It has helped my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The pace of the game has been Hermosillo's biggest adjustment.
In Mexico, he's a post-up target, where the team focuses on getting
him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   With the Galaxy, he's just another piece on the front-line with
speedsters Cobi Jones and Clint Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasized trying to get him the ball around the 18
(yard-line), but it wasn't like we set up practices specifically
for that,'' Schmid said. ``The service guys have been finding him,
but they're finding him because he's been far more active lately.
His activity level has helped more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Dallas series, Hermosillo was working both sides of the
field, hurrying to get in scoring positions. Two of his goals were
opportunistic; he was in the right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All great strikers in the world go through ebbs and flows like
that, and it can be frustrating,'' Schmid said. ``If strikers don't
get goals, everybody looks at them very critically. And when they
get goals, they're playing with a lot of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big mind game that they have to figure out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo has done that. Now, he just has to figure out whether
to return to the Galaxy next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
