<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 03:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     11-17 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NOTES FROM THE UNDERGROUND  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The stuff people have in their basements ...
</P>
<P>
   Some folks have electric trains. Joseph Omran has the city's
first cable car operation in his basement, or at least the ghost of
the cable cars.
</P>
<P>
   Omran owns Le Beau Market at Clay and Leavenworth, atop Nob
Hill. The store's basement, or a corner of it, was the powerhouse
for Andrew Hallidie's first cable car line, the Clay Street Hill
Railroad. It opened for business Sept. 1, 1873, and ran for 18
years.
</P>
<P>
   Omran shows me the cavern-like powerhouse with the original
brick vaulted ceiling, iron pillars and glass skylights and
windows. This is where the big steel wheels cranked the fabled
cables that pulled Mr. Hallidie's crazy little cars up Nob Hill
from Kearny Street, changing forever the character of the city and
jump-starting Tony Bennett's singing career.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't the Beatles get started here?
</P>
<P>
   GRAYBAR HOTEL: In the basement of the Ramada Plaza Hotel, on
Market Street just across from Civic Center Plaza, a hotel
executive wraps his arms around a brace of lockers in the employee
locker room, pulls them away from the wall and exposes a locked
door, unopened in years. Behind it is a slice of San Francisco's
past.
</P>
<P>
   It's the city jail from the earthquake days. The '06 Quake
disabled City Hall, so the government was sort of homeless until
1911, when the owners of the Whitcomb Hotel (now the Ramada), then
under construction, offered use of the building as a temp City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   What is now the Ramada's lost-and-found locker was the vault
housing San Francisco's treasury. Much of the Whitcomb's basement
became the city jail for five years. Two dark, windowless (duh,
it's the basement) cells remain, the chrome bars still shiny in the
beam of a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   No glamour slammer for S.F. in those days. And I hear the room
service sucked.
</P>
<P>
   I DON'T KNOW what's in the basement of Tommy's Joynt, Van Ness
at Geary, but I suspect that's where they keep the herd of buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Joynt was born in '47 and is still the only place in town
that serves buffalo stew and buffalo chili. And I mean from the
buffalo, not from Buffalo, as in Buffalo wings. Tommy's buffalo
don't fly or cluck.
</P>
<P>
   The place has atmosphere. Objects dangling from the ceiling
include a pi &LR; n &LR; ata and a hockey stick from the Denver Invaders,
'63-64. I'm not sure if that was a hockey team or a convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best deal in town,'' enthuses Mr. Eat, my erstwhile
pseudo-foodie and fine-dining dilettante, ``is this frosty 12-ounce
mug of beer and giant double-yolk hard-boiled egg for $2.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wipe the foam off your nose, Eat,'' I reply.
</P>
<P>
   THE OLD JOINTS, if not the old Joynt, are fading fast.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not a personal medical complaint. New Joe's, on Geary
just a meatball's throw from Union Square, shut down recently.
</P>
<P>
   Same old story: Skyrocketing rent. I hear Joe's was paying
$22,000 and was facing a very stiff hike. So it took one.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful ethnic hand-gestures were exchanged, and a bit of the
old city went bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   A NEAR-DEATH dining experience: Trihack, the bon vivant cabbie,
alerts me that Harry Denton's restaurant hangs by a thread. Not
long ago at Harry's, on Steuart in the newly hip Embarcadero 'hood,
you needed a shoehorn and crowbar to get through the groovy people
in the jazz bar to a table for a superb meal.
</P>
<P>
   Now Harry's is open for continental breakfast only, and I'm not
sure which continent. A week from now, who knows, you'll walk past
and the place will be a hip little Starbucks/ Rite Aid/BofA.
</P>
<P>
   YOU WANT good news? Okay, after vandals did a major graffiti job
on the monument to the WWII cruiser San Francisco, the Land's End
park maintenance crew worked like dogs and cleaned up the mess in
about one day.
</P>
<P>
   If the paint-wielding cretins are ever caught, give 'em spray
cans and a wall and have them write 100 times the names of the 100
sailors and Marines who died on that ship 59 years ago off
Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF old ships with bad luck:
</P>
<P>
   In 1857, the Central America picked up a big load of
Forty-Niner-mined gold in Panama, headed for New York and ran into
a hurricane. The ship went down with 425 passengers and crew.
</P>
<P>
   The sunken treasure was salvaged 10 years ago, and now about 400
pounds of bars, dust and coins from the cache will be auctioned,
after being displayed today through Friday at Union Bank of Calif.
on California St.
</P>
<P>
   I'd get into the bidding, but I've got plenty of those coins,
collected over the years from hotel pillows.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THE DEAL, wonders Jeff Gillenkirk, with the ad in this
paper's ``Death Notices'' section, for ``Bay Area resales _ Plots,
crypts''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like the housing crisis is spreading,'' Gillenkirk says.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ammiano's next crusade: Rent control for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   OK, no more cryptic comments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 0347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
