</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-RANGES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE COSTLY CLEANUP ON THE HORIZON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Defense Department struggles to keep up with billions of
dollars of cleanup work at military bases across the country,
another problem is looming that could end up being more expensive
than the combined cost of every environmental cleanup program the
government has under way.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50 million acres of land in the United States have
been used as bombing and target ranges by the military. Cleaning up
just five percent of the land would cost $15 billion, according to
the Defense Science Board, a Pentagon advisory group.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potentially massive liability, the Defense
Department has moved slowly on the issue. In an audit this year,
the General Services Administration cited the failure to account
for training-range and weapons-system cleanups as a serious
deficiency. It said the undisclosed liability was ``likely to be an
additional tens of billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the military is spending $51 million a year to clean
up training ranges. The total Pentagon environmental budget is $3.5
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Several internal Environmental Protection Agency documents warn
of the huge cost of cleaning the ranges.
</P>
<P>
   ``In summary, as measured by acres, and probably as measured by
number of sites, ranges and buried munitions represent the largest
cleanup program in the US,'' wrote Ken Shuster, the EPA's expert on
military range waste.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA and military have been haggling for five years over a
``range rule'' that would govern the cleanup of training ranges.
Gary Vest, the principal assistant deputy underecretary of defense
for environmental security, said he expected the plan to be
finalized by next summer. Vest added that the cost of the work will
be ``pretty substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   In an April letter, Timothy Fields Jr., an EPA assistant
administrator, urged the military's top environmental official,
Deputy Undersecretary of Defense Sherri W. Goodman, to move faster
on creating a cleanup plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the last several years, EPA has become increasingly
concerned with the (unexploded bombs) and hazardous chemical
contamination situations at military ranges nationwide,'' wrote
Fields. ``For many reasons, it appears that closed, transferred,
and transferring military ranges are not being adequately addressed
in a manner consistent with accepted environmental or explosive
safety standards and practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the EPA said it found evidence that the National
Guard training range at the Massachusetts Military Reservation on
Cape Cod was significantly contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Petroleum byproducts from missiles and heavy metals contained in
bombs and bullets threaten soil and ground water at many ranges.
There is also the danger posed by unexploded ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   Some ranges were used as burial sites for hazardous waste and
excess munitions. In addition, the military still burns munitions
waste and excess fuel in open pits across the country. The practice
is allowed because the facilities were exempted when laws were
passed in the 1980s governing the disposal of hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
   Fields, in a second internal document, listed other examples of
problems at ranges, including:
</P>
<P>
   --The military failing to clean up property contaminated with
unexploded ordnance before transferring it to private parties or
other government agencies. At the Tobyhanna Army Depot in
Pennsylvania, a 20,000-acre area used as a range is now a state
park. The park was closed in 1997 when 53 unexploded 37mm shells
were found.
</P>
<P>
   --Poor regulatory oversight of unexploded ordnance removal. A
scrap-yard worker in California was killed in 1997 when he cut into
an antitank shell he thought was inactive. The piece was one of 55
explosive shells mistakenly shipped to the scrapyard by workers at
the Army's Fort Irwin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
