<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-FUDS-B     11-17 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-FUDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAIN LAND PURCHASE PROVES COSTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the federal government offered to sell 78 acres of land to
the rural community of Marion, Ohio, in the late 1950s, everyone
agreed the dollar-an-acre asking price was a bargain. The city used
the land to build a sprawling school complex that was the envy of
neighboring communities, and in 1963, the first graduates marched
out of the new River Valley High School.
</P>
<P>
   But today, there are fewer positive feelings in town about the
school. Many of the River Valley graduates are sick with leukemia
and other cancers. Several have died.
</P>
<P>
   After health officials began investigating the cancer cases two
years ago, the residents of Marion learned for the first time that
they unknowingly built their school on top of a former US Army
dumpsite filled with toxic waste.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of communities across the country had done the same
thing as Marion, buying land on the cheap from the military in the
decades following World War II. It is only in the past few years,
however, that many new owners of the surplus military property have
realized what is buried on their land.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio officials have determined that at least 11 other schools
were built on military sites and that four of the sites need to be
cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, there are more than 500 sites formerly used by
the military which are now private property. And, as in Ohio,
officials here are finding problems. Several hundred of the
Massachusetts sites need some sort of environmental action, ranging
from simple evaluations to costly removal projects, but a lack of
federal funding results in only a few a year being cleaned up, said
Anne Malewicz, the federal facilities section chief for the state
Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, funding for the US Army Corps of
Engineers to identify and remove hazardous waste from former
military sites in Massachusetts has been cut from $10 million a
year to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funding problem is narrowing the priority list at a time
when we are looking at problems out there and thinking the list
should be expanded,'' said Mark Begley, the director of the
Division of Response and Remediation for the state Bureau of Waste
Site Cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Begley said sites that need to be cleaned up in Massachusetts
are contaminated with asbestos, PCBs, lead paint, leaking oil
tanks, old bombs, and chemical solvents.
</P>
<P>
   Two sites in the state that need action, but are not receiving
any, are located in the South Shore town of Hingham.
</P>
<P>
   At Wompatuck State Park, officials suspect a former military
burn pit may be contaminated with heavy metals and unexploded
ordnance. Grass has not grown on the site for 40 years. In the
Beals Cove area, remnants of bombs have been spotted on an
embankment and high concentrations of lead and copper have been
found in a nearby public recreation area.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 9,000 sites _ called Formerly Used Defense
Sites, or FUDS, by the military _ across the country that were sold
off after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are places where people are already living, working,
playing, and going to school,'' said Lenny Siegal, director of the
Center for Public Environmental Oversight, an advocacy group.
``They were transferred before people knew what hazards existed
there. It's not just the military's fault. No one paid much
attention to these kinds of problems in the '60s and '70s.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers has declared many of these sites to
be in need of no further cleanup action. But state environmental
officials have begun their own checks of the properties. Last year,
six states said they found contamination at half of the sites that
the Corps said needed no more action.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Corps clarified the no-further-action
classification, telling states that if they find problems on these
sites, it will consider doing cleanup work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, the number of leukemia cases among River Valley
graduates is five times higher than what would be expected,
according to state and federal health officials. The finding
prompted an investigation of the school property, located on the
edge of town in an area rich with cornfields.
</P>
<P>
   A review of town records and old aerial photographs revealed
that the school complex was built on a former Army vehicle depot
and dumping area, and a camp for prisoners during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In the soil and water, investigators found byproducts from the
dumping. Arsenic, used to delouse prisoners, was found in the soil
at a level 23 times what is typically found elsewhere in Ohio.
Metals were found in the water at unhealthy levels. And the school
and a neighboring property were contaminated with
trichloroethylene, a chemical suspected of causing cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Huge fences were quickly erected around 10 acres of playing
fields and 1,350 tons of soil was trucked away. Today, the testing
continues and scientists and public health officials are trying to
confirm the cause of the leukemia cases.
</P>
<P>
   There is both resentment and anger in Marion over the discovery
at River Valley. ``The government sold us a bill of goods,'' said
Don Millard, the owner of a local appliance store and the father of
a River Valley graduate with cancer. ``We have a deed saying this
land was unused, and now we find out it was a chemical dump.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tolnar, who graduated from River Valley in 1982, has no
doubt her leukemia was caused by the chemicals now being discovered
on the school grounds. Tolnar underwent a grueling bone marrow
transplant and massive amounts of chemotherapy in 1993, just six
months after she was married. The process saved her life, but left
her physically beaten and unable to have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never run again. I don't have a good knee or ankle. I
will never know what my child looks like,'' she said. ``All of
those things were taken away from me because I went to a school
that had chemicals in its land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2367 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-DEVILL     11-17 1868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-DEVILLARS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATOR'S INTERVENTION DENOUNCED AS FAVORITISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the Boston office of the Environmental Protection
Administration told the officers of Cape Cod Hospital in April 1996
that it was starting an enforcement action against the facility,
the hospital turned to the state's congressional delegation for
help.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA had accused the Hyannis hospital of illegally converting
wetlands it owned into cranberry bogs, thereby violating federal
laws. The potential penalty was stiff _ a six-figure fine, plus
costly restoration of the wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   But with help from local congressmen, the hospital was able to
make its case to John DeVillars, the EPA's regional administrator.
DeVillars drove to the hospital to personally inspect the property
and kept close tabs on the case, EPA records indicate. In the end,
the hospital did not have to pay a fine, despite firm and repeated
assertions by the EPA enforcement staff that a cash penalty was
warranted.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has strong policies to prevent the appearance of
favoritism in enforcement cases, but in the Cape Cod Hospital
matter, at least two of those rules appear to have been violated.
</P>
<P>
   Some enforcement staffers complain that DeVillars has
compromised the agency by intervening in cases of interest to
congressmen and questioning the actions of staff after a political
inquiry. They said those actions undermine the agency's credibility
and create the perception that complaining to DeVillars can
influence enforcement outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars acknowledged examining cases of interest to
politicians, saying if any member of Congress calls, ``I take a
personal interest.'' But he strongly denied showing favoritism
toward any party in an enforcement case, or violating EPA rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of cases where congressmen have called me where
they had clear concerns about what the agency does and where we
have stuck to our guns or took stronger stands is a very long
list,'' he said. ``So the fact a congressmen calls does not by
definition mean the outcome of the case will change and at no time
has a call resulted in any lessening of the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars said he has bucked political pressure in several
high-profile cases, most notably at the Massachusetts Military
Reservation on upper Cape Cod, where he has won praise from
residents and environmentalists for pushing the Pentagon to clean
up the site.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a survey of New England EPA enforcement personnel
last year done by Public Employees for Environmental
Responsibility, a Washington group representing federal
environmental employees, more than half of the 40 respondents said
violators received preferential treatment after contacting
DeVillars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that was most disconcerting was that the business
community perceives it as well,'' said Jeffrey Ruch, the PEER
executive director. ``They know they can go to the local regional
administrator or a congressman and get a better deal cut.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars angrily denounces the criticism by PEER as uninformed
and unfair, and several local environmental groups have come to his
defense, praising his enforcement record. EPA chief Carol Browner
has also backed DeVillars.
</P>
<P>
   But the hospital matter is one example of how a political
contact to DeVillars changed the complexion of a case.
</P>
<P>
   The demands of congressional aides on behalf of the hospital
played an important role in internal discussions about the case,
according to EPA records, including some the agency has refused to
release. Congressional aides also were invited to EPA offices in
Boston to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Portions of publicly released records related to the case were
deleted by EPA lawyers, who said the law allowed documents related
to decision-making and attorney-client communication to be removed.
Some of the passages contain critical remarks of DeVillars and his
actions in the case and make reference to congressional
interference, according to original copies of the records.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Cape Cod Hospital, the facility enlisted the help
of Mark Forest, an aide to US Representative William Delahunt, a
Quincy Democrat, and prior to that, US Representative Gerry Studds,
who left Congress in 1996. US Senator John F. Kerry also sent a
letter to DeVillars, asking that the action be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   In memos to DeVillars, EPA enforcement lawyers and wetlands
experts working on the case charged that the hospital's contractor
had illegally filled 20 acres of wetlands without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Mark Stein, the lead attorney for the EPA, wrote the
hospital, saying a settlement of the case would be considered with
a significant monetary penalty and restoration of the wetlands.
Later that month, the enforcement staff wrote a memo saying the
fine should be $94,768.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars, meanwhile, made handwritten requests for updates in
the margins of memos discussing the political interest in the case.
</P>
<P>
   What the congressional aides made clear was that a fine was
unacceptable. In another deleted passage, the EPA's congressional
liaison sent a message to the enforcement staff saying Forest
considered the penalty issue ``paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   For several months, the enforcement staff attempted to negotiate
a settlement with the hospital. In February 1997, the staff
recommended issuing an order to the hospital to pay a fine and
restore the wetlands. It was signed by then-enforcement chief
Harley Laing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DeVillars told the staff to continue negotiating and on
April 1, 1997, the hospital signed an agreement that did not
include a fine but did require it to restore the damaged wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   As the case was being negotiated, the EPA kept congressional
aide Forest updated, communication which appears to violate agency
policies prohibiting staff from ``sharing information about
enforcement investigations, negotiations, litigation, or settlement
strategy or tactics with members (of Congress), their staff, or
other outside parties.''
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to Laing two weeks before the case was settled, EPA
congressional liaison Al Frezza wrote: ``I contacted Mark Forest of
Delahunt's staff and told him the EPA was hopeful the CCH case
would be resolved by the end of the month. . .and that there would
be no penalty. I offered to provide him with more specific
details.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars and his staff said the information provided to Forest
does not violate agency policy, saying they would have provided the
same information to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Forest said he contacted DeVillars because the hospital believed
it was convicted without a hearing. When asked if DeVillars
influenced the decision not to issue a penalty, Forest said, ``I
would like to think the hospital made (its) case.''
</P>
<P>
   In a final move, which also appears to violate EPA policy,
records indicate the Boston office brokered the contents of a press
release with the hospital. The EPA prohibits negotiation of any
terms of enforcement press releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was under the impression that any release, if one did occur,
would be innocuous to the hospital,'' the hospital's lawyer wrote
after reviewing the EPA's proposed press release. Records indicate
several changes were made to the release, including the addition of
comments praising the hospital, after the lawyer complained and
sent back proposed revisions.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Lubber, the assistant EPA regional administrator, said
that in rare instances the agency shares press releases with the
subjects of enforcement action before they are released. She
denied, however, that the contents were negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars and Laing insisted that congressional interest had no
bearing on the decision not to issue a fine, saying the decision
was ultimately made by the case team.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in an interview recently why no fine was issued, Stein
said: ``It was a very close call, but the call got made.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyla Bennett, who was coordinator of wetlands enforcement at the
time, said she agreed to drop a fine from the setttlement after
superiors said they would not support one. ``We agreed like the
people on the Titanic agreed the boat was going down,'' she said.
``I felt I had no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of Cape Cod Hospital is not the only one where members
of Congress intervened. More recently, US Representative Joseph
Moakley, a Democrat from South Boston who is credited with helping
DeVillars win his appointment as regional EPA administrator,
contacted DeVillars on behalf of campaign supporters accused of
filling wetlands to build a parking lot at the North Stoughton
Industrial Park.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars took an immediate and active role in the case,
according to agency records, overruling his enforcement team's
recommendation, which included ordering the property owner to rip
up a parking lot and restore the destroyed wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   The building owners, the consultant to the building owner, and
several Reebok executives _ whose corporate headquarters are on the
site _ were campaign contributors of Moakley's. The congressman and
DeVillars discussed the case on at least three occasions. In
addition, Moakley aide Joseph Moynihan was in frequent contact with
the EPA on the case.
</P>
<P>
   At several points, according to enforcement staff, it appeared
Moakley's office was provided confidential information, in
violation of EPA policy. A case lawyer noted in the file that she
was told by the EPA's congressional liaison that Moynihan indicated
things were ``going in the right direction'' regarding the case,
even though the EPA had yet to formally tell the property owner
what it proposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars pushed his top enforcement officials to change their
recommendation on the case and develop a plan to create new
wetlands and leave the parking lot untouched. Even though this
proposal ran contrary to EPA policy for wetlands cases, DeVillars
said he thought his approach would result in a better environmental
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the building owner determined it would be cheaper to
agree to what the case team originally wanted _ rip up the parking
lot and restore the wetlands _ than the DeVillars proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A Moakley spokeswoman, Karin Walser, said Moakley simply asked
DeVillars to take a look at the case. ``Joe Moakley's feeling is a
lot of times when we call it doesn't change the outcome, but
hastens it a little bit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars, who announced last week he would soon leave the EPA
for the private sector, conceded it is unlikely he would have
become involved in the Stoughton case if not for Moakley's
interest. But he rejected any suggestion he did Moakley's bidding
in the matter. He said his only motivation was to ensure the best
possible environmental outcome. He cited the property owner's
decision to agree to the original proposal because it was cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is it is such a humdinger of a proposal they
chose not to accept it,'' DeVillars said. ``I don't see what the
big deal is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
