   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ In an opening that would be the
envy of a New York gallery, Mexico's ruling party held a glittery
art exhibit on the eve of its first-ever primary to select the
party's presidential nominee. ``The Art of Doing Politics'' raised
money to finance the Institutional Revolutionary Party as it heads
to the presidential election in 2000. The message was: Here is the
new PRI, the democratic PRI, the transparent PRI that is openly
raising money for what promises to be a tight, closely watched
presidential race. By SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (''a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-ABDUCTION (Laredo, Texas) _ Hundreds of children trapped
in custody battles between their immigrant parents end up in
Mexico, U.S. officials say. And a congressional report to be
release next year finds that Mexico is among the countries least
likely to comply with an international agreement for the return of
abducted children. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIPPIE-FASHION (San Antonio) _ Call it neo-hippie chic. Call it
Bohemian. Call it a backlash against boredom. Bohemian dressing
stands in sharp contrast to the plain styles that have dominated
the fashion scene for many years. Forget tailored blazers and
basic-black T-shirts. We want color, and we want embellishments
such as embroidery, feathers and fake fur to crank up the wardrobe
volume. By ROSE MARY BUDGE.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY-PERIODS (San Antonio) _ She still plays with dolls and
likes to hear bedtime stories, but your little girl is growing up,
maybe faster than you think. In the United States, average age
girls begin to menstruate is 12.5. However, girls may start as
early as age 9, catching parents _ and the girls themselves _ off
guard. It is not unusual for girls in third or fourth grade to get
their menstrual periods, says Judy Robinson, director of the
National Association of School Nurses. By ELDA SILVA.
</P>
