u a BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-III-AR     11-17 1708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-III-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENFORCEMENT IS LAX, RANDOM 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Enforcement of the nation's environmental laws is
often haphazard and lax, creating a system where major polluters
can operate with little fear of being caught or punished, according
to court and enforcement records.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration has promoted the notion of an
environment-friendly presidency, and federal agencies have
trumpeted record-breaking fines against polluters, some enforcement
officials on the front line say they are losing the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton people have gutted environmental enforcement,''
said Gregory Sasse, a federal prosecutor in Cleveland with 13 years
of experience pursuing polluters. ``It is not a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Larger companies, particularly those with political muscle, are
often treated differently than smaller businesses that lack legal
resources and clout, according to some prosecutors and
environmental watchdogs.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental enforcement in the United States is so uneven that
whether or not a company or individual is prosecuted by the federal
government for polluting is largely a factor of where it does
business, according to an analysis of seven years of records for
every federal court district in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In eastern North Carolina, for instance, the US attorney did not
prosecute a single company or person for an environmental offense
from 1992 through 1998, the last year for which records are
available. Federal prosecutors in Maryland, by comparison,
prosecuted 42 environmental cases in 1998 alone.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has among the most anemic enforcement records in
the country, according to federal criminal prosecution data and
internal records of the Environmental Protection Agency. In
addition, records indicate that John DeVillars, the EPA
administrator for New England, has become personally involved in
cases where members of Congress or their staff have lobbied the
agency to soften enforcement action against corporate polluters.
</P>
<P>
   In at least two cases, the New England EPA appears to have
violated agency rules designed to prevent the appearance of
favoritism in enforcement cases. The regional agency has also
embraced a national movement to combine enforcement with
``compliance assistance,'' a program whereby it tells companies
what they should be doing and allows them to voluntarily fix
pollution problems to avoid penalties.
</P>
<P>
   It is a controversial approach that critics say coddles
polluters and sends a message that enforcing environmental laws is
not a priority. In addition, businesses can reap the economic
benefits of polluting for many years, and not have to pay a price
for breaking the law in the past.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars and top officials in the Clinton administration,
however, say the new approach results in more businesses improving
their environmental performance. In addition, they say compliance
assistance is not replacing traditional enforcement, but is being
offered in concert with tough sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard criticism from those who believe compliance
assistance is tantamount to not enforcing. I think that is a false
criticism,'' said Sylvia Lowrance, the EPA's deputy assistant
administrator for enforcement. ``Our view is a strong enforcement
base is absolutely essential. What incentive is there if you don't
have the deterrent backup of a strong enforcement program?''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America, however, appears unconvinced that the
government is taking a tough line on enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's largest environmental consulting companies,
the International Technology Corporation of Pennsylvania, said
government enforcement of environmental laws is so lax that the
firm's business is being hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand for the company's services is heavily influenced by the
level of enforcement of environmental laws and regulations,''
according to the company's 1997 annual report. ``During the 1990s,
spending by commercial clients has slowed primarily due to reduced
implementation and enforcement activities by governmental
regulatory authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   In its 1998 annual report, the company again cited weakening
enforcement by federal, state, and local regulators. Environmental
decisions by private industry in the United States, the company
said, are now driven by economic concerns and not regulatory or
legal ones.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to policing the country's polluters, the
environmental cop is not walking the beat, said Michael Casey of
the Environmental Working Group, a nonprofit organization in
Washington that studies environmental enforcement data.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson here is if you are a big, politically-connected
polluter, you can endanger public safety and health with
impunity,'' he said. ``Environmental crime pays.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EPA disregards key law
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When discussing its environmental record, the White House points
to a three-page-long list of accomplishments _ from a $1.5 billion
plan to restore the Florida Everglades to the approval of tougher
clean-air standards.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even when highlighting its achievements in a White House
paper called ``Protecting our Environment and Public Health,'' the
Clinton administration strikes a cautionary note:
</P>
<P>
   ``A third of us still breathe unhealthy air, and 40 percent of
our waterways are still too polluted for fishing and swimming.
Development threatens open space and environmentally sensitive
lands, and global warming threatens the stability of the earth's
climate.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's own report of enforcement efforts last year highlights
the continuing disregard of several key environmental laws. The
agency reported that:
</P>
<P>
   --Approximately 20 percent of the nation's incinerators and
landfills are in significant noncompliance with hazardous waste
laws.
</P>
<P>
   --One in four drinking water systems in the nation is in
violation of public health standards.
</P>
<P>
   --Half of the country's wastewater treatment facilities failed
to comply with clean-water laws during at least one-quarter of
fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of a battery of environmental laws in the past 30
years was supposed to solve many of those problems. However, many
of the laws are not being aggressively enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Water Act was a seminal ecological event when it was
passed by Congress in 1972. Yet today, according to environmental
groups and internal EPA records, the enforcement of the law is so
weak that many serious and chronic polluters operate with virtual
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   One indicator of the sorry state of the country's water supply
is the explosive growth of the bottled-water industry. Bottled
water sales in the United States rose 9.5 percent last year from
the previous year, according to the Beverage Marketing Corp. The
industry cites the fear of contaminants in water supplies as a
driving force in growing sales.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's Inspector General last year found that enforcement
staff in Alaska and Idaho failed to take any action against 75
percent of the companies that were in significant noncompliance
with the Clean Water Act. The polluters ranged from the US Army to
a major seafood processor. The pollutants included excess amounts
of nitrogen, ammonia, oil, grease, and chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, many serious and chronic violators are escaping
enforcement, and even those who are punished often receive only a
slap on the wrist, according to the Public Interest Research Group,
an environmental activist organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 study of water enforcement, PIRG concluded that one of
every five major wastewater discharges violated the Clean Water Act
during a 15-month period. The group is updating its study, and a
preliminary analysis has indicated little change.
</P>
<P>
   Those who pollute the air also benefit from lax enforcement of
the Clean Air Act, which was created in 1962 and toughened in 1990,
according to both the EPA's Inspector General and analysis of EPA
enforcement records.
</P>
<P>
   As it does with many enforcement programs, the EPA often pays
states to enforce the Clean Air Act. But both the agency and the
states have failed to do the job effectively, the EPA Inspector
General concluded last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found inconsistent implementation of agency directives, and
in other cases the states or EPA regions disregarded the agency's
requirements,'' the report stated. ``As a result, the effectiveness
of air-enforcement programs suffered. Numerous significant air
pollution violators went undetected and many of those identified
were not reported to EPA. Moreover, these violators were not made
known to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The Inspector General reviewed enforcement actions in six
states, including Massachusetts, and found widespread failure to
detect major air polluters.
</P>
<P>
   A study this year by the Environmental Working Group made
similar conclusions: ``Without question, the Clean Air Act is not
being effectively enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   The group analyzed the EPA's enforcement record and found that
one of every three major facilities in auto assembly, iron and
steel, petroleum refining, pulp manufacturing, and metal smetling
violated the Clean Air Act in 1997 or 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only a third of those violating the law were fined and the
fines that were levied were too small to have any effect, the group
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is a strong threat of enforcement, people will
break the law,'' said John Coequyt, who oversaw the study.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA and Justice Department said action it took against 24
electric utility companies earlier this month is proof the Clinton
administration is serious about cracking down on air polluters.
</P>
<P>
   The government filed seven lawsuits in the south and midwest,
accusing the companies of illegally releasing massive amounts of
air pollutants and contributing to one of the most severe
environmental problems facing the country. The lawsuits seek fines
against the companies and action to force them to spend money on
new pollution-control devices. The companies have denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
