<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-III-2N     11-17 2112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-POLLUTION-III-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 WASHINGTON: ... any wrongdoing.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are few federal prosecutors in the country with as much
experience pursuing polluters as Gregory Sasse.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the EPA awarded Sasse a silver medal for superior
service for his work on a task force that secured the first
criminal indictment of a company violating the law designed to
prevent the release of chemicals hazardous to the ozone. That was
one of dozens of environmental cases the northern Ohio prosecutor
has investigated in 13 years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said Sasse, is that his boss and others in the
Justice Department don't want him doing his job so well. They may
talk of getting tough with polluters, but the reality is much
different, he said in an interview with the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Clinton administration took office, environmental
crimes were immediately dropped as a top priority,'' he said.
``They were consigned to the slagheap of priorities past, like
gambling and auto theft.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasse, according to a whistleblower complaint he filed in 1996,
said his superiors punished him for going after polluters,
downgrading performance evaluations and ordering him to abandon
promising cases. He said the retaliation started during the Bush
administration, but began anew with increased intensity during the
Clinton years. The same supervisors were responsible for all of the
alleged reprisals and remain in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Sasse said he was briefing his supervisor on
allegations that a steel company was illegally releasing toxins
into the air and sickening nearby residents.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor responded by saying, ``If they don't like it, why
don't they just move,'' according to Sasse. When Sasse said the
plant's illegal polluting could be making people sick, the superior
was not sympathetic. ``People get sick all the time,'' Sasse said
his superior replied. ``I was sick last month and nobody opened a
criminal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasse's lawsuit is pending. He is not the only federal
environmental enforcement official making such a claim. In Texas,
prosecutor Ruth Ann Weidel filed a similar complaint in 1997. Her
lawsuit is also pending.
</P>
<P>
   Weidel, who has since left the US attorney's office, was a
veteran prosecutor and the former vice chair of the American Bar
Association's Environmental Crimes Committee. She prosecuted the
first criminal environmental cases in Arizona and the Los
Angeles-area district.
</P>
<P>
   While working in the southern Texas district, Weidel said she
experienced open hostility among superiors due to her work pursuing
environmental violators, according to the complaint she filed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, she said her superiors failed to investigate political
interference in a case involving a major Clean Air Act violation by
a Texas corporation. She said state regulators and the EPA cut back
their involvement in the case because of political pressure
``exerted at the very highest levels of Texas state government.''
</P>
<P>
   Weidel said her role in environmental cases was diminished, in
part, because defense attorneys for polluters complained she was
too aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   One result, she said, was the assignment of inexperienced
lawyers to important cases, including one that resulted in a major
decision against the Department of Justice that narrowed the
definition of a polluter. The case attracted national attention,
and according to Weidel's complaint, prompted a top Justice
Department official to loudly complain of ``the ineptitude and
incompetency'' of the Texas office.
</P>
<P>
   Weidel declined an interview request. The Justice Department has
denied her charges and Sasse's.
</P>
<P>
   Sasse is a reluctant critic of federal environmental
enforcement. He has never spoken publicly before about his
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I see it, enforcement of environmental crimes protects the
integrity of the whole regulatory scheme,'' he said. ``The cold
economic reality is (that) noncompliance saves money and even if
you are caught, the civil fines are virtually never greater than
what it would have cost to comply. Without criminal prosecutions,
the system doesn't work. Not only is there a powerful incentive to
pollute, but complying is economic suicide. A lack of integrity in
the system breeds a lack of integrity in the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No enforcement gains
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Congress approved funding for 200 criminal agents to
work for the EPA chasing down polluters. It took seven years to
hire and train all of the new agents, who were expected to add
credibility to the ultimate threat against any polluter: the
possibility of a criminal indictment.
</P>
<P>
   While the agents have generated a modest increase in recommended
charges, there has been no noticeable rise in prosecutions. Justice
Department records indicate the number of criminal cases filed last
year is virtually the same filed during the last year of the Bush
administration, which was perceived as hostile to environmental
causes.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, there is a wide disparity in the number of polluters
charged with a crime. In some regions, there is virtually no
criminal environmental enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts ranks near the bottom of the 90 federal districts
in both the number of environmental cases referred for prosecution
and the number of cases prosecuted, according to an analysis of
case activity for every US attorney's office in the country. The
Globe obtained the case data from Transactional Records Access
Clearinghouse at Syracuse University, a research group that studies
Justice Department enforcement records.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 through 1998, Massachusetts prosecuted environmental
crimes at a rate one-fourth the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 criminal agents assigned to the New England office of the
EPA ranked last in the country for the average number of cases
initiated last year _ an average of 2.9 cases per agent as compared
to 4.4 nationally and as high as 6.3 in the San Francisco region.
The average number of criminal referrals developed by the office
was also well below the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some regions of the country, there is no dedicated
environmental crimes unit at the US attorney's office in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald Stern said the statistics don't give his
office credit for several major civil environmental cases it is
handling, as well as other cases that were environmental in nature
but classified as something else because the charges also involved
fraud. ``I place a high priority on environmental prosecutions,
both criminally and civilally,'' he said. ``Although we don't have
a separate unit, we have not failed to prosecute cases because of a
lack of resources or interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Attorney General Janet Reno sets priorities for the
nation's prosecutors, whether or not environmental crimes are
pursued is very often a local decision.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Florida, for instance, an environmental unit of six
lawyers generates cases and prosecutions at more than three times
the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watts-FitzGerald, the chief of the unit, said the decision
to dedicate the six lawyers to environmental enforcement is largely
the decision of the local US attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has a national unit, based in Washington,
pursuing environmental crimes. That unit, however, has been under
attack from Congress. The unit's budget today is $7 million less
than it was in 1992 when adjusted for inflation. The practical
effect has been fewer people to handle cases. The impact shows on
the number of environmental prosecutions conducted, with
enforcement levels failing to increase from the Bush years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Congress this year slashed the EPA's enforcement
budget by $10.6 million, forcing the agency to cut such programs as
the Northeast Environmental Enforcement Project, which provided
legal and technical assistance to Massachusetts oficials
investigating environmental crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Justice Department defended the Clinton record
on environmental enforcement as impressive. The agency said it is
doing more complicated cases with greater environmental impact,
something which is not accurately accounted for in case statistics.
It points to a multistate action to clean up the Mississippi River
and criminal action against a major cruise line operator as
examples of its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmental enforcement is a very high priority for me, for
Attorney General (Janet) Reno and this administration,'' said Lois
Schiffer, assistant attorney general for environment and natural
resources. ``We have now as strong and effective an environmental
enforcement program as you can have.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing criminal sanctions against polluters is only part of
the enforcement picture. Most cases are handled by issuing fines,
administrative orders, or warnings.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, Massachusetts again falls short, producing fewer
enforcement actions per capita than the rest of the country,
according to EPA statistics. The New England area has 7 percent of
the country's enforcement personnel, but accounts for only 3
percent of the civil penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Local EPA officials say the statistics are misleading because
they don't measure the quality of cases or their outcomes, such as
the benefit to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go out and nickel and dime people all day long and pump
our numbers up,'' said DeVillars, who last week announced he would
soon leave his post as regional administrator for the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   The New England region, however, is a battleground over a new
approach to environmental enforcement, one that is gaining currency
nationally. The chief component of the strategy is ``compliance
assistance,'' or working cooperatively with business and industry
to improve environmental performance.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol Browner introduced the phrase in 1993
and reorganized the agency's enforcement program under the newly
named Office of Enforcement and Compliance Assistance. Promoting a
more cooperative approach toward business found support in
Congress, where Republicans have complained of overzealous and
unfair enforcement by the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Few regions of the country have adopted compliance assistance
with the enthusiasm of the New England EPA district.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars said he is a ``firm believer in a collaborative
approach'' and a ``force for education and empowerment.'' But he
rejected the notion that his office has softened its level of
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   He said enforcement is vigorous in this region and is used in
combination with compliance assistance. In addition, he said his
office is targeting industries with the most serious pollution
problems, at the expense of improving the region's enforcement
numbers by pursuing smaller cases.
</P>
<P>
   Yet critics of this strategy say it allows businesses to get
away with crimes. Internally, the DeVillars approach has stirred
controversy. Several enforcement officials say the agency has
become subservient to business, sending a dangerous message to
polluters that penalties can be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental problems today are less visible, but still
quite important,'' said one member of the regional legal team, who
like others asked not to be identified because they fear job
reprisals. ``Things will not change until the bottom line is
impacted.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars attributes much of the dissatisfaction with his
approach to a shakeup of the bureaucracy at the agency. He added,
however, that it is difficult to know if his tack is having a
greater effect than traditional enforcement. ``We are trying to
come up with measurements of success.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he has established a goal of making the Charles
River safe for swimming and fishing by Earth Day 2005. He said
traditional enforcement programs would never identify such a goal,
focusing instead on the number of enforcement actions and fines.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the same nationally. After detailing its
compliance assistance efforts, the EPA this year said, ``At the
present time, EPA has only limited data on the effects of
compliance assistance activities on environmental results.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Ruch, the executive director of Public Employees for
Environmental Responsibility, a group representing many federal
enforcement personnel, said there is no evidence the less
confrontational, more educational approach toward industry is
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deal with this kind of thing all over the place,'' Ruch
said. ``The agency says compliance is up or the environment is
better off. The problem there is they never identify how the
environment is benefiting in a way that can be verified. All that
is being offered is unsupported rhetoric.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
