<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2381 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN18-COX     11-17 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friends expect you to do right
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was a routine stop at the office ATM, and
suddenly I felt as if I had been transported to Las Vegas or an I
Love Lucy episode.
</P>
<P>
   I asked for $120, but the machine started spitting money at me:
$480, all counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the machine still raining money?'' asked the guy behind me,
grinning wickedly, as if to say, ``If only it were Friday, life
would be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   I could just picture Ricky saying, ``You've got some 'splaining
to do'' as I clutched my fistful of bills and hopped into the car
of a friend waiting to pick me up for lunch. ``Do you have a cell
phone?'' I demanded. ``I need to call security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to call them this minute?'' my friend laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, sure,'' I said. ``I don't want them to think I ran off
with the cash.'' And I don't want to get too comfortable with that
money padding my wallet, I thought to myself.
</P>
<P>
   There was no question of not returning the money, of course. Yet
the thick wad of bills weighed on me with the full force of
conscience, and of possibility. How far could you trust yourself?
How much money would it take to tempt an honest person?
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you had no fear of security cameras or bank records. If
there were absolutely no chance of getting caught, could you be
sure you would do the right thing?
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those instances when life imitates your
book-of-the-moment _ in my case, Anne Tyler's 1998 best-seller, ``A
Patchwork Planet.'' At the heart of the novel is the issue of
trust, and of doing the right thing when no one is looking.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old protagonist, Barnaby Gaitlin, lost everyone's
trust as a teen-ager, when he committed a series of break-ins. His
buddies nabbed the cash, while he became the notorious ``Paul Pry''
thief, poring over love letters and photo albums.
</P>
<P>
   As an adolescent, he is saved from jail by his parents'
considerable wealth and clout. As an adult, he refuses to work for
the Gaitlin Foundation, the family trust, choosing instead to do
manual labor for Rent-A-Back, where he does heavy lifting for
elderly clients.
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby moves through life aimless, immature. Until he falls in
love with Sophia, a kind, responsible woman and incorrigible cooker
of Crockpot dinners. Her goodness, he hopes, will rub off on him.
</P>
<P>
   When Sophia's aunt, one of Barnaby's clients, accuses him of
stealing $2,600 she hid in her flour bin, Sophia stands by Barnaby
_ in all the wrong ways. Believing her lover to be guilty, she
replaces the money in the flour bin.
</P>
<P>
   When the real money turns up in the pocket of her aunt's
bathrobe, Sophia fesses up to her suspicions. Her actions prove her
love, she explained to Barnaby, because she loved him no matter
what. Barnaby can't articulate, even to himself, the source of his
dismay: He wants to be loved for the man he has become, a man who
can be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   I had become attached to Sophia, and I wanted to yell at her,
``Cut it out! That's no way to run a relationship! Why, I trust my
husband more than I trust myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophia's act of loyalty was in another way an act of disloyalty,
her vote of confidence a vote of no-confidence. It is his
customers, ironically, who believe in Barnaby's innocence, swamping
him with orders.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's nice to be trusted. What's your hurry, my friend said,
about calling security? ``There's no way anyone would believe you
took that money. You wouldn't be capable of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what any of us is capable of, given the wrong
circumstances? But suddenly I understood how Barnaby felt.
</P>
<P>
   You count on the people in your life to trust you more than you
trust yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
