   POLLUTION-BASES (Undated) _ With the US having a military
presence in more than 140 countries, the question of how Washington
should deal with complaints of overseas environmental contamination
is emerging as a prickly financial and diplomatic issue. By David
Armstrong. 700 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-III (Washington) _ Enforcement of the nation's
environmental laws is often haphazard and lax, creating a system
where major polluters operate with little fear of being caught or
punished. By David Armstrong. (2 takes) PHOTO. GRAPHIC: 45 picas x
6 inches: ``Cases reaching the courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-DEVILLARS (Boston) _ Some enforcement staffers
complain that New England EPA chief John DeVillars has compromised
the agency by intervening in cases of interest to congressmen and
questioning the actions of staff after a political inquiry. By
David Armstrong. 1900 words. PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-IV (Northbridge, Mass.) _ A relatively unknown group
of 200 EPA criminal agents have been responsible for some
high-profile prosecutions. But there are accusations that some
agents have bullied padded enforcement statistics on the backs of
small business owners accused of minor offenses. By David
Armstrong. (2 takes) PHOTO.
</P>
