<HEADER>
A2386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BIRTHDAY18-COX     11-17 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTHDAY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whatever happened to candles, hats and Pin the Tail on the
Donkey?
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Commandment No. 1 from the Children's
Birthday Party Bible: Always RSVP.
</P>
<P>
   That's repondez s'il vous plait. Meaning, let the host know in
advance whether you'll be . . .
</P>
<P>
   Oh, nevermind.
</P>
<P>
   No one RSVPs anymore. Might as well doodle on the invitation for
all the good writing ``RSVP'' does.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe it, but many people do not know what RSVP
means,'' etiquette author Dana May Casperson says. ``No one ever
taught them. Or else they just don't bother anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's just a handful of confetti these days compared to
other egregious breaches in polite behavior at children's parties.
</P>
<P>
   Like the mom who brings little Johnny to the party . . . along
with five of his hungry, thirsty, noisy _ and uninvited _ siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Or the dad who drops off little Susie an hour late . . . and
picks her up an hour after everyone else has gone home.
</P>
<P>
   Or the parents who ``dump and run,'' leaving the party host to
manage their inquisitive toddler while they get hours of kid-free
shopping done at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just the guests. The hosts _ out to impress their
children and every other parent in the neighborhood _ often go so
overboard with Broadway-sized birthday productions that they forget
basic points of politeness.
</P>
<P>
   Like greeting guests as they arrive, or seeing them to the door
as they leave.
</P>
<P>
   Or sending ``thank you'' cards after the soiree.
</P>
<P>
   Or teaching little Susie not to yell ``I ALREADY HAVE ONE OF
THESE!!!'' when opening her presents. Heck, some parents just
collect gifts like a door charge and have the kids open them later.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say birthday parties are a great chance for parents to
teach kids social skills they can use the rest of their lives. Like
being a gracious host who thinks of guests first. Or being a
gracious guest who remembers the party is for honoring the birthday
boy or girl, not snatching all the party favors their little hands
can hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children have to be reminded over and over to develop those
skills so it becomes second nature,'' Casperson said. ``It's not
just for one party. It carries over into bigger events when they
get older, like weddings and housewarmings.''
</P>
<P>
   For hosts, it's important to teach children that while the
soiree is for them, they have to be considerate of others'
feelings. That means including all the children in whatever
activities are planned and making sure everyone is served. Equally
apportioned goodie bags also go a long way. ``Bag envy,'' as those
in the birthday biz call it, has led to more than a few fisticuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Giving older children a choice in their parties can teach them
how much work goes into the planning and preparation. Let them fill
party favor bags, help make the cake or prepare invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Altman says her son James' best birthday party was the one
he never had. Altman is editor of Parenting Plus , a magazine that
publishes in the Palm Beaches and Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   During vacation this year, Altman took her 6-year-old trout
fishing, something he'd always wanted to try. Sure, it was at a
trout farm, but he didn't know the difference.
</P>
<P>
   After he caught the trout, the farm operators told them he could
have the fish mounted as a trophy _ for a steep fee.
</P>
<P>
   Altman offered him a choice: a birthday party when they got back
home or the mounted trout. The trout won.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we're terrible for that,'' she said. ``But we had
a little cake in our cabin for him and he's going to get a fish on
his wall, something he actually wanted. And we got to avoid the
circus of having a birthday party.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach parent Beth Cole says she has tried to follow a
common-sense approach with her parties for daughter Laura, 6, and
Peyton Jr. (PJ) , who is 4.
</P>
<P>
   The past two years, she's opted to have PJ's party at school.
Along with having cake and party favors for his classmates, she's
hired wildlife handlers to bring kid-friendly birds, lizards,
skunks, snakes and porcupines to his pre-school so that all the
kids can participate. That way, PJ gets to be with his friends, no
one gets excluded, and Cole's carpet and furnishings stay free of
juice and ice cream stains.
</P>
<P>
   For her daughter, she usually lets her invite three or four
girlfriends somewhere away from home, such as a water park.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal with the parties is to never have a large group of
children in my house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The closest she's come is having a handful of her daughter's
friends sleep over after the party. Even that simple plan became a
fiasco when two girls had a fight and one decided she wanted Cole
to call home so her mother could come get her.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's pet peeves: Parents who invite too many kids or who host
parties that are inappropriate for the age. ``You do not take a
group of kids to a PG-13 movie when they're 6 or 7.'' And lunchtime
parties that don't serve food until 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the parents who use parties as weekend day-care.
</P>
<P>
   After one party, Cole found herself baby-sitting a 4-year-old an
hour after everyone else went home. Cole said that when the boy's
mom finally got there, ``She said, 'Oh, hi. I'm here.' She didn't
even thank me for watching her kid for an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   For today's parents, birthdays are especially tough because
parties are a much bigger deal now than a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were young, it was a cake, Pin the Tail on the Donkey
and we were done,'' said Ann Hallock, editor of Family Fun
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine recently offered a series of birthday tips. Among
them: Start small, especially for kids ages 3 to 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to be hiring a trapeze artist,'' Hallock said.
``For kids that age, balloons and cake are pretty exciting. And if
you start off with it being unbelievable and you have to take a
week off work to plan it, you're only creating a problem for next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Good advice, but South Floridians may not be listening. In
January 1995, Bill and Robin Lanting hosted the greatest show on
earth for their son Parker's 3rd birthday: elephants, llamas,
clowns, trapeze artists and a 70-foot-long, big-top tent.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, for son Chase's 6th birthday party, they
arranged for three Humvees full of Army regulars and reservists
from the West Palm Beach garrison to arrive with camouflaged faces
and toy guns and invade the house.
</P>
<P>
   The Lantings rented bumper boats for the backyard swimming pool
and dumped in dry ice to give the pool a foggy effect. Uniformed
U.S. Naval Sea Cadets supervised the kiddie naval battles.
</P>
<P>
   The children dined on military-styled grub: chipped beef, mashed
potatoes and peas. The parents got catered seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my mission in life,'' Robin Lanting said at the time.
``I'm a mother who likes throwing parties for my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Such excess almost always leads to trouble, etiquette maven
Casperson said. Parents wind up spending more time planning and
carrying off the party than they do spending time with their
children or teaching them how to behave in a social situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, the kids wind up expecting each year that their birthday
party will be the most wonderful thing in the world,'' she said.
``That's out of proportion to reality, of course. These lavish
affairs are nothing more than a showing of financial success most
times. And they're not fair to the children because it causes
overstimulation and wears them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tips for a successful birthday party
</P>
<P>
   Have you really thought of everything? Local party experts and
several birthday-tested parents offer these tips for planning a
successful birthday party:
</P>
<P>
   _ Include your child. Let children help plan the party,
including choosing a theme, decorating invitations and picking out
party favors. Surprises are fun, but kids like to get involved in
planning, and this is a time when they're motivated to be
especially helpful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Start early. Check out your options, get the best price,
create a fallback plan if necessary. Start two to three months in
advance if you're going to involve your children. If you choose a
theme, carry it through from beginning to end, including
invitations, crafts, games, cake and party favors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make the party manageable. It's tempting to invite the whole
second-grade class for the afternoon, but you'll likely regret it.
Follow the old rule of inviting the same number of guests as your
child's age.
</P>
<P>
   _ Experiment. Think creatively and put away that rectangle cake
pan. Or better yet, opt for decorated cupcakes instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ Party time. If you're planning a Saturday afternoon party at a
popular attraction, be prepared for a mob. If you can swing a
weekday party, you'll get a calmer atmosphere and maybe a better
price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beware of sleep-overs. For kids under 10, it's often
impossible to get past midnight without at least one ``I want to go
home'' problem. For pre-teens, sleepovers seem to have become the
party of choice, but be specific about when kids are expected to go
to sleep, or they won't.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a list of party necessities. If you're holding a party
away from home, remember to bring camera, film, refreshments,
matches, knife, bag for taking gifts home, notepad for keeping
track of who gave what, wet wipes for getting kids clean enough to
sit in your car.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't be afraid to ask for help. Recruit helpers for big
parties. Unless you're sure you'll have help from parents, hire
baby-sitters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget thank-you notes. No matter the age of your child,
it's proper etiquette to send written thank-you notes. A parent can
write the note if the child is under age 5 or hasn't learned to
print.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be prepared. Parents think nothing these days of bringing
along a couple extra siblings. Plan for unexpected guests. It's
normal to have extras show up at parties, so have extra food and
favors ready.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
E-mail: jeffhouck(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
