<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High Court holy war
 &HT;    By RowlanD Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Get ready, America. The Supreme Court is juggling
a Hail Mary pass lobbed from Texas that will influence the national
school prayer struggle.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where football is religion and religion is a contact
sport, a church-and-state controversy that erupted at a public high
school football game will be decided by the republic's nine highest
constitutional refs.
</P>
<P>
   Their decision will be final.
</P>
<P>
   Let's roll the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Several families asked officials with the Santa Fe Independent
School District, located in the flat land south of Houston, to stop
having students lead the audience in prayer before the Indians took
the field against visiting high school teams.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe school officials denied the request.
</P>
<P>
   Two families, one Mormon and one Roman Catholic, went to court
claiming that the practice, which was under control of government
employees in the public school district, violated the U.S.
Constitution's First Amendment that says, ``Congress shall make no
law respecting an establishment of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year a federal appeals court ruled in favor of the
families. Santa Fe's officials appealed the ruling and have
continued student-led prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, the man who would be president, signed a
brief urging the Supreme Court to hear the case. Eight other states
did likewise.
</P>
<P>
   They asked for it. Now they've got it. The case now is in the
hands of the justices.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe school officials also asked the Supreme Court to review
a federal appeals court decision that ruled students could offer
prayers at graduation ceremonies as long the prayers did not
proselytize and were nonsectarian.
</P>
<P>
   School officials claimed this ruling forced officials to
officially discriminate.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has never taken up the question of student-led
prayers at graduation ceremonies, although it did rule in 1992 that
public schools could not invite members of the clergy to lead
graduation prayers.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the families said Santa Fe officials were
deliberately circumventing the court's 1992 decision by having
student surrogates lead a captive audience in government-controlled
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   The justices took the football-prayer appeal, but not the
graduation-prayer appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The court may now hear arguments over the difference between a
government-controlled prayer at a graduation ceremony and a
government-controlled prayer at a football game.
</P>
<P>
   If the argument is put forward that graduation ceremonies are
more solemn and important and therefore more likely to demand
involuntary attendance than football games, then the justices, none
of whom are from Texas, need to understand that this thinking is
reversed in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, attendance at high school graduation ceremonies is
more likely to be voluntary while attendance at high school
football games is more likely to be involuntary.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea is that the government can approve religious
observances regardless of the feelings of the audience only when
the ceremonies are solemn and serious, then the justices need to
understand that football is worshipped in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting hairs between student-led prayers at two Texas rituals
replaces the wall between church and state a with transparent veil.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a crushing setback to Thomas Jefferson, who wrote
the following to the Danbury Baptist Association on Jan. 1, 1802:
</P>
<P>
   ``I contemplate with sovereign reverence that act of the whole
American people which declared that their legislature should `make
no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the
free exercise thereof,' thus building a wall of separation between
church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
