<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ALTOIDS18-COX     11-17 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTOIDS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powerful (gasp!) new star in the firma-mint
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For all the mints crowding store shelves
these days, you'd think Americans had the collective breath of
German shepherds.
</P>
<P>
   And not just any breath mints, but ``power'' mints. That's the
name the industry gives to the kind of confection that makes your
throat feel like you've inhaled a bucket of dry ice. Heck, there's
even an aptly named line of Powerful Mints, part of the $302
million breath freshener market.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Altoids, the ``curiously strong'' mint, that has long
blown away the competition in its whoosh of peppermint scent. Now a
third flavor has joined the small but powerful Altoids line-up.
Imagine opening your mouth to a 40-below wind-chill and sprinkling
in a little cinnamon, and you have the flavor experience. (Altoids
is even releasing a promotional film to introduce consumers to a
Sindy, the female embodiment of the new cinnamon mint.)
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon is the third flavor for Altoids, which first appeared
in England about the time the colonies were rebelling against King
George III. (The others: original peppermint and the newer
wintergreen, which debuted this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the competition, Altoids has a curiously strong fan base.
The mints even found their way into government documents, thanks to
Monica Lewinsky, who exchanged e-mails with President Clinton about
the alleged effects of including Altoids in certain intimate acts.
That correspondence became part of the Starr Report.
</P>
<P>
   Since demand for power mints began increasing about a year ago,
Starbucks has rolled out After Coffee Mints and Neiman Marcus
introduced a characteristically understated (but hardly
under-flavored) ``the mint.'' Certs amped up their offerings with
Powerful Mints. Scott Adams, creator of the comic strip Dilbert,
has even given his approval to a new line of Perfor-mints, which
are shaped like the strip's characters.
</P>
<P>
   The next target: women. The folks who make Altoids, Callard &AMP;
Bowser, just unveiled a less-potent, female-targeted hard candy
under a different name, La Vie de la Vosgienne. (Slogan: ``Say La
Vie.'') The candies come in tin containers which, the ads brag,
give other sweets ``a packaging complex.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right, flavor is not enough. Part of Altoids' appeal has
long been those metal containers, used since the 1920s. So popular
are the tin boxes that the company trumpets their versatility in
ads: ``The distinctive tins have hundreds of household uses, such
as holding nails, fishing tackle, coins, pins, paper clips. One
wilderness group even uses them as emergency stoves.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the tin drum is Penguin, a mint that's now the rage in
Silicon Valley among computer chipheads mostly because of their
caffeinated peppermints. (Why not just call them Amphetimints?)
Their frozen-tongue-in-cheek warning: ``For use while driving or
operating heavy machinery.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the ``cold'' front this winter: Mentos Cool Chews,
billed as the ``first chewy strong mint.'' Their makers are
spending millions in marketing aimed at MTV-aged viewers, including
Mentos-sponsored rock concerts, a mail-in offer for a free
Freshmaker Tour CD, and a contest offering the chance to sit
onstage at a concert in a La-Z-Boy recliner that will later be
shipped to the winner's home.
</P>
<P>
   Why this sudden American yen for powerful tastes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have an openness toward food now,'' says Susan Smith
of the National Confectioners Association. ``They like ethnic food,
spicy food and lots of high flavors. And it's not just adults who
like them. My 11-year-old son, who sometimes even forgets to brush
his teeth, is crazy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I equate it to salsa outselling ketchup,'' says Pamela Byrne
of Warner-Lambert Co., manufacturer of Certs. ``America wants
robust flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
E-mail: jeffhouck(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
