<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In one take this week.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: The U.S. Supreme Court is considering the issue of
grandparents' visitation rights. Can you list the names of the
justices, and their address, so we can write to express our opinion
and tell our stories?
</P>
<P>
   A: The nine justices: William Rehnquist (chief justice); Stephen
Breyer; Ruth Bader Ginsburg; Anthony Kennedy; Sandra Day O'Connor;
Antonin Scalia; David Souter; John Paul Stevens; Clarence Thomas.
The mailing address: Supreme Court of the United States, 1 First
St. NE, Washington, DC 20543.
</P>
<P>
   But you need to know that letters from the public will not have
any effect on the Supreme Court's decision-making process, on this
or any other issue under consideration. As a representative said,
it's not a court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the Newbery Medals? Who gives them out, and when did
they start?
</P>
<P>
   A: The medals are awards given every year by the American
Library Association to the author of the book considered the most
distinguished contribution to American literature for children.
</P>
<P>
   The medals originated in 1921 when a bookseller named Frederic
Melcher decided that authors would write better books for young
readers if there were an award for high-quality childrens'
literature. At the time, most books published for youngeters in the
United States were formula fiction, such as those featuring Hardy
Boys, Nancy Drew and the Bobbsey Twins.
</P>
<P>
   So Melcher created the Newbery Medal _ named after John Newbery,
an English publisher and bookseller in the mid 1700s _ and asked
childrens' librarians who were members of the American Library
Association to decide which book was the most distinguished of the
year. A committee of 15 such librarians who are members of the
ALA's Association of Library Services to Children meets each year
to make the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did ``Indian summer'' get its name?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, let's explain what Indian summer is. It's a short
period of especially fair weather and mild days usually coming in
late October and early November, when the leaves are turning and
falling, following the autumn's first cold spell.
</P>
<P>
   World Book Encyclopedia explains that the origin of the term is
uncertain, but speculates that the American settlers named the
period after the American Indians, who told the settlers in advance
that this period would come. And every year it did, right on cue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picturesque Expressions: A Thematic Dictionary'' says the
American Indians, who always took advantage of the unseasonably
warm weather to make their final preparations for winter, called
the period the special gift of a favorite god, Cautantowwit, the
god of the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We were talking about baseball the other day, and the name of
Josh Gibson came up. Someone said he hit more than 900 home runs in
his career. Do you have any information about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Specific statistics are in question because, as the book ``A
Who's Who of Sports Champions'' states, the Negro Leagues didn't
keep documentable records. But there's no disputing that Gibson was
a great hitter. Satchel Paige went so far as to call him ``the
greatest hitter who ever lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was born on Dec. 21, 1911, in Buena Vista, Ga. His family
moved to Pittsburgh in 1924, where he started playing semipro
baseball. He began playing in the Negro Leagues in 1930. A catcher,
he played mostly for teams in and around Pittsburgh, including the
Homestead Grays and the Pittsburgh Crawfords. He also played winter
baseball in Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Gibson is believed to have hit about 800 home
runs, including one measuring an astounding 575 feet. He was
credited with as many as 84 home runs in a season, which may have
included as many as 200 games.
</P>
<P>
   He died suddenly of a brain tumor on Jan. 20, 1947, the year
Jackie Robinson became the first black player in the Major Leagues.
In recognition of his accomplishments, Gibson was inducted into the
Baseball Hall of Fame in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The History Channel recently featured John DeLorean and his
gull-wing sports car from the early 1980s. It mentioned that he's
planning a new lightweight car made of plastic. Do you know
anything about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Still the visionary engineer obsessed with aerodynamics,
lightweight materials and speed _ think of the sleek time-travel
car of the ``Back to the Future'' movies _ John Z. DeLorean does
indeed have on the drawing board a new sports car. According to
him, it would rocket from zero to 60 mph in 3.2 seconds, and would
cost less than $20,000. Like the earlier DeLorean, and the
Mercedes-Benz 300 SL coupe before that, it would have flip-up
gull-wing doors.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, DeLorean declined to provide any
specifics about his partners or source of financing. But he said he
was sure he would build the car, perhaps in two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   His initial sports car, made in Northern Ireland, was an
attention-getter for its styling and performance, but failed in the
marketplace after DeLorean was tried on charges of cocaine
trafficking and fraud. His accusers said he was trying to raise
money by illegal means to save the troubled DeLorean Motor Car Co.
He was acquitted in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is the flight recorder in airplanes called a black box,
when it's actually orange?
</P>
<P>
   A: Aviation veterans say the black boxes were never black. They
were tan, yellow or _ the standard today _ orange. That's to make
them easier to find. In military aviation, the term referred to any
compact experimental or secret high-technology electronics
equipment, especially radar. The phrase has stuck to this day, now
used mainly to describe a flight recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Former Sen. Bob Dole is heading a campaign to raise $100
million in private donations for the planned World War II Memorial.
Where can we send contributions?
</P>
<P>
   A: We've printed the information before, but it's well worth
repeating. If you want to send a check, make it out to World War II
Memorial and mail to: World War II Memorial, P.O. Box 96766,
Washington, DC 20090-6766. Credit card donations also can be made
online _ www.wwiimemorial.com/donorprograms/donation.cfm _ or you
can call 1-800-639-4992 to make a credit card donation or to get
information. The estimated cost to design, construct and maintain
the memorial is $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Groundbreaking for the memorial is scheduled for Veterans Day
2000. It's expected to be a reality three years after that. As of
June, about $60 million has been received from individuals,
corporations, veterans' groups and other donors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was astronaut John Casper's background, and what is he
doing now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Casper is a veteran of four spaceflights. He was the pilot
for a scientific mission by space shuttle Atlantis 1990 and was
commander for three other shuttle scientific flights in 1993, 1994
and 1996. He logged more than 825 hours in space.
</P>
<P>
   A retired Air Force colonel, Casper was born in Greenville,
S.C., in 1943. He lived in the Atlanta suburbs of Doraville and
Chamblee as a child. He attended Georgia Tech for a year, then
entered the Air Force Academy, where he received a B.S. degree in
engineering science in 1996. He earned a master of science degree
in astronautics the following year from Purdue University.
</P>
<P>
   Although he lives in Houston, Casper still considers
Gainesville, Ga., to be his hometown. He is director of safety,
reliability and quality assurance for the Johnson Space Center in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Norman Rockwell has been in the news recently because of an
exhibition of his works opening in Atlanta. In all the coverage
about his life and career, I haven't seen any mention of the cause
of his death. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: In announcing his death on Nov. 8, 1978, at his home in
Stockbridge, Mass., his wife, Molly, said simply: ``He didn't die
of anything except being 84 years old.'' Rockwell had been in
failing health for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand the Titanic was trying to win the Blue Riband
for speed when it went down. What was that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Blue Riband was (and still is) a British title that has
commemorated record-breaking trans-Atlantic passages for more than
160 years. It's verbal only, meaning there's no actual trophy or
ribbon. While some believe that it should be preserved for liners
of old, or at least kept for ocean-going successors worthy of the
mystique, others disagree and claim it for more modern vessels,
such as sailboats and water-jet propelled craft.
</P>
<P>
   The first Blue Riband was conferred on the paddlewheel steamer
Great Western in 1838. The title simply related to the fastest
Atlantic crossing, east or west, in a day when merchant vessels
were the only links between the continents. The terminal points
varied for many years until they were set as Ambrose Light off New
York and Bishops Rock Light off England's Scilly Isles.
</P>
<P>
   Other vessels capturing the Blue Riband have included the City
of Brussels, which took it for Belgium in 1869; the Teutonic, for
Germany, in 1891; the Lusitania and the Mauretania, for England, in
1909; the Rex, for Italy, in 1933; the Normandie, for France, in
1935; the Queen Mary, for England, in 1938; and the United States,
for the United States, in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
