<SLUG> BC-PECANPIE-RECIPIES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Go nuts for pecan pieBy Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If it's your first Thanksgiving in Texas, get
with the program. The state tree is the pecan, so it's no surprise
that this tasty nut shows up on the holiday table in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular is that ultra-rich pecan pie, a quick
mix-and-pour-in-a-pastry-shell dessert. Whether you use two eggs or
three, dark corn syrup or light, white sugar or brown is all a
matter of preference or family tradition. Here are a trio of
recipes to tempt you. Clip and save. The pecan crop is good this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Elsie East's Pecan Pie
</P>
<P>
   Unbaked 9-inch pie shell
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon (scant)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup broken pecans
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients and pour into an unbaked pie shell. Bake at
300 degrees on low rack for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Grametbauer's Pecan Pie
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup melted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 heaping cup pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   9-inch deep-dish unbaked pie shell
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs. Add remaining ingredients except pecans and crust.
Pour into unbaked pie shell. Sprinkle pecans over filling. Bake at
350 degrees for 45 minutes. Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   Kahlua Pecan Pie
</P>
<P>
   9-inch pastry crust
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Kahlua or other coffee liqueur
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dark corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole or chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream and pecan halves (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Line a 9-inch pie pan with your favorite pastry recipe. Chill.
Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In large bowl, cream together butter,
sugar, vanilla and flour. Mix well. Beat in eggs, one at a time.
Stir in Kahlua, corn syrup, evaporated milk and pecans. Mix well,
pour into pie pan. Bake for 10 minutes. Then reduce heat to 325 and
bake until firm (about 40 minutes). Chill. Garnish with whipped
cream and pecan halves, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
