A2397 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-BRUSSELS-SPROUTS18-CO     11-17 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUSSELS-SPROUTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's something about Brussels sprouts
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be honest. Did anyone ever look at the Thanksgiving table and
say, ``Oh, goody! Brussels sprouts!''
</P>
<P>
   But as sure as turkey is the main course, it's guaranteed that
November food magazines will have pictures of the bird surrounded
by little green Brussels sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's to add eye appeal for the camera, a bit of color, a
different shape. Maybe it's because of the season. Thanksgiving may
be a celebration of the harvest, but by the end of November the
produce harvest is mostly past. The green beans probably come from
California or south of the border, and often look it. Broccoli is
the green vegetable we'll be stuck with for months to come _ hardly
a reason for celebration. Snow peas and sugar snaps are too new to
the American culinary scene to be grounded in tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Brussels sprouts, however, like any good member of the cabbage
family, seem suited to the season.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck with the phenomenon, food writers take steps to add to the
appeal of these miniatures.
</P>
<P>
   One technique that shows up sometimes is to separate the sprouts
into individual leaves before they're cooked. I did that once, and
it is not something you want to do on a busy day.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be busy this year, for there will be 20 at our
Thanksgiving table. Given the division of labor, it falls to me to
make the stuffing, the mashed potatoes, the pumpkin pie and the
vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   The immemorable vegetable. But there must be one on the
sideboard, even if it is a token. So this year I took the challenge
and started early, testing various recipes, looking for a
preparation that would earn a nod of approval if not enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   I found one. It may not invite seconds, not in competition with
the garlic roasted mashed potatoes and the biscuit and cornbread
stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe next year someone will say, ``Oh, goody! Ann's
Brussels sprouts!''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to double the recipe, use two large skillets.
</P>
<P>
   PAN-BROWNED BRUSSELS SPROUTS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Brussels sprouts, of even size
</P>
<P>
   4 large cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pine nuts, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Rinse sprouts in cold water. Trim the bottom stem and remove
loose outer layers. Cut sprouts in half lengthwise. Cut garlic into
very thin slices.
</P>
<P>
   In a large, heavy skillet, melt 2 tablespoons butter with the
oil over moderate heat, then cook garlic, stirring, until pale
golden. Transfer garlic with a slotted spoon to a small dish lined
with a paper towel. Reduce heat to low and arrange sprouts in the
skillet, cut sides down, in a single layer. Sprinkle with salt to
taste. Cook sprouts, without turning, until tender and undersides
are golden brown (about 15 minutes). Resist the temptation to turn
up the heat to speed the process. Check doneness with the tip of a
knife.
</P>
<P>
   With tongs, transfer sprouts to a serving plate, browned sides
up. Add the golden garlic, pine nuts and remaining butter to the
skillet and cook over moderate heat, stirring, for about 1 minute.
Spoon over the sprouts and sprinkle with freshly ground black
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Toast the pine nuts in a 350-degree oven for 10 to 12 minutes,
until golden.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This makes 4 moderate servings, about all anyone will
spoon up unless they are ardent fans of Brussels sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 245 calories, 21 g
fat, 25 mg cholesterol, 31 mg sodium, plus salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from Gourmet magazine).
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
