<HEADER>
A2398 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-CENTURY-FOOD18-COX     11-17 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-FOOD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The birth of road food
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We drove our new cars across America, and plugged in to the
electricity that wired the country. Speedy transportation and
instant power would dramatically alter the way Americans cooked and
ate in the second quarter of the century.
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy that would soon fail tragically, the dark days
of the Great Depression and the beginning of World World II also
colored our culinary landscape. Home cooks were without kitchen
help when the Depression hit, and many took to the job with relish,
learning about the regional foods they sampled while on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Travel they did: Americans moved about in mass numbers for the
promise of better jobs, or just to see the country. Road food was
born, and more than ever, restaurants became social as well as food
venues.
</P>
<P>
   In metropolitan areas, moving pictures captured the essence of
Hollywood glamour and elegance. Cocktails before dinner and lavish,
sophisticated parties inspired a new approach to entertaining _
with alcohol as a main beverage.
</P>
<P>
   On the farms, radio made homey recipe chats popular. Cooks
across the nation were hearing about the same foods and recipes and
were introduced to new technologies at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens were modernized _ toast popped up from toasters and
didn't need to be watched. Refrigerators were larger, and included
freezing compartments, just right for Clarence Birdseye's
newfangled idea: ``frosted foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Health issues continued to grow, and food additives were
scrutinized carefully by the FDA. Vitamins and minerals necessary
for healthy bodies were identified and added to foods to prevent
many common diseases. The seven food groups were outlined as the
nutrition standard for Americans. We become vitamin-crazed _ only
laxatives outsold vitamins in pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the 1930s brought World War II rationing, and
economical recipes used during the Depression remained on the
table. Cooks became creative with fewer meats and more starches _
rice salads and macaroni and cheese came of age.
</P>
<P>
   Women were in factories, not in the kitchen, as the war
progressed. Dozens of gadgets made the cook's job easier and
faster. The pressure cooker, invented for the military, was sold to
wartime cooks, who put it to work canning vegetables from their
victory gardens.
</P>
<P>
   This was the decade of instant foods: instant coffee, boxed cake
mixes, Nestle's Quik chocolate mix, instant mashed potatoes and
frozen orange juice concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation flew into the '50s, the men came home from the war
and women returned to their homes _ but not to their aprons. They
were primed to get out of the kitchen and into the workforce. Home
dining declined, and restaurant meals grew in a trend that
continues today.
</P>
<P>
   Our soldiers brought food ideas from the countries where they
had served. Chefs would soon pick up on Italian pastas, Hawaiian
tropical fruits and French wines. The coming decade would bring
even more ethnic changes to menus, supermarket shelves and tables
across America.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Norris writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
