<HEADER>
A2399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-CENTURY-FOOD-RECIPE18     11-17 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-FOOD-RECIPE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Popular recipes from the second quarter of the 20th century
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Credited to an insurance salesman and
hobby cook in California, the chiffon cake was described as a
``high-rising new cake that melts in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   General Mills bought the recipe in 1947 and printed it in a
leaflet.
</P>
<P>
   CHIFFON CAKE
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4cups sifted cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   5egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   3/4cups cold water
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1cup egg whites (7 or 8 egg whites)
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Sift flour, sugar, baking powder,
and salt into large mixing bowl. Make a well in center, and add
oil, egg yolks, water, vanilla and lemon zest. Beat until smooth
with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Whip egg whites with cream of tartar until they hold a stiff
peak. Pour yolk mixture gradually over beaten whites, gently
folding in with a rubber spatula just until blended.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into ungreased 10-inch tube pan, and bake 55
minutes. Raise the oven temperature to 350 degrees and bake 10 to
15 minutes longer or until surface springs back when lightly
touched.
</P>
<P>
   Invert pan immediately on top of a funnel to cool to room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Turn pan right-side up and rap sharply on counter to loosen
cake. Turn cake out and frost or glaze as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: For orange chiffon, omit vanilla and lemon zest, and
add 3 tablespoons grated orange zest. Substitute orange juice for
the water.
</P>
<P>
   For chocolate chip chiffon, increase sugar to 1 3/4 cups, and
omit lemon zest. Just before pouring batter into pan, fold in 3
ounces semi-sweet chocolate, grated.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes make 1 10-inch tube pan cake.
</P>
<P>
   During their 1927 honeymoon in Rome, Douglas Fairbanks and Mary
Pickford dined on this fettucine dish at Alfredo's restaurant. It
came to be known as Fettucine Alfredo. The recipe from Alfredo's is
simple _ no cream, no mushrooms, nothing fancy. Just pure
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   FETTUCCINE ALFREDO _ THE ORIGINAL
</P>
<P>
   1pound fresh fettuccine noodles
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unsalted butter at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese (use Parmigiano-Reggiano
for authentic results)
</P>
<P>
   black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cook fettuccine noodles until al dente _ just tender, but with
chewiness. Fresh noodles take only about 2 minutes. Dried noodles,
inferior, need more time.
</P>
<P>
   Dice butter into heated large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly drain pasta, turn into the bowl with butter, and add
Parmesan, tossing well. Add several twists of the peppermill; serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipes adapted from ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean
Anderson, 1997, Potter Books.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
