<HEADER>
A2400 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-PIE-TIPS18-COX     11-17 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIE-TIPS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pie tips in a nutshell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is an electric mixer required to make a pecan pie?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, in fact, it's better not to use one. Overbeating the eggs
results in a foamy filling. During baking, the foam will rise to
the
</P>
<P>
   top, coating the nuts with an atypical sugary crust.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does light or dark corn syrup make a better pecan pie?
</P>
<P>
   A: It doesn't matter. The syrups can be used interchangeably. If
you prefer a light-colored pie, use light corn syrup and granulated
</P>
<P>
   sugar. Brown sugar can be used in pumpkin pies but may cause
slight weeping. Pecan pies made with dark brown sugar and dark corn
syrup will be dark-colored, have a molasses flavor, a slightly
curdled look and some weeping.
</P>
<P>
   But they taste great.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many pecans should you use in a pecan pie?
</P>
<P>
   A: For a 9-inch pie, any amount from one to two cups can be used
without altering the other ingredients. And it doesn't matter if
</P>
<P>
   the pecans are chopped or halved.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many eggs are needed for a pecan pie?
</P>
<P>
   A: The basic formula is three eggs for a 9-inch pie. Four eggs
will produce a slightly firmer pie. Five eggs is too many; the
filling
</P>
<P>
   tends to curdle.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can you tell when pecan pie is done?
</P>
<P>
   A: Insert a knife halfway between the center and the edge of the
pie. The blade should be clean when removed. If there is cloudy
filling on the knife, bake longer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you keep pie crust from getting soggy?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are baking your pie in a metal or foil pie pan, place
the pie on a preheated heavy-duty cookie sheet for the entire
baking time. This procedure is not necessary with glass pie dishes,
which conduct heat evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
