<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2401 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-TURKEY-HOWTO18-COX     11-17 1983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-HOWTO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alternatives for holiday meal: A tale of two turkeys
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Two of the most popular ways to cook a
Thanksgiving turkey are brining _ which produces a super-moist bird
_ and deep-frying, which gives diners a chance at a crispy skin.
</P>
<P>
   Both methods are unusual and require special equipment and
storage space. We have tried both methods, and they are successful
if you follow the directions.
</P>
<P>
   Brining may be easier for most cooks, though finding a fresh,
not frozen, turkey may be difficult. Order now from butchers to
ensure a fresh bird. Plan for refrigerator space or a deep cooler
that will hold the trash can and the bird. It must be kept cool.
</P>
<P>
   Deep-frying requires outdoor space and a propane cooking setup,
and should be done carefully.
</P>
<P>
   But for alternatives to the roasted bird, these turkeys are the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   BRINED TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe for the brine can be increased as needed to
cover the turkey. To figure how much brine is needed, place turkey
in container to be used (a new trash can works well) and measure
how much water you will need to cover turkey completely. You must
have a lot of space in your refrigerator, because the turkey needs
to soak there overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Total time required: Overnight for brining; plus normal roasting
time
</P>
<P>
   Equipment:
</P>
<P>
   6-gallon stockpot or new, clean plastic wastebasket to hold
15-20 pound bird
</P>
<P>
   Large liquid measurer (clean milk jug is good)
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerator shelf to hold stockpot and turkey
</P>
<P>
   For turkey and brine:
</P>
<P>
   115- to 20-pound fresh turkey
</P>
<P>
   2cups kosher salt or 1 cup plain (noniodized) table salt
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons dried sage
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon dried marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon celery seeds
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   Seasoning vegetables for stuffing:
</P>
<P>
   1medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1medium carrot, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1medium celery rib, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons ( 3/4 stick) unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   About 1 1/2 quarts homemade turkey stock (made with giblets from
turkey) or canned chicken stock, plus more as needed for gravy as
desired
</P>
<P>
   The night before roasting, rinse turkey inside and out with cold
water. Remove neck and giblets from cavity and use for turkey
stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a very large stockpot, mix 2 gallons cold water with salt,
rosemary, thyme, sage, marjoram, celery seeds and peppercorns,
stirring until salt dissolves. Note: Brine mixture can be increased
proportionately as needed to cover the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Place cleaned turkey in pot. Cover and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Position a rack in lower third of oven and preheat to
325(degrees).
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, mix onion, carrot and celery.
</P>
<P>
   Remove turkey from brine and rinse well, inside and out, under
cold running water. Pat skin and cavity dry with paper towels. Turn
turkey on its breast. Loosely fill neck cavity with onion mixture.
Using a thin wooden or metal skewer, pin neck skin to the back.
Fold the turkey's wings akimbo behind the back or tie to the body
with twine. Loosely fill the large body cavity with the remaining
onion mixture. Place the drumsticks in the wire lock or tie
together with kitchen string.
</P>
<P>
   Place the turkey, breast side up, on a rack in roasting pan. Rub
well with butter. Tightly cover breast area with foil. Pour 2 cups
of turkey stock into bottom of pan. Throughout cooking, add stock
as needed as it evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   Roast turkey, basting all over every 30 minutes with juices from
pan bottom (lift foil to baste breast area). Cook until a meat
thermometer put in meaty part of the thigh (do not touch a bone
with it) reaches 180 _ about 4 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Remove foil during last hour to allow breast to brown;
re-cover with foil if skin becomes too brown.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer turkey to serving platter and let stand for at least 20
minutes before carving.
</P>
<P>
   Use reserved drippings for gravy. Note: Do not add extra salt to
gravy before tasting, as the turkey juices will be salty.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 15 to 20 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Do not stuff this turkey with traditional stuffing; the
extra salt in turkey's juices would ruin the stuffing. Instead,
loosely fill cavities with seasoning vegetables and bake stuffing
in separate pan.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from ``Thanksgiving 101'' by Rick Rodgers, 1998,
Broadway Books.)
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for deep-fried turkey became popular with fans of
Paul Prudhomme, who says it originated in Louisiana's Cajun region.
The seasonings used here are Cajun seasonings; you can vary them to
suit your tastes, however.
</P>
<P>
   Because this is a somewhat dangerous cooking method, a few notes
on safety: Set the pot and burner on a level, firm surface, such as
a patio or walkway with spacious clearance. Children and pets
should be kept well away from the cooking area at all times. Have a
safe place set aside to cool the pot of oil after cooking. Remember
to turn the gas off at the tank after closing off the burner.
</P>
<P>
   DEEP-FRIED TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Time: Overnight to season; about 2 hours preparation and cooking
</P>
<P>
   Equipment:
</P>
<P>
   Heavy bottomed stockpot (8 gallon)
</P>
<P>
   Propane burner
</P>
<P>
   Deep-fry thermometer, attached to wire so it can be in oil at
all times
</P>
<P>
   Meat injection needle or basting tube with needle attachment
</P>
<P>
   Two thick wire coat hangers or professional meat hook for
lifting turkey in and out of hot oil
</P>
<P>
   Oven mitt
</P>
<P>
   Paper-lined platter for draining turkey
</P>
<P>
   FOR TURKEY:
</P>
<P>
   5gallons peanut or vegetable oil, or enough to cover bird in pot
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons ground red pepper (cayenne is best), optional
</P>
<P>
   12- to 15-pound turkey, cleaned and legs tied
</P>
<P>
   For injection puree:
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup finely chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup finely chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons ground peppers that have been packed in vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon plus 1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon ground cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup turkey or chicken stock, made with giblets
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Mix 2 teaspoons salt and 2 teaspoons cayenne pepper in small
bowl; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Clean turkey, removing the giblets and neck packed in the
cavities. Rinse and pat dry. If the turkey has a ``pop-up''
doneness indicator, remove and discard it.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet over high heat, melt butter until half
melted. Add onions; saute about 3 minutes, stirring occasionally.
Add celery, garlic, ground hot peppers, 1 tablespoon plus 1
teaspoon salt, 1 tablespoon red pepper and black pepper. Cook until
mixture is a rich golden brown, about 3 minutes, stirring and
scraping pan bottom frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Add stock and Worcestershire; bring to a boil, stirring
constantly. Remove from heat; immediately transfer to a blender.
Blend on highest speed until mixture is very smooth _ it must go
through tip of basting needle.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse and drain turkey well. While puree is still hot, pour it
into the meat injector or basting tube, and inject the puree into
turkey, making holes about 2 inches apart. (Note: Take care not to
pierce through meat to turkey cavity.) To fill the hole formed by
injector needle, as you draw needle out, continue injecting puree.
</P>
<P>
   Pour any remaining puree into cavity of turkey and rub over
inner surface.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle reserved salt-cayenne mix evenly over bird and inside
the cavity, rubbing in by hand and using all. Close legs and tail
together with metal prong (or fold legs back into skin flaps or tie
legs with kitchen twine). Cover. Refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   To fry turkey: Heat oil in large pot over burner to 400 degrees.
Attach thermometer to edge of pot; it must touch oil at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Remove turkey from refrigerator one hour before frying. Let it
sit on several layers of paper towels to collect any juices. The
bird should be very dry when placed in oil to prevent spattering.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare harness for turkey. Thread a metal hanger through turkey
and twist its ends together securely. Thread second hanger through
loop made by first. Secure ends well. Form a loop on end of second
hanger for handle. Make sure all wire ends bend inward so as not to
snag on pot's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Practice lifting turkey up and down over pan to adjust your
grip. Slowly and carefully lift turkey into oil to prevent
splashing.
</P>
<P>
   (Wear heavy apron, long sleeves and boots in case oil
splatters.)
</P>
<P>
   Turkey should be completely submerged. Check thermometer: It
should be at 350 degrees and remain so during cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   Cook 35-45 minutes at a steady 350 degrees (roughly 3 minutes
per pound). If turkey bobs, and does not remain submerged, use
long-handled grill fork to push turkey down or turn slightly so all
of turkey is cooked through.
</P>
<P>
   Remove turkey by carefully lifting out of pot. Have pan lined
with paper ready on sturdy table nearby. Place turkey _ breast side
down _ on pan and allow to sit for 20 minutes to drain before
removing leg holdings and carving.
</P>
<P>
   Cool oil in safe place away from foot traffic, children and
pets.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This turkey is best when still warm.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 main dish servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from ``The Prudhomme Family Cookbook'' by the
Paul Prudhomme family, Morrow, 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   To vary the flavor of the smoking, use herb bunches (rosemary,
thyme) placed directly over the chips, and use an aromatic liquid
such as apple cider or bourbon, to soak chips. Note: This can be
done in an outdoor smoker; use the recipe book that came with it
for instructions on using your smoker.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKED TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Time required: One hour preparation; about 2 1/2 hours cooking
time
</P>
<P>
   Equipment:
</P>
<P>
   2 large disposable foil turkey-roasting pans
</P>
<P>
   1 cake or cookie rack or any rack that fits inside roasting pan
</P>
<P>
   3 to 5 pounds wood chips for smoking (apple chips recommended )
</P>
<P>
   Liquid for soaking chips
</P>
<P>
   For the turkey:
</P>
<P>
   112- to 18-pound turkey, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   2onions, peeled, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2oranges, peel on, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2apples, peel on, quartered
</P>
<P>
   For rub:
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons crushed thyme
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons crushed sage
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Mix rub ingredients; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse and clean turkey, removing giblets for gravy. (Note: pan
drippings from smoked turkey are too bitter to use in gravy, so
plan to have extra stock on hand.) Stuff cavity with quartered
onions, oranges and apples.
</P>
<P>
   Rub turkey with seasonings; put leftover rub inside cavity and
rub cavity well. Let turkey sit with rub for about hour on rack
before smoking. Meanwhile, soak chips in desired liquid 30 minutes
before using.
</P>
<P>
   Place one turkey roasting pan over two burners. Put soaked chips
in bottom of pan. Cover with second roasting pan, and turn burner
to medium high until chips begin to smoke. (Make sure stove
ventilation fan is on.)
</P>
<P>
   Once chips are smoking, place turkey on rack, over chips. Cover
with second pan and turn heat to medium low. Check every 20 minutes
to see if chips need to be replaced; add more as needed to keep
smoke steady.
</P>
<P>
   Cook under cover 1 1/2 hours, over medium-low heat. Remove
turkey from smoker and place into pan that was used as cover.
</P>
<P>
   Finish roasting in the oven at 350 degrees. until done,
approximately 1 hour for a 12-pound bird; longer for a bigger bird.
Rely on a meat thermometer placed in meatiest part of thigh reading
175. (Note: A pop-up doneness indicator will work for this turkey.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove; allow turkey to stand on platter for 20 minutes before
carving. A pink tinge may be present; this is from the smoke and
does not indicate raw meat.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from Chef Roderick Smith of the Country Club of Florida,
Village of Golf.)
</P>
<P>
   Jan Norris writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
