<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, November 18, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ GIVERNY, France _ I came to see Claude
Monet's home and gardens. Claude wasn't home. He hasn't been for
quite a while. One of the fathers of Impressionism, he died in
1926, well into his 80s. Just as well. His eyes were gone by then
and he could no longer paint. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED
TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It was a routine stop at the
office ATM, and suddenly I felt as if I had been transported to Las
Vegas or an ``I Love Lucy'' episode. I asked for $120, but the
machine started spitting money at me: $480, all counted. That got
me to thinking. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Get ready, America. The Supreme
Court is juggling a Hail Mary pass lobbed from Texas that will
influence the national school prayer struggle. In Texas, where
football is religion and religion is a contact sport, a
church-and-state controversy that erupted at a public high school
football game will be decided by the republic's nine highest
constitutional refs. Their decision will be final. Let's roll the
videotape. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
