<HEADER>
A2405 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-SPROUTS-TIPS18-COX     11-17 0096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPROUTS-TIPS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freshness is forever foremost
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When buying Brussels sprouts, remember that freshest is best.
They shouldn't be stored more than two or three days. And smaller
Brussels sprouts are milder in flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid sprouts misted by one of those supermarket produce jets.
The sprouts need to be dry before being stored in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2406 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-WINE-COLUMN18-COX     11-17 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bid adieu to '99; bonjour to nouveau vintage reds
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all this millennium hoopla, you'd think some savvy wine
marketer would have come up with a way to slap ``Vintage 2000'' on
the label of their new bottling.
</P>
<P>
   Without a time machine, though, that's not quite feasible. Even
with today's technology, it still takes time to pick the grapes,
crush 'em, ferment the juice and bottle it.
</P>
<P>
   Not much time, mind you. That's why you'll have no problem
saying goodbye to 1999 with a glass of 1999 vintage wine in your
hand _ if you're so inclined. And if you want to get a head start,
stop by your local wine shop Thursday and check out the
viticultural equivalent of the new-model-year automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   It's that time again, to stain our teeth with the ruby-purple
juice we call Beaujolais Nouveau and with their lip-smackin'
cousins from other wine regions.
</P>
<P>
   Beaujolais Nouveau began as a phenomenon in the bars and bistros
of Beaujolais and Lyons in France. Every year, shortly after
harvest, eager locals would line up in cafes to fill their empty
pitchers from the winemakers' barrels, and a good time was had by
all. Presumably.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Paris got into the act, and the French government stepped
in to decree that Nouveau Day would occur each year on the third
Thursday of November. Wherever the Nouveau Beaujolais went,
importers had to agree not to sell the fermented grape juice before
that date (though nouveau wines from other regions faced no such
restriction).
</P>
<P>
   Georges Duboeuf, the Beaujolais region's top producer, has
proclaimed this year's nouveau celebrations ``the perfect way to
kick off millennium-end merriment.'' Duboeuf says exceptional
weather has produced an excellent vintage of nouveau, and while
it's hard to remember when wine producers called a press conference
to announce a lousy vintage, the descriptions of this year's wine
does tantalize.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Duboeuf's take on his '99: ``Beautiful deep crimson
tinged with purple. Held to the nose, it exhales scents of kirsch
amidst a red-fruit bouquet blending ripe strawberries, morello
cherries and blackcurrant with accents of cocoa, blueberry, rose
and violet. This wine offers more to savor than in previous years
and is harmonious, pleasing and captivating.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. That's a mouthful of wine for $9.69 a bottle. The
millennium awaits.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: markfisher(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
