<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU DON'T GET CASH, YOU WON'T PAY FEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's shocking news: A federal judge in California predicted
the other day that those new laws prohibiting banks from charging
fees for using their ATMs will turn out to be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Who woulda guessed?
</P>
<P>
   You know the deal. Voters in San Francisco and the City Council
in Santa Monica recently approved bans on the surcharges that most
banks levy on ATM withdrawals when the person taking the cash
doesn't have an account at the bank that provides the machine. The
judge made his prediction at a hearing in which he granted a
preliminary injunction that allows banks to continue charging ATM
fees while they challenge the new laws in court.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press report on the hearing said that the judge
ordered the banks to put the fees in escrow _ in case the laws hold
up and the money has to be returned to ATM users.
</P>
<P>
   A word to the wise: The ATM users might not want to hold their
breath.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a judge, a lawyer or a constitutional
scholar to see that municipal government shouldn't be butting into
private enterprise just because some consumers are feeling put
upon. Banks have a right to charge fees for the services they
provide; consumers have a right to avoid the fees by declining to
use the services.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that simple, as Ross Perot likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. I get annoyed when I'm trying to score some
cash out of an ATM and the dreaded message appears on the screen:
``So-and-So Bank charges a fee of $1.25 (or $1.50 or $2 or $2.50)
for the use of this machine.''
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't end there, sad to say. Not only do you have to
pay the bank that's churning out the money _ your own bank slaps
you with an additional fee as a penalty for using the other bank's
machine.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? Right after the ATM tells you how much it will
cost you to make a withdrawal, it sends you another message _ the
escape clause. You can push a button, get your ATM card back and
presto _ you're fee-free.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you don't get the money you wanted. But that's a
choice that is imposed on us each and every day in our free
enterprise system: Are we willing to pay the going rate for a
product or service, or would we prefer to do without?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, folks, but I can't jump aboard the indignation bandwagon
on this issue. It would be one thing if the fees were imposed
without giving the customer the option of terminating the
transaction _ although you'd have to figure that any customer with
half a brain would catch on after getting hit with a fee once or
twice.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is, there's no deception of any kind. The banks
couldn't be any more forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   And let's face it: When it comes to economic injustice, these
ATM fees are about as penny ante as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   So why all the wailing and gnashing?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, as we approach a new millennium, we just like to hear
ourselves wail and gnash. Maybe we feel so powerless in this age of
high-tech wonderment that we simply can't resist the urge to rise
up in protest over the slightest affront.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem in this case, as there is in so many
situations where consumers stage a revolt against some minor
inequity. In the end, they'll be worse off than they were before
the revolt.
</P>
<P>
   When San Francisco and Santa Monica decided to ban the ATM fees,
Wells Fargo and Bank of America decided to reprogram their machines
to reject cards other than their own. The message was clear: If you
don't want to pay for the convenience, then the convenience won't
be available.
</P>
<P>
   If the anti-fee movement should hold up in court and become a
nationwide phenomenon, rest assured that the banks will retaliate.
If we set out to punish the banks, we shouldn't be surprised if the
banks set out to punish us.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we'll suddenly be paying a fee to use our own bank's ATM.
Maybe those ubiquitous cash machines that we've become so dependent
upon will suddenly be harder to find than a parking space downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we'll end up wishing that we had shut up and paid the
fees.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
