<HEADLINE>
ATTN. EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos and graphics are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The US government is among the world's worst polluters. Federal
agencies have contaminated more than 60,000 sites across the
country. The cost of cleaning up the worst sites is officially
expected to approach $300 billion. And wherever US bases have been
located around the world, similar problems have occurred. In a
four-part series, the Globe explores the dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-I (Undated) _ &UR;  &LR; The United States government, which
acts as steward and protector of the nation's environment, is
itself the worst polluter in the land. By David Armstrong. PHOTOS.
GRAPHIC: 46 picas x 5 inches: ``Environmental challenges facing
federal agencies.'' (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-RANGES (Undated) _ &UR;  &LR; An estimated 50 million acres of
land have been used as bombing and target ranges. Cleaning them up
could be more expensive than the combined cost of every government
cleanup plan now under way. By David Armstrong. 675 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-FUDS (Undated) _ Hundreds of communities across the
country bought land on the cheap from the military in the decades
following World War II. It is only in the past few years, however,
that many new owners of the surplus military property have realized
that toxic stews are buried on their land. By David Armstrong. 1045
words.
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-II (Madapdap, Philippines) _ As countries like the
Philippines begin to come of age environmentally, they are
awakening to a toxic disaster at former and current US military
bases. By David Armstrong. PHOTOS. (3 takes) (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-BASES (Undated) _ With the US having a military
presence in more than 140 countries, the question of how Washington
should deal with complaints of overseas environmental contamination
is emerging as a prickly financial and diplomatic issue. By David
Armstrong. 700 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-III (Washington) _ Enforcement of the nation's
environmental laws is often haphazard and lax, creating a system
where major polluters operate with little fear of being caught or
punished. By David Armstrong. (2 takes) PHOTO. GRAPHIC: 45 picas x
6 inches: ``Cases reaching the courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-DEVILLARS (Boston) _ Some enforcement staffers
complain that New England EPA chief John DeVillars has compromised
the agency by intervening in cases of interest to congressmen and
questioning the actions of staff after a political inquiry. By
David Armstrong. 1900 words. PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-IV (Northbridge, Mass.) _ A relatively unknown group
of 200 EPA criminal agents have been responsible for some
high-profile prosecutions. But there are accusations that some
agents have bullied padded enforcement statistics on the backs of
small business owners accused of minor offenses. By David
Armstrong. (2 takes) PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the General National (a) category code.
</P>
