<HEADLINE>
CELTICS TO FACE REVVED-UP CAVALIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They still are not packing them in at Gund Arena. Blame
it on Fratello Hangover. The Cleveland Cavaliers are nothing like
their namesakes from the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   These guys run. They pass. They score. They're worth seeing.
</P>
<P>
   They've averaged nearly 106 points a game over the last four
games. Oh yes, they're also 4-2. They can score inside and out and
they still defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're quick in transition and they hold opponents to 41
percent shooting,'' Celtics coach Rick Pitino said Tuesday. ``They
are like Miami in that they have changed their style.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right. They don't plod. They don't squeeze the innards
out of the 24-second clock. New coach Randy Wittman not only has
his team playing at a much faster clip, he's also apparently
resuscitated Bobby Sura and Brevin Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve NBA teams are averaging 100 points a game or more. The
Cavs are one of them, even after scoring a Fratelloish 84 in a
season-opening loss to the Knicks. (They avenged that four days
later in Cleveland.) Only five teams are holding opponents under 42
percent shooting. The Cavs, despite the absence of big center
Zydrunas Ilgauskas, are one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've adjusted to the (new) rules,'' Pitino said. ``They
have three guards who can push it. They have a lot of weapons and
are very difficult to guard. They have great shooters who can hurt
you and they're getting a lot of easy baskets in transition.''
</P>
<P>
   When hoop historians start chronicling the Pitino Years in
Boston, they'll notice an early, heavy Cleveland effect. One of the
Ricktator's first free agent signings was ex-Cav Chris Mills, who
lasted less than a 24-second violation in Boston. There also was
the Boston meltdown in Gund Arena last year (113-86), which
prompted Pitino to say that he'd change his lineup (he didn't) and
that the Globetrotters played better defense (they did).
</P>
<P>
   Then there was last year's trade that sent backup center Andrew
DeClercq &UR;  &LR; to the Cavs for backup center Vitaly Potapenko and
Boston's first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino still likes the trade because he feels Potapenko is an
upgrade at the position. Entering Wednesday's game, both lads are
starting, DeClercq because of the foot injury to Ilgauskas,
Potapenko by default. DeClercq is averaging 11.2 points, 7
rebounds, and 1.17 blocks in 27.5 minutes. Potapenko is averaging
7.6 points, 7.9 rebounds, and 0.86 blocks in 26.9 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs selected heady Utah point guard Andre Miller with
Boston's pick, which turned out to be eighth overall. Miller is
averaging 8.8 points and 5 assists in only 19.2 minutes. He came in
for Knight against the Bucks last Saturday and had 13 points, 5
rebounds, 4 assists, and a steal in 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It's premature (or post-mature?) to say what the Celtics would
have done with the pick. They didn't interview anyone or bring in
anyone for a workout, but Miller is a possibility. So is Shawn
Marion.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs look at the Potapenko-DeClercq deal and see that they
swapped backup centers, got out of having to re-sign Potapenko
while having DeClercq locked in for three years at reasonable
numbers, and got a No. 1 pick on top of it all. The Celtics look at
the deal and see an improvement in the position and a rookie named
Adrian Griffin who's cheaper, and, for now, better than a lot of
players taken in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a trade that helped both teams. The Cavs are
happy. The Celtics are happy. Potapenko says playing against the
Cavs is ``no big deal'' because it happened twice after the trade
and he's used to his new digs. The game starts a rough stretch for
the Celtics. They host the Nets Friday, then have four
back-breakers with Miami (away) and the Pacers, Spurs, and Bucks
all at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pierce has made a dramatic recovery from what was termed a
strep throat Monday. ``It was a little sore throat,'' Pierce said
Tuesday after going through practice without incident. ``I really
felt bad but I got a lot of rest and I'm feeling much better. I got
through practice fine and didn't feel any weakness. I'll be ready
to go.'' That, of course, was just what Pitino wanted to hear.
``The wonders of penicillin,'' the coach said. ``It makes me feel
very good. I was beginning to feel very bad.'' . . . The Cavs could
have Lamond Murray on hand Wednesday. He has been out all season
with a sprained knee ligament . . . Calbert Cheaney (ankle) will
miss his fourth straight game with a sprained right ankle, but
Pitino is hoping Cheaney can play Friday against the Nets . . .
Pervis Ellison, meanwhile, is getting in better shape and,
according to Pitino, could start seeing some action. Ellison has
not played in the last three games . . . Pitino said he may use
Dana Barros and Doug Overton together in certain situations. One of
those would be Wednesday night, where Barros could defend the
smaller Knight and Overton, while still playing the point, could
defend the taller shooting guard . . . Pitino keeps preaching pass
before shoot, but after one drill Tuesday of many, many passes and
no shots, he said, ``That's great if you have a 45-second clock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
