<SLUG> BC-FBN-FAULK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE KEVIN FAULK WAS THE LONE PATRIOTS STANDOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Having just turned their prime-time network
showcase into ``Monday Night Foolball,'' the Patriots were
receiving their reward as they headed to the locker room: a cold
shower of abuse on a numbing November overnight. And this was from
their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing their local heroes with the personal touch, the
vitriolic gantlet above the runway from the north end zone to home
headquarters at Foxboro Stadium offered a special imprecation for
each participant in the 24-17 loss to the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe (15 for 36, 170 yards, 2 touchdowns, 3
interceptions, 3 sacks) was saluted for his abysmal passing in
bedeviling winds. Terry Allen (14 carries, 36 yards) was hailed as
the fulcrum of a running game that existed only in theory. Coach
Pete Carroll was exalted for going for a touchdown instead of a
sure field goal on fourth and goal from the 1 in the second
quarter, a play on which Allen got jammed back to the 2. The
members of the defense were acknowledged for getting shredded by
Jets quarterback Ray Lucas (18 for 31, 153 yards, 2 TDs, 2
interceptions, 0 sacks), a Patriot practice squad reject; running
back Curtis Martin (31 carries, 149 yards, 36-yard TD), a Patriot
refugee; and coach Bill Parcells, a Patriot until he could duck out
of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Only running back Kevin Faulk was spared.
</P>
<P>
   As Faulk proceeded among the last stragglers, the fans
disengaged their hands from making obscene gestures long enough to
give Faulk a brief burst of applause. He acknowledged it by holding
two fingers monentarily aloft _ a peace offering, obviously, for it
couldn't have been a ``V'' for victory. Then he politely walked
past the outstretched hands _ minus weapons _ extended from above.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that the crowd was taking pity on an innocent rookie;
it was, rather, that they appreciated Faulk for providing two of
the too-few highlights on their night out: a 95-yard bolt with a
kickoff return in the second quarter and a nimble 13-yard touchdown
reception in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the locker room, Faulk refused to accept any consolation
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the team loses, there's nothing positive that comes out
of it,'' he said. ``No matter what I did on special teams or
whatever, there's nothing positive that comes out of a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, but at least the second-round draft pick from LSU
displayed a couple of glimpses of potential.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had the Jets taken a 7-0 lead with 8:47 left in the
first half than Faulk fielded a John Hall kickoff 3 yards deep in
his end zone. He raced up the middle through an opening, bounced
off a tackle, and angled to his right in a footrace that he
eventually lost to Jets cornerback Marcus Coleman, who caught him
at the 8-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he'd gotten into the end zone,'' said Carroll, who was
in no mood for kudos in the wake of the debacle, ``because we
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this was the infamous series on which the Patriots
bypassed the field goal as three runs by Allen and a Bledsoe pass
to him produced nothing but frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it had been a singular effort by Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their kickoff team is one of the tops in the NFL,'' he said.
``I read the coverage and found a seam.''
</P>
<P>
   With 10:07 left in the game and the Patriots down, 24-3, Faulk
provided their first sign of a pulse when he took a screen pass to
the right by Bledsoe and threaded into the end zone, dragging
linebacker Roman Phifer the last few yards, to make it 24-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great call by Drew,'' said Faulk, ``and I got some
good blocking in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   His voice was a barely audible monotone, his eyes focused on the
floor in front of his locker, as he reluctantly described his
exploits. Faulk, who is basically serving an apprenticeship behind
Allen this year and carried only twice for 7 yards Monday, could
see no short-term benefits from his performance. In the long run,
he briefly conceded, it could yield dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me more confidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he immediately returned his focus to the grim overall
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still an awful lot we've got to work on,'' he said,
repeating his mantra: ``There's nothing positive that came out of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the trick is for Faulk and his teammates to consign Monday's
futility to history and focus on Sunday's visit to Miami in a game
that looms as an AFC East survival test for both the fourth-place
Patriots (6-3) and the first-place Dolphins (7-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a day to get over it, then we come back to work,''
he said. ``We've got to put it behind us. We got hurt bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Faulk, the pain might have been worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
