<HEADLINE>
ON THE WEB, WRITERS WRITE THEIR OWN TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the journalistic equivalent of the naked bootleg, the
football play in which the quarterback deserts his blockers and
runs alone against the opposing team. In this example, a seasoned
journalist abandons the comforting context (and the paycheck) of a
newspaper or magazine, and hangs out a shingle, saying to readers,
in effect: Forget the others! Read only me!
</P>
<P>
   Now rolling out on the naked bootleg is policy scribe Mickey
Kaus, formerly of the New Republic, Newsweek, and the online
magazine Slate. Sometime last spring, Kaus decided he had had
enough working for other people. Now he is the owner-occupier of
one of the more interesting single family dwellings on the Web:
kausfiles.com.
</P>
<P>
   This has been done before. Eight years ago, the popular Dallas
sports columnist Skip Bayless went solo with a fax-based
subscription service. He lasted four years, but the going was
tough. ``I thought people all across Dallas would subscribe to my
sports column just the way they subscribed to the newspaper,'' he
recalls. But instead they took his faxed columns to the copying
machine, effectively picking his pocket. Bayless is now a lead
columnist with the Chicago Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   The Web changes the terms of trade, as Matt Drudge and Harry
Knowles, the engaging omphalos of the movie site
aint-it-cool-news.com, have shown. Kaus pays $30 a month to a
company that runs his page off a computer in Reno, and he devotes
several hours a week to formatting his columns. Otherwise, he's
free and clear to succeed or fail on his own.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes kausfiles from the other stand-alone
journalism sites is that it's good. I enjoy Drudge and salute his
services to the nation, but, like Knowles, Drudge is a
hunter-gatherer, not a writer or reporter. Al Gore's former
roommate Bob Somerby runs a site called The Daily Howler
(dailyhowler.com), which, his education at the World's Greatest
University notwithstanding, is exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   Kaus is churning out Pretty Serious Journalism. The author of a
well-reviewed book on welfare, he writes punchy and informative
copy on a subject that puts normal people to sleep. He can be very
funny, and he's good in attack mode, especially when tilting
against the mediacracy. He administered a memorable mugging of the
New York Times's sloppy obituary of Judith Campbell Exner that led
to a backtracking ``Editor's Note'' in the newspaper of record two
days later.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago, he caught the esteemed Naomi Wolf pushing
the line that George W. Bush's campaign advisers are racist, a
piece of demagogy that might have been taken more seriously if
someone else had said it. I think the New Yorker's Joe Klein has
become more critical of Bill Bradley since kausfiles accused him of
``falling in love again,'' but Kaus isn't taking credit for that.
</P>
<P>
   What do journalists want? They want to maximize each of three
axes: money, freedom, and fame. So where does Kaus stand? For a
mainstream reporter, his freedom coefficient is close to 100, the
best possible score. For money, he gets a score of 50, which is
better than the zero he was earning for the first several months of
kausfiles' existence. Just last month, Slate editor Michael Kinsley
offered Kaus half a salary to give Slate readers a 24-hour jump on
Kaus's columns before he posts them on kausfiles. Kaus lives alone
in Manhattan, and Kinsley's mite ``pays the rent,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   What about audience, or fame? His ``unique browser hits'' per
week seem to increasing from the 5,000 level to the 8,000 level,
Kaus says tentatively. By comparison, Slate claims 1.4 million such
hits every week. It would be nice to attract advertisers, ``but I'm
not worrying about that this month,'' Kaus says. ``That's one of
the virtues of having no business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience will increase. But fame, well, fame always proves
elusive. Just after he launched the site, Kaus attended his 30th
reunion at Beverly Hills High School. ``Many of my classmates had
become California's leading doctors and lawyers, and inevitably,
one of them asked me what I do for a living,'' Kaus recalls. ``I
said, `I have a Web site.' And this guy paused for a moment, and
replied, `My daughter does, too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
