u f BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-17 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKS IN THE CHAINSAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a time, Albert J. Dunlap, former chief executive and
president of Sunbeam Corp., was the darling of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap's slash-and-burn approach to restructuring and layoffs
led to the nickname ``Chainsaw Al,'' a fitting moniker for a man
who, it turns out, was neither a compassionate employer nor an
astute businessman. But in a world where mere mention of a
restructuring or a downsizing could trigger higher stock prices,
shareholders adored Chainsaw Al. And so did many in the media.
</P>
<P>
   John A. Byrne, a senior writer at Business Week, was among a
handful of journalists and analysts who saw through the facade.
Byrne's new unauthorized biography, ``Chainsaw: The Notorious
Career of Al Dunlap in the Era of Profit-at-Any-Price''
(HarperCollins Publishing Inc., 1999), paints a troubling portrait
of how big egos and greed can destroy a company and the people it
employs.
</P>
<P>
   As I delved into the book, I found myself struggling to make
sense of Dunlap's popularity and the cadre of supporters who jumped
at his every command _ even when a command made no sense.
</P>
<P>
   One example: The 1997 shutdown of a 59,000-square-foot plant in
Bay Springs, Miss. Factory workers at the site produced the highly
efficient positive temperature coefficient (PFC) wires embedded in
Sunbeam's electric blankets, one of a handful of products that were
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Shutdown of the building, which Sunbeam occupied for free, would
save the company less than $200,000 in transportation costs. But
the transfer of equipment to a plant some 40 miles away would
result in as much as $10 million in relocation costs.
</P>
<P>
   According to Byrne, aides tried to convince Dunlap that the move
was foolhardy, but the Sunbeam chief wouldn't listen. When the
mayor launched a campaign to keep the plant open and accused Dunlap
of treating workers like ``depreciating pieces of equipment,''
Dunlap declared war.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 125 workers, or about 5 percent of Bay Springs' entire
population, lost their jobs as a result. Sunbeam offered them jobs
in Hattiesburg, but it was too far from the workers' homes and the
pay was too low. ``They couldn't drive 200 miles a day for $6 or $8
an hour, and he knew it,'' Mayor Jerry Evon Smith told Byrne.
Dunlap ``was offering them jobs so he wouldn't have to pay them
unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as workers in Bay Springs were trying to make sense of
the job cut and were worrying about their future, Dunlap's chainsaw
tactics were fast becoming role models for managers.
</P>
<P>
   The now 61-year-old ex-paratrooper was ousted by the Sunbeam
board in 1998 for not meeting earnings projections. But his legacy
lives on. One reason, the book suggests, is the pressure
institutional shareholders began placing on corporate managements
in the early 1990s, a shift that led to a significant change in the
way public corporations are governed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, a public company's goal was to manage a firm for
employees and customers as well as for shareholders, suppliers,
community residents, and the firm's own financial interests.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1990s, such companies had shifted their focus, making the
creation of shareholder value their primary goal. By appeasing
shareholders' yen for profits through downsizing, some US firms not
only realized short-term gains but were able to make a balance
sheet look a lot healthier than it was.
</P>
<P>
   Apply that formula to today's go-go economy, and it is easy to
see why thousands of workers are still losing jobs. When Chicago
outplacement firm Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas looked at layoffs in
1999, it found that more than 575,000 jobs have been cut thus far,
11 percent higher than in all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the best way to improve and grow a company is to
increase staff and assets, develop products, or venture into viable
new markets. Unfortunately, Dunlap chose the slash-and-burn route,
cutting 12,000 jobs at Sunbeam. And his impact on the company
didn't end there. ``In one year,'' says Byrne, ``Sunbeam's losses
totaled $898 million, a sum that wiped out all the net income the
company had made under'' both of its previous chief executives
``for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The book not only recounts Dunlap's business decisions, it
examines the man behind the title, including the elderly parents
Dunlap abandoned, the son he ignored, the ex-wife he abused, and
the dogs he adored.
</P>
<P>
   We learn, for example, that Dunlap's first wife, Gwyn, returned
to her family with her toddler son because of abusive treatment.
The daughter of a plumber, she wanted to make a better life for
herself and saw Dunlap as a man who would probably succeed at
fulfilling his own lofty dreams. The couple married in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   By 1963, Gwyn Dunlap had had enough. Barred from using the
family car and fearful of her husband's temper, she packed her bags
a year later and left with her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Christmas holidays of 1963, while at her parents'
home in New Jersey, Dunlap shoved his wife so hard that she fell
over a coffee table and onto the living room floor,'' Byrne writes.
``I will kill you, and step all over you and take that baby,''
Dunlap is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The need to overpower was also present in the executive suite.
In fact, working with Al Dunlap was a lot like going to war, the
author says. ``The pressure was brutal, the hours exhausting, and
the casualties high. . . At Sunbeam, Dunlap created a culture of
misery, an environment of moral ambiguity, indifferent to
everything except the stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would throw papers or furniture, bang his hands on his
desk, knock glasses of water off a table, and shout so ferociously
that a manager's hair could lift from his head by the stream of air
that rushed from Dunlap's screaming mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrne's book is packed with behind-the-scenes information, much
of it from people who were right there in Dunlap's orbit. Still,
the end of the book was something of a letdown for me, not because
Byrne failed in telling the tale, but because I wanted Dunlap to
get his.
</P>
<P>
   Chainsaw Al received his pink slip over the telephone. Maybe
Sunbeam's board was so afraid of the chief executive's roar, it
cowered at the thought of delivering the news in person. What a
pity.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he left the company, Dunlap was earning $26.9
million a year, which included $13.7 million to reimburse his
income tax bill for his company stock and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Where is he now? When he's not on the golf course or collecting
big fees on the lecture circuit, Chainsaw Al is relaxing in his
multimillion-dollar home in a gated community in Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, concerns or story ideas? Contact Diane Lewis at
work(at)globe.com or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
