<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-SMITH-CHASTAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH, CHASTAIN: THEY'RE INSEPARABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mr. Brandi Chastain and Mrs. Jerry Smith were talking last
spring about the odds of hitting the spousal double this year.
Wouldn't it be great if her US women's soccer team won the World
Cup and his Santa Clara women's varsity won the NCAA championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we dreamed of,'' says Smith, now that he and
his wife are on the verge of a cosmic parlay. ``This is something
that's almost storybook.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, dumped from the squad before the last Cup, boots home
the winning goal against the Chinese, rips off her jersey, and
instantly becomes rich and famous. Smith's headstrong Broncos are
21-0, have been ranked No. 1 since Day 1 and are favored to win
their first national title.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the next time husband and wife see each other, at
the Final Four in San Jose three weekends from now. ``I haven't
spent a full day with Brandi since before the World Cup began in
June,'' says Smith, whose team hosts plays to UCLA in a third-round
tournament match Saturday. ``We both have crazy schedules. Thank
God for cell phones. I don't think we'd ever talk to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   They knew the summer (for her) and fall (for him) would be
insane, but Smith and Chastain figured there'd at least be a few
weeks after the World Cup and before the college season when they
could be housemates again. ``Brandi was thinking about coming home
and hanging out and doing laundry,'' Smith says, ``but she was just
catapulted into the stratosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain found herself on the cover of Time, Newsweek, and
Sports Illustrated all in the same week. Whenever she answered the
phone, somebody like Nike or Volvo or Power Bar was offering to
sign her to a deal _ the endorsement tally is $2 million and
counting. ``I don't know half the things she's involved in,'' says
Smith. ``Brandi's schedule is so crazy I don't think I could keep
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been out flat himself ever since August as his Broncos
have run off to their best season ever. Santa Clara plays in the
West Coast Conference, which means twice-a-week treks from Malibu
to Spokane, plus a cross-country jaunt to face perennial champs
North Carolina (i.e. Mia U.). ``We certainly didn't dodge
anybody,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   Since Smith, whose teams have made 11 straight NCAA tournaments
and six Final Fours, is something of a campus icon, he's in demand
as a speaker at university events. This week, he'll be addressing
the Oakland alumni chapter. And since he's head regional coach for
the Olympic development program, Smith has to pencil another two
dozen events a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday, we played Brigham Young in a tournament game,''
he says. ``At 4:40, I was on a flight to Bozeman, Montana, then on
to Laramie, Wyoming, for site visits for summer camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain knows the routine well. She was Smith's full-time
assistant until her pre-Cup camp and travel obligations with the US
team convinced them that she had to scale back to volunteer status.
``The coach of the women's soccer team is a very demanding guy,''
Smith says. ``I wanted someone to be here so I wouldn't be buried
24/7.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith had his thing, Chastain had her thing and that was
understood even before they married a year before the 1996
Olympics. ``Brandi and I have always been our own people,'' he
says. ``We're very respectful of each of us having our own dreams
and aspirations. I love what I'm doing; she loves what she's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   When they were engaged in 1995, Chastain wasn't even in the
national team's player pool. She was dropped from the roster after
winning a gold medal in the inaugural Cup in 1991 and didn't get
back on until a players' strike a year before the 1996 Olympics
created an opening. ``I know what it was like for her not to be
involved all those years,'' says Smith. ``How crushing, how
devastating it was for her.''
</P>
<P>
   After Chastain won a gold medal in Atlanta and was invited to
train with the squad for this year's Cup, both she and Smith
decided that she should ride the wave as long as she could. That
meant residency camps, trips to Australia, Brazil, China, Portugal,
and Japan while Smith stayed home coaching in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   They still hadn't even had their honeymoon. They finally found
time during the summer of 1998. ``We spent it at the (men's) World
Cup in Paris,'' Smith says. ``Not a bad place for a honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chastain played in this summer's Cup opener before a full
house at the Meadowlands, Smith and his 11-year-old son from a
previous marriage took the red-eye from LA to watch. When Chastain
slammed home The Kick in the Rose Bowl, Smith was in the stands. He
watched his wife rip off her shirt in front of the world _ and
didn't find it odd.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch soccer every day, like Brandi and I do on TV,
it's hard not to see someone take off his shirt after scoring a
goal,'' Smith says. ``Taking off your shirt in soccer is like an
NBA guy slam-dunking and staring at his defender. People thought it
was Nike's idea. No. It was just the moment and the passion and
Brandi's wanting to do what her heroes had done.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Chastain or Smith was prepared for immediate fame and
fortune that followed. ``We were naive about what it all meant,''
he says. While Smith has been coaching his Broncos, his wife has
been frequent-flying all over the United States making appearances,
doing commercials, shooting a movie, playing on an indoor tour with
her teammates, hobnobbing with celebs.
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday afternoon, Chastain phoned him. ``I've got something
you're going to want to do,'' she told her husband. ``Tiger has
asked me if I want to play nine holes with him. Want to join us?''
``Love to,'' Smith sighed. ``But I've got to scout these games.''
</P>
<P>
   His volunteer assistant understands. The season takes priority.
When she returned home from the Cup for ``Brandi Chastain Day,''
Smith was out of town recruiting. He has been at the job for 13
years, taking Santa Clara from nowhere to national prominence
almost instantly. ``For the first three years, I was making $3,200
a season,'' remembers Smith, whose record is 221-50-14, fifth on
the all-time US list. ``Now, that's not even a month's salary.''
</P>
<P>
   His varsity has been ranked No. 1 once before, when Chastain was
a senior in 1990, but this year has been magical. The Broncos have
outscored opponents, 98-9, and allowed just one conference goal.
They dominated the WCC all-star list with six first-teamers and
three second-teamers, and have three All-Americas in forwards Mandy
Clemens and Jacqui Little and defender Nikki Serlenga.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, who wrote a big check from her post-Cup windfall to
the university's athletic booster fund (``Wow, you must be making
some money,'' her husband told her) has stayed true to her school
obsessively by cellular. ``My phone will ring minutes after a game
and it'll be Brandi saying, `Who played well?'', Smith says. ``We
were having a meeting once and (midfielder) Aly Wagner's phone
starts ringing. It's Brandi, wanting to know how practice went.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain did make it back last month for the Notre Dame game,
where she was being honored. ``Our first goal came on a penalty
kick and our whole team took off their shirts and waved them
around,'' Smith says. ``How appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain also returned for the final week of the regular season,
which was the longest time she and Smith had been together in more
than five months. ``That meant a lot to our players,'' he says,
``because they know that when Brandi's with us, she's turned
something down to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos make it to December, Chastain will be there on
the sideline. Then she and Smith will go off to the Caribbean and,
finally, exhale. ``We still haven't sat down and talked about it,''
he says. ``We haven't had a chance to catch our breath and say,
wow, take a look at all this stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
