<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON A BETTER FIT FOR BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's funny how no one seems to talk much about Joe
Thornton these days. In his first season, 1997, after he was the
first overall choice in the NHL draft, many wondered about
Thornton, who didn't get a lot of ice time with Boston and wound up
with three goals and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   Then last season, Thornton had a sterling campaign, racking up
41 points, 16 via goals. And he was the Bruins' No. 3 scorer in the
playoffs with 9 points (three goals) in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Now we seem to take him for granted, it seems. He's more mature,
and at 6 feet 4 inches, 220 pounds, he's 15 pounds bigger than he
was as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   In 18 games this year, Thornton has three goals and 12 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have been putting the puck in the net,'' said
Thornton, 20. ``I've been hitting the guys with some good passes.
As far as the goals, I'm not concerned. I'll keep on playing strong
and as long as I get a lot of chances, I'll help the team that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton skates on a line with Sergei Samsonov, who has 11
points, including five goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well together,'' Thornton said. ``He definitely
knows how to put the puck in the net. All I have to do is get him
the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever kidded Thornton about being the league's top
draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard about being the first player taken overall,
or this or that,'' he said. ``Everybody just goes out and plays
their game. Once you get on the ice, everybody's just occupied.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a couple of years in the league, they kind of forget
who's the first or second pick and stuff like that. You just go out
and play your best. They forget where you were drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   There were mild chuckles about how slowly Pat Burns brought
Thornton along that first season, but Thornton understood: He was
just a youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been sent back to juniors that year, I'm not sure how
last year and this season would have gone for me,'' he said.
``Every year I just want to get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things picked up the second half of last season and in the
playoffs; that's when I picked up the pace. And if I feel I'm
getting better each and every day, I think I'll get more points
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs last season were particularly exciting for
Thornton. He loved being on the ice in the important moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bunch of opportunities to play a lot last season in
the playoffs,'' he said. ``I had a good share of ice time in the
playoffs and it was really exciting to have that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton is better able to handle himself in tough situations
now, too. He doesn't back away from a fight. The weight he put on
while working out with fitness boss Mike Boyle in the summer of
1998 certainly gave him a boost, and Thornton kept his weight up
last summer while working with his personal trainer at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body just naturally found its weight,'' he said. ``I'm a
big guy and I just naturally filled out. Plus, I watch what I eat.
I only eat good food.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
