<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUARD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI QB HUARD NO FISH OUT OF WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ The Miami quarterback controversay that
really wasn't all that controversial turned more frothy here Sunday
when Damon Huard _ Dan Marino's, you know, controversial backup _
was sacked, smashed, and otherwise trash-compacted at Ralph Wilson
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Huard's line in a humiliating 23-3 loss to the powerful Buffalo
Bills: 9 for 25, 65 yards, no touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Huard's line after the loss: ``To me, the whole quarterback
controversy is absurd. My job right now is to back up Dan Marino.
If he's ready, he's the man.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, has been the incontrovertible, and not the
least bit controversial, truth in Miami for 16-plus seasons and
60,000-plus yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Dophins and Patriots meet Sunday at Pro Player Stadium in
what became an even more critical matchup for the New Englanders
after their 24-17 loss to the Jets (no strangers to QB
controversies themselves). Who will steer the Miami offense against
New England? If the nagging nerve in Marino's neck stops pinging,
then it undoubtedly will be the 38-year-old legend's game to lead.
</P>
<P>
   If it's not Marino, then the 26-year-old Huard, who went
undrafted in '96 after smashing all the passing records at the
University of Washington, will make his fifth straight start since
moving in as Marino's emergency replacement against the Patriots
Oct. 17. Prior to being shredded Sunday like a small order of
Buffalo wings (mild, very mild, with lots and lots of celery),
Huard had directed four consecutive wins _ including the 31-30
triumph over the Patriots _ connecting on 70 of 120 passes for 813
yards and 4 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   In the predictable, all-variables-covered world of the NFL,
Huard quickly had gone a long way in establishing himself not just
as Marino's stand-in, but also as the somewhat-surprising heir
apparent to the Marino monarchy. The Dolphins weren't exactly
crushing people with a Huard-led offense that had totaled 49 points
in 12 quarters, but the defense had limited the likes of
Philadelphia, Oakland, and Tennessee to only 22 points. Run-and-gun
wasn't getting 'em there, but the Dolphins were winning, and that
was enough to keep head coach Jimmy Johnson's hair straight (never
a doubt) and his eye fixed on Huard as his offensive maestro.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Sunday's setback, when the Dolphins were cruising along
at an impressive 7-1, Johnson pointed to two factors in Huard's
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, going to Europe and getting the experience, I think,
was really a big key for him,'' said Johnson. ``When he came back
from Europe a year ago, before last season, I said, `Man, this guy
is not the same guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 is the Dan Thing, Huard's attempt to craft himself into a
Marino clone, even in the way, some suggest, he walks and talks.
Nearly a dozen years Marino's junior, the 6-foot-3-inch, 215-pound
Huard has spent two-plus years practicing, working out, even
golfing (they played Ireland courses together last spring) like the
famed 6-4, 228-pound Marino. Some of his teammates refer to him
affectionately as ``Baby Dan.'' Up until the banging around he and
his teammates took against the Bills, it was working pretty well
for the one-time pride of the Frankfurt (Germany) Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan has been great,'' said Huard, who could be seen at the
sidelines in Foxborough last month, absorbing every word the
injured Marino hollered through his helmet during the
come-from-behind triumph. ``He tells me just to hang in there and
that the games will come down to the fourth quarter. He goes over
the pictures and the defenses. Everything that you can imagine that
somebody would do to help a guy, he's done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing Marino could do for Huard when faced with
the Bills. He was sacked three times and forced constantly to
release failed passes, a collection of underthrows and overthrows
that, in part, led Miami to only 101 yards of net offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to focus,'' said Huard, dismissing the fact that the
day's elements _ Buffalo's powerful defense and the wintry Western
New York wind _ were daunting. ``I obviously didn't focus enough.''
</P>
<P>
   As for that controversy that won't go away, Huard only wishes he
could have shrugged off Bruce Smith as easily as he dismisses the
notion that he's truly in a me-or-Marino mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't annoy me,'' he said. ``That's life, I guess.
There's always controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   That Huard is even in the mix is a surprise. As promising as he
was at Washington, there was still that incredible slight of having
gone unpicked in the '96 draft. In fact, the pros were so
unimpressed by his college numbers (5,692 yards, 34 touchdown
passes), he wasn't even invited to the NFL combine.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Miami Herald story, an NFL general manager revealed
that it was a former Seattle Seahawks personnel director who
ultimately denied Huard the opportunity to attend. The league's two
scouting services were split on Huard, according to the GM, and in
such cases it is the local NFL club that determines whether a
college player from its area gets invited.
</P>
<P>
   According to the GM, the Seahawks executive out-and-out
``trashed'' Huard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like it was personal or something,'' said the GM.
``Normally, you just say yea or nea, and go on. But it was more
than that. It was kind of strange.''
</P>
<P>
   More than three years later, his career resurrected, Huard
passed off the remarks as ``the highs and lows of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit one of those lows in the summer of '96 when he was
invited as a free agent to the Cincinnati Bengals camp. He threw
well, appeared in one exhibition game, even tossed a TD pass on his
first drive, but ultimately fell victim to the depth chart. No job.
No prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati would go into a constant case of QB shuffle over the
next three years, and a disappointed Huard went off on a job
search.
</P>
<P>
   A business major at Washington, he won a position with Football
Northwest, a Paul Allen company formed for the purpose of steering
through the proposal to build Allen's Seahawks a new stadium. Only
months after a Seahawks boss kept him from the combine, there was
Huard, thumping the tub for a billionaire in need of a tax break.
Seattle execs now credit Huard's lobbying, in part, for gaining
public approval to build the $300 million stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Huard signed as a free agent with the
Dolphins and impressed everyone enough with his arm and his
scrambling to stay all year, if only on the sidelines. Itching to
get in some action, he spent the spring of '98 in Germany,
directing the Galaxy to a 7-3 record and a spot in the World Bowl
before wrenching a knee. He hit on nearly 55 percent of his 290
passes and piled up nearly 2,000 passing yards and 12 touchdowns.
Most of all, the experience got his game charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned how much I enjoyed playing the game,'' he recently
told the Florida Sun-Sentinel. ``Really, over there, it's not very
sophisticated. We didn't practice all day and watch film all night.
You just went over and played the game. Our offense was as simple
as simple can get.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back,'' said Johnson, ``and had a flair for the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   What Huard can do that Marino can't _ or hasn't had to _ is run
when necessary. No one ever has gotten rid of the ball faster than
Marino. Anyone else has to make up for a less-than-lightning
release, and Huard has done that with his legs. He'll routinely run
out of the pocket and search for options downfield. He'll take the
sack if necessary; the Patriots piled him under nine times and
knocked him down a dozen more.
</P>
<P>
   As bad as Sunday was, Johnson didn't once look over his shoulder
and summon ex-New Englander Scott Zolak into the action. Huard went
down throwing, his final toss to Tony Martin overthrown while _
what else? _ under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' said Huard, looking ahead to Sunday,
a game he might or might not play, depending how this week's
controversy plays out. ``I'm sure it will be a hard-fought game,
just as it was a few weeks ago. That's the way our conference is
going to be, a rat race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
