</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBOLDENED JETS REACTED TO OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Steve Sidwell couldn't have emphasized the
importance of preventing ``the big play'' more than he did in the
15 days between games.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots defensive coordinator looked at the first eight
games and found 10 running plays of 15 or more yards and 18 pass
plays of 15 or more yards. He called this situation ``lousy.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a situation the Patriots corrected in Monday night's
24-17 loss to the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just aren't tackling well,'' said defensive tackle Chad
Eaton. ``Sid always tells us we're a good defense but we're poor
tacklers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very basic. For our defense to work, we have to tackle.
It's that simple. There were a few times when we had Curtis
(Martin) stopped but he got past us. That's what I'm talking about.
We've got to make the plays when we have a chance to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, they couldn't prevent a Ray Lucas scramble
for 17 yards that may have given the young quarterback confidence
that he could at least run if everything else failed. That drive
ended in Lucas throwing an interception, which is what the Patriots
thought there'd be more of.
</P>
<P>
   But that interception didn't rankle Lucas. He got bolder.
Knowing that Martin was having success running the ball opened up
the passing game for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had stopped Curtis, it would have meant everything for
us,'' said Eaton. ``Ray was throwing those dinky passes and he was
completing them because we bit on the play fakes because they were
running the ball so well.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that one big play snowballed into another.
</P>
<P>
   A 26-yard pass to Wayne Chrebet early in the second quarter got
the ball to the Patriots' 18, and Lucas soon took the Jets in for
their first score.
</P>
<P>
   After the Patriots answered with a field goal, Lucas wasn't shy
about going to the air on the first play. He got another gain of
greater than 15 yards in the form of a diving 17-yard grab by
Keyshawn Johnson on the left sideline.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the defense to get stung by the run.
Three plays later, Martin took a straight handoff, quickly kicked
it out to the right, and was gone for a 36-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The right side of the Jets' line tied up the left side of the
Patriots' line. Linebacker Chris Slade missed Martin after a few
yards and that sprung him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make adjustments on the field, and at that point
the crowd noise was so high I'm not sure everyone heard the call,''
said Eaton. ``We might have had some guys playing one defense and
the other side playing another. It was miscommunication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people are quick to blame the coaching, but it's not
them. We have to make those adjustments on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   With 48 seconds remaining in the half, the Patriots fell asleep
on defense. They allowed a 15-yard pass on first down again, Lucas
to Chrebet, following a Marcus Coleman interception. That put the
Jets in business at the Patriots' 21. With New England thinking
pass, the Jets ran, with Ray Anderson scampering 10 yards. Three
plays later, a very confident Lucas fired an 11-yard touchdown pass
to wide-open tight end Fred Baxter to make it a 21-3 game.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots made adjustments in the second half, holding the
Jets to 3 points. The longest pass play was 14 yards, from Lucas to
Johnson, but it was during a 19-play drive that ate up 11:23,
including the final 8:52 of the third quarter. That led to the
field goal, which made it a 24-3 game.
</P>
<P>
   While the Patriots were better at preventing the big play, they
were terrible on third down. During the drive, Martin ran for 3 on
third and 1, Lucas passed to Johnson for 14 on third and 12, Lucas
passed to Johnson for 8 yards on third and 7, and Anderson run up
the middle for 4 yards on third and 2. The only time the defense
held was on third and goal at the 8.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ran roughshod for 149 yards on 31 carries, a 4.8-yard
average. Stopping him was priority No. 1 heading into the game, and
if that priority had been met, the Patriots would have taken their
chances with Lucas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
