<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2511 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NET-POWER-BOS &LR;      11-17 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-POWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET-BASED LIAISONS IMPROVE ENERGY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How simple it used to be to buy electricity. Your local utility
ran a power plant, maybe bought some power from Canada on summer
afternoons, and every month sent you a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a growing number of states, deregulation and technology
have turned the electric business into a boggling picture of
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Power plants now compete with each other for business. So-called
aggregators representing groups of customers bicker with brokers
and traders to get the best deal. And an hour-by-hour spot market
sets the ultimate price for power.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it has made huge inroads into other types of
business-to-business commerce, the Internet is playing a large and
rapidly growing role in the electricity market. On-line electric
sales will exceed $1 billion this year, and could reach $100
billion within five years, according to Forrester Research of
Cambridge, Mass. US consumers buy about $215 billion worth of
electricity annually, some of it sold under contracts that change
hands several times, pumping up the on-line sales figure.
</P>
<P>
   While hardly household names yet, two companies are playing what
many observers call starring roles in the new world of
Internet-based electric marketing: privately held Enermetrix.com of
Maynard, Mass. and Houston Street Exchange of Portsmouth, N.H., a
unit of BayCorp Holdings Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   While aimed at slightly different parts of the market between
power plant and plug, Houstonstreet.com and Enermetrix.com are
offering dramatically more efficient systems for buying and selling
electricity _ and ultimately many other types of energy _ than are
the old-line world dominated by brokers trading phone calls and
faxes all day long.
</P>
<P>
   (Essential.com of Burlington, Mass., meanwhile, is trying to
become a one-stop shopping center for not just electricity but home
heating fuel, telephone, and Internet access, although currently it
acts as a sales agent for only one electric company, New England
Electric System's AllEnergy unit, and only in limited parts of
Massachusetts.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is having an explosive impact on this industry,
and we haven't really seen all the ways that the Internet is going
to act on this industry,'' said Ethan Cohen, an energy consultant
with The Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely estimated that last year $70 billion worth of
electricity was traded, double the amount a year earlier and
probably eight times the 1997 level. (A large fraction of that sum
represents contracts to sell power that changed hands several times
before the producer delivered it.)
</P>
<P>
   About 100 companies have licenses from the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission to trade electricity in the United States,
and about half of them are active in Northeastern markets.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason these companies even exist is that in
Massachusetts and a growing number of other states, utilities have
been forced out of the power generation business to promote
stronger competition and lower prices for producing electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Edison of today, for example, operates as a regulated
monopoly carrying power from producer to buyer, although virtually
all of the residential power it supplies is through a ``standard
offer'' deal of 3.7 cents per kilowatt-hour because little
competition has developed for home customers.
</P>
<P>
   The kinds of deals being made, a growing number through the Net,
can range from a hastily negotiated contract to provide power to
replace a plant that suddenly goes down, to a 12-month pact to
supply a group of municipal governments with their power, to a
purely speculative resale of a pending contract in response to
market-moving weather forecasts or changes in the price of natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Enermetrix, based in the former Digital Equipment complex in
downtown Maynard, likes to compare itself to Sabre, the American
Airlines-owned ticket reservation system that allows travel agents
to compare various flights and fares on different routes.
</P>
<P>
   Through Enermetrix, buyers representing hundreds of companies
can shop around for gas and electric contracts from about 50
suppliers and brokers, then close the deal on line.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Street, in contrast, acts as a ``platform'' for more
than 80 electric suppliers and brokers to make deals among
themselves. Typically it carriers 10 to 15 bids each morning for
different amounts of power at different places for different time
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in the Northeast in early July, Houston Street quickly
expanded by mid-September to cover all 12 major power grids in the
continental United States. It hopes to go public next year.
</P>
<P>
   Both sites allow buyers and sellers to negotiate anonymously up
to the point where they strike a deal, at which point they are
responsible for settling accounts and paying a fee to Enermetrix or
Houston Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're growing like crazy,'' said Enermetrix chief executive
John Gaus, who predicts his company will double its current
40-person employment roster within a year.
</P>
<P>
   The company has received $6 million in venture capital financing
and is halfway toward amassing a third round of $20 million in
venture investment, Gaus said. Customers buying electricity through
Enermetrix-arranged deals include the Pittsburgh airport, Benjamin
Moore Paints, and about 11,000 Connecticut businesses that have
formed a buying group. Enermetrix said customers typically save 19
percent on their power bills.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other dot-coms that launch a concept and then try to
find customers, Enermetrix was founded in 1995 as North American
Power, brokering deals by fax and phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We developed the business first and then found a great tool to
do our business through the Internet'' starting in January 1998,
said company president Jeff DeWeese, a former Boston Edison
engineer who cofounded the company with Gaus. ``It's like comparing
e-mail to the Post Office, the efficiencies are so dramatic,''
DeWeese said.
</P>
<P>
   Within several months, Gaus said, Enermetrix will add coal, fuel
oil, gasoline, and other energy products to its market. It also has
plans to expand to Europe, Japan, and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Houston Street chief Frank W. Getman Jr. said, ``We've
basically created a great plaform for trading whatever the hell you
want to trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Enermetrix currently views itself as having no direct
competition, to some extent by design. ``They've been kind of a
sleeper so far in terms of marketing,'' said The Yankee Group's
Cohen, particularly in contrast to Houston Street, which made a big
splash at a recent energy industry convention with a sweepstakes
giving away a Cobra sportscar.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Street, based in offices near the Pease International
Jetport, is battling for business with so-called proprietary
systems offered by Altra Energy, Bloomberg, and Enron. Their
systems generally require people to buy software or special trading
devices before they can start doing deals. Houston Street, in
contrast, merely requires a customer to open an account and have a
computer that can get on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   However, Getman said, ``Our real competition is the phones,
trying to break the inertia and get people off the phones and onto
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Street takes a sliding-scale fee of 1 to 2 cents per
megawatt-hour traded, reduced as the volume traded increases. While
it sounds paltry, given that some 3 billion megawatt-hours were
traded in 1998, had Houston Street been able to handle every one of
those traded, it could have grossed over $30 million. And trading
volume is projected to explode.
</P>
<P>
   In its first four weeks, Houston Street said it handled 270,000
megawatt-hours of deals (worth about $2,500 in commissions), but
since then it has declined to publicize trading figures.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies face a Catch-22, in that more companies will not
sign up to participate until more companies have signed up and
participate. Gaus said his sense is that ``Houston Street gets a
lot of traffic from people looking at prices, but they don't get a
lot of people doing deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob LaRochelle, a Virginia-based energy trader who works for
Central Vermont Public Service, said of Houston Street, ``It's a
pretty slick site,'' but said he probably does barely 10 percent of
his deals through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically there just needs to be more people being active on
it,'' LaRochelle said. ``Like anything, it takes time for people to
get comfortable with it.'' LaRochelle still makes heavy use of a
``squawk box'' on his desk where traders call out offers during the
day, and is leery of posting bids on too many computer systems in
case he suddenly needs to yank them back because electric prices
have soared or plunged.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, The Yankee Group's Cohen said Enermetrix is like a
Sabre airline reservation system that only has three or four
airlines. Enermetrix now counts 50 so-called sell-side members _
suppliers of electric and natural gas _ and seven buyers who
collectively represent thousands of businesses. Buyers include AEP,
Control Solutions, Scana, Unitil, and the 11,000-member Connecticut
Business Industrial Association.
</P>
<P>
   Unitil, the Hampton, N.H., parent of Fitchburg Gas &AMP; Electric
and two small southern New Hampshire utilities, is both a heavy
user and a financial backer of the site.
</P>
<P>
   While most New England utilities have been swept up in a
frenzied drive to merge, Unitil chief executive Robert G.
Schoenberger said he is far more interested in exploiting the
capacities of Enermetrix to get new customers than in merging with
a bigger utility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a real role for a company to help
customers negotiate their way through this maze of services and
offers,'' Schoenberger said. ``What customers are telling us is,
`We don't care if you own the pipes and wires _ we want the
service.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be on the side of the industry where the most
innovation is going to come from, and I don't think it's the
hard-assets side,'' Schoenberger said. ``We want to own the
customer relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
