<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-IPOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET-RELATED IPOS LEAD IN THE QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten companies New England launched their intial public offerings
between July and September, but investors were seriously enamored
with just three of them, sending their stock prices soaring.
</P>
<P>
   And what does the trio have in common? The Internet and the
World Wide Web, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Engage Technologies Inc. of Andover, Mass. has seen its shares
more than triple to 47 7/8, after raising $82.4 million at $15 a
share on July 20. The company, which provides Internet marketing
services, has seen its market valuation soar to more than $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Engage went public, ART Technology Group of
Cambridge, Mass., which provides a suite of Internet customer
relationship management and e-commerce software, raised $54.8
million in its IPO. Not only has its stock price soared from its
$12 offering to close at 67 3/16 Friday, but five days ago the
nine-year-old company successfully launched a second public
offering, selling 4.5 million shares, raising $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   SilverStream Software Inc., may be considered the most
successful of the trio, based on the rise of its stock. In its
mid-August IPO, it sold three million shares at $16 each and
watched its price nearly double in the first day of trading. Since,
it hit a high of 94 last Wednesday, and closed at 80 on Friday. The
three-year-old, Burlington, Mass. company develops Internet
software that helps firms create their own e-commerce software.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the other seven companies have also seen their stock
prices rise since their IPOs. The largest offering by far was
Fairchild Semiconductor International Inc. of South Portland,
Maine, which was spun out as a separate company from National
Semiconductor Corp. in a management-led buyout in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In early August Fairchild, one of Maine's largest corporations
with 8,000 employees, sold 20 million shares at $18.50 each,
netting $345 million after underwriter fees. Shares closed Friday
at 26, giving Fairchild a $2.3 billion market valuation.
</P>
<P>
   The only two IPO companies whose shares have declined are both
nontechnology firms. Cambridge-based Biopure Corp. raised nearly
$38 million at $12 a share, but has since seen its stock fall,
closing Friday at 10 5/8. The biopharmaceutical firm has developed
an emergency blood substitute for dogs and is developing another
blood product for people.
</P>
<P>
   The second, Yankee Candle Co., is a 30-year-old business that
raised $97.5 million. Despite reaching profitability this year, its
stock has seen a modest decline from its IPO price of 18, closing
Friday at 15 7/8. Based in Whately, Mass., the company has 85
stores in 26 states, including its South Deerfield, Mass. emporium
that attracts 2.5 million visitors annually.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the overall climate clearly shows that IPOs are back in
fashion. In last year's third quarter, only six firms went public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
