u f BC-VENTURE-QUARTER-BOS &LR;      11-17 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET START-UPS DRAW LOTS OF VENTURE CAPITAL IN 3D QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet start-ups and high-speed communications firms accounted
for more than two-thirds of the $926.7 million venture capitalists
poured into New England companies over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   That hefty third-quarter investment total was below the record
$1.07 billion set in the second quarter. Still, it was almost 70
percent higher than the $550.8 million invested in the year-ago
quarter, according to the Boston Globe/PricewaterhouseCoopers Money
Tree survey.
</P>
<P>
   Between July and September, 113 New England companies, most of
them in Massachusetts, received venture funding, with the region
accounting for 10 percent of nationwide investments. High-speed
communications and software and information services _ the latter
dominated by business-to-business Internet companies rather than
those aimed at consumers _ accounted for more than half of those
113 deals, and for nearly 71 percent of the $926.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers made New England second to Silicon Valley in
funding, which reported $3.324 billion in 298 companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the East Coast as a whole is catching up. The New York
metropolitan area ($688.5 million in 68 deals) and the
Washington/Baltimore metropolitan area ($638.1 million in 61 deals)
both made significant gains, mostly from one or two large deals.
The increased funding in those regions was predominantly due to
business-to-business Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, venture capital investment in the third quarter rose
to a record $9.04 billion, far exceeding the previous record of
$7.64 billion in the second quarter and 138 percent higher than the
$3.79 billion recorded a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, in the first nine months of 1999 venture capital
investments nationally amounted to more than $21 billion, compared
to about $14 billion for all of 1998, noted Patrick M. Gray, a
partner in the PricewaterhouseCoopers Global Technology Industry
group.
</P>
<P>
   The summer period is usually when venture capital funding slows
down. But this year the pace remained hot, as 993 companies
nationwide received funding, compared to 707 a year ago. At the
same time, average funding per company increased 70 percent to $9.1
million, compared with $5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is further evidence that technology is driving the US
economy: technology companies added to the Dow Jones industrials,
the Nasdaq breaking 3000, a selective but strong IPO market, and
venture capital filling the pipeline with the companies of the
future,'' said Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies are changing their focus. In the crowded
business-to-consumer Internet arena, firms need access to millions
of customers, many of whom are impulse buyers shopping for
relatively low-priced items, and with a random chance of becoming
repeat customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the business-to-business model operates quite differently.
Generally, corporate customers spend a lot more money, with formal
contracts and terms and high expectations for customer service.
While consumers often deal directly with an electronic commerce
provider, such as Amazon.com, the business-to-business marketplace
often relies on intermediaries _ companies that perform a variety
of sales and marketing functions for an e-commerce provider.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest of those intermediaries to receive funding in
the third quarter was MarketSoft Corp. of Lexington, Mass., a
40-employee firm whose customers include Compaq Computer Corp. and
Covad Communications, a provider of high-speed communications
services to businesses. The 20-month-old company, led by founder
and chief executive Greg Erman, received $15.25 million in
second-round funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned down $10 million more,'' said Erman, who nearly
three years ago sold Waypoint Software, an Internet company he
founded, to Open Market Inc. of Burlington, Mass. ``The
business-to-business space is heating up, as the amount of money
available has increased exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet intermediary, Bow Street Software Corp. of
Portsmouth, N.H., is attracting significant attention trying to
automate some of the selling processes and provide directory
services. Initially funded by Silicon Valley venture capital
powerhouse Kleiner Perkins Caulfield &AMP; Byers, Bow Street garnered
$20 million in funding in the third quarter. The company, whose
software costs $250,000 per year, recently helped an insurance
company's sales force get policy quotes to its customers over the
Internet in 10 minutes as opposed to three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think that the Internet has done what a lot of people
predicted in commoditizing transactions for consumers,
business-to-business is infinitely harder, because you build
long-term relationships,'' said Jack Surface, Bow Street cofounder
and chairman. ``You are measured more for the services you provide
to customers, since the products you are selling are the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Bow Street boasts a dozen major corporate clients, including
Federal Express, the Sabre airline reservation unit of AMR Corp.,
A. C. Nielsen, and Nortel, plus partnerships with IBM, Microsoft,
Oracle, and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Surface and others say that within five years,
business-to-business companies will command 80 percent of Internet
usage, with just 20 percent for business-to-consumer.
</P>
<P>
   For the Internet to remain robust, higher-speed switching
hardware and software will be needed. Of the $926.7 million raised
in the quarter, nearly $330 million went to companies such as Avici
Systems of North Billerica, Mass., which raised $44 million from
eight venture firms in a third-round financing.
</P>
<P>
   Not far behind are five companies that each raised more than $20
million. One of those is iBasis Inc., which received $25.1 million
in mezzanine financing this summer, only to launch an initial
public offering Nov. 10. Its stock has already more than doubled,
from 16 a share to a 34 3/4 close Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller amounts went to several niche companies such as
eTang.com Inc. of Concord, Mass., which received $4.5 million in a
first-round financing to develop an Internet portal from mainland
China, and HighWired.com, which raised $7 million to focus on
developing an on-line network for public and private high schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the largest investment in the third quarter went to
StorageNetworks Inc. of Waltham, Mass., among the early leaders of
firms providing on-line data storage services to large
corporations. The firm received $50 million in second-round
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable third-quarter investments:
</P>
<P>
   --Shuttle America Corp. of Windsor Locks, Conn., which recently
began an air service between Hanscom Field and several Northeast
cities, received nearly $1.5 million in second-round financing.
</P>
<P>
   --Zoots Inc. of Newton, Mass., which provides dry cleaning
services with Internet links in 12 Massachusetts communities,
received $38 million _ the third-largest investment behind
StorageNetworks and Avici Systems.
</P>
<P>
   --iDolls of Manchester, N.H., a spinoff of KidGalaxy Inc.,
received $7 million in first-round financing to market children's
dolls over the Internet, from Stardust Classics to the
top-of-the-line Gotz collection from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   --Nearly $60 million was invested in six biotechnology companies
_ the highest amount since the fourth quarter of 1997 _ led by a
$19 million second-round financing for Variagenics Inc. of
Cambridge, which is studying genetic variations to develop more
personalized drugs. Nationally, New England's biotechnology
investments were second to the $81.2 million invested in Silicon
Valley biopharmaceutical firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotechnology start-ups are not growing in other parts of the
country other than New England and Silicon Valley,'' said Gray of
PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   The third-quarter survey results were based on a package of
questionnaires, with a follow-up fax and telephone survey in which
504 venture capitalists participated, representing a 62 percent
final response rate, according to PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
