<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      11-17 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLFEISMS; POOR SPORTS; SHERMAN'S BAD RAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To call Tom Wolfe a peerless social observer is to get it only
half right, if the term observer implies a sociological neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes the man in the white suit such fun to read is
that his technicolor descriptions of the contemporary scene are
salted with withering opinions. Wolfe is at it again in this
month's edition of the British magazine Tatler, this time with a
twist: He appraises the United States at the turn of the millennium
from the perspective of one writing from the future.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some of his observations are recycled or updated
versions of previously published Wolfeisms, as when he relocates
the ``Masters of the Universe'' from Wall Street to Silicon Valley.
He argues, as he has for 20 years, that the term ``working class''
is laughably outdated at a time when ``the average electrician,
air-conditioning mechanic or burglar alarm repairman lived a life
that would have made the Sun King blink.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not they buy that, future observers will probably
agree with Wolfe's description of America 2000 as a land consumed
by a ``feverish emphasis on sex and sexiness,'' where ``sexual
stimuli bombarded the young so incessantly and intensely, they were
inflamed with a randy itch long before reaching puberty.'' The 21st
century may also be as amused as Wolfe is by some of the silly fads
our intelligentsia succumb to. Here is Wolfe on deconstructionism:
``Oddly, when deconstructionists required appendectomies or bypass
surgery or even a root-canal job, they never deconstructed medical
or dental `truth' but went along with whatever their
board-certified, profit-orientated surgeons proclaimed was the last
word.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sports is anything but a game to those who run it, as we are
reminded yet again in Tennis and Esquire magazines this month.
</P>
<P>
   In Esquire, bicyclist Lance Armstrong describes the ugly
backdrop to one of the best sports stories this year: his comeback
from cancer to win the Tour de France. Armstrong recounts the
coldblooded way his old team discarded him when he was diagnosed
three years ago. No other teams stepped forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought people would be jostling for the chance to be the
good guys, to help with the comeback,'' he says. ``But there were
no good guys. . . . Nobody was really out to give the cancer kid a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong made his own breaks, but it's clear that any illusions
about his sport have been permanently shattered. ``Cycling is so
much chew-'em-up, spit-'em-out, rider du jour _ anybody can be
replaced,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That same principle animated the lords of Wimbledon, who three
decades ago saw nothing wrong with awarding men's champion Rod
Laver nearly three times as much prize money as women's champion
Billie Jean King. But then King was relatively lucky: At smaller
tournaments, men got up to 12 times the prize money women did.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis magazine describes how King, Rosie Casals, and a
redoubtable handful of other players fought to change their world
by forming their own tennis tour in 1970. Within three years, women
were receiving purses equal to men's. An ironic sidelight: The
economic lifeline for the upstart tour came from none other than
Philip Morris, which saw a chance to promote its new cigarette for
women, Virginia Slims. It may have been the last time a cigarette
company played the good guy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With irony and cynicism suffusing the newsstands, there's
something invigorating about the near-utopian optimism of Astronomy
magazine's forecast for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomy sees big things ahead for the new millennium,
including possibly the discovery of life-bearing planets and the
answer to a couple of questions that have been nagging at me
personally for a while now: ``Where do we come from, and are we
alone in the cosmos?''
</P>
<P>
   According to associate editor Robert Naeye, the answer could
come from a NASA program called Origins that relies on the
so-called Next Generation Space Telescopes. Equipped with a large
mirror and ultrasensitive infrared detectors, these telescopes
apparently will make the Hubble space telescopes look like the
space paperweights Dave Barry says they are. According to Naeye,
the newfangled telescopes will be able to peer so far back in space
and, thus, time that they ``will see the first galaxies assembling
a few hundred million years after the Big Bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarring, isn't it, how quickly science fiction morphs into
science fact nowadays?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William Tecumseh Sherman's march through Georgia is one of those
long-ago events that can still start fierce arguments _ and
historian Victor Davis Hanson is likely to start some doozies with
his lucidly argued brief on behalf of Sherman in American Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman is seen in many quarters, especially in the South, as a
bloodthirsty barbarian who invented ``total war'' as he terrorized
civilians on a burning path through Georgia to the sea. But Hanson
contends that Sherman has been misunderstood and misrepresented. He
writes that the fierce-visaged general and his 60,000 soldiers
overwhelmingly confined their energies to the destruction of
property, with very few killings or rapes during the march. The
march ``redefined'' the Civil War, in Hanson's view, and saved many
thousands of lives in the South and North alike.
</P>
<P>
   Horrific as the destruction was, the civilians of the South _ as
defenders and economic beneficiaries of slavery _ did not exactly
occupy the moral high ground, Hanson points out: ``Once the free
Southern leadership and its citizenry chose to fight and kill on
behalf of human bondage, the destruction of their private property
. . . took on the logic of retribution and atonement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
