<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2522 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-TURKEY-2TAKES-BO     11-17 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TURKEY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARM YOURSELF WITH TURKEY TRUTHS _ AND SURVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanksgiving is demanding on many levels. First come the
horrible traffic and long lines at the grocery store. Then, the
menu boasts a main course so large, nothing else fits into the
oven. And when the other dishes do go in _ well, it seems like
they're all orange. There are the individual quirks to attend to,
as in family members who like, and expect, certain things. Those
items were probably instituted around the time you were born. Now
that Thanksgiving is held at your house, you're wondering, do you
have to go out and buy marshmallows?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the guest list situation and family dynamics in
general. Let's face it. Not everyone in attendance would be there
if they weren't blood relations. But look at it this way: Almost
everyone in every corner of the country is hosting or attending a
Thanksgiving celebration, and they're going through all of this,
too. Try a little Pollyanna.
</P>
<P>
   Like so: Thanksgiving is a chance to smooth family wrinkles and
eat well. The fall harvest boasts some of the finest cooking
ingredients. And don't worry about the small stuff: Everything will
get cooked or reheated, because you have all day. Tom Turkey is the
most patient guest of all.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips to get you through the day.
</P>
<P>
   First, set the table. Do this a couple of days in advance and
make place cards. Position your most accommodating guest next to
your boorish uncle, and try to solve all those other little
personality problems. Don't seat husbands and wives next to each
other, and alternate guests like this: exuberant, bashful,
exuberant, bashful.
</P>
<P>
   Deal with the main course. The most-often-asked question is: How
long does it take to thaw a turkey? In the refrigerator (breast up,
in a pan large enough to hold it), it will take 1 day per 4 pounds.
There are other methods, such as thawing in cold water (see chart),
but we don't recommend thawing in the microwave because it's not
safe. Our advice: Buy a fresh, natural turkey or a kosher turkey.
If you really care about the taste, these do taste better. When the
turkey is done (see accompanying chart), even if it's sooner than
you expected, remove it from the oven and let it sit in a warm
place. It's fine for 1 hour. Turkeys can't be carved right away,
anyway. You need to leave them on the counter for at least 20
minutes so the meat reabsorbs some of its juices, tastes moist, and
carves more smoothly. The best system is to time dinner so the
turkey comes out of the oven 1 hour before the guests arrive, you
can reheat the side dishes, and everyone can have something to
drink (including you).
</P>
<P>
   Now, make turkey stock. Use the neck and giblets from the turkey
and the vegetable scraps from cooking (celery tops, carrot and
onion ends, etc.) to make a pot of rich stock. Add chicken necks
and backs, if you have some in the freezer. Let it simmer for 2
hours. Later, use it for gravy (see recipe) and to moisten
stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Solve the orange vegetable glut and the two-potato dilemma. If
you make a potluck Thanksgiving, assign each guest one of the
classic orange items. At least it won't be you staying up past your
bedtime preparing redundant vegetables. But if you host a meal that
you make all by yourself, choose one or two, and don't make
yourself crazy trying to please everybody (you can't). Certainly
you don't need both pureed squash and mashed sweet potatoes. And
you'd be foolish to offer mashed sweet potatoes along with mashed
white potatoes. Then, of course, you'd have to dispense with
pumpkin pie. Try that, and the family will stage a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Make the mashed potatoes ahead. Except for the turkey, almost
everything on the harvest menu can be made entirely in advance.
Some people maintain that you can't do mashed potatoes ahead, but
here's how. Choose starchy potatoes (Idahos or russets) and mix
them with yellow ones (Yukon gold or Yellow Finn). Boil them in
water and milk (see recipe), then drain and mash them as usual,
adding hot milk and butter. Then pour a thin layer of hot milk onto
your beautiful mashed potatoes. When you reheat them just before
serving, you can stir the potatoes back to their original
fluffiness. It's magic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on to the green vegetable problem. You owe your guests
something crunchy. Steamed broccoli is a logical accompaniment, but
it's cumbersome to make for more than eight guests. Brussels
sprouts aren't light enough to fit the bill (though they're awfully
good steamed lightly, then sauteed with bacon). Green beans are out
of season, so the quality is undependable. You could offer salad
greens tossed with vinaigrette dressing. Or a cabbage and carrot
slaw with a slightly sweetened vinaigrette (see recipe). We add
lots of scallions and parsley right at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Make enough stuffing. If you want lots of stuffing and some left
over, you really need to make a separate dish in addition to what's
inside the bird. Double whatever you're making to fill the bird,
and put half into a well-buttered baking dish. Just before you
reheat the baking dish of stuffing, moisten the top with a couple
of generous ladles of turkey stock. The top of the stuffing should
brown while the inside remains moist.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the gravy, a nuisance for any cook. Good gravy is great,
so make the effort. The first step is to get the bird out of the
pan. Enlist a guest, roll up your sleeves, and go one, two, three,
heave-ho onto a large, warm platter. Cover the turkey loosely with
foil and set it aside in a warm place. Pour 1 cup of boiling water
into the pan. You don't need to set it over a burner. Simply scrape
up all the sediment on the bottom of the pan. Add another 1/2 cup
of water if necessary. Then tip the contents of the pan into a
saucepan to make the gravy (see recipe). The roasting pan is
cumbersome and, once set over two medium burners, it's a recipe for
wrist burns.
</P>
<P>
   First things first. What do you serve before a meal that is far
too abundant in the first place? You can always do an updated
version of the relish tray. Be sure to include celery hearts,
leaves intact, along with radishes, stems intact. (The French
spread a little butter on their radishes, but they're also
wonderful with kosher salt.) Big green unpitted olives should also
go on the tray, along with a little pot of chutney and a bowl of
crackers, or something heartier, like a roasted caponata or Cheddar
cheese spread.
</P>
<P>
   What about guests who want to bring something? Some cooks are
comfortable assigning recipes, others not. Take your stance and
announce it. If you want help, it's there. If you want to do it all
yourself, there are still bits and pieces your guests can bring:
flowers or fruit for a centerpiece, apple cider, wine, ice. Maybe a
pie. Or a relish for the hors d'oeuvres tray. If you were expecting
something homemade and it isn't, don't say a word or let anyone see
that funny disapproving look. When life gives you seared, fatty
drippings and sediment, remember: Make gravy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
MAKE-AHEAD MASHED POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In general, allow 1 medium potato per person, but on
Thanksgiving, when the table is full of side dishes, you can
stretch a pot of mashed potatoes to serve more people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 medium potatoes (half Idaho or russet, half Yellow Finn or
Yukon gold)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups 1 or 2 percent milk
</P>
<P>
   1 quart whole milk, heated to scalding
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and cut them into 2-inch pieces. Combine them
in a large pan with water to cover them completely. Add plenty of
salt and the 2 cups of 1 or 2 percent milk. Bring to a boil, lower
the heat, cover the pan, and simmer the potatoes for 15 minutes or
until they are tender. Drain them into a colander.
</P>
<P>
   Return the potatoes to the pan and add 1 cup of the whole milk
with 2 tablespoons of the butter. Sprinkle with plenty of salt and
pepper, and mash the potatoes until they are smooth. Add 1/2 cup
more milk and the remaining butter. Continue mashing until the
potatoes are fluffy. (You can add more butter, if you like.) Add
1/2 cup more milk, if necessary. The potatoes should be exactly the
consistency you like for serving. Taste for seasoning and add more
salt and pepper if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
