<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-TURKEY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     11-17 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TURKEY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... if necesssary.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Use a plastic spatula to scrape down the sides of the pan.
Smooth the top of the potatoes. Pour enough of the remaining milk
on top of the potatoes to make a very thin layer.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the pan with the lid and set the potatoes aside for
several hours. Just before serving, set the potatoes over medium
heat and reheat them, stirring constantly, until they are hot and
fluffy. Transfer to a warm bowl and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12 (in small portions).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CABBAGE AND CARROT SLAW
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 firm head green cabbage, cut into wedges, cores removed
</P>
<P>
   6 large carrots
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 green bell peppers, cored and seeded
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches scallions, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 head parsley, leaves removed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Use a food processor, mandoline, or chef's knife to shred the
cabbage. In a food processor or on a box grater, shred the carrots.
Transfer both to a large bowl, sprinkling the layers with salt. Let
the vegetables stand for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cut the peppers into the thinnest possible 2-inch
strips.
</P>
<P>
   Lift the cabbage mixture from the bowl, leaving the liquid
behind, and transfer the vegetables to a clean bowl. Add the green
peppers, cider vinegar, sugar, and canola oil. Add plenty of black
pepper to taste. Use tongs or clean hands to toss the cabbage
mixture so it is well mixed. Cover tightly and refrigerate
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, add the scallions and parsley. Taste for
seasoning and add more salt and pepper if you like. Transfer to a
serving dish, cover tightly with plastic wrap, and set aside at
room temperature until serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
TURKEY GRAVY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before transferring the turkey to the oven, scatter 2 halved
onions, 2 halved carrots, and a stalk of celery around the bird.
Add 1 cup of water to keep the vegetables from drying out, though a
little burn is OK. The caramelization will give your gravy some
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drippings from 1 roast turkey
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   3 cups turkey or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red or white wine, brandy, or port
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cornstarch or arrowroot mixed with 1/3 cup cold
water (stir again just before using)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After you lift the bird from the roasting pan, set the pan in a
heatproof place where it will sit firmly. Add 1 cup of the boiling
water and scrape the bottom of the pan until you release all the
sediment. Add the remaining 1/2 cup of water if necessary. Tip the
contents of the pan into a saucepan (including the vegetables),
scraping the bottom well. Add the turkey stock and bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the pan from the heat. Tip it slightly. Use a large metal
spoon to discard the fat from the surface of the liquid. There is
no way to shortcut this; just take your time.
</P>
<P>
   Return the saucepan to the heat and let it bubble steadily. As
the mixture boils, notice little pools of fat on the surface.
Continue skimming until the liquid is free of fat. Add the wine,
brandy, or port with salt and pepper. Simmer the mixture, stirring
occasionally, for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Use tongs to remove the onion, carrot, and celery from the
sauce. Taste the mixture for seasoning and add more salt and pepper
if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Stir the cornstarch or arrowroot mixture with the water. Stir
half the cornstarch mixture into the boiling gravy and when it
thickens, see how you like the consistency. If you want the gravy
thicker, add the remaining cornstarch. Simmer the sauce for 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the gravy into a sauceboat or bowl and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
