<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLOVED STOCKS MISS THE RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call them the unloved.
</P>
<P>
   As the stock market continues to zoom ahead and the prices of
many individual issues climb to dizzying heights, some other
companies can't get the time of day from investors.
</P>
<P>
   Rate the public companies of Massachusetts by their price in
relation to profits and you would find a predictable collection of
troubled companies on the last rungs of the ladder, such as
Carematrix Corp. shares trading at less than three times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty of other companies with no earnings
disasters or serious balance-sheet blemishes near the bottom, too.
Does that make them a screaming buy? Probably not to the degree you
might expect.
</P>
<P>
   Those unloved are mostly financial stocks of different stripes:
local thrifts, a regional brokerage, and an investment management
firm tied to a big insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Their stocks are often down compared with recent years. But they
are palest in comparison to the rest of a stock market that has
been propelled to unusually high valuations by very aggressive
expectations for growth.
</P>
<P>
   A passel of smaller Massachusetts thrifts, including Hingham
Institution for Savings, Medford Bancorp, and Andover Bancorp, all
trade near or even below 10 times trailing earnings, according to
Bloomberg News data.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Freedom Securities, the Boston-based brokerage and
investment banking firm, can be purchased for around 10 times
earnings recorded in the last year. The same is true for Liberty
Financial Cos., the Boston investment firm majority-owned by
Liberty Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a startling point of comparison: We count seven local
companies each with a stock market value of more than $500 million
that trade north of 100 times trailing earnings. (Kopin Corp. is
tops with a stock trading about 867 times earnings.) That doesn't
even take into account mega-popular small companies with no
price-earnings ratio because they have no profits.
</P>
<P>
   Many cheap stocks are even inexpensive compared with their own
prices of recent years. But often, the gap is less impressive than
it appears.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the local thrift stocks trade around 10 times earnings.
That price-to-earnings ratio was about 14 two years ago and
typically hit a high of about 17 somewhere in the intervening
period.
</P>
<P>
   Merger activity among thrifts tended to push most of those
stocks up at the time and those opportunities, though far from
dead, are fewer today.
</P>
<P>
   Go back further in time, and the average thrift stock price
looks a lot more like today's valuations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average thrift stock is cheap historically speaking over
the near term,'' said analyst James Ackor of Freedom Securities.
``But on a longer time horizon, they're not way out of whack. I
think there's some money to be made owning these stocks, but you're
not going to see the doubles like you once did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackor's pick among the unloved local thrifts: First Essex
Bancorp of Andover.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem for the unloved stocks: Their lower-growth
reputation is a true stigma in today's market, and it isn't going
to change soon.
</P>
<P>
   But investors who purchase stocks on the other end of the
spectrum, where prices are highest, face an entirely different kind
of dilemma. Some of those stocks will soar further, but many more
are likely to lose ground or melt down entirely.
</P>
<P>
   We tracked down 13 Massachusetts companies that were trading at
a minimum of 50 times earnings two years ago, a very heady
price-earnings multiple at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 13 have lost money since then and five have given up
more than half their value. The biggest winner in that go-go crowd:
Sapient Corp., which appreciated 570 percent. (Some companies with
no earnings at the time scored even bigger gains, such as CMGI Inc.
of Andover and its 3,633 percent appreciation.)
</P>
<P>
   All of the most expensive stocks of two years ago had appealing
high-growth stories and analyst forecasts to support them. But
picking which companies could grow fast enough to make good on such
projections and not stumble wouldn't have been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that get the big price-earnings multiples are
typically younger companies that have to prove they have a business
strategy that is scalable and can be met,'' said Barbara Friedman,
manager of the John Hancock Mid Cap Growth fund. ``It's a very
difficult task.''
</P>
<P>
   Our question: If most of the stocks trading at more than 50
times earnings two years ago have failed to appreciate since then,
what's likely to happen to the seven priced at 100 times profits
today?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1400EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
