<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2533 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-PERSONAL-RITUALS-ART-     11-17 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-RITUALS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHETHER SECULAR OR SACRED, RITUALS BRING PEACE OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all love our rituals, especially this time of year. Soon
those hideous turkey-shaped candlesticks will get dusted off, trees
will get trimmed in the same manner, holiday presents opened in the
same order, with the same sort of fanfare. Rituals are universal,
and they run the gam-
</P>
<P>
   ut from simple to sublime.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet cup of coffee to get the day started. A religious rite,
like attending Sunday Mass. Or a cultural rite of passage, like a
bar or a bat mitzvah for a 13-year-old. It could be inherited or
invented. Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, for example, is a
veritable cuckoo clock of rituals, stepping up to the bat in a
particular rhythm, tugging at his batter's
</P>
<P>
   gloves in between pitches, scraping his feet in the batter's box
just before the ball is thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rituals provide time for the mind to become quiet and the body
to relax,'' says Oregon psychologist Marilyn Sorensen, author of
``Breaking the Chain of Low Self-Esteem,'' which touts the use of
ritual in daily life. ``They keep our personal goals in focus and
maintain peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the 20th century, peace of mind can mean
something different than it did even a decade ago. Not
surprisingly, contemporary rituals have evolved to meet
contemporary needs. Here are four examples.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Releasing distractions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Tecce's life is full of distractions. The car radio. Voice
mail. E-mail. Those noisy boomboxes, which he regards as ``one of
the worst inventions in the world.'' But he is not a man to suffer
distraction gladly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have this constant emotional stirring,'' says
Tecce, who teaches psychology at Boston College. ``If we are
bombarded with information every minute of the day, how can we ever
reflect on who we are, and what's meaningful in our lives?''
</P>
<P>
   So Tecce has devised what he calls ``a ritual of meditation,''
which, he says, controls the distractions in his life and improves
his ability to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a day _ once before breakfast and again before dinner _
Tecce closes the door, shuts off the lights, and meditates for 30
minutes. But unlike more traditional meditation techniques, which
strive to focus a person's attention, this so-called
distraction-meditation allows the mind ``to wander all over the
place and let out the distractions that you've been suppressing all
day,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual is based on research results he has published,
showing that distractions interfere with brain activity. ``The goal
is to allow the distractions, which typically dribble in and out of
your consciousness all day, to come with full force and intensity
in a short period of time,'' says Tecce. ``Then they will be less
likely to crop up during unwanted moments during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   He has taught the technique to his students (more than 3,700 of
them so far, he estimates), and he begins and ends each class he
teaches with a 10-minute meditation ritual. A faithful practitioner
of this ritual for 25 years, Tecce says it has increased his
ability to work intensively, quickly, and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he knows it contradicts conventional American lifestyle
practices. ``Society says, `Don't just sit there; do something.' ''
Tecce, on the other hand, advocates the act of simply sitting
there. Doing so, he says, represents ``a declaration of
independence from a busy and demanding world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The power of prayer
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tony Wray, 53, is not a religious man, at least not in the
conventional sense. The retired Framingham, Mass. businessman and
Y2K expert was raised in both the Catholic and Baptist faiths, and
today, he says, ``I'm not a great believer in organized religion.''
</P>
<P>
   But he does believe in a higher power, which he feels ``is there
for those who seek it. If you prefer to go through life struggling
on your own, so be it. But my belief system says there is a power
there that is yours for the asking.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Wray asks. For more than 30 years he has conducted what
he calls a daily ``ritual of prayer,'' which he practices no matter
where he is and which enables him to ``tap into this power. I not
only ask for support but also offer thanks for assistance given.''
Every night at bedtime, he asks his God _ out loud _ to ``let me
wake up tomorrow'' and offers his thanks for what has happened
during the day. He is careful also to add that he is ``looking
forward to tomorrow.'' Every morning he says, ``Thank you for
letting me wake up this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If perchance I forget one day, I will apologize, because I
truly believe we are given permission to live on this earth, and
that we can't take it for granted,'' Wray says.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual is in keeping with his take on modern life. ``I have
a very positive outlook on life. I believe that everything will be
OK for those who are prepared. I guess that extends to my feelings
regarding the year 2000,'' says Wray, a former IBM marketing
executive who now does consulting on career and business management
for Levy Wray and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've researched it. I have gotten my documents together and
paid up my bills. I have alternative sources of heat and light.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this, he says, ``is empowering.'' As is prayer. ``I never
think there is a situation that will come up in which my God will
not either take care of me, or use it as a lesson.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Female celebration
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Amy Rewakowski was going through ``a
particularly tragic year'' of poor health and high stress. ``I had
many, many losses,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have made it without my friends,'' says Rewakowski
of Boston, now 34. ``They offered moral support and tangible,
concrete support, like bringing food.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was better, she decided to thank her friends by
inviting them to her home for a potluck gathering. To help break
the ice, since her friends didn't all know one another, she asked
each one to bring something ``symbolic of where they were in their
lives.'' Pictures of their children. Poems they had written.
Rewakowski, an artist and an administrator, made everyone a
thank-you gift.
</P>
<P>
   To her surprise, she found the impact of the event deeply
powerful _ and a ritual was born. ``A heartfelt connection
developed between the women,'' she says. ``These were women who had
been through a lot of changes and loss and self-searching, and they
all realized they weren't alone.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the gathering Circle of Friends. Today, it has
evolved into an annual tradition she describes as ``a celebration
of the power and empathy of women's friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a year, Rewakowski invites her friends back, always
choosing a theme such as ``gratitude'' or ``changes in our lives''
or ``celebrating the unknown.'' The Circle of Friends _ as many as
20 of them, between the ages of 21 and 40 _ come from as far away
as Ohio and the Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start the circle and welcome people, and have people share
on the theme if they want to,'' says Rewakowski. After each woman
has spoken, she lights a candle and sets it in the center, where it
joins those lit for the others. ``It's as though, symbolically, we
are not in darkness anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes deliberate effort for her highly mobile generation,
says Rewakowski, to build communities. ``A real sisterhood of
friendship'' doesn't evolve naturally from neighborhoods or
villages. ``It's these simple but important things that keep us
human and keep us together,'' she says. ``It's a way of being
nurtured, like a massage, but it's something free, and something we
can count on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Power breakfast
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Lee used to live in New Hampshire. And in California, and
Germany, then California again, Switzerland, Germany again, New
York, and Pennsylvania _ all in the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others in academia, ``I've moved around constantly,''
says Lee, 33, an assistant professor of sociology at Penn State's
Du Bois campus. ``My limit for being in the same spot is two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his peripatetic lifestyle, he developed a knack for coping
with change of any sort. But there is one change he can't abide:
``My breakfast ritual,'' says Lee. ``My breakfast always has to
have the same ingredients. I can tolerate a weird lunch or dinner,
but without this breakfast, my day is shot. I get hungrier faster,
I'm not as relaxed, and unpredictable things are harder to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just any old ingredients go into this breakfast _ an
oatmeal-based cereal concoction made with yogurt, fruit, and nuts
inspired by the breakfasts he ate in Europe. All have been
carefully selected _ and painstakingly accumulated. Each component
represents an earlier time and place in Lee's life.
</P>
<P>
   The oat groats, which his grandfather taught him to eat and
which he hand rolls each night, are distributed by a Mennonite
farmer in Pennsylvania. (``Why a Mennonite? They have old-fashioned
values that occasionally overlap with mine.'') The raisins and
almonds come from the San Joaquin Valley in California, where he
was born. The yogurt comes from Vermont. And the Ost-Freisen tea is
German.
</P>
<P>
   He considers his breakfast to be ``autobiographical,'' combining
facets of his fragmented personal history into one unified,
predictable whole. ``It's a very postmodern, global thing,'' says
Lee, who studies rituals as a sociologist. ``Every time I move I
add something that really seemed to impress me in the place I
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the academic, he has analyzed his morning ritual and come
up with a theory for it. ``It speaks to the need for constancy and
stability when I am constantly bombarded with new things,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   It also speaks to his need to reduce complexity in a society
inundated with choices. ``It simplifies my life in at least one
area,'' Lee says. ``I don't have to think about the procedure
anymore. And when I'm done, I can start anything, no matter where I
am, because I've done this procedure that is so familiar and so old
and so me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
