<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TIMELINE-BOS &LR;      11-17 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIMELINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIMELINE' JOURNEY AMUSING, BUT INCOMPLETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TIMELINE 
By Michael Crichton. Knopf, 384 pp., illustrated, $26.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Timeline,'' Michael Crichton's 12th novel, is slovenly but
sort of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton's literary specialty is to put a new spin on the plots
of old movies. What is ``Jurassic Park'' but ``Godzilla'' with more
up-to-date science? In ``Jurassic Park,'' Crichton brought the
prehistoric world into the 20th century. Now, in ``Timeline,'' he
reverses the process, sending a team of young academic historians
and archeologists back to a time and place earlier in the
millennium: the Perigord, in France, during the Hundred Years' War.
</P>
<P>
   The new spin is that our team returns there through an
application of quantum theory, to which Crichton devotes several
laborious pages of explication. A century ago, Mark Twain had it
easier when he wanted to deliver a Connecticut Yankee to King
Arthur's court _ a blow on the noggin was enough to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason these young people are fighting in the Hundred Years'
War is that they want to rescue their mentor, a Regius professor of
History at Yale, who has sent them a note that he is trapped there,
and dated it 4/7/1357. The reason the professor has gotten back
there is something Crichton keeps to himself for 300 pages, so
there's no point is spoiling the fun by telling you here _ this is
also presumably why all press comment on ``Timeline'' was embargoed
until Tuesday's publication date.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear from the beginning is that the professor and his
students are subsidized by a large, rich, secret corporation with
headquarters somewhere out in the middle of nowhere (Black Rock,
N.M., described as ``one hour north of Albuquerque,'' which is
about where Santa Fe is, and that is far from nowhere). Robert
Doniger, the brilliant founder of the corporation, has some
sinister purpose in view. One of the ways you can tell this is that
he is peremptory when he issues orders to his female assistant,
Diane Kramer. Ultimately, he does reveal his plan, in a speech to
the media, but once the design is out in the open, it hardly seems
worth all the buildup, and besides, readers of Crichton have met it
before, in ``Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes Crichton quite a while _ 164 pages, in fact _ to lay
the groundwork, some of it red-herring stuff, deliberately
misleading. Or is this simply a case of a first draft that changed
course midway, without ever turning back to fix up the beginning?
Crichton elaborately introduces characters and even plotlines for
which he will have no further use. He sets up a nosy cop named
James Wauneka from Gallup, N.M., for example, to be an antagonist
for Doniger, but then apparently changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   What finally happens when our crew arrives on the shores of the
Dordogne River, near the monastery, the mill, and the opposing
castles, Castelgard and La Roque? Well, they notice straight off
that there is no ambient noise from radio, TV, airplanes, or
passing cars; before long they discover that castle toilets don't
smell all that bad. There are some bad guys, however, that they
should have recognized from their own experience of TV _ Sir Robert
de Kere, for example, or the sneering Sir Guy de Malegant, a black
knight whose name means ``bad glove.'' Our friends try to keep
their mouths shut in an environment where everything is menacing,
but when they have to, they can communicate in English, French,
Latin, or Occitan, begin their sentences with ``Certes,'' and, when
all else fails, take flight. Soon, they are caught up in a 150-page
high-speed chase across historically correct battlements, with lots
of swordfighting, whizzing arrows, and double-dealing, not to
mention a high-spirited beauty named the Lady Claire. The professor
will find it prudent to invent gunpowder, just as Twain's
Connecticut Yankeee did. One of our heroes swings his lance wildly
in the air, ``like a metronome,'' which doesn't swing wildly (and
anyway, Herr Maelzel didn't get around to manufacturing that useful
device until 1816).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's a bad day at Black Rock. Is there any way the
professor and his proteges can make it back to the relative safety
of the 20th century? Will it have to be over Doniger's dead body?
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Crichton has done a fair amount of homework and
supplies a 3 1/2-page historical bibliography as well as an
additional half-page of references to quantum physics; he outlines
some historical facts, and the bare text is adorned with maps,
illustrations, and computer graphics so that the reader can
understand the architecture and structure of castles and mills the
characters are racing around.
</P>
<P>
   All this is fun, but Crichton fails at what should be the most
fun of all: convincingly put the reader back into the Middle Ages.
Instead, it puts the reader back into Errol Flynn movies. Crichton
lists no novels in his bibliography, and the best historical novels
do accomplish what Crichton never even attempts. Looking at
Marguerite Yourcenar's ``The Abyss,'' or any of the novels of Zoe
Oldenbourg, or any of the scrumptious confections of Dorothy
Dunnett, might have helped him show how people thought, believed,
moved through their own landscapes. His characters are only
insubstantial shadows on a screen, and ``Timeline'' is not a novel,
but a shooting script.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
