r l BC-ACTRESS-PENELOPE-CRUZ     11-17 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTRESS-PENELOPE-CRUZ-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASURE CRUZ  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When the Spanish actress Penelope Cruz got a call that many
actors wait and wait for, it was she, at the tender age of 18, who
kept the caller waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drying my hair in the toilet, and my boyfriend at the
time told me, `Almodovar is calling.' I said, `Yes, of course,' and
kept drying my hair, thinking he was joking. Finally, I picked it
up after he'd been waiting so long, and he told he wanted me to
audition for `Kika.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz proved too young to play the title role in Almodovar's 1993
film, but the director gave her a small part in ``Live Flesh'' and
eventually offered her a major role in this fall's ``All About My
Mother,'' which debuted to great acclaim at Cannes and opened the
New York Film Festival on Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   In it, the beautiful Cruz plays against type: She's a nun who's
had an affair with a drag queen, then learns she is pregnant _ and
dying of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want always to play the pretty woman,'' Cruz says in
her Spanish-tinged English. ``There is always going to be someone
more beautiful. I like to change. I like roles that people don't
recognize me in.''
</P>
<P>
   For his film adaptation of the Cormac McCarthy novel ``All the
Pretty Horses,'' due out next spring, director Billy Bob Thornton
knew right away he wanted Cruz to play the role of a wealthy and
beautiful Mexican girl in love with drifter Matt Damon. The studio,
however, was less certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy met me in L.A. one year ago, but for eight months I was
doing tests for the movie. We had to show Columbia that I had
chemistry with Matt, so I flew to Rome, and Anthony Minghella (who
was directing Damon in the upcoming ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'')
directed the audition. We were singing and dancing in that test.
Then we did more tests. Finally, Billy told me I got the part.
Imagine if I hadn't, after all that work!''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, who's passing through Los Angeles between Brazil and San
Francisco, where she's shooting ``Woman on Top'' for Fox
Searchlight, adored working with Damon, whom she calls ``very
smart.'' But it was Thornton who won her heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great director, actor and writer, and everyone around
him is in awe of him because he does everything, and he does it all
perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old actress, who's been working nonstop since she
was 14, has had enough experience to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always very precocious,'' she says. ``I really wanted to
be a dancer, so I went to drama school and danced many hours a day.
Eventually, I had to realize I was getting sick from working too
hard, and I had to choose one career.''
</P>
<P>
   She threw herself headlong into acting. As a teen, she starred
in major European films like ``Jamon Jamon'' and ``Belle Epoque''
and landed her English-language debut last year in Stephen Frears'
``Hi-Lo Country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen `Dangerous Liaisons' 14 times,'' she says. ``It's
one of my favorite movies. When he called me, he came to Madrid,
where I live, and we did only one test. The next day he told me I
had the part. So I was spoiled, because I thought it was going to
be so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Pictures president Amy Pascal describes the actress'
appeal this way: ``Penelope Cruz is very sexy, but not threatening
_ both vulnerable and strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz blushes a little bit when she hears the compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think those things about myself,'' she says. ``I know
I've been coquettish since I was 3 years old. I like clothes and I
like seduction in general, but I am like that with everybody:
children, dogs, men and women. I admit I want people to like me _
who doesn't? But not for just the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she makes clear, she remains loyal to her Czech
boyfriend, an assistant director she met on a European film who
shares her house in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spoke five languages, but he had to learn Spanish after he
met me. Czech is too difficult! We are very different, but I think
that's good. That Spanish temper is too strong to have two Spanish
people together.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
