<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2545 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-17 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP THE LIGHT ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ How could Bill Galvin find 2,100 ``lost'' John
Hancock policyholders in a weekend when the insurer couldn't find
them in a year?
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts secretary of state proved again that he is a
man of exquisite timing with a nose for a headline when, on the eve
of the lone public hearing on Hancock's conversion to a stock
company, his computers were able to churn out the addresses of
policyholders who may be in line to cash in on the public offering.
Those policyholders will now be able to measure in dollars or
Hancock stock just what state government did for them this year.
</P>
<P>
   It was a direct hit for a man who has never minded tossing
spitballs at the powerful. We can only dream what might have been
had Galvin, and not Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt, been
overseeing the conversion of Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock surely has a little egg on its face and some questions
to ask about what it got for the $4 million it spent locating lost
policyholders. But say this much for the state's largest insurer:
It got the most important decision right. After pushing a very bad
law through the Legislature that would have allowed it to form a
holding company and go public without paying its policyholders a
dime, it reversed direction. Instead, it opted for a traditional
demutualization, which will allow the entire worth of the company
to be doled out to policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Did Hancock's board really believe a demutualization was the
fair way to go? Or did it come to believe that not even mutual
policyholders, the most docile bosses any executive ever had,
wouldn't swallow the too-good-to-believe holding company farce? In
the end, what matters is that Hancock did the right thing. Now what
about you, Massachusetts Mutual?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday a sea of gray suits was expected to pack the hearing
on Hancock's conversion plan. Hancock's chairman, Stephen Brown,
will speak, followed by a series of executives who will testify why
the conversion is good for the company and its 2.8 million
policyholders. Then a string of consumer activists will tell us how
Brown &AMP; Co. are cheating those same policyholders out of what is
their's.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance is all about trust; we give our money to them,
trusting the insurers will stand by their promises. But in the past
few years that trust has been badly damaged. Company after company
has paid dearly to settle charges of deceptive sales practices _
Hancock among them, agreeing to provide policyholder benefits worth
$350 million or more to atone for its misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Should we now trust Hancock and other insurers like it to do the
right thing in the most important financial transaction in their
history, converting to a public company? Only if we keep their feet
to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance division's hearings will focus on issues that no
human being, only an actuary, could love. Should we use the
historic or historic plus prospective method in determining which
policyholders should get what? Why aren't variable life
policyholders eligible? Slightly more accessible is the question of
whether policyholders should get cash or stock.
</P>
<P>
   There are few right or wrong answers in this world, only
actuarial opinions that can range all over the lot. But the stakes
are huge: This is a world where hundreds of millions can be shifted
from one group of policyholders to another with the shift of one of
those opinions.
</P>
<P>
   How to feel safe in this arcane world? Let the light shine in.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance is infamous for its nondisclosure culture, both by the
companies and the regulators themselves. There is far too much time
negotiating with corporate executives behind closed doors, far too
much effort spent keeping the gadflys at arms' length. Regulators
might not want to admit it, but their little toy departments are
sadly outgunned by the industry they are trying to oversee. Love
them or hate them, Jason Adkins, Joe Belth and the others like them
are regulators' natural allies, not the enemies they make them.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Galvin just showed how one gadfly can make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can reach me at 617 929-2902 or sbailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
