<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-INVISIBLE-ENERGY-ART-     11-17 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVISIBLE-ENERGY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVISIBLE ENERGY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KATHRYN BROWN  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Four Times Square, a new 48-story office tower, looks much like
any other modern skyscraper in the heart of New York City. But the
top 11 floors of the sleek glass exterior are unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The building's fashionable, light-blue skin contains an array of
electricity-generating solar panels.
</P>
<P>
   Dig a little deeper, and you'll find a bank of giant fuel cells
lurking on the fourth floor, silently turning natural gas into
power. Four Times Square is its own freestanding environmentally
friendly electric utility.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as corporate dealmakers and the general public
understand the value of these kinds of buildings, they're going to
insist on them,'' predicts Bob Fox, the building's lead architect.
</P>
<P>
   Since Edison's first lightbulb, an increasing number of people
have tied their energy fulfillment needs to the grid of
interconnected power lines. Now the trend is reversing, and
do-it-yourself power is taking off.
</P>
<P>
   Local blackouts and Y2K anxieties have home owners and office
managers alike worrying about a power-grid failure.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, freestanding energy sources are getting
cleaner, cheaper and prettier. They can even be money-savers.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty states now require utilities to use net metering, which
allows consumers who generate their own power to cut their energy
bills by selling back any excess.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, many buildings could sport solar cells on the roof,
natural-gas turbines and fuel cells in the basement and a link to a
wind turbine up the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most dramatic changes have popped up in solar power,
long dismissed as visually unappealing and impractically expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Architects who once shunned bulky blue solar panels are
marveling at solar cells incorporated discreetly into the surface
of roofing shingles, windows, skylights and wall facades.
</P>
<P>
   Misawa Homes of Japan, that nation's largest home builder,
recently showed off its spare, modernist Eco Energy House, which
turns its solar accoutrements into elegant design elements.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, President Clinton has launched the Million
Solar Roofs Initiative to get solar-energy tiles on the tops of 1
million buildings by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prices keep dropping. Two decades of engineering
sweat have brought solar electricity costs down to an average of 20
cents per kilowatt-hour.
</P>
<P>
   In sunny cities like San Diego, an equivalent flow of
conventional electricity during peak daytime hours can cost as much
as 28 cents, says Nancy Bacon, senior vice president of Energy
Conversion Diversion in Troy, Mich. At night, solar homes in San
Diego can switch to power from the local utility.
</P>
<P>
   First Solar in Toledo, Ohio, is starting to grow transparent
solar cells directly onto glass panes during their manufacture, at
a total cost only slightly higher than that of conventional glass.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, a typical glassmaker rolls out 600 tons of panes for
use in buildings. If just one plant were converted for making solar
glass following First Solar's technique, the glass it produced
would generate about 1 gigawatt of power a year, says Gary Dorer,
the company's vice president of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost 10 times more than today's total solar-power
production worldwide,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel cells could also generate compact, do-it-yourself power.
The cells generate electricity by combining hydrogen _ usually
drawn from a fuel like natural gas or methanol _ with oxygen,
launching chemical reactions that spark a current. They work
silently and cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   Four Times Square uses the cells for only a fraction of its
total power needs, but in other settings they could pull much
heavier duty. A basement fuel cell working in tandem with solar
cells on a house's roof could churn out all the necessary local
energy, rain or shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a tactical standpoint, it's a beautiful combination,''
says Thomas Hoff, head of Clean Power Research in Napa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, a home's solar power would rev up, especially in
the middle of the day when it is needed most. In the darker days of
winter, the fuel cell would kick into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel cells generate warmth as they work, so they can be used to
heat rooms or water as well. Add energy-efficient lights and
appliances, and you've got a system that could drastically cut
emissions of carbon dioxide and reduce the threat of global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   If advanced fuel cells eventually power some cars _ and
companies like Ford, DaimlerChrysler and Toyota are betting they
will _ mobile and stationary energy needs might someday merge. At
the end of the day, a home owner might plug the house into the
family car to light up the night.
</P>
<P>
   Most existing fuel cells rely on fossil fuels, but future
versions may tap cheaper renewable energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, several breweries are powered by fuel cells that run
off waste gas produced during fermentation. Methane leaking from
landfills could become another useful source of
electricity-generating gas for fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere you have a source of hydrogen-rich gas, you might
think of fuel cells,'' says Adam Serchuk of the Renewable Energy
Policy Project in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Energy Conversion Devices is combining solar and
fuel-cell technologies into the ultimate pollution-free home energy
system. Electricity from solar cells on the roof can split water
molecules into hydrogen and oxygen. The hydrogen could then be
siphoned off, stored and used to power fuel cells in the home and
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the greatest demand for high-tech distributed power
sources is coming from poor communities overseas. Worldwide, 2
billion people live without electricity. In rural villages in
China, Mexico and India, on-the-spot energy sources such as wind
turbines, solar panels and small biomass power plants make a lot of
sense.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the solar cells and wind turbines made in the
United States are shipped to such remote areas. These markets have
supported the development of do-it-yourself power even while the
United States has continued to rely on cheap oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the technology works,'' says Mike Bergey, president of
Bergey Windpower. ``Now it looks like we'll get a chance to prove
it here in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Kathryn Brown is a regular contributor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
