<HEADLINE>
WAS AGNEW RIGHT ABOUT TV NEWS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ He was well-dressed and soft-spoken. He seldom
shouted or waved his arms. Spiro T. Agnew was a unique vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little over a week ago, I took a rather unusual step for a
vice president,'' he told a Republican dinner at Harrisburg, Pa.,
on Oct. 30, 1969. ``I said something. Particularly, I said
something that was predictably unpopular with the people who would
like to run the country without the inconvenience of seeking public
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Agnew chose the targets of his icy wrath himself, just as he
chose the words from his off-kilter vocabulary. College students
protesting the war in Vietnam were ``encouraged by an effete corps
of impudent snobs who characaterize themselves as intellectuals,''
he said. Agnew was an overnight sensation among Republicans 30
years ago, which brought him to the attention of President Richard
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon saw a bigger target: television news. Nixon's
speechwriter, Patrick J. Buchanan, ``went over the speech line by
line with the president,'' according to another Agnew speechwriter,
William Safire. Nixon approved Agnew's speech in Des Moines Nov.
13, to be telecast live, saying to Buchanan, ``This really flicks
the scab off, doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   The Agnew speech attacked the ``instant analysis and querulous
criticism'' after a Nixon speech on Vietnam and rallied conspiracy
theorists against ``a tiny and closed fraternity of privileged men,
elected by no one and enjoying a monopoly sanctioned and licensed
by government.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene McCarthy called Agnew ``Nixon's Nixon,'' after the
slasher role Nixon played as VP for President Dwight D. Eisenhower
in the 1950s. The parallel also applied to Agnew's Throttlebottom
status. Ike mostly ignored Nixon and Nixon did the same to Agnew.
Another bond: Nixon and Agnew barely escaped jail.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later after this clumsy intimidation, conglomerates have
chewed up conspiracy theories. Some conservatives still see ABC,
CBS, and NBC as liberal, but a tiny and closed fraternity? Among
millions of stockholders in Disney and General Electric?
</P>
<P>
   One change has been good for those concerned about politics and
policy. C-SPAN is a beacon of such merit and probity that one wants
to pinch it. Instead, fans can cite the giddy Celia in
Shakespeare's ``As You Like it'': ``O wonderful, wonderful and most
wonderful wonderful! And yet again wonderful, and after that, out
of all whooping!''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the constants in television remain time and money.
The Television Advertising Bureau says that the average American
home set works a full shift, flickering for seven hours and 15
minutes daily. That dominance translates to total broadcast TV
revenues of $34.6 billion in 1998, up almost 7 percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   When a television station comes up for sale, a new Gold Rush
erupts. Here in the nation's fourth-largest market, The Chronicle
Co. sold Channel 4, KRON-TV, for $823 million to Young
Broadcasting. The prospectors included the Gannett Co. and Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp. and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Since Agnew's attack, the networks have shrunk in budget and
influence and lost their central place in television news. ``The
networks have a smaller piece of the pie because of cable news and
local news,'' says Barbara Cochran, director of the Radio and
Television News Directors Assn. ``People don't rely on networks for
breaking news, so like newspapers, they depend more on analysis and
follow-up. Not only has the quantity of news increased locally, but
so has its influence. No one believes me when I say this, but local
television is the most trusted source of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Agnew's complaint is sometimes still echoed by those who enjoy
many more choices. The First Amendment still allows every citizen
to turn the dial or even to try out one of the most satisfying
features of every television set, the off button.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
