<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE CAN'T IGNORE THE FIRESTORM OF SCHOOL TESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The firestorm of school testing is raging out of control, with
thousands of children howling, trapped on the high floors of
expectation. The great debate is what to do next, whether to rush
in and save them from this test, or to tell them to jump, even
though we have made it clear that there is no safety net.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing for sure is that if we do not decide quickly, the
children and their futures will become ashes.
</P>
<P>
   This was evident from the 1999 Massachusetts Comprehensive
Assessment System scores. Passing the MCAS will be a mandatory
requirement for graduation in 2003. If it was mandatory today, 32
percent of 10th graders would fail in English and language arts, 38
percent would fail in science, and 53 percent would fail in
mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   For the 10th graders, that represented a slight decline in
performance on the test. As bad as that is, the story for
African-American and Latino students is much worse.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of the 1998 MCAS scores released last week, the
Gaston Institute for Latino Community Development and Public Policy
at UMass-Boston found that among 10th graders, 49 percent of
African-American and 58 percent of Latino students failed English.
In science and technology, 65 percent of African-American and 70
percent of Latino students failed.
</P>
<P>
   In mathematics, 80 percent of African-Americans and 83 percent
of Latinos failed. A separate study by Tufts University found that
79 percent of Native American students also failed math.
</P>
<P>
   The failure rates are so high that the Gaston Institute predicts
that nearly one out of every three Latino students and one out of
every four African-American students will drop out of school.
``This is devastating to the community,'' said Miren Uriarte, a
researcher at the Gaston Institute. ``It will have a very heavy
economic impact in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a five-alarm emergency. While African-Americans and
Latinos are taking the hardest shots from the test, the Gaston
study showed that 13 percent of Asian and 10 percent of white
students may also give up and drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting an emergency like this will require parallel
strategies. Some parents are courageously challenging the validity
of the test itself as a mandatory part of graduation. Despite the
rush by politicians to impose high-stakes tests on school children
all across the nation, there is unbelievably little data, whether
at the K-12 level or at the college level, to prove that one-shot
standardized tests truly measure all the capabilities and skills
needed by individual students for either graduation or to predict
what they will become in college.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in their book ``The Shape of the River,'' former
Harvard and Princeton presidents Derek Bok and William Bowen
researched what became of 700 African-American students who would
have been bumped out of their chosen schools on test scores. About
70 of the freshmen became doctors, about 60 became lawyers, about
125 became business executives, more than 225 earned professional
degrees or doctorates, more than 300 are leaders of civic
activities. The average earnings of the 700 are more than $71,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Test scores and grades are useful measures of the ability to
do good work, but they are no more than that,'' Bok and Bowen
wrote. ``They are far from infallible indicators of other qualities
some might regard as intrinsic, such as a deep love of learning or
a capacity for high academic achievement. Taken together, grades
and scores predict only 15 to 20 percent of the variance among all
students in academic performance and a smaller percentage among
black students.''
</P>
<P>
   The parallel reality is that the disastrous scores of
African-American, Latino, and Native American students in
particular and the mediocre statewide scores in general are utterly
unacceptable. Students must be held accountable within their normal
classwork for levels of reading, writing, and arithmetic necessary
to avoid being zombies in an economy that metaphorically speaking,
offers them only two choices, Microsoft or McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   But since many studies have well established that many urban
school systems have low expectations of their students, and since
the state cynically imposed the MCAS with all the subtlety of a
spiked gauntlet, fully expecting half of students to fail,
improvement will not come willingly from the schools or the state.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure for achievement must come from parents, churches,
civil rights organizations, and student peer groups. If communities
decide to put their energy into teaching to the test, fine. If they
decide to fight the test, fraught as it is with issues of unequal
resources in the schools, and demand a richer curriculum, that
would be better. Doing nothing is not an option. That would leave
our children at the mercy of the leaping flames of school testing.
Their future is well on the way to being cremated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
