<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-MOAKLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOAKLEY POLITICS PLAY WELL IN EL SALVADOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR _ US Rep. J. Joseph Moakley never claimed to be a
global thinker. The South Boston Democrat brags he is a
``bread-and-butter politician'' and proudly recalls that when he
first heard of El Salvador more than a decade ago, he couldn't find
it on a map.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason Moakley is so popular here.
</P>
<P>
   He was first sent to El Salvador to investigate a crime that
erupted into a diplomatic crisis: the killing of six Jesuit
priests, exactly 10 years ago this week. But when Moakley returned
here last weekend for the anniversary of the murders, along with
Representative James P. McGovern of Worcester, his former aide, he
was treated more like a local hero than a foreign diplomat. And
there were signs his involvement has helped pave the way for El
Salvador to begin solving bread-and-butter problems of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrilla rebels who once fought to topple the government now
lobby officials for access to clean drinking water. Roads once
dotted with security checkpoints are now being paved in an attempt
to focus on public works. And on Monday, for the second time in
Salvadoran history, officials opened a constituent services center
where voters can speak directly with their elected leaders _ an
idea straight out of the Moakley book.
</P>
<P>
   The civil war in El Salvador ended just seven years ago, and the
country is still plagued with severe problems, including a
staggering violent crime rate and soaring levels of poverty. But
faith in the democratic system is starting to grow, a development
that by many accounts grew out of the process Moakley set in motion
with his 1989 investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundations of democracy are strong,'' said Ruben Zamora,
a member of the Salvadoran National Assembly who worked closely
with the Massachusetts congressmen during the investigation. ``That
is a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley, after touring the country for three days, summed it up:
``The people that were shooting bullets at each other are now
shooting ballots at each other in the legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Such changes were virtually unimaginable on Nov. 16, 1989, when
the six Catholic priests, their cook and her teenage daughter were
dragged out of bed and shot dead in the garden of the University of
Central America where they worked.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of the crime scene were splashed across international
newspapers, arousing the passions of many Americans previously
unmoved by a war that had raged in El Salvador for years. House
Speaker Thomas Foley immediately demanded an investigation to
determine which of the warring factions had committed the murders _
leftist guerrillas or the Salvadoran military.
</P>
<P>
   It took Moakley and McGovern nearly two years to complete what
became known as the Moakley Commission, a controversial report that
concluded that top Salvadoran brass had ordered the Jesuit priests
killed because of for their leftist sympathies. The report made
Moakley a pariah among US foreign policymakers who supported the
Salvadoran government as part of the Cold War effort to back
anti-Communist forces around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But among many Salvadoran civilians _ who rarely heard US
politicians attack their government so vehemently _ the
investigation made Moakley and McGovern into symbols of justice.
Even today, McGovern says, the case grew into a larger crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both Catholics, so at first there was an element of,
`How dare they go out there and kill these priests?' '' McGovern
said. ``But as we got into it more and more, we realized this case
was an example of the larger issues in El Salvador. We realized
that a lot more was riding on this than just finding out who did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe the Moakley Commission set the stage for the 1992
ceasefire that ended the civil war and allowed democracy to take
root. But brokering a peace agreement was never quite on Moakley's
agenda. He was busy adopting the Massachusetts-sized country as a
sort of sister constituency, having grown attached to so many
Salvadorans during his time there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People knew my name,'' he recalled. ``They always felt they
had a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a role he still revels in. Returning last Friday to speak
at the university where the priests were killed, Moakley and
McGovern were greeted by dozens of Catholic priests and local
officials. Many still requested their help, as much in solving
local problems as in elevating El Salvador's status in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Driving an hour outside the capital of San Salvador to a region
devastated by Hurricane Mitch, the congressmen stood in the blazing
sun and listened through a translator to a local leader describe
the living conditions: No electricity. No water. Virtually no
income from their meager crops.
</P>
<P>
   As they entered another town, young children stood at the edge
of the road holding homemade signs that read, ``We want dikes,
roads, drains!'' The congressmen pressed US Embassy and Salvadoran
officials about the timetable for getting public works in place,
aware that some of the $25 million in US funds allocated for
Hurricane Mitch relief would be picking up the tab. At one point,
McGovern encouraged a village resident to contact him in six months
to let him know whether a rural electrical system had been
installed.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the residents seemed to understand the process of getting
their own elected officials to help, but they were eager to learn.
Mauricio Ramirez Santos, a former rebel fighter with the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front, said he would welcome the
government into his 77-family community if it would mean new roads
and food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the government cannot do everything in the post-war
period, but we think it is their responsibility to see how to solve
our problems,'' Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   The government faces many problems throughout the country, many
of which seem insurmountable in a stagnant economy that is only
getting worse. Some 30 percent of the country has no drinking
water, a higher rate than anywhere in Latin America. And crime is
worse in El Salvador than virtually anywhere else in the western
hemisphere, according to official estimates. More than 100,000 of
the country's 6 million civilians carry guns, according to one
account, and as many as two dozen people are killed by violent
crime each day.
</P>
<P>
   Yet according to surveys conducted by US Agency for
International Development, confidence in all branches of the El
Salvadoran government has increased. Charles E. North, director of
USAID's strategic development office in San Salvador, said the
agency is constantly asking itself: ``Are we making headway on
democracy issues?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we are, in some ways,'' North said. ``We have seen
some improvements that, in some cases, are quite striking. Even
confidence in the police has been rather high.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, one Salvadoran paid homage in a unique way to
Moakley's impact here. Nelson Recinos, 40, a financial consultant
for a coffee cooperative, said he had had a conversation that led
him to worry about Moakley's safety on the trip, and he decided to
contact authorities.
</P>
<P>
   To Recinos, his decision to report his qualms in itself signaled
a change. ``I felt confident that I was doing the right thing. I
wouldn't have thought that 10 years ago,'' he said. ``I even said
they could use my name. . . It was my way of showing thanks. It's a
way of thanking Moakley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
