u i BC-MEXICO-SCHOOLS-BOS &LR;      11-17 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO SCHOOLS IMPORT A US-STYLE SECURITY TACTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULTITLAN, Mexico _ With one exception, the typical school day
at the Juan Ignacio Ramirez High School is pretty much the same as
it always was.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,200 students at this suburban Mexico City campus wear
their required maroon and green plaid uniforms with crisp white
shirts. Gym class is held in a dusty, enclosed playground, between
the concrete basketball court and the row of blooming
bougainvilleas. And the curriculum is the usual mix of basics,
English, and college-prep courses.
</P>
<P>
   But now students have to be ready at any moment for ``Operation
Backpack,'' when teachers and administrators conduct surprise
searches of their bags for anything that shouldn't be there _
especially guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know these are good kids,'' Francisco Islas Austria, the
school's principal, said last week while standing in his office,
full of trophies recently won by students. ``But it's gotten to the
point that we have to do this out of our conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   A sad but common reality of American school life has trickled to
its southern neighbor. Out of growing concern for troubled students
_ influenced by US-exported media images and affected by family
problems ranging from alcoholism to divorce _ teachers here have
adopted the American-style tactic of searching students' belongings
in order to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Islas said his school has been conducting these spontaneous
searches for a year, apparently making the school one of the first
in the country to resort to this strategy. At any point in the day,
even in the middle of a class, a small of group of teachers may ask
students to open their bags for inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Education officials in Mexico state, the densely populated
region that arcs around the capital city, recently decided to
expand the bag-searching program to include all of the state's
14,000 elementary, middle and high schools. A total of 3.2 million
students would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Adding urgency to the implementation of ``Operacion Mochila,''
as the project is known in Spanish, was an incident two weeks ago
at Juan Ignacio Ramirez High School.
</P>
<P>
   A student brought a .22-caliber pistol to school by hiding it in
his bookbag on a day when no searches were done. He accidentally
shot himself and another student while taking the gun out to show
his friends. One of the students _ officials would not say which
one _ lost a thumb, but neither was seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators insist that such incidents are rare in Mexican
schools, which are known for imposing a heavy dose of discipline.
What's more, authorities said, the country's strict gun ownership
laws make it difficult for anyone to have easy access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Gun permits must be obtained directly from the military. And
large-caliber weapons are forbidden to civilians, although they can
be bought on the black market, which smuggles US-made weapons
across the border.
</P>
<P>
   While many teachers and parents here say they have heard the
stories about places like Columbine and Jonesboro, where American
students opened fire on their classmates, their decision was not
based on worries that a similar tragedy would happen here.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of what really affects students happens outside the
school, with friends, family, or strangers,'' said Eduardo Luis
Rivera Garcia, Tultitlan's former schools director. ``It's beyond
teachers' control, so this is a way to take some of our preventive
measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor adding to teachers' concerns about what students
are doing outside the classroom, Rivera said, is the growing number
of students who show signs of problems at home.
</P>
<P>
   An indication of that, perhaps, is that teachers are finding
more drugs, knives, and other ``problem'' items in the backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children learn first from their parents, then from the
media,'' Rivera said. ``When the parents aren't there because of
money, alcohol, or separation, then that's when the problems begin,
and eventually those problems show up at school.''
</P>
<P>
   A few schools in Mexico City already use metal detectors to
check students for weapons. But Operation Backpack would be the
largest effort of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they will begin the program once all schools
have received approval from parents' organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Most mothers and fathers, as well as local human rights groups,
seem to support the idea so long as the searches are limited to
students' bags and not their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's appropriate, especially if it means making things
safer for our children,'' said Magdalena Ornelas, 31, as she walked
near the town square with her 10-year-old daughter, Daniela. ``But
teachers must respect the children's privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she thought about the project, Daniela wrinkled her
nose in a half-frown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want someone going through my things,'' she said,
tossing a quick glance up toward her mother. ``But now I won't keep
anything special in my backpack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
