<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CHILD-ABDUCTIONS-HNS &LR;      11-17 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-ABDUCTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEES LITTLE COOPERATION FROM MEXICO IN ABDUCTION CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Norma Luna is proud that her Texas-born daughter
speaks fluent Spanish and could easily visit with relatives in
Mexico. It was a place where her daughter could learn about her
family's culture and history.
</P>
<P>
   But Luna, who lives in Buda, south of Austin, never suspected
that Mexico would become a hideaway where her now-missing daughter,
Laura, and hundreds of other children could be stashed by parents
bent on revenge after losing often-bitter custody battles in court.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department reported this month that at least 750
children caught in custody battles have been abducted by a parent
and taken to Mexico since 1991. It is the leading destination,
followed by Canada and Europe, for one parent fleeing the other
with their American children in tow. A congressional report to be
released in January finds that Mexico is among the countries least
likely to comply with an international agreement for the return of
abducted children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her and miss her; I am willing to do anything to get
her back,'' a tearful Luna, 25, said late last week of 7-year-old
Laura, who has been missing two years.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe that the girl was taken by her father,
Joel Garcia, to the border state of Tamaulipas. Officials say
problems can arise when parents have dual citizenship and in
determining whether an order by a judge in one country is valid in
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matters involving the welfare and custody of children are some
of the most difficult and emotional cases with which we must
deal,'' Mary Ryan, the State Department assistant secretary for
consular affairs, told a congressional panel earlier this month.
``When a parent abducts, or wrongfully retains, a child from his or
her home and prevents the child from having a relationship with the
other parent, the trauma to the child is immediate and compounded
each day the child is not brought home.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustration, rage and sadness about children spirited from the
United States have led some parents to hire lawyers, lobby
government officials, recruit former soldiers trained in abduction,
and resort to ``snatch backs'' _ literally snatching a child and
bringing him or her back across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are Americans taken out of America,'' said Thomas Carter
Jr., a former Green Beret and co-founder of Strategic Security
Group Inc., a company that charges as much as $100,000 to recover a
child. ``The longer (parents) wait, the harder it is for us,'' said
Carter, who recently helped parents recover children abducted in
Uruguay and South Africa but has not been hired for a similar
mission in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a rough deal. The Department of State has limits on what
it can do,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has traveled through mountains and jungles and posed as a
tourist to recover missing children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can either go through the legal system and not get your
child, or you can be proactive and get your child,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jess Ford, director of international affairs for the U.S.
General Accounting Office, the investigative branch of Congress,
said the federal government has had mixed results in recovering
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of upset parents out there,'' said Ford, who
in mid-October forwarded to Congress a preliminary report on
international child abduction. ``It is a nasty situation. You are
talking about custody fights,'' he said from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's findings single out Mexico, Austria, Honduras, Mauritius
and Sweden as ``the most serious'' violators of an international
agreement regarding parental-child abductions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Mexican Embassy in Washington declined to
comment about the situation, as did the Secretary of Foreign
Relations in Mexico City. t( At the center of debate is the 1980
Hague Convention, an agreement among 54 nations that establishes
procedures to find children and resolve custody cases. State
Department personnel say that, while the agreement has been
successful, it can take years to get a child back and there are no
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Marshal, director of children's issues for the State
Department, said that while progress is being made to improve the
recovery of children, as the world changes, there are more cases of
a parent abducting a child and fleeing the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an ever-increasing problem as more and more
couples are multicultural,'' said Marshal, whose office helps
parents pursue the return of abducted progeny. ``It is more
importantly a family problem. These are children, and sometimes
parents in their anger forget what is best for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are hamstrung in dealing with Mexico on these
cases. While the United States honors about 80 percent of the
return requests from Mexico, Mexico honors about 3 percent of the
U.S. requests, according to statistics from the National Center for
Missing and Exploited Children, an organization funded by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Mexican officials have met in California and most
recently in Mexico City to discuss international child abduction.
In what was described by the State Department as a ``small step,''
Juan Rebolledo, the Mexican undersecretary of foreign affairs,
agreed on the importance of the issue and suggested that
representatives of both nations meet as soon a possible to explore
solutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
