<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Nov. 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Beijing) _ Workers at an outmoded textile factory
in Beijing say the trade accord comes too late to help them _ their
factory is a likely casualty _ but they welcome it, railing against
their Communist Party-appointed managers. The big question is
whether the government can provide a safety net for them and
millions of others. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ In a long-awaited concession, the IRA
says it will talk to the disarmament commission. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-MUSHARRAF (Islamabad) _ An interview with Gen.
Musharraf, the coup leader and new ruler. In other developments,
many rich people are arrested after the deadline to repay big bank
loans expires; the government also enacts a new anti-corruption law
aimed at politicians. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLY-LAND (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II, who has long wished
to make a pilgrimage to the most important sites in the Bible, will
tour the Holy Land in the second half of March 2000, the Vatican
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GREECE (Athens) _ With continuing security fears, which
led President Clinton to put off trip to Greece until Friday, the
Greek government bans demonstrations in central Athens, the
harshest such measure since the military junta fell 25 years ago.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TALKS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Chechnya and earthquakes are
on people's minds as leaders gather for summit meeting of
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which starts
Thursday. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TURKEY (Dateline to kum, Turkey) _ Clinton's day; he is
scheduled to meet later with Ehud Barak, Isarel's prime minister.
By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The U.N. Security Council reviews
its Iraqi oil-for-food program. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall on the crash of EgyptAir
Flight 990. By David Johnston and Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-INQUIRE (Washington) _ On the complication of diplomacy
in an investigation of the air crash. By Neil A. Lewis and Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-PILOT (Cairo, Egypt) _ More on EgyptAir 990's crew. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   Others as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments in the budget
process: One knotty problem that remains to a final budget deal:
the impasse over the tiny across-the-board spending cut. By Tim
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-TEACHERS (Washington) _ Roman Catholic bishops are
expected to approve a revolutionary measure that requires those
teaching in Catholic Universities to first be approved by their
bishops. In the view of some, the change would be a disaster and
create all sorts of mistrust; but the majority said that it would
reassert control over the universities so that they do not go the
route of now-secular Harvard and Yale. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-GORE (Atlanta) _ Bill Bradley and Al Gore are in Atlanta
speaking to students and faculty of the Morehouse College medical
school. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-LIFESPAN (Undated) _ Yielding a sharp insight into the
genetic reasons for death, a team of Italian scientists has
discovered a gene that controls lifespan in the mouse. In people,
where the gene was first found, the effects are unknown, but the
Italian scientists and other experts in aging say they can envisage
drugs that affect the gene being used as an anti-wrinkle skin cream
and perhaps for more serious rejuvenation effects. The new gene
fits into a pattern of other findings about aging, many of them
recent, which highlight the role of oxygen damage to the tissues as
a major driver of the aging process. By Nicholas Wade. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JUPITER (Undated) _ Measurements from the Galileo spacecraft
suggest that Jupiter formed farther out in the solar system than
where it now orbits, and that it somehow moved inward, wreaking
havoc on theories of the early years of the solar system. By James
Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-THALIDOMIDE (Washington) _ Thalidomide is found to be
effective against myeloma, an otherwise intractable form of bone
marrow cancer. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices were subdued in October,
rising at 0.2 percent _ in line with expectations and the slowest
pace since June. The core rate of the Consumer Price Index, which
excludes food and energy costs, rose 0.2 percent after a 0.3
percent increase a month earlier. Cheaper energy prices were cited
as the reason for the slowdown from September, when consumer prices
surged 0.4 percent, even though energy prices have been rising
sharply over the last two weeks. Still, the tame data should
solidify expectations in the market that the Federal Reserve is
done raising interest rates for some time. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (London) _ Shares of Mannesmann fall as much
as 8.5 percent in Frankfurt. Other developments on Vodafone's bid.
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-GERMANY (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Looking at how the
prospect of a hostile takeover is playing in Germany. By Edmund L.
Anderews.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ U.S. stocks were down in mid-afternoon
trading. European markets were also lower: London is down 0.56
percent and Frankfurt is down 0.45 percent. The Nikkei closed up
0.66 percent, and the Hang Seng index ended up 0.10 percent. By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Hewlett-Packard reports
fourth-quarter earnings after the market closes, the last Dow
component to report quarterly earnings. The consensus forecast is
for 73 cents a share. Also, Agilent Technologies, the instrument
and testing spinoff, prices its initial public offering. By
Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-HYPERMARKETS (Jakarta) _ The turmoil that accompanied
the collapse of Indonesia's corrupt regime could have been expected
to wreck the economy, impoverishing the affluent. Instead,
Indonesia's middle and upper classes have survived the crisis
intact, thanks to traditional values of thrift and mutual family
support, economists say, and now control a reservoir of wealth
capable of returning the region to long-term economic health.
Nowhere is this island of affluence amid a sea of recession more
visible than in a boom in hypermarkets. Carrefour and another
French chain, Promodes, now have five sprawling stores in Jakarta.
By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BANK (Jakarta) _ The former president of Bank Bali is
at the heart of a financial scandal that has shaken Indonesia. But
he has also kept the loyalty of his former employees. In what has
turned a scandal into a spectacle, Bank Bali staff members
demonstrate almost daily in Jakarta's business district to support
their old boss and to vilify their new ones. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NTT-CUTBACK (Tokyo) _ Nippon Telegraph and Telephone confirms
plans to cut 21,000 jobs, or about 9 percent of its work force and
sharply curtail investment over the next three years in an effort
to enhance its competitiveness. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   William Safire's ``Essay'' and Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
