<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Nov. 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Beijing) _ Workers at an outmoded textile factory
in Beijing say the trade accord comes too late to help them _ their
factory is a likely casualty _ but they welcome it, railing against
their Communist Party-appointed managers. The big question is
whether the government can provide a safety net for them and
millions of others. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ In a long-awaited concession, the IRA
says it will talk to the disarmament commission. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-MUSHARRAF (Islamabad) _ An interview with Gen.
Musharraf, the coup leader and new ruler. In other developments,
many rich people are arrested after the deadline to repay big bank
loans expires; the government also enacts a new anti-corruption law
aimed at politicians. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLY-LAND (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II, who has long wished
to make a pilgrimage to the most important sites in the Bible, will
tour the Holy Land in the second half of March 2000, the Vatican
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GREECE (Athens) _ With continuing security fears, which
led President Clinton to put off trip to Greece until Friday, the
Greek government bans demonstrations in central Athens, the
harshest such measure since the military junta fell 25 years ago.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TALKS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Chechnya and earthquakes are
on people's minds as leaders gather for summit meeting of
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which starts
Thursday. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TURKEY (Dateline to kum, Turkey) _ Clinton's day; he is
scheduled to meet later with Ehud Barak, Isarel's prime minister.
By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The U.N. Security Council reviews
its Iraqi oil-for-food program. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
