process: One knotty problem that remains to a final budget deal:
the impasse over the tiny across-the-board spending cut. By Tim
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-TEACHERS (Washington) _ Roman Catholic bishops are
expected to approve a revolutionary measure that requires those
teaching in Catholic Universities to first be approved by their
bishops. In the view of some, the change would be a disaster and
create all sorts of mistrust; but the majority said that it would
reassert control over the universities so that they do not go the
route of now-secular Harvard and Yale. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-GORE (Atlanta) _ Bill Bradley and Al Gore are in Atlanta
speaking to students and faculty of the Morehouse College medical
school. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-LIFESPAN (Undated) _ Yielding a sharp insight into the
genetic reasons for death, a team of Italian scientists has
discovered a gene that controls lifespan in the mouse. In people,
where the gene was first found, the effects are unknown, but the
Italian scientists and other experts in aging say they can envisage
drugs that affect the gene being used as an anti-wrinkle skin cream
and perhaps for more serious rejuvenation effects. The new gene
fits into a pattern of other findings about aging, many of them
recent, which highlight the role of oxygen damage to the tissues as
a major driver of the aging process. By Nicholas Wade. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JUPITER (Undated) _ Measurements from the Galileo spacecraft
suggest that Jupiter formed farther out in the solar system than
where it now orbits, and that it somehow moved inward, wreaking
havoc on theories of the early years of the solar system. By James
Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-THALIDOMIDE (Washington) _ Thalidomide is found to be
effective against myeloma, an otherwise intractable form of bone
marrow cancer. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices were subdued in October,
rising at 0.2 percent _ in line with expectations and the slowest
pace since June. The core rate of the Consumer Price Index, which
excludes food and energy costs, rose 0.2 percent after a 0.3
percent increase a month earlier. Cheaper energy prices were cited
as the reason for the slowdown from September, when consumer prices
surged 0.4 percent, even though energy prices have been rising
sharply over the last two weeks. Still, the tame data should
solidify expectations in the market that the Federal Reserve is
done raising interest rates for some time. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
