and testing spinoff, prices its initial public offering. By
Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-HYPERMARKETS (Jakarta) _ The turmoil that accompanied
the collapse of Indonesia's corrupt regime could have been expected
to wreck the economy, impoverishing the affluent. Instead,
Indonesia's middle and upper classes have survived the crisis
intact, thanks to traditional values of thrift and mutual family
support, economists say, and now control a reservoir of wealth
capable of returning the region to long-term economic health.
Nowhere is this island of affluence amid a sea of recession more
visible than in a boom in hypermarkets. Carrefour and another
French chain, Promodes, now have five sprawling stores in Jakarta.
By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BANK (Jakarta) _ The former president of Bank Bali is
at the heart of a financial scandal that has shaken Indonesia. But
he has also kept the loyalty of his former employees. In what has
turned a scandal into a spectacle, Bank Bali staff members
demonstrate almost daily in Jakarta's business district to support
their old boss and to vilify their new ones. By Mark Landler.
</P>
