<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TAKES A STEP TOWARD CLEANER AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD   
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki recently proposed that New
York adopt California's toughest-in-the-nation auto emission
controls. His decision provides an opportunity to inject a hearty
dose of reality into the fight to reduce pollution and impede
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The contaminants spewed by each and every moving vehicle, but
more so by some than by others, contribute mightily to fouling the
air we breathe. It is a permanent truth, as certain as death and
taxes, that Americans will continue to elect to transport
themselves to work, personal chores and play in private cars and
trucks, forsaking public transportation when it happens to be
available.
</P>
<P>
   To combat such undermining of air and water quality, along with
helping to alter established weather patterns, many forms of
pollution need to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   For many activists, the demanding California standards were a
weapon to bludgeon car makers into producing zero-emission
automobiles. For a while, much hope was invested in electric cars.
The realities of producing a functioning and practical model put
that prospect on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the darling of those who seek a non-polluting auto is a
car fueled by hydrogen. Early signs point that this possibility is
at best also many years off.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, it is eminently sensible to hold in abeyance the
part of the California standards that called for 10 percent of new
cars to have no emissions within five years. Instead, it is more
realistic to use those tougher requirements to compel manufacturers
to produce a more realistic product, one in which steady yet
incremental reductions are achieved for their fleets on average. By
these means, tailpipe emissions would be reduced by half or more
over the early years of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Without having to hold our collective breaths waiting for the
electric or hydrogen car to materialize as the answer to our
pollution problems, it is preferable to force car makers to upgrade
vehicle performance today.
</P>
<P>
   This means that Washington and the states have to end the
practice of giving in to industry pleadings and pressures for
exceptions and postponements of performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   The weightiness of the announcement made by New York's
Republican governor resides in the fact that the auto industry from
now on will have to cope with more stringent regulations in their
two largest markets in this country. As Massachusetts has also
declared readiness to go along, auto manufacturers face a coalition
of three states in which the industry sells approximately one out
of every four vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Environmental Protection Agency announced its own
tougher requirements. Both sets of rules are more demanding, and
will in stages include sports utility vehicles, which along with
small trucks had enjoyed immunity from regulation not shared by
conventional cars. Because they are bigger and heavier, they use
more gasoline. Because they are so strikingly popular with car
buyers, they loom as a major and increasing polluting factor in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Left unconstrained by the sort of emission requirements imposed
on cars, they would vastly boost the speed at which the environment
would be undermined. There is no sign that the love affair between
Americans and their cars will diminish. Mobility is the
underpinning of the dynamics of our economy and, indeed, our
society and culture.
</P>
<P>
   It is very much worth preserving, but on terms that do not harm
our health and welfare. If there is any country in the world where
the skills and abilities exist to provide for cars that meet those
standards, it ought to be the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
