<HEADER>
A2592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-EARLY-PERIODS-HNS &LR;      11-17 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-PERIODS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS, GIRLS URGED TO DISCUSS MENSTRUATION EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELDA SILVA  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ She still plays with Barbies, loves Disney movies,
and likes to hear bedtime stories, but your little girl is growing
up _ maybe faster than you think.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the typical girl begins to menstruate at
age 12.5. However, girls may start as early as age 9. It is not
unusual for girls in third or fourth grade to have menstrual
periods, said Judy Robinson, director of the National Association
of School Nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard thing to imagine, but it does happen and these
young women need to be prepared,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When is the right time to have The Talk with girls about
menstruation?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a social debate as to when to start talking to children
about sexual education, but I think certainly by the fourth grade
the concept of menstruation should be discussed with young girls,''
said Craig Witz, assistant professor in the department of
obstetrics and gynecology at the University of Texas Health Science
Center in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Weston, a columnist for Girls' Life magazine and the
author of five books, including ``Girltalk: All the Stuff Your
Sister Never Told You,'' said discussing menstruation should be an
ongoing conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers should seize the opportunity to discuss the subject when
it arises, said Weston, who is featured in ``Straight Talk ...
Period,'' a 20-minute video produced by Playtex Products Inc. The
video is inteneded to stimulate conversation between girls and
parents about menstruation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that your daughter is going through your purse
looking for a toy or a dollar and there's a tampon there. You
shouldn't say, `That's none of your business' or even in a nice way
`That's not for you' or `I'll explain that later,''' Weston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if your daughter is just, say, 9, you can go ahead and
say, `You probably know mature girls and women have something
called their periods once a month and this is something that I use
for that.' You can kind of normalize all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents should start talking to their children about their
bodies early on, Robinson said. ``They'll often ask about body
parts. We encourage parents to name them properly rather than
giving them cutesy names, just like you would talk about your
stomach. We encourage parents to talk about `your penis' or
whatever, so kids start to name things (correctly). And that takes
away from it being something to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   When it is time to talk about menstruation, a girl's body will
provide cues, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a matter of watching the changes that are going
on in children, and if your daughter is showing some of those
signs, that would be the time to start talking to her about what to
expect with those body changes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the first signs of puberty in girls are the budding
of breasts, some hair under the arms and the pubic area, and a
rapid growth spurt. Robinson said girls typically will have their
first period about six months later.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1997 study by the American Academy of Pediatrics,
girls are entering puberty earlier than previously suggested in
medical textbooks, budding breasts and sprouting pubic hair as
early as age 8. The same study says the average age at which
American girls begin to menstruate, however, has not changed
significantly in the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason that young girls are going through puberty earlier
than they did before has to do with nutrition almost assuredly,''
Witz said. ``Young girls who are better nourished have menstrual
periods at an earlier age. There's been all this concern and
arm-waving: Does it have to do with environmental factors and other
toxins? Are little girls being exposed to hormones earlier? Maybe.
But probably the big issue is, compared to 100 years ago in
industrialized nations, young women are given better nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   While the age the mother got her period may be a good indicator
for when her daughter will start, Robinson said parents should not
assume a girl will get her period at the same age her mother did.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the menstruation cycle lasts 28 days. About two weeks
before the start of the menstrual period, an egg is released by one
of the ovaries. The egg travels down one of the fallopian tubes to
the uterus. During the cycle, the uterus has developed a thick,
velvety lining to nourish and protect a baby in case of pregnancy.
If the egg is not fertilized by a man's sperm, the lining is shed
through the process of menstruation.
</P>
<P>
   The fluid that leaves the body through the vagina is
brownish-red in color, and though it may seem like more, it is only
about four to six tablespoons. Typically, menstruation lasts three
to five days.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, a girl's period may last longer. For the first couple
of years, menstruation may be irregular.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sometimes is a little bit disconcerting,'' Witz said.
``Older women during the reproductive age can predict when they're
going to have bleeding, which is every 28 days or so. That's
typically not the case with a 12-year-old. It's going to be
irregular, so she needs to be prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
