<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Nov. 18:
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHELSEA-BUILDING (New York) _ Two architects, G. Phillip
Smith and Douglas Thompson, find a vacant lot in Manhattna's
Chelsea area and the rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BLUES-CLUES-HOME (New York) _ What's it like at the top when all
your colleagues are animated and you live in a paper-cutout house?
Steve Burns is the human host of Nickelodeon's Blue's Clues, the
most watched preschool television show in the United States. A
man-boy who is not afraid of looking dumb, Steve towers,
physically, over the Muppets, the alien Teletubbies and the pocket
monsters that are the rock stars of the kiddie-entertainment
circuit. If Pokemon is mythically hip, Steve is nerd transcendent.
By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-MUSEUMS (New York) _ When two Gustav Stickley cabinets go
up for sale at Christie's on Nov. 29, as part of Barbra Streisand's
Arts and Crafts collection, representatives of the Craftsman Farm,
the Stickley home that the cabinets were designed for, will be
there bidding. Whatever the outcome, house museums are busting the
dust on the way they do business. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-CRAFTS (New York) _ Contemporary crafts are the focus of
``To Life &AMP; Light _ A Celebration of Judaica,'' a four-day show and
sale at the American Craft Museum in Manhattan. And what could be
more contemporary than a titanium dreidl? Indeed, all of the works
in this show celebrate the modern. By Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   COLE-LIRTHOGRAPH (Catskill, N.Y.) _ The limestone tablet was
lying face down, a mere doorstop in the dusty remains of Thomas
Cole's painting studio here. On a Saturday afternoon last month, an
architectural historian visiting the cobwebby old studio in back of
the house, picked it up and turned it over. ``I was astonished to
find a drawing on it,'' said Barksdale Maynard, who is researching
the life of Cole, one of the most famous artists of the Hudson
River landscape school. The ``drawing'' he discovered was in fact a
eerie rendering of a castle, done on a lithographic stone. ``Cole
died in the 1840s,'' he said. ``It's astounding that this artwork
would be just kicking around, for 150 years.'' By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   EAMES (Undated) _ At age 38, Eames Demetrios, grandson of the
influential designers Charles and Ray Eames, recalls visits to his
grandparents' house with a child's sense of adventure. Who wouldn't
relish rummaging through the vast storehouse of 901 Washington
Boulevard in Venice, Calif. _ the Eameses' trolley factory turned
studio _ with its countless totems and toys, musical contraptions,
models and banks of drawers stuffed with objects, from around the
world? By Tom Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   COLLECTIBLES-DISPLAY (Undated) _ Life just gets curiouser and
curiouser. With more than $10 billion in sales of manufactured
collectibles last year _ a category whose best sellers include
Beanie Babies, the beanbag toys; Precious Moments, porcelain
figures with inspirational messages; and Department 56, a line of
miniature buildings _ American furniture manufacturers have figured
out that adult collectors, who now number more than 36 million,
could use a place to put it all. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
