<HEADER>
A2625 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-REFORMATION-COMMENTAR     11-17 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORMATION-COMMENTARY-2500(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERHAPS IT'S TIME FOR ANOTHER MARTIN LUTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL S. HORTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most of America's tots were going door-to-door for candy,
many Protestant churches were celebrating the day that a stocky
German monk nailed 95 debating points to a church door. Only this
year, on the 482nd birthday of that event marking the Reformation,
the Roman Catholic Church and a major worldwide Lutheran body
reached a milestone agreement on how human beings are saved, or
reconciled to God.
</P>
<P>
   I want to offer this sweeping indictment: Generally speaking,
Protestants no more than Roman Catholics give much thought to the
disturbing question that drove Martin Luther, as it did the
prophets and apostles before him: ``How can I, knowing who I really
am, ever hope to find a merciful God?''
</P>
<P>
   According to recent surveys, even most professing evangelicals _
who have counted themselves guardians of the gospel _ confuse the
gospel with helpful tips for life. Some reputable studies
demonstrate that 86 percent of this conservative Protestant
grouping agree with the statement, ``God helps those who help
themselves,'' and 75 percent say that human beings are basically
good.
</P>
<P>
   I expect this when I catch Robert Schuller on TV, but now
evangelicalism and mainline Protestantism seem to be generally
characterized by vague moralism _ not an outright rejection of the
beliefs that have shaped their communities in the past so much as a
lazy love affair with the present moment.
</P>
<P>
   We all want to believe that, deep down, we're good people who
just need a little direction. But Christianity tells us that the
bad news is worse than we thought. ``There is no one righteous, no
not one,'' Scripture declares. What we need is not redirection but
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   These alternative ways of viewing salvation no longer represent
Roman Catholicism and Protestantism, respectively. Today, despite
their official theology, Protestants are just as likely to think in
terms of pulling themselves up by their bootstraps.
</P>
<P>
   I know a lot of Catholics who don't believe that they are
accepted by God because of their merit, and no doubt those who
reached the recent Lutheran-Catholic agreement thought that they
were defending both unity and the gospel. But not all of us are
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   I do not think that Rome has changed. (In fact, Rome would want
us to say that it has not changed in its doctrine.) But it's
incontrovertible that Protestantism has.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Attended with regal celebrations, Cardinal Edward Idris Cassidy,
the papal emissary for church unity, and Bishop Christian Krause,
president of the Lutheran World Federation, officially agreed that
the central issue of division is no longer an obstacle to unity.
</P>
<P>
   That apparent obstacle to unity is the doctrine of
justification.
</P>
<P>
   According to Luther, John Calvin and a host of Reformers whose
spiritual descendants represent the largest and most vibrant branch
of Protestant Christianity, Scripture is perfectly clear about how
salvation happens. It starts with a sober view of human nature
after the fall of our first parents, leaving all of us helpless to
save ourselves _ even with God's help.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect righteousness and holiness that God's character
requires (with which God endowed humanity in creation) has been
lost, and it cannot be regained by human effort. Even the
Christian's best deeds are mingled with self-interest and
self-righteousness, so (as St. Paul addressed the subject) ``the
righteousness which is of the law'' is a path that can only lead to
condemnation, while ``the righteousness which is of faith'' is a
gift.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: God sent Jesus Christ into the world, not
merely as a moral example to show us how to become acceptable to
God but rather to live under the terms of the law, perfectly
fulfill its righteous demands, while taking upon himself our guilt
on the cross. There he was judged by God for our unrighteousness;
and in his resurrection, we _ the guilty _ are now declared
righteous.
</P>
<P>
   Our guilt is ``imputed'' or ``credited'' to Jesus Christ, while
his righteousness is imputed to us. Luther called it ``the
marvelous exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   However, at the time of the Reformation (as in our day, across
the denominational landscape), popular religion had been seized by
superstition and ignorance. This is not even disputed by Cardinal
Joseph Ratzinger, chief doctrinal officer for Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Salvation could even be purchased, as a popular ditty expressed
it: ``When the coin in the coffer clings, a soul from purgatory
springs.'' It was this practice that Luther's famous theses
targeted.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   When Renaissance scholars began to investigate the original
Greek New Testament texts, many among their number concluded that
the medieval church had fundamentally misread the Scriptures. A
popular slogan of medieval theology was: ``God will not deny his
grace to those who do what lies within them.'' Do your best, God
will take care of the rest _ or as Benjamin Franklin put things,
``God helps those who help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The official Roman Catholic position adopted at the Council of
Trent in response to the Reformation was that although salvation is
by grace (God's unmerited favor), it is not by grace alone. Initial
grace in baptism was a gift, but it could be improved or lost based
on one's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, believers could never be certain that their
obedience and cooperation were sufficient to merit final
justification _ that is, acceptance before God on Judgment Day.
</P>
<P>
   Is this righteousness or justice that God requires possible in
this life? That was one of the big questions. Maybe not in this
life, said Rome, but perhaps in the next (i.e., purgatory).
</P>
<P>
   The Protestant Reformers argued that here again Scripture was
perfectly clear. Jesus announced that his mission was ``not to call
the righteous, but sinners,'' which is only good news if one really
recognizes and experiences oneself to be a sinner. Although a
Christian will never be good enough to deserve God's acceptance,
even with God's grace working in one's life, he or she could be
fully accepted in Christ through faith alone. Christ's
righteousness alone, not the believer's, made one acceptable to
God.
</P>
<P>
   That was the heart of the Reformation _ in comparison to which
debates about such matters as the authority of the pope, the nature
of the sacraments and the role of Mary paled. St. Paul called the
doctrine of justification by grace alone, through faith alone,
because of Christ alone, ``a stumbling block'' _ even a
``scandal.'' It was and still is a tough pill to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Rome's Council of Trent ``anathematized'' (condemned) this
teaching that the churches of the Reformation regarded as nothing
less than the gospel itself, and classed its adherents as heretics.
</P>
<P>
   So why this walk down memory lane? Because nobody seems to
remember. Most _ even regular churchgoers _ just haven't heard
these distinctions in a generation or two. The ignorance in
Protestant churches today may even rival that of medieval religion.
People today, including evangelicals, appear to be more interested
in being ``relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to be useful to a culture driven by fads doesn't exactly
accommodate a faith that has historically been concerned about
passing the convictions of one generation of Christians down to
another. Doctrine, that rewarding but difficult matter of what one
believes and why one believes it, is a liability these days.
``Whatever works for you,'' people say, as if there were no such
thing as a God of justice as well as mercy, a future reckoning or a
future life. Religion equals therapy, at least one version of it.
</P>
<P>
   Other Protestants have increasingly come to regard religion as
the expression of one's own inner experience or social and
political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Luther's warning is, therefore, just as relevant today among
Protestants and Catholics alike: If you look within, at your own
inner experience, resources, morality or felt needs, you will never
find salvation. It only comes by looking outside of oneself, to the
God who has spoken clearly in Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``gospel'' means ``good news,'' and if salvation
depends on my performance to any degree at all, then I would say
that Christianity represents a serious instance of false
advertising. A recent convert could reasonably complain: ``Look,
you told me that my salvation depended entirely on what God has
done in Christ _ and now you believe that it's OK to believe that
it depends in part on what God has done in Christ and in part on
what I have done for God.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not a different emphasis, an improvement on theological
hair-splitting _ rather, it determines whether we're fudging a bit
when we say that this is good news.
</P>
<P>
   I'm aware of the ecumenical discussions that have taken place in
recent years. In fact, I've closely studied the ecumenical
documents from the time of the Reformation (when the Reformers
themselves burned the midnight oil to attempt to achieve agreement
with Rome) to the present. There have been great successes in this
process.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this past Oct. 31 in the city of Augsburg,
Germany, where the Lutheran Confession was adopted, the
announcement was that agreement on justification had been achieved
at last, even though there was no evidence of Rome having changed
its official position.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the rhetoric is more charitable. In fact, phrases
are used that seem to affirm that salvation is by God's grace alone
on the basis of Christ alone through faith alone _ but these things
are not actually said. They are not actually said because Rome
continues to affirm, as its most recent catechism illustrates, that
after believers die, ``they undergo purification'' in purgatory
``so as to achieve the holiness necessary to enter the joy of
heaven'' (page 268).
</P>
<P>
   ``Moved by the Holy Spirit and by charity, we can then merit for
ourselves and for others the graces needed for our sanctification,
for the increase of grace and charity, and for the attainment of
eternal life'' (page 487).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's not Rome that has changed, but Protestants. While
Rome has remained reasonably faithful to its principle of ``semper
idem'' (always the same), modern Protestantism has craved
innovation, often at the expense of what some of us would still be
willing to call ``truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I'm not suggesting that we return to a
period like the 19th century in which we caricatured each other's
views, and feared that any day the pope would try to take over the
world (or at least America) through Irish immigration. Furthermore,
who can doubt that we have a lot to learn from each other and to
affirm together?
</P>
<P>
   The conversation should continue. In fact, judging from the
state of affairs in Protestantism, conservative to liberal,
misunderstanding the gospel is a serious problem for all of us. The
difference is that Rome still officially condemns the message that
we are ``justified freely by his grace apart from works of the
law,'' as Scripture puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is willing to make a choice between the gospel's
clarity and pursuing the unity of Christ's visible church. But the
general reporting on this event has ignored the dissent of millions
of relatively friendly, open-minded Christians who insist on the
priority of the gospel over unity.
</P>
<P>
   For us, it's not about winning an argument or getting the other
side to admit they were wrong. It is a lot deeper than that. It has
to do with whether we can know that we have peace with God and
confidently relate this good news to other sinners like us. There
is no reason for accepting this age-old division if Protestantism
itself is largely mired in a benign moralism that has reduced it to
a feel-good religion for America's middle class.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's only religious bigotry that would keep us
divided when there were not inalienable matters of conscience at
stake. But for those of us who are still convinced that
justification or acceptance before God is, as St. Paul declared,
``by faith apart from the works of the law,'' the denial of this
leaves us in complete despair.
</P>
<P>
   These two gospels are easily distinguished without a lot of
theological jargon. One says that on Judgment Day, God will find in
me the righteousness that he justly requires because I have
fulfilled his will. The other says that on that day, although God
will find nothing more in me to merit eternal life than he might
find in the most vilified criminal, the merit of Christ is
sufficient to acquit me before his bar and robe me in perfect
righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   Is this just a bunch of theology, remote from our concerns? If
so, it only measures the extent to which our churches have been
willing to ignore the most important part of their job. Those who
think that they are good enough to appear before God's judgment in
their own righteousness, albeit assisted by God's grace, are
welcome to give it a try. But, convinced that a day of reckoning is
up ahead, a lot of us are still unwilling to call that ``good
news.''
</P>
<P>
   (Michael S. Horton, author of a number of books on this subject,
teaches theology at Westminster Seminary in Escondido, Calif., and
is the vice chairman of the Alliance of Confessing Evangelicals
(www.alliancenet.org). He wrote this for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
