<SLUG> BC-HIPPIE-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIPPIE COUTURE IS COOL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSE MARY BUDGE  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Wow, man. What a flashback. Embroidered bell
bottoms, peasant blouses, ponchos, fringe and beads _ plenty of
beads _ have emerged from nostalgia as free-spirited hippie styles
make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Call it neo-hippie chic. Call it Bohemian. Call it a backlash
against boredom. Bohemian dressing stands in sharp contrast to the
plain styles that have dominated the fashion scene for many years.
Forget tailored blazers and basic-black T-shirts. We want color,
and we want embellishments such as embroidery, feathers and fake
fur to crank up the wardrobe volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the most colorful things you've ever seen _ really
fun clothes _ and just seeing them puts you in a good mood,'' said
Donna Kaler, who runs Anniegoglin, an apparel boutique in San
Antonio. ``There's a strong influence from other countries and
cultures, lots of pattern mixing, decoration and texture. But the
secret lies in the mix. You combine the elements in your own way,
which gives every outfit personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Sui, Marc Jacobs and Tom Ford for Gucci are just a few of
the big names into the mix. And they're charging big prices (you
need $3,000 for those feather-trimmed Gucci jeans). The good news
is, there's no need to pay so much. Watch for inexpensive knockoffs
_ there are plenty of them for less than $50. Thrift shops and
second-hand stores also are an option. Get some faded bell-bottom
jeans and add your own embellishment.
</P>
<P>
   With free-wheeling hippie haute, the attitude counts more than
the label. There hasn't been such a liberated attitude in fashion
since the '60s when flower children shed their ladylike suits and
panty girdles for braless blouses, bell bottoms and embroidered
denims. Couturier Yves Saint-Laurent sanctioned the movement in the
1970s when he presented an entire collection of folkloric looks and
peasant dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Kaler gets a kick watching teen-age customers discover Bohemian
dressing. ``They just go wild over the possibilities,'' she said.
``But the styles aren't just for the young. Almost everything is
suitable for any age. And for those of us who've worn it and loved
it all before _ oh, what memories!''
</P>
<P>
   Trend-tracker David Wolfe of the New York-based Donnegar Group
thinks nostalgia is behind the Bohemian boom. People are reflecting
on times past and longing for lighthearted clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Bohemian styles fill the bill. They help you connect with
history and with other cultures. They allow you to play with fun
stuff such as fringe, feathers, embroidery and beads. In an age
that's mass-marketed and machine-produced, the styles celebrate
arts, crafts and individuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put the clothes together almost any way and it's
fine,'' said Irene Ojeda of Christine's in San Antonio. ``Long
coats work with short skirts, stripes can mix with animal prints
and feathers can go with fur. You can dress the clothes up, you can
dress them down _ the look can be casual, exotic, Oriental,
contemporary or just about anything else. There really aren't any
rules. I guess you sort of make up your own rules as you go
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all this fashion freedom might make some people
nervous. For the fashion-timid, Kaler said, one or two pieces
instead of a complete turnout might be best. For example, a woman
could wear embellished jeans with a conservative sweater, carry a
crochet bag with an afternoon dress or combine an embroidered top
with a business suit. Little touches can reflect the trend, she
explained. But you will never know how much Gypsy is in your soul
without experimenting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to ``A History of Fashion'' by J. Anderson Black,
Madge Garland and Frances Kennett (William Morrow &AMP; Co., $15.95)
Bohemian dressing originated with the Gypsies who traveled Europe,
adding colorful elements to their costumes everywhere they went.
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s and '70s, this ethnic dressing moved to the
forefront when designers got interested in other cultures. Gaucho
trousers tucked into Russian Cossack boots, cheongsams from the Far
East, sarongs from the East Indies and embroideries from Japan
marched down the runways shaking up couture. Eventually it all
filtered down to the hippies, who naturally gravitated to offbeat
forms of dressing.
</P>
<P>
   But is offbeat dressing appropriate most places?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the occasion and the crowd and make sure the outfit's
appropriate,'' Ojeda said. ``Maybe underplay things if you're
really concerned. But on the other hand, don't worry too much. To
make a fashion statement these days, you need to be a little
daring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
