<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e NEW&AMP;NOTABLE &LR;      11-17 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 NEW &AMP; NOTABLE  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Fixing creditline to make it  &UR; Special for The Arizona
Republic)
</P>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE &QL; 
Anne Stephenson &QL; 
Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``MY MOVIE BUSINESS'' &QL; 
By John Irving (Random House, $19.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, New &AMP; Notable has had occasion to talk with a
number of good writers whose books have been made into movies,
including Alice Walker (``The Color Purple''), Michael Ondaatje
(``The English Patient''), Sue Miller (``The Good Mother''),
Russell Banks (``The Sweet Hereafter''), Anna Quindlen (``One True
Thing'') and David Guterson (``Snow Falling on Cedars''). Almost
without exception, the happiest among them were those who had
relinquished control, who recognized from the start that they were
writers of novels, not screenplays. They took the money, handed
over their books and waited to see what came of it. Over the years,
John Irving has chosen a different path. He declined to write the
screenplay for ``The World According to Garp,''but he was involved
enough in the filmmaking process to rankle under the changes that
Steve Tesich made in his novel. He also declined to write the
screenplay for ``The Hotel New Hampshire,'' then watched as Tony
Richardson made a farcical exaggeration of the book. Irving did not
decline to write a screenplay for ``The Cider House Rules.'' In
fact, he wrote many of them, draft after draft for director after
director. Over the course of 13 years, he worked with four
directors and wrote so many versions of the script that he learned
how to do it right. His first draft, written when he still believed
a film should be true to a novel, would have made a nine-hour
movie. The final script whittled a 500-page novel down to 136
pages. By that time, Irving knew that ``a screenplay, as a piece of
writing, is merely the scaffolding for a building someone else is
going to build.'' This memoir of his moviemaking experiences is
unabashedly self-indulgent, a chance for Irving to talk about his
novels, his children and friends, his grandfather (whose work as an
obstetrician influenced the story of ``Cider House'') and his
success. It's also a chance to plug the movie, which is set to open
here next month. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE ART OF THE STORY'' &QL; 
Edited by Daniel Halpern (Viking, $40) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This international anthology of contemporary short stories
includes work from 78 contributors from 35 countries. All of the
writers were born from 1938 to 1970 and were chosen by Halpern to
represent a greater sensitivity to popular culture than those
included in his earlier volume, ``The Art of the Tale.'' These
stories, he says, are ``less in `the classical mode' and more
reactive to the media in all its venues. These younger writers have
distanced themselves _ sometimes subtly, sometimes less so _ from
the influential writers practicing during the first two or three
decades of the 20th century.'' Raymond Carver just made the cut, as
did Margaret Atwood, Richard Bausch, Ian McEwan, Joyce Carol Oates,
Amos Oz, Kenya's Ngugi Wa Thiong O (EDITORS: how it's listed at
amazon.com ) and Argentina's Luisa Valenzuela. Among the younger
writers are Lorrie Moore, Ben Okri, Salman Rushdie, Bobbie Ann
Mason, Tobias Wolff, Barry Hannah, James Kelman, Richard Ford,
Deborah Eisenberg, Banana Yoshimoto, Martin Amis, Turkey's Murathan
Mungan, Ghana's Ama Ata Aidoo and Lebanon's Hanan Al-Shaykh. Also
here are writers from Cuba, Nigeria, Martinique, India, Haiti,
Vietnam, Russia, Hungary, Somalia, Uruguay, France, Tanzania,
Poland, Scandinavia, South Africa and China. &QL; 
``ENCHANTED NIGHT'' &QL; 
By Steven Millhauser (Crown, $17) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the night of revelation. This is the night the dolls
wake. This is the night of the dreamer in the attic. This is the
night of the piper in the woods.'' This passage is a sign of
ethereal things to come. Millhauser, who won a Pulitzer Prize for
``Martin Dressler,'' has written an otherworldly story in brief
passages that portray people in a Connecticut town one hot summer
night. There is Havershaw, a 39-year-old man who lives in the attic
of his mother's house and struggles to find some justification for
his life. There are ``the outlaws,'' a gang of teenage girls who
break into houses and steal unimportant things (refrigerator
magnets, toothbrushes), always leaving behind the same note _ ``We
Are Your Daughters.'' There is Janet Manning, a young woman with
sensuous thoughts of the handsome stranger she met on the beach
that day, and William Cooper, a young man with a crush on a lovely
mannequin in the window of a department store (a mannequin that
will, on this magical night, come to life). And all across town,
the old, forgotten dolls stored in attics begin to wake up and
shake their dusty limbs. Some town, huh? Millhauser's dreamlike
tale _ a mere 109 pages long _ is grounded in the familiar longing
of his characters and played out under a big, white moon on an
enchanted summer night. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``FRONTIER CHILDREN'' &QL; 
By Linda Peavy and Ursula Smith (Oklahoma, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was sadder to see than the graves of children who died
along the westward trail as their families traveled with the wagon
trains of the mid-1800s. And nothing was more triumphant than news
of children who made the journey and began a new life. Peavy and
Smith, whose previous collaborations were ``Pioneer Women'' and
``Women in Waiting in the Westward Movement,'' offer a clear-eyed
view of what frontier life was like for youngsters of Chinese,
Hispanic, Native American, African-American and European
backgrounds. Because the experiences of these children were largely
undocumented, the authors have relied on stories handed from one
generation to another, the few existing letters and diaries written
by frontier children, journals kept by explorers and missionaries,
and, most important, photographs. Their text is accompanied by 206
black-and-white images, and some of them will break your heart. &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson &LR; worldnet.att.net via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1608EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
