<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEWEST WAVE: MUSIC GOES DIGITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 Eds: This is one in a series of articles on online shopping)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only a year ago that Diamond Multimedia introduced the
Rio PMP300, the world's first portable MP3 music player, and
spurred an audio revolution in downloaded music.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are more than a dozen variations on the theme,
portable players offering features like FM-radio tuners and
easy-to-use controls. More important, the players _ costing from
about $200 to $400 _ are moving toward improved storage capacity so
they can carry more tunes. Most players store no more than 64
minutes of high-quality music.
</P>
<P>
   So far, fewer than a million MP3 players have been sold in the
United States. But audio market analysts and MP3 player makers say
they expect sales to be brisk this holiday season and beyond. One
reason is that mainstream America has begun discovering digitized
music on the Internet. Every day, about 17 million MP3 files are
downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous portable players, MP3 players have the
significant advantage of having no moving parts. As a consequence,
they are practically skip- and flutter-proof and the batteries they
use last longer. And the sound is near CD quality.
</P>
<P>
   The rage for MP3 has manufacturers scrambling to ride the next
digital wave. In the spring, Samsung Electronics plans to introduce
an MP3 player that will play not only downloaded music files but
also still pictures and video from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the widening popularity of online music and portable
devices that play it, Packard Bell NEC recently introduced the NEC
Home Music Studio system, a personal computer that is designed to
capture, manage and make digital music. Built-in software allows it
to download and upload music to and from an MP3 player.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is no guarantee that MP3, which is a format for
compressing and storing digital audio signals, will continue to be
the compression format of choice. Sony has introduced a digital
player that uses its own audio format. And there are other software
approaches to storing digital music on the way from major players
like Microsoft, IBM, Liquid Audio and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But a Betamax-style demise of MP3 may be years off, some
analysts say. In the meantime, one MP3 maker, Creative Labs, is
hedging its bets with its new Nomad II, a digital player equipped
to adapt to whatever audio format is winning the day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such future-proofing comes with a cost: about $100
more than the price of its nearest competitor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. SONY CD WALKMAN D-EJ01 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sony's CD Walkman D-EJ01, a sleek, slick and shiny update of the
portable CD player, looks as if it might have fallen off the
starship Enterprise. Breaking with classic clamshell design, the
D-EJ01 does not open; it loads CDs with a slide-in mechanism and
plays them with remarkable fidelity and power. Besides being
reasonably shock resistant, the $349.95 player also promises 62
hours of continuous playback with NiMH rechargable batteries. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. SKIPDOCTOR  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SkipDoctor is a $34.99, handheld, hand-cranked device that lives
up to claims that it can repair damaged optical discs, whether they
are CD, CD-ROMs, DVDs or game discs like those used in Sega's
Dreamcast. SkipDoctor is best used to repair troublesome scratches,
and is reliable and fairly simple to use. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. PANASONIC DVD-L50 PORTABLE DVD/CD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD-L50 Portable DVD/CD player by Panasonic is nothing less than
a home theater that can fit in the palm of your hand. Amazingly
compact, the $999 player opens to reveal a five-inch LCD color
screen and half-dollar-size stereo speakers linked to a fully
functioning DVD/CD player. Films are remarkably sharp whether they
are seen on the player or are piped to a television with supplied
patch cords. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. REPLAYTV 2001 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first of several new tapeless video recording devices to
arrive this year, ReplayTV lets you watch a ``real-time recording''
of a live program, put it on pause to answer the phone or grab a
snack, then return to pick up your viewing where you left off, even
as the recording continues.
</P>
<P>
   The ReplayTV 2020 model ($699) records up to 20 hours of
television programs on a hard disk drive and enables couch potatoes
to create their own television channels based on their favorite
themes _ not just series names like ``Star Trek'' but also
``fishing'' or ``Michelle Pfeiffer.'' It requires a phone jack to
download the latest program schedules each night, but in doing so
it also automatically resets the clock. The era of the flashing
12:00, alas, is over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   5. SONY MDR-IF330RK CORDLESS HEADPHONES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MDR-IF330RK cordless headphones by Sony ($129) are designed for
anyone who wants to have his sound delivered without being tethered
to its source. The headphones, which also connect to home audio
systems, televisions and VCRs, provide a solid sound with good deep
bass capacity. Its transmitter, which promises 100 hours of
(rechargeable) battery life, has a range of 24 feet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. AUDIOVOX MP DJ &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lower-cost MP DJ by Audiovox is a late but notable entry
into the MP3 music player category. Tiny, even by MP3 standards,
the MP DJ has a startling sound nonetheless. Taking advantage of
its odd, stop-watch shape, the MP DJ has a large liquid crystal
display and logically placed controls. The $179.95 player comes
with 32MB on board and can be upgraded with additional memory. Even
the download software that comes with it is cute. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. SRS LABS WOW THING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WOW Thing by SRS Labs is a makeup-case-size device that when
plugged into a personal computer's sound system creates stunning
power and 3-D sound effects _ on the cheap. Costing $29.95 and sold
only on the Web at www.wowthing.com, the device is simple and
effective. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. CREATIVE LABS CD-RW BLASTER 8432 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD-RW Blaster 8432 by Creative Labs is a handy and, better yet,
speedy way to use a personal computer to create or copy CDs and
CD-ROMs. The $299.99 CD writer and rewriter is among one of the
fastest and most modestly priced devices of its kind. It can record
(to write-once disc) 60 minutes or 545 megabytes of data in under
nine minutes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9. AUDIBLE.COM MOBILEPLAYER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to take the author Frank McCourt on the road,
Audible.com, which offers thousands of downloadable versions of
books on tape available for PCs and PDAs, also makes the
MobilePlayer. The 2-megabyte device can hold two hours of audio and
comes with a cradle for downloading. Alone, the player is $99; the
player is free when you purchase $9.95 of content from Audible.com
every month. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10. RIO 500 DIGITAL AUDIO PLAYER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The more powerful version of the planet's first MP3 player, the
new Rio ($269) is elegant and packed with 64MB of memory that can
be expanded with an additional memory card to 96MB. The Rio 500
connects to computers (PCs running Windows 98 and Macs) by way of a
USB port and a much improved download software. Most of all, its
sound is rich, full and detailed.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   11. SONY MINIDISC MZ-R55 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a year on the market, MiniDisc MZ-R55 by Sony is still the
finest and smallest digital device to record and play back
prerecorded music. While it is barely larger than the
2.5-inch-square blank minidisc, the device can faithfully record up
to 74 minutes of music on the disc from practically any source.
Handsome in its metal skin, the $349 MZ-R55 produces a sound that
is true, full of dynamic range and highly resistant to skips. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   12. SONY GLASSTRON PLM-S700 PC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLM-S700 PC Glasstron virtually allows wearers to carry a large
screen in their pocket. A pair of hyperhi-tech wraparound glasses
by Sony, the Glasstron, which cost $2,599, can render computer
graphics or the output of any audio-visual device with an S-video
high-speed connection in the privacy of the glasses. The effect
creates the impression of a 30-inch screen being viewed from about
6 feet away. Headphones are included. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   13. I2GO EGO &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EGo by i2Go is the first MP3 player on the market that is
designed specifically for use in the car. Appearing like the sport
utility vehicle of pagers, the $299 eGo can hold just more than one
hour of near CD-quality music on a 64MB memory card. The unit can
be mounted in the car by way of a cassette adapter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   14. YAMAHA (AT)PET RP-U100 PC RECEIVER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yamaha's solution to the blight of poor off-the-shelf PC audio
systems, this $500 minitower packing 30-watts per channel is
designed to stand between the computer and its speakers. Using
home-entertainment-center style enhancements, the receiver can
deliver a no-nonsense surroundlike sound, just right for enjoying
the latest DVD movies or computer games.
</P>
</TEXT>
