<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     11-17 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTION WITH DRYER'S EXHAUST VENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not difficult to attach an exhaust vent to a clothes
dryer, but the hookup must be done properly to avoid the
possibility of fire. According to the National Fire Protection
Association, almost 14,000 fires each year are caused by improper
venting of the dryer or careless maintenance procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Before hooking up a vent line to your dryer read the owners
manual. This will outline the steps for installing the vent, but
beware, because some of guidelines may not meet code requirements
in your community. A few manuals, for example, say that it is
acceptable to vent the dryer indoors if it is in a large, open
room.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons this is not a good idea. In the first
place, most codes prohibit this type of venting. Second, the
average load of wash from the washing machine will retain about one
to two gallons of water after the final cycle. The dryer pulls that
moisture from the clothes and expels it into the air as vapor. This
extra humidity will eventually condense on insulation, timbers and
metal, causing them to deteriorate, rot or rust. Also, venting a
gas dryer indoors can be dangerous because the air discharge can
contain a combination of potentially lethal combustion gases.
</P>
<P>
   Dryer manuals specify the diameter of the ducting to be used for
venting. Most dryers have a four-inch diameter male take-off
fitting on the back of the appliance. Attach a duct of the same
diameter to this fitting. Using duct with a narrower diameter would
restrict the airflow. Using a wider duct would diminish the force
of the airflow and allow lint to settle at the bottom of the duct
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Codes are often strict about the length of a dryer vent. Most
codes limit a straight run, without bends, to 25 feet. Subtract
five feet from that distance for each 90-degree bend. Thus a dryer
vent with two 90-degree elbows cannot exceed 15 feet in length. The
type and size of the vent hood at the end of the duct also affects
the total length. The standard vent hood that has a four-inch and
will not affect the length of the duct run. If, however, you
substitute a hood with a narrower two-and-a-half-inch reach you
must subtract six feet from the length of the total duct. Thus the
15-foot dryer vent in the previous example would now be shortened
to 9 feet if a two-and-a-half-inch hood were attached.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even with a hood the duct is still an open hole that
could prove inviting for small rodents, birds or insects. Some
homeowners place a piece of screening across the opening to keep
out pests. The problem with screening is that it captures lint and
restricts the airflow. This could cause the dryer to overheat
during operation. It is better to install a back-draft damper
(available at home centers and appliance supply stores) in the
duct. The damper has a spring-controlled flap that remains shut
until the force of the dryer air pushes it open.
</P>
<P>
   Duct material includes flexible vinyl, flexible Mylar foil,
flexible aluminum and rigid aluminum. Flexible vinyl was once
popular as a ducting material, but now many codes prohibit using it
and foil for dryer ducts. The main problem with using flexible
ducting is that the ridges throughout the length of the duct catch
lint. These accumulations of lint will block the airflow so the
duct must be cleaned periodically. This is not a problem with rigid
aluminum ducts. For this reason rigid aluminum ducts, not flexible
ones, should be used if the duct is to be enclosed in a wall or
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Now matter what type of ducting material you use, the sections
should be joined end to end with either approved clamps or tape.
There are two types of duct clamp available. One is all metal and
it looks like a large hose clamp for a washing machine or
automotive radiator hose. The other type of clamp is made of
flexible plastic. Both are available at home centers.
</P>
<P>
   You can use the familiar gray fabric duct tape or metal foil
tape to join sections. Fabric tape is cheaper than metal foil tape
but not as durable. The hot air passing through the duct will cause
it to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you use clamps or tape is largely a matter of
preference. Do not, however, use sheet metal screws or pop rivets
to joint sections of duct. These would snag lint and pose a fire
hazard.
</P>
<P>
   All dryer ducts should be inspected and cleaned at least twice a
year. This may require disconnecting a section or two so you can
look inside and vacuum out lint accumulations. Afterward,
reassemble the sections then check all the connections to make sure
they are secure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
