<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SPENDING (Washington) _ As the White House and the
Republican-led Congress appear near a final deal on the federal
budget, the possibility of a government shutdown looms. Some
lawmakers threaten to stall the legislation _ and a resolution to
keep government running past midnight _ unless money is added for
higher dairy price supports and tobacco-lawsuit proceeds are
diverted to shore up Medicare and Social Security. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL-WARNINGS (Washington) _ More than 100 consumer health
groups urge the federal government to require that warnings on
alcoholic beverages be clear, consistent and placed on the front of
the bottle. By JENNIFER CORBET DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEETING (Washington) _ President Clinton is to attend a
meeting of the leaders of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe starting Thursday, where the main topic
promises to be the same issue that helped lead to the formation of
the organization _ Russia. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-TV (San Francisco) _ Children today spend so many hours
watching television, playing video games and the like that media
use could qualify as their full-time job. A new study by the Kaiser
Family Foundation finds that the typical American child spends more
than 38 hours a week as a ``media consumer'' in a home that
averages three TVs, three tape players, three radios, two VCRs, two
CD players, a video game player and a computer, as well as
newspapers, magazines and comic books. By VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ Closing arguments begin in the
capital murder trial of Shawn Berry, one of three white men accused
in the slaying of a black man. The jury is expected to begin
deliberating and will be sequestered overnight if necessary. By
PATTY REINERT and RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Washington) _ An advance on George W. Bush's foreign
policy speech Friday, which is being accompanied by ads and
national interviews to coincide with the release of his
autobiography. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ Saddled with a 2-7 record and facing the
prospect that hotshot rookie Steve Francis might be suspended, the
Houston Rockets try to regroup as they return home to face the
Sacramento Kings on Thursday night at Compaq Center. By JONATHAN
FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-NL-MVP (Undated) _ Chipper Jones of the Atlanta Braves is
expected to win the National League Most Valuable Player Award over
Jeff Bagwell of the Houston Astros. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-AFCEAST (Undated) _ Four of the teams went to the playoffs
last year, and the same number appear headed for the postseason
again this season. Such is life in the AFC East, the NFL's best
division, where the Indianapolis Colts and Miami Dolphins share
first place with 7-2 records. But the New England Patriots and
Buffalo Bills are only a game behind at 6-3. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
