<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN'T HAVE GOODS SENT TO A MOUSE PAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (One of a series of articles on holiday online shopping) 
 (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By IAN AUSTEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-Commerce is like comedy. Coming up with ideas is easy;
delivery is hard.
</P>
<P>
   If the explosion in online shopping had taken place in 1959
instead of 1999, getting packages delivered might have been easier.
In 1959, many homes still had milk boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sort of a disconnect,'' said Carter Griffen, a
co-founder of Mental Physics, an e-commerce systems company, based
in Vienna, Va., that is hoping to profit from the situation. ``The
front end of e-commerce _ placing an order _ is very sexy, very
easy. Receiving the order, however, is problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   His company is one of a few promoting the idea of a jumbo
mailbox for online parcels. After recently purchasing the patent
rights to Smartbox, a roll-up household parcel container that was
invented by a Kansas City, Mo., dry cleaner but never made it to
market, Mental Physics is developing a series of locked, reinforced
boxes of various sizes that will sit outside houses.
</P>
<P>
   To allow access to all delivery services, the yet-to-be-named
devices will be wired to the Internet. When the box owners make an
online purchase, special software will create and transmit a code
for each order. A delivery driver can punch in the code on a keypad
to unlock the box and make the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Streamline.com, has at least one variation of
that idea already in place. The company, which runs errands and
delivers a variety of goods to suburban customers outside Boston
and Washington, installs boxes with a full-size
refrigerator-freezer and two room-temperature shelves in the
basement or garage of customers as part of its service fee of $30 a
month. To allow its drivers access to the boxes, Streamline also
fits keypad locks on its customers' doors. About 3,700 houses now
have Streamline's boxes, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a widespread belief that any kind of superbox for
parcels will be a hard sell and perhaps unworkable outside spacious
suburbs. Even Streamline is developing portable dry ice containers
that it will leave outside the houses of customers who will not, or
cannot, accept more permanent boxes. It's a solution that has been
used for decades by Omaha Steaks, a mail-order giant turned
e-commerce merchant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see boxes working right now,'' said Elaine Rubin,
chairman of Shop.org, a trade group for online retailers. ``I've
got enough bikes, baseball bats and other junk in my garage
already. I don't need a big box in there as well. Outside, it's an
eyesore. And how often do people order online, anyway? About three
times a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out where parcels can be safely sent is an issue that
buyers from ordinary mail-order catalogs, which outsell online
merchants by a wide margin, have long encountered. Jill Frankle,
director of retail research at Gomez Advisors, said she expected
online buyers to use the same kinds of solutions for the next three
to four years. ``The current system works for most people,'' Ms.
Frankle said.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, Ms. Frankle suggested, a solution is getting
packages delivered at work. While she knows of no firm data that
support her view, Amazon.com's ``purchase circles'' lend it at
least some anecdotal support. To help its customers make choices
about books, music CD's and videos, Amazon creates best-seller
lists grouped around shipping destinations, including corporate
offices.
</P>
<P>
   While some of those lists are filled with books that are
probably work-related (Boeing's is heavy on engineering and
computer tomes, and the most popular book on Microsoft's list is
the latest offering from its chairman, William H. Gates 3rd), many
strongly suggest that either a lot of niche book clubs are meeting
in cubicles or offices have become a handy delivery spot for
Amazon's boxes. The top seller at the Gillette Co. is Bret Lott's
``Jewel,'' a novel about a child with Down syndrome, which is
followed on the list by Thomas Harris' novel ``Hannibal.'' At
Nabisco, the cookie and snack maker, diet books figure prominently.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Amling, the director of e-commerce for United Parcel
Service, has no doubt that many of the boxes its brown vans deliver
to offices are either online or catalog purchases. While he is not
aware of any companies that have complained to UPS about being
overwhelmed by employees' holiday shopping, Amling said, ``As
volumes continue to increase, it would make sense that some
employers would object.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rubin, of Shop.org, anticipates that as online shopping
increases, the answer to delivery problems will come from the
delivery companies themselves, who might start allowing customers
to schedule delivery times, particularly after work. ``I think
that's more reasonable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amling said such schemes would not be viable for some time.
Until then, he said, solutions depend on drivers' initiative. ``Our
drivers,'' he said, ``have a relationship with their customers that
allows them to know who wants us to leave the package under the
lawn chair and who wants it on the front porch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
