<HEADLINE>
ITEMS FOR AN ELECTRONICS SHOPPING LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This is one in a series of articles on online shopping) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   APPLE IMAC DV
</P>
<P>
   DV or not DV? That is the question when trying to choose among
the three new models of iMacs from Apple. You could go for the
$1,299 iMac DV (digital video) in one of five colors or, if your
budget permits, the stylish gray iMac DV Special Edition at $1,499.
The slot-loading DVD drive lets iMac DV owners use CD-ROM discs,
play CD audio discs and even watch DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   DELL DIMENSION XPS T500
</P>
<P>
   This $1,339 system includes a 500-MHz Pentium III processor, 64
MB of RAM with 512 kilobytes of Level 2 cache, a 6.4 GB hard drive,
16 MB of video memory on a Voodoo 3 graphics card, a 48X CD-ROM, a
17-inch monitor, Harman Kardon speakers, a 56K modem, a floppy
drive and a free year of Internet access _ backed by Dell's
reputation for reliability and support.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ PRESARIO 5900Z-700
</P>
<P>
   Based on a 700-megahertz Athlon processor with multimedia game
extensions, this Compaq computer includes 128 megabytes of RAM, a
high-speed 27-gigabyte hard disk, a 10X DVD drive, a 4X CD-RW
(rewritable) drive, 32 MB of graphics memory on a Creative 3-D
Blaster TNT-2 Ultra graphics card, a 19-inch monitor, a Klipsch
Promedia THX surround-sound speaker system and a DSL modem. All for
$2,912 on Compaq's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   DIAMOND VIPER V770 ULTRA
</P>
<P>
   Based on the nVidia Riva TNT2 Ultra processor, this 3-D/2-D
graphics card ($179) is the ultimate game and video engine for
Intel and AMD computers. It has 32 MB of high-speed graphics memory
and 4X AGP (graphics card) performance (for up to 100 frames a
second), and 32-bit rendering and 32-bit Z-stencil buffering. The
result: nonpareil 3-D game play.
</P>
<P>
   MONSOON MM-1000
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd to hear 3-D sound from what are almost 2-D
speakers, just one inch thick, but this system (two flat-panel
satellite speakers and a subwoofer) punches it out while taking up
minimal desk space. Music fills the room, jets zoom overhead and
monsters creep up behind you, courtesy of Sonigistixs sonic imaging
technology. This system sells for as little as $150 online.
</P>
<P>
   IBM T-55A 15-INCH FLAT PANEL MONITOR
</P>
<P>
   Flat-panel monitors are sleek and stylish, but they are at least
triple the cost of conventional CRT displays. This ``stealth
black'' beauty, a $1,249 work of desktop sculpture, offers
brilliant images and as much usable screen space as a 17-inch CRT
but takes up only one-third the desk space (and saves energy).
There is no glare and no compromises on color or image sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT INTELLIMOUSE EXPLORER
</P>
<P>
   With its sleek silver-and-gray body and glowing-red underbelly
and taillight, this mighty mouse is unlike anything else out there.
It uses optical sensors to find its way around with greater
precision than any conventional mechanical mouse. The big
difference is that it uses a tiny video camera instead of a more
traditional rolling ball and scans any surface (except glass) 1,500
times a second, which translates into high-precision control of
cursor movements.
</P>
<P>
   The Intellimouse Explorer has five buttons, including a scroll
wheel, which makes it an ideal mouse for World Wide Web browsers.
Web pages rarely fit in one screen, and a scrolling wheel means
that the user doesn't have to mouse over to a scroll bar and click
up or down. The Explorer works with Macs as well as Windows, and it
costs $74.95. It has no mechanical or moving parts, and it doesn't
accumulate the belly-button lint that causes mechanical mice to
skip, get stuck or lose their bearings.
</P>
<P>
   SONY SPRESSA CRX100E/X USB CD-RW DRIVE
</P>
<P>
   This versatile drive is not the flashiest, but it does
everything well. It backs up as much as 650 MB of data on a blank
CD-R (write-once disc) or CD-RW disc, writes CD-audio discs
(including a CD labeling system) and reads any disc that can be
read by a CD-ROM drive, including Photo CD. This external USB
version lists for $399 but can sell for much less; it works with
Windows and Mac machines. If you want to burn your own music CDs,
this is a hot burner.
</P>
<P>
   ITOUCH KEYBOARD
</P>
<P>
   Logitech's Internet keyboard ($39.95; wireless version $99.95)
lets you open e-mail or search the Net with one touch of a button.
</P>
