<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-CRAFTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAFTS SHOW AND SALE OF JUDAICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Crafts as up to date as a titanium dreidel are the
focus of ``To Life and Light: A Celebration of Judaica,'' a
four-day show and sale at the American Craft Museum, 40 W. 53rd St.
``We are not showing any reproductions,'' said June Sgobbo, vice
president for retailing at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is the first Judaica event in the museum's 43 years. A
jury headed by Laura Kruger, a curator at the Hebrew Union College
Gallery in Manhattan, chose works by 40 artists from 90 who
applied. Eighteen of the artists created one-of-a-kind pieces, and
five Israeli artists are showing work in the United States for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The objects range from unusual Hanukkah dreidels _ four-sided
tops, each side bearing a Hebrew character _ like those made by
Kathleen Gahagan in titanium and sterling ($122 to $439), to
custom-made wedding canopies by Jacqueline Lissy, a New York
artist, and a pared-down aluminum traveling Sabbath set of
candlesticks, candles and matching kiddush, or benediction, cup by
Yaakov Greenvurcel of Jerusalem. Kristina Bozic, a Chicago artist,
created simple, satin-finish aluminum candlesticks and
nine-branched Hanukkah menorahs ($56 to $467).
</P>
<P>
   The craft works can be seen and bought in the museum's
lower-level exhibition space Thursday through Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
