<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOUSE-MUSEUMS-ART-2TA     11-17 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-MUSEUMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN NOTEBOOK: HOUSE MUSEUMS GET PUSHY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Va., Calif., Fla., N.Y., N.J., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When two Gustav Stickley cabinets go up for sale at
Christie's on Nov. 29, as part of Barbra Streisand's Arts and
Crafts collection, representatives of the Craftsman Farms, the
Stickley home that the cabinets were designed for, will be there
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the farms, a nonprofit house museum, began raising
$75,000 as a war chest to recapture the cabinets. It also made
public its frustration with Ms. Streisand for refusing to donate
the pieces or sell them privately to the Stickley house. But the
tactic may be backfiring: with the winds of war _ and publicity _
rising, the estimates have escalated from $26,000 to $34,000 to
$40,000 to $60,000 each. Whatever the outcome, one thing is clear:
house museums are busting the dust on the way they do business.
</P>
<P>
   They now number 4,000 to 5,000, from the White House, with 1.25
million visitors annually, to the typical out-of-the-way
institution like Craftsman Farms in Parsippany, N.J., which had
10,000 visitors last year. After years of polite attrition, they
are capitalizing on the potential of their cultural assets. With
tourism breaking attendance records at the nation's large
institutions, house museums are pushing hard at endowment goals to
restore buildings, add visitors' centers and expand programming,
and they are exercising a new aggressiveness in their strategies
for acquiring objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The historic house field is the next phase of American museums
to professionalize,'' said Kenneth Snodgrass, curator at the Samuel
F.B. Morse Historic Site in Poughkeepsie, which began construction
on a 22,000-square-foot visitors' center last year. Snodgrass, a
graduate of the New York University museum studies program, is an
example of the new breed of historic site curator: he does much of
his shopping for the Morse house online, at eBay.
</P>
<P>
   In Hartford, Conn., at the Mark Twain House, filmmaker Ken Burns
is shooting the orientation film for a visitors' center scheduled
to open in 2001. Because Twain was a humorist, Garry Trudeau, Roy
Blount Jr. and Calvin Trillin have appeared for evening events.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, said John Boyer, executive director of the Mark
Twain House, ``the entire framework with which collections are
built has changed because of the aggressive marketing strategies of
Christie's and Sotheby's and the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   House museums need the goods, and they are going after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the historical site business is all about,'' said
Edward Bosley, director of the Gamble house, designed by Charles
and Henry Greene, in Pasadena, Calif. ``It's very rare to step into
a house and be confronted with what was there in 1908, for
instance.''
</P>
<P>
   Reproductions don't work, Bosley continued, adding: ``In many
cases, the reproductions are too good; they're better than the
originals. They're overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   When house museums don't have the money, they use pull. Or try
push.
</P>
<P>
   When an urn designed by Frank Lloyd Wright for the Susan
Dana-Thomas house in Springfield, Ill., now a state-owned site,
came up for sale at Christie's New York earlier this year, former
Illinois Gov. James Thompson made the successful bid on behalf of
the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went off to New York with $150,000,'' said Thompson, now
chairman of Winston &AMP; Strawn, a Chicago law firm, having gone down
his list of chief executives and friends, including the Pritzker
family. It cost him $260,000; Thompson's list made up the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   He also went to The Chicago Sun-Times before he left town, which
ran several articles on the house's interest in returning the urn.
Thompson is on the paper's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I needed all the help I could get,'' said Thompson.
He added that he didn't think the maneuver was a conflict of
interest, or that it gave him an unfair advantage over other
bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have to compete against publicity,'' he said,
``only compete against my dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also bid on items for the Dana-Thomas house at
Christie's in 1987, as governor. Because of advance publicity that
the house wanted them, Thomas Monaghan, then chairman of Domino's
Pizza, who was Wright's most active private collector, gave
Thompson $25,000 toward purchases, agreeing not to bid against him.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said that collectors' attitudes had changed. In 1987,
``there was forbearance on the part of the collecting community,''
he said, to allow the Dana-Thomas house to make the winning bids.
``They thought it was a noble purpose,'' he said. In 1999, in the
case of the urn, he said, ``Collectors now are willing to go up to
bat against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Stein, the curator at Monticello, said with philosophic
sadness, ``Our entrepreneurial values so far outweigh the idea of
public patrimony.'' Ms. Stein added that the dilemma would only get
worse: ``The decorative arts are becoming increasingly valuable,
and being treated more like works of art, like paintings.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most older house museums, Monticello has rarely depended on
the kindness of strangers. When she wanted two chairs from the
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis sale at Sotheby's in 1996, Ms. Stein
made arrangements with Patricia Kluge, a neighbor and benefactor,
who bought them with an agreement that they would go to Monticello
in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was not so lucky. It lost the bid on a writing
table at which President John F. Kennedy signed the nuclear
proliferation treaty, though it had expressed interest in the item
privately, prior to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis auction had its historical irony.
As first lady, Mrs. Kennedy virtually invented the patriotic
popularity of returning objects to the White House, including a
French chair from the Monroe administration that a woman in
Pennsylvania donated after recognizing its matching table on
television during the first lady's 1962 White House tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her televised tour was a major factor in publicizing the
interest in bringing things back,'' said Betty Monkman, the White
House curator.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Kennedy's style of civic responsibility has become as
rare in the world of house museums as the objects they hope to
retrieve.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crying shame,'' said James Rees, resident director of
Mount Vernon, ``when truly wealthy collectors place their objects
at auction, often without even contacting the houses in question.
Even if they don't intend to donate, it's nice to think that the
home would be given a chance _ like a right of first refusal.''
Rees added: ``Most times, I am aware that an item is coming up when
we receive the printed catalog. At that point, it's very hard to
put together the funds to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional incentives like tax advantages for charitable
donations must now compete with the prospect of inestimable prices
realized in the open market, especially in fashionable, fast-moving
collecting fields like Arts and Crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein at Monticello said that newer financial devices like
the bargain sale helped to attract donors, by bridging the gap.
``The seller sells an object to a museum, at something under its
appraised value, and is able to claim the difference as a
charitable donation,'' she explained. ``There's an element of
philanthropy as well as benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements with larger, more prestigious institutions, like
long-term loans or the promise of gifts, present themselves less
frequently to small house museums. ``It can take generations to get
it right,'' Morrison Heckscher, a curator of American decorative
art at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, said of fruitful
relationships with collectors. ``It's not something that can be
rushed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the specter of public sale can produce impatience, if not
panic. Tommy McPherson, executive director of Craftsman Farms
Foundation, is prepared to take a quicker offensive, and risk
professional disapprobation, as the foundation is doing with the
Streisand sale. ``It would be more unfortunate for the foundation
not to attempt to return them and simply wait for another
generation of collectors to return them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House museums have no reason to believe that the next generation
of collectors will be charitable. ``Though there's a huge
transition of wealth now, to the baby boomers,'' Boyer said,
``there's a part of me that worries about the upper middle class
giving away objects when you look at the rest of their lives:
educating their kids, managing retirement, putting their parents in
nursing homes.'' As collectors, he continued, ``they may have
bought objects because they loved them, but they might be forced to
view them as investments.'' Collectors strapped for cash ``won't be
able to be art patrons,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But taking collectors to task for selling objects on the open
market discounts the role they play in conserving the furnishings
at all; in many cases, they are alone in their interests _ and
their investments _ until their collections create appreciation at
auction level.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Wolfson has collected decorative arts for 30 years for
his public collection, the Wolfsonian at Florida International
University in Miami Beach. It was only after he bought neglected
treasures like Harry Clarke's stained-glass window, commissioned,
then rejected, by the Irish government as its contribution to the
League of Nations in Geneva, that institutions like the Irish
government sought their return.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made them respectable,'' he said of his possessions,
`` &UR; then &LR;  they wanted them back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-CHELSEA-ART-2TAKES     11-17 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHELSEA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING AN OASIS OF CALM ON THE EDGE OF CHELSEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALASTAIR GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One Sunday morning back in the 1980s, long before the
art galleries invaded Chelsea, two architects were riding their
bikes down the old West Side Highway. As the men, G. Phillip Smith
and Douglas Thompson, turned off at 23rd Street, pedaling east,
they noticed a vacant lot on the northwest corner of 10th Avenue.
``We came screeching to a halt when we saw the `For Sale' sign,''
Smith said. ``It was love at first sight.''
</P>
<P>
   The corner lot was the perfect size for their purposes. Once the
site of two brownstones, it measured 54 by 40 feet. They also liked
the rough-edged, mixed-use nature of the neighborhood, which had a
gas station on one corner, the old elevated train tracks to the
west and the Empire Diner and London Terrace apartment complex
across 10th Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this thing about vacant lots,'' Thompson said. ``It's
the blank piece of paper, the empty canvas. We always had a dream
to claim a corner of space and build ourselves a decompression
chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't want to renovate an old building. They wanted to
start from scratch and create their own structure from the ground
up. That's why they started to ride their bikes around the city
every weekend searching for an empty lot. The architects phoned the
real estate broker first thing the next day and learned that the
property had already been sold, for $50,000, but they asked the
agent to keep them posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let her know that we really wanted the property,'' Thompson
said. After three years of waiting, their patience paid off. The
property came back on the market, for more than $200,000, four
times the previous price. This time, armed with a drawer full of
credit cards (which they quickly maxed out) and a short-term
construction loan, the architects were able to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Working in a gradual, reflective way in contrast to New York's
frantic pace of life, the two men began to evolve a concept for
their space. In their spare time, they sketched ideas out on
napkins and tablecloths, planning a building that would serve
several purposes: living space, a design studio for Smith &AMP;
Thompson Architects, and _ to help pay its own way _ commercial
tenants. All would be mixed into an intriguing village of spaces,
courtyards and terraces that could also provide an oasis from the
urban environment.
</P>
<P>
   How often does the chance come along to own a piece of
Manhattan? Not often, unless you're Donald Trump. Most people are
used to renovating an older building, fitting into the envelope of
someone else's design. But New York offers a surprising number of
options for those who are resourceful and adventurous, willing to
challenge conventions. Vacant lots in odd configurations or out in
peripheral, frontier neighborhoods wait to be developed. Smith and
Thompson, through a combination of imagination, methodical planning
and a kind of do-it-yourself Zen persistence, would spend the next
10 years shaping their dream into a reality. ``Remember,'' Smith
said, ``none of this had anything to do with real estate
speculation. We weren't interested in maximizing the site for
future profit. We wanted to make a beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   The dream had been percolating in their imaginations ever since
they first met as architecture students at Columbia University
during the turbulent 1960s. After completing their studies, both
men, with the help of fellowships, went on design pilgrimages
around the world, studying ancient and modern architecture. Smith
worked for the Indian architect Balkrishna Doshi, whose buildings
would have a profound influence on his later work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doshi's office in Ahmadabad was in a built-up urban
neighborhood,'' he recalled, ``but it had a courtyard, and you went
in from this noisy street into a quiet and magic environment.''
Later, he would work with the Japanese architect Fumihiko Maki, who
left a deep impression on Smith by successfully combining
transparency and openness on a gritty street corner in Tokyo with
his 1989 Tepia Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   For their oasis in Chelsea, Smith and Thompson would synthesize
traditions of 20th-century modernism with ideas they had
accumulated in their travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, we thought about just living like gypsies on the
site,'' Thompson said, ``parking a trailer on it and building a
swimming pool. Then we could drive away whenever we felt
restless.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually a more realistic idea evolved, one that acknowledged,
even honored, the geometric reality of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think of Manhattan as a closed, finite kind of
space with the grid as the dominant force,'' Smith said. They
decided to try to maintain the urban grid while inserting a fluid
sequence of spaces within the enclosed area.
</P>
<P>
   They knew from the start that there had to be a courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Noguchi museum in Long Island City was a constant
touchstone,'' Smith said. ``It is one of our favorite places in the
city.'' They also knew that they wanted to establish a presence on
the corner of 23rd and 10th, with at least two stories, respecting
the lines of the street and giving the structure an inner
transparency.
</P>
<P>
   Another important influence on their thinking was an old house
in Cairo that they had seen in a book about traditional Egyptian
architecture. ``It was extremely rich in plan and elevation, with
so many different levels of interest,'' Thompson said. There were
many similarities to what they ended up designing: an L-shaped
building organized around an open courtyard for both public and
private functions, with balconies and multi-level terraces.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, they looked for an economy of means and
flexibility. By designing everything themselves, they were able to
eliminate architectural fees, and they also acted as their own
general contractors. To save costly labor, all phases of
construction were carefully orchestrated. After the foundation work
ended, a framework of steel I-beams was bolted and welded into
place like a jungle gym, a job that took only two days because
steel sections had been stacked on the delivery trucks in the order
of assembly.
</P>
<P>
   More money was saved by using cold-rolled steel as it came
directly off the mill, in precut sheets of 10 by 20 feet. The size
of the plates established a modular 10-foot-square unit that the
architects used throughout the project. (This also worked nicely
with the dimensions of the lot.) The architects searched through
stacks of steel the way decorators look at fabric swatches. ``Every
steel mill has a unique finish,'' Thompson said. ``Most come out
fairly black.'' A set that came from a mill in Pennsylvania had a
consistent powdery red finish, a kind of cordovan color, that
caught their eye.
</P>
<P>
   After the exterior steel walls were in place, they were coated
with a parafin-based sealer to prevent rusting and to protect
against graffiti. Conventional timber framing was used for the rest
of the structure and then covered in some places with gray stucco
or white resin-coated fiberglass, which contrasts with dark steel.
Cubic elements stacked like blocks were designed in such a way that
different spaces could be combined and recombined over time and
could easily be adapted to changing functions. The building, which
is approximately 4,800 square feet, ended up costing about $140 a
square foot.
</P>
<P>
   The courtyard and two gallery spaces on the lower floors were
finished first, in 1997. Several restaurants expressed interest in
renting the space, for higher revenues, but Smith and Thompson
wanted sympathetic neighbors in their little village. The J.
Cacciola Galleries moved from Soho into the ground-floor space,
with 2,400 square feet, including a subterranean level. Jim Kempner
Fine Arts also left Soho and moved to the second floor (1,400
square feet).
</P>
<P>
   ``The building is helping us all to be together,'' Smith said.
``It's really like a small community.''
</P>
<P>
   As you approach from the west, the building appears to be
hovering like a lantern in the late October twilight. It seems too
thin at first _ rice-paper thin _ too insubstantial for this city,
more like a temporary structure erected for a street fair. Where
are the defensive barriers? The thick walls and narrow entry points
that normally signal the line between public and private space?
They are almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Getting closer, you begin to see that the effect is a skillfully
composed illusion. The perimeter walls are not paper after all, but
armor-plated with steel. Step through the portal into the
courtyard, and something changes. Even though the outer membrane is
only a quarter-inch thick, street noises are muffled, and it is
surprisingly peaceful, even meditative. The city is still out
there, rude and clamorous, but it suddenly seems distant.
Everything fits neatly into a framework of solid and void, except a
parabolic opening that has been cut to accommodate the branch of a
tree that stretches into the courtyard. The floor of the courtyard
is covered with gravel. Pavers, made from recycled plastic decking,
have been placed like stepping stones in a Japanese garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't see many buildings like this in New York,''
said Dru Arstark, the director of Jim Kempner Fine Arts. ``Everyone
loves it. We have so many new clients. Many of them just walk in
off the street. The building draws people in.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``My heart melted when I first saw the opening in
the wall for the tree. What kind of architects would do that? I
loved their sensitivity to the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   For such a relatively small structure, there is a great deal
going on. Each space leads into the next with a surprising clarity
of purpose. One is constantly aware of the sky and the drama of the
street. Lines of sight are intentionally arranged to create a
shifting play between privacy and exposure, transparency and
opacity. Multiple views and openings divide and transform the
action on the outside of the building into a series of
mini-theatrical events: advertisements on the side of a bus,
pedestrians passing, the yellow flash of a speeding cab are
glimpsed briefly through slit-like openings.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional borders were further dissolved in the way the
architects arranged their combination work-and-living area on the
third floor. A system of ``Murphy desks'' fold up into the wall so
that the space can be open for entertaining or living on the
weekends. Then there is a small sleeping loft, perched precariously
above the design studio.
</P>
<P>
   The architects led the way up a folded steel-plate staircase to
one of two roof terraces. Looking out over the busy intersection of
23rd Street and 10th Avenue, Smith pointed out how the building
continues to grow as a work in progress. New spaces set back like
rooms of a pueblo village will soon rise in tiers toward the bare
wall of an adjacent building. The roof terrace will become a ``sky
room,'' with walls but no roof and a private sanctuary for
sleeping. ``This process is completely open-ended,'' Smith said.
``The building continues to unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the hectic city streets, this building is a study in
slowness. This gradual, almost organic approach is not just for
small buildings, they believe, but can just as easily be applied to
much larger projects. (The team recently completed an award-winning
design for the phased expansion of the Jacques Marchais Center of
Tibetan Art on Staten Island.)
</P>
<P>
   There is something inherently quiet about the place and the men
who designed it. In explaining their philosophy about living and
working in one place, Smith paraphrased a Zen Buddhist saying he
heard in Japan: ``The real master in the art of living makes little
distinction between his art and his leisure,'' he said. ``He simply
pursues his vision of excellence in whatever he does, leaving
others to decide whether he is working or playing. To him he is
always doing both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
