<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ The Irish Republican Army said
Wednesday that it ``unequivocally'' backed the Northern Ireland
peace agreement, and it agreed to appoint a go-between to the
commission charged with bringing about paramilitary disarmament.
The eagerly awaited statement For the first time in its history,
the outlawed, secret paramilitary force showed a willingness to
consider the dismantling of its arsenal, a taboo subject it has
traditionally associated with surrender. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Beijing) _ Workers at an outmoded textile factory
in Beijing say the trade accord comes too late to help them _ their
factory is a likely casualty _ but they welcome it, railing against
their Communist Party-appointed managers. The big question is
whether the government can provide a safety net for them and
millions of others. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
