<HEADLINE>
COOKBOOKS ADD NEW FLAVORS TO JEWISH DISHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHY FRISINGER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just like its population, ethnic cuisine evolves. Four recently
published Jewish cookbooks prove that time, and gefilte fish, march
on.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Jewish Holiday Cookbook, An International Collection
of Recipes and Customs''
</P>
<P>
   By Gloria Kaufer Greene
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $27.50
</P>
<P>
   As savvy American cooking has become increasingly influenced by
flavors from the far corners of the earth, so Jewish cuisine has
expanded in recent years beyond the traditional Eastern European
dishes Ashkenazi Jews brought to America in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated Jewish cook preparing a celebratory meal today
is likely to look for Spanish, Middle Eastern or even
Indian-influenced dishes to add interest to the holiday table.
Glora Kaufer Greene's ``The New Jewish Holiday Cookbook,'' the
cream of this cookbook crop, combines a smattering of traditional
Eastern European recipes with a wide range of international,
especially Middle Eastern, dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is an explanation of how to braid a Sabbath challah,
but there are also recipes for djaja m'kafli (Moroccan-style lemon
chicken with olives) for breaking the Yom Kippur fast, and
picadillo (spicy ground beef with fruit and almonds) for
celebrating Tu B'Shevat (the New Year of the Trees).
</P>
<P>
   Organized by holiday, each section begins with an explanation of
customs from various Jewish cultures associated with that holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a knock-'em-dead flourless dessert for Passover? How
about hazelnut-chocolate Viennese torte or pears poached in red
wine?
</P>
<P>
   This book's a winner.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The 2nd Ave Deli Cookbook, Recipes and Memories From Abe
Lebewohl's Legendary Kitchen''
</P>
<P>
   By Sharon Lebewohl and Rena Bulkin
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Hot pastrami!
</P>
<P>
   ``The 2nd Ave Deli Cookbook'' is as much a celebrity salute to
the New York City deli scene as it is a recipe guide. Looking for
the definitive recipe for chicken soup? There are four here: Aunt
Mary's chicken soup; chicken soup Live! With Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee;
Antonio Pagan's chicken soup; and Art D'Lugoff's Moroccan chicken
soup.
</P>
<P>
   Who's Art D'Lugoff? A jazz impresario who founded the Village
Gate on Bleeker Street, which hosted such music greats as Paul
Robeson, John Coltrane and Billie Holiday, we're told as an
incongruous lead-in to a recipe for vegetable cholent.
</P>
<P>
   And so this book goes. A picture of Paul Reiser and Jerry
Seinfeld here, a recipe for schmaltz and gribenes there.
</P>
<P>
   Buy this book for the memories, buy it for fun, but don't buy it
to expand your repertoire of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Shabbat Shalom, Recipes and Menus for the Sabbath''
</P>
<P>
   By Susan B. Friedland
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Rabbis tell Jews who want to become better acquainted with their
religion to begin by rediscovering the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   This day of rest _ a gift from God _ is meant to be a day of
joy. Indulge the senses. Sex on the Sabbath is good. Likewise,
wonderful food should be enjoyed on this day.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a conundrum: Work is forbidden on this holiday, and
that includes cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, Jews have developed a repertoire of Sabbath
foods, elaborate dishes lovingly prepared before the Sabbath to be
eaten on Friday night (Sabbath evening), and slow-cooking stews and
bean dishes warming overnight on a fire and eaten on Saturday
(Sabbath day).
</P>
<P>
   ``Shabbat Shalom'' is a reverential compilation of these
traditional recipes with commentary on the history and religious
significance. The notorious gefilte fish, for instance, has its
origin in the belief that removing bones from fish was work, making
it impossible to eat whole fish for a Sabbath meal. So fish was
boned, mixed with filler and stuffed back into the skin (in later
years shaped into balls) _ and thus gefilte fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shabbat Shalom'' is an excellent book for someone new to
Judaism, or for someone trying to re-create the feel of Friday
nights at Grandma's house.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``A Drizzle of Honey: The Lives and Recipes of Spain's Secret
Jews''
</P>
<P>
   By David M. Gitlitz and Linda Kay Davidson
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   In the late Middle Ages, the Inquisition terrorized the Jews of
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Many converted to Catholicism, but others went underground,
secretly holding on to their Jewish faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Drizzle of Honey'' is a culinary salute to these
crypto-Jews.
</P>
<P>
   These recipes from the Sephardic Jewish tradition combine
techniques from Christian and Islamic cooks with Jewish dietary
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   There are foods from Spain, Brazil, Mexico, Peru and other
countries. Lamb, fish, eggplant, chickpeas, almonds, cilantro and
cumin are featured prominently in these recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling adventurous? Try Maria Garcia's dove pie, Canary Islands
goat stew or Jewish mint pistachio partridge.
</P>
<P>
   Not up to something quite that exotic today? There's Diego Diaz
Nieto's haroset balls for a change of pace for the Passover meal,
or Mexican halvah for a treat any time.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable collection of recipes, this beautiful book serves
as a reminder to respect and cherish the many cultures of our wide
world.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCAN-STYLE LEMON CHICKEN WITH OLIVES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 garlic cloves, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried cilantro leaves or 2 tablespoons finely
chopped fresh cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   About 31/2 pounds meaty chicken pieces, skin removed
</P>
<P>
   1 medium fresh lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup green olives, whole or pitted with any pimento removed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh lemon cut in wedges for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In a Dutch oven, combine water, grated onion, chopped onion,
garlic, parsley, cilantro, ginger, turmeric and pepper. Add
chicken, and bring liquid to a boil over medium-high beat. Lower
heat and simmer, covered, for about an hour, until chicken is very
tender.
</P>
<P>
   While chicken is cooking, use a sharp knife to score four or
five very shallow 1-inch cuts in the surface of the lemon peel. Put
lemon into a saucepan and cover it with water. Bring to a boil,
then reduce heat and simmer, covered, for 30 minutes. The peel
should be very tender. Rinse lemon under cool running water to stop
the cooking. Cut open lemon along one of the scored marks. Discard
seeds and any loose lemon pulp. Cut peel (without any attached
pulp) into small pieces. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   While lemon is cooking, bring olives to boil in plain water, and
simmer for 3 minutes; discard water and let olives soak in cool,
clean water. When chicken is tender, stir 2 tablespoons lemon juice
into sauce. If chicken has given off a lot of liquid and the sauce
is thin, raise heat and boil sauce down until it has thickened to
desired consistency. Reduce heat to low, and stir in olives and
reserved pieces of cooked lemon peel. Simmer gently about 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, put chicken on large platter, and spoon sauce with the
olives and lemon pieces over the top. Garnish with lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 227 calories, 11 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 28 grams protein, 79 milligrams cholesterol,
771 milligrams sodium, 43 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New Jewish Holiday Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN HALVAH
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sesame seeds, plus 2 tablespoons sesame seeds for
topping
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   Grind 1/2 cup sesame seeds, sugar and almonds as finely as
possible. In medium saucepan, heat sesame oil, water and honey.
Bring mixture to boil over medium heat. When it foams, turn down
heat to simmer. Stir in ground nuts, sugar and sesame mixture, Cook
over a low heat, stirring constantly, about 5 minutes, until
mixture thickens and begins to set. Pour into a heatproof glass or
metal pan. Smooth with a spatula. Sprinkle with 2 tablespoons
sesame seeds. Let halvah cool, and cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per piece: 194 calories, 10 grams fat, 25
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 4 milligrams
sodium, 48 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Drizzle of Honey''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
