<P>
   REFORMATION-COMMENTARY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ While most of America's tots were going door-to-door
for candy, many Protestant churches were celebrating the day that a
stocky German monk nailed 95 debating points to a church door. Only
this year, on the 482nd birthday of that event marking the
Reformation, the Roman Catholic Church and a major worldwide
Lutheran body reached a milestone agreement on how human beings are
saved, or reconciled to God. I want to offer this sweeping
indictment: Generally speaking, Protestants no more than Roman
Catholics give much thought to the disturbing question that drove
Martin Luther, as it did the prophets and apostles before him:
``How can I, knowing who I really am, ever hope to find a merciful
God?'' By MICHAEL S. HORTON. Story has moved in ``k'' commentary
category. &QL; 
