<HEADER>
A2673 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SHOPPING-CHEAP-NY     11-17 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-CHEAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAP DIGITAL CAMERAS ABANDON THE ORDINARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This is one in a series of articles on online shopping) 
(th) 
 By TOM VANDERBILT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is the holiday camera buying guide made simple: Buy the
Holga 120S.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when the camera has become little more than a computer
with a lens, the Holga stands at the ready, fully Year 2000
compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at these somewhat peculiar features: Place of
manufacture: China. Body: plastic (you will need to cover the back
with electrical tape to keep out the light). Lens: plastic
(fuzziness, flares and occasional warping included at no extra
charge). F-stops: two. Shutter speed: one. Chance of frame slippage
or problem in advancing film: great. Price: around $15. Neck strap:
included.
</P>
<P>
   The Holga, like the celebrated Russian Lomo camera or the YN-300
Fantastic Plastic 35-millimeter camera, is a toy camera. Its
primary audience, however, is not children, but photographers who
have grown weary of the tyranny and sterility of the perfect image.
In addressing the fabled Diana, a predecessor to the Holga
manufactured by the Great Wall Plastic Factory of the Kowloon
district of Hong Kong, in his book ``Photographic Possibilities,''
Robert Hirsch wrote: ``The Diana summons up the Dadaist traditions
of chance, surprise and a willingness to see what can happen. This
lack of control can free you from worrying about doing the `right'
thing and always being `correct.'''
</P>
<P>
   So even if children are by and large not flocking to the Holga,
it is still a toy, and thus its chief virtue is that it allows its
user to play, even if it is capable of performing the same
essential function as a $3,000 Leica.
</P>
<P>
   Freed from Bauhaus rationality and high-tech sobriety, toy
cameras possess a sense of fun, not only in their occasionally
whimsical design, but in the very way they take photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures on the Nickelodeon Photo Blaster, for example, come
four to a photograph, which means that the user can not only
quadruple the number of shots but also that it is a mystery _ more
Dadaism _ as to which pictures will be juxtaposed next to which
pictures when the film is finally printed (you can go up to 144
shots).
</P>
<P>
   The big thing in photography, of course, is the market for
digital cameras. The good news is that the lower end of the market
has begun to expand, and there are now several bona fide toy
digital cameras, which, like their analog counterparts, possess a
certain charm in their imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the digital cameras in this price range produce
anything approaching the resolution of the simplest point-and-click
camera, they can be used to produce instant images for e-mail
dissemination. An additional feature is that their flaws, as well
as the flaws one can build in with the available software,
occasionally make for compelling images.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most entertaining of these is Nintendo's Game Boy
Camera, an heir of sorts to two previous beloved, and now defunct,
child-tested, artist-approved digital camera technologies:
Pixelvision and Fax Camera, both from Fisher-Price.
</P>
<P>
   The Game Boy Camera is essentially a cartridge you plug into a
Game Boy as if it were a game; a small, movable orb captures the
images. Indeed, the resulting ``funtography'' (Nintendo's phrase)
is akin to a game, with the same graphics and music of a typical
handheld video game accompanying the production of images.
</P>
<P>
   The images themselves are of the infrared, surveillance-camera
variety. But even these have a captivating expressionism, as well
as providing the novelty of seeing yourself in real time on a Game
Boy screen, as if you had been transported to the innards of the
game. Many effects are possible, as well, like panoramic images and
time-lapse photography; features like those can make the unit a
kind of portable history of the medium. As a final step, you print
the image on calculator tape.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of its limitations, the Game Boy Camera has developed a
cult following. Intrepid sorts have created programs to transfer
its still and moving images to the computer and to video, opening
up possibilities for Game Boy auteurs worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   KB Gear Interactive's JamCam looks and handles like a
traditional digital camera, but at a retail price of less than $90,
its makers are billing it as the cheapest 640-by-480-pixel
resolution camera on the market.
</P>
<P>
   With its rubberized side grips and large buttons, the JamCam is
clearly intended as a primer camera for children, but its
durability and ease of use make it ideal for experimentation at all
age levels. At its highest-resolution setting, the JamCam can store
eight pictures; at its lowest, 24.
</P>
<P>
   After uploading into a computer, images can be manipulated with
Microsoft Picture It 99, ArcSoft Photo Fantasy or Pictureworks' Hot
Shots (all included). Only the last program, however, will work
with a Macintosh. None of the other low-end digital cameras
reviewed here worked with a Macintosh, which seems surprising given
the popularity of the iMac among younger users.
</P>
<P>
   If you are impressed by the graphic design or in-ring antics of
professional wrestling, then Toymax's Slam Cam might appeal. An
unfortunate mix of red and gray plastic with a spray-painted WWF
logo blaring out from the face, the Slam Cam is one of a number of
toy cameras on the market that have a theme; Mattel's flowery and
pink Barbie Photo Designer camera is another.
</P>
<P>
   The Slam Cam and Barbie Photo Designer cameras sell for similar
prices, about $80, and have similar features _ users can put
themselves into a variety of fashionable Barbie environments or
into the headlock of Stone Cold Steve Austin. One senses an
opportunity for a new strike by the same media pranksters who a few
years back switched voices on Barbie dolls and G.I. Joe dolls.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything disquieting about these cameras, it is the
emphasis on manipulating a photo to make it ``better'' or on
inserting oneself into environments of someone else's making. It is
as if reality is no longer sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn the most ordinary photo into a work of art by applying
some special effects,'' the instruction book for the Slam Cam says.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, the special appeal of toy cameras is that one
never wants to take an ordinary photo, as if the ordinariness of
the camera itself had freed the user to find art in everyday life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
