<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-ENRIQUE-IGLESIA     11-17 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ENRIQUE-IGLESIAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENRIQUE IGLESIAS ENJOYING CROSSOVER SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enrique Iglesias, already one of the best-loved Latino crooners
in the world, is about to get even more popular.
</P>
<P>
   Poised to release his first English-language album, ``Enrique,''
next week, Iglesias is no stranger to the top of the pop charts. He
reached No. 1 over the summer with the compelling ``Bailamos''
(``We Dance'') from the ``Wild Wild West'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's hard to imagine that initially, Iglesias _ 24-year-old
son of globe-trotting ``Latin lover'' Julio Iglesias _ was
considered a hard sell by record companies.
</P>
<P>
   Back when he was starting out at age 19, Spanish ballad singers
were supposed to be 40 and up. Iglesias was rejected by three
labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to take a chance,'' he said Monday from Paris,
where he was in the midst of a brief promotional tour. ``I believed
in what I was doing, but people in the industry said it wasn't
possible for someone so young.''
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias, born in Madrid but raised in Miami, spent his early
teens listening to Top 40 acts like Bruce Springsteen, Fleetwood
Mac, Billy Joel, Peter Gabriel, Sting, John Mellencamp and Dire
Straits, realizing that while these artists were considered
rockers, their biggest hits were actually ballads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple ballads, too _ no more than three or four chords,''
Iglesias explained. ``Spanish pop at that time was so complicated,
with too many chords, too many changes, too many violins and cheesy
lyrics instead of being simple and direct.''
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias began writing his own songs, striking gold with his
1995 self-titled debut, which sold more than 6 million copies, as
did his second effort, ``Vivir'' (``To Live''). His third album,
``Cosas del Amor'' (``Love Things''), was issued last year.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic and sincere, Iglesias is anxious to prove that the
English-sung ``Bailamos'' was just the beginning of a long-term
bilingual career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enrique'' (Interscope/UMG), which arrives in stores Tuesday,
includes the single ``Rhythm Divine'' (which reunites him with the
Groove Brothers production team behind ``Bailamos'' and Cher's
``Believe'' smash), and showcases a mix of Latin and Mediterranean
rhythms, romance and classic pop influences.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the flamenco-tinged ``Bailamos'' and five new
songs penned by Iglesias, the forthcoming disc features the
singer's first-ever duet, with Whitney Houston on the Diane
Warren-written, David Foster-produced ballad ``Could I Have This
Kiss Forever,'' recorded at the suggestion of Arista Records
president Clive Davis, who masterminded Santana's current hit
single and album.
</P>
<P>
   Another moment sure to attract attention is Iglesias'
tip-of-the-hat tribute to one of his favorite artists _ a cover of
Springsteen's ``Sad Eyes'' _ a track suggested by Interscope
co-chairman Jimmy Iovine, who helped oversee the completion of
``Enrique'' and previously worked with Springsteen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Why don't you try this song?''' Iglesias said. ``So,
here's a Latino doing Springsteen. I expect people will say, what
the hell is this about? But everyone really loved how it came
out.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Iovine said he knew Iglesias had the potential to
sell truckloads of albums to both Anglo and Spanish audiences even
before figures were released showing sales of Spanish-language
music in the U.S. had jumped 12 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught his live show, which was incredibly strong,'' Iovine
said. ``He's a rock-based performer and judging by what his stage
show looked like, it was clear this was someone who could do
extremely well for a long time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his commitment to continue recording in Spanish,
Iglesias' new album contains Spanish-language versions of three
songs: ``Ritmo Total'' (``Rhythm Divine''), ``Mas es Amar'' (``Sad
Eyes'') and ``No Puedo Mas Sin Ti'' (``I'm Your Man'').
</P>
<P>
   Like fellow Latin-pop superstars Ricky Martin and Luis Miguel,
the 1997 Grammy-winning Iglesias has seen chart explosions before.
The fact that he sold more than 14 million copies of his first
three Spanish-only albums and scored 12 No. 1 Latin singles since
1995 led to his reported $40 million multirecord deal with
Universal's Interscope Records (which released ``Bailamos'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict Enrique will have a long career in both Spanish and
English and with his new single (``Rhythm Divine''), I can see he's
definitely heading in the right direction,'' said Pio Ferro,
program director at local Spanish-language adult contemporary radio
KLVE-FM (107.5), one of the first stations to spin ``Bailamos'' as
a European import two months before the song erupted on Spanish-
and English-speaking radio throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   To appeal to KLVE's audience, the station often takes the
Spanish and English versions of a hit like ``Bailamos'' or Martin's
``Livin' la Vida Loca'' and ``mates'' them, creating a special
bilingual mix, Ferro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're playing the Spanish version of `Rhythm
Divine' and if it takes off, we'll make a bilingual version,''
Ferro said.
</P>
<P>
   With such hip-hop-tinged, nonsymphonic material, Iglesias _ set
to appear with Sting, Andrea Bocelli, Aretha Franklin and others at
Celebration 2000, a high-profile New Year's Eve event at New York's
Jacob Javits Center _ clearly reaches a much younger audience than
his father does.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about his relationship with his famous dad, who
several years ago was the top Latin pop singer in the world but was
apparently too busy to spend much time with his three children from
his first marriage to a Spanish socialite, Iglesias demurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a good work ethic from him,'' Iglesias says. ``But I
can't see us ever singing together. I do respect his music even
though it was never my favorite thing to listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the son _ crowned 1998's ``Sexiest Man Alive'' by People
en Espanol, the Spanish-language edition of People magazine _
outsells the father. And Iglesias, who is single and lives in
Miami, says he never wants the ``Latin lover'' tag his father
embraced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like women as much as the next guy but I don't ever want to
be known for that,'' he said. ``That's his thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
