<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS18-COX     11-17 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray and Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Willennium''
</P>
<P>
   Will Smith. Columbia. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The general notion has been that the song you won't be able to
escape on New Year's Eve will be Prince's ``1999.'' And that may be
the case. But the best choice for an album to play until the
countdown is this one. Offensive only to people with an aversion to
fun, ``Willennium'' offers well-chosen samples such as Diana Ross'
``Love Hangover'' on ``Freakin' It'' and the Clash's ``Rock the
Casbah'' on ``Will 2K.'' There are also such surprising but
well-chosen guests as hard-core rappers Eve (``Can You Feel Me?'')
and Lil' Kim (``Da Butta''). And somehow in all this good company,
even Will Smith himself manages to do his thing _ and get to the
end of the album before his game of rhyme time becomes sickening.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Science of Things''
</P>
<P>
   Bush. Trauma/Universal. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   What Electric Light Orchestra was to the Beatles, Bush is to
Nirvana. That is, a brazen rip-off of infinitely less consequence,
but fun in a cheesy, lowbrow sort of way. Bush, a foursome of
sour-faced rockers led by mopey hunk Gavin Rossdale, seem all too
aware that critics find them a pale reflection of the gods of
grunge. To make amends, the group recycles riffs lifted from Kurt
Cobain and company into consistently catchy radio fodder. Bush's
third release is its most irresistible, as Rossdale and the boys
crank up the guitar and angst in the service of several soon-to-be
alterna-hits, including ``The Chemicals Between Us'' (already a
radio anthem) and ``Prizefighter.'' Rossdale sounds more
gruff-but-lovable than ever, croaking such supremely self-conscious
(and amusingly apt) lines as ``I memorize the basics, making
strange faces / Tread slowly for I know there's a thousand miles to
go'' (from the roaring lead-off track, ``Warm Machine'').
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightlife''
</P>
<P>
   Pet Shop Boys. Parlophone/Sire.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Ever prone to pithy album titles (see: ``Please,'' ``Very'' and
``Disco''), the Pet Shop Boys have christened release No. 9 with
their most bluntly obvious moniker to date. Anybody who has ever
shimmied and swayed on a dance floor to the strains of ``West End
Girls,'' ``Opportunities'' or ``It's Hard'' knows the British
twosome's work has always been about nightlife _ Neil Tennant's and
Chris Lowe's songs evoke disco ennui, stolen kisses in the back of
rented limos and caustic quips over martinis at an after-hours
bistro. Following their halfhearted 1996 release, ``Bilingual,''
which featured some truly wrongheaded forays into Latin fusion, the
Boys are back in fine form. A few tunes, including the rueful ``You
Only Tell Me You Love Me When You're Drunk,'' rank among the duo's
cleverest compositions. Yet there's a strong whiff of deja vu about
the album, suggesting that the Boys' all-night party may come to an
end sometime soon.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray and Doug Hamilton write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
