<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-POWERS18-COX     11-17 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-POWERS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Spy' a hilarious romp in bad taste
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Chaos hits Carnaby Street when our favorite dentally impaired
British superspy has his mojo, and much of his second movie, stolen
by Dr. Evil. But because Mike Myers plays both the good guy and the
bad guy (and a third character to boot), he has only himself to
blame for the scene-stealing.
</P>
<P>
   This gas of a sequel gives us a new curvy love interest (Heather
Graham) while bringing back Seth Green as Dr. Evil's sullen son
Scott and Robert Wagner and Mindy Sterling as No. 2 and Frau
Farbissina. We also get Rob Lowe doing a perfect Wagner imitation
as Younger No. 2 and tiny Verne Troyer as Dr. Evil's clone,
Mini-Me.
</P>
<P>
   As shaggy as it is shagadelic, ``Spy'' is really just an excuse
to revel in gleeful bad taste. That includes toilet humor involving
a greasy, flatulent, kilt-wearing, obese Scotsman (Myers in a body
suit); a genital-biting battle between Austin and Mini-Me; and
scatological shadow play. The gags this time out are more body
humor than boudoir. In other words, kids will love it.
</P>
<P>
   While the movie doesn't always hit its comic targets, it's
peppered with celebrity cameos _ Tim Robbins, Willie Nelson, Woody
Harrelson and more. These celebrity visits underscore the charm of
the flick. It's a pop-art party where the host is happy to do
anything to keep the guests laughing, whether that means wearing
rotten teeth and a chest pelt or running around in a bikini.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
