<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2680 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-POP18-COX     11-17 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple's `Pawn' lush and luminous listen
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laugh at her if you will. But we need performers who dish out
their dizzy idiosyncrasies as they grow up in public, fearless even
when feckless, and always aware that in our disconnected lives a
grand foolishness may be the better part of wisdom. Fiona Apple
fills the bill with an awkward, guileless manner that can't be
faked, something you can read scribbled between the lines in the
ongoing psychodrama of her songs.
</P>
<P>
   If the title of the 21-year-old musician's second album, a
90-word poem that begins ``When the Pawn ... ,'' is self-conscious
babble better left to a journal entry, the song cycle it introduces
is so winningly accomplished that you can't fault the audacity.
Hooked up with producer Jon Brion (on board for Apple's
breakthrough debut, ``Tidal''), the singer comes up with a richly
layered collection, one that combines her unerring feel for an
early-1970s quirky-but-soulful songwriter vibe with an eclectic,
post-hip-hop ear for musical detours and sonic hiccups. The
assertive yet vulnerable persona evoked by her lyrics is fleshed
out in the fluid jazz inflections of her voice. It thrives in the
solitude of a sparse few piano notes and swings into high gear
before the syncopations that make Apple's songs sound like nothing
else in pop right now. Tunes such as ``Limp'' emphasize that
sophistication, tossing a percussive jam session into the middle of
a three-minute pop song, as Apple points her finger: ``You fondle
my trigger, then you blame my gun.'' Nothing if not Freudian, the
singer, like the old psychoanalyst, appreciates a good joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Pawn ...''
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Apple. Clean
</P>
<P>
   Slate/Epic. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1720EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-RAGE18-COX     11-17 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAGE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Full-throttle Rage cranks it up loud in `Battle' assault
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might be misleading to call this the best rock album of the
year. In so many ways, Rage Against the Machine's third effort
sounds like the only rock album of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it suggests the pyrotechnic blues of Jimi Hendrix gone
thermonuclear by way of Public Enemy, the band's ruthless sonic
assault comes off less self-consciously retro than radically sliced
and diced. And, importantly, it's virulent, where most of what's
marketed as alternative rock is designed to be harmless or
boneheaded.
</P>
<P>
   The group's mix of left-wing warrior cries (Hispanic rapper Zack
De La Rocha, armed with a soapbox and a megaphone) and guitar
heroics (the ungodly good Tom Morello) owes steep dues to punk-era
acts such as the Clash, Gang of Four and Minutemen, bands that, for
the most part, did it better.
</P>
<P>
   What Rage does with such punishing success, as De La Rocha
chants on ``Guerrilla Radio,'' is ``turn that (stuff) up!''
Especially Morello, who, like the Stooges and Sonic Youth before
him, knows that distortion and idiosyncratic tunings can make a
guitar into a symphony of terrible beauty.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say what percentage of the band's audience cares
about the issues it raises _ from Central American politics to
``the naked cold millions gaspin' for air.'' It's a problem Bruce
Springsteen, whose ``The Ghost of Tom Joad'' has been covered by
Rage, can relate to. But there's nothing halfway in their
presentation. ``The Battle of Los Angeles'' is fought tooth and
nail _ and amps cranked to 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Battle of
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles''
</P>
<P>
   Rage Against the Machine. Epic.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
