<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time to revisit some reliable holiday treats
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The requests from Marie Musser and Judy Ackerman were
for recipes we've published before that are particular favorites
during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Musser lost her copy of Spiced Cranberries, which ran in a
Thanksgiving story two years ago. With a bumper crop of cranberries
this year, it sounded like a good time to reprint the Ursula's
Cooking School version.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman asked for Pumpkin Cookies, saying they are among her
husband's favorites. We published this recipe from Tennessee in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Spiced
</P>
<P>
   Candied Cranberries
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh cranberries, washed and picked over
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup port wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apricot preserves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple jelly
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   Spray a large Dutch oven with cooking spray. Add the
cranberries, sugar, vinegar, port, preserves, jelly, raisins, curry
powder, cinnamon, ginger, salt, allspice, cloves and cardamom.
Bring to boil over medium-high heat. Reduce heat to low and simmer
about 40 minutes. Cool about 45 minutes. Cover and refrigerate
until ready to use. Serve cold or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4-cup serving: 157 calories, less than 1 gram protein, no
fat, 41 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 78 milligrams sodium,
1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Raisin Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 5 dozen
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12-15 minutes per batch
</P>
<P>
   For the cookies:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups buttermilk baking mix
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground pumpkin pie spice
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) can pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   1 small (5-ounce) can evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cups quick-cooking (not instant) oats
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon orange extract
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the cookies: Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Grease cookie
sheets and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, stir together baking mix, sugar and
spice. Add pumpkin, evaporated milk and oil, mixing well. Stir in
oats and raisins. Drop by rounded teaspoonfuls onto prepared cookie
sheets. Bake 12 to 15 minutes, or until brown. Cool on racks before
frosting.
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting: In a small saucepan over low heat, combine
evaporated milk and margarine and stir until margarine melts. Add
orange extract. Remove from heat and stir in confectioners' sugar,
beating well.
</P>
<P>
   Per frosted cookie: 98 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 15), 21 grams carbohydrates, trace
cholesterol, 77 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
