<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini movie reviews
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Tea With Mussolini'' (PG) _ Known in 1930s Florence as ``the
scorpioni,'' thanks to their collective sting, a band of British
and American expatriate women (Maggie Smith, Judi Dench, Joan
Plowright and Cher) become surrogate mothers of a young boy named
Luca. Based on his autobiography, director Franco Zeffirelli's film
is an uneven but enjoyable tale of a boy growing up in Blackshirt
Italy, entrusted to a handful of Auntie Mames. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'' (R) _ Loses its way all too
often, but never loses its audience. Disconnected and dreamlike,
Mike Figgis' episodic film is as maddeningly self-indulgent as it
is disturbingly primal. A British filmmaker (Julian Sands) in
Tunisia thinks back on various former selves: a little boy in
Kenya, a fat boy in gym class, a lust-filled teenager. Meanwhile, a
very black Adam and a very white Eve act out their Garden of Eden
tragedy on a decaying estate. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Instinct'' (R) _ Resist your instinct to see it. Oscar
winner Anthony Hopkins plays an anthropologist locked up in a
psychiatric prison, surrounded by ``colorful'' inmates (a la ``One
Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest''). It seems that, after living for
months with gorillas in the African wilds (a la ``Gorillas in the
Mist''), he went berserk and killed two natives. Why? It's up to a
psychiatry student (Oscar winner Cuba Gooding Jr.) to pick his mind
(a la Hopkins' own ``Silence of the Lambs''). It's twaddle. Grade:
D+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Castle'' (R) _ A sunny little sleeper from Australia. A
cheerfully dimwitted working-class bloke named Darryl (Michael
Caton) takes on the system when the neighboring airport decides to
expand and tries to force him and his family out of their home.
It's a genial and just-goofy-enough David-and-Goliath
(Darryl-and-Goliath?) comedy that aims to do little more than put a
smile on your face. Which it does. Handily. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Phantom of the Opera'' (PG) _ In this version the phantom
doesn't wear a mask, just greasy long hair. What makes him scary is
that he's played by career weirdo Julian Sands. In this
surprisingly lackluster tale from Italian goremeister Dario
Argento, the scares are outnumbered by the sillinesses. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
