<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holiday help isn't far away
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the original hotline between the White House and the
Kremlin that was set up to avert nuclear confrontation during the
Cold War, a telephone hotline suggests an emergency. With the
number of food-related hotlines up and running for the holidays,
you could get the idea that cooking a turkey is akin to dismantling
a bomb _ an activity fraught with danger and dread.
</P>
<P>
   Well, cooking a turkey should hardly be anxiety-inducing. The
death toll from roasting turkeys is virtually nil, and if you use
common sense (just think of it as a big chicken), it's not only
fairly simple, but fun. And there's no potpourri on earth that
smells better than a turkey roasting in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   That said, just in case you do have a question or something
unforeseen happens in your holiday kitchen, you can relax. There's
probably no other undertaking that elicits such a proliferation of
easily accessible information. Food companies, farms and government
agencies all pitch in staffing hotlines and tip lines to help you
get that holiday meal successfully to your table.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY TIPS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Butterball Turkey Talk-Line, 1-800-323-4848: An army of home
economists and nutritionists will be on hand to help you out of any
turkey quandary you may encounter. 9 a.m.-9 p.m. weekdays through
Nov. 25; 9 a.m.-7 p.m. Nov. 21-22; 7 a.m.-7 p.m. Thanksgiving Day.
Online: www.butterball.com/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  USDA Hotline Meat and Poultry Hotline, 1-800-535-4555: This is
the number to call if you suspect your turkey is less than fresh or
you have questions about labeling or food-borne illness.
Year-round, you can quickly reach a specialist from 10 a.m. to 4
p.m. weekdays; even on Thanksgiving Day, you can call from 8 a.m.
to 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Your tax dollars are also at work at the Center for Food Safety
hotline. For reams of recorded information about the safety and use
of just about every food, call 1-800-332-4010 anytime.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perdue Farms, 800-473-7383: Experts will put in overtime
during Thanksgiving week to help with turkey problems. Hours for
Thanksgiving week are 9:30 a.m.-
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. Monday-Tuesday, 9 a.m.-9 p.m. Wednesday and 7 a.m.-3 p.m.
Thanksgiving Day. A booklet titled ``Perdue Guide to Safe Handling
of Chicken and Turkey Products'' is available free via the hotline.
Online: www.perdue.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Honeysuckle White, 1-800-810-6325: Automated assistance for a
host of turkey questions is available through Dec. 31. Online:
www.honeysucklewhite.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reynolds Wrap Turkey Tips Line, 1-800-745-4000: This 24-hour
recorded hotline is available through Dec. 31. Online:
www.reynoldskitchens.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Better Homes and Gardens Online: Visit www.bhglive.com/food
</P>
<P>
   /cookhelpers/turkqna.htmhotline for answers to previously asked
turkey-related questions, plus a list of other hotlines.
</P>
<P>
   BAKING ADVICE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Land O Lakes Holiday Bakeline, 1-800-782-9606: Experts are
available 9 a.m.-7 p.m. seven days a week through Dec. 24. Online:
www.landolakes.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Betty Crocker, 1-800-328-6787: Advice and recipe ideas from
the Betty Crocker Kitchens and General Mills. Experts are on call
8:30 a.m.-5:30 p.m Mondays-Fridays except holidays. Online:
www.bettycrocker.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fleischmann's Yeast Baker's Help Line, 1-800-777-4959: If you
don't get an answer by following the extensive automated system,
you can speak to a professional baker or other expert with
questions about yeast or other Fleischmann's products, including
those of Spice Islands, Durkee and French's. 10 a.m.-10 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays except holidays. Online: www.breadworld.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rhodes Frozen Dough Bake Line, 1-800-876-7333: Answers to
questions about frozen dough. 10 a.m.-7 p.m. weekdays. Online:
www.rhodesbread.com
</P>
<P>
   OTHER HELP
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Campbell Soup Leftover Hotline, 1-888-453-3868: If you need
ideas for using up leftovers. Online: www.campbellkitchen
</P>
<P>
   .com/leftover.cfm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shady Brook Farms Dial-A-Chef Holiday Hotline, 1-888-723-4468:
Recorded tips on planning holiday meals, recipes, entertaining and
wine pairings. Faxed menus; automated. Online: www.dialachef.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For scores of hotlines run by food companies, associations,
schools and government agencies, go to
ianrwww.unl.edu/ianr/lanco/factsheets/081-98.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For safety concerns, the National Food Safety site lists
hotlines covering everything from soup to nuts.
www.foodsafety.org/wheel/ww2133.htm
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
