<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-MINIMAL17-COX     11-17 2646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MINIMAL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A short route to a truly knockout feast
 &HT;    By Susan Puckett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ingredient list for these dishes could hardly be shorter _
but they're all long on flavor. Cookbook author Rozanne Gold, the
source of most of these recipes, carries the minimalist theme over
to her table settings _ showing off their vibrant colors on
oversize dark-white dishes and placing small, natural centerpieces
down the center of the table instead of one big arrangement in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Deviled Pecans
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These addictive nibbles are sure to whet the appetite. Be
careful, though; they're hard to stop eating.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce, plus more for drizzling
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In nonstick skillet, melt butter and add Worcestershire sauce.
Add pecans, pinch of salt and freshly ground pepper. Stir and cook
over medium heat for a few minutes, until nuts are coated.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to baking sheet and bake for 10 minutes, stirring
often. Drain on paper towels. Sprinkle with salt, pepper and
additional Worcestershire sauce. _ From ``Entertaining 1-2-3'' by
Rozanne Gold (Little, Brown, $27.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4-cup serving: 203 calories, 2 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 91), 5 grams carbohydrates, 4
milligrams cholesterol, 19 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BEVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   Autumn Leaf Cocktail
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rozanne Gold devised this refreshing cocktail especially for her
Thanksgiving guests. We tried it with Pernod, which adds a subtle
licorice flavor.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple cider (Gold prefers unpasteurized)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce arrack or Pernod
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly squeezed lemon juice, plus 1 strip lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   Put 4 ice cubes in large old-fashioned or rocks glass. Add cider
and arrack, and stir. Add lemon juice and stir again. Serve with
long, thin twist of lemon rind and stirrer. _ From ``Entertaining
1-2-3''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 102 calories, trace protein, trace fat (percent
calories from fat, 1), 15 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 4
milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Pear, Endive
</P>
<P>
   and Boursin Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This pretty salad tastes like fall.
</P>
<P>
   1 (5.2-ounce) package Boursin cheese with garlic and herbs,
well-chilled
</P>
<P>
   8 medium Belgian endives
</P>
<P>
   4 medium-large ripe green or red pears
</P>
<P>
   For the dressing: Break cheese into several pieces and place in
bowl of food processor. With the motor running, slowly add 1/2 to
2/3 cup cold water and process until smooth, thick and creamy.
Taste and add a little salt if needed. If using immediately, set
aside at room temperature while you prepare salad. If using later,
cover and refrigerate. Let come to room temperature before using.
If it's too thick, add a little water.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare salad: Immediately before serving, wash endives and
pears and dry well. Cut endives on the bias into slightly less than
1/8-inch-thick slices. Place in mounds in center of 8 large plates.
Cut pears in half through the stems and remove seeds. Cut each pear
half in 1/8-inch-thick slices. Drizzle several tablespoons dressing
over each mound of endives. Shingle pear slices on top. Drizzle
with 1/2 tablespoon dressing. _ From ``Entertaining 1-2-3''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 112 calories, 4 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 44), 13 grams carbohydrates, 18 milligrams
cholesterol, 117 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Michael's Perfect Roast
</P>
<P>
   Turkey With Lemon
</P>
<P>
   and Sage
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3-3 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 16- to 18-pound fresh turkey, bought from your butcher, at
room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dried sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 large lemons
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the fat from the rear of the turkey. Melt it in a small
nonstick pan. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the neck of the turkey, slip your fingers under the
skin and carefully separate the skin from one entire side of the
breast; most of your hand eventually will be under the skin.
Continue downward and, with your index finger, separate the skin
around the thigh. Repeat on the other side of the bird.
</P>
<P>
   Crumble the sage leaves and sprinkle them with freshly ground
black pepper. Spread 1 tablespoon sage on breast and thigh, beneath
the skin, on each half of the turkey. Prick each lemon several
times and insert in the bird's cavity.
</P>
<P>
   Put the neck and giblets in a baking pan; do not use liver. With
a pastry brush, thoroughly coat the breast with the rendered fat,
then sprinkle the entire bird with more pepper. Fold a double
thickness of paper towels in half and cover the entire breast.
Carefully pour cold water on the towels to thoroughly moisten them,
then cover the breast area with an aluminum-foil tent. Place the
bird on a rack over the gizzards and put in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Every 20 minutes, pull the turkey from the oven, remove the foil
tent and thoroughly moisten the paper towels with cold water. Some
water will flow into the pan and into the turkey; it will become
part of your pan juices.
</P>
<P>
   After 2 1/2 hours, check the turkey temperature with a meat
thermometer; the thigh should be about 145 degrees and the breast
125 degrees. If they are not, continue to cook (cooking time will
depend on the initial temperature and size of the bird).
</P>
<P>
   If they are, remove the foil and the paper towels and return the
turkey to the oven for about 45 minutes. The breast will brown and
temperatures will be 175 degrees to 180 degrees in the thigh and
155 to 160 in the breast.
</P>
<P>
   Take the turkey out of the oven and remove the lemons. Tip the
liquid inside the turkey into the roasting pan and then transfer
all the pan juice and brown bits to a saucepan. Let the turkey rest
under the foil tent. Skim the fat from the saucepan. Add 1/2
tablespoon juice from one of roasted lemons and bring to a boil.
You should have about 1 1/2 cups liquid; either add water or reduce
the liquid accordingly. Carve the turkey and serve with the pan
juices. _ From ``Recipes 1-2-3'' by Rozanne Gold (Little, Brown,
$22.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 357 calories, 48 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 1 gram carbohydrates, 139
milligrams cholesterol, 116 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   White Polenta
</P>
<P>
   With Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation and cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Polenta _ for Thanksgiving? If you favor corn bread stuffing,
it's not as weird as you think. In fact, it is quite delicious _
especially smushed up with the turkey, pan juices and cranberry
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups white cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, pushed through a garlic press
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Place the cornmeal and 1 teaspoon salt in a large saucepan.
Gradually add 5 cups water and then the garlic, stirring constantly
with a wooden spoon to remove any lumps. Bring to a boil, reduce
heat to medium, and cook, uncovered, about 10 minutes. Add 5
tablespoons grated cheese and continue cooking and stirring
frequently for 5 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Spread polenta on a heatproof platter, sprinkle with the
remaining cheese, and broil 1 minute. _ From ``Recipes 1-2-3''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 103 calories, 4 grams protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 19), 18 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 89 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Simple Green Beans
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3-4 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fresh string beans
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons good-quality olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Wash string beans and trim ends.
</P>
<P>
   Using a small, sharp knife, cut beans in half lengthwise to make
2 long, thin halves.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a medium pot of salted water to a boil. Add beans and cook
3 to 4 minutes over high heat until beans are bright green and
tender.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together oil and vinegar in a small bowl. Add salt and 1/4
teaspoon butcher-grind black pepper. Combine warm beans and
vinaigrette and toss thoroughly to coat. Serve immediately. _ From
``Recipes 1-2-3 Menu Cookbook'' by Rozanne Gold (Little, Brown,
$25)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 117 calories, 2 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 79), 6 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 5 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Orange and
</P>
<P>
   Gold Potato Puree
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This mixture of sweet potatoes and Yukon Golds has a lovely hue
and just a hint of sweetness. And the buttermilk adds rich flavor.
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds large sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds Yukon Gold potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup buttermilk, at room temperature (plus more, if needed)
</P>
<P>
   Peel the sweet potatoes and the Yukon Gold potatoes. Cut them in
large chunks and put them in a large pot with cold salted water to
cover. Bring to a boil, lower heat and cook 30 minutes, or until
potatoes are very soft. Drain the water. Mash potatoes with a
potato masher or put them through a ricer. Mix well, adding
buttermilk until potatoes are creamy and smooth. Add salt and
pepper to taste. Reheat gently before serving, adding buttermilk if
needed. _ From ``Recipes 1-2-3''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 155 calories, 3 grams protein, less than 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 3), 35 grams carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 32 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Mashed Turnips
</P>
<P>
   With Bacon and
</P>
<P>
   Caramelized Onions
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds turnips, peeled and cut in even chunks (rutabagas or
celery root may be substituted)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound bacon, cut in 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan over medium heat, cook the turnips in
lightly salted water to cover until tender, 25 to 30 minutes.
Meanwhile, in a heavy skillet over medium heat, fry bacon until
crisp and brown. Drain on paper towels; pour off all but about 6
tablespoons fat from the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Drain turnips and return pan to low heat for a minute or so to
remove all the moisture. Mash the turnips with a potato masher or
large fork until fairly smooth but still a bit lumpy. (May be done
1 or 2 hours ahead up to this point.)
</P>
<P>
   Heat bacon drippings over medium heat, then add onions, sprinkle
with pepper and cook, stirring, until caramelized, 8 to 10 minutes.
Stir onions and bacon bits into the turnips, reserving a few bits
of bacon for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 115 calories, 5 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 43), 12 grams carbohydrates, 9 milligrams
cholesterol, 284 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Olive Oil Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 20 biscuits Preparation time: 5 minutes Cooking
time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a medium bowl, combine flour and
salt. Make a well in the center and add milk and 7 tablespoons
olive oil. Stir until blended. Do not overwork, or biscuits will be
tough.
</P>
<P>
   On a lightly floured surface, roll dough to 1/3-inch thickness.
Cut in 1 1/2-inch rounds with a plain or fluted cookie cutter;
place on a baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 10 minutes, until biscuits just begin to turn golden.
Using a pastry brush, brush tops with remaining 1 tablespoon oil
and sprinkle lightly with salt. _ From ``Entertaining 1-2-3''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 52 calories, 2 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 13), 10 grams carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 190 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   A co-worker shared these recipes, which he makes every
Thanksgiving. Make the relish first, then, without even washing the
food processor bowl, throw in the ingredients for the butter.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry-Orange Relish
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 large orange, washed, seeded and cut in chunks (do not peel)
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fresh cranberries
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, place orange chunks, cranberries and sugar.
Process until finely chopped. Pour into a 3-cup bowl and chill
until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 21 calories, trace protein, no fat, 5 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, trace sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Butter
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup fresh cranberries
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons grated lemon or orange peel (optional)
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, chop cranberries with citrus peel (if
using) and sugar until coarse. Add butter and process until all
ingredients are combined but slightly chunky.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 57 calories, trace protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 90), 2 grams carbohydrates, 15 milligrams
cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin-Eggnog
</P>
<P>
   Flan With Custard Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here is a simple, elegant take on pumpkin pie. The sauce tastes
like creme anglaise; who'd ever guess it's commercial eggnog that's
simply been cooked down to a thicker consistency?
</P>
<P>
   2 level cups pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   pie filling
</P>
<P>
   4 cups eggnog
</P>
<P>
   4 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In bowl of electric mixer, put
pumpkin pie filling and 3 cups eggnog. Mix well. Add eggs and blend
very well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour mixture evenly into eight 6-ounce custard cups. Place cups
in a deep baking pan. Pour boiling water in pan until it reaches
halfway up sides of the cups. Bake 40-50 minutes, until firm.
Remove from water bath and refrigerate until very cold.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Serve with eggnog custard sauce: Put 1 cup remaining
eggnog in small heavy saucepan. Reduce by half very slowly, 20 to
25 minutes, over low heat, whisking often. Chill custard sauce well
and spoon 1 tablespoon on top of each flan, smoothing down with a
small, flexible spatula or a butter knife. _ From ``Recipes 1-2-3
Menu Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 204 calories, 10 grams protein, 9 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 22 grams carbohydrates, 226
milligrams cholesterol, 134 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Black
</P>
<P>
   Walnut Bars
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This rich-tasting cake actually becomes moister and more
flavorful if you wrap it well in foil before cutting it in bars. It
makes a nice accompaniment to the pumpkin flan.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups honey graham cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups coarsely chopped black walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 (14-ounce) can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Put the graham cracker crumbs and walnuts in a medium-size bowl.
Slowly add the condensed milk and a pinch of salt. Mix with a
wooden spoon. Mixture will be very thick and gooey.
</P>
<P>
   Pack into a nonstick 8-inch square pan or into a 9 1/2-inch
round, removable-bottom pan lined with parchment paper or coated
with nonstick cooking spray. Wet your hands with cold water and
smooth the dough on top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 25 to 30 minutes. Let cool. Wrap the leftover cake very
well in plastic wrap or aluminum foil. Keeps for weeks, and flavor
improves overnight. _ From ``Recipes 1-2-3''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 185 calories, 5 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 21 grams carbohydrates, 9
milligrams cholesterol, 80 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Puckett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
