<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-MINIMAL18-COX     11-17 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MINIMAL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thanksgiving around the corner, opt for minimal preparations
 &HT;    By Susan Puckett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MINIMALIST
</P>
<P>
   With only a week left until T-Day, you're cutting it close if
you're still thinking of preparing
</P>
<P>
   a full-fledged, made-from-scratch feast. Unless, that is, you
opt for today's menu. It's stylish, sophisticated
</P>
<P>
   and superbly flavored _ and includes dishes calling for only
three ingredients
</P>
<P>
   In years past, I knew of but one way to improve upon the
traditional Thanksgiving menu: Embellish it.
</P>
<P>
   I would start with the basic recipes, then personalize them with
as many of my own flourishes as I could dream up. I might float a
turkey-shaped puff pastry cutout in the squash soup. Spike the corn
bread dressing with a shot of armagnac. Simmer cranberries and
exotic spices into a complex chutney. Throw chocolate chips into
the pecan pie.
</P>
<P>
   So what if it took every pot and pan in my kitchen and left me
with an arsenal of ingredients guaranteed to rot long before they'd
ever get used again. Or that, deep down, I was fully aware that a
pumpkin pie made straight off the Libby's can label would have
suited my guests just fine. For me, the thrill of Thanksgiving has
always been trying to outdo all previous efforts, without veering
too far out of the realm of tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But this year I'm taking a radically different tack. I'm going
radically simple. Instead of adding ingredients to my shopping
list, I'm paring it down. Way down.
</P>
<P>
   No dish on the menu I'll be serving, in fact, will contain more
than three ingredients (assuming you don't count salt, pepper or
water). Yet not one of the fabulous flavors and textures and smells
that I love about this holiday will be sacrificed. After giving it
a test drive, I can attest that it not only works, it's delicious.
</P>
<P>
   For inspiration I turned to Rozanne Gold, a New York chef and
restaurant consultant who has written three award-winning cookbooks
on the three-ingredient principle. I've been hooked on her 1996
book, ``Recipes 1-2-3,'' ever since my husband made me a
five-course birthday dinner that was as wonderful as any restaurant
meal in recent memory _ entirely from Gold's book. And as I explore
her sequels _ ``Recipes 1-2-3 Menu Cookbook'' and ``Entertaining
1-2-3'' _ I become more convinced that Gold's less-is-more theory
isn't just another gimmick, but a winning formula for producing
great food without stress.
</P>
<P>
   Gold admits that, like many other contemporary chefs, she has
been guilty of engaging in ``flavor cover-up: masking a dish's
elemental flavors by piling on too many ingredients.'' Then, a few
years ago, she imposed on herself the challenge of achieving
maximum flavor by going in the opposite direction, focusing on the
fewest possible ingredients. Now it's a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very manageable,'' Gold says. ``You don't get overwhelmed
during the shopping or the cooking. And that's important,
especially when you're entertaining for the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   But would that concept fly at Thanksgiving?
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it last year at my house, and I will be this year,
too,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   So how does she go about planning the menu?
</P>
<P>
   First, by focusing on the flavors she most associates with the
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet potatoes, sage, the flavor of cooked bones, members of
the allium family _ those say `Thanksgiving' for me,'' Gold says.
``I like the sharpness of the cranberries, the interplay on the
plate between sweet and salty and savory.''
</P>
<P>
   Bearing those tips in mind, I put together this menu _ along
with a few of my own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised at how easy it was to find three-ingredient
recipes that came so close to tradition. And all of us who sat down
to eat it were even more amazed at how satisfied we were by meal's
end.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't even miss the corn bread stuffing with Gold's
garlic-and-Parmesan-flavored polenta in its place, which tasted all
the better when doused with the sage-scented turkey drippings.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most liberal-thinking of cooks, I realize, may have a
hard time buying that one. So make an exception _ you won't hurt
Gold's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't serve stuffing last year, and nobody seemed to miss
it,'' she says. ``But to tell you the truth, I love stuffing. I
just make the Pepperidge Farm kind, adding twice as many
caramelized onions and some crumbled sausage.''
</P>
<P>
   By combining recipes with just a few ingredients, you can
orchestrate a wonderful meal with elegance and ease. And at
holidays especially, it keeps you from getting overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rozanne Gold, author of ``Recipes 1-2-3''
</P>
<P>
   S I M P L E M E N U W I T H S T Y L E
</P>
<P>
   Deviled Pecans / Autumn Leaf Cocktail
</P>
<P>
   Pear, Endive and Boursin Salad
</P>
<P>
   Michael's Perfect Roast Turkey With Lemon and Sage
</P>
<P>
   White Polenta With Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   Orange and Gold Potato Puree
</P>
<P>
   Mashed Turnips With Bacon and Caramelized Onions
</P>
<P>
   Simple Green Beans
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry-Orange Relish
</P>
<P>
   Olive Oil Biscuits / Cranberry Butter
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin-Eggnog Flan With Custard Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Black Walnut Bars
</P>
<P>
   Susan Puckett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
