<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-TURKEY-METHOD18-COX     11-17 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-METHOD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do it your way: Relax _ and don't fret all the fun out of
cooking the turkey
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom about cooking the Thanksgiving turkey is
that none exists. Every year at this time the newspaper food
sections and cooking magazines are filled with a panoply of advice,
tips and techniques guaranteed to pop your pop-up timer.
</P>
<P>
   You start the oven on high, and then turn it down. You start low
but not so low that your guests are felled by salmonella. You
stuff. You don't stuff. You roast the turkey upside down. You tent
foil over it. You wrap it in cheesecloth. You immerse it in hot
oil. You buy frozen. You buy fresh. You baste every 20 minutes like
your life depends on it.
</P>
<P>
   One year, for an article, I decided to put it all to the test
and cooked so many turkeys my family worried for my sanity. I
cooked turkey after turkey until I reached a couple of conclusions
about the whole enterprise:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The first and most important conclusion is that overcooked
turkey is not such a terrible thing. Seriously. I'd rather have
overcooked turkey than overcooked roast beef or overcooked
asparagus any day. The white meat will get that weirdly crumbly
texture if you leave it in a couple of hours too long, but it's
nothing that extra gravy and stuffing can't rectify. And the dark
meat is close to indestructible. So relax.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The second conclusion is that technique does make a
difference, but it all depends on you _ your skills, your kitchen,
your pots and pans. You'll have much greater success cooking the
turkey the way Mom or Betty Crocker taught you if the effort
required for some of these other techniques gives you the willies.
</P>
<P>
   That said, I pitted three stylish turkeys _ one brined, one
wrapped in cheesecloth, one upside down _ against a gobbler cooked
Mom's way, i.e., plunked in a disposable roaster and tented with
foil. I didn't try deep-frying; I'm sorry, but a cauldron of
350-degree oil is not something I want to contend with on
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   All the various techniques have the same goal: to keep some
moisture in the breast meat while giving the legs the time they
need to cook through.
</P>
<P>
   The brining was a fascinating technique. You rub the turkey
inside and out with 2 pounds of salt, then cover it with water and
let it soak for 4-6 hours. Then you rinse it well and roast as
normal. The one I brined did have better flavor and more succulence
than regular turkey, though succulence is a relative term when
you're talking turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, I'm not sure it's the kind of project I want to
undertake on Thanksgiving. I don't want to donate four-fifths of my
precious refrigerator space to a bucket of salt water big enough to
immerse a 25-pound carcass in.
</P>
<P>
   The cheesecloth method calls for wrapping the whole turkey in
several thicknesses of cloth, then smearing it with soft butter or
oil. I ended up with no noticeable betterment of the breast meat,
but a gorgeous skin _ the kind of mahogany shellack that I had seen
only in commercials. Nonetheless, I didn't like having to demummify
the turkey prior to serving, particularly since the cheesecloth
stuck to the skin in several places.
</P>
<P>
   The upside-down method seemed a winner through and through. I
bought an adjustable V-shaped rack. I painted the turkey with
melted butter and roasted it, breast down, in the rack. While the
sky-high thighs cooked faster, the juices ran down into the breast.
Before the last hour of cooking time, I flipped it with wads of
paper towels, which wasn't as difficult a task as you might think.
It did look a little pointy _ like a baby delivered with forceps _
but I managed to rack up a lot of compliments on that turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mom's turkey wasn't so different. Like Mom, I roasted the
turkey with foil loosely tented over it until the last hour or two
of cooking, then removed the foil and began basting every few
minutes to get some color into the skin.
</P>
<P>
   When all was said and done, though, I switched to the
upside-down method. It works for me and, well, I invested in that
V-shaped rack. What other time am I going to use it?
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
