<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SHOPPING-TOYS-ART     11-17 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-TOYS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PARENTS AND STORES ANXIETY OVER HOT TOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Eds: This is one in a series of articles on online shopping)  
 (af)  
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For parents who fruitlessly searched empty store aisles for last
year's blockbuster electronic toy, Furby, or who braved lines that
would have done the retail system of the Soviet Union proud to wait
for a Tickle Me Elmo in 1996, take heart: the toy industry feels
your pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good actually,'' said Alan Marcus, a spokesman
for FAO Schwarz, in discussing the annual shortages that seem to
turn the quest for each year's hot toy into a frustrating treasure
hunt. ``It builds customer excitement. It keeps customers on their
toes. It makes the experience fun when people keep their
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Weary parents can expect even more perspective this year,
perhaps enough to wonder whether these apparent shortages aren't as
manufactured as Furby's canned speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way hot toys become hot toys is completely marketing and
hype,'' said Marianne Szymanski, president of Toy Tips
(www.toytips.com), which tests toys in affiliation with Marquette
University. ``First, their manufacturers declare them to be the hot
toy of the year. It's just their opinion, but it gets picked up by
the media. Then it's been my experience that when parents rush out
to stores, they can't get the toys. That suggests that either the
toys are not there or the manufacturer won't get them there until
the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Toy makers and retailers, however, recoil at the suggestion that
they create shortages _ or at least the impression of shortages _
to build interest. ``It would never benefit us to create any kind
of shortages,'' said Lana Simon, a spokeswoman for Tiger
Electronics, the Hasbro unit that makes Furby. ``We don't win;
customers don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Simon said the production of Furbys was intended to
be sufficient but demand had been unexpectedly high. ``Last year
between Oct. 2 and the end of December we sold four million
Furbies, which is a lot of product,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Furby, like many toys, was first unveiled to buyers during last
year's American International Toy Fair, the biggest toy trade show
in the Western Hemisphere. Toy Fair takes place in February, just
after toys from the previous holidays have been broken or
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Although Furby's fuzzy exterior was still incomplete and its
full set of electronic tricks were still in development at the 1998
fair, Marnie Lawrence, a senior buyer for FAO Schwarz, knew that
Tiger had a winner. ``Even in that form you could see that it was a
wonderful toy, innovative and interesting,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   By late spring of 1998, most stores had ordered their holiday
stock. In the summer, the creatures were mass-produced in China,
where nearly all electronic toys are now made. Then they were then
shipped by sea to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Szymanski concedes that long lead times can make it
difficult for toy sellers and makers to estimate how many units it
will take to sate the public's appetite for a new toy. Furby was
scheduled for an elaborate introduction on Oct. 2, 1998, at FAO
Schwarz's flagship store in Manhattan. Before it was released, the
toy got a head start from a long, laudatory article in Wired
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Thanksgiving, the demand for Furby started to
outstrip store inventories, and Tiger was soon caught in a squeeze.
After an order was placed by Tiger at its headquarters in Illinois,
it took 10 days to manufacture a Furby in China and two to four
weeks to ship it by sea. In November, Tiger began flying the toys
across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lawrence confesses that she didn't foresee that come
November 1998, a Furby famine would quickly develop, creating a
black market in the nattering dolls and empty shelves in toy stores
everywhere. ``Oh my goodness, no,'' she said. ``It's one of those
toys that comes along once in a career.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the fact that another six million Furbys have been
sold this year, during the slowest period for toy sales, suggests
that the holiday backlog was probably impossible to overcome last
year, Ms. Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with several toy industry representatives produced
no clear answers to the question of what electronic toy might
follow Furby as this year's runaway hit _ or even if there will be
a toy that will scale such heights.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Barlett, a spokeswoman for the Toy Manufacturers of
America, said that while many _ if not all _ new toys were billed
as the next big thing, those claims were proved only when the
holiday buying season was well under way. While Tickle Me Elmo
dominated the 1996 season, she said, ``it wasn't until the Friday
after Thanksgiving that Tickle Me Elmo was declared to be a hot
item.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever really knows for sure what's going to be hot,''
she said. ``I haven't heard about any surprise hit for this year.
I'm as curious as anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   For parents who can't take another season of long lines but also
fear disappointing their children, Ms. Szymanski offers a consoling
thought: ``Before the hype begins, the hot toy of the season is not
at the top of children's lists.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, her research has found that the gadgety features that
have become a required feature of hot sellers often hold little
sustained appeal for children. Much to Ms. Szymanski's amazement,
every annual survey of toy popularity Toy Tips has conducted since
1991 has been topped by the same toy: the Twister game, where a
vinyl sheet is about as high-tech as things get. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Choices for Electronic Toys Include Old Favorites and Some New
Challengers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hot or not, here are some choices for electronic toys this
season. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. HAMMERHEAD FX The smoothly sculptured Hammerhead FX game pad
($39.99) houses tiny vibrating motors that offer force-feedback
shakes, rattles and rolls in response to on-screen blasts and
bang-ups. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. LEGO MINDSTORMS No computer is needed for two new products in
the Mindstorms line of buildable, programmable robots _ the
Robotics Discovery Kit ($149.99) and the Droid Developer Kit
($99.99). Instead, there are programming buttons on the systems'
brick-size microcomputer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. SIDEWINDER FORCE FEEDBACK PRO This $129 game controller from
Microsoft is perfect for those whose love to shake, rattle and
roll. A standard joystick costs closer to $29, but the SideWinder
is better engineered and smarter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. SAITEK R100 RACING WHEEL Why should anyone not use a racing
wheel and pedals to hurl their virtual speedsters through their
paces? This $50 system attaches quickly and easily to any PC game
port. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. SEGA DREAMCAST The best television-based game platform around
(for now), the 128-bit Dreamcast system produces dazzling 3-D
graphics and CD-quality sound. At $199, it can play games that
rival those played on a good computer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. QX3 COMPUTER MICROSCOPE Mattel and Intel created a clever toy
and learning tool that for $99.95 magnifies anything from bug wings
to flower petals up to 200 times _ showing its findings on
computers running Windows 98. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEO GEO POCKET COLOR The first true challenger to the ubiquitous
Nintendo Game Boy and Game Boy Color, the 16-bit Neo Geo has a
larger screen, can display more vibrant and varied colors and has a
natural-feeling horizontal design. There are 20 or so games
available for the $69.95 Neo Geo, by SNK.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1723EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2693 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SHOPPING-BOTS-ART     11-17 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-BOTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SHOPPING GUIDES HUNT FOR BARGAINS, THE BARGAINS THEY WANT
YOU TO SEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (Eds: This is one in a series of articles on online shopping)  
 (af)  
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agents are ready for service. The question is, whom will
they serve?
</P>
<P>
   For years, futurists have said that the World Wide Web will
enable automated shopping robots, or bots, to instantly scan
hundreds of merchants to help penny pinchers find the best goods at
the lowest price.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been some comparison shopping services, but they
have often been on small sites started as hobbies or technology
demonstrations. Often users found searches that turned up either
nothing or too many, often irrelevant items.
</P>
<P>
   But now, just in time for the holiday shopping frenzy, there is
a new generation of bots to help shoppers sort through the vastly
expanding array of merchandise on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest services, like America Online and Yahoo, have them.
And some of the little startups, like MySimon (www.mysimon.com) and
DealTime (www.dealtime.com), have raised money and are upgrading
their sites with more products and better searching technology.
</P>
<P>
   There are comparison services for special areas, like Cnet
Shopper for computers (shopper.cnet.com/) and DealPilot for books
and music (www.dealpilot.com/). And even Amazon.com
(www.amazon.com), the giant of electronic commerce, has just
introduced its ``all product search'' shopping agent, which will
help people find out who carries items that Amazon does not stock.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these can help shoppers save time and money. But buyer
beware: that shopping agent is probably a double agent, with
loyalties to someone other than the consumer. The evidence: many of
the sites, like MySimon and Cnet Shopper, have stopped
automatically listing items with the lowest cost first. They put
items from advertisers first unless the user requests otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   America Online and Disney's Go Network will not even list
merchants that do not pay for exposure.
</P>
<P>
   And even services that loudly proclaim that their shopping
listings are unbiased, like Frictionless Commerce on Lycos
(www.frictionless.com/), still take payments from merchants for
sending customers to their stores.
</P>
<P>
   The only bot that does not take money from merchants appears to
be Amazon. But to no surprise, its search engine skips over Barnes
&AMP; Noble and other big competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The other shopping agent companies say they have no choice but
to take money from the very merchants they are trying to compare.
After all, shoppers show little interest in paying fees to see
unbiased comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customer, in terms of who pays the bills, is the
merchant,'' said Josh Goldman, chief executive of MySimon, one of
the more popular shopping sites. ``The technology is very cool that
can bring product information and prices to consumers, but it's
very threatening to merchants. They think comparison shopping is a
threat to their brands and a threat to their profit margins.''
</P>
<P>
   So Goldman changed the site so that merchants can pay to add
their logos and information about their promotions and special
services. Moreover, instead of listing products with the lowest
price first, it gives priority to these paying merchants.
</P>
<P>
   At first, merchants tried to block the shopping bots. And even
now, Ebay is blocking sites like AuctionWatch and Bidder's Edge,
which want to compare its auctions with those of other auction
sites.
</P>
<P>
   But most merchants now largely accept the comparison sites as
another source of customers. Although Amazon, the best-known name,
does not actively cooperate with other shopping agents, neither
does it block them from searching its site.
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com (www.buy.com), a site devoted to selling computers,
books and other goods at near break-even profit margins, got many
of its initial customers through shopping bots.
</P>
<P>
   And even some merchants that are not the cheapest in the market
are embracing the shopping agents, particularly those that
de-emphasize price shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the comparison services are a good thing,''
said Greg Drew, chief executive of 800.com (www.800.com), a site
that sells consumer electronics. ``But I work to make sure the CEOs
of those sites understand that for complex products, like the ones
we sell, there are other factors besides price, like service,
after-purchase support and whether the merchant is an authorized
dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   The 800.com site has bought preferred placement on sites like
MySimon and Bottomdollar.com.
</P>
<P>
   But online shopping analysts say that as customers begin to
understand that many sites are now favoring advertisers, there may
be a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the search result is sorted by price, it doesn't leave any
room for editorial misdeeds,'' said Ken Cassar, a shopping analyst
with Jupiter Communications. ``But as soon as they alter the sort
order to one that is not relevant to the consumer, they raise
questions of integrity. And in the long run, users will gravitate
to the sites that are the least biased.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman says MySimon is providing a better service to consumers
than most other agents, because it lists 1,800 merchants and most
of them do not pay the company anything.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we list everyone in the world we can think of,
whether they pay us or not, says we are the only bot that can claim
to be unbiased,'' he said. ``Does someone say the Yellow Pages is
biased because one plumber has a quarter-page ad with a picture of
their truck and their phone number in big type?''
</P>
<P>
   But in fact shopping bot users seem to respond to these
promotions the way Yellow Pages users will often call the plumber
with the big ad.
</P>
<P>
   For example, only 21 percent of the users of the Cnet Shopper
site select the button that sorts listings by price, with the
cheapest first. If they do not, advertisers who paid to have their
logos displayed are listed first, followed by those that paid for
bold listings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked'' by how few people sort by price, said Kevin
McKenzie, the co-head of electronic commerce at Cnet. ``But a lot
of people will pick a branded listing even if it is way off the
lowest price.'' This is great news for Cnet, which hopes to get
half its revenue from selling listings on the shopping site.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike MySimon, Cnet and many other sites will not even list
merchants unless they agree to some sort of payment.
</P>
<P>
   This is actually a benefit for both consumers and merchants,
argued Kevin D. Brown, the head of shopping strategy for Inktomi, a
company that operates the shopping search for a variety of sites
including Disney's Go Network, Time Warner's CNNfn and Merrill
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers don't want 100 undifferentiated merchants,'' he
said. ``And we can say to companies that are nervous about
comparison shopping that we are not overloading a category, so you
have a good shot of getting to a consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which operates the busiest shopping mall on the
Internet, just introduced a new service that lets users search and
compare more than one million items. But all those items are sold
by the 275 merchants who pay millions of dollars a year to be on
its shopping channel.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Gates, the head of AOL's shopping service, argues that
customers will find all the goods they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the 80-20 rule,'' he said. ``The brands we have online
drive the majority of the business.'' But there are notable
exceptions. Since Barnes &AMP; Noble is the exclusive bookseller on
AOL, Amazon, the No. 1 Internet retailer, never shows up in AOL's
product search.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's search does not give certain merchants priority over
others. But neither does it give users the option to sort results
by price. The only criteria for listing is the company's
proprietary ``relevance'' ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not hearing a lot of demand for price comparison from
our customer base,'' Gates said. ``People want to find the products
they are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's shopping search also emphasizes those merchants who pay
to be in the Yahoo Stores mall. But unlike AOL, which caters to the
richest merchants, Yahoo Stores is mainly a way for mom-and-pop
businesses to go online with relatively low cost.
</P>
<P>
   Thus a search on Yahoo Stores is likely to turn up unusual items
at small vendors but will miss many of the largest online
merchants. Unlike AOL, however, Yahoo offers a second search
option. After a user looks at all the offerings of its stores, it
will offer to search other nonpaying merchants on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the big portals get into the comparison shopping
business, there is a generation of new services that purport to be
the better bot, often by claiming to be more objective.
</P>
<P>
   One example is Frictionless Commerce, an offshoot of MIT
research, which lets users describe what they are looking for based
on a number of criteria.
</P>
<P>
   So shoppers can say whether they want the cheapest price, the
most liberal return policy or the strictest privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Search results will be ranked based on these factors and cannot
be influenced by advertising. But if a merchant that it lists has
an ``affiliate program'' that pays for referring customers,
Frictionless will sign up and take the money.
</P>
<P>
   DealTime is a service that lets users camp out on the steps of
merchants, waiting for prices to fall. Users enter what they want
to buy and the price they want to pay, and DealTime will e-mail
them as soon as it finds someone offering that price. Advertisers,
however, are listed first on its site.
</P>
<P>
   Another new approach is shopping bots that hover in the
background as a user surfs the Web. Once a user finds something,
say, a book on Amazon, the bot will search other sites to see
whether there are better deals elsewhere. These services are just
being introduced by ClickTheButton (www.clickthebutton.com/) and by
DealPilot, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne Ehrlich, the founder of ClickTheButton, says that the
year-old company is too new and that he does not know yet how it
will make money, but that it will probably try to earn some sort of
commission for introducing buyers to sellers.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the company does not exclude nonpaying merchants,
and it will always list items with the cheapest first, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who use comparison services don't want to go through
four screens to find the lowest price,'' Ehrlich said. ``The people
who say that price doesn't matter all have stock options and don't
care how much they pay for things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
