<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2699 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SHOPPING-ONLINE-2     11-17 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-ONLINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BEGINNING TO LOOK A LOT LIKE PANIC
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was how my holiday shopping began this year: As we were
driving home the other day, my 8-year-old middle daughter leaned
forward into our car's front seat airspace, brushed her bangs from
her eyes for the 10th time that hour and said: ``Dad, you're
Jewish, and so are Zoe and Clementine and me. We celebrate
Hanukkah. So why do we get presents on Christmas, too?''
</P>
<P>
   My husband said, ``Because your mother grew up with Christmas,
and she loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Ella replied wearily: ``Dad, how many times have I told
you? You should have stopped to think, before you married her,
about how confusing this was going to be for us kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully, Ella, sorting out which holidays to celebrate can be
very confusing even for the adults in our family. The uncertainty
manifests itself in our annual holiday shopping system, which I
would describe in general terms as a belligerent refusal to
confront either an impending holiday or the need to shop for it
until, say, the day before. This is followed by a frazzled dash to
an overcrowded mall where we buy the children gifts for both
Hanukkah and Christmas, although spoiling them only results,
apparently, in even more cheekiness.
</P>
<P>
   That is why I vowed to change this year by doing all my holiday
shopping early and online.
</P>
<P>
   But holiday shopping does not migrate to the computer screen so
easily. The British anthropologist Daniel Miller has theorized,
after all, that shopping for those closest to you is an intimate
way to define your relationship to them. Holiday shopping,
therefore, is fraught with far more painful emotional overtones
than buying groceries or toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are really obsessed by are a few close personal
relations, with partners, children and so forth,'' he told me
recently. ``The consequence of the physical act of shopping for
those people is that you confront and define your relationships to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what I hoped to avoid. I wanted to bypass the sensations
of touching, of smelling, of wondering if a certain fuzzy grayish
blue sweater the exact color as Ella's eyes would be a more
appropriate gift for Hanukkah or for Christmas, then wondering
darkly if my decision would be symbolic of an unconscious
ambivalence toward _ oh, let's not get into it here.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, let's just say I was looking forward to a comparatively
clinical approach. Online, I could point, click, enter some
emotionally neutral information about the expiration date of my
credit card. By changing the rules of the ritual, I hoped to
transform the fundamental nature of the shopping experience itself.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what happened:
</P>
<P>
   _ I bought no Christmas tree ornaments. Why is this significant?
Because I always buy Christmas tree ornaments. In other words, the
kinds of things I bought online were different. If I were wandering
through real stores redolent with holiday smells of candles and
potpourri and the subtle pressure of carols piped into the sound
system, I would have made holiday-related impulse purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I bought safe things that I didn't need to see or to
touch to appreciate, like books and board games that I played with
as a child. Later, I found out that this pattern of buying is
typical.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a living example of my research, I must say,'' said
Eugene Fram, a professor of marketing at the Rochester Institute of
Technology in upstate New York, who has conducted two studies of
online shoppers' habits in the last five years. ``You're in
cyberspace, and cyberspace is cold. So online shoppers buy safe
products, those without risk of color, fabric, style, complexity. A
book is a book is a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, safe does not have to mean boring. I bought bottles
of invisible ink, a set of pens to tint black-and-white photographs
and a cardboard playhouse with walls you can color, all from Flax
Art and Design (www.flaxart.com), a San Francisco art supply store
that I would not have stumbled into except online.
</P>
<P>
   _ I started shopping earlier than ever. And instead of a single
shopping marathon, I shopped a little bit each day. It was so easy
to do without leaving my desk.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, I still couldn't beat the crowds. For instance, when I
visited www.mujionline.com, a Web site that was set up to attract
overseas holiday shoppers to the Japan-based Muji department store,
two of the three items I wanted were sold out _ in early November.
Only when I tried to add them to my shopping basket did I learn
they were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   At www.toysRus.com, the crowds were so thick one recent
afternoon that it took me an hour to get onto the site's Big Book
page, where the company is offering first-time buyers $10 off
purchases of $25 or more through Nov. 20. Once there, I found
problems. The price on one item, a Play-Doh Super Value set, did
not match the price in a print catalog that I received in the mail
a few days earlier. So I didn't buy it. Also, the site was so
sluggish that it took me 13 minutes to successfully place two items
into a shopping basket, and then it took an additional 17 minutes
to complete the order.
</P>
<P>
   This could be because, as a company spokeswoman explained to me
later, 62 million people received the same catalog that I did,
causing the site's traffic to increase 1,000 percent in a single
week. Good for Toys ``R'' Us sales? Maybe. But very annoying for
me.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominous, online shortages and traffic jams are
expected to get worse. ``Shop early, because I think there will be
some major problems with fulfillment of orders; a lot of these
virtual retailers and distributors will not be able to handle the
movement of goods in a timely fashion,'' said Jack Gifford, a
professor of marketing at Miami University in Oxford, Ohio. ``I
just bought two pieces of software online from Microsoft _ who
should be good at this _ and there's a 40-day wait. I probably
could walk into a real store and get it today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some online businesses are starting with a storefront, but
don't have the fully integrated back-room systems that real stores
would. They're madly building warehouses to try to catch up. But
that takes time,'' Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   So, as the holidays loom closer, follow the advice of Nick
Karris, a senior analyst at Gomez Advisors, which publishes reviews
of online merchants at www.gomez.com. ``Ask yourself, is this a
credible site?'' Karris said. ``How long has it been in business?
And ask yourself, do they have a clear policy on how they are going
to support me if I have to return something or if I have a
question?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   _ I saved money. Comparison shopping was so much easier to do
online, where I could check out a dozen or more merchants' prices
in a half-hour. And I found that the selection was much better. For
instance, when I went hunting for Playmobil dollhouse furniture, I
learned that I could beat the price advertised at www.etoys.com by
$5 by bidding on the same item at www.ebay.com. Of course, the Ebay
item was not new from a store. But it did arrive in a never-opened
box that looked just like new.
</P>
<P>
   And I saved in other ways. While shopping for books to ship to
five nieces and nephews, I found that the prices were virtually
identical at www.amazon.com and at www.barnesandnoble.com. Since
Barnesandnoble.com was offering free shipping the second week in
November (an incentive for early shoppers that may not be repeated
this holiday season, a spokesman said), I did my research on
Amazon, where its software knows my preferences, then placed the
order with Barnesandnoble.com. My savings: $7.75. A few days later,
however, follow-up e-mail from Barnesandnoble.com listed shipping
charges. I called the site's toll-free number; a polite customer
service representative apologized for what he described as a system
error and credited my account.
</P>
<P>
   _ I began to crave human contact. Well, what I really missed was
advice from helpful sales clerks. So I went to www.thegift.com,
which has a Gift Finder assistant to help shoppers make selections.
The site's chief executive, Jeff Swearingen, had told me in a phone
interview that after I entered information about the recipient, the
tool would search through a database of about 500 gifts to come up
with a list of 30 that would be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   So I told the Gift Finder the recipient of the gift (my
husband), his age (over 20) and how much I wanted to spend (any
amount). That last answer was a lie, of course, but to put a price
on love (one of the other options was ``$20 or less'') seemed a
little cold, even for me.
</P>
<P>
   Then I got hung up describing the recipient's personality
traits; none of the eight choices, ranging from ``homebody'' to
``dainty and demure,'' conjured a mental image of my husband. I
settled for ``career-minded,'' but the recommended gifts all
sounded too impersonal, so I gave up. I mean, what would your
husband say if you handed him a three-pound tin of jumbo cashews
($28) and called it a gift?
</P>
<P>
   The problem here, and at a number of other sites that steered me
toward merchandise sold by their merchandising partners, was that
the selection was too limited. It made no sense, to me, to retreat
to the restrictive setting of Internet shopping malls that
showcased a limited number of retailers, like www.bocado.com and
www.foofoo.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ I bought just as much for myself as usual. Maybe more, come to
think of it, because more of the things I wanted were available
online than, say, if I had been standing in the science-kits aisle
of a local toy store. Online, I bought a wooden artists' mannequin
and a political poster from the Cultural Revolution that depicts
cheery Chinese farmers walking home from work.
</P>
<P>
   So far, I have completed about half of my holiday shopping
online. While the experience has been, for the most part, pleasant
_ I'm convinced that I am living in the golden age of shopping _ it
has not changed the fundamental nature of the shopping experience.
No, Ella, it did not miraculously make everyone in our family
Jewish. It didn't even give us all the same last name. Nor did it
help me decide which holiday would be more appropriate for someone
to receive a heather-gray V-neck sweater from www.delias.com (free
shipping on orders of more than $40).
</P>
<P>
   When I reported my conclusions to Professor Miller at University
College London, he said that maybe I had expected too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just finished a new book about the use of the Internet,''
he said, ``and I found that it makes far less difference than
people seem to expect. When the telephone first came out, we
thought it would change basic relationships. Instead, it's just a
tool.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the tool made it easier to buy two sweaters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
