<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Nov. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Milder weather will spread east from the Plains reaching the
southern Great Lakes and Middle Atlantic states by Thursday
afternoon. High pressure centered over the Carolinas will circulate
the warmer air toward southern New England Friday. Sunshine will
abound Thursday from the southwest Plains to the central Atlantic
seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a mound of frigid air will push southeastward from
Quebec into northern New England. Clouds and a few patches of light
snow will develop over the higher terrain and in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore winds will bring ocean clouds and perhaps a shower to
eastern Florida. More humid air streaming north into Texas should
produce fog in the hill country. Despite strengthening winds from
the south, which will gust to 35 miles an hour, bright and
unseasonably warm conditions will cover the central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance developing over Nebraska will begin to cause
inclement weather in the upper Plains. Showers will commence in the
central Dakotas in the afternoon, but farther west, rain will
change to snow with a few inches likely in eastern Montana and
western North Dakota. Snow showers will linger in the higher
elevations of Wyoming, eastern Utah and western Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Much cooler air will be the rule in the Rockies. High pressure
cresting over Idaho will keep temperatures near seasonal levels.
The interior Southwest will turn cooler while offshore winds will
bring sunshine to southern California. Breezes from the south will
direct milder, dry air into the Northwest, but clouds will increase
ahead of cold front off the Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Lenny's Legacy
</P>
<P>
   With a central barometric pressure of 27.55 inches on Wednesday,
Hurricane Lenny became not only the strongest November hurricane of
record, but also one of the most powerful storms in the northeast
Caribbean. The tempest rapidly intensified Wednesday in a part of
the sea that usually finds hurricanes weakening. Most storms are
just entering the Caribbean from the east when they encounter a
band of high-level winds from the west that inhibit their
development. Instead, Lenny was aided by this wind flow and
strengthened further as it moved east through the northern Leeward
Islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2702 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SHOPPING-CHARITY-     11-17 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-CHARITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE ELECTRONIC CONSUMERS CAN GIVE AS WELL AS RECEIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(One of a series of articles on online holiday shopping) 
(jt) 
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-Commerce may do many things, but wiping out world hunger won't
be among them. Nonetheless, the anticipated droves of consumers
heading online this holiday season may come across a proliferation
of charity malls and other Web-based programs that offer
opportunities to donate to a worthy cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet shopping is good for philanthropy,'' said Mark
Rovner, director of CMS Interactive, a Web consultancy for
charitable organizations based in Arlington, Va. ``People who've
bought five or more items online are more likely to give online as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most prevalent and convenient ways holiday shoppers
can make donations while they shop on the Internet is through
charity malls, including iGive.com, 4Charity.com and
Greatergood.com. These sites are set up to let consumers buy
products from leading online merchants and designate a charity to
receive a percentage of the money spent. When a shopper registers
at iGive (www.igive.com/html/intro.cfm), for example, then heads to
the American Greetings site to buy a stack of Christmas cards,
American Greetings will contribute up to 15 percent of the purchase
to a selected cause.
</P>
<P>
   The charity mall model also extends to portals that do not
necessarily have philanthropy as their focus. When shoppers
register at Zipple.com, for example, &UR;  &LR; a new Jewish portal
(www.zipple.com), a percentage of the proceeds from the products
they buy at Zipple links will be donated to Jewish charities like
the Jewish Federation of Chicago and the Jewish Federation of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Although the idea of giving till you drop may have an appeal,
some charity malls keep part of the proceeds to pay for their
overhead. In addition, many online merchants who participate in
such programs require minimum purchases before the charity receives
its portion of the proceeds. As a result, experts say there are
more effective ways to donate money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen whether any of the charity portals are
going to reach critical mass,'' Rovner said. ``I think the
Internet's real promise is for facilitating direct relationships
with the charities themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of such online charitable programs say even
incremental sums of money gathered from consumers while they shop
online are worth seeking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's money that wouldn't otherwise be going to the charities
to begin with,'' said Dan Langan, a spokesman for the National
Charities Information Bureau in Manhattan. ``If they can give while
shopping at L.L. Bean, that's all to the good.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the charity malls, a number of sites let shoppers
direct rebates, gift certificates and rewards to charitable
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dash.com, a virtual mall at www.dash.com where 100 retailers
offer 5 percent to 25 percent discounts on their products, will
give consumers the option of donating the money saved to one of
four charities: the American Cancer Society, Greenpeace, the United
Way of America or the World Wildlife Federation, beginning
Thanksgiving Day. Dash charges no administrative fees, and the
charities receive the entire amount of the discounts, said Andrew
Surwilo, Dash's vice president for partnership marketing.
</P>
<P>
   _ GiftSpot.com (www.giftspots.com/Giftspot/default.asp.) sells
gift certificates for retailers, including eToys and Sharper Image.
Shoppers can apply the full amount (or the change) to charities
like the American Lung Association and Easter Seals.
</P>
<P>
   _ ClickRewards.com, a site that uses air miles as a reward for
consumers who shop at one of 60 retail partners at
www.clickrewards.com, will match every dollar donated to CARE, Dads
and Daughters, Rainforest Action Network, the Special Olympics and
Unicef with two ClickMiles, which are redeemable for frequent-flier
miles and upgrades at nine airlines.
</P>
<P>
   _ MyPoints.com rewards its members by giving points for
responding to retail advertisements on its site
(www.mypoints.com/index.html). Members who usually apply their
points toward gift certificates to retailers like Macy's and Barnes
&AMP; Noble can turn their points into cash to be donated to the
American Red Cross or the Toys for Tots Foundation through the end
of December.
</P>
<P>
   Online gift catalogs produced by smaller nonprofit organizations
like the Heifer Project (catalog.heifer.org) and World Vision
(www.worldvisiongifts.org/worldvision/appeals.nsf/stable/agc) allow
shoppers to make donations in someone's name as a gift without
having to shop at another online retailer. The Heifer Gift catalog
features a selection of animals, birds and trees that can be bought
for a family in need in any of the 60 countries it sponsors. At the
World Vision site, shoppers can buy animals, sponsor a child or
donate money toward the distribution of clothing and food.
</P>
<P>
   Other gift catalogs, including One-Nest.com (www.onenest.com),
which goes live in December, and World2Market.com showcase and sell
artwork, jewelry and crafts made by artisans around the world
(www.world2market.com). Both organizations work with nonprofit
organizations to help artisans establish businesses over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers who are low on funds or just browsing can head to the
Hunger Site (www.hungersite.com), where it's not necessarily the
thought, but the click that counts. Hitting the Donate Free Food
button will call up a page of banner advertisements from companies
including Games2Learn and ProFlowers. Each company pays the Hunger
Site a half-cent every time its advertisement appears, enough to
buy a quarter-cup of rice for the United Nations World Food
Program, which serves 80 countries. The combined sponsors add up to
about three cents for each click, ultimately generating 100 tons of
food each week, said John Breen, a computer programmer based in
Bloomington, Ind., who opened the site in June.
</P>
<P>
   Before you participate in any online giving program, the
National Charities Information Bureau recommends searching the Web
site for clearly stated privacy policies, detailed descriptions of
how the money is sent to the charity and information on how to get
in contact with the charities directly.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau provides reports on each of the charities it
evaluates. Consumers can go to its Web site (www.ncib.org) or call
(212) 929-6300 to order reports for $9.95 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
