u a BC-CIR-SHOPPING-HANDHELD     11-17 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-HANDHELD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BEYOND THE PALM PILOT: NEW BRANDS AND FEATURES FOR PDAs  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to personal digital assistants, ``Hey, beam me your
number'' might become the most popular line in singles bars before
too long. With the success of the Palm Pilot line, the era of the
personal digital assistant has truly arrived. Features have
increased, prices have decreased and the devices are becoming
ubiquitous in certain circles. Think about how many of your friends
have innocently purchased one and then become wholly engulfed by a
new love and a cult-like zeal, caressing the device at frequent
intervals and scouring the Web for hot new applications to download
and lovingly install.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the peaceful era of the PDA may be ending, a victim of the
gadget's success. There are so many new features being added _ tons
of RAM, wireless communications capabilities and interchangeable
expansion modules, for example _ that today's PDA may be
unrecognizable in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Consider its history: The first two models of the Palm Pilot,
both released by U.S. Robotics in 1996, each had less than a
megabyte of RAM within their square gray plastic cases. But the
Pilot was a winner because of its ease of use, the speed and
flexibility of its operating system, its ability to synchronize
easily with a desktop computer (Windows or Macintosh) and its
fairly accurate handwriting recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Three years and several names and models later, the trusty Palm
Pilot _ or just Palm, as most of the new ones are called _ has
become a must-have accessory for everyone from fashion mavens to
stockbrokers. For those who want a truly pocket-size PDA that
wrangles their contact and schedule information with blazing speed
while still leaving plenty of zip and room for scads of other
programs, Palm Computing offers a range of Palm models and prices.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has taken the opposite tack with its PDA operating
system, Windows CE, which it offers to hardware manufacturers like
Casio and Compaq. While the Palm provided a platform that expanded
to handle different models with thousands of software applications,
Windows CE devices try to cram an entire Windows desktop inside a
PDAs tiny plastic frame. Mobile professionals who need multimedia
and a familiar computing environment for the road may want to
consider one of the Windows CE devices. Some of the newer models
will let you play audio files, view full-color images and, if you
have the right equipment, even record your own mini-movies.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you choose among PDAs, knowing that, as with personal
computers, a new platform or feature may leave you technologically
stranded? One alternative may be the Visor, the recently introduced
handheld organizer that uses the popular Palm operating system and
has some nice features of its own, like the Springboard cartridge
slot on the back that expands the unit's functions. Cartridges that
will let you turn the Visor into an MP3 player, a multicity travel
guide and a video-game player are out or in the works. For users
investing in the future, the Visor mixes Palm power with room to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your needs in terms of pocket computing, there is bound
to be something out there that will fit your needs this holiday
season. And with miniature computers becoming smaller and faster
with each generation, it seems as if it won't be too long before
they will be tiny and indispensable enough to be directly implanted
into the brain (although the add-on cartridges might be a little
uncomfortable).
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   SOME POPULAR PDAs
</P>
<P>
   1. PALM VX  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the major complaints about the Palm Vx's predecessor, the
Palm V, was it came with only two measly megabytes of RAM
installed. Ample RAM is important for storing the things that
really make the Palm a vital tool: third-party programs. The Palm
Vx fixes that problem by giving users eight megabytes of memory in
that same wafer-thin, anodized-aluminum case. While this model does
not offer built-in wireless connectivity and instant Internet
access, as Palm Computing's Palm VII model does, the Palm Vx is
small and robust enough to make itself indispensable for those with
a budget large and robust enough to handle its $449 price tag.
Those who still pine for wireless access might want to hold on
until early next year, when OmniSky Corp. and AT&AMP;T will roll out a
wireless modem and Internet services for Palm V-series users.
</P>
<P>
   2. HANDSPRING VISOR DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   Although Handspring's new Visor, which runs on the Palm OS, may
seem like a budget version of the Palm, it has an ace up its
sleeve: the Springboard slot, which handles cartridges containing
games, reference guides and MP3 players. Although there are not
very many Springboard cartridges on the market yet, there are
plenty in the works. The most expensive model, the Visor Deluxe,
sells for $249 and comes with eight megabytes of RAM, a built-in
microphone, USB connectivity, a leather case and the cradle needed
to synchronize the device with a desktop computer. All the Visor
models work with both Windows and Macintosh systems.
</P>
<P>
   3. CASSIOPEIA E-105
</P>
<P>
   Color screens are a popular reason for picking a Windows CE
device over a Palm OS device, and the Cassiopeia E-105 screen seems
brighter and crisper than those of its CE competitors. The
expensive ($599) E-105 is also a versatile multimedia device; it
comes with a CD of audio and video programs that let you play music
and watch film clips after you have finished scheduling your
appointments for the day in the Pocket Outlook program that comes
with the unit. The Cassiopeia E-105 has 32 megabytes of RAM and a
Compact Flash card slot on the back for expansion modules. One nice
add-on: Casio's JK-710DC digital movie camera card for $299; it
lets you make your own tiny color movies, which can be exported to
your desktop machine.
</P>
<P>
   4. RHINOSKIN TITANIUM SLIDER
</P>
<P>
   Once you have sunk your money and all your personal data into
your trusty PDA, the last thing you want to do is to drop it on the
cold hard ground and watch its screen shatter. The new Titanium
Slider case from Rhinoskin ($99.95) for Palm computers has a
pewter-colored industrial finish on its hard outer case and a
neoprene inner lining to absorb shocks on the inside. True to its
name, the Slider's cover smoothly opens and slides under the back
for easy access to your machine.
</P>
<P>
   5. DOONEY &AMP; BURKE LEATHER PALM V CASE
</P>
<P>
   If your taste runs to the classic, try one of Dooney &AMP; Burke's
fine leather cases for Palm organizers. The Palm V case ($49.95)
comes in several colors. Other covers fit the larger Palms and
pagers.
</P>
<P>
   6. STOWAWAY THINK OUTSIDE
</P>
<P>
   Getting lots of text into a handheld computer is difficult and
tedious. The new Stowaway from Think Outside ($99) is a full-size
keyboard that folds up to the size of a handheld and can fit in a
pocket. It's the perfect accessory for a Palm V, and versions are
in the works for the Visor and the Compaq Aero 2100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1733EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
