u a BC-CHILDREN-TV-HNS &LR;      11-17 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-TV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS CHILDREN ARE HOODED ON TV, COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICKI HADDOCK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Children spend so many hours watching
television, playing video games and the like that media use could
qualify as their full-time job, a study released Wednesday shows.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the Kaiser Family Foundation finds that the typical
American child spends more than 38 hours a week as a ``media
consumer'' in a home that averages three televisions, three tape
players, three radios, two VCRs, two CD players, a video game
player and a computer, as well as newspapers, magazines and comic
books.
</P>
<P>
   Children are less likely to live in a home with just one
television than in a house with five or more. Forty-two percent of
the children surveyed reported that a television is on at home
``most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The study showed that a third of young children and two-thirds
of older children have televisions in their bedrooms. More than a
third of all children have their own VCRs and/or video game
players, and about one in six has a bedroom computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to look at this research and not be hit square in
the face by the sheer amount of media that all kids use,'' said
Drew Altman, president of the Kaiser Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The study is based on a representative sampling of 3,155
children ages 2-18 and was compiled based on school questionnaires,
in-home interviews and weeklong media-use diaries. It is the first
extensive study that takes into account not just television but the
full spectrum of media. It did not analyze or judge content - just
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser officials indicated, however, that the amount of time the
children spent with the various media is not cumulative, in that
the children sometimes did two things at the same time, such as
reading while listening to the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that the typical child spends 5 1/2 hours per
day using media, and that television still overshadows all the
other options. Despite widespread access to computers, fewer than
half of children use a computer each day, and they spend very
little time doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Television viewing accounted for 2 hours and 46 minutes per day,
followed by listening to CDs or tapes (45 minutes); reading
magazines, books, comics and newspapers (44 minutes); listening to
the radio (39 minutes); using the computer for fun (21 minutes);
playing video games (20 minutes); and using the Internet (8
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Supervision is often minimal or nonexistent. Half of the
children surveyed do not have any parental rules limiting their
time in front of the television or the kinds of programs they may
watch. For children 8 and older, 61 percent said they watch what
they want, when they want.
</P>
<P>
   Altman contends that the media saturation of childhood merits
special attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how these kids will relate to nature and to
real human relationships,'' he said. ``What happens when they drive
to a mountaintop and take in a spectacular view: Will they get it,
or will it not move fast enough for them?''
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Children from poor, single-parent, black or Hispanic families
are more likely to be heavy television watchers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Children who watch a lot of television also spend more time
reading on average than children who watch less television.
</P>
<P>
   _ Four out of five children will read or be read to in a typical
day, not counting school or homework, but they still spend five
times as much time in front of a television or computer screen as
they do reading. And the older they get, the less they read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1733EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
