<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS, HANUKKAH AND KWANZAA: THE VIRTUAL TRADITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., N.C., Mich., Ore.) (rk) 
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Religious holidays abound at this time of year, but so do
holiday Web sites, which means you don't have to take a course in
comparative religion to figure out what to buy for what occasion or
to simply satisfy your curiosity about celebrations of Christmas,
Kwanzaa and Hanukkah.
</P>
<P>
   Searches for Christmas topics typically yield thousands of
vendors, family pages and other types of home pages. Several sites
explore the meaning of Christmas and how it is celebrated around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   A Holy Christmas 1999 has dozens of pages and links
(www.Rockies.net/spirit/sermons/christmaspage.html). There are
biblical accounts, Advent calendars, songs, sermons, classic
stories, games, articles on holiday stress and pages on Christmas
customs in Mexico, Germany, Poland and Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the personal pages that are linked to the Holy Christmas
site no longer exist, but it is still an excellent resource for a
variety of information.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Eternal, from the Lattimer Memorial Methodist Church
in Belton, S.C., explains the origins of Christmas traditions like
Santa Claus, candy canes and placing candles in windows
(Members.carol.net/asmsmsks/xristmas.htm).
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Recipe.com (www.Christmasrecipe.com/) has everything
from cranberry salad to hot spiced cider, as well as multiple
recipes for fruitcake.
</P>
<P>
   The history and care of Christmas trees, holly, mistletoe,
poinsettias and other holiday plants are explored in an article on
About.com called ``The Botany of Christmas'' 
(Botany.miningco.com/education/scilife/botany/library/weekly/aa12239
7.htm).
</P>
<P>
   The Web also has sites for finding exotic holiday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Shop, for instance
(www.Therussianshop.com/russhop/christmas/christmas.htm), sells
brooches, cards based on historic Russian lacquered box paintings
and handmade nesting dolls, like those of Grandfather Frost and a
family of penguins.
</P>
<P>
   The Iguana site offers art items from around the world,
including Mexican tin Christmas ornaments and European blown-glass
ornaments (St14.yahoo.com/iguanacgs/christmas.html).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Internet has opened the borders for Christmas speeches
from around the world. Anglophiles and British expatriates can
watch Queen Elizabeth's annual address on the BBC site
(News.bbc.co.uk).
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa is celebrated for seven days beginning Dec. 26.
Festivals.com is a good starting point for learning about the
holiday (www.festivals.com/kwanzaa/). It has links to several other
Web sites, including the official Kwanzaa page, which begins with a
greeting from Dr. Maulana Karenga, who started Kwanzaa in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   There are also links to pages for events to be held in North
Carolina, Washington and New York; a Swahili dictionary (there are
more than 40 words for gift), and recipes for the Kwanzaa feast,
including two for African vegetable stew and another for futari, a
dish of squash and yams simmered in coconut milk.
</P>
<P>
   Melanet (www.melanet.com/kwanzaa/) also has extensive
information, including a detailed description of Kwanzaa's rituals.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a room for online chat about the seven principles
that form the holiday's core teachings: unity, self-determination,
collective work and responsibility, cooperative economics, purpose,
creativity and faith.
</P>
<P>
   Most Kwanzaa sites suggest giving educational gifts. The Melanet
page has a list of books about Kwanzaa for children, and a page at
the site of the public library in Flint, Mich., has a bibliography
that includes videos and fiction and nonfiction titles for children
and adults
(www.flint.lib.mi.us/fpl/resources/holidays/kwanzaa.html).
</P>
<P>
   There are many places on the Internet to purchase menorahs for
the eight nights of Hanukkah, including Jewish Source
(www.jewishsource.com/chanukkah/) and the Simon Wiesenthal Center
Museum of Tolerance (www.wiesenthal.com/bstore/galleria.html).
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution (or kaution) when searching the Web for
information on Hanukkah: it is variously spelled Hanukah, Hannukah,
Chanukah and Chanuka. Chanuka.com (www.chanuka.com/index.shtml) and
Holidays.net (www.holidays.net/chanukah/) offer pages for learning
more about the holiday, with history, recipes, games and links to
other sites.
</P>
<P>
   Two promising sites are still under construction _ and they had
better hurry, since Hanukkah begins at sundown on Dec. 3. Virtual
Jerusalem will offer children's pages and information on holiday
customs (www.vjholidays.com/chanukah/index.htm), and Chanukah 99
says it will have menorah lighting ceremonies around the world,
Hanukkah trivia and games with spinning dreidels
(www.chanukah98.com/).
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Communication Network (www.jcn18.com) offers a
slightly irreverent look at the holiday (search on ``Hanukkah''),
with songs like ``Hanukkah in Santa Monica'' and ``Macabees Are
Coming to Town.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also recipes for latkes, including one with jalapenos
and another with crab meat, which is a prohibited food for Jews who
follow kosher dietary laws. ``Must be the Alabama Baptist
influence,'' the page's editor notes.
</P>
<P>
   There are several calendars that note other December holidays.
The Multnomah County Library in Oregon has a comprehensive
diversity calendar
(www.multnomah.lib.or.us/lib/divcal/december.html) that includes
the start of the Islamic month of fasting, Ramadan (Dec. 9), and
Las Posadas (Dec. 16), a Mexican holiday leading up to Christmas
that re-enacts the journey of Mary and Joseph to Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Many holiday Web sites have links to sites like Blue Mountain
Arts, where you can send a free e-mail card for Kwanzaa, Hanukkah
or Christmas (www.bluemountain.com/eng/seasonal/).
</P>
<P>
   Blue Mountain Arts has many seasonal cards, including one with a
dog, a cat and a mouse holding paws before a rising sun, in the
spirit of peace on earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
