<HEADLINE>
TOOLS THAT LEVEL THE FIELD AND EASE THE RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is one in a series of articles on online shopping)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN C. MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the business traveler _ the Road Warrior or the home-based
worker, there is a wide range of useful gadgets that can help level
the competitive playing field or at least provide some fun.
</P>
<P>
   The trend as always is to make things smaller, faster and more
powerful, but also to combine functions and cut the cord. Wireless
is the buzzword. High-technology companies are releasing products
and services that deliver information from one of the wireless
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Those products and services include everything from interactive
pagers to Web surfing on a cell phone. You can check your e-mail
from the back of a cab, get real-time stock information on a pager
or bounce a signal off a satellite with a handheld computer to
pinpoint your location.
</P>
<P>
   Laptop computers, the Road Warrior's best friend, have gotten
lighter, smaller, more powerful and _ finally _ cheaper. (The
recent earthquakes in Taiwan may have disrupted the shipment of key
components enough to send prices back up.)
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of a DVD the new batch of laptops can double
as a portable office and a traveling entertainment center: audio
CDs or DVD movies counteract the limited choices on airplanes or
the expensive hotel fare.
</P>
<P>
   For those who work at home, the trend is to save space and be
efficient, making devices like flat-panel monitors and all-in-one
copier-printer-fax machines popular. The goal is to use these
devices to compensate for not having the support services you would
if you worked in a large company.
</P>
<P>
   Less technological but useful are items like: screen wipes,
canned air to get the dust out of keyboards, personalized mouse
pads and books about anything but computers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. GBC GUARDIAN CROSS-CUT 35x &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shredders have come out of the wastebasket and onto the desktop.
The self-contained GBC Guardian Cross-Cut 35x ($99.99) shreds three
to four sheets nicely into 400 unreadable chips (dumped into an
enclosed drawer that must be emptied frequently).
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't want to clutter up their desktop with a
shredder, the device can be mounted on the wall. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. DIGITAL PERSONA U.ARE.U FINGERPRINT RECOGNITION SYSTEM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now you can forget your password, again. For $99, the U.are.U
system from Digital Persona can read your fingerprint from any
angle and compare it with a securely stored image.
</P>
<P>
   The USB system, which does not require any power supply of its
own, can protect any or all of your applications, e-mail accounts
and Web pages. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. CASIO ALGEBRA FX 2.0 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As soon as handheld calculators appeared in classrooms,
educators warned that students would turn into mathematical
invalids. With the release of the Algebra FX 2.0, Casio
acknowledges that the doomsayers were partly right.
</P>
<P>
   The $149 calculator, designed for students in grades seven and
up, teaches by allowing students to work out the solution step by
step to math problems and corrects their efforts along the way. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. COREX CARDSCAN EXECUTIVE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Corex CardScan Executive, which retails for $299, plus
$14.95 for shipping and handling, solves the problem of getting
business cards out of your wallet and into your database.
</P>
<P>
   Connected to your personal computer or laptop, it can read a
surprising number of idiosyncratic business cards and gets the
information correct. One new feature in the software allows the
device to go online and update all the changes in area codes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   5. TEC-2000 LAMP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Working at home often starts with the search for enough
electrical outlets. One solution is the power strip, and a lot of
crawling under your desk. A more elegant solution is a lamp ($145)
from Ki-tov Lamps of Brooklyn that puts the power strip in its base
along with a data port for modems. Best of all, there is enough
light to see what you are doing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. SIEMENS POCKET READER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Text scanners, like the Pocket Reader from Siemens ($99.95), are
starting to resemble highlighters. Hold the Pocket Reader upright,
roll it over a sentence, then download the data to a Windows or
Macintosh computer. A screen lets you check on the captured text. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. CREATIVE LABS VIDEO BLASTER WEBCAM GO &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Video Blaster Webcam Go is a standout among a slew of relatively
inexpensive video cameras made to work through a PC. The Webcam Go,
a $150 device made by Creative Labs, does just that _ it goes,
breaking away from its PC base. It can snap still pictures and
capture snippets of video. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. VTECH E-MAIL POSTBOX &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E-mail-only devices offer low-cost text e-mail access without a
PC _ no Web surfing, no graphics, no attachments. The e-mail
PostBox from Vtech plugs into a standard phone jack and offers easy
use, large letters on a clear screen, a full-size keyboard and
compact design. The device is $99.99 and can be ordered only
through the Web site (www.vtechworld.com) or by calling (888)
468-8324; an e-mail account costs around $8 a month. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Road &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. COMPAQ ARMADA M300 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Compaq Armada M300 takes a lot of the compromise out of
choosing a laptop. At about $1,899, it manages to deliver a compact
system with a nearly full-size keyboard and a decent-size screen.
Even with a portable docking station, it weighs only about four
pounds. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. LODIS EXEC-ON-THE-GO &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting a computer off your shoulder calls for a case on wheels.
The Lodis Exec-On-The-Go models, which range in price from $275 to
$400, bring style and elegance to the pedestrian computer roller
bag. The all-leather bag does not look like a computer bag; it
looks like what it is, a fine piece of luggage. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. SHARP TELMAIL TM-20 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Using the Pocketmail system, the Sharp Telmail TM-20 allows you
to send and receive e-mail without modems, cables or antennas: just
hold a Pocketmail device up to any phone (home, office, cordless,
pay phones, analog cellular) and the messages are sent and received
through barely audible transmission signals. The lightweight
Telmail also acts as an electronic organizer that connects to your
PC. The price ranges from $99 to $120, and a Pocketmail account
(through www.pocketmail.com) costs $9.95 a month for unlimited
access through a toll-free number. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. ELECTROFUEL POWERPAD 160 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like many business travelers, Captain Kirk was always begging
for more power. The PowerPad 160 from Electrofuel ($499), which
sits flat under the laptop, will power a computer for as long as 16
hours. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. OLYMPUS DS-150 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Breaking memory limits on early digital recorders, the Olympus
DS-150 ($199) can hold up to 2 hours and 40 minutes of dictation or
chat, then can easily download the captured words to any PC with a
USB connection. The DS-150 comes packaged with an older version of
IBM's Via Voice software for automatic, although not flawless,
transcription. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. KESTREL 2000 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Web may offer seemingly infinite weather data, but it is not
much good when you are in the middle of nowhere. The $119 Kestrel
2000 (www.kestrelinstruments.com) is effectively a pocket-size
weather station that indicates temperature, wind speed and wind
chill. For an extra $40, the Kestrel 3000 also measures relative
humidity and calculates both the dew point and heat index, the warm
weather version of the wind chill factor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. GARMIN EMAP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Garmin's eMap wants to be the iMac of GPS receivers
(www.garmin.com/eMap.html). Colored a stylish purple-blue and not
much larger than a calculator, the $242.84 unit is more a handheld
map than an electronic compass and includes a base highway map of
North and South America that among other things shows the service
centers coming up. The $300 deluxe version has a computer
connecting cable and additional memory that lets its users download
detailed city maps of major cities from CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
