</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PREVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROAD TO THE FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Joe Drape chooses 16 teams with the weapons and the nerve
to make a run at the Final Four, which will be held at the RCA Dome
in Indianapolis, Ind.) 
(jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; LAST TEAM STANDING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (22-9)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they were the Baby Bruins _ as high spirited and
impetuous off the court as they were talented on it. Now, they are
a year older and boast the most talented 10-man rotation in the
nation. Nine of them started last year because Coach Steve Lavin's
``This-ain't-no-country club'' credo meant playing time was earned
in practice and awarded game-to-game. You want addition by
subtraction? Baron Davis was the NBA's third pick.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Earl Watson takes over for him at point guard, and the
Bruins may be better off for it. Last year, Watson proved he had a
better head than the gifted Davis. He played the most minutes,
scored 13.3 points a game, handed out 4.5 assists, and was UCLA's
best defender as a shooting guard. The Bruins are big: 6-10
sophomores Dan Gadzuric (8.6 points) and Jerome Moiso (10.8) have
moves to go with bulk. They are athletic: sophomores JaRon Rush
(7.3 rebounds) and Ray Young (5.4 points) key a frenetic fast
breaking offense. Freshman Jason Kapono is a 6-7, 3-point shooter.
Leading them to a championship will be Watson, fittingly, a player
John Wooden would have loved to coach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANOTHER THREE FOR INDY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT (34-2)
</P>
<P>
   Can Khalid El-Amin replace Richard Hamilton as the Huskies'
go-to guy, as well as provide the defensive grit of departed Ricky
Moore? No, as UConn found in its opening loss to a less talented
but more committed Iowa squad. He is special college player, but
not superhuman. The trick for the Huskies is becoming even more of
a T-E-A-M than last year's superb edition. Forward Kevin Freeman,
center Jake Voskuhl and guard Albert Mouring were vital role
players on one of the most balanced and unselfish bunches in
college basketball history. Those three need to do more and El-Amin
less if the Huskies are to repeat. The point guard will get his
points and steals, but he's most effective setting up others. The
Huskies' smothering defense will hold the line until someone
develops into a scorer.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPLE (24-11)
</P>
<P>
   Every year the combination of a disciplined offense and a
nettlesome zone defense earns praise for Coach John Chaney at
tournament time. Nobody wants to face the Owls. This time around
the focus will be on Temple's big-time talent. Mark Karcher (13.4
points) has lost 30-pounds and can score as much as Chaney will let
him. Lamont Barnes, 6-10 (12.9 points), and Kevin Lyde, 6-9, are
impenetrable in the blocks. Senior Pepe Sanchez (5.9 assists)
directs, if you can believe it, an explosive Temple team.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA (24-10)
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Guthridge has won the most games ever for a
second-year coach - 58 - but has been under relentless criticism
from the Carolina for essentially not being Dean Smith. The coach
fires back this season with senior Ed Cota directing an up-tempo
attack that was absent last year. Sophomore Jason Capel (9.1
points) is pain free after off-season back surgery, and 7-foot,
265-pound center Brendan Haywood promises to be a more fearsome
presence after a confidence building campaign with the USA's gold
medal-winning World University Games over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOUR KNOCKING ON THE DOOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN (29-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers return four starters, including Southeastern
Conference player of the year Chris Porter, from the team that went
to the round of 16 last year. They will terrorize the South with a
swarming baseline-to-baseline attack. Porter, a 6-7 senior who
averaged 16 points and 8.8 rebounds, owns the inside. He also has
plenty of help from the SEC's best center, 7-0 Mamadou N'diaye, who
blocked 77 shots last year. And point guard Doc Robinson (11.5 and
5.0 assists) runs a deep, balanced offense.
</P>
<P>
   SYRACUSE (21-12)
</P>
<P>
   The Orangeman have all five starters back from a team that was
alternately dazzling and disastrous last year. Center Etan Thomas
was lithe enough with his 6-9, 247-pound frame to block 4 shots a
game and be named Big East defensive player of the year. Jason Hart
(13.9 points, 4.3 assists) is an all-America-caliber point guard.
Ryan Blackwell (11.7) and Damone Brown (9.5) can score. No doubt
they are talented, but now must find a steady heart.
</P>
<P>
   DePAUL (18-13)
</P>
<P>
   Three sophomores figure to return the Blue Demons to the
national stage, including last year's national freshman of the
year, Quentin Richardson. The 6-7 forward is another Mark
Aguirre-type _ an inside-outside player who averaged 19 points and
10 rebounds a game. Bobby Simmons, 6-7, gives them more punch in
the paint, after averaging 11.2 points last season. Finally, 6-9
Lance Williams, the team's second-leading scorer last year at 13.9,
will roam between the wing and center. That's because 7-0 freshman
Steven Hunter is that good. Don't be surprised when they get this
far.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH (28-5)
</P>
<P>
   Hanno Mottola is back; Andre Miller is not. Still, the Utes
remain the-second best team in the West. Mottola, the 6-10 Finnish
center (15.3 points), and 6-7 forward Alex Jensen (12.1 points, 7.6
rebounds, 3.4 assists) are tough-minded finesse players. And Rick
Majerus is one of the most adaptable coaches around. He'll move the
attack inside. Utah will be precise and disciplined. More talented
opponents will beat themselves. The Utes will get themselves deep
into the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EIGHT THAT COULD HANG AROUND LATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OHIO STATE (27-9)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Redd (19.5) and Scoonie Penn (16.9) are the nation's
best backcourt and are intent on returning the Buckeyes to the
Final Four. But it is Kevin Johnson who holds Ohio State's keys to
Indianapolis. The 6-11 senior center managed just 6.4 points and
5.7 rebounds in the regular season before coming alive in the NCAA
tournament with 21 blocked shots. If he begins the year like he
ended it, the Buckeyes contend for the title.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA (22-9)
</P>
<P>
   They're not quite Kentucky, but the Florida Gators have the
thoroughbreds to run Rick Pitino's full-court defense and
bombs-away offense. Skinny sophomore Mike Miller led the Gators in
scoring with 12.2 last year. Sophomore Ted Dupay contributed 11
points, and center Udonis Haslem, undersized at 6-7, pulled down 5
boards a game. He gets help from Donnell Harvery, a 6-8 freshman
who averaged 23.8 in high school and heads another blue chip class
of recruits.
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN STATE (33-5)
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Mateen Cleaves was all set to return the Spartans to
the Final Four. Then he suffered a stress fracture in his right
foot when practice started last month, had surgery, and won't
return until December. Can returning starters Andre Hutson (5.2
rebounds) and Charlie Bell (7.8 points) - along with last year's
super sub, Morris Peterson (13.6 points), hold Michigan State
together in the meantime? Will Cleaves be able to pick up where he
left off. Whatever, it's a tough way to start.
</P>
<P>
   ST. JOHN'S (28-9)
</P>
<P>
   No team in the nation lost as much as the Red Storm did when Ron
Artest decided to turn pro. But St. John's still has sophomore
point guard Erick Barkley (4.7 assists), shooter Bootsy Thornton
(14.9 points) and slasher Lavor Postell (13.1). If Anthony Glover
lives up to his high school promise after sitting out as a
non-academic qualifier, the Red Storm can surprise again.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (27-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats are Autumn's perennial darlings who never quite
bloom in the spring _ they've lost in the second round in the last
three tournaments. The muscle inside returns with 6-9 Kenyon Martin
(2.4 blocked shots) and 6-6 Pete Mickeal (14.9 points) and the
perimeter game should get a boost from freshman Dermarr Johnson - a
6-9 shooter who thought about going pro after averaging 26.9 points
in high school. Maybe this year, the Bearcats live up to
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY (28-9)
</P>
<P>
   If Jamaal Magloire keeps his head better than he did when he
first entered and then withdrew from the NBA draft, the Wildcats
may be dangerous come tournament time. The 6-10 center (66 block
shots) and point guard Saul Smith (Coach Tubby Smith's son) have to
provide the experience for a team that replaces three starters with
very young talent. Among them is the sophomore Tayshaun Prince, who
added 30 pounds to his 6-9 frame, and looks like a better- shooting
Jamal Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE (37-2)
</P>
<P>
   Last year's runner-up for the national title has devolved from a
team for the ages to one that needs aging. Gone early to the NBA
are Elton Brand, Corey Maggette and William Avery. But Coach Mike
Krzyzewski has four new McDonald's all Americans to replace them.
Jason Williams is the first true freshman to start at point guard
for Duke since Bobby Hurley. Carlos Boozer, a 6-9, 260-pounder from
Alaska, bangs inside like Brand. Mike Dunleavy Jr., whose father is
the Portland Trailblazers coach, is a pure shooter. Returning
starters Chris Carrawell and Shane Battier will help develop the
youngsters in a hurry. They lost twice in last week's Coaches
Against Cancer tournament, but will be rounding into form
tournament time.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA (22-7)
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats replace Jason Terry with 5-10 freshman and 22.6
points a game high school scorer Jason Gardner so Arizona's
tradition of back court excellence continues - Damon Stoudamire,
Mike Bibby. The story here is up front: 6-7 sophomores Richard
Jefferson and Michael Wright combined for 25 points a game last
year. They might double that this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIVE WHO WILL DOMINATE THEIR POSITONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Point guard:
</P>
<P>
   Matt Santangelo, Gonzaga, 6-1 senior.
</P>
<P>
   He out Stocktons the Bulldogs' forerunner and future NBA Hall of
Famer John Stockton. He averaged 12 points, five assists and made
35 percent of his three-pointers. As the nation learned when
Gonzaga made it to the Final Eight, a two-handed chest pass can be
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting guard:
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Guyton, Indiana, 6-1, senior
</P>
<P>
   He is a Hoosier's Hoosier who apparently doesn't mind Bobby
Knight as he would have been a first round draft choice in each of
the last two drafts. He averaged 16 points last year on 45 percent
shooting by weaving in an out of a maze of screens. Great range and
can take it down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Center
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mihm, Texas, 7-0, junior
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he showed Tim Duncan-type footwork and soft hands to
average 13.7 points and 11 rebounds. Over the summer, he worked on
his face the basket moves and three point shooting. Biggest knock
is that he doesn't play hard every game. An all out effort will
make him the best college center since, well, Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Power Forward
</P>
<P>
   Mark Madsen, Stanford, 6-9, senior
</P>
<P>
   He's never far from the ball _ when it bounces into the stands
he dives face first to get it. Last year, he put up 13.1 points,
grabbed 9.1 rebounds and shot 60 percent. Most impressive? 109
offensive boards. A more talented Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   Small Forward
</P>
<P>
   Terence Morris, Maryland, 6-9, junior
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he was overshadowed by Steve Francis _ except
statistically. His 15.3 points and 7.1 rebounds is just a hint of
what he can do. Morris was the only player in the premier Atlantic
Coast Conference to finish in the top ten in field goal and free
throw percentage, blocked shots, steals, rebounding and scoring. He
quite possibly is the best all round player in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
