<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACNEIL-BOOK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALIST SINGS PRAISES OF BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SUSAN L. RIFE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The instant and personal communication between an author and a
reader is what appeals to Robert MacNeil about books.
</P>
<P>
   ``In picking up a book, I don't feel condescended to, I don't
feel patronized, I don't feel exploited, I don't feel my
intelligence is being insulted,'' MacNeil said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something very personal that comes from reading that
you don't even get from watching TV. The nearest analogy is the
radio _ you feel you are being spoken to personally. With
broadcasting I feel I'm part of an audience, that I'm a piece of an
audience, often a piece of, as Pauline Kael said, `that jerk
audience.'''
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil, of course, was for nearly 40 years on the other side of
the screen from the broadcast audience, first as an ``NBC News''
correspondent, then as a reporter for the BBC, and then for 20
years as partners with Jim Lehrer on public television's
``MacNeil/Lehrer Report,'' later called ``The MacNeil/Lehrer
NewsHour.''
</P>
<P>
   He retired four years ago to devote much of his time to writing,
although he still works with MacNeil/Lehrer Productions on
documentary projects.
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil's recently published novel, ``Breaking News,'' draws on
his 40 years of journalism for a look at television news, which, to
judge from the novel, is in a sorry state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the problem: There's been a huge cultural shift away
from early evening news,'' MacNeil said in a telephone interview
from his New York City home.
</P>
<P>
   Because viewership of networks' early evening news programs has
dropped, there is a vacuum of national news programs late in the
evening. Fragmentation of the audience through cable television has
forced network television news shows to ``look over their shoulder
all the time at what cable might be doing to suck viewers out of
their orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil's response of late has been to work with MacNeil/Lehrer
Productions to develop an 11 p.m. nightly news program ``that would
be an alternative to local news.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite his continuing involvement with the broadcast world,
MacNeil, 68, prefers the written word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started off at the beginning of this life wanting to be a
creative writer,'' he said, adding that after more than 40 years of
journalism he realized ``I want to go back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that I'd just done it long enough and I longed for days
when I wasn't forced to every morning fill my head up with that
stuff. You have to be up-to-date. Now I can read it in the
newspaper, or not, as I choose. To have command of your own
attention is a wonderful gift, to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside of MacNeil's retirement is what he calls
``deinstitutionalization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The routines of television, especially if you do daily
television _ it institutionalizes you in many ways. And then you
also have enormous assistance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on a recent trip to Germany for work on a
documentary about the 10-year anniversary of the fall of the Berlin
Wall, he told his guide he would send a copy of a book he had
written about the building of the wall. Sending the book meant
spending half a day finding a copy, wrapping it for mailing,
filling out customs forms and waiting in line at the post office _
all tasks an assistant would have handled in the ``MacNeil/Lehrer''
days.
</P>
<P>
   Mundane tasks aside, MacNeil loves the writing life and
advocates the reading life to people of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``A book is a product of a single mind, usually, and that
creates a different kind of communication from what is created by
many people,'' he said. ``What a reader is getting in 250 pages of
a book is the distilled creative energy of one person over hundreds
and hundreds of hours. You are getting intimately the product of a
human brain, which may be one of the best brains that's ever walked
the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider that you pay $25 for a hardcover book, and
you're getting the gift of one person's intellectual energy over
hundreds and hundreds of hours, that's a tremendous gift to pass on
to somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Books, once people are hooked on them, ``have an appeal that is
unlike anything else,'' MacNeil said. ``A book, in a way, is a
conversation highly organized and, one hopes, beautifully presented
_ a conversation for hours at a time with the most interesting
person you could possibly meet at that time, and alone with you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
