<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-COLE-LITHOGRAPH-NYT &LR;      11-17 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLE-LITHOGRAPH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP A RIVER, BEGGING FOR PAINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CATSKILL, N.Y. _ The limestone tablet was lying face down, a
mere doorstop in the dusty remains of Thomas Cole's studio here. On
a late-summer afternoon, an architectural historian visiting the
cobwebby old studio in back of the house picked it up and turned it
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was astonished to find a drawing on it,'' said the
historian, Barksdale Maynard, who is researching the life of Cole,
the father of the Hudson River School of landscape painting. The
drawing he discovered was in fact a romantic pencil sketch of a
castle, done by Cole on a lithographic stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cole died in the 1840s,'' he said. ``It's astounding that this
artwork would be just kicking around for 150 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The sketch is only moderately valuable _ the image is not fully
realized _ but it is ``very significant, very important and still
rather mysterious'' as it relates to the undocumented history of
the house and studio, Maynard said.
</P>
<P>
   While the stone is now safe with one of the house's trustees,
Maynard fears for the Cole house itself. Although it has received a
financial boost from the state and a fund-raising campaign, the
project needs more than $3.5 million of an estimated $4 million to
restore the house and grounds and establish a museum there.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the Cole house is not grand or full
of priceless antiques; in fact, it is viewed by some as kind of a
poor relation of Olana, the Moorish mansion just across the river,
conceived and built by Cole's student Frederic Edwin Church,
another master of the school.
</P>
<P>
   But the restoration of the Cole house, known as Cedar Grove, is
not about aesthetics. Its backers do not want it to be just another
house museum, treasured only for its celebrity associations and its
pretty window swags. They see it as a significant cultural and
historical link to one of the nation's most important artistic
movements. ``Without Cole's role as the first to rhapsodize about
the Hudson River and the wilderness in general, in his paintings
and in his teachings, the story is vastly diminished,'' said
Darlene Lee Downing, executive director of the Catskill Center for
Conservation and Development.
</P>
<P>
   There is a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the house is closed to the public and is probably
past what might be called the ``fixer upper'' stage. In fact, it
may have reached the next stage: wreck. The porch is sagging; the
plaster walls are cracked; an old wooden shutter bangs open and
shut, knocking against the brick facade of the 1810 building, a
yellow federal villa.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, Cole descendants who were still living there
offered to sell it to the state for $125,000, with its furnishings
_ including what would now be valuable Cole paintings. But the
state refused.
</P>
<P>
   That decision was not as ridiculous as it sounds today. The
Hudson River painters were then out of vogue. Take the famous Cole
landscape ``The Oxbow,'' at the Metropolitan Museum. Worth more
than $5 million now, it probably would have fetched less than
$250,000 at the time, several dealers and curators say.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the paintings and furniture _ originals, in many cases _
were eventually piled up on the lawn and sold off in 1979, when the
descendants moved to Florida. The house was then bought by the
Catskill Center, which promptly arranged for an easement to protect
the buildings and the land and then sold the property to the Thomas
Cole Foundation, whose principals included the Manhattan gallery
owner Ira Spanierman, a specialist in Cole and other Hudson River
artists. (This week, Spanierman called the house ``the spiritual
birthplace of American landscape painting.'') But the foundation
let the house languish. In 1998, it agreed to sell it for $92,500
to the Greene County Historical Society, which appointed a
committee to oversee the restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been watching this house disintegrate for 20 years,'' Ms.
Downing said. Looking at the two front parlors, with their marble
fireplaces and high ceilings, she said she hoped that at least
those two rooms would be open to the public by summer, with some
historical material.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a little money,'' she said, ``and we'll see what
color is appropriate to the period.'' Furnishing the rooms is
tricky, she said, because so little of the furniture is original.
(A roomful of late Victorian carved rosewood, upholstered in pink,
is hardly consistent with the 1810 house or with the tenure of
Cole, who died in 1848.)
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bernadette Castro, the state commissioner of parks,
recreation and historic preservation, said the state had recently
turned down another chance to buy the Cole house, because the
restoration would cost so much. Her agency is overwhelmed with the
ambitious restoration of Olana, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she was excited about the Cole house, especially
when she thought of the two houses as part of an assemblage of
artists' homes. ``Although we won't own both of them, we look
towards a link through some kind of interpretation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that her office had just given $192,500 to the Cole
project, money that was more than matched by private contributions.
But the state and private contributions come to less than $500,000,
and the state money, Ms. Castro said, can be used only for exterior
work.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the money for the interior come from? Can the Friends
of Olana help the friends of the Cole house?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they're supportive of our efforts,'' said Raymond
Beecher, a retired schoolteacher who is the Greene County historian
and a vital force behind the efforts to restore the Cole house.
Beecher, 82, contributed $130,000 of the private matching funds,
although, as he put it, he is ``not a millionaire.'' The Olana
supporters, he explained, are ``busy raising their own money.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Friends of Olana is trying to raise $20 million for its
own house, the grounds and the collections, said Sara Griffen, the
executive director. And although the idea of an ``artists' trail''
that would include the Cole house has come up, ``other priorities
have taken over,'' she said. Asked if her group might help raise
money for the Cole house, Ms. Griffen said it was ``outside the
purview of our mission statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs at Cedar Grove, the front room where Cole painted in
the winter, and where he died, needs only some paint and plaster.
And this fall, the house received a new furnace. Thanks to the
state grant and the matching donations, it will probably also
receive a new roof.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``it's still very far away from being saved,''
Maynard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
