<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-GAMES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMES TO SUIT EVERY PLATFORM AND EVERY TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This is one in a series of articles on online shopping) 
(th) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Industry sources on Wall Street and in Silicon Valley have
informed me that Santa has signed co-branded content and e-commerce
agreements with Sony, Nintendo and Sega, promising to drive traffic
in return for sales commissions and (most important) stock options.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt this is a smart strategic arrangement for all
concerned, considering the volume of video-game requests to Santa's
headquarters and the difficulty of keeping track of every hardware
manufacturer and software publisher. (At the North Pole, as
everywhere, good database administrators are in short supply.)
</P>
<P>
   Santa has assured analysts that wish-list processing and
Christmas Eve delivery will meet or exceed traditional standards of
quality and reliability. But which gifts light up the television or
computer screen this holiday season, that's up to you.
</P>
<P>
   With three video-game consoles on the market (and hundreds of
millions of dollars being spent to promote them), the burning
question is which system to buy, especially because that decision
also commits you to a particular library of software titles.
Despite the surfeit of choices, each console has clear strengths
and drawbacks, depending on who you are (or for whom you are
buying).
</P>
<P>
   NINTENDO _ If you're buying for a young child, Nintendo is
probably the best bet. At $99, Nintendo 64 costs three times as
much as a Furby, but it will take much longer to wear out.
Nintendo's software is also skewed to a young audience (under 10
years old) and tends to be less violent than Sega or Sony fare.
There are fewer titles available for Nintendo than for Playstation,
but for parents that is a definite advantage _ there's less to beg
for. And the titles out there make up in quality what they lack in
quantity.
</P>
<P>
   The 900-pound gorilla of Nintendo's Christmas season is Donkey
Kong 64 (published by Nintendo, $69.95, for all ages). Like Mario
and Zelda, Donkey Kong has made the leap to 3-D, and the results
are spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Mario and Zelda, Super Smash Brothers (published by
Nintendo, $49.99, for all ages) features them and other members of
the old-school Nintendo posse in a combat free-for-all, in case
you're in the market for a fighting game.
</P>
<P>
   In the racing category, F-Zero X (published by Nintendo, $29.99,
for all ages) is superb _ although 1080 Snowboarding (published by
Nintendo, $39.99, for all ages) has an edge among extreme-sports
fans. For its innovative play and controls, Glover (published by
Hasbro Interactive, $59.95, for all ages) is a personal favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Lest one forget the Pokemon phenomenon, there is the Nintendo 64
cartridge called Pokemon Snap, in which the player scours a
tropical island on a photographic expedition to document the
creatures. And, of course, there is the original Game Boy
capturing-and-collecting cartridge, which now comes in three
flavors: red, blue and yellow. Different-colored cartridges feature
the same game but contain a different menagerie of creatures. The
idea is that you link your Game Boy with one that has a different
cartridge and exchange Pokemon until everyone has a complete
collection.
</P>
<P>
   If your child argues that he or she needs more than one Pokemon
cartridge to complete a collection, feel free to point out that
players are meant to acquire Pokemon by trading with other people
and that just buying another cartridge is a lazy shortcut and might
even be considered cheating.
</P>
<P>
   Another Nintendo toy to consider is the Game Boy Camera ($59),
which allows the schoolyard set to take thumbnail-size pictures and
add custom effects, then trade the images or turn them into
stickers on a miniature printer, which is sold separately. The
resolution is low, but pixel for pixel, the Game Boy Camera is more
fun than digital cameras with 10 times the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   SONY _ The price of the Playstation has also dropped to $99; it
delivers tremendous video-game bang for the entertainment buck, and
it's probably the best bet for gamers 12 and older. There are
thousands of games in the Playstation library, and the greatest
hits can be had for $19.99 apiece after their initial flush of
popularity has worn off.
</P>
<P>
   With Sony's next-generation console on the horizon, the
Playstation will be singing its swan song this holiday season. But
the Playstation 2 will be backward-compatible _ all the old games
will work on the new system, including this season's hottest games.
The original format is expected to play well into the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   For role-playing fans, there is Final Fantasy 8 (published by
Squaresoft, $49.99, for teen-agers), the latest sprawling epic in
the best-selling series by Squaresoft. Final Fantasy 8 is a big
commitment, falling somewhere between ``The Lord of the Rings'' and
``The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire'' in terms of the time
required to play. But for fans of the genre, it's a no-brainer.
This game is The One.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your aesthetic sensibilities, there are two racing
games worth playing. Wipeout 3 (published by Psygnosis, $39.99, for
all ages) is a rave-inspired future fantasy with a techno
soundtrack. It's a deep-dish slice of graphic design and club
culture, a sly piece of eye candy for the fashion-conscious gamer.
</P>
<P>
   Gran Turismo 2 (published by Sony, $40, for all ages) is less
trendy and more muscular, a spectacularly meaty showcase of
real-world cars, high-performance engines and screeching tires.
Playing Gran Turismo is the automotive equivalent of air guitar.
</P>
<P>
   On the fighting front, there are two ways to go. For spectacle,
Tekken 3 (published by Namco, $27.99, for teen-agers) rules the
Playstation. But for hands-on play and sheer coolness, Fighter
Maker is the champ. Fighter Maker (published by Agetec, $42.99, for
teen-agers) lets you choreograph a fighter from templates or from
scratch, fine-tuning everything from upper cuts to victory taunts.
Tweaking wire-frame models teaches you a lot about computer
animation _ Fighter Maker is more a design exercise than a martial
arts contest. It's more fun to make your own.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to creature breeding and training, Monster Rancher
for Playstation (published by Tecmo, $39.99, for all ages) is among
the quirkiest titles on any platform. The game uses regular music
CDs to ``spawn'' baby monsters. (Playstation reads the audio disc's
number and track lengths and converts that data into monster DNA.)
</P>
<P>
   Once your creature is born, you are responsible for feeding and
training it into a fierce fighting beast to pit against other
monsters in single combat. Monster Rancher is a virtual pet with
teeth, ensuring its appeal to both boys and girls. And for
audiophiles, nothing is more satisfying than seeing what your music
library looks like as a digital zoo.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for an addictive puzzle game, buy Devil Dice
(published by THQ, $39.95, for all ages). It's better than Tetris.
Enough said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SEGA _ If you have to be the first kid on your block to own the
coolest game machine, you'll be celebrating the millennium with
Dreamcast (if you haven't got one already). The Dreamcast is this
year's cutting-edge box, although its processing speed and graphic
capacities will be superseded by next year's Playstation 2.
</P>
<P>
   Sega's top game, bar none, is NFL 2K (published by Sega, $49.95,
all ages), which is the best-looking football game ever. Similarly,
Soul Calibur (published by Namco, $39.99, for teen-agers) is the
best-looking fighting game ever. Many of the other new Dreamcast
titles are arcade conversions, so a trip to the local coin-op
emporium should give you a pretty good test drive.
</P>
<P>
   For something completely different (and geared to younger
children), Pen Pen Tri-Icelon (published by Infogrames, $39.99, for
all ages), a penguin racing game from Japan, is worth picking up.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER GAMES _ For graphics quality, the computer is still
king, especially when it's equipped with a graphics accelerator
card. As usual, there is a slew of CD-ROMs for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Half-Life (published by Sierra, $49.95, ages 17 and up) is the
benchmark action shooter, although Unreal Tournament (published by
GT Interactive, $39.99, ages 17 and up) provides an excellent
death-match experience for people too shy to venture onto the
Internet. (The CD-ROM functions as training wheels for multiplayer
action; think of it as Deathmatch for Dummies.)
</P>
<P>
   Need for Speed 3: Hot Pursuit (published by Electronic Arts,
$19.99, for all ages) is the hottest racer. Homeworld (published by
Sierra, $39.99, for all ages) and Command and Conquer: Tiberian Sun
(published by Virgin, $47.99, for teen-agers) are top picks for
sci-fi strategy.
</P>
<P>
   For history buffs, Sid Meier's Gettysburg (published by
Electronic Arts, $19.99, for children or adults), Railroad Tycoon 2
(published by Gathering of Developers, $39.95, for all ages) and
Microsoft's Age of Empires 2: The Age of Kings (published by
Microsoft, $54.95, for teen-agers) allow you to replay the Civil
War, the robber baron era or the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy adventure fans can revel in Drakan (published by
Psygnosis, $37.99, 17 and up), a gorgeously rendered story world
featuring a leggy female dragon rider. (Move over, Lara Croft.)
SimCity 3000 (published by Electronic Arts, $49.95, for all ages)
beckons armchair urban planners to construct their own metropolis,
while Creatures 3 (published by Mindscape Entertainment, $39.99,
for all ages) serves up a digital terrarium to breed new forms of
artificial life.
</P>
<P>
   For children of all ages, Midnight Play (published by Simon &AMP;
Schuster Interactive, $15) is a beautifully crafted story book. And
for sheer nostalgia, there's Pong: The Next Level (published by
Hasbro Interactive, $19.95) _ bell-bottoms are optional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
