<HEADER>
A2730 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-KID-QUOTES-$AD     11-17 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-KID-QUOTES-$ADV19-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO SAYS WE HAVE EDUCATIONAL PROBLEMS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, Nov. 19)  
 (EDS: The numbers in graf 9 should be subscript)  
(lh) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it seems to you that the current crop of presidential
candidates is lacking in original ideas, it could be because they
have been out of school too long.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are (possibly) real quotes lifted (probably
illegally) from students' papers by (sneaky) grade-school teachers
from around our (or somebody else's) country and posted (possibly
by means of witchcraft) on the Internet (whatever that is):
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of `I give' is `I take.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Verb conjugations have never been my strong suit, but this
sounds right. Of course, it's possible that the subject was not
English grammar but economics, in which case the answer is
definitely right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parts of speech are lungs and air.''
</P>
<P>
   I think this student is forgetting the diaphragm, the lips and
the tongue. Unless the person is a politician, in which case you
also have to include the speech writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water is composed of two gins Oxygin and hydrogin. Oxigin is
pure gin. Hydrogin is gin and water.''
</P>
<P>
   This kid is destined to be either a chemistry major or a
bartender. The only problem is that when you take a shower, you
come out smelling like a martini.
</P>
<P>
   Define H2O and CO2: ``H2O is hot water and CO2 is cold water.''
</P>
<P>
   Mix them together and you get El Nino. Or a gimlet. Or
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``A virgin forest is a forest where the hand of man has never
set foot.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems like an awkward way to walk through a forest, virgin
or otherwise, but if that's what it takes to save our trees, then I
guess I'm all for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general direction of the Alps is straight up.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you happen to be standing on top of the Alps, in which
case the general direction is straight down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who followed the Lord were called the 12
opossums.''
</P>
<P>
   I have a terrible confession: I ran over one of the Lord's
opossums while driving home from work the other night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spinal column is a long bunch of bones. The head sits on
the top and you sit on the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds dreadfully uncomfortable. Couldn't I at least have a
pillow?
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not raise silk worms in the United States, because we
get our silk from rayon. He is a longer worm and gives more silk.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like ol' Rayon is one busy worm. After a hard day of
spinning silk for the entire USA, I bet he pours himself a stiff
oxygin/hydrogin cocktail _ shaken, not stirred.
</P>
<P>
   ``A scout obeys all to whom obedience is due and respects all
duly constipated authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be tricky. Should scouts demand to see an empty box
of Ex-Lax from the authority in question before they obey? What
about authorities that are just constipated part of the time? It
seems like a secret handshake, or something, would make a lot more
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``One by-product of raising cattle is calves.''
</P>
<P>
   Other by-products include oxygin and hydrogin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver Cromwell had a large red nose, but under it were deeply
religious feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if he had been born earlier, he might well have been
one of the 12 opossums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word trousers is an uncommon noun because it is singular
at the top and plural at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas T-shirts are plural at the top and singular at the
bottom. This new grammar is easy once you get the hang of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syntax is all the money collected at the church from
sinners.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what we need. Another tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spring, the salmon swim upstream to spoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad trick, considering salmon don't have hands. Presumably
by fall, the more dexterous salmon have advanced to a knife and
fork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iron was discovered because someone smelt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps iron is another by-product of raising cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of the 18th century, all the morons moved to
Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not true. Some of them didn't arrive until much later.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person should take a bath once in the summer, not so often
in the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it wasn't iron that someone smelt.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1745EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
