<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-WIRELESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK-CHANGE PHONES TO MATCH EVERY MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget utility, convenience and productivity. In the wireless
world, style rules.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you feel the need to match your cell phone with the
clothes you are wearing _ even the color of your lipstick _ you
can. The popular Nokia 5100 and 6100 series cell phones have
removable face plates. On the 5100 you can snap them into place.
The 6100 requires a screwdriver. The interchangeable face plates
are available from Nokia or third-party suppliers, mostly on the
Web. Try www.gost.fi or www.mobileart.com.
</P>
<P>
   At sites like these, you can order a plate bearing your
astrological sign or the flag of your choice. You can even design
your own face plate. While you're at it, swap the generic number
pad for one with big squishy buttons. And last week, Nokia,
together with AT&AMP;T and Disney, began selling face plates featuring
Mickey, Minnie, Goofy and Donald.
</P>
<P>
   Sound matters, too: not just quality but musical taste. Digital
phones, of course, come with a variety of options for ringing
tones. Now you can program your phone with a ringing tone of your
own creation. Make a sound file of the Notre Dame fight song, for
example, transfer it to your phone and impress your fellow alumnae.
</P>
<P>
   Other cell phone manufacturers are catching on to the style fad.
Motorola sells interchangeable battery covers with NFL logos for
its new Startac Talkabout phones. The logos are also available on
leather holsters and pager carrying cases. Body Glove, the folks
who brought style to the wet suit crowd, makes neoprene fashion
statements out of shock absorbent, water-resistant cell phone and
beeper covers. It started with the Cell Suit for the Startac. The
coolest by far is the cover that wraps around the Nokia 5100 and
6100 phones, with snap-on flaps that come in various colors.
</P>
<P>
   Headset sales are rising, and headsets designed for mobile
phones are getting a new look, too. Plantronics, the Santa Cruz,
Calif., company known for its high-quality headsets, has introduced
a new line for cell phones with a decidedly younger, trendier
customer in mind. Try a hook-behind-the-ear model, or if you would
like to style yourself after Jodie Foster in ``Contact'' or after
Tom Cruise in ``Jerry Maguire,'' try an over-the-head unit.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of wireless headsets is improving, and they will get
even better as products built with Bluetooth, a technology that
uses radio frequencies, show up on the market over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case you're not a total slave to fashion.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   SOME WIRELESS PRODUCTS
</P>
<P>
   Here is a selection of phones and pagers that do considerably
more than ring and beep.
</P>
<P>
   Cell Phones
</P>
<P>
   1. QUALCOMM THIN PHONE
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Phone is definitely slim, thanks to interesting battery
innovations, and it weighs a little more than 4 ounces. It has a
four-line screen, which means it is not going to give you much in
the way of Web surfing, but it will give you simple pieces of
information off the Web, like the weather, stock quotes, flight
schedules and sports scores. The cost of the Thin Phone ranges from
$79 to $149, depending on the carrier's subsidy. Networks that use
the phone include Sprint, PrimeCo, Bell Atlantic Mobile, GTE
Wireless and AirTouch Cellular.
</P>
<P>
   2. NOKIA 8860
</P>
<P>
   This is no ersatz Web browser. In fact, it's no Web browser at
all. The Nokia 8860 is pure style. It doesn't offer Internet
access, but this pricey ($799 to $999) chrome, trimode phone, which
switches from analog to digital cellular to PCS networks, is the
high-priced phone of choice for customers on the AT&AMP;T Wireless
network. At just under 4 ounces, it is probably the only digital
phone that could be mistaken for a cigarette lighter, which means
it isn't for anyone with big or clumsy hands. You turn the phone on
and off by opening and closing the sliding cover: no flipping
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   3. NEOPOINT
</P>
<P>
   This little phone with the big screen is still getting a lot of
attention as the first microbrowser-cum-cell phone to seem useful.
The screen is a reasonable size, 11 lines long, with a highly
readable liquid crystal display. The phone uses a special system
for speeding up text entry and also has speech recognition. The
phone comes with a docking station that lets you synchronize
information with your PC and recharge the phone battery at the same
time. The Neopoint, $399 from Sprint PCS, weighs 6.4 ounces. It
also doubles as a wireless modem. The only caveat: carry a bottle
of screen cleaner with you, because the screen is very
smudge-prone.
</P>
<P>
   Pagers
</P>
<P>
   4. MOTOROLA PAGEWRITER 2000X
</P>
<P>
   The Motorola Pagewriter 2000X, a two-way pager billed as a
``wireless communications center,'' looks like a personal digital
assistant, and it is just as functional. You can send and receive
pages and e-mail, call up the weather, buy and sell stocks, buy a
book, bid on Ebay, load up a scheduler, synchronize data with your
PC and play blackjack. The unit starts at about $360, and service
fees vary depending on what you choose. As for the marks against
it: it's expensive, and it's not a cell phone, but at 6.7 ounces
it's still heavier than one.
</P>
<P>
   5. MOTOROLA i1000 PLUS
</P>
<P>
   The $299 middleweight (5.4 ounces) Motorola i1000 Plus phone,
used only on the Nextel and SouthernLinc networks, has a two-way
digital radio that lets you reach other users on your network. Two
of the phone's best features are the see-through flip cover and the
speaker-phone option. The built-in microbrowser gives you access to
the usual suspects _ stock prices, airline information, weather
reports and more. The phone's biggest aesthetic drawback is an
oddball bump protruding from the front of the flip cover.
</P>
<P>
   6. RESEARCH IN MOTION
</P>
<P>
   The new pagers from Research in Motion are a departure from
conventional paging, and a move toward wearable computers. The RIM
850 costs $359, with an additional flat rate of $59.95 per month
for the wireless service from American Mobile or Skytel. The pager
gives you access to a variety of e-mail accounts, as well as Web
access. There is also the $399 RIM Blackberry, which is more like a
handheld organizer. The Blackberry gives you access to e-mail and
the Web and provides flat-rate air time for $39.95 per month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
