</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for THURSDAY, November 18,
1999
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: SCHOOL-CHOICE, BAXTER
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Please note coverage of Jewish General Assembly meeting in
Atlanta in International, National, Political and Religion
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-CRASH _ CAIRO _ As the probe into what caused the crash of
EgyptAir Flight 990 focuses more on co-pilot Gamil Hamid
el-Batouty, this Islamic nation is responding with incredulous
anger at what people here are calling a knee-jerk reaction based on
Muslim stereotypes. Egyptians here are rallying around Batouty, a
respected pilot who came from a well-known wealthy family, and seem
to be taking the suicide-based conspiracy theories surrounding the
fatal crash personally. That's because suicide is looked upon with
shame in Islam. Meanwhile, Batouty's family continues to believe he
is being used as a scapegoat (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-OSCE _ ISTANBUL _ President Clinton, attending a summit
of the 54-nation Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE), has a face-to-face meeting with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin regarding the Russian military assault on the
breakaway republic of Chechnya. Clinton is also expected to
announce a deal on an oil pipeline in the Caspian region.
Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). ETA: 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BARAK _ ISTANBUL _ ISTANBUL _ President Clinton meets
with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak about the status and
progress of the Middle East peace process. Developing. (Deans, Cox
News Service) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OSCE-JOHNSON _ VIENNA _ An interview, if possible, with U.S.
Ambassador to the Vienna-based OSCE, David Johnson, a career
diplomat and young father of three from Columbus, Ga. Developing.
(Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-LENNY _ SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Hurricane Lenny, an
unusually powerful late-season tropical storm, is expected to level
the Virgin Islands as it barrels through the eastern Caribbean.
Developing. (Williams, Cox News Service). ETA: 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ASSEMBLY-STEIN _ ATLANTA _ Q and A with author Ken Stein on the
Middle East process. Stein expects an eventual deal acceptable to
both Israelis and Palestinians _ though probably not by the
currently announced deadlines. Even with that, he sees much work to
be done in the Middle East and expects America's involvement will
be long. (Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-ASSEMBLY _ ATLANTA _ Delegates are focusing on
international issues, attending lectures and workshops on topics
ranging from War reparations to be paid to victims of the Holocaust
to the peace process in the Mideast. We attend a few sesssions,
talk with delegates and try to see what's being said about these,
and other, international topics. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/JEWISH-IDENTITY _ ATLANTA _ Pull together three Jews and ask
them to detail their thoughts on Jewish identity and you'll get
three different answers. This is the biggest topic being explored
within the Jewish community, even bigger than the relationship
between Israel and the U.S. We talk about this touchy topic with
delegates and officials attending this week's Jewish General
Assembly in Atlanta and lay and spiritual leaders in Atlanta's
Jewish community. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving on (l) Lifestyle category
</P>
<P>
   WACO-INQUEST _ An inquest will be held six years late into the
death of Michael Schroeder, who died on the day of the ATF raid on
Mount Carmel. After the resurgence of interest in the Branch
Davidians, Justice of the Peace David Pareya of West discovered the
oversight while recently looking through documents. Pareya went out
to view the body in 1993 and got information on Schroeder's death,
but FBI officials, despite
</P>
<P>
   repeated requests, never turned over the ballistic
</P>
<P>
   tests done on Schroeder's body. He also could
</P>
<P>
   never get an answer from ATF on who actually shot Schroeder.
Schroeder was shot when he attempted to reenter the compound Sunday
afternoon _ he was at a nearby Davidian gun shop hangout when the
morning raid took place. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   STRIPCLUB-INDICTMENTS _ ATLANTA _ Federal prosecutors have
charged the Gold Club, an Atlanta adult entertainment
establishment, and its owners in a racketeering indictment that
includes prostitution for customers, bribes to Atlanta police
officers and ties to organized crime. The 97-page indictment,
unsealed today, accuses two Atlanta police officers of accepting
bribes, two Delta Air Lines employees of providing illegal favors
to club officials and two dancers of participating in prostitution
with unnamed professional basketball players. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-FIRES _ ATLANTA _ We go back to North Georgia to cover the
wildfire news of the day and hopefully talk to some firefighters
about what it's been like to fight this blaze. (Badie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ANESTHESIA _ WASHINGTON _ The chief anesthesiologist at Bethesda
Naval Medical Center, where congressmen, the president and other
dignitaries are treated, has been relieved of his command for
refusing to carry out an order to allow nurses to administer
anesthesia without physician supervision. Dr. Alvin Manalaysay said
he was told that when VIPs are treated, they will continue to be
under the care of physician anesthesologists, but ordinary sailors
will go to sleep under the unsupervised care of nurse anesthetists.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER _ ATLANTA _ Reflections from watching Bradley and Gore on
the same day in Atlanta. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CHOICE _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Congress have
quietly agreed to a ``school choice'' deal that could enrage
teachers unions, annoy school boards and please many poor parents.
The provision would give parents of children in failing schools
that receive federal Title I anti-poverty aid the right to transfer
their child to any other public or charter school within their
district that had enough room. The agreement adds the provision to
the education spending bill and gives school districts $135 million
to carry it out. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore makes afternoon
appearance at United Jewish Communities 1999 general assembly at
Atlanta Civic Center. (Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ ATLANTA _ Bill Bradley comes to Atlanta for a
fund-raiser at the home of media magnate Anne Cox Chambers and
several public events, including at Morehouse School of Medicine.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-IDENTITY _ ATLANTA _ Pull together three Jews and ask
them to detail their thoughts on Jewish identity and you'll get
three different answers. This is the biggest topic being explored
within the Jewish community, even bigger than the relationship
between Israel and the U.S. We talk about this touchy topic with
delegates and officials attending this week's Jewish General
Assembly in Atlanta and lay and spiritual leaders in Atlanta's
Jewish community. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
