<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2734 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV25-     11-17 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PARENTS, A LIBRARY TO THE RESCUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.) (For release Nov. 25)  
(rk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was predicting a long week with my two children. My husband
was leaving for a business trip to Dallas. The weather was getting
too chilly for much outside play. The kids were growing restless
from short days and long nights.
</P>
<P>
   Ordering early Christmas presents from amazon.com and eToys.com
had depleted my budget, so I couldn't even bribe myself out of the
situation with a movie and pizza.
</P>
<P>
   These are the times I love the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any requests?'' I asked my 8-year-old as I dropped him off at
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something that tells you about `Star Wars.' You know, all the
detail stuff. David knows all these FACTS about `Star Wars,' and I
never know them,'' came the reply.
</P>
<P>
   I thought every 8-year-old had an encyclopedic knowledge of
``Star Wars,'' but apparently someone had trumped Adam, and he was
determined to brush up on his trilogy trivia.
</P>
<P>
   I knew my 3-year-old's requests. She has some favorite library
books and CDs that she firmly believes are hers because we check
them out so often. She'd be disappointed if she ever discovered
they were actually community property.
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up, I loved any library. There was the one at
my elementary school, with its complete Bobbsey Twins series and a
large selection of horse adventure books with titles like ``Blaze
and the Forest Fire.'' At the public library, I learned about
preteen angst and first love through Judy Blume novels.
</P>
<P>
   Since my children were born, I've been lucky enough to live in
two towns _ Plant City and Mountain Park, Ga. _ with new, fully
stocked libraries. Both are wonderfully designed for children.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when I have a serious library trip planned, I go alone. I
am my family's personal librarian.
</P>
<P>
   I always make a few safe selections, popular books I know the
kids will like. But I always take a few chances as well. Adam
really enjoyed ``Sarah Plain and Tall'' and ``Baby,'' both by
Patricia MacLachlan, although I was afraid he might think they were
``girl'' books.'' And ``The Wave'' by Pearl Buck enthralled both of
us for a week at bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   This trip was high-stakes. For my own self-preservation, I
needed a good selection in just 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In less than 15 minutes, I had made my choices.
</P>
<P>
   For Sarah: the latest issue of ``Ladybug,'' Disney's ``Under the
Sea'' video, ``Moonbear's Friend'' by Frank Asch, ``We're Going on
a Bear Hunt'' by Michael Rosen, and ``We Were Tired of Living in a
House'' by Liesel Moak Scorpen.
</P>
<P>
   For Adam: ``The Ghost in Tent 19,'' Disney's original ``Treasure
Island'' video, the ``Making of the Phantom Menace'' and the ``Star
Wars Encyclopedia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All right!'' Adam crowed, as I handed him the stack of ``Star
Wars'' research material and he disappeared into the basement.
</P>
<P>
   I even found a few books for Jim to read on the plane: ``The
Complete Idiot's Guide to Chess'' and James Brady's ``The House
that Ate the Hamptons.''
</P>
<P>
   That should keep everyone happy for a while. Maybe even happy
enough that I can get a good start on my thick library copy of
Wally Lamb's ``I Know This Much is True.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
