<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, November 18, 1999,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX _ LAS VEGAS _ It wasn't so long ago that networking
computers was widely viewed as a job for office professionals. But
with the advent of households with two or more computers,
inexpensive and simple home networks are on the rise, enabling
users to share fast links to the Internet, printers, scanners on
through the home phone lines with no added wiring. Comdex trots out
the latest wrinkles. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX-INTERNET _ LAS VEGAS _ PCs that rely more on the Internet
than on software and servers are all the rage these days. What does
this fundamental change in the way computing is done mean to the
companies that make them - and their suppliers? (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MALL-TV _ ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting will create a new
channel, based on a smorgabord of its current programming, to air
nationwide in malls owned by Simon Properties. The yet unnamed
channel is part of a strategic alliance with Simon, by far the
largest mall developer. The alliance will also create a Web site,
interactive kioks and family entertainment centers based on Turner
Broadcasting programming. The alliance is part of a larger effort
by Turner Broadcasting to establish the names of its 18 channels as
brands recognized beyond the television. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PILOTS _ ATLANTA _ Any air accident undermines the public's
confidence in airlines, but the possibility that a pilot bent on
suicide crashed an airliner creates a new level of anxiety. We'll
examine what the major carriers do to ensure that the men and women
in the cockpit are competent and stable. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-SUIT _ ATLANTA _ The plaintiffs in a racial-discrimination
suit against Coca-Cola Co. said Wednesday the company has
repeatedly violated court orders requiring it to hand over relevant
documents in the case. As a result, the plaintiffs said, the court
should set a ``date certain'' requiring the Atlanta-based beverage
giant to comply with its obligations, as well as severe punishments
for continued non-compliance. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LODGIAN _ ATLANTA _ Lodgian's board of directors is expected to
discuss an unsolicited offer to buy the company by a Kentucky-based
hotel group. We get a few comments from chief executive Robert
Cole, who is not saying much, and trying for analysts on the bid
price. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KFC _ ATLANTA _ An African American KFC franchisee has acquired
four restaurants in Atlanta. KFC sold the company-owned units to
JFS International of Lithonia, bringing JFS's total holdings to
eight. Soon, KFC plans to sell another 200 company-owned stores in
a move to bolster the number of minority franchisees. Minorities
will get the first nod on about 50 of those stores. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-OLDPLANE _ ATLANTA _ Ship 41, one of Delta's first
airliners, takes first flight, with Delta CEO aboard. Plane has
been refurbished by retirees and Delta workers over some months.
(Minter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NICKLAUS-COURSE _ATLANTA _ Jack Nicklaus and golf course
developer Club Corp. are building a 500 acre golf course/housing
development on the banks of the Chatahoochee northeast of Atlanta.
The 18-hole facility will replicate 18 of the Golden Bear's
favorite holes from across the world. Homes will range from
$250,000 to $1 million. It's set to open by mid-2001. (Meadows,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in (s) sports category.
</P>
