<HEADER>
A2759 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-SCHWARTZ-BOS     11-17 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-SCHWARTZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENJAMIN SCHWARTZ, 82: HARVARD PROFESSOR, CHINA EXPERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Benjamin Schwartz, an expert on China who taught history and
political science at Harvard University for many years, died of
cancer Monday in his home in Cambridge. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   According to Elizabeth Perry, a professor of government at
Harvard, Mr. Schwartz had an ``enormous impact'' on the field of
Chinese studies because he was ``equally at home in ancient and
contemporary history.''
</P>
<P>
   She said he was one of the first scholars to demonstrate that
Chinese communism was not simply a carbon copy of Soviet communism,
but had its own historical roots and contemporary practices.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Schwartz was born in Boston. He graduated from Harvard in
1934, earned a master's degree at the school in 1941 and a
doctorate in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   He was a secondary school teacher before serving in the Army
during World War II. He first served as as a cryptoanalyst on
breaking Japanese communications codes, then as a censor during the
occupation of the defeated country.
</P>
<P>
   It was during his time in Japan that he became fascinated with
what he called the ``mysterious Orient'' in the 25th anniversary
report of his class at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he returned to Harvard, where he earned his
doctorate in East Asia studies.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Harvard faculty in 1950, and remained at the
school until his retirement in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The author of several books including ``Chinese Communism and
the Rise of Mao,'' and ``The World of Thought in Ancient China,''
he was an adviser to US governmental agencies and testified before
congressional panels several times.
</P>
<P>
   In the 50th anniversary report of his class at Harvard, he wrote
that ``past experience of mankind (both its wisdom and folly)
remains of burning relevance to our present concerns'' and added
that his work ``provided an exciting opportunity for a Westerner to
explore the cultural-historical experience of a non-Western
civilization from a comparative point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Bernice; a son, Jonathan; a daughter,
Sara-Ann Erichson; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0232 </DOCNO>
