<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2770 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SHOPPING-UNUSUAL-     11-17 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-UNUSUAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICHE SITES OFFER CHANCE TO CREATE OR PERSONALIZE GIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online shopping may be a good way to avoid the shopping-mall
parking lot, but it does not guarantee that you will avoid the
homogeneity of the shopping-mall experience. In fact, the
likelihood that you will give or receive The Gap's latest V-neck
sweater style (boiled lamb's wool with a ribbed trim at the cuffs)
is sure to increase this year, as online shoppers from even the
most remote places click on trusted brands.
</P>
<P>
   But although Web portals channel shoppers to the same
high-profile stores, the Web itself offers an antidote to the herd
mentality. Tiny, family-run stores abound _ many of which suggest
gifts that you would never find at J.C. Penney or the retail shops
that surround it. Online niche shops allow you to buy monthly
deliveries of caviar for your friends, for example. There is at
least one shop where you can order aerial photographs of your
grandparents' favorite national park.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also makes it easy to personalize gifts. Fill in a
Web form about your child to order a custom-printed book or a song
sung in your child's honor. Pick your favorite tunes from an online
database and have them put on a custom CD.
</P>
<P>
   If you know what you are looking for, you can find these shops
by plugging key words into search engines. If you are starved for
ideas, here are some sites to try:
</P>
<P>
   PERSONALIZED CHILDREN'S BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   www.booksforme.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BooksForMe creates books with heroes whose names are the same as
those of the children who are reading the stories. To order,
parents must fill out a form, entering the child's name, age,
birthday, town and other details related to the story. ``My Space
Adventure,'' one title, will put your child in command of a
backyard spaceship on its way to the planet Love. BooksForMe will
also insert your child as a character in more traditional books
like ``Bambi'' and ``Mother Goose.'' Each book costs $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   w3ent.com/abcpersonalized.htm &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like BooksForMe, ABC Storybooks obtains its books from a single
publisher, Create-a-Book, in Gulf Breeze, Fla., and acts as
distributor. ABC Storybooks' custom books feature holiday themes,
including Christmas and Kwanzaa. Some, like ``The Magic Little
Christmas Tree,'' are pop-ups to boot (though these are
personalized with stickers inserted on each page instead of
integrated text). Prices run from $12.95 to $19.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   www.kidcartoons.com/  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KidCartoons takes the custom concept to another level. The
artists at KidCartoons will create comic-book covers, comic books
and cartoon videos based on a child's photograph. The site is
operated by K Design, a computer graphics company in Brentwood,
N.Y. Prices are $9.95 for the comic-book covers, $14.95 for the
comic books and $19.95 for the cartoon video.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONALIZED CHILDREN'S SONGS
</P>
<P>
   www.kidtraxsongs.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If print is not enough, several companies will put a child's
name into song. At the Kid Trax Creations site parents can order a
17-minute tape containing five songs that mention their child's
name more than 30 times. A cassette and song-book set costs $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   www.cakencandle.com/  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the site for Cake and Candle Cassettes parents may order a
personalized lullaby, a birthday song or Christmas carols that
mention the child's name 18 times. The tapes cost $8.50 each.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONALIZED SONGS FOR ADULTS
</P>
<P>
   www.giftsongs.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   P.S. I Love You, the Personalized Song Company, creates
professionally recorded CD's or cassettes of custom songs. The
company's president, Mark Baker, has composed tunes for the
Temptations and other groups. Now he will write a song for you or
your loved ones. Cassette tapes cost $39.95 each; CD's cost $49.95
each.
</P>
<P>
   www.psycholaborations.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For something heavier in a personalized song, consider a
``Psycholaboration'' with Pat DiNizio, lead singer for the pop-rock
band the Smithereens. DiNizio will turn lyrics into personalized
songs. Enter your own lyrics, prose or poetry into the order form
on his Web site ; choose the type of music you want _ rock, folk,
disco _ and the format _ cassette, CD, MP3. The result costs $350.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER CUSTOM GIFT IDEAS
</P>
<P>
   www.wrappedup.com/
</P>
<P>
   Looking for an alternative to Christmas cards? Wrapped Up, an
online retailer in Bay Minette, Ala., will wrap chocolate bars with
a label of your choice. Select clip art from the Web site or
request a custom graphic for an additional $25. Chocolate choices
include Hershey bars, Mr. Goodbar and small KitKats, most of which
cost $1.35 each with the custom wrappings. Not responsible for
melted arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   www.edier.com/special/occasion/multimedia.htm
</P>
<P>
   Someday, traditional photograph albums _ full of static
snapshots and devoid of sound and video _ will seem awfully dull. A
small company called Edier Developer produces multimedia CD-ROM's
of events in a person's life, based on videotapes, audio recordings
and still photographs that are sent to the company's studio. (In
most cases, music used for the CD-ROM's has to come from Edier's
own collection so that the company steers clear of copyright
violations and royalty payments.) Edier Chiong, the founder, said
that he decided to make a business of personalizing CD-ROM's after
Hurricane Andrew swept through Miami, where Edier Developer is
based, in 1993. ``It wiped out most of the pictures we had,''
Chiong said. But if they had been saved on a CD-ROM, he said, ``We
wouldn't have lost those pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   www.tide-in-stitches.com/
</P>
<P>
   If you know grandparents who like to brag about their
grandchildren, they just might like a sweat shirt embroidered with
the children's names. Ruth Andrick has been doing personalized
embroidery for more than 12 years from various addresses and
recently opened an online shop. The sweat shirts for grandparents
are her best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had kept track of every single kid's name I have put
on these shirts,'' Ms. Andrick said. ``It's got to be in the
millions.'' That includes names of children born years after a
sweat shirt was made. ``I'm constantly adding names on ones I've
done before,'' she added. Adult-size sweat shirts with up to three
names cost $30 each; each additional name costs $3.
</P>
<P>
   www.unique-sports.com/
</P>
<P>
   Your sports-obsessed friends cannot be true fans if they don't
have a helmet lamp _ that is, a table lamp, complete with shade,
that extends from a real football or baseball helmet base. You can
order them for your friends, featuring their favorite team's logo,
from this site. Baseball lamps cost $150; football, $165.
</P>
<P>
   Other gifts include the Good Sport Snack Machine (a gumball
machine adorned with plastic props apropos of your favorite
sporting event) and framed photographs of professional scoreboards
that have been altered using photography software to digitally show
a person's name in lights.
</P>
<P>
   www.musicmaker.com/  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   College students might have the time to sit around hitting
Record and Pause buttons as they create custom cassette tapes for
their friends, but most other people don't. MusicMaker.com offers a
much faster alternative on line for CD's. The site provides a
database of more than 200,000 tracks from more than 100 music
labels. And it does so legally, by paying royalties to the artists
whose works are selected. MusicMaker offers suggestions of song
combinations as well, like ``Space Age Spectaculars'' for the
``Star Trek'' set, which includes soundtracks from movies like
``Star Wars,'' ``The X-Files'' and ``2001: A Space Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   terraserver.microsoft.com/
</P>
<P>
   How about something special for your security-minded friends: an
aerial photograph of their house, captured by American or Russian
satellites. If they live in a big house, in a city or suburban
area, there is a chance that such a photograph exists. You can
search for it using the TerraServer, a site that offers a database
of aerial and satellite photographs from the U.S. Geological Survey
and SPIN-2, a Russian-American satellite venture.
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning your search, however, you may need to know the
latitude and longitude of your friends' homes. The TerraServer
suggests going first to MapBlast.com, which provides that data
after you enter a street address. The TerraServer is also a source
of aerial shots of famous geological sites, like Niagara Falls.
Prints of the photographs range from $7.95 to $24.95. TerraServer's
newest product is a CD-ROM of satellite photographs of Area 51, the
military zone in Nevada that has been the subject of conspiracy
theories and supposed alien sightings.
</P>
<P>
   silver.chartshop.com
</P>
<P>
   Astrologists and psychics are attuned to the nuances of
e-commerce. IVillage.com's astrology expert, Kelli Fox, suggests
buying an in-depth destiny report (or a family, love or career
report) for yourself or as a gift at Chartshop.com. One of the
latest offerings is the Love Potential Profile, which includes a
compatibility report and a monthlong romantic forecast.
</P>
<P>
   members.aol.com/Ipredict7/
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Luciano, who is described on her Web site as ``a
professional psychic with 38 years of experience,'' invites you to
order a private reading in an AOL chat room. To encourage
newcomers, she has reduced her prices to $35 for a half-hour for
first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   GIFTS THAT KEEP COMING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.of-the-month.com/
</P>
<P>
   www.greatclubs.com/
</P>
<P>
   www.cigarmonthclub.com/
</P>
<P>
   www.beermonthclub.com/
</P>
<P>
   www.chocolateofthemonth.com/
</P>
<P>
   Judging by their number, gift clubs for fine-food lovers and
``of the month'' clubs appear to be thriving online, and most offer
gift memberships. Of-the-month.com sells deliveries of cheese or
cheesecake, coffee or caviar, soap or seashells and many other
items. Other sites cater to popular sins, like beer and cigars.
Chocolate is one of the most common offerings. What better way to
kick off your friend's New Year's resolution than to send two
pounds of toffee?
</P>
<P>
   www.enews.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.magmall.com/  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magazine subscriptions have always been the gift of choice for
those who would rather avoid shopping, gift-wrapping and standing
in line at the post office. Now you can order gift subscriptions
online instead of waiting for an annoying subscription card to fall
out of the next magazine you open.
</P>
<P>
   Enews.com sells subscriptions to more than 850 titles and
features a page called the Magazine Matcher, which suggests
magazines for animal lovers, military buffs, computer fans and
more. MagMall.com offers 900 titles and enables users to search for
gift subscriptions by price range.
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND GIFTS
</P>
<P>
   www.cardsupply.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.preciousyou.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.americangreetings.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.photoloft.com/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.amazingmail.com/
</P>
<P>
   If the thought of picking out and addressing dozens of holiday
cards is already bringing out your inner Grinch, you'll be pleased
to hear that the Internet can make the task easier, without
necessarily making it less personal. If you order cards from
CardSupply.com, you can click through categories like
``interfaith'' or ``snowflake, stars'' to narrow your search for
boxes of cards to be delivered to your home. The site also
encourages you to order custom envelopes with your return address.
The Precious You site specializes in holiday cards with pockets or
corner mounts for attaching family photographs.
</P>
<P>
   American Greetings offers a slightly less personal option: pick
out a card you like, type in a greeting and the company will mail
it without your ever having to set your hands on it.
</P>
<P>
   PhotoLoft.com lets you upload a digital photo, then select a
greeting-card style and type in a message and your recipient's
postal address. To save more time, you can also upload your address
book to the site. PhotoLoft will create the photo-finished cards
and mail them via second-day air, saving you that visit to the post
office. Or you can send them free by e-mail. Prices for the
snail-mail service start at $1.22 a card, featuring designs for
Christmas, Hanukkah, Kwanzaa and other major holidays throughout
the year.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't mind a postcard format, a slightly less expensive
alternative is offered through Amazingmail.com. For 99 cents a card
(or less if you buy in bulk), the site will send a postcard via the
postal service with your own photo (or one of theirs) on one side
and a personal message on the other.
</P>
