<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CRICHTON-BOOK-REVIEW-     11-17 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRICHTON-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 `TIMELINE': IMAGINATIVE TALE OF TRAVEL TO THE 14th CENTURY  
 (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An elderly man is found wandering alone in the Arizona desert,
suffering from mysterious physical defects and babbling
incoherently about ``quantum foam.'' As he lies dying in a
hospital, it's learned that he possesses a detailed ground plan of
a 14th-century French monastery and that he works for a New
Mexico-based company that specializes in quantum technology.
</P>
<P>
   The company is run by a brilliant but supremely arrogant
physicist who has already made a fortune developing ``new new''
technology and is impatient to rush to completion a project he is
backing to reconstruct a medieval community in the Dordogne section
of France. When he pressures the team of Yale historians
researching the site, its members are astonished to learn that the
ground plan found in the possession of the babbling man in the
desert contains more information about the monastery than they have
come up with.
</P>
<P>
   After questioning how the company knows so much, the professor
who heads the Yale team is flown to New Mexico for further
briefing. A day or so later the professor's assistants dig up at
the Dordogne site some 650-year-old parchments wrapped in oilskin.
Among them is a message in the professor's hand, written in ink
that also proves to be six centuries old. It says, ``Help me'' and
is dated 4/7/1357.
</P>
<P>
   So begins ``Timeline,'' Michael Crichton's latest exercise in
exploiting technological possibility and imagining its
Frankenstein's-monster consequences, in this case the horror of
traveling back in time and getting caught in the middle of the
Hundred Years' War.
</P>
<P>
   As with Crichton's previous thrillers, like ``The Andromeda
Strain'' and ``Jurassic Park,'' the neatest thing about the plot is
the ingenious way he gets it started. According to one perfectly
plausible view of quantum reality, a character in ``Timeline''
explains, an infinite number of universes impinge on one another,
each containing a version of reality, some of them earlier versions
of ours.
</P>
<P>
   So what is thought of as time travel is actually space travel, a
sort of faxing of a human being into a universe containing a past
version of our own. Any cracks in this logic are filled by Crichton
with sentences like ``To be precise, we use quantum technology to
manipulate an orthogonal multiverse coordinate change,'' or ``We
compress it'' _ that is, the information about the human form being
sent _ ``by using a lossless fractal algorithm.'' OK, so we believe
it.
</P>
<P>
   And, as is usual with Crichton's thrillers, the story doesn't
quite live up to the idea that gets it rolling. Three of the
professor's grad students are faxed over to fish him out of the
14th century. The machinery breaks down. The Yalies have to run a
dangerous obstacle course before they can come back, featuring
warring English and French armies, jousting knights,
plague-infested rats and all the other fun things that prompted
historian Barbara Tuchman to pronounce the 14th century calamitous
in her book ``A Distant Mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Timeline,'' plenty of action takes place, the pages begin
to turn themselves, but everything seems a little helter-skelter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Crichton makes a number of imaginative points along the
way. When the time-space travelers first arrive in 14th-century
Dordogne, one of them is struck by the fact that he doesn't hear
anything. ``That's right,'' a more experienced character explains.
``There's no ambient noise here: no radio or TV, no airplanes, no
machinery, no passing cars. In the 20th century, we're so
accustomed to hearing sound all the time, the silence feels
creepy.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, impressed by the fury of two knights practicing
swordplay, another character reflects that he had ``imagined a
slower fighting style'' only ``from an unconscious assumption that
men in the past were weaker or slower or less imaginative than he
was, as a modern man.'' Again and again Crichton's story makes the
point that the past doesn't think of itself as being the past.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, another character grows increasingly impressed by the
emptiness of his graduate-school debates over ``whether formalist
criteria outweighed objectivist criteria, whether derivationist
doctrine concealed normative commitment.'' This relates to the
bright side of the arrogant company president's ambitions, which is
to apply technology to the humanities and make it possible to
practice a discipline called experimental history.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, his plans go awry when his probes of the past reveal that
Lincoln delivered the Gettysburg Address in a voice that sounds
``like Betty Boop'' and Washington, crossing the Delaware, was
``huddled in the back of the boat,'' not good advertisements for
what the company is trying to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton himself ends up with a problem in advertising. In his
concluding acknowledgments, he writes of the medieval period: ``An
age that was once thought to be static, brutal and benighted is now
understood as dynamic and swiftly changing: an age where knowledge
was sought and valued; where universities were born, and learning
fostered; where technology was enthusiastically advanced; where
social relations were in flux; where trade was international; where
the general level of violence was often less deadly than it is
today.''
</P>
<P>
   This is contrary to the view of a number of books listed in his
extensive bibliography, not least among them Ms. Tuchman's
aforementioned ``Distant Mirror: The Calamitous 14th Century,''
which was written in part to reassure its readers that things in
the 20th century were not uniquely awful.
</P>
<P>
   Most emphatically is it at odds with Crichton's own cheerily
nihilistic portrait of the 14th century, where life is not only
nasty and brutish but also as short as that of a condemned man with
his head on the chopping block.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TIMELINE'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Crichton
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 450 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $26.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      11-17 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: PAGE TO SCREEN, AND BACK AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: in 4th graf, replace (EQUALS) with the typographical
symbol)  
 (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now here's an astonishment to both publishing and Hollywood:
this holiday season, more readers are likely to be getting their
literary fix from the movies than they are from books.
</P>
<P>
   The conjugality between Hollywood and serious novels and
nonfiction is hardly new. After all, Paramount put ``Great
Expectations'' on the screen in 1917, and Dickens has lingered
about the front lots like a ghost ever since, along with other
great writers. But for this prime period of pre-Thanksgiving
through New Year's, there seems to be an extraordinary number of
literary books that have made it to movie screens or are in
production. More than anyone seems to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, publishers are happy. Freshly redesigned paperback
editions of these books are being issued with photographs from the
movies on their covers. Sturdy back-list books that were only found
in bookstores alphabetized, two or three copies, on shelves labeled
``Literature-Fiction'' are now in heaps at the front of the stores.
So once again, it's hooray for Hollywood in the book business.
</P>
<P>
   It takes roughly two years to make a movie, and Hollywood, like
book publishing, is trend-driven. So what happened at the Academy
Awards two years ago accounts in large part for this season's high
number of literary movies: 1997 was the year of the independents.
``The English Patient,'' based on Michael Ondaatje's novel, won
nine Oscars; ``Fargo,'' ``Secrets and Lies'' and ``Shine'' also
won, and they were not studio-produced either. For Hollywood the
equation was simple: independents (EQUALS) excellence (EQUALS)
literary.
</P>
<P>
   Movie producer Lynda Obst put it this way: ``Literary material
into movies usually only happens after there's either a disaster
for the studios at Oscar night or in some mysterious way an adult
market starts to rear its head, and big-name directors used their
leverage to get studios to buy literary.'' So the next question
was, why can't the studios put that literature on the screens, win
the awards, make the money?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is they can, when they get caught in the drift, and
what followed is this year's cinema of the consequential and the
lettered, which started last week with the release of ``Anywhere
but Here,'' with Susan Sarandon and Natalie Portman, based on Mona
Simpson's well-received novel of more than a decade ago. The list
of such books that are racing Hollywood's engine includes Jane
Austen's ``Mansfield Park,'' which opens Thursday; John Irving's
``Cider House Rules,'' Frank McCourt's ``Angela's Ashes,'' Graham
Greene's ``End of the Affair,'' David Guterson's ``Snow Falling on
Cedars,'' Susanna Kaysen's ``Girl, Interrupted'' and Strindberg's
``Miss Julie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' is based on the novels of Patricia
Highsmith. And, of course, Washington Irving's ``Legend of Sleepy
Hollow'' is Tim Burton's spooky ``Sleepy Hollow.'' E.B. White's
``Stuart Little'' has popped onto the screen, and so too has
``Titus,'' which is more or less Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   What is fascinating is that not all these titles were mainstream
books, like Stephen King's ``Green Mile,'' but Hollywood's sorcery
is most certainly furiously trying to turn the literature into
mainstream movies.
</P>
<P>
   The association between publishing and movies has always been
integral, but also capricious and quixotic. (Several years ago, for
instance, it wasn't terribly uncommon for an agent to sell a
manuscript to the movies first, then use that clout to drive up the
author's advance from a book publisher. This simply put the cart
before the literary horse.) The moviemaking team of Merchant and
Ivory showed in film after film that art could make money in the
movie houses, for relatively little money invested, although many,
if not most, of the period pieces are more expensive to make than
contemporary stories. Still, Jane Austen and Washington Irving
don't have agents to bargain for their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Messitte, associate publisher of Vintage, who has a handful
of paperbacks being made into literary movies, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a wealth out this season. All our books have
movie art on the covers; what we do is beneficial to the movie
companies as well. They have free advertising placed in every
bookstore in the country. In `Snow Falling on Cedars' we have about
3,000 displays in stores around the country going into the
holidays. They should sell the movies as well as the books.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bookman, an agent for the Creative Artists Agency, said that
for about a year, until recently, books were a hard sell to the
movies for several reasons. There was, first, a conscientious
effort to bring down budgets. ``Then the youth market returned, and
for the younger generation there really was no pre-existing
material,'' he said. ``Since there was a lot of stuff in the
pipeline, there wasn't going to be much spending on books unless
they were truly special. Very successful authors would be bought
but not the mid-level success, which also cost a fair amount.'' In
the swaying of biases of Hollywood, that is beginning to change
again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Hollywood is betting on the literary, but, even
with all the hype associated with movies, there is still
finger-crossing over whether any of these books, except perhaps
``The Green Mile,'' will really become a mainstream movie. If not,
the solution to the industry's heebie-jeebies will be swift and
rudimentary, back to basic principles: toss Tom Cruise at the
problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
