<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-OSCE-1118-COX     11-17 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OSCE-1118-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EUROPE SUMMIT OPENS WITH ALL EYES (AND IRE) ON RUSSIA'S YELTSIN
 &HT;    (650&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With CLINTON-BARAK-1118.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ President Clinton leads his Western allies in
talks with Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Thursday, hoping to
manage one of the most difficult moments in U.S.-Russia relations
since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia are in direct conflict over three
key security issues:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Russia's air war against separatist rebels in Chechnya;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the future of nuclear arms controls;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and a U.S. plan to route huge volumes of Caspian oil out of
Russia's control for the first time in history.
</P>
<P>
   Those are precisely the sorts of tensions the 54-nation
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, or OSCE, was
designed to help ease.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as Clinton, Yeltsin and the other OSCE leaders gather
for a summit here Thursday, these troubles threaten to hijack
proceedings diplomats had hoped would focus on ways to strengthen
the 25-year-old organization.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton planning to use the summit to lead a chorus of
opposition against Yeltsin's campaign in Chechnya, White House
officials were struggling over how to deliver a forceful message
without making Yeltsin feel as though he'd come under siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a question of ganging up,'' White House
National Security Advisor Samuel Berger told reporters here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually everybody here wants Russia to succeed in its
transformation . . . to a working democracy with a working economy,
with having shed its empire,'' Berger said. ``All of those things
are extraordinarily important.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Berger said, leaders will use Thursday's summit to press
Yeltsin to end his military campaign in Chechnya and seek a
brokered peace accord with rebels seeking independence from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of (the international community) expressing
serious concern,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Two months of Russian bombing has killed hundreds of civilians
near Chechnya's capital, Grozny, and left more than 200,000 others
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin blames Chechen rebels for starting the violence. He
claims they've exploded bombs and performed other acts of terror
killing civilians in Russian cities to promote their call for
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The White House more or less accepts Yeltsin's characterization
but has assailed Moscow's response _ what Clinton has called
``indiscriminate'' bombing of civilian centers in pursuit of
alleged terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the level of civilian casualties and
the number of refugees that are being created,'' Berger said. ``The
means being used are causing inordinate harm to civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also spend much of Thursday highlighting agreements
to build a pair of pipelines to transport huge volumes of Caspian
Sea oil and natural gas to a Mediterranean port.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme, if it bears fruit, would give the United States and
its allies a strategic alternative to Persian Gulf oil and open the
door to deals potentially worth scores of billions of dollars to
American energy and construction companies.
</P>
<P>
   The pipelines are no victory, though, for relations between the
United States and Russia. Yeltsin has tried for years to scuttle
the pipelines, aiming to keep Moscow's hand on the spigot of the
world's last known source of large untapped crude oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   One part of Clinton's case, though, has been made for him.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in Chechnya has highlighted the vulnerability of
Caspian oil supplies to disruptions inside Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A pipeline running through parts of Chechnya en route to a
Russian port on the Black Sea has been shut down since last summer,
due to fighting in the war-torn region.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Clinton signed on five years ago to a policy
of building new pipelines that circumvent Russia in getting crude
oil and natural gas to markets outside of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he will sign as a witness to a pair of
multinational agreements clearing the way for commercial
construction of two new pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   One would transport 1 million barrels a day of crude oil from
the Caspian port of Baku in Azerbaijan through part of the
neighboring republic of Georgia and into to the riverport town of
Ceyhan in southern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Financing isn't yet in place for the 1,100-mile Baku-Ceyhan
pipeline, which would cost an estimated $2.4 billion. There are
extensive engineering problems to be worked out as well, and U.S.
officials estimate it will take another five years to get the
pipeline built and running.
</P>
<P>
   A second pipeline is planned to carry natural gas from
Turkmenistan to Ceyhan. That pipeline would travel some 1,200 miles
and cost about $2.7 billion to build, U.S. officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and Clinton are also slated to take up a broad nuclear
arms control agenda during a meeting between the two of them on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders are at odds over refusal by the Russian
parliament, or Duma, to ratify strategic arms reductions agreed to
during the Bush administration, as well as efforts to move forward
on two separate sets of further nuclear controls negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   With Duma elections set for December, and Russian presidential
elections slated for next June, the way forward on these talks is
anything but clear.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
