<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-EGYPT-CRASH-1118-COX     11-17 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-CRASH-1118-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM GOVERNMENT TO STREET, EGYPTIANS DON'T ACCEPT SUICIDE THEORY
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    EDs: Note spelling of Batouty's full name.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ Many Egyptians find it more likely that EgyptAir Flight
990 was destroyed by a secret agent than a suicidal pilot from a
respected family.
</P>
<P>
   As a stream of law enforcement leaks, but little concrete
evidence, emerged in the Western press Wednesday, Egyptians
considered and rejected the prevailing theory that a pilot may have
intentionally lead 216 people to their death.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane crashed Oct. 31, less than an hour after take off
from John F. Kennedy Airport in New York. It was bound for Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investigators say there were no apparent mechanical or
weather-related problems. After three days analyzing a 30-minute
cockpit voice recording, officials reportedly suspect relief pilot
Gameel el-Batouty of plunging the plane into the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of the average Egyptian's values, which shun
suicide and suspect Western pronouncements, such an idea is
unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious crash confronts a country where ancient riddles
are accepted and reliable information is often hard to come by. The
government of 18-year President Hosni Mubarak controls much of the
press.
</P>
<P>
   While outgoing and hospitable, much of the population is
illiterate. Many feel Israel and the West have disrespected their
country and Islamic religion. It is widely accepted that Diana,
Princess of Wales, was killed by the British Royal Family because
she dated an Egyptian.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a flood of law enforcement leaks _ some contradictory
_ the famous Egyptian street-corner conspiracy mill was in full
gear Wednesday. Theories fit the local world-view better than any
suicide scenario.
</P>
<P>
   One asserted that agents from the American CIA or the Israeli
Mossad _ two agencies with actual checkered histories in Egypt _
downed the plane because 33 Egyptian army specialists were on
board. Another is that airplane manufacturer Boeing Co. was trying
to use Batouty as a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   The Batouty family was in seclusion Wednesday, with undercover
police keeping watch outside their apartment.
</P>
<P>
   A couple family representatives repeated a list of facts that
indeed made a suicide hard to imagine. Batouty owned land and
villas. His 10-year-old daughter's Lupus condition appeared to be
improving. He had plans for a New Year's and wedding anniversary
party.
</P>
<P>
   Family representatives insisted that unofficial pronouncements
from investigators should be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if they would believe it if, for example, an official FBI
conclusion found Batouty responsible, cousin Sherif el-Batouty
said, ``Maybe.'' Another cousin, Dr. Galal el-Batouty said, ``No.
Not Gameel.''
</P>
<P>
   In a land where religion and status are a top priority,
Egyptians found it unthinkable that Batouty, the 59-year-old son of
a wealthy mayor in the Nile Delta would disgrace his family with
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not possible,'' said Abdelatif Nouri, an assistant to
Magdy Greish, a wealthy Cairo executive killed in the crash. ``We,
as Egyptians, would not do such a thing unless we were uneducated
and uncultured.''
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian government officials asked for a pause before anyone
drew conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping from a Cabinet meeting and making the lead in the
evening news, Egyptian Information Minister Safwat Sherif called
the reports from U.S. investigators, ``just mere speculation,
hypothesis and imaginings that don't reach the level of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Egypt sent its top civil aviation official and a
team of experts to Washington to review the cockpit voice
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Osman, director of the State Information Service, said
Egypt should be allowed to review the evidence before decisions
were made about the course of the investigation _ such as whether
transportation officials will refer the case to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a tragedy in the country's national air carrier, Osman
reiterated statements from President Mubarak that attention be paid
to possible dangers in the air space near New York rather than the
rushed conclusions of investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take it day-by-day, knowing the nature of the American
media,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Disbelief in the suicide theories had not, as of Wednesday,
simmered into anger toward Egypt's close ally and aid donor, the
United States. Many Egyptians said they still trusted Americans to
continue the probe.
</P>
<P>
   American officials stressed that Egyptian authorities were being
included in the crash probe, and Egyptian officials appeared to
want to avoid a diplomatic row. Some noted that more Americans died
in the crash than Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
