<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft findings spark debate
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Microsoft suffered what Business Week (Nov. 22) calls
``a complete rout'' when a federal judge declared that the software
giant used its monopoly power to crush competitors. The logical
next question, the business weekly asks, is whether consumers would
be better off if the company were broken up.
</P>
<P>
   One suggestion is to break the company into ``Baby Bills'' _ for
co-founder and Chairman Bill Gates _ the way AT&AMP;T was broken up
into Baby Bells, Business Week says. Another is tighter government
regulation _ ``rules of behavior'' _ to curb the company's abusive
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' says Business Week, ``is that there are no
perfect options.''
</P>
<P>
   The trustbusters did such a good job of proving their case that
they would look like wimps if they let Microsoft off too easily,
says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if they insist on breakup, they could prescribe a cure
that's worse than the disease,'' says Business Week.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (Dec. 6) asks this question of the court's antitrust
findings: ``Are we crazy here, or what?''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is the company ``that for years has led the boom in
stocks and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going out of our way to burst the very bubble we've
ridden so happily and profitably for so long?'' the magazine asks.
</P>
<P>
   While the outcome of the case is still in limbo, Fortune notes
that Dell, Compaq and Gateway continue to produce desktop, laptop
and notebook computers that are running on Microsoft's Windows
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see how market forces or government intervention
will change that,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   YOU CAN'T BE TOO CAREFUL
</P>
<P>
   An editor at Forbes (Nov. 29) challenged a private investigator
to dig up dirt on him. The results, says the magazine in its cover
story, are terrifying to anybody who worries about prying eyes or
credit card scam artists.
</P>
<P>
   The private eye, using only a keyboard and a phone, discovered
Forbes Senior Editor Adam Penenberg's Social Security number, how
much was in his bank account, his salary, his rent, two unlisted
phone numbers and how much he pays his psychotherapist, among other
facts.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes offers a laundry list of steps people can take to protect
their privacy, if there's any left. Among them: Don't write checks
in stores, inform your bank in writing not to share your records
with anyone, don't put personal information on a Web site and don't
send anything confidential by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
