<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RABAN-BOOK-2TAKES-NYT     11-17 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABAN-BOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EACH VOYAGE OF DISCOVERY IS ONE FOR THE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Shortly into his new book, ``Passage to Juneau: A Sea
and its Meanings,'' set around his solo voyage in a 35-foot ketch
from Seattle to Alaska, Jonathan Raban makes an intriguing
admission that grows increasingly apt as the disparate strands of
this sweeping travelogue come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid of the sea,'' writes this British-born author. ``I
fear the brush-fire crackle of the breaking wave as it topples into
foam; the inward suck of the tidal whirlpool; the loom of a big
ocean swell, sinister and dark, in windless calm; the rip, the
eddy, the race; the sheer abyssal depth of the water, as one
floats, like a trustful beetle on the surface tension.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, Raban continues, ``a timid, weedy, cerebral type, never
more out of my element than when I'm at sea.'' And yet, he says,
``for the last 15 years, every spare day that I could tease from
the calendar has been spent afloat, in a state of undiminished
fascination with the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime readers of Raban (pronounced RAY-bin), who was drawn to
this water-surrounded city from London nine years ago and now makes
his home here, will recognize his attraction to water as well as
the itinerant curiosity and quest for adventure that suffuse
``Passage to Juneau'' (Pantheon). He once spent four months in a
16-foot aluminum outboard traveling down the Mississippi River for
his 1981 book ``Old Glory,'' and he sailed solo in a tubby ketch
around the British Isles for ``Coasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Even writing 1,000 miles inland about Montana homesteaders for
his most acclaimed book, ``Bad Land: An American Romance,'' Raban
could not quite escape nautical images. ``Breasting the regular
swells of land, on a red dirt road as true as a line of longitude,
the car was like a boat at sea,'' begins ``Bad Land,'' which won
the 1997 National Book Critics Circle Award for general nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a Seattle restaurant recently _ as the fog rolled
over Elliott Bay, disappearing for a bit to reveal some grand
autumnal light and then sweeping right back in again to obscure it
_ Raban, 57, said he was quite comfortable with the notion of
himself as literary vagabond, whether on land or sea. A smile
breaking across his craggy face, he said he was delighted several
years ago when immigration officials presented him with the
so-called green card _ it is pink, actually, he demonstrates by
producing it _ that officially proclaims him to be a ``resident
alien'' in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of always been a resident alien,'' said Raban, who
has written 11 books in all, including several about the United
States, and served as editor for ``The Oxford Book of the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's sort of the job of a writer to be a resident
alien,'' he continued. ``I was certainly a resident alien in
England. But it wasn't until I came to live in the United States
that somebody actually gave me this formal title and a card to put
inside my wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   Water, he said, has mesmerized him since he was a small boy in
Norfolk exploring the first stretches of the River Wensum, just a
few hundred yards from his home. ``I think I had sort of an
addiction to water,'' he said. ``The best moment of having a bath
was pulling the plug and watching the water spin in a whirlpool''
down through the drain. ``I was transfixed by puddles.''
</P>
<P>
   The sea, of course, is a far cry from the bathtub, and Raban
really only learned to sail when he decided to write ``Coasting''
in the mid-1980s. He was afraid then, he says, and he remains
afraid now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear is part of the fascination,'' said Raban, who kept a
nervous eye on Puget Sound even on an afternoon sail out of
Bainbridge Island, the Washington state ferries passing nearby, the
Seattle skyline comfortably in view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why Conrad writes so well of the sea is, like any
professional seaman,'' he fears it, he said. ``People who love the
sea, who say they love the sea, are the real amateurs. I never
believe anybody when they say that. I think, `Well, you just don't
know much about it.' It means they've been on a cruise ship
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who's had to deal firsthand with the sea and its real
dangers knows that its extraordinarily mercurial nature _ from
being the friendliest thing to the most dangerous _ is part of its
overwhelming fascination. Nothing could be more tumultuous than the
sea. It is a model of chaos, of all the things that can go
haywire.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have been talking about the theme of his new book. If
the idea that ran through ``Bad Land'' was failure _ the book was
about the crushed dreams of the settlers lured to the Great Plains
by the railroads at the turn of the century _ the motif of
``Passage to Juneau'' is turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   The book explores the physical turbulence of the water itself,
as he considers the physics of waves and whirlpools in the Inside
Passage during the 1,000-mile trip. It embraces the disquieting
mythology and fantastic art and imagery that coastal Indians
employed to give their meaning to the sea. And it inquires into the
tensions and human turbulence that beset the crew of Discovery,
Capt. George Vancouver's ship, which he sailed up the Inside
Passage in 1792, to prove that the fabled Northwest passage between
the Atlantic and Pacific oceans did not indeed exist.
</P>
<P>
   As he studied the diaries of those seamen, Raban discovered that
``what began to emerge was a fascinating picture of just about the
most miserable ship that ever sailed in the 18th century, outside
possibly of the Bounty.'' The ship, he said, was laden with a
``bunch of snobbish aristos,'' ages 16 to 22, who had been packed
off on ``sort of a cheapo version of the Grand Tour,'' and they met
a stormy captain who was not at all grateful to have them as his
crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made their life miserable, and they made his life
miserable,'' said Raban, for whom the unhappy voyage amounted to
another mesmerizing strand of turbulence for the book.
</P>
<P>
   And then, finally, there is turbulence in his own life, from the
illness and death of his father, for which he has to break up his
journey and return to England, to problems that emerge in his
marriage. He is also racked by ambivalence about being out to sea
at all. Having become a father for the first time at age 50 in
1992, he finds himself consumed by longing for his daughter back in
Seattle, and part of the narrative revolves around his often
unsuccessful attempts to find any working phone along the foggy,
wind-battered shores of the Inside Passage so he can call home.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he found turbulence all around.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Seattle intrigues him. In this ``city of virtual reality,'' he
developed a curiosity about the rugged precincts of its Fishermens'
Terminal, home port for dozens of Alaska-bound fishing boats. ``It
is always a pleasure to come to this last bastion of old-fashioned
work,'' he wrote, ``with its nets, crab pots, paintbrushes and
carpentering; to its outdoor faces, seamed with experience, and to
its long-established family air, generation following generation
into the same industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this gangly, raspy-voiced author is at work on yet another
book, a novel set in Seattle in which the theme is not only water
but the city's high-tech culture as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fascinated by the talk of it, the social life of it, or
the absence of social life of it, the appearance of people in it,
the transformations that it makes of people,'' he said of the
dot-com life here. ``I mean, I know some of these people who had no
money at all three or four years ago'' and who now are
millionaires, at least on paper.
</P>
<P>
   And at New Year's he will be off for two weeks in the southwest
Indies on a 45-foot boat with friends, researching a magazine
article. ``Somebody's got to do these jobs,'' he said drily. ``What
I really want to do is write about a different color of water.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon enough he'll return to the waters here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful sea to be living on the lip of, and hugely
interesting,'' he said, beckoning past his ketch and out to Puget
Sound. ``Just within the last 200 years there was a tribal sea that
compared very, very closely with the sea as described by Homer. I
mean, you couldn't go into the Mediterranean and find, as it were,
the Homeric sea alive in 1792.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, marinas were springing up already in the
Mediterranean in 1792. English yachtsmen were basing their boats
there. Whereas here, almost within living memory, you've got an
animist sea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
