u e BC-TV-QUIZ-SHOW-NYT &LR;      11-17 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-QUIZ-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: GAME SHOWS WITH AN `OUR TOWN' TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If I won a lot of money,'' said the contestant on ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire,'' a forthright housewife with double chins,
``I'd like to lie in a bath of melted chocolate.''
</P>
<P>
   Her bath would be in England, where she was a contestant on the
original version of the quiz show. No one has said anything quite
so refreshing on the phenomenally successful ABC version, but then
sweetness and sincerity are the marks of the game's American
cousin. Despite astonishing similarities to the English original,
the ABC ``Millionaire'' also displays a connection between
wholesomeness and making money that is as bedrock American as Ben
Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   As in England, a contestant can get a phone friend or the
strangers in the audience to help. If he hears a question he
doesn't want to answer, he can pick up his money and walk away.
Competition is so soothing and benign here, it seems positively
virtuous.
</P>
<P>
   It took just one generation of copies to unveil the darker side
of this healthy competitive spirit, though. The Fox show ``Greed''
is the evil twin of ``Millionaire.'' Although in many ways it is
such a slavish imitation that it practically dares the
``Millionaire'' creators to sue, ``Greed'' offers a Darwinian
vision of ruthless competition. ``Millionaire'' reflects Americans
as we wish we were; ``Greed'' reveals what we fear (and perhaps
believe) we must be to survive. Both are close enough to reality to
hit a cultural nerve, yet exaggerated enough to be escapist fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' has done more than
reinvigorate the game show genre and ABC's fortunes. (It finishes
its latest run on Wednesday, with its inevitable return date
undecided.) Its impact even goes beyond the way ``Final answer?''
has become a catch phrase, understood and overused by almost
everyone. What is most revealing is how the show's feel-good
attitude has evoked a visceral response in an exceptional range of
viewers, of all ages and classes.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC promo shrewdly pinpoints at least part of that appeal:
``They look like ordinary people; they could be your friends.'' The
contestants do look as if they might be strolling around a mall in
a white, suburban, middle-class neighborhood. They are dentists and
teachers from towns with names like Cherry Hill and Falls Church.
When asked what they would do with their winnings, they say they
would pay off their parents' mortgages or send their children to
college. And unlike Hollywood glamour-pusses, they are often in
need of diets and orthodonture.
</P>
<P>
   But the viewer's ability to identify with the person next door
is not the deepest reason for the show's resonance. On an
unconscious level, ``Millionaire'' creates an idealized vision of
America as a society of tolerant, generous, good-willed people.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the contestants have been white men _ until Tuesday,
when the show had two players, both of them women. ``It's ladies
night,'' the host, Regis Philbin, announced in anticipation on
Monday, with evident relief. Even that homogeneous group of men,
though, reflects a changing, inclusive America. With a
matter-of-factness the sitcom ``Ellen'' could only have dreamed
about a few years ago, one gay contestant brought a man introduced
as ``his partner'' to root for him. When he returned for his second
night on the show, he told Philbin how he had celebrated the night
before: with dinner from McDonald's. It is hard to imagine a more
Middle American value than that.
</P>
<P>
   Another white man brought his African-American girlfriend; the
camera went to her often, notably when he lost and she sweetly
mouthed the words, ``That's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Davies, the show's executive producer, says that
contestants are chosen on their ability to play the game, with no
questions asked about their private lives and no attempt to balance
the group by race or sex. (That must be true; surely there would
have been a greater range if they had tried.) In the quiz show
variation of ``don't ask, don't tell,'' loved ones are introduced
any way the contestants wish, with no one prodded to say ``friend''
instead of ``partner,'' or vice versa. As Davies says, each player
has a life story, and ``we tell their stories.'' Those
mini-narratives may seem like time fillers, but they give the show
its ``Our Town'' aura.
</P>
<P>
   Davies, English by birth, is in a good position to note the
differences between the original show and the American adaptation.
In England, people who want to become contestants are chosen at
random in the first round of screening, rather than qualifying
through a phone quiz as the Americans do. ``In this country,
lottery winners are not really respected because they never earned
it,'' Davies says.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the American and British shows are as similar as
two Starbucks, with a mirror-image set, the same searchlights and
clanging music, even the same phrases repeated by the host. ``It's
a good one,'' the English host says of a correct answer. (And we
thought that was a Regis line.) But where the English host
deliberately unsettles contestants, Philbin is a cheerleader. The
shows' franchised sameness may reveal the global-village unity of
the media age, but the differences in tone help explain the
American appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Part of America's diversity, of course, is the room it leaves
for opposing points of view. ``Do you feel the need for greed?''
Chuck Woolery asks his ``Greed'' contestants, waving piles of cash
under their noses, acting out the quiz show host as Mephistopheles.
Here, if contestants choose to move ahead, climbing what is called
``the Tower of Greed'' toward a jackpot of $2.2 million, they MUST
answer the question. And while a ``Millionaire'' contestant who
reaches $32,000 will leave with nothing less, on ``Greed'' a wrong
answer means losing everything _ except, that is, the $10,000 bonus
a player can get for eliminating a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   There is the essence of ``Greed.'' The show has a team of
players, but when a flashing light called ``The Terminator'' hits
one of them, that person gets to challenge a teammate to face off
on a single question. The loser leaves the game; the winner takes
his money. Behind the facade of teamwork, contestants are waiting
to stab each other. Turning a game show into a blood sport is not a
surprise, coming from the network that has given the world ``When
Good Pets Go Bad.'' And though nothing like the phenomenon of
``Millionaire,'' ``Greed,'' now in its third week, has been a
success for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   As a spectator sport, ``Greed'' is a more dramatic game than
``Millionaire.'' But it evokes uglier sentiments and brings in less
conventional contestants. In a blood sport, after all, the audience
needs villains as well as heroes. The less appealing players on
``Greed'' are not vile as in professional wrestling, but the
principle is the same. Along with wholesome types like historians
and librarians, its contestants have included an oversized
nightclub bouncer.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable contestant has been an air traffic controller
named Curtis, with a personality that veers between cocky and surly
and hair that seems a cross between Edward Scissorhands and a
porcupine. At the start of tonight's show (at 9) he and his two
teammates return to decide whether to risk the million dollars they
have won, taking a chance to double it.
</P>
<P>
   Why are there such eccentrics on ``Greed'' and not
``Millionaire''? Because on ``Greed,'' a contestant's entertainment
value counts. Bob Boden, an executive producer of the show (along
with Dick Clark), explains that in an early selection round,
potential contestants must pass a quiz as they do on
``Millionaire.'' After that, they audition by playing a test game
and are chosen not only on their skill but also on ``looks,
telegenic quality and personality,'' Boden says. ``Our goal is to
represent society with the greatest possible range.''
</P>
<P>
   These contestants are not model-gorgeous, either, but they are
not so uniformly, wholesomely Middle American as the
``Millionaire'' players. And they are not so dominated by white
men. (No one has a satisfactory explanation for that part of the
``Millionaire'' phenomenon, though the idea that men are quicker to
punch in keypad answers is high on the list of desperate guesses.)
</P>
<P>
   However contrived, ``Greed'' sends its own visceral message,
similar to the chilling one Michael Douglas delivers in Oliver
Stone's 1987 film, ``Wall Street.'' As Gordon Gekko, the snaky
financial genius, he proclaims, ``Greed is good,'' justifying
cutthroat competition as the foundation of American capitalism.
That may seem like a pure '80s vision, but it may also be ready for
a return in this healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   And game show viewers get to choose between two vicarious
experiences: they can be as happily competitive as Ben Franklin or
as savage as a Wall Street shark. One show offers an appealing
picturesque fantasy; the other may be closer to the truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
