<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LION-KING-THEATER-2TA     11-17 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LION-KING-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONDON ZOOLOGY OF LIONS LEARS AND LOST LOVES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Benedict Nightingale is the chief theater critic of The Times of
London.  
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ You want to know what has most exhilarated the London
critics this fall? No, it has not been the performance of Nigel
Hawthorne (star of the stage and screen versions of ``The Madness
of George III'') as the most celebrated of mentally challenged
monarchs in Yukio Ninagawa's revival of Shakespeare's ``King
Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not talking of the new plays by Alan Ayckbourn and Mark
Ravenhill that have recently hit the West End, or even of the
Redgrave siblings, Vanessa and Corin, though both are excellent in
Noel Coward's ``Song at Twilight'' at the Gielgud.
</P>
<P>
   What has left even The Sunday Times' intellectually rigorous
John Peter crying ``wonderful, wonderful'' is Julie Taymor's
restaging of her Broadway production of Disney's ``Lion King'' at
the Lyceum Theater here: a judgment confirmed by reports that the
show is booking until next September and that some Londoners are
mortgaging their mothers to meet the prices the scalpers are asking
for seats. But more of that remarkable musical and its reception in
a moment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, let's just say that if you are in search of
imaginative stimulus, neither Sir Nigel with his stringy white hair
nor Ms. Redgrave in her preposterous blond wig can compete with a
giraffe that resembles a multicolored wigwam topped by a skull-like
sculpture, or those stampeding satyrs in their huge wildebeest
masks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vanessa Redgrave brings a transforming magic to a revival
first staged with Corin but without her at a north London
pub-theater last January. ``Song at Twilight'' was always worth
including in this year's celebrations of Coward's centenary because
it is the most self-revealing, even self-accusing play he ever
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be sidetracked by the fact that the dramatist based his
protagonist, Sir Hugo Latymer, on Somerset Maugham and made the
portrait as charmless as he could. Like the real-life Maugham and
the fictional Latymer, Coward was a homosexual at a time when the
law combined with prejudice to make it perilous as well as
humiliating for any man to venture out of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps because this was an awkward, touchy subject back in
1966, when ``Song at Twilight'' first appeared, the dialogue
sometimes gets cumbersome. Certainly, the play lacks the confident
elegance of ``Private Lives'' or ``Design for Living.''
</P>
<P>
   Wit remains in short supply at the Gielgud; but the arrival of
Ms. Redgrave has brought fresh punch and stylishness to the
production, which is directed by one of Coward's biographers,
Sheridan Morley. Ms. Redgrave plays Carlotta, Latymer's mistress
before he found fame as a novelist, and the owner of the passionate
letters he wrote to a male lover who has recently died destitute.
</P>
<P>
   Is the lady intent on blackmail or revenge or something subtler?
Tough yet impish, Ms. Redgrave keeps both the audience and
Redgrave's Latymer guessing. Imagine one of Ms. Taymor's big,
trundling rhinos trying to cope with her nimble cheetah and you
have the rough zoology of their combat.
</P>
<P>
   Corin Redgrave recently demonstrated his ability to play hard,
implacable men in the London-Houston-New York production of
Tennessee Williams' prison drama, ``Not About Nightingales,'' and
he does so again here, adding the snappish sophistication the role
demands. He also finds a rawness and vulnerability inside Latymer's
thick leathery defenses.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps partly because she is so seldom seen on the stage
these days, it is Ms. Redgrave who grabs the attention, giving a
performance that ranges from sly mockery to quiet outrage. She
pricks her quarry's pomposity with skittish Beatles parodies and
unsettles him with jokily mimed kung-fu.
</P>
<P>
   She manipulates, she dominates _ and she fully explains why the
embattled Latymer ends up facing his own emotional dishonesty and
spiritual dereliction.
</P>
<P>
   Why is the Royal Shakespeare Company's ``Lear'' so
disappointing? After all, the production it has brought to the
Barbican, and is about to move to its Stratford headquarters,
begins as promisingly as any I have seen. Hardly has Nigel
Hawthorne bustled irritably onstage than we sense dangerous
tensions in his nervously bowing court: rivalry between Lear's
elder daughters for the attention of a father who does not even
bother to listen to their protestations of love, a preference for
Cordelia so overwhelming he dotingly places her on his throne,
unusually early signs of Goneril's sexual distaste for the husband
she will eventually try to have murdered. Yet the dramatic stakes
proceed to lessen, the emotional temperature to dip.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is because the production's most obvious strengths
turn out to be its prime weaknesses. Ninagawa is renowned for the
daring with which he combines Western texts with Japanese visual
effects, and, as he showed in ``The Madness of George III,'' Sir
Nigel is expert at embodying helpless anguish.
</P>
<P>
   But when Ninagawa spends the entire storm scene noisily dropping
small boulders from the flies, as if our all-too-familiar English
rain were a bizarre sort of bouncy granite, you fear for the king
in all the wrong ways. Not only may his brain end up even more
cracked than it is supposed to be: those rocks inevitably upstage a
Lear whose rants are already lacking in force and vindictiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his mildly menacing start, Sir Nigel proves too passive,
too underpowered, too kindly, too nice for Lear. After all,
Shakespeare is writing about a smug, proud tyrant who learns
through suffering what it means to be a mere man. He must travel
from A to Z, not just from M to N, generating a rare intensity of
pain and depth of anger en route. But Sir Nigel plays even the
maddest scenes for pathos and a wry humor that sometimes had the
first-night audience laughing when it might have been gulping.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the production is likely to be remembered partly for
Ninagawa's ability to rivet you with majestic parades that glide
past towering walls embossed with Oriental flowers, partly for such
supporting performances as Sian Thomas' Goneril, who bucks current
trends by refusing to suggest psychological excuses for her
beastliness and being bluntly, boldly, ferociously evil.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who was offended by the violent sadomasochism in Mark
Ravenhill's ``Shopping and ... '' can be reassured that his new
play contains nothing more openly shocking than the sight of a gay
Russian hedonist trying to bring the corpse of his British lover
back to sexual life. The disturbing thing about ``Some Explicit
Polaroids,'' which has just left London for a regional tour, is its
dated obsession with the c-word, which is of course capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the younger generation of British playwrights,
Ravenhill sees contemporary urban life as empty and lawless, but,
unlike any of them, he clearly hankers for an era when Margaret
Thatcher had not fully happened, Socialist ideology still had power
over minds, hearts and events, and left-wing writers felt they
might change the world.
</P>
<P>
   All the skills of Max Stafford Clark's Out of Joint Company
cannot conceal the plot's basic unsubtlety. Imagine Rip Van Winkle
reawakening in one of the universe's black holes, and you have Nick
Dunning's infinitely glum Nick, a Marxist class-warrior who has
returned to London after a long prison sentence for maiming some
wealthy entrepreneur. All the people he encounters seem to be
selling their bodies, or dancing in sleazy nightclubs, or letting
themselves be beaten up by their partners, or refusing the drugs
that might stop AIDS from killing them, or running for parliament
on the Tony Blair ticket, or otherwise displaying what Ravenhill
sees as passivity, selfishness and loss of faith.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatist's picture of Britain today is vivid and troubling
if not exactly balanced. But is nostalgia for the big political
battles of the past really the answer to the nation's woes?
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Alan Ayckbourn looks to the future and doesn't much
like what he sees. He has dabbled in sci-fi before, notably in
``Henceforward,'' in which robots were worryingly apt to go awry,
putting babies in microwaves and pies in cots. But in ``Comic
Potential,'' artificial intelligence wreaks only aesthetic
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The soaps of tomorrow are being performed by android actors.
Dress one of these in a long green gown, feed a plot into a
computer, press the emotion button when a child expires or vengeful
surgeons start hurling scalpels at each other _ and, lo, you have
``Son of Chicago Hope'' or its British counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   So what's new? Isn't that pretty much what's happening right
now? Well, work set in the future often satirizes the present; and
``Comic Potential'' is at its best when it involves the practice
and politics of dumbed-down television. We get a terrifying tycoon
in a wheelchair, a venomous station manager and an android doctor
who, thanks to cuts in the machine-maintenance budget, tells an
android sportsman on air that he is going to amputate his foot ``at
the uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   But the unseemly giggles of a robot nurse at this point combine
with the arrival in the studio of an idealistic young writer to
push the play in a new direction. Janie Dee's Jacey is developing
human reactions; Matthew Cottle's Adam falls in love with her; the
1970s American television star David Soul, playing a crusty
American director who yearns for the good old days of the 20th
century, gives them encouragement; and Alan Ayckbourn gets
unwontedly sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   True, there are some hilarious moments when Adam and Jacey run
off together. Perhaps you recall the scene in ``Pygmalion'' in
which Shaw's Eliza Dolittle causes consternation at a posh tea
party by saying rude things in a genteel accent? Dee's attractively
ingenuous android has a comparable impact on diners, waiters, shop
assistants and even the knife-wielding pimp she hurls to the
ground, yelling like the lesbian cop she played in yet another
soap.
</P>
<P>
   But her author's attempts to find pathos in her predicament and
poignancy in her romance _ well, how would you feel if the Tin Man
started an affair with Dorothy at the end of ``The Wizard of Oz''?
Not great, that's how.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 1999 has not been a notable year for new work in the
British theater. Revivals have filled the gap, along with the
occasional American import, such as Richard Greenberg's ``Three
Days of Rain,'' which has brought Elizabeth McGovern to the Donmar,
and Donald Margulies' ``Collected Stories,'' now with Helen Mirren
at the Haymarket.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been a long time since a Broadway musical had as much
impact in London as, say, ``The Phantom of the Opera'' and ``Les
Miserables'' have had in New York. John Peter's acclamation of ``a
wonderful, wonderful musical, thrilling, warm-hearted, inventive
and original'' wasn't the only highbrow hosanna to ``The Lion
King.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph called the show ``dazzling,'' The
Independent declared that ``pure delight floods the Lyceum,'' and
The Daily Mail announced that ``it restores true magic to the West
End.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, I felt much the same way. The changes from the show
now running on Broadway are minimal, scarcely more than a matter of
conceding that, though wisecracking meerkats obviously originate in
Brooklyn, other African-based animals are as likely to have British
as American accents.
</P>
<P>
   Myself, I was still slightly troubled by the schism between the
wonderful Zulu chants and the sometimes clunky dialogue _ but how
could anyone but a terminal curmudgeon beef about a show that,
thanks to Ms. Taymor's bravura with puppets and masks and just
about everything else, might be a ritual retelling of an exemplary
tale of death and rebirth on the Dark Continent?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
