<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT MEMBERS TO URGE YELTSIN TO SETTLE CONFLICT WITH CHECHNYA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Russia, defending its attacks on Chechnya
citizens and battling a Western-backed oil pipeline, intends to
face its accusers Thursday as a European security summit opens with
world leaders pondering how to handle the former superpower.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-member Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, the region's crisis management group, initially planned to
craft a blueprint for its 21st century security needs and a new
pact on conventional forces in the wake of the Soviet Union's
demise.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia, an OSCE member, remains very much on the agenda. The
organization is moving to pressure Moscow to stop its military
action and negotiate with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin arrived Wednesday, telling reporters he
will change the minds of his Western critics. Yeltsin renewed
Moscow's campaign against Muslim rebels following a series of
summer bombings in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope everybody will understand that Russia is acting in
Chechnya in accordance with international, civilized rules and
norms,'' Yeltsin said in an Interfax news agency report. ``I hope
common sense will prevail with those who have not been ready for
that so far.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will meet on Thursday with Yeltsin to express
concern over Moscow's retaliatory military campaign, which has
claimed the lives of hundreds in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen representatives also arrived in Istanbul to make their
case to OSCE leaders, but Clinton had no plans to meet with them.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the president's national security
adviser, said the president will stress to Yeltsin that Russia's
current strategy will be unproductive and that Moscow should
negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Russia has a right to fight terrorism within its
borders. Clearly, this round was begun by Chechen rebels attacking
Dagestan. But our concern here is that the means being used are
causing inordinate harm to civilians,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the United States expected other world leaders
from Europe to Asia to voice similar concerns to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe virtually everybody here wants Russia to succeed in its
transformation that it's been undergoing for the last 10 years, to
a working democracy with a working economy, with having shed its
empire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   OSCE officials have conducted fact-finding tours into Chechnya
and are expected to report to their members this week. OSCE also is
undergoing a charter revision that will stress its role as an
``instrument of conflict prevention in troubled regions'' before
conflict begins, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian campaign presents a delicate issue for the West.
U.S. jets pounded Yugoslavia last spring as the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization mounted a campaign to protect
independence-minded Kosovars who were under attack by Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Russians have accused the West of hypocrisy on the Chechnya
issue because of its bombing of civilian targets in Yugoslavia. Joe
Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said NATO forces took
extraordinary steps to protect civilian lives during the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   A key reason for Russia's campaign against the Islamic rebels of
Chechnya involves its oil supply. The major Caspian Sea oil
pipeline passes through the Chechen capital of Grozny from Baku,
Azerbaijan, to the Russia port city of Novorossiysk. The pipeline
has been closed because of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has accused the West of attempting to undermine its
influence in the region where oil reserves could rival those in the
North Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Russia's opposition, Clinton intends to watch Thursday
as Azerbaijan, Georgia and Turkey sign a pact on a $2.4 billion,
1,200-mile oil pipeline from Baku to Turkey's Mediterranean port of
Ceyhan. Russia last weekend sent envoys on an unsuccessful mission
to persuade Azerbaijan to scuttle the deal. The same three nations
will join Turkmenistan for a second agreement on a natural gas
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements stem from a diplomatic push by the Clinton
administration to encourage the construction of a pipeline that
would bypass Iran.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official who spoke to reporters
Wednesday attempted to soft-peddle the impact on Moscow, noting
Russia's Lukoil is part of the 10-member oil consortium called
Azerbaijan International Operating Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are part of this package,'' the official said.
``We would welcome Russian oil into Baku-Ceyhan. So it's not
excluding them; it's just a different kind of cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal agreements being signed today will allow the
construction of the oil and gas pipelines. But not all oil
companies have signed onto the plan. A senior administration
official suggested their reluctance may be a negotiating position.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the price is right and the risks are in line then they're
going to have to go to Ceyhan,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the official conceded the pipeline plans have a long way
to go to fruition. ``But this first step is quite historic, this
kind of cooperation, this kind of economic and political
cooperation just hasn't happened among these countries,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took the advantage of the gathering of leaders to meet
privately with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. Negotiations
between the Israelis and Palestinians have hit a rough spot over
which portions of the West Banks the Israelis will hand over.
</P>
<P>
   Berger reported there was no breakthrough after the 35-minute
meeting, but declined to discuss specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told Israeli reporters: ``We discussed progress on all
tracks of the peace process.'' Israeli officials described the
atmosphere as ``very positive and warm.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the fourth day of a 10-day trip to southeastern
Europe, also played the tourist. First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and daughter Chelsea joined the president on a walking tour of the
ancient city of Ephesus, a major archaeological site near the
Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   After the two-day OSCE summit, the president will travel to
Greece, Italy, Bulgaria, Macedonia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
