<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-COLLECTIBLES-DISPLAY-     11-17 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECTIBLES-DISPLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL YOU, NOW ON VIEW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Fla., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life just gets curiouser and curiouser.
</P>
<P>
   With more than $10 billion in sales of manufactured collectibles
last year _ a category whose best sellers include Beanie Babies,
the beanbag toys; Precious Moments, porcelain figures with
inspirational messages; and Department 56, a line of miniature
buildings _ American furniture manufacturers have figured out that
adult collectors, who now number more than 36 million, could use a
place to put it all.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the collector's cabinet, or curio, as the industry calls
it: a glass-fronted, glass-sided, glass-shelved living room
sarcophagus the size of a small-town bank vault. It lights up; it
locks. New Yorkers might be more tempted to sublet it than use it
for display.
</P>
<P>
   The curio _ or the power curio, the leading edge of the trend
(at 50 inches or wider and up to 82 inches tall, it is more R.V.
than armoire) _ is the retail-furniture business' acknowledgment of
collecting's grip on the nation's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major companies have targeted collectibles display as a growth
area,'' said Pam Danziger, the publisher of the Collectibles
Industry Report, because baby boomers, the bulk of the market for
both collecting and furniture buying, ``buy collectibles for the
purpose of decorating.'' Ms. Danziger estimated last year's sales
figure for curios and other display pieces at $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Christley, the senior vice president for sales at the
Pulaski Furniture Corp. in Pulaski, Va., which offers 175 curio
models ranging from $199 to $3,000, said: ``We came to the
realization that we weren't in the furniture industry but the
collectibles industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulaski, which became a licensee for Precious Moments in 1998,
advertises in magazines like Teddy Bear and Friends but not House
Beautiful. It is trying to capture buyers with cabinets specific to
popular collectibles. A curio for die-cast Nascar racers has a
carved car pediment and a mirrored racetrack background. A
golf-ball curio has tees set in glass shelves. A cabinet for dolls,
a category that with figurines like Precious Moments accounts for
57 percent of the collectibles market, employs standard light bulbs
_ not halogen, a popular new curio feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't have halogen lighting on a doll,'' Christley said. ``It
will change the color of her hair. You have to think about things
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   With sales exceeding $200 million this year, curios represent
half of Pulaski's business. An optional brass plaque, which
commemorates the purchase as a gift for a special occasion, such as
a birthday or wedding, makes the cabinet itself a collectible,
Christley added.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pulaski has included curios in its line of occasional
furniture for 15 years, other manufacturers have flooded the field
in the last two years, including unlikely high-end companies like
Henredon, which now has 31 curios at prices up to $11,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing a dust-free display that also keeps
collectibles safe from children and pets, the curio is being
promoted as a kind of show-and-tell for adults who don't collect,
to put on view prize possessions or family mementos: a pocket
museum, a three-dimensional scrapbook page or a supertitle that
says to visitors, ``These are a few of my favorite things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we're experiencing, it's becoming part of the
living room,'' said Carlos Capo, a co-owner and merchandising vice
president of El Dorado Furniture in Miami, a furniture retailer
with seven locations and $60 million in sales last year. Capo
stocks 36 models in his stores, including his newest, at $2,299,
which has a dome ``like a cathedral in Italy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago we were selling 300 curios a year,'' Capo
recalled. ``Now, it's over 1,000. Many people aren't looking for
curios when they come into the store; they're shopping for the
living room or family room. They see the curios and realize it's
not just for collectors, it's for memories, nice things from trips,
instead of putting them in drawers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Moultry Howard, who bought a wrought-iron curio from
Capo for her house in Cooper City, Fla., keeps crystal figurines
and wooden elephants in it. ``It caught my eye. It was quite
unique,'' she said. For Ms. Howard, the $1,199 curio has created a
collecting problem rather than solving one. ``Before I had the
cabinet, I didn't buy all that crystal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Swift, the buyer for Kerr's Furniture Showroom in Butler,
Pa., and the store's interior designer, has watched curio sales
double in two years. They are now her strongest Christmas item.
Recliners are No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men come in on Christmas Eve and haul a $1,200 curio off the
floor for their wives,'' she said. Ms. Swift is pleased by the
trend but baffled by the phenomenon. ``I do a lot of in-home
design,'' she explained. ``I have a gentleman who collects little
motorcycles. I have a lady who collects clowns. I don't collect;
I'm amazed at how much stuff people have.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Swift was recently reminded, it all stays behind, like
the moral to a tale. She decorated the reception rooms of a local
funeral home with curio cabinets that can be used to display
touching personal effects: a sparkling afterlife of objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They worked exceptionally well in that situation,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
