<HEADLINE>
GEEK NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking Some of the Tedium Out of Checking Footnotes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twelve scientific and scholarly publishers this week announced
an electronic reference-linking service that will allow researchers
to move easily from a citation in a journal article to the content
of that article with a click or two of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The new service will eliminate the multiple, often cumbersome
steps now required to look up a reference or footnote, said Susan
Spilka, a spokeswoman for John Wiley &AMP; Sons, one of the members of
the new partnership.
</P>
<P>
   At first, approximately 3 million articles from 3,000 journals
will be linked through the service, and more than half a million
more articles will be linked each year thereafter, Ms. Spilka said.
Among the other partners are the American Association for the
Advancement of Science, Elsevier Science, Kluwer Academic
Publishers and Nature.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Spilka said the partnership was not limited. She called
the collaboration an ``open initiative'' and said that other
journal publishers were invited to join at any time. ``More are
being added as we go forward,'' she said. The service is expected
to begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATIE HAFNER
</P>
<P>
   The Same Old Old Faithful, With a Newfangled Twist
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the only way to see the country's most famous
geyser, Old Faithful, in action was to trek to Yellowstone National
Park in northwestern Wyoming and wait in long lines or freezing
temperatures to see it spout steam high into the air.
</P>
<P>
   But now it can be seen in real time from the comfort of home or
office. The National Park Service has set up the Old Faithful
WebCam, (www.nps.gov/yell/oldfaithfulcam.htm), to offer a still
image of the geyser that is updated every 35 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Park naturalists are usually available to post predictions for
eruptions, which occur every 80 to 90 minutes (predictions will
resume Dec. 15 when the Old Faithful Visitor Center reopens.) The
eruptions are dramatic, but the geyser is hardly inactive between
them, with small white and gray plumes that can have a hypnotic
effect on the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MINDY SINK
</P>
<P>
   Calendars Made for Sharing, For the Online and Handheld Set
</P>
<P>
   The Internet calendar craze has moved to handheld devices.
WeSync.com not only lets you create an online calendar but lets you
share it with family and friends by synching it to a Palm Pilot or
any other device running the Palm Operating System. Companies have
been using shared online calendars for several years, but the
concept is just now moving to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that it will be valuable to have family members share
data about their activities,'' said WeSync.com president Pete
Grillo. . ``The service takes on the aspect of an electronic
bulletin board because each person who has permission can update
the shared calendar.''
</P>
<P>
   The WeSync software also lets you view multiple calendars on a
Palm device. You could create a business calendar, one for the
family and one for golfing buddies, listing tee times.
</P>
<P>
   The software, available on the company's Web site
(www.wesync.com), is free, but it runs advertisements on your PC
during synchronization. No ads are loaded on the handheld device.
``We don't want to do anything to adversely affect the Palm user's
experience,'' Grillo said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN C. MILLER
</P>
<P>
   The Band Plays On: The Nonstop MP3
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get enough of MP3.com's free musical downloads,
well, now maybe you can. A new MP3 player, Personal JukeBox, can
carry 81 hours of high-quality digital music _ that equals about
1,200 songs, estimates the manufacturer, HanGo Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   The device, which was designed by Compaq, is about 6 inches by 3
inches by 1 inch, weighs about 10 ounces and incorporates a
miniature hard drive that stores the tunes. Other MP3 players on
the market store music in memory chips and are limited to storing
about two hours or less.
</P>
<P>
   The Personal JukeBox's rechargable lithium ion battery is
estimated to allow 10 hours of play after a full 3-hour charge. A
10-minute memory buffer reduces the chance the music will skip,
even if the box is jolted. The unit attaches to a desktop computer
with a USB cable and comes with management software that lets
listeners organize music by category, like jazz or pop, which is
displayed along with band name, song name, volume and time
indicator.
</P>
<P>
   Although well suited for MP3 downloads, some computer CD-ROM
drives aren't compatible with the player, which means you can't
always capture from CDs. The device, which will be available in
stores next month, will cost $750 to $850.
</P>
<P>
   If 81 hours of music still isn't enough, don't worry. The
specification sheet indicates that a newer drive might hold 140
hours of music _ almost a week's worth of tunes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROY FURCHGOTT
</P>
<P>
   An Easy Way to Expand A Laptop's Hard Drive  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Microtech International wants to make it easy to add gigabytes
of additional hard drive space to the often skimpy capacity of
portable computers. Its new PortableDrive 25 is a slim box that
contains a 2.5-inch IDE hard drive with connectors that plug into a
laptop's USB port or PCMCIA card slot.
</P>
<P>
   This external device comes in a range of hard drive sizes, from
4.3 to 10 gigabytes. While data transfer rates are slower than
internal drives, a Microtech spokesman said the
four-megabyte-per-second transfer rate (using a PCMCIA connection)
was fast enough to run applications from the PortableDrive 25
``adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Balce, director of sales and marketing for Microtech's
portable storage division, said the device was a dependable method
for backing up data as well as for storing sensitive data in
corporate environments in which laptops and notebooks were shared.
The PortableDrive 25 is available in a do-it-yourself version
($99), essentially a box in which you install your own hard drive.
Balce said that was an excellent way to regain the use of a drive
that had been swapped out of a laptop for a larger one.
</P>
<P>
   The PortableDrive 25 is only sold online, at sites that include
Microtech's, www.microtech-pc.com. Prices for the device, with a
drive installed, range from $399 for 4.3 gigabtyes to $939 for 10.
It requires Windows 95 or 98. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   New TV Software Allows Instant Language Translations
</P>
<P>
   Just when the French have started rioting against the
encroachment of American culture, new technology has arrived to
enable the latest episode of ``Dawson's Creek'' to be broadcast
with French subtitles in France _ at the same time it appears in
the United States in English.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, GlobalTV, was created by Multilingual Media, a
new company based in Natick, Mass. It is based upon proprietary
translation software that takes the words typed for closed captions
and almost instantaneously translates them into different
languages. English captions can be converted into Spanish,
Portuguese, Italian, German and French. French, German and Spanish
captions can be translated into English.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the creators of GlobalTV will tell you, the
technology was not designed to multiply the audience for ``Dawson's
Creek'' or other popular soap operas, at least not primarily. Its
purpose is to enable people worldwide to watch news programs in
their own language as soon as the news breaks.
</P>
<P>
   For television to be a global medium, said Multilingual Media
president and chief executive Larry Silverman, ``you have to be
able to access it in your own language.'' Until more people have
access to the same news programs that English-speaking people enjoy
daily, he added, it is as if ``the rest of the world really is made
up of second-class citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverman said Multilingual Media was marketing its product to
international cable companies and to networks like CNN and the
International Channel. Someday, he predicted, people will be able
to buy television sets that are already equipped with the software.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Entrusting Medical Data To an Internet Site  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of privacy, few things are as sacrosanct as
personal medical records. So when PersonalMD.com, a Web site that
began operating this summer, offered to store records on line so
that in emergencies doctors anywhere could retrieve them, skeptics
doubted there would be many takers.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's representatives say that so far more than
60,000 people have become members of its Web site
(www.personalmd.com) and that more of them are uploading their
medical histories.
</P>
<P>
   PersonalMD.com chief executive Suresh Challa said lives could be
saved by having medical records sent quickly to emergency rooms. By
putting information like a person's blood type and EKG and other
medical data online, it can be made available almost
instantaneously for doctors and other medical workers.
</P>
<P>
   The information can also be sent by fax to the many emergency
rooms that do not have Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Challa said that the medical information on the site was
encrypted for security and that someone could gain access only with
a password and PIN code.
</P>
<P>
   PersonalMD.com is not alone. MedicalRecords.com is also parking
medical records in cyberspace for rapid delivery to doctors and
hospitals around the world in cases of emergencies. The records are
also available if doctors need to treat people who are traveling
far from home.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who suffered a serious allergic reaction while traveling
in Mongolia said she had been able to get the proper medication
when doctors there quickly got her medical history at
www.medicalrecords.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   Techie Sneakers That Measure A Child's Personal Best
</P>
<P>
   Starting in December, there may be a new sound at recess:
electronic beeps emanating from a new line of children's sneakers
by Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   Called Traxtars, the shoes attempt to go one better than the
ever-popular sneakers with flashing lights in the soles. They can
measure, record and signal a child's running or jumping ability.
</P>
<P>
   A microcomputer encased in what Reebok calls a pod is attached
to the tongue of the left shoe. This pod includes three buttons
represented by symbols for a sprint, long jump and high jump. Press
the button for the long jump, and a series of beeps, accompanied by
flashing lights, provides an electronic countdown of ready, set,
go. That's when the shoe tells its wearer to, well, take a running
leap.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the child lands or stops running, sensors embedded in
the pod take note. The child then receives a score of one to six,
again in a series of beeps. By checking that score against an
information card that comes with the shoes, children can find out
approximate measurements for how fast they ran or how high and far
they jumped. The shoes can also remember previous scores and will
signal when a new level of athletic skill has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much in the spirit of getting kids off the couch,
not playing video games,'' said Matt Feiner, director of children's
products for Reebok. The shoes, which go on sale in selected
markets listed on the Traxtar.com Web site, will sell for $55 and
$65, depending on the shoe size.
</P>
<P>
   Feiner said the shoes were just the first in a line of Reebok
footwear and accessories (like sunglasses) that would be endowed
with intelligence. No word, though, on when or if smarty pants may
make it to market.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
