<HEADLINE>
POPULAR PLACES TO SHOP ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Online Shoppers, a Virtual Mall as Big as All Cyberspace
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling, by no means complete, of popular places to
shop online, with examples of what each sells.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON.COM: www.amazon.com _ The granddaddy of book sites has
branched into home electronics, music and zstores, an online bazaar
for small businesses and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES AND NOBLE: www.barnesandnoble.com/ _ The brick-and-mortar
retailer's online division sells books, magazines and calendars,
and it offers downloadable titles for the Rocket eBook.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK BUYERS OUTLET: www.bookbuyer.com/ _ An online store for
books, games, software and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANCED BOOK EXCHANGE: www.abebooks.com _ A source for out of
print titles. The site boasts that it has 5,300 book sellers and 15
million titles.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS: www.borders.com/ _ The home page offers books, music
and videos, and, like other online bookstores, Oprah's latest pick.
</P>
<P>
   1BOOKSTREET.COM: www.1bookstreet.com/ _ This site sells books
only, but it also has an online mystery magazine called ``Hard
Evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   POWELLS: www.powells.com/ _ This retailer has rare titles and
used hardcover and paperback editions, and it offers
recommendations from independent book sellers.
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHING
</P>
<P>
   ASHFORD.COM: www.ashford.com/ _ The store offers accessories
like leather bags, sunglasses and jewelry. It also offers watches,
new and vintage, including a Rolex watch from the 1950s for around
$2,700.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE FLY: www.bluefly.com/ _ Blue Fly offers discounts on
designer apparel and accessories, from long-sleeve shirts by
Sweetpea to glassware by Mikasa, with short profiles about most of
the designers.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKS BROTHERS: www.brooksbrothers.com/ _ The quintessential
men's store has dressed Presidents Lincoln and Kennedy, and
heartthrobs like Clark Gable and Cary Grant, and the store takes
credit for introducing the argyle sock to America in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   LANDS' END: www.landsend.com/ _ Everyday fashions, even school
uniforms, for everyone. There are images in full color, sizing
charts and even an interactive on-screen body image for women to
try on various outfits.
</P>
<P>
   L.L. BEAN: www.llbean.com/ _ The Maine retailer sells lots of
cozy winter clothes at this time of year, in addition to outdoor
gear like sleeping bags rated to minus 20 degrees Fahrenheit and
aluminum snowshoes.
</P>
<P>
   SHE GETS DRESSED: www.shegetsdressed.com _ This online boutique
has a small selection, but enough to outfit a working girl from
scarf to shoes.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS
</P>
<P>
   APPLE: www.apple.com/ _ The iMac and the iBook are featured
along with software and peripherals for the personal computer that
offers an alternative to a Windows-based system.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUSA: www.compusa.com/ _ Everything a shopper would find in a
CompUSA store, from books to computers. Customers can build a
computer or look for a deal on existing systems.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERMARKET.COM: www.gocybermarket.com/ _ Cybermarket is one of
dozens of online retailers that sell computers, software,
peripherals and parts. There is a detailed search engine but not
much descriptive text and not every model is always available.
</P>
<P>
   DELL: www.dell.com _ All sorts of computers, from desktop to
notebook, which can be built to customer specifications. There are
also refurbished computers that come with the same guarantees as
the new models, and peripherals and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   GATEWAY: www.gateway.com/home/ _ The Gimbels to Dell's Macy's,
Gateway offers similar products and services, including limited
on-site labor and parts replacement. Like Dell, it also has digital
cameras and scanners.
</P>
<P>
   DEPARTMENT STORES/MALLS
</P>
<P>
   HARRODS: www.harrods.com/global/index.htm _ The premiere British
department store sells apparel, electronics and toys. And then
there are the store's own blends of tea and tins of biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   iMALL.com: www.imall.com _ This shop-by-category site is made up
of small merchants like the NY Sock Exchange,
www.nysockexchange.com/, and the Power Marketing Group,
www.imall.com/stores/pmg/pmg.html, which sells ``The Belle Figure
Liposome Reducing System,'' an herbal product to help customers
lose ``measurable inches of excess fat in 24 hours,'' for $189.95.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's: www.macys.com/ _ The home page for the all-American
department store features fashions, furnishings and fragrances, and
a link to pages for the 73rd annual Thanksgiving Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Value America: www.valueamerica.com/ _ The site sells mainstream
products from vendors like Seiko, Compaq, Black &AMP; Decker, Addidas,
Polaroid and Bic. It also sells lesser-known items like Replogle
globes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   Chukar Cherry Co.: www.chukar.com/ _ Chukar sells trail mix,
chocolates, preserves and sauces, but its signature product is
fruit: three kinds of dried cherries, plus dried blueberries,
cranberries and strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Great Food.com: www.greatfood.com/consumer/default.asp _ Foods,
searchable from appetizers to vegetables. A shopper can also search
by choosing the type of meal being planned, including backpacking,
cocktail party, tailgating, romantic meal and Easter dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Hotta Mo Betta:www.mohotta.com/ _ Hot and spicy sauces of all
kinds, from Mean Mama Jamma's Zombie Juice to Crazy Charley
Bar-B-Cue Sauce, with a chart that ranks the fiery products.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Cookie Co.: www.pacificcookie.com/ _ The classic cookies
like chocolate chip, oatmeal and lemon drop, plus chocolate cherry
pecan and ``mint condition,'' a double chocolate cookie with green
mint chips.
</P>
<P>
   Pangea: www.pangeaveg.com/ _ This store in Bethesda, Md., offers
vegan foods and other products like household cleaners or shoes
that are not made from animals products. There is Vegan
Worcestershire Sauce, Dairy-Free Macaroni and Cheese and
VeganSweets Donuts.
</P>
<P>
   HOME
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com: www.furniture.com/ _ The furniture is sold like
in a store, arranged by rooms. Consumers can use a search engine to
choose styles, colors and a price range, everything but sit on the
couch.
</P>
<P>
   Garden.com: www2.garden.com/ _ The site offers 20,000 products,
including seeds, bulbs, plants and trees, garden furniture, tools
and books on garden design and getting started.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen Classics: www.kitchen-classics.com/ _ Cooks can fill a
kitchen with products like pots and pans, knives, mixers, food
processors, cookbooks, utensils, cutting boards and measuring cups,
and, if they are in Phoenix, they can take some cooking classes.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen Emporium: www.kitchenemporium.com/ _ Everything for the
kitchen but the you-know-what: there are pasta machines, fondue
sets, cutlery, cookbooks, pots and pans, deep fryers, ice cream
makers, wine racks, kitchen carts, gravy boats, serving platters,
rice steamers, coffee makers and timers.
</P>
<P>
   S. Timberlake: www.stimberlake.com/ _ This Bethel, Maine,
company, one of hundreds of small furniture companies online,
offers reproduction Shaker tables, benches, chairs, tables and
dressers.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker Palace: www.wickerpalace.com/ _ The company does not have
a printed catalog for its bathroom vanity, planter, cabinets and
foyer table, so customers have to shop online or go to
Friedensburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   TOYS
</P>
<P>
   Etoys.com: www.etoys.com/ _ Customers can search by age, brand
name and categories like make believe, dolls, stuffed toys and
radio control. There are sections featuring 50 favorite toys for
each age group, finds from small toymakers, and, to remind boomers
of their childhood, classic toys like Potato Head, Tinker Toys,
Easy Bake Oven and Viewmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Shop Heaven.com: www.shopheaven.com/ _ Shop Heaven sells various
products, including toys, and it has a search feature that many
aunts, uncles and grandparents will appreciate: the ability to
search for gifts for teen-agers in different price ranges. For
instance, a search for gifts under $60 shows a Groucho Marx dummy
that teenagers can program with their own wisecracks ($48).
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us: www.toysrus.com/ _ The site for the store chain has
the full lineup of children's favorites _ Barbie, Lego, Nintendo
64, and, of course, Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com: www.toysmart.com/ _ Toysmart sells toys designed
to promote learning and imagination, like Brio wooden train sets,
rattles to encourage motor development and products from Go Fly a
Kite. The site has articles and tips for parents, kids and teachers
for everything from understanding dyslexia to how to hang pictures
in classrooms with cement walls.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE
</P>
<P>
   Beyond.com: www.beyond.com _ Beyond.com, like other sites, sells
software and computers, books and handheld items. The site is
organized by category, with many software titles, articles and
information, and a breakdown of software by publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Egghead: www.egghead.com/ _ Once a brick-and-mortar store,
Egghead now sells its software, hardware and peripherals
exclusively over the Internet. The software is searchable by
categories, like home, education or productivity, and customers can
check out an auction section and liquidations to find good deals.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet: www.zdnet.com/ _ ZDNet is an all-purpose site, with
reviews and information on shopping, Internet, computers and
technology. The shopping section offers an outlet store, auction
links, a holiday guide and lots of products.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   Fogdog: www.fogdog.com/ _ In addition to the usual sports,
Fogdog offers products for cheerleading, fishing, motocross, diving
and wrestling.
