<SLUG> BC-EAMES-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AN EAMES, THE LEGACY IS CHILD'S PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TOM VANDERBILT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 38, Eames Demetrios, grandson of the influential
designers Charles and Ray Eames, recalls visits to his
grandparents' house with a child's sense of adventure. Who wouldn't
relish rummaging through the vast storehouse at 901 Washington
Blvd. in Venice, Calif. _ the trolley factory turned Eameses'
studio _ with its countless totems and toys, musical contraptions,
models and banks of drawers stuffed with objects from around the
world?
</P>
<P>
   Young Eames even managed to get his pudgy fingers onto the
screen in his grandparents' film ``Tops,'' a sublime seven-minute
homage to the toy. Years later, that film and those fingers are on
the wall of the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum, where adults
(and children) are savoring ``Charles and Ray Eames: A Legacy of
Invention,'' an exhibition midway through its tour of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Demetrios has applied his now more slender fingers to shooting
hours of films, hundreds of stills and helping to create a CD-ROM
in an attempt to understand his grandparents' storied legacy and
pass it on to others.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing a visitor notices at the exhibition are
children: sitting on the floor, watching with fascination as an
Eames plywood chair takes a beating (but keeps on seating) inside a
rotating chamber that Charles Eames created to demonstrate its
durability; or spinning gleefully in the designers' classic black
leather lounge chair.
</P>
<P>
   The work has a kind of youthful optimism, and touring the
exhibition with Demetrios, it is easy to sense his enchantment.
Memory inhabits every turn. He eagerly shows a visitor the rebus
letter Charles Eames sent to his grandchildren from Russia. (It was
signed with ``L's'' in a fire _ charred ``L's,'' of course,
standing for Charles.)
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last 10 years, Demetrios and his mother, Lucia
Eames Demetrios, have been working and living with these memories.
As director of the Eames Office, with a dozen employees, Demetrios
preserves and markets the designers' legacy, sometimes at the
expense of creating his own. It is, he admits, ``a balancing act,
but it's one that I'm enjoying right now.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Harvard University, Demetrios gained
attention with ``901: After 45 Years of Working,'' an elegiac
half-hour 1989 film documenting the closing of the Eameses' office
in Venice, Calif., after Ray's death in 1988. With Demetrios'
sparse narration and hurdy-gurdy in the background (the sound is
Charles' beloved hand-cranked organ), the film explores every last
corner of the office. ``Even empty,'' Demetrios said at the film's
conclusion, ``there was a way the space was carved that was still
Charles' and Ray's.''
</P>
<P>
   As curator of the film and media components of the exhibition,
Demetrios is also trying to reassert the importance of the Eameses'
own photography and films. They made more than 100 short features;
many had no narration, others avoided pedanticism. The couple's
films aim to instill wonder and curiosity in viewers. At the
museum, visitors _ especially children _ crane to decipher the
shimmering patterns projected on the floor in their short
``Blacktop.'' It was created by hosing soapy water over asphalt but
looks more like an extraterrestrial ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Demetrios' interviews with friends and associates of the
designers, ranging from employees to other family members to the
composer Elmer Bernstein, form the opening segment of the
exhibition, and a number of them have been collected on a CD-ROM.
The CD-ROM, called ``Powers of 10,'' after the Eameses' 1968 film,
which might be their best-known effort other than a chair, takes a
look at scale. Unfortunately, while the idea of an interactive
version is certainly in the spirit of the Eameses' work, the CD-ROM
lacks their simplicity and directness.
</P>
<P>
   In a kind of electronic corollary to the retranscribing of
medieval texts, Demetrios also spent a year rephotographing images
in ``Glimpses of the USA,'' the pair's seven-screen presentation of
clover-leaf highways, freshly minted suburbs and other icons of
postwar America that dazzled Muscovites at the 1959 American
National Exhibition in Moscow but was never seen in the United
States. With the original negatives lost, the images were reshot,
one by one, with a still camera, and color corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Ray Eames' exhaustive photographs account for nearly
5 percent of the Prints and Photographs Division of the Library of
Congress, the largest photo archive in the world. Theirs was not
just a penchant for snapshots, but a process that informed their
work and organized their thoughts. ``Charles didn't feel he
understood a piece of furniture until he had photographed it,''
Demetrios said. ``It allowed him to have a fresh look.'' Like a
dominant trait, that need to make a visual record has passed down
to Demetrios and the four other Eames grandchildren, all with
design or artistic backgrounds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Demetrios shuttles between the Eames Office in Santa Monica,
where activities range from issuing textile patterns for the Eames
sofa, and England, where he is finishing work on an oral history of
the century as told by people born in 1900. He is also shooting a
documentary on the Emeco anodized aluminum chairs commissioned by
the Navy (and built in conjunction with Alcoa) in 1944. The chairs,
which relate only to the Eameses in their simplicity, have evolved
into a design staple, and he admires their ability to seem at home
in a number of settings. ``If you went to a diner on the Eastern
Shore, it would not look out of place,'' he said. Yet it's at the
Paramount Hotel in Manhattan, ``and that's fine too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He shares a house minutes away from the new Eames Office in
Santa Monica with his wife, Shelley Mills, a fellow filmmaker (they
met on a shoot) who helps run the Eames Office, and their sons,
Xander, 11, and Guthrie, 8. And it's furnished how? ``There's a lot
of Eames furniture,'' he said, almost sheepishly. But it is no
postwar paragon; Demetrios, like most people, moved into a house
designed and built by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   His goal is simply to make it a place where he and his wife can
live and work and his children can play with their Legos. ``One of
the major impressions Charles and Ray made on me was that design
should address the needs,'' he said. ``We're just trying to make
the house work; one of the lessons of the exhibition is that design
is not about making a statement for the sake of making a
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his grandfather's lasting lessons is that good design
comes without pretension. He recalls the Eameses being asked to
redesign the logo for Budweiser beer. They turned down the job,
saying the logo was fine as it was.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 14 and working at the Steinhart Aquarium in San
Francisco, Demetrios was given the chance to travel to the South
Pacific to swim with a 30-foot whale shark for an aquarium
documentary. His grandfather gave him an inexpensive camera to
record the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that if I borrowed my parents' Nikon, I would be so
petrified of dropping it in the water I would just leave it in the
room,'' Demetrios said. As it turns out, Demtrios' first published
pictures were taken with that camera, and inexpensive as it was, it
contained some priceless lessons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
