<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2856 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PRICE-THEATER-ART-2TA     11-17 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICE-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ARTHUR MILLER, A PAST RECOLLECTED GIVES LIFE ITS FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arthur Miller may be his own worst publicist. Even
his mildest cautionary pronouncements on the state of the American
theater tend to have the moral force of something lifted from the
Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 84, still tall, lean and ramrod-straight, he has
both the silhouette and the rectitude of a patriarch. There he
stands, ever vigilant, watching over a society that, in his
lifetime, has shown an increasing affection for the flawed, the
trivial, the sentimental and, in particular, anything new that is
instantly disposable.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the past, he insists, the past. The past is the
present, and if there is no past, the present is without form or
meaning, a murky gray chaos.
</P>
<P>
   It makes no difference that Miller is right most of the time,
but his public image intimidates. It gets in the way of his work,
suggesting that his plays must somehow be good for you: heavy,
weighty, stern and a bit of a slog. Which is why, I suspect, that
whenever we come back to one of the great plays we can be dazzled
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   We discover, as if for the first time, that he is not only a
master of the complex mechanics of the theatrical idiom, but also a
writer of spontaneous grace, compassion, humor and delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   When well served, a great Miller play can soar, leaving you
light-headed with a joy that illuminates all of the other
contradictory emotions you have just experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case with James Naughton's fine, sturdy revival of
``The Price'' at the Royale Theater. It must now be apparent (as it
wasn't to a number of critics when it first opened on Broadway in
1968) that ``The Price'' is one of the great Miller works. It ranks
alongside ``Death of a Salesman'' and, in its sheer playwriting
craft, it may even be the superior of that classic.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a four-character drama, unfolding in the real time
shared with the audience (2 hours and 25 minutes), in which Miller
manages to explore the American experience over much of this
century. No flashbacks, no fantasies, no scrims, no gimmicks.
Instead, ``The Price'' moves forward with the gathering momentum of
a primal whodunit as it reveals, betrayal by betrayal, the history
of one American family.
</P>
<P>
   Simply from the technical point of view, this is an astonishing
piece of work. In the context of the Miller canon, it's a more
mature, more introspective, less tricky play than ``Salesman.''
Hidden malignancies in fraternal and marital relationships are
exposed without breaking the skin. It's a play of anger,
melancholy, love, frustration and regret, also of moments of great,
robust laughter.
</P>
<P>
   The time is 1966, the setting the attic of a brownstone on the
West Side of Manhattan. At the center is a small, cleared area,
surrounded by stacked-up furniture, appliances, clothes, musical
instruments, athletic equipment and other objects defining the
family that once lived below. This is no ordinary attic, though.
It's a battleground for Victor Franz, a New York City policeman who
is nearing 50 and retirement from the force; his trim, pretty,
steadfast but no longer patient wife, Esther, and his older
brother, Walter, a successful surgeon, a star in his field, whom
Victor and Esther have not seen or spoken to in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The de facto referee for the tumultuous confrontations is
Gregory Solomon, the furniture dealer called in by Victor to
appraise and, he hopes, to buy the attic's contents. Old (almost
90), stiff in the joints, with a Yiddish accent and locutions that
are pure poetry, Solomon is not idly named. He is tough, shrewd and
beyond perfunctory answers _ he has lived too long to rely on them.
Like the goods he has been asked to examine, he is a link to the
past. He is also one of the richest characters the playwright has
ever written.
</P>
<P>
   If you have read ``Time Bends,'' Miller's autobiography, a
memoir of Dostoyevskian scope, you know that virtually everything
that has happened in this American century has its origins in _ or
was radically changed by _ the Great Depression. So it is with
Victor and Walter Franz.
</P>
<P>
   When their millionaire father was wiped out in the 1929 market
crash, he never recovered. He simply gave up. Their mother, in
mourning for the musical career she never had, retreated into her
own private world. Victor, who planned to become a scientist,
dropped out of college to take a job to support his parents,
eventually joining the force. When his mother died, he moved up to
the attic, which he shared with his father until marrying Esther.
Walter, however, continued his medical studies, working on the side
and sending home $5 a month. He never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Victor thus embraced a martyrdom that Walter recognized, but
only half-heartedly tried to talk him out of. In the course of the
accusations and justifications that mark their reunion in the
attic, each man successively tops _ and is topped by _ the
revelations of the other. Walter, it seems, very early realized
that love had never been what held their family together, which is
why their father shamelessly used Victor while saving his
admiration for Walter, the son who had abandoned him.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly exposed are secrets that cut deep. Tentative
reconciliations are accepted one minute, only to be scorned the
next. By the end, the brothers are no closer to coming to terms
than they were at the start, which is not to suggest, as some of
the play's initial critics did, that they are just where they were
when the play began. Not true. Each has a new comprehension of the
past, which makes possible a new beginning. Things change.
</P>
<P>
   Though I saw the original production of ``The Price'' with Pat
Hingle and Arthur Kennedy as the brothers, I have no memory of
being as moved and as peculiarly cheered by it as I was by the
current production.
</P>
<P>
   As staged by Naughton (whose most recent Tony Award was for his
grand performance as Billy Flynn in ``Chicago''), this ``Price,''
like Michael Mayer's Roundabout Theater Company production of ``A
View From the Bridge,'' realizes all of the text's dangerous
tensile strength. It is both immensely satisfying and, in a way
that straight plays are not often cited for, entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, are the performances by Harris Yulin (Walter Franz),
Jeffrey DeMunn (Victor Franz), Lizbeth Mackay (Esther) and Bob
Dishy (Solomon). Note also two other prominent team members:
Michael Brown, who designed the atmospheric set, and Rui Rita,
whose lighting design helps to create a claustrophobic purgatory in
a space as wide and deep as any conventional Broadway stage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is an awful lot of painfully jocular exposition to be
waded through before Woody Harrelson makes his entrance in ``The
Rainmaker,'' the Roundabout Theater Company's revival of N. Richard
Nash's 1954 rustic fable at the Brooks Atkinson Theater. Yet he's
worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson brings with him a dynamic if still evolving stage
presence, as well as the same actorly intelligence that informed,
without condescension, both the sweetly out-of-it bartender he
played on ``Cheers'' and the sly grotesqueries of Larry Flynt in
``The People vs. Larry Flynt.'' His role in ``The Rainmaker'' is
well chosen, that of the self-styled Bill Starbuck, a charming con
man who masquerades as a miracle worker and succeeds in spite of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Starbuck possesses an impressive provenance, being a variation
on a quintessential character identified with 19th-century American
folk literature. He is the rootless, larger-than-life rascal, often
a teller of tall tales, who roamed the frontier, sometimes fighting
bears as big as mountains and not always being politically correct
in his treatment of widows, American Indians and others equally
disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   As conceived by Nash, Starbuck has been cleaned up and whittled
down to fit the needs of his sentimental comedy, about how the
smooth-talking Starbuck, hired by the Curry family to end a
ferocious drought, saves Lizzie Curry, a plain farm maiden, from
lifelong spinsterhood. The time is 1936 and the setting is the same
parched, depressed American landscape that sent the Joad family on
their epic journey from Oklahoma to California.
</P>
<P>
   The Starbuck character still has its appeal, but ``The
Rainmaker,'' first done as a television show in 1953, doesn't wear
well. It's a faux-naif comedy that has to be played with the sort
of consistent idiosyncratic style that distracts attention from the
fundamental stickiness of the endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Darren McGavin and Geraldine Page headed the original Broadway
cast, and Burt Lancaster and Katharine Hepburn were the stars of
the 1956 film adaptation. The 1963 musical adaptation, ``110 in the
Shade,'' had an even longer Broadway run than the play, possibly
because the Tom Jones and Harvey Schmidt score supplied a sense of
romantic wonder that is absent from this revival.
</P>
<P>
   The cast, a good one, includes Jayne Atkinson (memorable in
``How I Learned to Drive''), who plays Lizzie, and David Aaron
Baker and John Bedford Lloyd as her brothers. Yet the production,
directed by Scott Ellis, is both fancified (by superfluous
directorial touches) and, when Harrelson isn't front and center,
dull.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Atkinson's Lizzie seems almost self-satisfied, even
matronly. Her performance is legitimate, without mannerisms or
tricks, but she and Harrelson never convincingly connect.
</P>
<P>
   The script doesn't help. It is the playwright's idea that Lizzie
is persuaded of her own worth and beauty by Starbuck's insistence
that she ``dream'' that she is ``somebody.'' We are in that generic
Disney land where wishing makes anything so. He also tells her that
every woman is pretty in her own way. Of such epiphanies was much
of the Golden Age of television composed.
</P>
<P>
   Even James Noone's unit set, which looks pretty when you first
take your seat in the theater, begins to seem misconceived the
longer you stare at it. In a comedy of this sort, there is no need
to overdo the Dust Bowl aspect, but the copper-colored hills we see
surrounding the Curry homestead suggest Montana mining country, not
the broad, pancake-flat plains of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is all that straw-colored grass that surrounds
the farmhouse and the little town nearby. How did it grow to be as
high as an elephant's eye without rain, and why did no one harvest
it before it dried up? Do the male members of the Curry family ever
do any chores, or are they simply obsessed with finding Lizzie a
husband?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rainmaker'' raises a lot of questions, all of them
irrelevant to good theater. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If ``Fuddy Meers,'' the surreal, cockeyed comedy now on Stage 2
at the Manhattan Theater Club, is to be believed (and I think it
should be), then David Lindsay-Abaire is a smart new playwright to
be watched.
</P>
<P>
   The title? It's the way that an unfortunate woman named Gertie,
the mother of Claire, the play's central character, pronounces
``funny mirrors.'' They are found at carnivals, being the things
you stand in front of that make your feet and head look as if they
had been pumped full of helium. Gertie, having had a major seizure,
talks ``stroke-talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire, played by the delectable J. Smith-Cameron, is a serenely
unflappable, big-eyed Kewpie doll, who also has suffered a trauma,
as a result of which she forgets who and where she is every time
she goes to sleep. Each morning she has the opportunity to start
all over. God gives her 365 clean slates a year. Make of this what
you will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuddy Meers'' is about one crucial day in Claire's ever-new
life. While her husband is out of the house, she is abducted to
Gertie's by a worried, low-browed fellow identified in the program
as Limping Man, an escaped con. Also involved in the confusion that
ensues: a foul-mouthed hand puppet, another escaped con, a tough
young woman masquerading as a policewoman and Claire's pot-smoking
teenage son.
</P>
<P>
   The play is a real-life cartoon of a comedy that, like Gertie's
speech, makes far more sense than you might think at first. For
much of the time, it is also uproarious. Think Christopher Durang,
though Lindsay-Abaire is, possibly, an original. He also can write
lines that haunt as they amuse.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a childhood memory about her father that suddenly
returns to Claire: ``And Daddy would walk all these dogs at once.
Seven or eight at a time. All these leashes pulling in different
directions. And he'd come over that hill looking like a map of the
universe. Yeah, Daddy's yellow hat was the sun and he had all these
dog planets revolving around him.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a mind at work here.
</P>
<P>
   David Petrarca is the director who keeps everyone on the same
benignly crazed wavelength. By the final blackout, you adore them
all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
