<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO DEFEND TAIWAN AGAINST MILITARY ATTACK FROM CHINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Saber-rattling before making what he bills as a
major foreign policy speech Friday, George W. Bush says as
president he would defend Taiwan against military attack from
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would help Taiwan defend itself, you bet,'' Bush told ABC
newsman Sam Donaldson as part of an interview broadcast Wednesday
on ``20/20'' and released the same day on ABC's Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that a promise that the United States will back Taiwan
against China will make it clear to both sides that they will have
to work out their dispute between themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose is to promote the peace,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the governor made similar remarks in August, People's
Republic of China Ambassador Li Zhaoxing criticized unspecified
``American politicians'' who talk about defending Taiwan against
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is a very dangerous statement,'' Li said at
the time. ``Taiwan is a part of China. Taiwan is not Florida,
Hawaii or Guam. The issue of Taiwan is entirely China's internal
matter, brooking no foreign intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Iowa on Wednesday, Bush dealt with another area
of foreign policy by urging the Clinton administration to move
quickly on an $800 million program designed to send surplus farm
commodities to hungry nations.
</P>
<P>
   Such a step would aid nations in need and be welcomed by farmers
who are almost done gathering this year's crops. A heavy harvest
again this year has left the country awash in surplus grain and
driven commodity prices to historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   Bush plans to deliver his first major foreign policy speech
Friday at the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library in Simi Valley,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The speech is expected to be closely watched because of the
growing concern about Bush's ability to handle foreign affairs. He
has made several small mistakes in the names of the natives of
several countries, and recently failed a reporter's pop quiz on the
names of the heads of state in four international hot spots. In
that same interview, he described the Pakistani military coup as
``good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides say Bush does not plan to plow new ground with his
address. He is less interested in producing headlines, they said,
than he is in showing he is capable of dealing with substantial
foreign policy issues in broad themes.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of this year Bush has been studying foreign policy
under a team of advisers who helped develop his policy speech,
including former Secretary of State George Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy had been a strength of Bush's father, former
President Bush. The elder Bush had been ambassador to China and CIA
director in the 1970s. Clinton, in his successful 1992 bid to
unseat Bush as president, made an issue of Bush's cooperation with
the communist Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa on Wednesday, Bush continued voicing his support for
China's entrance into the World Trade Organization, a move that is
supported by only one other Republican presidential candidate, Sen.
John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for Iowa. I think it's good for Texas to
open up those vast new markets,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deal has been opposed by conservative congressional
Republicans as well as presidential rivals Steve Forbes and Gary
Bauer, who declared last week there will be ``more heated debate''
on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   China could serve as more evidence, along with Bush's reluctance
to discuss abortion and other hot-button, right-wing issues, to
conservative Republicans that Bush is aligning himself with
centrists of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said that opening China to trade will create a Chinese
middle class, an ``entrepreneurial class.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also has been critical of the Clinton administration for
calling China a ``strategic partner.'' Bush said China should be
considered an economic competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also criticized the Clinton administration in May for
taking inadequate action after accusations arose that the Chinese
were stealing U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published Wednesday in the Wall Street Journal,
Bush said he believes the prospects for good relations with China
at this point are better than with Russia. He said in Russia ``the
concept of a rule of law and the basic accounting principles ...
are murky and weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told The Associated Press in another interview that he
would be willing to share technology to help Russia develop an
anti-ballistic missile system if Moscow pledged to stop the
proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said he would seek to cut off international aid to
Russia if the bloodshed in Chechnya continues. The two-term Texas
governor said Russia, China, the Middle East, and Central and South
America would be his top priorities as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to talk about optimism and keeping the peace,
keeping the peace not only for this generation but to keep the
peace for a lengthy period of time,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to
talk about the need for America to seize the moment, to set a tone
for a new American internationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to achieve our objective will be through a strong
military, through economic policy based upon fair trade and through
strong alliances,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the GOP field, Bush wants Russia to amend the
1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty to allow the United States to
develop a national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to signal that the move would be defensive, Bush
said he would offer to share technology to help Russia develop its
own missile-defense system. Russia must first pledge to stop
spreading nuclear weapons technology to other nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped the steps would persuade Russia to amend the
treaty. ``If they don't, we have the option to exit the treaty,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest threats facing the nation is Russia's
ability to provide nuclear weapons technology to rogue nations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to persuade them that we need to change ABM. We would
be willing to share the technology so long as they make a pledge
against the spread of weapons technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has proposed helping Russia develop
radar technology in hopes that Russia amends the treaty. Condoleeza
Rice, Bush's top foreign policy adviser, said that while the
administration is discussing a narrow incentive to Russia, Bush is
talking about a broader _ but not yet specific _ approach to
sharing technology ``that might have any number of elements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anti-ballistic missile technology is good for all peace-loving
nations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
