</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARAK-1118-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON URGES BARAK TO RESOLVE ISRAELI LAND TRANSFER ISSUE WITH
PALESTINIANS SOON
 &HT;    With CLINTON-OSCE-1118.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ President Clinton urged Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak on Wednesday to work with Palestinians to overcome the latest
snag in the tortured Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli replied that he expects to reach agreement with
Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat on the newest
land-for-peace dispute ``soon,'' said White House National Security
Advisor Samuel Berger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is it gets resolved,'' Berger told
reporters after Clinton's half-hour meeting with Barak. ``I hope it
will be resolved quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Barak also discussed ideas for invigorating
long-sidelined peace talks between Israel and Syria, Berger said,
though he provided no details and offered no evidence of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a harder threshold to get over to get the
parties engaged with one another in negotiations, and that is
something that we are working on very hard,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is here on the second leg of a 10-day swing through
southeast Europe. He heads to Greece on Friday before continuing on
to Florence over the weekend, and then Bulgaria and Kosovo before
returning to Washington late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak asked for Wednesday's meeting, White House aides said, to
take advantage of Clinton's presence in the region at a difficult
time in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Working against a self-imposed deadline, Barak and Arafat have
pledged to complete a basic framework by February 15 laying out the
requirements for ending decades of conflict and enmity. Their goal,
shared by Clinton, is to complete so-called final status talks _
which would include the deeply divisive issues of Palestinian
statehood and the future of Jerusalem _ by next September.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged Barak to stick to the timetable, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed the view that February 15 is not that far away
and we should continue to work at a brisk pace,'' to meet that
deadline, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, though, a fresh dispute erupted over Israeli promises
to withdraw from parts of the occupied West Bank and turn over
territory to Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has committed to handing over an additional 5 percent of
the West Bank, and authorities were preparing to turn over some
land on Monday when Arafat rejected parts of the Israeli withdrawal
formula.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat said Barak was proposing to give up sparsely populated
land of relatively little value.
</P>
<P>
   Barak countered that Israel was obligated to withdraw from a
certain amount of territory but was not required to clear specific
withdrawal maps with the Palestinians. To do so, Barak said, would
hand Arafat effective veto power over Israeli withdrawal schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton weighed in on the matter, but he declined to
characterize the president's position.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton did raise the issue and Barak expressed some
hope for a quick resolution, but added, ``I don't think that
anything I would say about that publicly ... would be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
