<HEADER>
A2882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      11-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POINTED QUESTIONS BREEZE BY BLEDSOE, CARROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Foxboro Stadium should have been called a
hard-hat area Wednesday, not so much for the planned construction
of a new stadium but rather to protect the Patriots from a supposed
falling sky after Monday night's loss 24-17 loss to the New York
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who wore only a cap on his head at his
weekly press conference, had rallied the Patriots from a 21-point
deficit to a touchdown with just under six minutes left when he
couldn't produce the equalizer in three subsequent possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was calling his own plays down the stretch, and many
wondered why he was trying to throw deep into a stiff wind rather
than stick to a short-to-intermediate range passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I've been playing, unless I'm throwing it way down
field, the wind usually doesn't effect my ball too much,'' said
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have a game where I don't play to my expectations, I
look at it and see why I didn't play well, then I put it out of my
mind,'' he added. ``I have extremely high standards, so it's
disheartening when I don't play to my standards. There were some
plays that were there for us that I didn't make for us. Our defense
gave us good field position after we'd put up two scores, and to
not convert that into points was a turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll was bombarded with questions about throwing
into the teeth of the wind.
</P>
<P>
   While he did not bar his players from speaking to the media, as
did coach Jimmy Johnson following the Dolphins' loss to the Bills
last Sunday, Carroll did interrupt an interview with offensive
coordinator Ernie Zampese to ask whether the media was bringing up
the ``wind thing'' again.
</P>
<P>
   He was more content to move on, while many still wanted to
rehash what could not be brought back. He was dodging not only the
sky but bullets from the Pete Carroll hate brigade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my life (after a loss like that),'' said Carroll.
``It's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   There are always things to talk about after a defeat. According
to Bledsoe, the wind affected only two of his throws, one of them
an interception as he was trying to hit Shawn Jefferson down the
right sideline.
</P>
<P>
   In calling his own plays, Bledsoe was merely doing what he
likes. Winging the ball down field is part of the Zampese offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Drew is in those situations, he takes bits and pieces
from the things we feature in our offense,'' said Zampese.
``Looking deep is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the challenge now is to muster an offense against the
Dolphins, who beat the Patriots, 31-30, Oct. 17, when the Patriots
knocked out quarterback Dan Marino but could not solve the
scrambling Damon Huard.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe completed under 50 percent of his passes in that game,
supported by virtually no running game, and Terry Glenn was shut
out by intermittent double coverage, with Sam Madison in particular
a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he studied films to see how he could free himself
from that double-teaming, Glenn responded: ``I don't have to watch
the films. I know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he sees a lot of merit in trying to get Glenn
involved in the offense right off the bat this week. He also agreed
that a shorter passing attack could be wise with his receiving
corps because Glenn, Shawn Jefferson, Troy Brown, Tony Simmons, and
Vincent Brisby all have the ability to elude their coverage and
make extra yards with their speed after the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get Terry involved,'' said Carroll. ``Now if
they're doing everything to stop him and it opens things up for
someone else, I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said: ``I just want us to get back to playing offense like
we were earlier in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   But back then, the Sam Madisons of the world weren't covering
him like a blanket. Add to that the fact the Dolphins' defense is
not so simple to crack, though the Bills did it last week with
their running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was nice to see someone able to do something
against them,'' said Carroll. ``It was tribute to Buffalo's
persistence and commitment to the running game. They ran it 48
times and averaged only 3.7 yards, but you could see they were able
to create some creases by the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the game in Miami, Patriots will be playing in
progressively colder weather and thus will need to be able to run
and shorten their passing game.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were also concerned about springing Ben Coates for
more intermediate pass plays, though the last the Patriots and
Dolphins met, time linebacker Zach Thomas did a great job shadowing
the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   The short week will benefit the Patriots, according to offensive
tackle Bruce Armstrong, since they won't have time to dwell on the
loss to the Jets and instead will focus on the task at hand. He
also stood before the team after the loss to the Jets and addressed
the defeat, as he has been wont to do in other low points in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong even sounded the first shot against the Dolphins:
``They're getting as little mouthier. It's getting easier to
dislike them. They're leading the league in talkative
personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll himself said the team moved forward to Miami Wednesday
as they took the practice field under a cold gray, still-standing
sky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
