<HEADLINE>
DREW BARRYMORE'S MOM SELLS HER BABY CLOTHES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Drew Barrymore &LR; 's mother has turned to the Internet,
gavelnet.com, to auction 18 lots of items that belonged to her
daughter, including baby clothes, a Christmas card sent by  &UR; Jack &LR; 
 &UR; Nicholson, &LR;  and the cowboy hat she wore in ``E.T.'' ($45,900
minimum, and no bids by late Wednesday morning).
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew is such a special, amazing, magical person,'' said
 &UR; Jaid Barrymore &LR; . ``I decided to put some of her things up on the
Web site to allow people to be a part of Drew's life.'' She said
also that she and her daughter are ``a bit estranged. It's been a
couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KNOWING WHEN TO STAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At a premiere party in New York for HBO's ``RKO 281,'' which
will be broadcast Saturday and concerns the making of ``Citizen
Kane,''  &UR; Liev Schreiber &LR; , who plays  &UR; Orson Welles &LR; , talked about
his career:
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is pronounced `lee-ev.' When I auditioned for
`Scream,' I hads &LR;  just broken my ankle and I was getting around on
crutches. I was the last person in the casting waiting room. The
assistant came in and said, `They just told me to tell you to
leave.' I thought maybe Hollywood casting was that rude. I hobbled
down the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came running after me shouting that she had misunderstood
when they mispronounced my name `leave.' Without the crutches I
would have been out of there so fast I would have lost the `Scream'
part. So that's what I call a lucky break.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IOWA IN SAN DIEGO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The 10th annual Iowa Film Festival took place last weekend in
San Diego. According to rules set by  &UR; Bob Ford &LR; , a native Iowan,
films selected for viewing can be any age, on any subject, but must
include mention of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The Duck's Breath comedy troupe provided an oldie but goodie,
its 10-year-old ``Zadar! Cow From Hell!'' This movie classic is
about the adventures of a Hollywood film crew that goes to an Iowa
farm town to make a horror film about a giant mutated cow. Its
two-night run in Iowa City was a smashing success, swears Duck's
Breath's  &UR; Steve Baker &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T JUST STAND THERE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is the Great American Smokeout Day, in keeping with
which the Department of Public Health of San Francisco's Tobacco
Free Project is introducing a Web site ``Curbside Smokers' Quit
Club,'' at www.dph.sf.ca.us. The page gives three-stage advice for
prospective quitters, based on the premise that they're all
standing outside, banned from no-smoking offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the perfect setup,'' says  &UR; Darlene Bahrs &LR; , Stop Smoking
Coordinator. ``They all smoke, they know each other, and they
already get together several times a day. ... If they start now,
they'll be ready to quit in January.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIFT IDEA NO. 5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Saveur magazine points to the Deja Vu Wine Bottle Renewal Kit,
which for only $29.95 allows its owner to turn an empty wine bottle
into a keepsake.
</P>
<P>
   The kit, available through the Wine Enthusiast catalog, includes
food coloring, a funnel and foil capsules to put over the top and
make the bottle look unopened. ``You can fill an entire shelf with
bottles of expensive colored water, and dream,'' says Saveur.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading about the man shaving his head while driving reminded
 &UR; Roger Farrow &LR;  of the time he saw a motorist eating a bowl of
cereal while driving, and the driver he saw the other day trying to
manipulate a Rubik's Cube on the road. ``At least the guy with the
cereal was looking where he was going,'' writes Farrow.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jim Schock &LR;  was amused by a recent New York Times ad for the
Rug Warehouse in New York: ``Memo to Hillary: If you're going to be
a carpetbagger, at least get a great one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``He tore off his clothes and went running through the office
shrieking, `I can't stand these earth tones.' Then he said he would
appoint Bill Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel, to the Supreme
Court. Then he lit up a joint and started listing all the heads of
state of Third World countries. The usual, in other words.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Kinsley, editor of Slate, Microsoft's online
publication, wryly answering badgering inquiries from the
Washington Post about what Al Gore did during a Monday visit to
Microsoft headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
