<HEADER>
A2892 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PIPELINE-BOS &LR;      11-17 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PIPELINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR IN CHECHNYA OVERSHADOWS CASPIAN PIPELINE SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After months of intense diplomatic activity, the United
States and its allies are poised to score a major victory in the
race to control the flow of billions of dollars of oil from the
Caspian Sea as a summit of 50 world leaders opens Thursday in
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But the war in Chechnya threatens to dominate the agenda for the
summit of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE), and cast a shadow over the expected announcement of a new
deal on building new pipelines to take oil and gas from the Caspian
basin to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions escalated Wednesday when the chief of Russia's air
force, angered by Western criticism of the Chechnya offensive, said
that nuclear-armed Russia was not a country the West could push
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to remind them _ Russia is not Iraq, nor is it
Yugoslavia. There you have it. We will deal decisively with any
interference. Let them not think we are totally impotent,'' Colonel
General Anatoly Kornukov told reporters in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   To ram home the point, Russia has in recent days tested a new
submarine-launched missile and threatened to send nuclear bombers
to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   That dims the celebration of an expected agreement on building a
multibillion-dollar pipeline across Turkey from the oil fields of
the Caspian Sea. The 1,240-mile pipeline would travel from the
Azerbaijani capital, Baku, through Georgia to the Turkish port of
Ceyhan on the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would kill the possibility of a pipeline passing
through Iran, and would defeat an alternative Russian proposal to
send Caspian oil past Chechnya across Russia's embattled North
Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   Winning approval for the Baku-Ceyhan route has long been a
priority of the Clinton administration, which sees the pipeline as
a way to help diminish Russia's influence over the landlocked
former Soviet states of Central Asia and the Transcaucasus. If the
most optimistic projections of the amount of Caspian oil pan out,
the pipeline could also possibly diminish US dependence on oil from
the Middle East in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with losing the race for control of oil and gas routes in
the Caucasus, Russia has turned up the heat in other areas,
threatening to block pacts on European Security and conventional
arms limitations _ two issues that will be affected by a large
Russian military presence in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   And Russia, also responding to the Western criticism of the way
its military is bombarding what it calls ``Islamic terrorists'' in
Chechnya, has lashed out with bellicose statements accusing
Washington of trying to muscle Moscow out of the Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya will also take precedence over planned discussions of
other regional conflicts that threaten stability in the regions to
be traversed by the planned pipeline, such as the separatist
Georgian region of Abkhazia, and the ethnic-Armenian enclave of
Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for a US-backed peace deal between Armenia and
Azerbaijan were dimmed by the assassination last month of eight
leading Armenian politicians. It was a grim reminder of the
inherent instability of the Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, US officials see a reduced role for Moscow as an
ingredient for greater stability, although in public remarks the
Clinton administration says it encourages Russian involvement in
Caspian oil pipeline deals.
</P>
<P>
   Oil exports from the region have traditionally moved by pipeline
across the Caucasus and through Chechnya to Russian ports on the
Black Sea, a setup that ensured Russian control over the region.
But since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, the newly
independent Caspian states have sought export routes as a way of
solidifying their freedom from Moscow, a process the United States
and its NATO ally Turkey have actively backed.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion in Chechnya has badly weakened Russia's designs
for the region _ many observers saw the 1994-1996 war in Chechnya
as motivated by the race for control over oil routes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Western governments and relief organizations accuse
Russia of indiscriminate violence against civilians and causing a
humanitarian catastrophe in its latest campaign in Chechnya, Moscow
leaders retaliate by accusing the West of conspiring to keep Russia
out of the contest for Caspian riches.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev accused
Washington of trying to oust Moscow from ``strategically important
regions of the world, above all the Caspian region, the
Transcaucasus and Central Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia says it will not stop its campaign in Chechnya until it
wipes out separatist militants it blames for attacks on neighboring
Russian regions and for a series of deadly apartment blasts that
killed 300 people in Russia last summer. The rebels deny
involvement in the explosions.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia and Azerbaijan, former Soviet republics in the
Transcaucasus, are worried the fighting in Chechnya will spread
south into their territories. Wednesday, Georgia's military accused
Russia of sending three helicopters to mine its border with
Chechnya. This came after the Russian military recently sought and
was refused permission to open a new front against Chechnya from
Georgian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is still putting pressure on Azerbaijan to reject the
Baku-Ceyhan route in favor of a new pipeline that would travel
across Russian territory north of Chechnya. But the plan carries
little favor in Baku.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, Russia's brutal carnage in Chechnya and clear
desire to dominate the Caucasus have reinforced the urgency of
developing a route independent from Russia,'' an Azeri diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   There is still the question of whether the Caspian holds the 200
billion barrels of oil predicted after the fall of the Soviet Union
_ second only to the Persian Gulf _ or the more modest 20 billion
barrels specialists estimate these days.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, with oil prices at 25-year lows, the pipeline looked
like a bad deal. But with crude prices more than doubling in the
past 10 months, the project is alive again, with the backing of
British Petroleum-Amoco and a promise by Turkey to pick up the
extra cost if building the Baku-Ceyhan pipeline exceeds the planned
$2.4 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
