<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLY-LAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE PLANNING TO VISIT MIDDLE EAST IN MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Seeking to fulfill Pope John Paul II's longstanding
desire to visit biblical sites during a Holy Year, the Vatican
announced Wednesday that he will visit the Middle East next March.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old pope has long expressed a desire to visit the
Holy Land in the year 2,000, which is both the start of a new
millennium and a jubilee year for the Roman Catholic Church. He has
received invitations from both Israeli and Palestinian authorities,
but papal planning has been roiled by disagreements between local
Catholic clergy and Israeli and Palestinian officials, most notably
in Nazareth, where the Israeli government recently gave permission
to Muslim leaders to build a mosque next to the city's main
Catholic shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican officials described that decision as an affront to
Christian pilgrims and unacceptable. The major churches in the Holy
Land have said they will shut for two days in November to protest
the proposed mosque. It is still not clear how the pope's
representatives will finesse that impasse.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the Vatican Wednesday, Archbishop
Crescenzio Sepe, who is in charge of the church's millennium
celebrations, stayed clear of firm details, saying that the trip is
expected to take place during the last 10 days of March, and will
probably include stops in Jerusalem and Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   The stooped and frail Pope, who suffers the symptoms of
Parkinson's Disease, has often prayed publicly for the strength to
guide the church into the third millennium. But the Vatican,
apparently concerned about how his grueling millennium plans could
affect his health, has quietly scaled back the number of public
appearances in Rome during the jubilee.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Vatican officials had said the pope would be seen every
day. But in Wednesday's news conference, the Vatican issued a new,
definitive calendar of 80 official appearances during the Holy
Year, which the church begins on Dec. 24, 1999, and ends on Jan. 6,
2001, the day of the Epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once and a while, there will be a greeting by the pope
but it won't be every day,'' Sepe explained. ``There will be a
papal blessing but that doesn't mean that the pope will appear
every night.'' He added that if people expected the pope to make an
appearance every day, ``it would mean we don't love the pope.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other political difficulties still thwarting the
pope's dream. To usher in the third millennium, the pope had hoped
to visit holy sites from both the Old and New Testaments. A top
Vatican official recently explained that the pope has a ``mystical,
almost romantic'' attachment to the Holy Land pilgrimage, and was
determined to respect chronological order.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul had hoped to begin his spiritual journey with a stop
at Ur, the city in Iraq that is believed to be the birthplace of
the patriarch Abraham. But that trip, tentatively planned for
December, remains uncertain as Vatican officials negotiate
conditions for the visit with the government of Saddam Hussein. The
State Department, which fears that a papal visit could lend
legitimacy to the Iraqi leader, asked Vatican officials to
reconsider the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican rejected Washington's arguments, insisting that the
pope's only interest was in making a religious pilgrimage. But that
has been held up by Iraqi officials, who have their own
reservations about the impact of a visit from a pope who has rarely
visited a country without preaching on the importance of respecting
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican advance team is expected to fly to Baghdad soon to
determine whether the Iraq visit can take place. The pope would
also like to visit Mount Sinai in Egypt, where Moses, according to
tradition, received the Ten Commandments.The pope then planned on
visiting Bethlehem, Nazareth, and Jerusalem, the cities associated
with the birth, childhood and crucifixion of Jesus. Bethlehem is
under Palestinian self-rule, Nazareth is the largest Arab city in
Israel, and Jerusalem is under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Paul VI visited the Holy Land in 1964, when the Old City of
Jerusalem was still under the control of Jordan. Like most states,
the Vatican has not recognized the Israeli claim to all of
Jerusalem, which is among the issues now being negotiated between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry welcomed the Vatican's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hope that this visit is going to reinvigorate and
support the spirit of peace and reconciliation between religions
and the peoples of the Middle East,'' said Effie Ben-Matityahu, a
ministry spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
