<HEADER>
A2897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CZECH-ANNIVERSARY-980     11-17 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-ANNIVERSARY-980(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL SAVORING THE OVERTHROW OF CZECHOSLOVAK COMMUNISM 10 YEARS
LATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALISON SMALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ This was a day for the has-beens, the
have-nots, the still-haves and the never-have-hads to come together
and remember the good times. And for people here, what times those
were!
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago Wednesday Czechoslovakia was giddy with righteous
resistance and rose up to overthrow communism so swiftly and
smoothly that the people called it the Velvet Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Proclaiming that ``truth and love must prevail over lies and
hatred,'' the playwright Vaclav Havel emerged from the oppression
and obscurity of dissent to run the revolution from the stage of
the Magic Lantern theater, and then, in a fairy-tale ending to a
magical month, moved into Prague's Castle as president.
</P>
<P>
   If the magic has since dissolved, its power could still be felt
Wednesday, as Czechs and Slovaks _ now citizens of different
nations _ savored anew their heady revolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was once in a lifetime,'' said Jan Bubenik, one of the
leaders of the Prague students, whose confrontation with Communist
riot policemen on Nov. 17, 1989, began the uprising, bringing to
Czechoslovakia the changes that had then already swept Poland and
Hungary and broke down the Berlin wall. ``Once in my life, I had a
moment when I knew exactly what was good and what was evil. It will
never come again, because now everything is sort of gray. But back
then I really felt like the knight on his white charger.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bubenik was speaking Wednesday at one of the many commemorations
organized by students, the revolution's leaders and their foreign
friends to commemorate the end of communism. Margaret Thatcher
unveiled a statue of Winston Churchill. President Bush, who
celebrated the first anniversary of the Velvet Revolution in
Prague, received an honorary doctorate at Charles University and
lauded what he called the transformed world that has emerged from
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   In the improbably grand surroundings of the vast Prague Castle,
Havel joined Bush; Mrs. Thatcher; Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the former
Soviet president; Germany's former Chancellor Helmut Kohl; his
fellow dissident and ex-President Lech Walesa of Poland; and
Danielle Mitterrand, the widow of former French President Francois
Mitterrand, in a reminiscence about the revolt and the
circumstances that forged it. Then he awarded them his country's
highest honor, the Order of the White Lion.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the Cafe Slavia, haunt of Czech men and women of words since
the last century, Havel joined a handful of reporters who covered
the revolution 10 years ago, and reminisced.
</P>
<P>
   The revolution went so fast, he said, that he cannot define his
favorite moment. Three events stood out, however: the resignation
on Nov. 24, 1989, of the ruling Politburo; a protest the following
day of some half a million people on Letna field, long the
Communists' preserve and favorite parade ground; and then the
announcement that the Communist Party had simply abandoned the
leading role it had written into the Constitution for 41 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the mass demonstration, Havel said, ``that I felt in
my mind that this really was the breaking point, because we had
always had to consider the possibility of a confrontation _ and
there I got the clear impression that there was not going to be
one.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was none: the neo-Stalinists who had expelled half
a million Communists from the party after the Soviet Union led an
invasion in 1968 to crush the Prague Spring reforms of Alexander
Dubcek gave up this time with barely a whimper. When the Politburo
stepped down that Friday night, Nov. 24, the shouting was left to
the tens of thousands who danced and drank beer on Wenceslas
Square, and to Havel and Dubcek on stage at the Magic Lantern,
toasting the Reds' departure with pink champagne.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The mood has soured in the decade since: the country has split,
the economic surge that came with capitalism has petered out into
stagnation. Czech unemployment, at 6 percent, is low but rising.
Much remains unfinished and imperfect, and the pall cast by high
hopes unrealized permeated even Wednesday's celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Communist regime got into our pores, and it's very hard to
get rid of that,'' concluded Pavel Zacek, another leader of
Prague's students in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Vaclav Maly, who introduced Havel and the other speakers who
electrified the crowds of November 1989, is now the Roman Catholic
bishop of Prague. He recalled the raw energy that came a decade ago
from those masses, but reflected that the revolution was actually
``too easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't like to hear that,'' he said, still _ like Havel
_ possessed of an almost boyish grin and engaging passion. ``People
don't want to change. They expect always a messiah, a savior. But
the savior won't come.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, if things are not quite what many hoped they would be,
very few Czechs _ even the 18 percent who now say they would vote
Communist _ say they would turn the clock right back to the days
when they had to fill out dozens of forms simply to get a paltry
amount of hard currency, or to make a coveted trip next door to
West Germany or Austria, or watched their own lives ruined and
their children denied study and other opportunities if they dared
to dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The revolution ``is the best thing that could have happened to
us,'' said Eva Hadkova, 29. ``When I look at my parents, basically,
their lives were almost wasted, much different than they could have
had. But I have no problem _ even though I know a lot of people are
complaining _ I can get a very good job, I can travel.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vladimir Valenta, 45, a janitor, said he lived better before the
revolution but still wouldn't turn back the clock. ``We keep
forgetting that things I now see on the street every day _ a good
car, a decent piece of clothing _ we could see only perhaps once
every half a year,'' he said. He said that standing on Wenceslas
Square 10 years ago was a drunken high without alcohol, ``better
than a rock concert,'' giving an unreal sensation of power, both
for the crowds and the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in one of the most tangible signs of the change the
revolution wrought, its makers are scattered in many different
careers and fields, and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   One who was absent Wednesday from Prague was Jiri Dienstbier,
who shared jail terms with Havel and emerged from the revolution as
his foreign minister. Now a lecturer in the United States and the
U.N. special rapporteur on human rights in the former Yugoslavia,
Dienstbier acknowledged that many expectations were dashed in the
past decade, but rejoiced that his people are now part of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people started coming to me after 1989, asking me `What
can I do for you?' I always told them to take as many young people
as possible to your universities, to give them a different
perspective, because everything was closed here.'' Even the
dissidents had to learn, taking high office in their 50s, ``things
we should have learned at 25,'' Dienstbier said. ``Even if a lot of
things were spoiled in these 10 years, these young people will be a
totally different generation. This is a fantastic basic change. If
that was the only success of all we did, it made it worthwhile to
do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOL-CHOICE18-COX     11-17 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CHOICE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUDGET DEAL OFFERS PUBLIC-SCHOOL CHOICE
 &HT;    FIGURES FOR COX STATES START AFTER GRAF 6
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tens of thousands of parents would win the right to
transfer their children from failing public schools to a better
public or charter school under the budget deal negotiated between
President Clinton and leaders of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators set aside $134 million in new federal funds to
help schools that perform badly despite help from Title I funds,
which go to about 46,000 schools with low-income students. But, in
return, the school districts would be required to offer transfers
to all students in any Title I school graded as low-performing for
two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders and administration Democrats
defended the new policy against an attack Wednesday by 20 national
associations of local and state educators and education officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mandate is inconsistent with the current effort to
provide more state and local flexibility in use of federal
education funds,'' said the letter from the 20 groups. Their
members include state school superintendents, big-city school
superintendents, elementary and secondary school principals and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Education Department spokeswoman Erica Lepping responded that
the administration agreed to the deal because ``we had some
frustration with low-performing schools that have failed
continuously and are not improving.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the department's most recent figures, covering the
1996-97 school year, showed that 7,516 Title I schools had been
classified as in need of improvement for at least two years in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN FIGURES FOR COX STATES
</P>
<P>
   That included 15 in Colorado, 29 in Florida, 236 in Georgia, 74
in North Carolina, 680 in Ohio and 40 in Texas. (all cq)
</P>
<P>
   END FIGURES FOR COX STATES
</P>
<P>
   ``School choice is finally poised to become a reality for
thousands of students stuck in substandard learning environments,''
said Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the House Committee on
Education and the Workforce. ``Republicans in Congress have been
looking forward to this day for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, some districts offer transfers, but others rely on
different school-improvement techniques, such as retraining or
replacing the staff of a low-performing school.
</P>
<P>
   Some school officials fear that transportation costs for
students transferring to schools far from their homes would use up
most or all of the new money, leaving nothing for improvement of
the failing schools. Others envision a flurry of lawsuits from
parents whose children aren't transferred if crowding at the better
schools forces a limit on the number of transfers.
</P>
<P>
   School officials and teachers were not reassured by Goodling's
statement that, since the plan specifies that required transfers
must conform with state law, it ``is not a mandate.'' They fear
that the federal law would prevail over state laws whenever the two
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very unhappy, but at this point it would take a nuclear
bomb to stop this deal,'' lamented Jeff Simering, legislative
director for the Council of Great City Schools.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the 20 groups asked Congress to reject the deal
and strip the provision from the $35.7 billion education spending
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The administration opposes that, Lepping said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $134 million wouldn't be distributed until July 1 of next
year, which will give us plenty of time to work with schools,
school districts and states to figure out ways to address their
concerns,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
