<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIFFERENCES' COMPLICATE EFFORT TO EXTEND IRAQI OIL FOR FOOD
PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ What the United States hoped would be a quick
and painless renewal of the program under which Iraq sells limited
amounts of oil to pay for goods to relieve civilian hardships
turned into complicated negotiations when Russia proposed changes
favorable to Iraq on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The extension of the ``oil for food'' program for another six
months requires Security Council action by the end of the week.
American diplomats hoped that approval would be more or less
automatic, so that the council could concentrate on the larger
issue of agreeing on a new arms inspection system for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Until Iraq meets disarmament obligations by proving that its
prohibited biological, chemical, nuclear and missile systems have
been destroyed, international sanctions remain in place.
</P>
<P>
   That larger agreement has no deadline, and the council is now in
its sixth month of debating how to replace the U.N. Special
Commission with another inspection system that all five permanent
members can force Iraq to accept. The government of President
Saddam Hussein has already rejected a draft version.
</P>
<P>
   The five permanent council members _ Britain, China, France,
Russia and the United States _ have been meeting daily to narrow
differences, but an accord is still weeks away, if not longer,
diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't there yet,'' Peter Burleigh, the American
representative working on the Iraq issue, told reporters Wednesday.
Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's representative, said there were
``significant differences'' among the five.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands, which now holds a rotating council seat, and
Britain are co-sponsors of the resolution being discussed. It
proposes a suspension, not removal, of sanctions when Iraq
demonstrates its compliance with disarmament requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But the five permanent members are far apart on issues including
how to decide when Iraq is in compliance, and for how long
sanctions may be suspended before the situation is reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat who has followed the largely secret talks
said that the real challenge now is to convince Iraq that the
Security Council can find a consensus that will hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise Iraq will say: `The council is divided; we are not
interested,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An Arab diplomat said that the old inspection system could lead
to a removal of sanctions. They look at the new proposal, this
diplomat added, and see only a suspension after meeting the same
goals.
</P>
<P>
   On the extension of the oil for food program, under which Iraq
earned more than $7 billion in oil sales in the six-month period
now ending, Russia is trying to introduce changes. They would relax
restrictions on air travel, double the amount of money allowed for
spending to upgrade the Iraqi oil industry and generally allow Iraq
more flexibility with available funds.
</P>
<P>
   American officials would like to keep all discussion about
substantive changes out of the debate on the oil for food
extension.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Security Council heard a report Wednesday from Benon Sevan,
who coordinates and directs the Iraqi oil for food program at U.N.
headquarters. Sevan again told the council of concerns about the
number of contracts for Iraq purchases put on hold in the sanctions
committee, where the United States frequently raises questions
about items Iraq wants to buy abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan sent the council a report this week
that was largely positive in assessing the progress of the program,
which has now delivered 12 million tons of food to Iraq over three
years, $729 million in medicines and medical equipment, as well as
agricultural supplies and material needed to repair basic services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding the enormous humanitarian difficulties faced
by the Iraqi people,'' Annan said in the report, ``the program
continues to have a positive impact.'' He noted that Iraq had
reduced some of the stockpiles of medicines and other goods stored
in warehouses. Special food supplements for new mothers and young
children are beginning to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But the report also says said that Iraq has been slow in
ordering long-term essential goods such as materials necessary for
water and sanitation improvements and is still not providing a high
enough daily caloric intake in rations distributed through the
program. Because of high world oil prices, Iraq now has more money
than at any time since the program began.
</P>
<P>
   Annan was critical of the Iraqis for curtailing the freedom of
the United Nations to monitor the distribution of imported civilian
goods by not making Iraqi escorts available.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. staff members cannot travel around freely or alone in areas
of Iraq controlled by the government in Baghdad. There is more
freedom of movement in Kurdish areas, where U.N. agencies
distribute goods and conduct regular surveys.
</P>
</TEXT>
