<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN SAYS HE'LL SIGN ARMS PACT US SENATE REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ Trumping President Clinton on the eve of a summit
with 54 heads of state, Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin
Wednesday declared he would sign a global arms control treaty the
US Senate rejected last month.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was the latest in a series of Russian moves that
could blunt expected widespread criticism Thursday of Yeltsin and
his nation's indiscriminate bombing campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   It also embarrasses Clinton before his European allies. Clinton
desperately wanted US approval of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
but the US Senate rejected the pact last month, depriving him of a
foreign policy highlight as president.
</P>
<P>
   European and other world leaders vehemently denounced the Senate
rejection of the treaty, which would ban nuclear weapons testing
worldwide. The United States has been operating under a voluntary
ban on testing, and will continue to do so, White House officials
insist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly welcome ratification by the Duma _ or the
Congress _ of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,'' National
Security Advisor Sandy Berger told reporters after Yeltsin's
comments.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement changes the tone of the meeting of the
Organization on Security and Cooperation in Europe, the region's
primary trouble-shooter on non-military issues.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's bombing of Chechnya has made it the bad boy of the
OSCE. President Clinton, set to meet one-on-one with Yeltsin, has
been prepared to chide Russia for what Clinton describes as an
unwarranted killing of civilians in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders are expected to express their dismay also with
Russia's behavior in Chechnya. One European leader, Estonian
President Lennart Meri, is boycotting the OSCE meeting because he
is frustrated with the organization's inability so far to solve the
Chechnya issue.
</P>
<P>
   Russia may also be asked about its apparent breach of the treaty
on Conventional Forces in Europe, which limits military force
levels. Russia has already notified OSCE that it has exceeded its
approved levels with its operation in the northern Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   The breach comes at a time when the OSCE is planning to update
the document to reflect a post-Cold War world. The treaty is now
arranged to maintain a balance of forces between NATO and the
Warsaw Pact. Since the Warsaw Pact no longer exists, and three
former Soviet-sphere countries _ Hungary, Poland and the Czech
Republic _ are now in NATO, the treaty must be changed, Berger
said. The new document, if approved, would set limits on a
country-by-country basis, instead of a territorial basis.
</P>
<P>
   The three items together put Russia in the hot seat at the
summit. But Berger said the group was not ``ganging up'' on Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think virtually everybody here wants Russia to succeed in
its transition'' to a democratic, economically stable,
post-communist nation, Berger said. ``I don't think it's a question
of ganging up. It's a question of expressing some concern. The
international community has a right to be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, making a rare foreign trip, arrived in Turkey Wednesday
on the defensive, saying Russia was well within its rights to fight
against what Yeltsin describes as terrorist forces in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope everybody will understand that Russia is acting in
Chechnya in accord with international civilian rules and norms,''
Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechnya crisis is as bureaucratically difficult for the
OSCE as it is diplomatically sensitive. Since the group operates on
a consensus basis, Russia must approve any resolution for it to
take effect.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the OSCE does is aimed at countries like Russia.
The organization mediates internal conflicts and promotes
democracy, free speech and human rights _ all issues Russia has
tangled with in its transition from communism to a market economy
and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is struggling to finesse the issue with Yeltsin,
making its anger over Chechnya clear while not isolating Russia
from the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tricky,'' said a senior Clinton administration official.
There are worries that Yeltsin might clam up under verbal siege,
and the bilateral meeting between Yeltsin and Clinton would produce
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope not,'' said David Johnson, the American ambassador to
OSCE. ``But it has the potential to.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior administration official said he could not speculate
on what, if anything, might come out of the bilateral meeting
between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing,'' the official said, ``as a predictable
meeting with Yeltsin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
