<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES FALL FOR A SECOND SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices fell for the second consecutive
session Wednesday after the Labor Department reported that the rise
in consumer prices in October met expectations. And for market
participants, it left the door open for another increase in
short-term interest rates by the Federal Reserve should inflation
accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell 1, to 99 29/32. Its
yield, which moves in the opposite direction of the price, rose to
6.13 percent from 6.06 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The economic statistics released Wednesday were somewhat
anticlimactic, some market participants said, because the data came
on the heels of the Fed's decision on Tuesday to raise the Federal
funds rate for the third time since June.
</P>
<P>
   October's Consumer Price Index rose 0.2 percent, the smallest
rise in the last four months, which kept the year-over-year
increase to 2.6 percent, economists said. While the rate of
increase in consumer prices did not accelerate, it is still higher
than the 1.6 percent pace seen last year.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, the chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
noted that the 2.1 percent year-over-year increase in the core rate
was a touch higher than the 2 percent rise seen in September, which
in turn rose from the 1.9 percent August reading, all of which
suggests that the core rate of consumer price inflation may have
already hit its low point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Housing starts in October rose a barely perceptible 0.1
percent and seem to have plateaued since April,'' he noted. ``But
there is virtually no evidence to date that would indicate housing
activity has begun a cyclical decline, and it's instructive to note
that slowdowns in aggregate economic decline are invariably
preceded by cyclical fall-offs in housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Schaja, an economist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
said the housing starts data confirmed that the housing sector had
peaked from the highs recorded earlier this year. ``Nevertheless,
single-family starts remained strong, pointing to continued strong
spending on housing items,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The housing sector is clearly not dead yet,'' said Sherry
Cooper, chief economist at Nesbitt Burns Securities. ``The recent
dip in mortgage rates has rekindled housing activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings analysts back to the interest rate increase by the
Federal Open Market Committee. ``The Fed's tightening move was
accompanied by both a shift to a neutral bias and a market
expectation that the FOMC will keep policy on hold for quite some
time,'' Fine said. ``But the prudent bond market assumption is that
the next Fed move will be another tightening unless economic data
suggest otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The realization that the Fed is acutely aware of, and ready to
act against, potential inflationary consequences of excessive
economic growth has brought the recent bond market rally to a
screeching halt,'' Fine said, ``and together with an overbought
situation and looming corporate supply has produced today's
negative tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Many corporate deals are coming to market for investors seeking
to add yield offered by nongovernment debt because they think gains
in Treasury securities are limited. Among them are Lockheed Martin
Corp., the giant aerospace company, which is planning to price $2.5
billion of debt Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, managed through Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and J.P. Morgan
Securities, will be in three parts: $750 million of six-year notes
that are expected to offer a yield 190 to 195 basis points over a
comparable Treasury; $750 million of 10-year notes, with yields
about 215 to 220 basis points over a comparable Treasury, and $1
billion of 30-year bonds yielding about 225 basis points over a
comparable Treasury. A basis point is one-hundredth of 1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
