u a BC-MA-SPANK-BOS &LR;      11-17 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SPANK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINISTER EXONERATED IN CHILD SPANKING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' highest court has ruled that a minister
did not abuse his handicapped son when he spanked him with a belt
and that the state Department of Social Services was wrong to label
him a child abuser.
</P>
<P>
   In a case closely watched by advocates and opponents of corporal
punishment, the Supreme Judicial Court ordered the Rev. Donald R.
Cobble Jr. of Woburn removed from a state registry of child
abusers. However, the court sidestepped the thorny legal issue
underlying Cobble's case: His claim that he had a constitutionally
protected right to discipline his child according to his religious
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The court criticized DSS for finding that Cobble had abused his
then-9-year-old son, Judah, by striking him on his clothed buttocks
with the soft end of a belt, saying the determination violated the
department's definition of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The child, the court noted, suffered only temporary ``pink
marks,'' not the sort of severe physical injuries that DSS labels
as abusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not judge this present case to be a close one,'' Justice
Neil L. Lynch wrote in the judicial equivalent of a harsh scolding.
``The effects of'' Cobble's ``physical discipline did not satisfy
the department's own regulatory definitions of physical injury or
abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the court stressed it was not giving blanket approval to
corporal punishment, pointing out that using a belt on a child in
other circumstances might clearly be abusive.
</P>
<P>
   The court admonished the DSS to do a better job of determining
when a parent has veered over the line from ``permissible physical
discipline'' to child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Cobble's attorney, Chester A. Darling, said he was disappointed
that the court did not address the underlying constitutional issues
dealing with parents' religious and privacy rights. ``That broke my
heart,'' he said. ``I had hoped they would decide that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobble, an associate pastor at the Christian Teaching and
Worship Center in Woburn, said he was pleased to shed the stigma of
child abuser after two years. The case began in 1997 when Judah's
teacher reported to the DSS that there was a possibility the boy
was being abused by his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is an agency that overstepped its bounds,''
he said. ``I just hope that people will wake up now and speak out
and say we need to change some things here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobble as well as the SJC noted that the DSS closed its file on
Judah after they substantiated the abuse report. If the DSS
believed Judah was being abused, his father asked, why did the
agency walk away after pegging Cobble as a child abuser?
</P>
<P>
   But DSS Commissioner Jeffrey A. Locke said he remained convinced
that Cobble's actions justified the agency's reaction. ``I think
when you wrap a belt around your hand and strike a child on the
back, it sounds more like a beating to me,'' Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the SJC ruling will not stop DSS from investigating
abuse claims linked to corporal punishment. ``No one should be
surprised, because we will be at their doorstep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a recognition in the case that corporal punishment
can be severe enough to warrant departmental action,'' Locke added.
``That's the position we have maintained from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and child welfare specialists, meanwhile, said the
court misunderstood the emotional damage a child may suffer from
corporal punishment. They also stressed that parents can still face
criminal charges in such cases. Cobble was never charged
criminally.
</P>
<P>
   David Deakin, head of the child abuse unit in the Suffolk
District Attorney's office, pointed to the case involving a Roxbury
woman who struck her 10-year-old son on his bare legs with a belt,
leaving raised welts that persisted for three days. Her boyfriend
held the child while the belt was used.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Frazier was convicted of assault and battery in August,
sentenced to two years of probation, and ordered to attend
parenting classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't prosecute people merely for spanking,'' said Deakin.
``People need to understand whether you injure a child in the name
of discipline, or for any other reason, they are at risk for
prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Strom, president and chief executive officer of the
Massachusetts Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children,
was furious that the court gave even limited approval to a practice
that specialists have concluded is always harmful to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it only make a difference when we break something?'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Strom said research has shown that spanking turns children into
bullies, as well as abusers of their own children and their
spouses, and is outlawed in other industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it domestic violence when you do it to your husband
that you love,'' said Strom. ``It's not discipline. It's not
teaching, and it isn't loving to physically hurt someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Strom also said the case was particularly disturbing because
Cobble will become a role model. ``What is the message here?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   But Cobble remained adamant he acted with God's blessing and in
the best interest of his son, who has a congenital disease that
requires him to use leg braces. He said other researchers disagree
with Strom's belief that corporal punishment is harmful.
</P>
<P>
   ``God says corporal punishment is a necessary part to raising
your child,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he does not believe his case will change people's
minds. ``All this has done is just fuel people's opinions. It
hasn't really changed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
