<HEADER>
A2946 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MOVIE-FELICIA-REVIEW-     11-17 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FELICIA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST IN THE MIDDLE OF ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  3 stars  
(Eds: Not for use before Friday, Nov. 19) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Things happen. Things take a turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the words of Mr. Joseph Ambrose Hilditch, one of the
sweetest monsters you'll ever see on the big screen. In Atom
Egoyan's powerfully disturbing new movie, ``Felicia's Journey,''
Hilditch uses those words as a kind of comfort whenever things take
a turn for the worse. And that's often the case in Hilditch's
world, although the outside observer would never know it by looking
at his small, nondescript life.
</P>
<P>
   Egoyan has given us devastating portraits of hidden worlds and
self-delusional people before, most notably in ``The Sweet
Hereafter'' and ``Exotica.'' Here, he has taken William Trevor's
award-winning novel and adapted it to suit his preoccupation with
memory, fate and time. It's basically a two-character study of the
ways people deceive themselves and the often tragic consequences of
such behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The meticulous Mr. Hilditch (Bob Hoskins) works as a catering
manager at a large factory, where he prepares the workers' meals
with exacting pride and precision. After work, he goes home and
cooks elaborate formal dinners for himself, working from kitschy
1950s videotapes of a cooking show hosted by a gaudily glamorous
French woman (Egoyan's wife, Arsinee Khanjian).
</P>
<P>
   Into Hilditch's lonely life comes another solitary figure, a
naive Irish girl, Felicia (Elaine Cassidy), who travels to the
English Midlands looking for her lover. In addition to her youthful
gullibility, Felicia has two problems: She's pregnant, and she has
no real idea where her would-be boyfriend is. In fact, she doesn't
know anybody in England _ until she meets Hilditch.
</P>
<P>
   Egoyan has always been adept at constructing cinematic jigsaw
puzzles, and ``Felicia's Journey'' is no exception. He has
essentially turned Trevor's novel into a Grimm's fairy tale, with
Felicia acting as Little Red Riding Hood and Hilditch as the
seemingly benign grandmother. The difference here is that Hilditch
never actually acknowledges his carnivorous appetites.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the film, Egoyan inserts scenes from his characters'
formative years _ and not always to the film's benefit. Felicia's
modest Irish roots are rendered in a much too simplistic manner,
with the cliches stopping just short of leprechaun territory. More
effective are the scenes that explore Hilditch's unloving childhood
and the hold it has on his life.
</P>
<P>
   Hoskins gives a remarkably measured performance, full of
chilling restraint and surprising compassion. The subtlety at work
here is nothing short of amazing, as Hoskins burrows inside the
mind of this tremendously complex man and shows us the depths of
his self-deceit. Newcomer Cassidy can't help but be dwarfed but
manages to achieve a tender delicacy that is heart-wrenching.
</P>
<P>
   The movie builds to an unforgettable climax in which the fates
come together and enable both Felicia and Hilditch to wash the
scales from their eyes and see the world as it really exists. It's
a conclusion that's simultaneously beautiful and horrible, which is
to say, par for the course in the dark, dreamlike world of Atom
Egoyan.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The film: &LR;  ``Felicia's Journey'' (PG-13; mature thematic
elements and disturbing images). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Bob Hoskins, Elaine Cassidy. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Written and directed by Atom Egoyan. Based on
the novel by William Trevor. Released by Artisan Entertainment. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 54 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  Laemmle's Sunset 5 in West Hollywood; Laemmle's Monica in
Santa Monica, Laemmle's Town Center 5 in Encino; Laemmle's
Playhouse 7 in Pasadena. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
