<HEADER>
A2954 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-17 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CUOMO'S QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was thought to be dangerous terrain, and the advice of some
high-powered political advisers was blunt. Don't go there.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty was a merciless quagmire for a politician. Even Bill
Clinton had said that the era of big government was over.
Politicians exhibiting an unnatural interest in the poor could
expect to be viewed as weirdos or, far worse, liberals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took over the department, I talked to one of the sharp
political guys in town,'' said Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of
Housing and Urban Development. ``He said, `Look, never say poverty.
It's political suicide for you. The impression is going to be that
you're an old-time liberal. You're the son of Mario. You're the
politics of yesterday.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo filed the advice. He set about remaking HUD, which for
awhile had been targeted for demolition by the Republicans.
President Clinton seemed to like the work he was doing. HUD's
budget grew.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cuomo started traveling the country, visiting places that
were _ despite the booming economy, despite the creation of
millions of new jobs _ still poor. He went to the tough
neighborhoods like Harlem and South Central Los Angeles, but also
to places far removed from the consciousness of most Americans _
scenes of economic devastation like Guadalupe, Ariz., and Kasigluk,
Alaska, and chronically depressed areas like Appalachia and the
Mississippi Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Administrations generally expect drum rolls and sustained
applause from their cabinet secretaries, at least in public. But
Cuomo would come back to Washington and write reports with titles
like ``Now is the Time: Places Left Behind in the New Economy.'' He
would show slides of people living in squalor on Indian
reservations and give speeches in which he would declare that now _
when the economy is surging and the budget surplus is huge _ is the
time to invest in those parts of the country that are hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not now,'' said Cuomo, ``when?''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as six or seven months ago that kind of behavior was
considered politically problematic. Some White House aides made it
clear they were not happy with the HUD secretary's insistence that
the economy had not cured all ills.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened to Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get struck by lightning. The president didn't suggest
that he zip it. And the media coverage he got was positive.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the secretary went out of his way, often, to tout
the administration's economic successes _ the balanced budget,
creation of 18 million jobs, the lowest unemployment rate in
decades, decreases in poverty among blacks and Hispanics, etc.
</P>
<P>
   But he would also say, as he did in a speech to the National
Press Club in April, ``I can tell you that the poverty rate, the
despair, is just as bad in some places as it has ever been.'' And
he characterized the conditions on some of the Indian reservations
as ``a scar on this nation's soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, it turns out, was onto something. Within a few months
America's most perceptive political observer, Bill Clinton, was
making his own tour of the nation's poorest venues, and reaping
rave reviews throughout. On July 5, in Hazard, Ky., with the
national press corps looking on, Clinton stood in the searing heat
and told a crowd:
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though this is a blessed time for America, not all
Americans have been blessed by it. This is a time to bring more
jobs and investment and hope to the areas of our country that have
not fully participated in this economic recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Poverty was back on the political/policy map.
</P>
<P>
   In their campaigns to succeed Clinton, Al Gore and Bill Bradley
are arguing all over the country about who would do best by the
poor, and even the Republicans are lip-synching the lyrics of
compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Will any of this translate into real help for real people?
Perhaps. If the economy holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different story when the people are worried or anxious
about their own circumstances,'' said Cuomo. ``Then they turn
inward. But if they're OK with their mortgage, and they're OK with
the tuition, then they can start to look at things beyond their own
circumstances. Another way of saying it is, all things being equal,
the better angels will win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
