<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2961 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-17 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PRE-SELLING A SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``If the Russian government attacks innocent women
and children in Chechnya,'' George W. Bush will say in his foreign
policy speech Friday, ``it cannot expect international aid.
Period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican front-runner himself vouchsafed it to me _ along
with The AP, Reuters and anybody else who would pick up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians must understand that they've overstepped the
bounds of human decency,'' he continued. ``They will discover that
barbaric treatment of women and children will be self-defeating. If
you overstep the bounds, there will be consequences. The
consequence is international aid. The consequence is international
opinion, and the president ought to lead the chorus when it comes
to international opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee. Such an excoriation of Moscow's savagery in Chechnya
sounded like just what I hoped for. ``Somebody said that you wrote
a column questioning whether or not that was going to be in the
speech,'' George W. said, switching easily from a tough to a
bantering tone. ``It's in there. Actually, it was in there before
you wrote it, but I'm going to play like you asked it and I put it
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's manipulating whom? Welcome to the world of symbiotic
drumbeating in the media echo chamber. First I let him get his
pre-speech teaser across:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to say that America has got to reject isolationism
and seize the moment, to not only foster free markets but to build
strong alliances; to remember we can't go it alone in the world;
that we can set a tone; that a president can set priorities. But
we're going to have to rely on our friends to help us achieve the
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In one swell foop, that blunts President Clinton's attack on the
GOP by joining it (``reject isolationism''), evokes Nixon (``seize
the moment'') and Reagan (``set a tone'') while pleasing business
(``foster free markets'') and the multilateral establishment
(``rely on our friends'').
</P>
<P>
   In return for this teaser, he lets me have six minutes of
questioning:
</P>
<P>
   Should we bring the Baltic states into NATO? ``It's important
for us to absorb the countries in NATO as they now are, and wait.
Open the door to possibilities but wait.''
</P>
<P>
   That's disappointing to hawks; after the condemnatory rhetoric
about Chechnya, Bush shies away from diplomatic action that would
really worry the Russians. (I hope Tim Russert asks him on ``Meet
the Press'' about aid to Eduard Shevardnadze's Georgia, on
Chechnya's border, which would drive Moscow batty.)
</P>
<P>
   When to deploy a missile defense? ``I think we ought to give
Russia a reasonable period of time ... if not, we ought to abrogate
the ABM treaty.'' How long is reasonable _ years? ``Months.''
</P>
<P>
   When we spoke in April, you had not decided if we should sell
anti-missile missiles to Taiwan. Any decision yet? ``You mean _
when we deploy the Aegis cruiser system, for example, will we sell
the technology to Taiwan? Depends on how the Chinese behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Invite China into the WTO, despite its brutal repression of the
Falun Gong? ``I think that China should be admitted into the World
Trade Organization.'' Use that as a lever to admit Taiwan also? ``I
think we should. In China's case, trade with the entrepreneur class
will help freedom.'' He notes that ``in this speech I do mention
India as an emerging power that the United States must open up a
bit more trade with.'' (Is that supposed to trouble China?)
</P>
<P>
   What quality do you want in a secretary of state _ a hands-on
negotiator like James Baker, or a conceptualizer with a world view
like Henry Kissinger?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fascinating question. I'll say hands-on negotiator, if I had
to pick right this minute.'' (On second thought, he preferred a
George Shultz type, who could be both.)
</P>
<P>
   Should using the CIA in covert action be a weapon in our foreign
policy? ``It's important to have a strong, viable CIA that not only
knows how to collect intelligence but can help on missions, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you willing to debate foreign policy with John McCain
one-on-one? ``To exclude all other candidates? We're going to have
to have all the candidates until the field narrows down, and that's
just a practical reality. I've got to go. Seriously, I've got some
people waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
