<HEADER>
A2965 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ASSEMBLY-STEIN18-COX     11-17 1899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSEMBLY-STEIN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mideast peace accord in sight, expert says
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Heroic diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kenneth Stein sees as he reflects on the Middle East
peace process during the years 1973-77, the period leading up to
the Camp David Accords of 1978. And that's what he chose to call
his recent book on the topic: ``Heroic Diplomacy: Sadat, Kissinger,
Carter, Begin and the Quest for Arab-Israeli Peace'' (Routledge).
</P>
<P>
   While Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and former President
Jimmy Carter used the power of the Oval Office, Egyptian President
Anwar Sadat and Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin made historic
compromises, Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their collective heroic diplomacy altered the direction and
changed the history of the Arab-Israeli conflict,'' he concludes in
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Stein is the William E. Schatten Professor of Contemporary
Middle Eastern History and Israeli Studies at Emory University.
He's also a Middle East fellow at the Carter Center and co-author
of a book with the former president. During the 1980s, he sat in on
conversations between Carter and almost every key player in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   His immersion in the history of the region makes him an able
commentator on the long and arduous peace process that continues
today. Now, as then, Stein says courage and commitment are needed
to make lasting peace a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Here are excerpts from a conversation with Stein:
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you compare the involvement of the Clinton
administration in the Middle East process today to that of the
Carter administration in the late 1970s?
</P>
<P>
   A: To be fair, you have to compare it in terms of what was going
on in the world at the time and what did each administration have
in terms of leaders of the region with whom to work. If you look at
the personalities in the region, Sadat was certainly more
impetuous, more pragmatic, less ideological than (previous Egyptian
President Gamal Abd al) Nasser. (Palestinian leader Yasser) Arafat
in 1977 was certainly the quintessential ideologue; he's not the
Arafat of 1993. It was relatively easy for both Kissinger and
Carter to accept Sadat because Sadat threw himself into our arms.
He said I'm turning from Moscow. I want Washington. I like U.S.
technology. I want American foreign aid. Sadat's turn to
Washington, I think, was the single greatest success of the United
States during the Cold War. And both Kissinger and Carter
understood that Sadat had to be nurtured.
</P>
<P>
   This was after Nasser's 20 years of anti-Israeli sentiment
building up enormous street opposition to Israel's very existence,
helping to organize the PLO. So when Sadat went toward the
Americans, the Israelis had to be persuaded that this guy was
sincere. And it's to Carter's credit that he ran with Sadat. I
think the fact that he did caused consternation amongst Israelis
because, what, an American president befriending an Arab president
_ this is a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to today, it's very easy for Clinton to be warm with
(current Egyptian President Hosni) Mubarak because you have a
relationship with Egypt that's gone on now for 20 years at a
minimum. There's a deep financial, economic commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you compare the Israeli leaders of the two eras?
</P>
<P>
   A: As far as Begin and (current Israeli Prime Minister Ehud)
Barak are concerned, Begin was an ideologue, Barak the
quintessential military man. Begin made a major compromise about
giving up settlements in the Sinai. He decided that if he returned
Sinai to Egypt, then he wouldn't have to make any compromises on
the West Bank. He wouldn't have to give up Judea and Samaria. He
could give the Palestinians autonomy, functional self-rule, but
never, never consider the possibility of returning any of the land
of Judea, Samaria, the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Barak on the other hand, like his predecessor (Yitzhak) Rabin
believed that a portion of this land should be provided to the
Palestinians so that they could have a place of their own,
self-government, self-rule, a state, self-determination, whatever
it's called. Barak feels he needs to sustain his relationship with
Egypt but at the same time the Palestinians need a place of their
own. He wants to separate the populations. Now whether that's
political as well as economic separation remains to be seen. Both
Begin and Barak believed in self-rule for the Palestinians or
self-government for the Palestinians. Barak takes it a bit further.
He said if they want to have a state, that's their business. The
last point is Begin would never have talked to Arafat. The PLO and
Arafat were like saying pork for an Orthodox Jew or someone who
keeps kosher. Barak sees a change. There's now six years when
Arafat has been negotiating with Israelis. So Arafat has changed,
and Arafat's political ideology has been circumscribed, narrowed or
reduced, which makes it much easier for Barak to continue what
Rabin started. And this is most important. The Israeli public has
internalized the reality of a Palestinian state. The concept in
1977, '78, '79 was about as far as Pluto.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does Barak bring to this process that his immediate
predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, could not?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot of it is a sense of trust, a willingness to fulfill
obligations previously signed. Netanyahu ran for office in 1996 on
a platform opposing (the 1993) Oslo (agreement, outlining a plan
for Israel to withdraw from Arab lands conquered in 1967 in
exchange for assurances of peace), opposing the provision to the
Palestinians of any land. Netanyahu did whatever he could to keep
this negotiating process in first gear. Barak on the other hand has
cranked this thing up to fourth. It has to do with ideology. I also
think it has to do with Netanyahu barely squeezing by in the '96
elections and Barak winning a smashing victory in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Israeli and Palestinian negotiators now have less than a
hundred days to reach their goal of creating a framework by
February for a final peace agreement. Will they succeed?
</P>
<P>
   A: Deadlines have historically been missed in these
negotiations. It's a target date and it should be seen as a target
date. You know they also figure they're going to get finished with
final status (the last phase of the talks) by September 2000. These
things get complicated, and that just won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   An outline for an agreement between the respective sides is
pretty well out there: a unified Jerusalem under Israeli
sovereignty. Palestinians have some self-rule and presence in East
Jerusalem but not a divided city. There will be no foreign army in
the West Bank and Gaza, no foreign army west of the Jordan River.
So the Palestinian state, if it's created, is going to have
circumscribed rights. Its privileges, its prerogatives will be
pretty well defined. The number of refugees that will be able to be
returned _ it won't be '48 refugees, it will be '67. It won't be
hundreds of thousands of them; there may be 50- or 60,000, over a
period of time maybe a hundred thousand. Israelis and Palestinians
will figure out ... how they're going to use water, because it's
the really scarcest commodity.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis aren't going to give up their control of Jerusalem.
The Palestinians aren't going to give up their desire for a
presence in Jerusalem. Then it becomes a discussion of what is that
presence, how does it manifest itself, how political is it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: That makes it sound like agreement is fairly close.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I don't know if it's close. I think the respective
sides wouldn't be sitting down to talk about a framework if they
didn't have a general idea that a framework could come into being.
I think there are differences about how it comes into being, the
details on final status issues, but I think there's a common will,
and I think there's probably even political courage on the
respective sides to make the necessary compromises that are
required. Without either side being really happy at what the
outcome is going to be, I think they both realized they've got to
nail this one, and sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   The big question now becomes how does Barak define separation.
Does he really mean that one-third of the Palestinian work force
will not be able to work inside pre-'67 Israel? What does that do
to the potential Palestinian economy, earning power, stability?
Barak is very concerned about the outcome and its impact on Jordan.
What will this do to the Jordanian regime, to Palestinians in
Jordan, to the Jordanian economy? Israel is very interested in a
stable Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think Americans are more likely to support Palestinian
rights now than in the past?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think Americans, and I think the press in general, are
tired. I think they're weary. I think people have internalized the
reality that this thing is going to be hammered out between the
respective sides. I think there's trepidation on people's part
about violence and terrorism and folks trying to throw wrenches
into this wheel. I'm not sure the American people are as tuned into
foreign affairs in general, let alone the Middle East and the
Arab-Israeli conflict in particular, as maybe they once were 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you seen a shift in American Jews' views?
</P>
<P>
   A: American Jews probably by and large still remain more anxious
about Palestinian and Arab intentions than do Israelis. I think
Israelis, those who live there, are a bit more pragmatic. Second, I
think American Jews, many of them, still wonder why Israel has to
trade land for peace. They won this in a war. Why shouldn't they be
able to keep it? Then when it's explained, well, what do you do,
are you going to absorb two million Palestinians or are you going
to ship them off in yellow school buses across the Jordan River?
The international community is not going to accept that. I think
there's a very rapid maturation in the American Jewish community
about what is the art of the possible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Looking globally, where does this conflict rank in terms of
ones that need to be resolved?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think the process toward resolution reduces tension in the
region, which is in the interest of the United States. I think Arab
states in general, forget the Palestinian state that may come into
being, have severe domestic problems. And the Palestinian issue is
not No. 1 on their agenda. It's important. But all of these states
have infrastructure problems _ sewer, water, garbage collection.
They have over-urbanization. They have under-employment. They have
unemployment. They have an Islamic factor to contend with. They
have difficulties between the governed and the ruler. Can these
societies inculcate human rights, civil rights? These are issues
that are there separate and apart from the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, even if we have a final agreement between Palestinians
and Israelis next year, there's a lot of work to be done?
</P>
<P>
   A: The day after an agreement, the day after the Palestinians
come home from being happy and jubilant and firing firecrackers and
roman candles, and they now have passports and they have a flag,
but the bottom line is: ``So what does it do to change my life? How
does it affect me on a day-to-day basis?'' And then the tough
questions still have to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
