<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Nov. 18. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ The Irish
Republican Army says it ``unequivocally'' backs the Northern
Ireland peace agreement and agrees to appoint a go-between to the
commission charged with bringing about paramilitary disarmament. By
Warren Hoge. (We plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i''
news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   Story runs with 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-TEACHERS (Washington) _ The nation's Catholic bishops
vote overwhelmingly to require theology professors at Catholic
colleges and universities to obtain a certification from their
bishop declaring what they teach is ``authentic Catholic
doctrine.'' By Gustav Niebuhr. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET
in ``w'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   IRS-WORKERS (Undated) _ Urged on by Congress to get tough on
abuse of taxpayers, the Treasury Dept. is formulating a plan to
subject IRS employees to more scrutiny than other federal workers.
But IRS managers and union leaders, and even some in the inspector
general's office, say intensified scrutiny will distract many IRS
agents as they defend themselves, making the agency less potent in
pursuing tax cheats. By David Cay Johnston. (Scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-RDP (Washington) _ The Egyptian government escalates
their condemnation of U.S. officials investigating the EgyptAir
crash, saying that by focusing suspicion on one of the pilots they
were rushing to judgment about the cause. Egypt's principal
spokesman says that a statement attributed to a relief pilot in the
cockpit is being misinterpreted and does not show he was about to
commit suicide by sending the plane into the Atlantic. By Neil A.
Lewis and Philip Shenon. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Eds.: See related story, AIRCRASH-PHRASE.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: SCI-THALIDOMIDE (Washington) _ In a serendipitous
discovery that grew out of the pleas of a lawyer whose young
husband was dying of cancer, scientists will report that
thalidomide can slow the course of a deadly bone cancer. By Sheryl
Gay Stolberg. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   GORE-JOURNALISM (Nashville, Tenn.) _ In September 1971, the
latest $95-a-week greenhorn, a shaggy-haired 23-year-old named
Albert A. Gore Jr., joined the Nashville Tennessean. The grizzled,
bourbon-swilling veterans presumed that the son and namesake of
Tennessee's recently deposed U.S. senator was looking to pad his
resume. But to their surprise, Gore stayed for nearly five years
and became a skilled investigative reporter. Many were caught off
guard when he abandoned the trade to run for Congress in 1976. By
Kevin Sack. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WORKERS-SHORTAGE (San Francisco) _ Thanks to the booming
technology-based economy, companies' long-standing scramble for
qualified technical workers has taken on an air of desperation
lately. A severe shortage of engineers who design hardware and
software and create Web pages has led companies and their
recruiters to try all sorts of tricks, like one persistent
entrepreneur who repeatedly called a Web site here looking for
Nevil _ unaware that Nevil is a black Labrador retriever. By Matt
Richtel. (The story has moved in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: SCI-GENE-LIFESPAN (Undated) _ Yielding a sharp insight
into the genetic reasons for death, a team of Italian scientists
has discovered a gene that controls lifespan in the mouse. In
people, where the gene was first found, the effects are unknown,
but the scientists and other experts in aging say they can envisage
drugs that affect the gene being used as an anti-wrinkle skin cream
and perhaps for less frivolous rejuvenation effects. By Nicholas
Wade. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GREECE (Athens, Greece) _ Giving a sample of the kind of
resentment President Clinton can expect Friday, more than 10,000
Greek protesters march in front of the U.S. Embassy, many carrying
banners branding Clinton a murderer. By Alessandra Stanley.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-QUIZ-SHOWS (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: ``Who Wants to be
a Millionaire'' and ``Greed,'' two visions of America. By Caryn
James. (The story has moved in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-PREVIEW (Undated) _ A walk through the Sweet 16. By Joe
Drape. (The story has moved in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
