<SLUG> BC-TV-SUNDAY-MOVIES-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDAY AT THE MOVIES ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  2.5 to 3 stars  
(Eds: Not for use before Sunday, Nov. 21) 
(Eds: Fact boxes at bottom) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Overkill is a proud American tradition, but its downside is
that incessant media noise surrounding any one topic just makes us
ignore it after a while. Parents might fret and scratch their
heads, but it's just a matter of time before Pokemon goes the way
of the Power Rangers and some other equally odd, and probably
dumber, fad emerges to consume our kids' attention spans and spare
change.
</P>
<P>
   Adults are no better. Here we are, 40 days from the year 2000,
and already everyone's had it up to here with Y2K hysteria and
anything to do with the millennium _ have you bothered to read a
Top-anything list lately? We're told that most systems should work
just fine when our clocks' second hands make that fateful tick into
the unknown _ the years that don't begin with a ``1.'' But no one
knows for sure and everyone's attitude seems to have become a blase
``we'll cross that bridge or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of books on how to prepare or panic _ ``The
End Times for Dummies,'' anyone? _ but television has been
suspiciously mum on the subject. Until now. NBC posits a
humdrummest-case-scenario teleflick, while PBS' ``Frontline'' news
series explains in depth why the few who are still carrying on
insist on doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K: The Movie'' _ as opposed to, presumably, ``Y2K: The
Game,'' which shuts down your computer and forces you to go read a
book _ probably has the shortest shelf life of any popular
entertainment in history. It stars Ken Olin as a crackerjack
computer expert who has gone to extraordinary lengths to ensure
that our world is safe on Jan. 1. Alas; for a genius, he fails
miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Power grids collapse globally, thrusting the planet into a new,
if temporary, dark age; nuclear power plants threaten to go postal.
Things really take a grim turn, however, when Olin's petulant
daughter sneaks out to a rave without permission. Though the power
goes out in Times Square, that doesn't prevent a newly engaged
couple from locating a bar lit by candles _ and, of course, a
working TV. (The filmmakers don't quite commit to their premise,
and despite widespread power outages, everyone seems to have easy
access to television.)
</P>
<P>
   Problems are solved by someone running around or tapping on a
keyboard _ you'll be on the edge of your seats! _ or, more
cinematically but just as indifferently, blowing something up. The
film opens with a disclaimer: ``This program does not suggest or
imply that any of these events could actually occur.'' Not to worry
_ anyone who would buy the military transport-size plot holes
presented in this film probably hasn't figured out how to turn on a
computer in the first place. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Frontline: Apocalypse!' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, ``Frontline'' takes a far more thoughtful and
fascinating look at potential impending mayhem as foretold, albeit
nowadays though contemporary filters, in the Bible. ``Apocalypse!''
filmmakers William Cran and Ben Loeterman point out a lot of stuff
that was overlooked in Sunday School. For example, the authors of
the Bible cribbed the concept of Hell from Greek mythology. And the
words ``anti-Christ'' and ``rapture'' don't even appear in the Book
of Revelation, the last book in the Bible and the one that has
foretold a presumably imminent cataclysm since its authorship at
the end of the first century A.D. There was, in fact, much debate
over whether Revelation belonged in the New Testament _ the Greek
Orthodox church omits it from its Bible to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apocalypse!'' shows how Revelation's iconography has been
adapted for each new era hoping to usher in Christ's return. The
seven-headed Beast, originally a symbol of Rome, the cradle of
oppression for both Jews and Christians, has variously been
transformed into an emblem espousing everything from socialism to
anti-Semitism. Still, some religious leaders today insist that
based on Bible prophecy, our generation is living in the End Times.
Of course, that's what they've been saying for 1,900 years now _
they're bound to be right sooner or later. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Winter's End' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another ``Sarah Plain and Tall'' movie is not, scripturally
speaking, a sign of the end of days, but likewise, it's not cause
to party. The first two films, ``Sarah Plain and Tall'' and
``Skylark,'' are among the most watched TV movies of the decade.
Tonight's entry, ``Sarah Plain and Tall: Winter's End,'' will
likewise draw viewers, but it's mildly disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it's 1918, and Jacob (a subdued Christopher Walken)
and his mail-order bride, Sarah (a beatific, noble Glenn Close),
have had the child promised in ``Skylark,'' and she's a sassy if
well-meaning handful (nicely played by Emily Osment, sister of
``The Sixth Sense's'' Haley Joel Osment). There's another addition
to the family, too _ Jacob's long-lost father John (Jack Palance)
has returned to Kansas, only to find Jacob still bitter that Pop
walked out on him and his mother all those years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable healing eventually occurs, and Sarah gets to drop
a lot of familial homilies along the way _ ``Love looks through the
heart, not the eyes,'' she observes at one point. Subplots
involving a flu epidemic, Jacob's oldest daughter pining for a
boyfriend overseas and the world's wimpiest blizzard buffeting
Sarah about scarcely ratchet up the drama a smidgen. ``Winter's
End'' is unfailingly pleasant, but never particularly compelling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
` &UR; S &LR; hooting the Past' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Masterpiece Theatre'' tonight and next Sunday presents
``Shooting the Past,'' which asks the intriguing question, how much
of our past is worth saving? Writer/director Stephen Poliakoff
introduces us to the quietly eccentric but insubstantial employees
of a photo archive boasting 10 million pictures in its library.
Alas, the stately manor housing their warehouse has been taken over
by an American company, which has no interest in the library's
resources _ its developer, Christopher Anderson (Liam Cunningham),
thinks he's being gracious by giving the employees a week to get
themselves and their photos off the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Oswald Bates (Timothy Spall), the curator with photographic
recall of virtually every snapshot in the collection, is too much
of a buffoon to impress Anderson, so it's up to Marilyn Truman
(Lindsay Duncan), who manages the library, to summon up some
backbone and stand up to Anderson. Duncan and Spall give realistic
and sympathetic performances _ Cunningham's a bit undone by his
cheesy American accent _ and Poliakoff, with the assist of an
evocative score by Adrian Johnston, evokes a melancholy and
sometimes cheeky tone. His photographic cornucopia of random images
underscores, simply and with breathtaking economy, the wealth and
breadth of human experience and emotion still photos convey.
</P>
<P>
   Poliakoff's denouement _ airing next week _ stretches
credibility a bit. But he's onto something somber and deeply felt.
As old books, photos and documents are bulldozed over in the
onslaught of today's flash-in-the-pan media concoctions, what we
lose most of all is the time and the chance to appreciate the sheer
scale of what we're losing.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``Y2K: The Movie.'' &QL; 
What: Cautionary fable about crashing computers. &QL; 
Who: Ken Olin, Joe Morton, Ronny Cox, Kate Vernon, Lauren Tom. &QL; 
Where: NBC (KNBC, Channel 4). &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 stars &QL; 
The show: ``Frontline: Apocalypse!'' &QL; 
What: Documentary exploring the early days of End-times theology,
up until modern times. &QL; 
Where: KCET. &QL; 
When: 9 p.m. Monday. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Sarah Plain and Tall: Winter's End.'' &QL; 
What: Third part of the trilogy about Sarah, who started out a
mail-order bride and grew to be a significant part of her Kansas
community. &QL; 
Who: Glenn Close, Christopher Walken, Jack Palance, George Hearn,
Lexi Randall, Christopher Bell, Emily Osment. &QL; 
Where: CBS (KCBS, Channel 2) &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 2.5 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Masterpiece Theatre: Shooting the Past.'' &QL; 
What: Miniseries about eccentrics who try to save an invaluable
photo library from the scrap heap. &QL; 
Who: Lindsay Duncan, Timothy Spall, Liam Cunningham, Emilia Fox. &QL; 
Where: KCET. &QL; 
When: 9 p.m. Sunday and Nov. 28.  &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars
</P>
</TEXT>
