<HEADER>
A2973 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-B     11-17 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS CITE DEFICIENCIES IN HANCOCK DEMUTUALIZATION SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. is finding
consumer advocates in unlikely places.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco on-line investment bank Wednesday criticized
Hancock's refusal to let millions of policyholders participate in
the giant insurer's highly-anticipated initial public offering. The
bank, W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co., said Hancock's plan shortchanges
policyholders, privileges Wall Street professionals over ordinary
investors, and downplays the true value of the giant insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht, part of a new breed of upstarts seeking to reshape
Wall Street's traditional culture, said it wanted to enlighten
consumers and industry regulators, not make a grab for Hancock's
business. But in the Web world's latest challenge to Wall Street, a
Hambrecht executive did not rule out a last-minute pitch to
distribute some of Hancock's shares.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Hancock, in a watershed transformation from a
mutual company owned by policyholders to a stock company owned by
investors, will issue around $2 billion in stock on January 28.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2.8 million policyholders are eligible for shares, cash, or
heftier policies as compensation for their ownership stakes in the
old company. (They also retain their policies.) Policyholders
opting for shares cannot acquire them at the IPO and will instead
be mailed stock certificates in March, leaving them with stock
worth whatever the new company is then worth.
</P>
<P>
   In most IPOs, including Hancock's, only institutional investors
_ pension funds, mutual funds, and insurers _ can buy shares at the
offering price, which is set by investment banks. In all, Hancock
estimates professional investors will own 30 percent of the new
company, while about one in three policyholders, generally those
with large policies, will own the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of who can buy into an IPO is hot at mutual insurers,
whose owners are the policyholders. Given that IPOs can rise
astronomically when issued, excluding policyholders from buying in
isn't fair, said Jonathan T. Fayman, a vice president and financial
analyst at Hambrecht. Indeed, he said, locking out Hancock
policyholders could hand up to $240 million in first-day gains to
institutional investors. ``That $240 million should not be a gift
to Wall Street,'' Furman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's plan upsets some policyholders, too. ``Make it
playable for us little guys to get in on the IPO process,''
Massachusetts policyowner Jim Thivierge told the state's Division
of Insurance, which must approve Hancock's transformation.
</P>
<P>
   At a packed public hearing Wednesday in Boston designed to air
complaints about Hancock's imminent change, Fayman urged regulators
and company officials to consider using an Internet auction system
in which ordinary investors bid side-by-side with the
professionals. The top bidders win, paying the price offered by the
lowest bidder in a group whose participants are collectively the
highest bidders for the available stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to democratize the process, and lets the market,
not an investment bank, set the price,'' Fayman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's decision not to grant subscription rights, as the
right to buy into an IPO is known, is more deleterious to
policyholders who opt for cash or heftier policies, Furman said.
That is because IPOs typically undervalue a company by offering
shares below a company's true market value, he said. Furman looked
at six mutual insurers that converted to stock companies this
decade and found an average first-day share price appreciation of
12 percent _ meaning that each insurer was priced around 12 percent
below its market value. Six months after going public, stock in the
six insurers had risen an average 40 percent. Two of the six rose
over 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual step designed to counter consumer perceptions that
its process is unfair, Hancock will cash out policyowners who opt
for money or policy credits at up to 120 percent of the IPO price.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock has tentatively priced its stock at $20 a share, though
in a standard procedure, that price will rise or fall the night
before the IPO to reflect market conditions. Dallas lawyer Michael
F. Pezzulli said Hancock was worth at least $36 per share on
opening day, based on the company's book value.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht is the second on-line financial firm to challenge
Hancock's IPO, for which the insurer is using blue-chip investment
bank Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co. as lead distributor. Wit Capital Corp.,
also of New York, made a clumsy proposal last week to distribute
Hancock's stock on line and to sell additional shares to
policyholders. Wit retracted its plan a day later, calling it
ill-advised and poorly thought out.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, which wants to cash out its smallest policyholders to
eliminate costly administration, said it wasn't practical to offer
subscription rights. The nation's 13th largest life insurer would
have to mail out 2.8 million IPO packets on the eve of the offering
_ a major and expensive hurdle. The procedure would push back the
IPO by weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   The delays could be dangerous, Hancock lawyer Bruce Skrine said,
because two other mutual giants, Metropolitan Life Insurance Co.
and Sun Life Assurance Co. of Canada, plan IPOs around April.
``It's better for us to be at the front of the line, not the
back,'' added Stephen L. Brown, Hancock's chairman and outgoing
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock defended its plan to offer top executives first-time
stock incentives one year after the IPO. ``Stockholders these days
definitely prefer to have management incented by stock,'' Brown
said. The insurer originally wanted to dole out goodies only six
months later but was rebuffed by state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also assailed Hancock's plan to set aside $150 million
in IPO proceeds to pay shareholder dividends. Under law the money
should go to policyholders, not shareholders, according to consumer
advocate and Boston lawyer Jason Adkins.
</P>
<P>
   Pezzulli, the Dallas lawyer, who is suing Hancock on behalf of a
disgruntled policyholder, attacked Hancock's plan to establish a
``closed block'' of assets to protect policyholder dividends. The
block, he said, was underfunded and assumed too high a return _ a
matter that could pit policyholders against shareholders in a scrum
for limited dividends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
