<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ULSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA'S GESTURE; UNIONISTS' CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To reassure Ulster Unionists that it is serious about making
peace, the Irish Republican Army has to give up, or
``decommission,'' a significant number of its weapons. The Unionist
refusal to enter a government with the IRA's political agent, Sinn
Fein, has not produced the desired decommissioning. Now former
senator George Mitchell has masterfully negotiated a compromise
that brings the IRA closer to providing proof that its war is over.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell has persuaded the Unionists' David Trimble, Sinn Fein's
Gerry Adams, and the IRA leadership to issue a series of linked
statements expressing a Unionist commitment to join Sein Fein in
the Northern Irish government, a Sinn Fein renunciation of
violence, and an IRA willingness to begin the decommissioning
process.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA did not, however, explicitly promise to give up weapons.
This is an important sticking point for Unionists and explains why
a majority of Trimble's party in the Northern Ireland Assembly
refused to endorse the compromise. He will have another chance to
win Unionist support when the 860-person party executive meets on
Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday, the IRA said it is ``willing to
further enhance the peace process'' and will appoint an
intermediary to begin talks with the decommissioning panel as soon
as the Northern Ireland government envisioned in the Good Friday
agreement is up and running. Unionists ought to endorse the
Mitchell compromise to test the IRA's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 18-month impasse following the referendum on the
Good Friday agreement, British troops are off the streets, and
Unionists are cooperating with Sinn Fein in some local governments.
But there are enough pockets of the old antagonisms to raise
legitimate fears that if the peace process does not take its next
logical step _ the formation of a provincial government _ violence
will inevitably escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble understands this prospect, which is why he has braved
dissent within his party to negotiate the compromise. Unionists who
want to get the guns out of the politics of Northern Ireland need
to follow his lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
