<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHECHNYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING CHECHNYA IN ISTANBUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The specter of Russia's savage assault on Chechnya hovers over
the meeting of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe that begins Thursday in Istanbul. Russia's President Boris
Yeltsin and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin have warned that they
will not tolerate sermons from Western leaders about the bombing
and shelling of Chechen towns and villages or the suffering of more
than 200,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO bombing of Belgrade lessened the West's moral
authority. But when he meets with Yeltsin and Putin, President
Clinton can hardly pretend that their hands are not covered in
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton must worry about continued cooperation in the
dismantling of Russian missiles and the prevention of nuclear
proliferation, he needs to weigh these US interests against other
considerations. The Kremlin's war aims and tactics are creating an
ominous precedent. Russian generals are bent on punishing the
Chechen population for having won its 1994-96 war for independence
and on recapturing the lost territory of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In an offensive justified by exaggerated charges of Chechen
terrorism and infused with racist contempt for all Chechens, the
Kremlin is putting the peoples of the Caucasus on notice that
Russia intends to retrieve a dominant position in that
resource-rich region. Russia's defense minister, Igor Sergeyev,
revived old patterns last Friday when he told a gathering of
generals: ``The United States' national interests require that the
military conflict in the North Caucasus, fanned from the outside,
keeps constantly smoldering.''
</P>
<P>
   The political danger from this sort of propaganda is obvious.
Nationalist pride and paranoia may supplant a rational debate about
Russia's true difficulties in upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should press hard for a cease-fire in Chechnya and offer
international mediation to address Russian concerns about terrorism
and criminal gangs. He should also make it plain that Russia has no
chance at its goal of becoming a ``normal'' country as long as
Yeltsin emulates the aggressive behavior of his predecessors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
