<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-TURKEY-NYT &LR;      11-17 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TURKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BETWEEN STATE BUSINESS, FIRST FAMILY TOURS TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ President Clinton's state visit to Turkey has
featured plenty of official meetings, dinners and speeches. But it
has not been all work and no play.
</P>
<P>
   With time to spare before a European security meeting with the
leaders of more than 50 nations here on Thursday, the president has
taken in many of Turkey's cultural gems. Earlier in the week, he
removed his black cowboy boots and walked in stocking feet across
the carpet of the spectacular Blue Mosque, a high point in Ottoman
architecture built on the orders of the Sultan Ahmet I in the early
1700s. ``I'm so honored to be here,'' Clinton said softly to Imam
Emrullah Hatipoglu, the imam of the mosque, who welcomed the
president, his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and their daughter,
Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   The president descended into the Underground Palace, a dimly lit
cistern that was featured in the James Bond movie ``From Russia
With Love'' more than a century after the Byzantines constructed it
to store the city's water supply. There, he walked past dozens of
stone columns as the soft rhythmic tones of an ancient Turkish
flute created a haunting atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday he strolled through the marble ruins of Ephesus,
where one of the Seven Wonders of the World _ the Temple of Artemis
_ was erected in 550 B.C. With security officials perched in the
surrounding hills, the president paused to admire the grassy Upper
Agora, once a marketplace and public square, and Trajan's Fountain,
which dates to 102 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton is an engaged tourist, gazing intently at
artifacts and offering observations to his tour guides, he also has
shown that he has his limits.
</P>
<P>
   In the old city of Istanbul on Tuesday, Clinton signed the guest
book at the Haghia Sophia, a cavernous museum that was built as a
Christian cathedral in 360 A.D. In 1453, it was converted into a
mosque after the Ottoman conquest of Constantinople, the Byzantine
name for Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, dressed in dark slacks and a black leather flight
jacket, took a pass on a ritual practiced by many visitors to the
dimly lit museum, widely considered one of the grandest religious
structures anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it, according to local guides, that if one presses
one's thumb into a special spot on a towering stone column, the
restorative powers of St. Gregory the Miracle Worker go into
effect. Clinton walked on with a dry thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling Lighter
</P>
<P>
   One of the officials who has been frequently at Clinton's side
during his state visit to Turkey is Sandy Berger, the president's
national security adviser. Make that a new slimmed-down version of
Berger. Thanks to a special diet that he did not want to go into,
Berger has lost 35 pounds in recent months. So svelte is he now
that he and his wife had run out to Saks Fifth Avenue a few days
before the trip to have his suits altered.
</P>
<P>
   There was a foreign policy connection to Berger's weight loss.
During the recent confrontation with the Senate over the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, the presidential aide joked to Trent
Lott, the Senate majority leader, that he would fast until the
Senate approved the landmark agreement. Lott, a Mississippi
Republican, told Berger he would likely not eat again _ and the
Senate went on to defeat the pact soundly last month.
</P>
<P>
   Affection is Mutual &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip to Turkey, longer than previous visits by George
Bush and Dwight Eisenhower, has given him gushing coverage in the
local media, and some interesting momentos. He received handmade
clay sculptures from some young earthquake victims, a prestigious
state award from President Suleyman Demirel, a Bible verse on
parchment from Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew and a watercolor
scene of boats along the Bosporus from the American-Turkish
Business Council. Clinton said he would treasure them all, and
would hang the painting in his new home in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Just as heart warming have been the banner headlines praising
Clinton for his efforts to strengthen ties between the United
States and Turkey and advocate Turkey's admission to the European
Union. ``Politicians, academicians, labor unions and the public
were very happy to hear from the U.S. president how vital Turkey
will be for the whole world in the next century,'' said an article
in the English-language Turkish Daily News. In Sabah, one of the
country's largest dailies, a screaming headline over a story on
Clinton's speech to the National Assembly called the president:
``LIKE A TURK.''
</P>
<P>
   Further down on the front page, however, was a related story
that left one member of the White House press corps red faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``LIKE AN AMERICAN,'' said the headline, which was coupled with
two photographs of a female reporter with her legs extended over
the seats in front of her during the National Assembly session. The
photo captain called her a ``mini-skirted journalist'' and poked
fun at her relaxed posture during the official proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   What the paper left out is that a delay in Clinton's speech
meant that American reporters were treated to well over an hour of
parliamentary debate on some rather contentious topic, all in
Turkish, of course. And a closer inspection would have shown other
correspondents in the pack with their legs down but their eyes
shut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
