<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2988 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CRICHTON-INTERVIEW18-     11-17 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRICHTON-INTERVIEW18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Timeline' his latest mix of science, letters
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you watch Michael Crichton _ author of ``Jurassic Park,''
creator of TV's ``ER'' _ striding toward you across a hotel lobby,
it gives new meaning to the term ``high-concept writer.'' Crichton
is 6-foot-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing about being so tall,'' says the world's
wealthiest novelist, who earned $65 million last year, ``aside from
transportation, is that cocktail parties are a horror. You can't
hear a thing that's being said.'' Pause. ``Or maybe that's a
blessing,'' he adds with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   With Crichton, 57, the pauses are refreshing. And puzzling. This
is one careful, thoughtful _ wary, perhaps? _ scribe. After
grousing that the morning talk-show appearances for his newest
novel, ``Timeline,'' wear him down, he begins, ``The trouble with
television ... '' and then lapses into a pause long enough for some
celebrities to thank all their their closest friends and members of
the academy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally he continues: `` ... is that it's so hard to say
anything meaningful in that amount of time, and yet it's so easy to
look like an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much chance of that, with his intellect. ``Timeline'' is a
tale _ due to be a Paramount film by Richard Donner (``Superman'')
_ of young scientists using quantum physics to travel to a parallel
universe. They become embroiled with the power struggles and
romantic intrigues of a 14th-century France coexisting in the same
moment with contemporary America.
</P>
<P>
   In brief: another, typically high Crichton concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is America's H.G. Wells,'' says author John Gregory
Dunne, a friend for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Knopf novel, for which Crichton (pronounced CRY-tun) is
believed to have been paid about $10 million, is rich with
cutting-edge technology and taut storytelling, in keeping with his
unusual resume of science and letters. Raised on Long Island, he
studied anthropology at Harvard, taught the subject at Cambridge,
put himself through Harvard Medical School by writing suspense
novels under various ali-
</P>
<P>
   ases. Just for a laugh, he lifted one of his noms de plume from
a real-life 17th-century dwarf. Crichton kept his voracious hunger
for science but switched his career to writer.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 30, the lean, handsome Crichton had published
two best sellers under his own name (``The Andromeda Strain,''
``Terminal Man''), had directed and written the screenplay for
``Westworld,'' established himself as a busy Hollywood bachelor
after divorcing the first of four wives. (Steve Martin once
famously asked him, ``Don't you believe in premarital sex?'')
</P>
<P>
   With all these accomplishments and no clear goal, Crichton was
miserable.
</P>
<P>
   So for the first time in his life, he took some serious time
off.
</P>
<P>
   But with Crichton, even leisure is intense. As he relates in
1988's ``Travels,'' a book of nonfiction that gushes with the
self-revelation absent from his novels, the writer tried to go just
about everywhere and do just about everything. Dodging a raging
elephant in Africa. Scuba diving within arm's reach of sharks in
the South Pacific. Touring a brothel of school-age girls in Bangkok
(Crichton waited outside while his friend partook). Having a demon,
or ``dark entity,'' exorcised from his spirit. Bringing himself to
forgive his late father, an Advertising Age editor whom he called
``a mean son of a bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The journeys of self-discovery, Crichton writes, raised his
energy level even higher when he returned to serious work in the
mid-80s. His 1987 marriage to screenwriter Anne-Marie Martin (they
collaborated on the ``Twister'' script) and the birth of their
daughter the following year brought long-belated peace.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, his rigorous exercise _ scuba diving, 14-mile hikes
_ is part of keeping himself in emotional balance. When it's
mentioned that ``Harry Potter'' author J.K. Rowling had to wear a
wrist brace from signing so many books, Crichton _ who signed at
Chapter 11 Discount Bookstore at Ansley Mall Wednesday (after
viewing the Norman Rockwell exhibit at the High Museum) _ cracked,
``I'm toughened up; I'm in shape.'' He seems almost abashed to
admit that he no longer runs 10Ks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical activity,'' Crichton says, ``has the nice quality of
stopping mental activity.'' He reaches up, still looking a bit
groggy, and massages his forehead with a rueful smile. ``Stopping
the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about as close to ``opening up'' as this seemingly
impervious, flaw-free man will get in an interview. Even old crony
Dunne keeps finding out things he never suspected about his fellow
writer. Once they were walking along the Malibu beach with Dunne's
wife, Joan Didion, and she described to the ex-doctor some
neurological symptoms that had her physicians baffled. Crichton
guessed multiple sclerosis, and the diagnosis proved correct. When
Dunne asked Crichton how he knew, he answered, ``Because I have it,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the wondrously tall, sinewy Crichton looks healthy enough
to run Bill Bradley, a contemporary, off a basketball court. But
his deep emotional reserve is still palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is so strict about keeping his private life from
getting entwined with his work,'' says Lynn Nesbit, his longtime
agent, ``that some people don't know about his generosity of
spirit. I've seen him organize these wonderful overseas adventures
for his friends and siblings, so I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Crichton and his family have homes in suburban New York, Hawaii
and Los Angeles, but the last rarely gets used these days. Cutting
back on his writing and screenwriting duties in Hollywood _ ``A
place where you can't learn about much except treachery, where
people act all the time,'' he declares _ Crichton settled down in
the '90s to write ``Jurassic Park,'' ``The Lost World,''
``Airframe.'' ``Disclosure'' revolved around a man being sexually
harassed, then being accused of the same, by a female exec;
``Rising Sun'' around the business practices of the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton's still smarting from being labeled the cranky
reactionary. He got a feminist earful from Elizabeth Wurtzel in her
book, ``Bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were whole rooms of people furiously debating books they
had obviously not read,'' he growls. ``It taught me that our
culture will reduce any serious argument to its most simplistic
sound bite.''
</P>
<P>
   And now comes ``Timeline.'' Which raises the question: Are there
indeed parallel universes, and will people visit them, and travel
through time, during our lifetime?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is serious debate on this, which means you can't rule it
out,'' observes Crichton, whose science fiction is often right on
the cusp of real scientific discovery. ``The instantaneous
teleportation of information has actually taken place, in three
experiments. `Beam me up, Scotty' is not such a far-fetched idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``When `Jurassic' came out, people said cloning of mammals was
20 years away, but Dolly (the cloned ewe) came along in four. Now,
If I had to plunk down a quarter and make a bet, I'd say none of us
will live long enough to see an actual time machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Another patented Crichton pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then,'' he adds, grinning, ``I'm a conservative guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
