<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-GARBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARBER ABOLISHES SHOOTOUTS IN MLS MATCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Garber has moved quickly to make his mark on soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Garber, who replaced Doug Logan as MLS commissioner in August,
announced Wednesday the abolishment of the postmatch shootout,
indicating that the league will promote substance over gimmicks.
Further, the game clock will count up to 45 minutes for each half
and will be controlled directly by the referee, who will signal the
amount of injury time, in accordance with FIFA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Though the shootout will survive as a tie-breaker for the MLS
Cup final between Los Angeles and D.C. United at Foxboro Stadium
Sunday, the change in the clock will be unveiled in that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an assumption that the American soccer fan is
different than soccer fans from outside the US,'' Garber said
Wednesday. ``But there are millions of players, from 5-year-olds to
amateurs to professionals in this country who play the game
(according to FIFA rules) on a regular basis, and the league has
bypassed this market and underestimated it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, we based our marketing on future fans. We have to go
back and shore up our existence with the core soccer fan and build
the model with the core fans, and it took the league a couple of
years to realize this. There was a negativity buzzing among the
hardest-core fans that reached a momentum that we had to address.
We do know from our research that there are approximately 60
million people in this country that consider themselves soccer
fans. We don't have 60 million people going to our games.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote by the MLS competition committee to shoot down the
shootout was unanimous, Garber said. But that is only because of
Garber's ability to not only build consensus, but unanimity.
</P>
<P>
   Garber, 41, certainly knows about a tough sell, having made his
reputation by promoting the NFL in Europe. And though Garber had
only minimal knowledge of soccer, he gained ``an enormous respect''
for the game by closely observing it England, Germany, and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But Garber appears to understand that simple, subtle changes can
have profound effects and are preferable to drastic,
smoke-and-mirrors alterations, especially in a sport with such a
long tradition.
</P>
<P>
   MLS regular-season ties will progress to a 10-minute
sudden-death overtime. And the point system will be 3-1-0
(win-tie-loss), as in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Garber also has made progress behind the scenes, apparently
helping to reassure sponsors, three of whom renewed commitments
through 2003 this week, and stabilizing relations with
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   There will be more consistency in the ABC/ESPN telecasts in an
attempt to capture ``destination viewing.'' Next season will start
in mid-March, and 28 games will be shown on 19 consecutive
Saturdays from June to September. Also, a 60-minute highlights show
will air on Monday, likely starting at 11 p.m. on the East Coast.
The regular season will end in mid-September and the MLS Cup final
will be in early October, likely in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted that three of the four sponsors have decided
to continue their commitment,'' ESPN vice president Steve Risser
said, ``and that there will be a shorter, more concise schedule.
The MLS is young; it is still in a growth pattern. When we started
in 1996 we did not set high expectations for the league. Our job is
to build ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   Risser said MLS ratings are similar to NHL regular-season
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The MLS will have three divisions _ West (Colorado, Kansas City,
Los Angeles, San Jose), Central (Chicago, Columbus, Dallas, Tampa
Bay), and East (D.C. United, Miami, MetroStars, Revolution) . . .
More than 35,000 tickets have been sold for Sunday's game, and
Revolution CEO Brian O'Donovan said a crowd of more than 40,000 is
expected . . . The Univision programming announcement is expected
Friday . . . Jay Heaps of the Miami Fusion was named MLS Rookie of
the Year. Heaps played 32 games during the regular season and
playoffs, displaying his athleticism and speed at right back after
spending most of amateur career as an attacking player. ``That is
the best position for me, but it took a few games for me to get
settled,'' Heaps said during a presentation Boston Common
Wednesday. ``Right now, I'm taking 2 1/2 weeks off. After my season
at Duke, I went right into basketball, then trained at Feyenoord in
Holland and went right to the college All-Star game in Fort
Lauderdale. I've had six days off in the last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
