<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGO-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TANGO ARGENTINO': IT MOVES IN CHARMING FITS AND STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes follow review.) 
(lh) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When nine dancing pairs take to the stage of the
Gershwin Theater for the finale of the sultry ``Tango Argentino,''
it is as if we are eavesdropping on nine intimate dialogues, each
with its own subtle inflections. Severe-looking couples in formal
attire with slicked-back hair and masses of jewelry entwine and
unlock like lengths of magnetic rope. They create, in effect, a
sultanate of suaveness.
</P>
<P>
   The production, which opened Thursday night, is essentially a
reprise of a hit Broadway show from 1985 that accomplished for the
tango in New York circles something akin to what Chubby Checker did
for the twist. With the proliferation of tango shows over the
years, the stylish South American dance has shed some of its
mystique. But as the stars of ``Tango Argentino'' demonstrate, it
still moves in charming fits and starts to the rhythms of amorous
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Though the evening passes in a comfortable haze, it does at
times have a Lawrence Welk feel; knowledgeable fans, of course,
will be excited by the participation of tango legends like Juan
Carlos Copes and Maria Nieves, Hector and Elsa Maria Mayoral and
Nelida and Nelson. There is no set to speak of, simply a screen
that rises and falls between sequences, and a generic Broadway
backdrop with twinkling stars. As performed by a 13-piece orchestra
of strings, accordions and piano, the musical interludes are
pleasant, but some of the numbers by powerful, veteran Argentine
singers like Raul Lavie and Jovita Luna, who do everything but
wring handkerchiefs as they pour out their souls in song after
tormented song, do cross the line into kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   The counterpoint between the overheated songs and the cool,
liquid dances may be a calculation by Claudio Segovia and Hector
Orezzoli, the show's creators and directors, who want to reveal to
us two distinct chambers of the Argentine heart. Or maybe their
desire is to give ``Tango Argentino'' a variety-show veneer; that
it must vacate the Gershwin early next year to make way for
``Riverdance'' is entirely fitting. In either event, it is the
dancers who do the most startling turns and deservedly receive the
loudest ovations.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging in age from their 20s to 70s, the tangueros are a
portrait of aging gracefully in poignant tableaux. The younger
dancers use the entire stage for their immaculate footwork and
acrobatic twists; think of Torville and Dean without the skates.
This athleticism is on display in a number called ``Tanguera,''
danced by Pablo Veron and Guillermina Quiroga. Their collaboration
owes as much to the gym as to the dance floor, and their
contribution here has a playful element of competition. This is the
tango as martial art.
</P>
<P>
   Their older counterparts are like black belts of the form who
move with urgency and pride but with no apparent need to show off.
(Well, actually, in their backless gowns, the mature women do want
you to admire their musculature.) In ``Patetico,'' for instance,
Copes and Ms. Nieves are affecting in their precision and genteel
physical accommodation of each other; in ``Milonguero Viejo,''
Mayoral, who gave President Clinton a tango lesson on a visit to
Buenos Aires, Argentina, incorporates a courtly sense of honor into
his partnering of Ms. Mayoral.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dances, which do become repetitive, are duets. An
exception is ``Milonguita,'' a tango ballet. It employs much of the
company, and it is the only piece that tries to tell a real story.
The theme is jealousy; the protagonist is a young woman (Vanina
Bilous) who is the object of fascination for a circle of covetous
men and women. The tango is ideally applied to the tale, as it is a
dance of encounter on the brink of violence, and Ms. Bilous is
appealing as a Siren whose exotic charms are her downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tango Argentino,'' though, is not in the business of breaking
new ground. It wants instead to show you the enduring vitality and
intensity, the passion under control, of dancing cheek to cheek.
That it does terrifically well. Watching the nine couples together
on a stage, each making the tango their own, you're reminded of the
many restless patterns in which romance can flower.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TANGO ARGENTINO'
</P>
<P>
   Production conceived and directed by Claudio Segovia and Hector
Orezzoli; sets, costumes and lighting conceived by Segovia and
Orezzoli; choreographic conception by Segovia; choreography by the
dancers; lighting consultant, Marcelo Cuervo; sound by Gaston
Brisky; production company manager, Roberto Antier; executive
producers, Daniel Grinbank, Fernando Moya and Isabel Chapur.
Presented by DG Producciones. At the Gershwin Theater.
</P>
<P>
   With: Dancers: Juan Carlos Copes, Maria Nieves, Pablo Veron,
Nelida and Nelson, Hector and Elsa Maria Mayoral, Carlos and Ines
Borquez, Norma and Luis Pereyra, Carlos Copello and Alicia Monti,
Roberto Herrera and Lorena Yacono, Guillermina Quiroga, Vanina
Bilous, Antonio Cervila Jr. and Johana Copes. Singers: Raul Lavie,
Maria Grana, Jovita Luna and Alba Solis.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
