<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-JEWISH-IDENTITY18-COX     11-17 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-IDENTITY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As Jews gather in Atlanta, movement grows to strengthen
community amid assimilation
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Breathing in the rich, earthy scent of Georgia clay, a
group of Orthodox Jews in central DeKalb County, Ga., bury their
worn holy books in an ancient tradition. In her Roswell home, Paula
Shapiro, a Reform Jew, lights Shabbat candles with her children.
And, at Marietta's Etz Chaim, a Conservative synagogue, Irwin Weitz
begins the day with prayer, then schmoozes with fellow congregants
over bagels at a nearby eatery.
</P>
<P>
   This is Judaism as it is practiced in the largest metropolis of
the deep South and, increasingly, around the world. Far from a
monolithic belief system and culture, modern Jewishness ranges from
ultra-orthodox to secular with many variations in between.
</P>
<P>
   As 4,000 Jews gather in Atlanta this week for their 68th General
Assembly, the underlying theme of many of their workshops and
seminars is what it means to be a Jew today. The freedom for Jews
to define their own Jewishness is both a blessing and a bane, say
the Jewish leaders who will address the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single most important thing about Jewish identity today,
if you look across the span of people who identify themselves as
Jews, is that it's incredibly diverse,'' said Jonathan Woocher,
executive vice president of the Jewish Education Service of North
America, a New York-based agency that promotes Jewish education.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity is the result of changes in society, both among
Jews and among non-Jews, he said. Once Jews had little choice but
to be identified as Jews. Anti-Semitism and life in ghettos or
ethnic enclaves ensured that they were seen as set apart from other
people. In recent decades, those invisible walls no longer hold.
Jews have the freedom to be as fully Jewish as they desire, or to
dispense altogether with their ethnic and religious identity.
</P>
<P>
   As Jews have blended into every aspect of American life, they
have intermingled and intermarried with other religious and ethnic
groups. Those who care deeply about the continuity of the Jewish
people see this widespread acceptance as a serious threat to the
preservation of their thousands-of-years-old heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their fears were confirmed by a 1990 National Jewish
Population Survey published by the Council of Jewish Federations.
The study showed that while 68 percent of all married born Jews
were also married to someone born Jewish, the choice of marriage
partners changed dramatically in the latter half of the century. By
1985, twice as many Jews married Gentiles as married other Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Even more troubling to Jewish leaders, only 28 percent of the
children of mixed households were being raised Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, American Jews, once focused on the survival of
Israel, turned their attention to the survival of their own
community, said Kenneth Stein, professor of contemporary Middle
Eastern history and Israeli studies at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned about how will Jews survive in the
assimilationist environment in America,'' said Stein. ``How do you
sustain Jewishness? How do you be sure that your kids don't
intermarry? How do you keep traditions and customs going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is that we want people to have the freedom to
leave,'' said Arnold Eisen, chair of the department of religious
studies at Stanford University. ``We want them to voluntarily
choose to come. You want to always give them reasons to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   As baby boomers age and the millennium winds down, many Jews are
experiencing a spiritual awakening that is evident in other
segments of American society, said Barry Shrage, president of the
Combinied Jewish Philanthropies of Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But helping individual Jews find a personal faith is not enough,
said Eisen. Jews must also build strong connections to other Jews.
``We've discovered that what American Jews are after from their
Jewishness is a combination of meaning and community,'' he said.
``When the Jewish world reaches out to people and gives them this
meaning to live for and the feeling that they're part of something
larger than themselves, they respond positively.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to strengthen Jewish community are centering on three
areas _ serious Jewish learning, caring for Jews in Israel and
throughout the diaspora, and a commitment to social justice, said
Shrage.
</P>
<P>
   Shrage, Eisen and Woocher are all taking part in a session of
the General Assembly on ``Jewish Renaissance and Renewal.'' All say
they see evidence that many Jews, no longer part of ethnic
neighborhoods, are seeking communities through Jewish
organizations. They point to growth in the number of synagogues,
Jewish schools and adult education programs across America as
evidence that people are choosing to connect with their Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, home to an estimated 100,000 Jews, a series of
lay classes for adults in everything from Yiddish to Jewish
spirituality quickly fills to capacity every year. The metro area
now has about two dozen synagogues, from Hassidic to humanistic,
many with current or recently completed building programs. And, the
Jewish Federation of Greater Atlanta launched a $50 million
campaign two years ago to expand and spruce up local Jewish schools
and agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that, the institutions reach a minority of Jews. Only
four in 10 metro Atlanta Jews belong to any Jewish organization,
according to a 1996 study by the Atlanta Jewish Federation, and
fewer than one in five attend synagogue at least monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jews go back and forth, being more or less Jewish
religiously and culturally during different times in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Weitz, 45, of Marietta was raised in an Orthodox synagogue and a
``semi-observant'' home by parents who survived the Holocaust, kept
kosher and did not travel on Saturday. But as an adult, his
involvement in Judaism was largely limited to attending synagogue
services during the High Holidays of Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he and his family _ a wife and four children _
have ``reconnected.'' He joined Etz Chaim to make certain he could
get tickets to holiday services, and eventually began attending
Shabbat services and even participating in a daily minyan, or
morning prayer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judaism is a set of values that helps me live my life,'' he
said. ``It is a history of my family and my people. It is important
for my wife and myself to carry forward the traditions and values
that we learned from our parents and that we feel are important and
pass them on to our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Benyomin Friedman, 42, believes part of his responsibility
is to help Jews discover the meaning of their Jewishness. While
many people will drift away from their heritage, others will claim
it with renewed vigor precisely because they must consciously
embrace it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish community is talking about continuity and wondering
if there will be continuity,'' said Friedman, rabbi of the Orthodox
synagogue Congregation Ariel in Dunwoody. ``This is what I
envision: The number of Jews will drop off greatly but the core
will get stronger. A vibrant core, it will far surpass previous
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
