<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INDONESIA-HYPERMARKET     11-17 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-HYPERMARKETS-ART-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S CONSUMER-LED RECOVERY PAYS OFF FOR FOREIGN-OWNED
HYPERMARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In October last year, deep in the midst of
Indonesia's financial breakdown, the French food retailer Carrefour
set up one of its sprawling hypermarkets on the edge of Jakarta. If
opening a fancy modern grocery in a shrinking Third World economy
seemed risky then, it seemed foolhardy a month later, when rioting
mobs came to the new Carrefour and looted it.
</P>
<P>
   In the year that followed, though, the supermarket has been
visited by a different sort of mob, one bent on buying as much as
it can.
</P>
<P>
   Carrefour and another French chain, Promodes, have been so
successful in Indonesia despite the country's severe economic
downturn that they now have a total of five stores in Jakarta and
plan to build more.
</P>
<P>
   The two global companies, which in August agreed to a $16.6
billion merger, are revolutionizing Indonesia's retail industry by
offering shoppers a greater variety of products at prices lower
than those at traditional markets, with no haggling and no pesky
flies. Besides illustrating the potential that exists for patient
foreign investors, the success of the French retailers illuminates
one of the most baffling aspects of Asia's financial crisis. The
phenomenon helps explain how Asia's cities managed to maintain a
surprising air of normality _ even a sober prosperity _ thanks to a
vast cushion of middle-class savings that helped sustain consumer
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say this reservoir of personal wealth is one of the
keys to Asia's unexpectedly rapid bounce-back from the financial
crisis touched off in Thailand in mid-1997. Even in Indonesia,
where the economy shrank 13 percent last year, cities seized by
riots over rising prices and official corruption quickly regained
their bustle. Now, calmed by a new democratically elected
government, the country is joining an economic recovery across the
region in which affluent households hold a vital role. Driven thus
far by low interest rates and government spending, economists say,
the recovery will increasingly depend on the bourgeoisie's ample
pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recovery has to be carried by households,'' said David
Fernandez, an economist with J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the crisis should have been a great leveler,
devastating the affluent by destroying the value of their property
and their shareholdings while eliminating jobs in such modern
industries as manufacturing and construction that were suffering
from excess capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Indonesia's middle- and upper-classes have survived the
crisis largely intact, thanks to traditional values of thrift and
mutual family support, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   It was this growing class of affluent Indonesians that lured
big-name foreign retailers to Indonesia in the first place. Though
the average annual income in Indonesia is just $600, the gulf
between haves and have-nots is tremendous. In a nation of 207
million people, the world's fourth most populous country, there are
roughly 20 million people in households that spend at least $1,200
a year on routine expenses like rent and food, according to A.C.
Nielsen, the market research firm. They represent a market of color
TV-owning consumers larger than the entire population of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge country with huge markets,'' said Percival
Manglano, a consultant with the Castle Group here, a consulting
company for foreign investors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Carrefour set its sights on Indonesia in the mid-1990s as part
of an expansion that led it into Taiwan, Malaysia, China and
Singapore. J.C. Penney and Wal-Mart Stores also set up shop in the
country. Because Indonesian laws prohibited direct foreign
investment in retailing, each had to find a local partner.
Carrefour teamed up with a powerful ethnic-Chinese family that owns
a distribution company, Tigaraksa Satria.
</P>
<P>
   The financial crisis that started in Thailand in mid-1997 and
soon spread to Indonesia changed everything. Wal-Mart and J.C.
Penney cleared out. Though the International Monetary Fund, as a
condition of its $43 billion economic aid package, compelled
Indonesia to lift its restriction on foreign retail investment,
Carrefour and Promodes delayed plans to open as riots shook
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   While the violence and demonstrations were bringing down
Indonesia's corrupt regime, the crisis was seemingly devastating
Carrefour's potential customers. The nation's currency, the rupiah,
plummeted more than 75 percent against the dollar, real wages fell
35 percent and the number of Indonesians the World Bank estimated
were living in poverty doubled, to 40 million.
</P>
<P>
   In outer islands, poor subsistence communities felt little
impact. Those that were growing cash crops that could be exported
even enjoyed a local boom as a result of the rupiah's plunge.
</P>
<P>
   It was the urban poor and villagers on overcrowded Java that
bore the brunt. ``The amount of money you need to live in squalor
has gone up tremendously,'' said Farquhar Stirling, managing
director at A.C. Nielsen's office in Jakarta. Some families had to
stop sending their children to school for a time and some Javanese
were forced to skip meals. For many though, strong family ties
provided a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who were laid off went back to their villages, and
their mothers and fathers took care of them,'' said Sri Adiningsih,
an economist at Indonesia's Gadjah Mada University. The middle
class also had its own insurance. Indonesians, like most Asians,
are prodigious savers, stashing away on average roughly a quarter
of their income. During the crisis, inflation eroded the real value
of these savings, but sky-high interest rates of more than 35
percent on deposits helped soften the blow.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious consumers cut back on spending, but with their bank
balances rocketing higher, many middle class and affluent city
dwellers felt wealthy enough to maintain a comfortable existence.
An indeterminate amount of spending money, economists say, came
from a sizeable ``informal'' economy: untaxed, traditional cottage
and service industries, mattress money and gold.
</P>
<P>
   So, while by official measures spending has not yet recovered,
many retailers and wholesalers say it has. That is in part because
money that has not been spent on airline tickets or automobiles has
entered the retail sector in ways that do not always show up in the
consumer-spending figures.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Determined entrepreneurs opened up roadside food stalls, serving
everything from humble noodles to steak and cappuccino, eventually
becoming a sort of trendy alfresco Bohemia. Flea markets
proliferated.
</P>
<P>
   And even during the worst of the Indonesian crisis, when orders
to manufacturers dried up, merchandise was still selling on the
street. Now orders are skyrocketing, said Wolfgang Piroth,
president-director of the Indonesian subsidiary of Bayer A.G., as
distributors scramble to rebuild their stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the scene at the glitzy Plaza Senayan shopping mall
in Jakarta, Indonesia's top savers never lost their appetite for
the finer things. Instead of flying to nearby Singapore to buy
their Cartier watches, they are buying them at home, said Victor
Sassoon, whose Rubina Watch is Cartier's sole distributor in
Indonesia. ``The country is very rich,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Plaza Senayan's Louis Vuitton outlet, employees say they were
never at a loss for customers. ``All the time, they're buying,
buying, buying,'' said Sadaeli, the shop manager. Across the way, a
new Bulgari outlet is opening.
</P>
<P>
   All of which helps explain why retailers with razor-thin margins
like Carrefour and Promodes are able to generate the kind of
volumes they need to flourish here. Indonesians with savings are
willing to spend on products they find attractive _ especially if
the merchandise is also perceived as a good value.
</P>
<P>
   To an American visitor, a Carrefour appears little different
from an overstocked Wal-Mart with groceries. But in Jakarta, it is
a novelty: brightly lit, with wide aisles and spotless linoleum
floors. Employees will clean and filet fish, and on a recent day
rap music was playing in the background.
</P>
<P>
   A traditional market nearby presents a stark contrast. Hot and
dank, the narrow alleys are littered with garbage. A cat wanders
through carrying a fish head in its mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood market has its advantages. A five-kilogram bag
of rice that goes for 17,000 rupiah ($2.45) at Carrefour costs just
14,000 rupiah in the market. And at the market, where she has been
shopping for more than 30 years, ``you can bargain,'' said Isa
Salim. Sure, the hypermarkets take credit cards, but at the market,
``if I forget my purse, I can borrow money from the shopkeepers,''
Mrs. Salim added.
</P>
<P>
   On a no-haggle basis, however, a bag of sugar costs about the
same at Carrefour and eggs are cheaper there. Meat is neatly
wrapped in cellophane; at the market it is covered in flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are realizing that hygiene is important, and wet
markets are not hygienic,'' said Manglano of the Castle Group. Even
his live-in maid has switched from the market to Carrefour in
search of cleaner meat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Jakartans long ago moved on to modern local grocers
like Hero Supermarket. But Carrefour and Promodes offer greater
selections and lower prices. Analysts say the two companies
benefited from their partners' wider and more efficient
distribution networks, which has allowed them to survive with
profit margins as low as 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors say the foreign grocers have no profit margin at
all, and some accuse them of selling below cost. ``They can't make
any profit if they continue selling that cheaply,'' said Steven
Sondakh, chairman of the Indonesia Retailers Association and a
director at Hero.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Carrefour nor Promodes responded to numerous requests
for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Sondakh says as the hypermarkets encroach, they are driving
small mom-and-pop stores out of business. He is leading an effort
to get Indonesia's Parliament to pass zoning laws that will keep
superstores like Carrefour and Continent out of downtown Jakarta,
where he says they will worsen the city's traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   The hypermarkets, which convey how the globalization of
Indonesia is continuing, are undeterred. Continent has opened three
stores and is planning a fourth; Carrefour has two and wants to
open two more, one in Jakarta and another in the nearby Javanese
city Bandung. At some point after the companies merge _ in a deal
that would create the world's second-biggest retailer after
Wal-Mart _ the two brands will become one.
</P>
<P>
   And as consumer spending revives, there will undoubtedly still
be room in the cities for traditional retailers, too, thanks to
loyal bargain-hunters like Mrs. Salim. ``For people with smaller
budgets,'' she said as she headed for the market butcher, ``this
will last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
