<SLUG> BC-EXECUTE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Case could influence Georgia electrocutions
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia soon may be forced to adopt another method of
capital punishment, legislators and attorneys on both sides of the
death penalty debate said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, Georgia lawmakers have considered, and
quickly dismissed, legislation to authorize lethal injection _
either as an alternative to or as a replacement for electrocution.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Supreme Court last month agreed to hear a Florida
case in which a condemned man argued that electrocution violated
his right of protection from cruel and unusual punishment,
following several recent mishaps during executions in Florida's
electric chair. In two electrocutions, flames shot from the body of
the condemned men when the switches were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be a bill,'' said state Rep. Jim Martin,
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, who called Wednesday's
committee meeting to hear from the state's death penalty defense
lawyers and others opposed to capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, with 121 inmates on death row, is one of only four
states that rely solely on electrocution. Seven other states use
the electric chair or another method, usually lethal injection.
While Florida uses only the electric chair, it has a ``backup''
statute that would automatically switch to lethal injection if
electrocution was found to be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Thurbert Baker would like to see the
Georgia Legislature do as Florida has, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking a position on what the alternative (method of
execution) would be, but we think it would be wise to have the
fallback position only if told by a court of competent jurisdiction
that we cannot use the electric chair,'' said Jeff DiSantis of the
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers believe Georgia would be better off if the court
rules that electrocution is constitutional. There would be greater
implications for this state if the court simply issued a limited
ruling that Florida's electric chair was unconstitutional, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it applies only to Florida, there will be a flood of
litigation about the differences between Georgia's and Florida's
chairs,'' said defense attorney Jack Martin, the committee
chairman's brother. ``Lethal injection is the less horrible of the
alternatives. It's unethical for a veterinarian to kill an animal
by electrocution, (yet) we're doing it to human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Martin said he opposes the death penalty, but if there has
to be capital punishment in Georgia at the very least the method
should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Another death penalty opponent said the Legislature should wait
until the high court rules before making changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the law is changed midstream ... lawyers are going to have
legitimate grounds for appeal,'' said Mike Mears of the
Multi-County Public Defender Office, explaining that those already
sentenced to die by electrocution could argue that their sentences
would be voided if the method was changed to lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't do anything until the Supreme Court tells us what the
law is,'' Mears said. ``If we start anticipating what the court is
going to do, inevitably we're going to get it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
