<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CRASH-PILOT-BOS &LR;      11-17 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-PILOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPICION MOVES TOWARD COPILOT IN FLIGHT 990 PLUNGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Egyptian officials prepared to review and
examine the evidence, federal aviation investigators have
identified the key words and movements of a backup copilot who they
suspect deliberately pushed EgyptAir Flight 990 into a suicide
dive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my decision now. I put my faith in God's hands,'' the
copilot, Gamil El Batouty, said before the jet's auto-pilot
disconnected and the aircraft began a steep dive that reached
near-supersonic speed, according to a federal law enforcement
source with knowledge of the airliner's cockpit recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Television reported Wednesday night that the copilot is
heard on the tape saying in Arabic: ``Tawakalna ala Allah.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase, used commonly in Egypt, is the rough equivalent of,
``God help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Those comments attributed to Batouty, a veteran airline pilot
who was not assigned to fly that early in the 11-hour trip, has
strengthened suspicions that the Boeing 767's 217 passengers and
crew died from a deliberate act _ and that Batouty was at the
controls when it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian officials dispatched here by their government are
expected to begin scrutinizing the cockpit recordings as well as
information from the flight data recorder, considered key pieces of
evidence that the Atlantic Ocean crash site 60 miles south of
Nantucket will soon be considered a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   But other authorities criticized news reports that the
investigation has shifted to Batouty and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Egyptian government did not receive until (Wednesday) the
American authorities' reports of the current investigation
concerning the EgyptAir crash,'' Egypt Information Minister Safawad
el Sherif said in a statement. ``What is being reported in the
foreign media is mere speculation, hypothesis, and imagination that
does not reach the level of documented fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board is not expected to turn
the case over to the Federal Bureau of Investigation until Egyptian
officials have had a chance to fully examine the current evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of showing them the evidence and laying it out
to get whatever their input might be,'' said one NTSB official.
``Before we move forward on a decision like this, we want to be
very careful, to make certain we are being thorough and methodical
and correct in our decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB said they hope the Egyptian officials will help fully
interpret the conversations, listening for nuances and voice
inflections as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still trying to figure out what this guy was doing,
what his thoughts were, when he was saying his prayer,'' said a US
official who has talked with Egyptian security authorities in
Cairo. ``I don't think anyone for sure knows for sure what was
going on with that person. (They) keep saying that this prayer this
fellow was saying was not unusual, that it wasn't unusual for him
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   An FBI official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Egyptians aren't convinced the jet was doomed by a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to hear all the evidence and hear everything before
turning it over to a criminal investigation,'' the FBI official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Using the jet's flight data recorder, which monitors scores of
the plane's mechanical functions, and its cockpit voice recorder,
which captures conversations and other sounds on the flight deck,
authorities are piecing together the final, terrifying moments of
the Cairo-bound jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-hour after an early-morning liftoff from John F.
Kennedy International Airport in New York on Oct. 31, the Boeing
767-300ER began a steep but controlled descent from 33,000 feet.
Within moments, it had reached extraordinary speed, and power had
been cut to the twin jet engines. The speed brake, used to slow the
aircraft in flight, had been deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The plane struggled back up to several thousand feet before it
pitched over in a final dive, breaking up just before it smashed
into the ocean about 60 miles off the coast of Nantucket in depths
that reach 270 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit voice recorder _ one of two ``black boxes'' _ was
retrieved from the ocean floor by a submersible robot last week.
The information on it has helped unravel some of the puzzling final
moments of Flight 990, and authorities will work through the
weekend to produce a transcript.
</P>
<P>
   After examining the recordings, sources said, investigators
believe the crash was deliberate because one pilot left the
cockpit, and the remaining pilot at the helm _ Batouty _ talked of
``going into death,'' according to some reports.
</P>
<P>
   Using sophisticated audio equipment, authorities are hoping to
electronically enhance the cockpit recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was not scheduled to fly until much later in the
flight to Egypt, Batouty had asked for and was given permission to
take over the plane's controls.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty, 59, was nearing retirement, sources said and his
daughter was critically ill with lupus. The Los Angeles Times said
he was worried about paying her medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that EgyptAir representatives
familiar with Batouty's voice identified it on the cockpit
recording, but officials cautioned that they had no other
verification of the backup copilot's voice. Four pilots were
assigned to the flight, including one other relief pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian officials will try to confirm the identification
and carefully assess the tone and intention of the words he
uttered. They will also try to pinpoint when the prayer is said in
the sequence of events that sent the plane plummeting.
</P>
<P>
   About the time the pilot is heard invoking God's name, the jet's
autopilot is turned off, and it plunged into a steep dive.
</P>
<P>
   The tape detects the cockpit's door opening as authorities
believe the pilot, Captain Ahmed El Habashi, returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on?'' he asks. Authorities believe Habashi then
tried to regain control of the jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pull with me. Help me. Pull with me,'' Habashi is heard saying
as the plane's elevators on either side of the jet's tail move in
opposition directions: the one controlled from the captain's chair
moved up while the other moved down.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation specialists say that indicated a struggle for control
of the airplane in the twin-yoke cockpit: as one pilot pulled up on
one yoke to make the plane climb, the other pushed the second yoke
forward to make it dive.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators continued their work here, NTSB Chairman James
E. Hall said the Navy will turn over responsibility for retrieving
more of the plane's wreckage to a Navy salvage team.
</P>
<P>
   A large salvage ship, now in Europe, is due at the crash site by
Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy's supervisor of salvage has been directed to contract
for a large ship with heavy lift capability that can operate in
heavy seas, and send it to the accident site as soon as possible
for the retrieval of human remains and aircraft wreckage,'' Hall
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Charles M. Sennott reporting from the Middle East and John
Donnelly of the Globe staff in Washington contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
