<HEADLINE>
FAMILY, FRIENDS DEFEND EGYPTAIR PILOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT AND NADIA ABOU EL-MAGD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ With investigators focusing on a copilot they suspect of
seizing the controls and forcing EgyptAir Flight 990 into a fatal
dive, the pilot's colleagues and family Wednesday lashed out at the
accusations and painted a portait of one of the carrier's best
pilots and a loving father.
</P>
<P>
   According to those who knew him, Gamil El Batouty, 59, was a
devoted husband and father of five who was nearing retirement after
flying for EgyptAir for more than 30 years and serving as a flight
instructor for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   He was wealthy, he was healthy, and he had everything to live
for, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure that he did not do this. The whole world must know
he is not capable of this,'' said his wife, Omayama Fahmi, 50,
dressed in black as she sat in the family home in Heliopolis, a
wealthy enclave of the sprawling city of Cairo near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go and ask EgyptAir, ask his friends, ask the neighbors. He
could never do something like this,'' she added, her voice hoarse
from crying and anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This day is harder than the day he died,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   An extended family of children, cousins, and in-laws clustered
around a television in the living room. A framed picture of
Batouty, a smiling, robust man with thick black hair, hung on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   CNN was broadcasting reports that Batouty was at the controls
and that investigators believed he may have intentionally sent the
Boeing 767 into a nose-dive, perhaps as a means of suicide, killing
all 217 people on board. The network was reporting that Batouty
murmured a prayer as the plane plummeted at near super-sonic speed
into the waters off Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty's brother-in-law, Yehia Hegazi, screamed at the
television and turned away in anger, saying, ``They are searching
for a scapegoat!''
</P>
<P>
   Anger at the allegations being reported in Western media were
felt not only by the family, but by Egyptians on the streets of
Cairo and throughout the Egyptian media.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's editions of Al-Wafd, a liberal newspaper published in
Arabic and English, headlined: ``Egypt rejects American Allegations
on Plane Disaster.'' The article said a phrase being attributed to
Batouty on the plane's cockpit voice recorder _ ``I made my
decision now. I put my faith in God's hands'' _ ``is a phrase
commonly used by Muslims facing a serious crisis and would have
nothing to do with suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Scrambling for explanations for the crash, some American news
organizations reported that Batouty may have been distraught over
the failing health of a 10-year-old daughter who suffers from lupus
erythematosus, a degenerative disease that attacks the joints and
immune system.
</P>
<P>
   But Fahmi said her daughter's health had been improving, that
she had only one treatment left, and that they were all hopeful she
would be cured. She said Batouty had taken the girl to UCLA Medical
Center several times for examinations and had planned to take her
back there in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Walid Batouty, a nephew of the copilot, dismissed any connection
between the accident and the daughter's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would never do this for the simple reason he would never
put his family through what they are going through right now,'' he
said. ``He loved his children. He worshiped them.''
</P>
<P>
   The young girl, whose name is Aya, looked on from another room,
smiling shyly. Her face and eyes were swollen from tears or perhaps
her treatments. But she had no apparent physical difficulty in
walking and playing.
</P>
<P>
   Before Batouty left on the New York to Cairo leg of the flight,
he had spoken with his wife and family on the phone, Fahmi said. It
was a typical conversation. He talked to his son about buying a
black jacket for him and wanted to know if it was the right style.
He also discussed buying two new tires for a sports car the son
owns, because they are cheaper in the US, and he asked his son to
pick him up at the airport to help him carry them home.
</P>
<P>
   His wife said he had also bought his youngest daughter a Barbie
Doll as a surprise because she had been wanting one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am bringing a beautiful gift for you,'' he told the girl by
phone, said his wife, who recounted the conversation in a voice
cracking with emotion and tears.
</P>
<P>
   His family said Batouty had much to live for. He was set to
retire in two months and he was considering working for another
carrier in the Arab world while also collecting his pension from
EgyptAir. But he wanted to work less, feeling that his family had
suffered from a schedule that had him traveling most of the time.
Just before leaving on the first leg of the ill-fated flight, he
had hosted a party for his son, Mohammed, 21, after his graduation
from police academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very proud of his children,'' said his wife, offering
to show a video of Batouty dancing and enjoying the evening of his
son's party.
</P>
<P>
   He was also planning a family party for New Year's Day to
celebrate the millennium and 35 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   His wife said that he often told her, ``This house is our
garden, and you are the most beautiful flower of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatouty's family called him a religious man, but not a fanatic.
They said he read the Koran and prayed five times a day, as is the
custom for devout Muslims. He attended a nearby mosque but not
faithfully, because he was so often away on flights. He was also
occasionally drank a beer or a glass of wine, which is forbidden in
Islam, said his landlord, Shafik el Banna.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was religious but not overly religious,'' El Banna added.
</P>
<P>
   Many family members said they were furious at the media for
suggesting that a man who prays as he faces imminent death is
somehow strange or perhaps a fanatic. Egyptian culture is very
traditional and prayers are part of the customs of everyday life,
they noted, and pointed out that suicide is an unacceptable sin for
a Sunni Muslim, as Batouty was.
</P>
<P>
   The family had no obvious financial concerns.
</P>
<P>
   They have two vacation villas, a weekend home in a suburb of
Cairo and another on the Mediterranean coast near Alexandria.
Batouty hailed from a well-known Egyptian family, and his father
was the mayor of the city Kafr el Bousy in the Nile Delta.
</P>
<P>
   He earned $48,000 a year, an excellent salary in Egypt. And he
had a side business of leasing family-owned land for farming.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir provided $75,000 of life insurance to all employees,
said EgyptAir Captain Roshdy Zakaria, who knew and worked with
Batouty. Recently, he added, pilots had negotiated to get an
additional $75,000 in insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty did not take out any additional insurance beyond that,
according to both Zakaria and Batouty's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not have insurance. He believed this was a bad omen,''
his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   He had flown the Boeing 767 on the overseas route to New York
and Los Angeles for nearly 10 years. He had also been an occasional
flight instructor for the Egyptian military.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had a dangerous profession, he would comfort his
wife by telling her it is ``more dangerous to drive a car than to
fly a plane.''
</P>
<P>
   His health was apparently excellent. His family said he often
joked that his younger friends envied his good health.
</P>
<P>
   If he had a fault, it was perhaps that he worked too hard,
family members said. They could remember Batouty taking only two
holidays in his career, once on a pilgrimage to Mecca _ the duty of
every devout Muslim who can afford it _ and once for a medical
checkup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man would hang on to life until the last second. He had a
family that he adored. And he loved his wife so much,'' said Walid.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she thinks happened on board the flight, his wife
answered, ``God only knows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
