<SLUG> BC-IRS-WORKERS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS INVESTIGATORS CONCERNED AS THEY BECOME TARGETS OF
INVESTIGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Urged by Congress to get tough on abuse of taxpayers, a new team
of Treasury agents plans a sharp increase in investigations of
Internal Revenue Service employees for misconduct _ anything from
harassing taxpayers to theft. Indeed, the number of cases expected
to be opened against IRS employees will soon nearly equal the
number of cases against Americans suspected of tax crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The new Treasury inspector general for tax affairs has set a
goal for the fiscal year that began last month that would increase
by half the number of IRS workers who will be investigated, and he
plans to increase the goal by at least 25 percent more the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS goal has stirred worries even within the inspector
general's own staff that investigators are being forced to search
for far more misdeeds than may exist, will waste time on trivia and
will be pressured to trump up cases.
</P>
<P>
   IRS managers and union leaders say the intensified scrutiny will
distract many IRS agents as they defend themselves, making the
agency less potent in pursuing tax cheats. Such distractions,
following years of cuts by Congress in the ranks of auditors and
tax collectors, are one reason the IRS plans to slash audit rates
by a third next year.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts are coming even as a growing number of Americans are
using aggressive tactics to avoid paying taxes. Some are taking
advantage of new rules intended to protect taxpayers from
overzealous IRS workers and others are betting that with a shortage
of auditors and collectors, no one will pursue them.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the stepped-up efforts say they are important
to prevent abuses by IRS agents. ``The intention of the new office
and the new law is not a witch hunt, but to ensure that IRS
employees and taxpayers are treated civilly and that problems are
reviewed by an independent oversight entity,'' said Sen. William
Roth Jr., R-Del., who sponsored legislation that created the
inspector general's office last year.
</P>
<P>
   If the goals are met, nearly one in 28 IRS employees will be
investigated in the next fiscal year for suspected misconduct _
anything from harassing taxpayers to theft.
</P>
<P>
   Among front-line tax workers, like auditors and tax collectors,
the numbers are even more stark. As many as 1 in 9 will be
investigated. By comparison, inspectors general will investigate
fewer than 1 in 2,000 workers at the Agriculture Department and the
Health and Human Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 235 misconduct investigations have been completed, of
which 161, or about 68 percent, were found to lack merit. In 33
cases, or 14 percent, some form of misconduct was found; in most
cases employees failed to pay their own taxes or threatened a
taxpayer with an audit. In 20 cases, misconduct was found that did
not involve taxpayers; the remaining 21 cases involved non-IRS
employees, such as people impersonating tax collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The misconduct investigations are only one issue vexing the IRS.
Senior IRS executives, meeting in Washington last month, expressed
their own worries that the agency barely had the minimum resources
to maintain compliance.
</P>
<P>
   These officials attributed this to fallout from the IRS Reform
and Restructuring Act of 1998, which created the inspector
general's office as a unit of the Treasury Department with the
understanding that it would aggressively pursue complaints of
wrongdoing against IRS employees at all levels. That law mandates
the firing of IRS workers who commit any of 10 acts, some of which
employees say are part of their routine duties. For example, the
law mandates firing any tax worker who harasses a taxpayer, and tax
collectors say the standard is so broad that they can be discharged
if they go to a store to collect taxes owed by the owner and
customers witness the effort.
</P>
<P>
   IRS employees are ``walking on eggshells'' out of fear they will
be investigated, disciplined or even fired just for doing their
jobs, the official summary of the meetings said.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner of Internal Revenue, Charles Rossotti, said he
does not share the concern of many of his executives about the
degree of scrutiny. ``It is critical that every allegation of
misconduct be investigated,'' he said in a statement, ``and in the
relatively small percentage of cases where misconduct has actually
occurred, employees should be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   David C. Williams, the inspector general, said his goals of
4,000 new cases this year and 5,000 next year are not quotas,
although he acknowledged that many of his own special agents were
skeptical, partly because one regional office did assign specific
numbers of cases to individual inspectors. Williams reversed that
directive.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the cases involve IRS workers. About 1,600 cases a year
involve people who have, for example, threatened or attacked IRS
employees.
</P>
<P>
   But in separate interviews, nine special agents in the inspector
general's office said they were told to press misconduct cases
after they had concluded they lacked merit and that managers seemed
fearful of dropping any investigation for fear of missing some
wrongdoing, however minor. But one special agent said inspections
were not aggressive enough. None of the 10 would speak without
being assured anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Quigley, president of the Federal Law Enforcement Officers
Association unit representing the Treasury inspector general's 445
special agents, praised Williams for his leadership, but said the
goals trouble investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numerical goals may allow the possibility of abuse, by
overzealous agents and by overzealous managers,'' Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said investigators also think they are wasting time pursuing
harassment complaints that clearly lack merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already seen spurious allegations made that, in the
opinion of the investigators, were designed to thwart the
administration of the tax laws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Williams, in e-mail to his staff, emphasized ``major cases and
high impact work,'' which is ``the most important element in
expressing our value to our stakeholders in Congress and the
Treasury.''
</P>
<P>
   That language has alarmed the National Treasury Employees Union,
which represents most IRS workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference between a goal and a quota?'' asked
Colleen Kelley, the union's president.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Frank Heffler, head of the union's New York chapter, said
anonymous accusations of minor misconduct, like leaving work early,
are treated as major cases. ``Your neighbors are asked if you are a
drug user or an alcoholic and your tax return is pulled,'' he said,
``so instead of finding people who aren't paying their taxes, you
are defending yourself from a charge that could have been proven
false in a minute by just looking at your time report.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Paul C. Light, who has studied inspectors general and is
director of government studies at the Brookings Institution, a
Washington research organization, said the goal of 4,000 cases
``seems to me investigation run amok.''
</P>
<P>
   Light said he found it ``ironic that the very thing that sparked
creation of the IRS' inspector generalship, the setting of
arbitrary quotas on property seizures and the like, is now being
applied to the IRS itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the ``chance of someone filing a false allegation
to cause trouble is present and can be substantial from time to
time, and we do our best to find those and to make sure that no
harm comes to the person who is falsely accused.'' He added, ``We
now are receiving large numbers of allegations that are untrue and
we do factor that in and we understand that we have to be there for
the ones that are true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
