<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-ISLAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSLIM SCHOLARS URGE CAUTION IN INTERPRETING TAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it happened like this: Just before the plane went down,
the Egyptian co-pilot said, ``I made my decision now. I put my
faith in God's hands,'' knowing he was going to sabotage the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it happened like this: Just before the plane went down,
the Egyptian co-pilot said, ``I made my decision now. I put my
faith in God's hands,'' realizing he was powerless to stop the
crash, and reaching out to God in the last moments of his life.
</P>
<P>
   As federal investigators struggle to translate the Arabic voices
on the EgyptAir Flight 990 cockpit voice recorder, Muslim scholars
caution that translation is an imprecise art. Language can be
vague, they say. Words carry different meanings in different
cultures. Officials want to be certain when exactly the co-pilot
uttered his words: before the plane went down, or after it started
to plummet.
</P>
<P>
   But with each news conference or leak about the cockpit tapes,
Muslim scholars note, comes more speculation and more stereotypes.
If a Muslim makes reference to God, Americans unschooled in Islam
assume, he must be talking about death.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this one, you really can use the phrase, `the rush to
judgment,' '' said John L. Esposito, director of the Center for
Christian-Muslim Understanding at Georgetown University. ``If you
don't handle it well, you create a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   America has been through this before. In the first days after
the Oklahoma City bombing, observers were quick to suggest that
Middle Eastern terrorists were responsible. Esposito was invited on
TV talk shows, to muse about connections that didn't exist. His
Muslim friends told him they got funny looks from people they had
known for years.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, Muslim leaders say, that prejudice stems from
ignorance. There are six million Muslims in America, and Islam will
soon become the nation's second-largest religion, said Ibrahim
Hooper, communications director at Council on American-Islamic
Relations in Washington. But the Muslim-American community is still
relatively new _ most immigrants arrived in the last three decades
_ and relatively unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many Americans have learned about Islam from the news,
in stories about the Iranian revolution of the 1970s, the US
hostages in Iran, and other hijackings and terrorist campaigns,
Esposito said. And many have been slow to realize that a few
fundamentalists don't reflect an entire religion, he said. It's as
if someone associated Christianity solely with abortion clinic
bombers who cited the Bible to justify their acts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When investigators analyze the cockpit tapes, he said, they need
to be aware of their ignorance, and cautious of making assumptions.
If the co-pilot were Christian and said, ``God forgive me,'' he
could have been admitting wrongdoing, Esposito said. Or he could
have been uttering a shorthand of the final Christian Act of
Contrition, clearing his conscience before death.
</P>
<P>
   And if EgyptAir co-pilot Gamil El Batouty were strictly
following his Muslim faith, he never would have sabotaged the
plane, Hooper said. The Koran _ which Muslims take to be the sacred
word of God _ explicitly commands against murder and suicide. God
alone has the power to say who lives and who dies, the Koran says.
</P>
<P>
   What Islam does preach is a constant closeness to God, as a way
to ward off temptations to evil, said Javid Malek, a Lexington,
Mass. consulting engineer who is active in the Islamic Center of
New England. That's why Muslims pray to Allah five times daily, he
said, and pepper even their most mundane conversations with tiny
prayers and references to God.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the words El Batouty uttered on the tape appear to be
the basic Arabic statement of faith, said Ihsan Bagby, professor of
international studies at Shaw University in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims are ``amazed that they would think this is a death
wish,'' Bagby said. In the context of surprise, amazement, or
horror, he said, ``it is totally understandable and it is a normal
reaction. It's like saying, `Oh my God.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Malek warns, Muslims can't dismiss investigators'
concerns outright. Islam might forbid suicide or killing, he said,
but individuals can go astray. The Koran warns about that
possibility, in passages about Shaitan, the devil.
</P>
<P>
   ``His job is to mislead you from the straight path,'' Malek
said. ``And perhaps sometimes he succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it may still turn out that Gamil El Batouty was
responsible for the crash, Hooper concedes. It may be that his
final prayer was a vital clue, a statement of intent. But if so, he
should be viewed as a deranged individual, not a deranged Muslim,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone else of any other faith was mentally unbalanced,''
Hooper said, ``no one would hold that against that person's
religion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
