<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3023 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-THORNBERRY-NAT     11-17 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-THORNBERRY-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        THORNBERRY, GOP SAY DEFENSE GOALS MET
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Nov.17 - Rep. Mac Thornberry, R-Amarillo, joined GOP
leaders Wednesday in celebrating this year's heavy spending on
defense programs and the formation of a new nuclear weapons agency.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress finishes up budget negotiations, GOP members of the
House Armed Forces and Intelligence committees held up the defense
$267.8 billion spending bill - which boosts defense spending by $13
billion over last year as a GOP victory. Republican lawmakers also
touted a new panel devoted to managing nuclear weapons as a win for
their party.
</P>
<P>
   For Thornberry, who authored the provisions to form the National
Nuclear Security Administration within the Department of Energy,
the creation of the new agency was one of the ``significant
accomplishments'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For twenty years, reports inside and outside the Department of
Energy have criticized the management structure over the nuclear
weapons complex,'' Thornberry said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The new agency will be completely insulated from the Department
of Energy, except that its head will report to the Secretary of
Energy, Bill Richardson. In the past, the nuclear weapons division
had taken orders from the secretary, as well as from several
assistant secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposing splitting the agency from the DOE oversight,
the president approved the defense spending bill, and signed into
law in early October.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Reps. Tom DeLay, R-Texas and Jerry Lewis, R-Calif.,
commended their own party for boosting defense this year, despite
Democrats' resistance, and bitterly refused crediting the
president.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said beefing up defense spending was one of Congress' top
three goals achieved this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget makes sure that America can meet tommorow's
challenges abroad with confidence,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said the budget's high defense spending levels corrects a
``misimpression'' that the U.S. gave the world by under-funding the
military in recent years. ``This year, we have corrected that
deficiency by raising military spending in appropriations by $13
over last year's level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thornberry said the new agency will improve nuclear weapons
oversight at Amarillo's Pantex plant and other sites because it is
semi-autonomous from the department, which Thornberry said puts
``accountability into the system.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the new system has a clearer chain of command: ``If you
give an order you know it's going to be followed, and if it's not
followed, you know who to hold responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornberry said this would clarify decision-making at nuclear
weapons facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better for the mission that [the facilities] have to
follow; there is accountability as well as some greater focus
because it's an autonomous agency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to form the panel was made amidst heightened
tension in Washington in February over security leaks from DOE
computers to China.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Thornberry's plan included Richardson, who worried
that giving the DOE less authority could create a less secure
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the new agency will name its own person to handle
intelligence and counter-intelligence. Critics say this would
duplicate the job of the security czar - FBI veteran Eugene Habiger
- who currently oversees intelligence for the whole department.
</P>
<P>
   Thornberry said of the doubling-up: ``It's not the way I would
have preferred it, but it's one of the compromises we made with the
administration when writing the final language of the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   One DOE official, who wished to remain anonymous, said the
department is panicked about the new agency. ``It basically has
split up and fractured things that we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tensions over the new agency are expected to flare next March,
when the law takes effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
