<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LODGIAN18-COX     11-17 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LODGIAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interest in buyout a boost to Lodgian
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of Lodgian (ticker symbol LOD) jumped as much
as 28 percent Wednesday after a Cayman Islands-based firm, with
offices in Fort Mitchell, Ky., expressed interest in acquiring the
hotel operator for $6.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Lodgian rose as high as $5.93 3/4 before finishing at $5.62 1/2,
up $1. More than 509,000 shares changed hands, or nearly five times
average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Casuarina Cayman Holdings disclosed in a filing
with the Securities and Exchange Commission that it now holds a 9.3
percent stake in Lodgian, which operates 133 hotels under such
brands as Holiday Inn, Crowne Plaza, Marriott and Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   Lodgian's board of directors is expected Friday to evaluate the
unsolicited bid for the company by Casuarina Cayman Holdings, which
is controlled by William Yung Sr.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Lodgian, Robert S. Cole, said the offer
``will be on the agenda for discussion, and a response will be
forthcoming following the meeting.'' He declined to comment
further.
</P>
<P>
   Yung, president of Casuarina Cayman Holdings, said Lodgian would
``fit perfectly with our hotel company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we can do a better job at operating the company
than the present management is doing, which is why we're able to
offer a premium over what the stock is trading,'' Yung said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his company would do differently, Yung said: ``I
don't know, that's why we would like to get a lot of details (from
Lodgian). We've asked for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Casuarina Cayman Holdings owns and operates 41 hotels, with four
more under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Lodgian was formed in 1998 after a merger between
Servico and Impac Hotel Group. The company owns and operates hotels
nationwide, including the Courtyard by Marriott in Buckhead and the
Holiday Inn Hotel &AMP; Suites in Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Paul D. Puryear, an analyst with Raymond James in St.
Petersburg, Fla., said Yung is a ``pretty substantial operator''
and someone knowledgeable about the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``the issue comes down to whether he is a qualified
buyer,'' Puryear said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lodgian has $1 billion worth of debt, so anyone who steps up
to be the buyer has to be able to refinance potentially part of
that debt and pass scrutiny with the lenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the $6.50 bid price may be too low, Puryear said.
He figures Lodgian could fetch $7 to $8 a share. ``An offer at this
level is inadequate. We're real pleased with what management is
doing. There's no question they've got the company on the right
track.''
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, Georgia's top two performers so far this year
reached 52-week peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Business Internet software provider Clarus (CLRS) rose to $45.62
1/2 before finishing at $45.50, up $6. Nearly 1.4 million shares
changed hands, or more than three times average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   The shares are up 312 percent since Oct. 26, when Microsoft and
Cisco Systems endorsed its products. For the year, the shares are
up 608 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications provider Powertel (PTEL), the object of
takeover speculation, climbed to $85.50 before settling at $79.62
1/2, up 62 1/2 cents. That brought its gain so far this year to 487
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues hitting highs were Home Depot (HD), which
advanced to $81.62 1/2 and closed at $79.93 3/4, up 18 3/4 cents;
and CompuCredit (CCRT), which rose to $30 and finished at $28.50,
down $1.
</P>
<P>
   Among issues hitting 52-week lows was shopping center developer
JDN Realty (JDN), which declined to $16.56 1/4, down 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff writer Robert Luke contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
