<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3032 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HOFFMAN-FILMS-ART-2TA     11-17 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOFFMAN-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALENT FOR CHARACTERS YOU LOVE AND/OR HATE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Jamie Malanowski's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
unsentimental holiday movies.  
 By JAMIE MALANOWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It must be harder than hitting a double bank shot for an actor
to play a moment in which his character is at once so repellent yet
so lovable that the audience wants both to turn away and to offer
the character a great big hug (or if not a hug, then the name of a
good therapist).
</P>
<P>
   Consider the scene in ``Happiness'' in which Allen, the
perverse, lonely, obscene phone caller, is spurned by the chilly,
controlling overachiever; she likes his dirty phone calls but not
his looks. Or the moment in ``Boogie Nights'' when Scotty J., the
amusingly awkward gay sound technician, is rejected after he plants
a kiss on the porn star Dirk Diggler at a New Year's Eve party and
ends up welcoming in the 1980s in a pit of self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   Or the scene in Joel Schumacher's ``Flawless'' (opening
Wednesday) in which a drag queen, Rusty _ brash, brave, what Bette
Midler might be like if she were not so shy and retiring and
unwilling to go over the top _ shrinks into invisibility when he
puts on a shirt and tie to attend his mother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes like these are priceless, lingering in the mind long
after the rest of the movie has left it, speaking to us about how
people resist easy categories and snap assessments. It can't be a
coincidence that all three characters have been portrayed by Philip
Seymour Hoffman, 32, the stocky blond character actor from the
suburbs of Rochester, N.Y., who at the moment seems a candidate to
become the last hot actor of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, that's sort of a trick; the clock is ticking fast, and
there's no new Skeet Ulrich with a film about to pop out of the
pipeline. But it is true that Hoffman is going to end the year in
sensational style, appearing in three buzz-generating movies.
</P>
<P>
   Along with ``Flawless,'' in which he plays opposite Robert De
Niro, he is in Paul Thomas Anderson's ``Magnolia'' and Anthony
Minghella's ``The Talented Ripley.'' And in February, he will
appear on Broadway in a revival of Sam Shepard's ``True West.''
Hoffman is not likely to cop a People magazine cover in the next
couple of weeks, but soon, an awful lot of people are going to know
who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman _ bleary-eyed and sleep-deprived on a sunny autumn
morning _ seems hesitant to embrace the possibility of becoming the
next big thing. ``I don't know, we'll see,'' he says dubiously. ``I
don't want to assume anything. I don't even want to assume that
people will like what I've done.'' OK, be that way.
</P>
<P>
   The showiest of the three roles is Rusty in ``Flawless,'' the
drag queen who lives in a Manhattan tenement upstairs from Walt, a
retired security guard played by De Niro. The two have a hostile
relationship, but after the abrasive, homophobic Walt suffers a
stroke and is prescribed singing lessons as therapy, he hires Rusty
to teach him, propinquity being the big attraction.
</P>
<P>
   There is also some business about drug money and murder and taxi
dancers and gay Republicans, but the story is really about the
relationship between two men who are very tough, very vulnerable,
very different, with quite a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman disappears in the part, which may seem obvious for a
role that requires a male actor to wear wigs and dresses and
high-heeled shoes. But apart from the look, Rusty is a fully
constructed persona, a personality built not only to serve his
deepest desires, but also to rebuff the ugly treatment he receives.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman didn't have to just create a character; he also had to
create a character who has created a character _ a far more complex
proposition. The result can be seen not only in the way Rusty walks
and stands, and in the different ways he presents himself to his
fellow drag queens and to his abusive boyfriend and to De Niro's
buddy, but also in his ferocity, loyalty, desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Along with directing, Schumacher wrote the screenplay; he says
he spent a lot of time doing research. ``Phil was the only actor I
met that I thought really understood the role,'' he says. ``Rusty
is not a drag queen or a gay man, but a transgender person, someone
who thinks he has been born into the wrong body. And while gay men
and lesbian women have been ostracized, transgenders really have no
solace. A lot of them are very lonely and tortured by it and don't
have a lot of support. Phil understood that, and understood it
immediately, and he brought a lot of humanity to the role.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman says: ``Rusty's just a person who wants to be loved, who
wants to feel safe, who wants to be free to do what he wants. Who
can't relate to that?''
</P>
<P>
   If unlocking Rusty's character went swiftly enough, the more
physical problems of playing Rusty remained; for the scenes in
which Rusty was onstage in full regalia, Hoffman had to wear a
padded bodysuit that snapped in an uncomfortable spot. ``It was
tough wearing that bodysuit, tough, tough,'' says Hoffman, who has
a habit of coming to grips with his answers by repeating key words,
as if he was using them to brick up the thought. ``It was tough to
get around in. I had a lot of anxieties about getting it right.
Joel and Bob were really very indulgent of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, says Schumacher. ``Bob is just ferocious about detail.
He went to the Rusk Institute to study stroke victims. He designed
weights for his arm so it would hang right. He designed four
different prostheses for his mouth so it would show his progress
over time. He had a therapist on the set, and if he didn't feel
that what we were doing wasn't absolutely, totally correct, we did
it over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Phil's the same way. He worked hard on every detail
about Rusty. He'd do a great take, and when we looked at the scene
on video playback, he'd say: `I don't like the way I'm holding my
pinkie when I'm smoking that cigarette. Can I have another take?'
He's calling that indulgent, but it's a passion for perfection, and
we were all there to serve it. Which, when you're working for
scale, as we all were, is the only way to work.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   About 180 degrees from Rusty is Hoffman's role in ``Magnolia.''
He plays a hospice nurse named Phil, a nice guy who has been hired
to care for Jason Robards and keep him company in his dying days.
``It's not a coincidence that he's named Phil,'' Hoffman says.
``Paul Thomas Anderson wrote the part for me. That is me.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, the part calls for no moments of intense self-loathing,
no lunging out of desperate loneliness, nothing pitiful or for that
matter hysterical, odious, ludicrous or any of the other adjectives
so frequently trotted out for Hoffman performances.
</P>
<P>
   In a sprawling movie with a big ensemble of actors who are often
thrust into excruciating emotional conflicts, Hoffman has the most
modest part of the bunch. He plays a simple man whose desire to do
good brings more knotted characters _ Robards, Tom Cruise, Julianne
Moore _ face to face.
</P>
<P>
   But playing a nice guy is not as simple as it seems. Two
showpiece moments in ``Magnolia'' are long, emotionally fraught
speeches, one given by Robards, one by Cruise. Hoffman is in both
scenes, listening to these eruptions. But he also acts, offering
subtle reactions that support the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason Robards is just such an extraordinary actor,'' Hoffman
says. ``He's really got what separates the men from the boys. Here
he is, playing a character who's old, who's sick, who's dying _ and
Jason's been sick himself _ and he has to do this, like, 17-page
speech. And I have to listen. Now, listening is hard acting. Some
of the best acting I think I've done has been sitting and
pretending to listen. It's hard. I have to create stuff to listen
to, and it's hard because I'm not very interested. But with Jason
it was just so simple, because every word, every thought, every
idea was so well done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's part in ``The Talented Ripley'' is small but pivotal.
The movie takes place in the 1950s, and Hoffman plays a rich man
from the Upper East Side in Manhattan who is gallivanting around
Europe turning everything into a party but who ends up suffering
when he becomes involved with a person who seems to be a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's honest and boisterous, but he comes across as not that
great a guy,'' Hoffman says of the character. ``And that's why I
like him, because he's right, he's right, he is right, he's on it,
but he's the only one who's on it. And because of that, he's
perceived as a jerk, and gets killed. So it's like, `Who does the
audience have sympathy with?'''
</P>
<P>
   How unusual: a Philip Seymour Hoffman character that the
audience has mixed feelings about. Where does that ability to
appeal to conflicting emotions come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just not afraid to play all sides of the character, even
the really ugly creepy things that go on inside all of our heads,''
says John C. Reilly, who has appeared with Hoffman in Anderson's
three films, ``Hard Eight,'' ``Boogie Nights'' and ``Magnolia'' and
will play on Broadway opposite his friend in ``True West,'' the two
of them alternating the roles of the introverted screenwriter and
his bellicose brother.
</P>
<P>
   Both actors got their start in theater, Hoffman in several
Off-Broadway productions including ``The Skriker'' in 1996 at the
Public Theater and ``Shopping and ...'' last year at the New York
Theater Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is now in Massachusetts filming David Mamet's ``State
and Main,'' an experience he is finding challenging on a couple of
fronts. For one, the part is his first romantic lead. A lot of
people may not think of Hoffman as leading man material,
remembering him as heavyset in ``Happiness'' and ``Boogie Nights.''
But he has lost a lot of weight and is now built like a muscled
compact wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those old-fashioned romantic leads,'' Hoffman
says. ``There's always obstacles keeping this guy from getting the
girl. There's always a dog getting in the way, or a door closing
that shouldn't close.''
</P>
<P>
   The other challenge for Hoffman is working with Mamet. ``Mamet's
a powerful guy,'' Hoffman says, ``and a great writer, a great,
great, great, great writer. He's very precise. And that's fine. I'm
not _ I usually leave things a little bit open for myself. And
sometimes I'll just fall right on my behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mamet just has a different agenda,'' he says. ``And so I have
a different challenge: how can I do what David is saying this is.
There is no other way but his. And he's a really smart guy. So if
you say, `Well, I disagree,'' he'll always have an answer for you,
always, always, always. And you don't have the time to debate with
him, you really don't.
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, then goes on. ``I find the most conducive
environments are where everything is enriched, where everything is
supported, and taken care of, with intelligence.'' It sounds as if
he has described the perfect petrie dish in which organisms like
Rusty and Allen and Scotty J. can grow.
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``Olivier says acting on film is rehearsing, and
he's right, because no matter how many times you rehearse it before
shooting, when you do it in front of the camera, you're really
doing it for the first time. And to be on a set that is designed
with that idea in mind is a good place to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-855&AMP;UP     11-17 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-855&AMP;UP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA ISSUES STATEMENT IN SUPPORT OF NORTHERN IRELAND PEACE
AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The Irish Republican Army said on
Wednesday that it ``unequivocally'' backed the Northern Ireland
peace agreement, and agreed to appoint a go-between to the
commission charged with disarming the paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   The long-sought statement made no reference to an actual
turnover of weapons, and it conditioned the naming of the middleman
on the establishment of the new power-sharing Northern Ireland
government that was called for in the April 1998 peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But in what was seen as a meaningful omission, the message did
not include the defiant claims of previous statements that the IRA
had no intention of ever disarming, and the group, an outlawed
secret paramilitary force, showed a willingness for the first time
to consider dismantling its arsenal, a taboo idea it has always
dismissed as a form of surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The statement represented the most dramatic move yet in a
choreographed series of reciprocal conciliatory comments and
pledges this week from the participants in the 11-week mission to
rescue the peace plan. The talks have been mediated by a former
U.S. senator, George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has maintained a cease-fire for more than two years to
support the role of its political wing, Sinn Fein, in peace talks,
but on Wednesday it made its belief in the accord explicit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our view,'' the organization said, referring to the April
1998 accord, ``the Good Friday agreement is a significant
development and we believe its full implementation will contribute
to the achievement of lasting peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Attributed to the traditional authenticating signatory, ``P.
O'Neill,'' at its end, the message expressed continuing confidence
in the leadership of Sinn Fein and pledged the IRA to ``the search
for freedom, justice and peace in Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was immediately welcomed by supporters of the
accord as a significant step forward, and denounced by opponents
who object to moving ahead with the start of the
Protestant-Catholic coalition government without any turnover of
weapons beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   The quickened sequence of events has turned what had become a
gradually flagging effort at bringing stability to this conflicted
British province into a sudden push for peace with onrushing
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Where there was growing despair just days ago among the
negotiating parties, frustrated by 19 months of delay and several
failed initiatives, there is now the prospect that in two weeks,
they could be taking up their positions in a new Northern Ireland
government with carefully crafted mechanisms dividing power between
the Protestant majority and the Catholic minority.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 accord had become deadlocked over the refusal of the
Ulster Unionists to permit Sinn Fein to take its leadership seats
in the Northern Ireland assembly unless the dismantling of arsenals
began first. Mitchell, the chairman of the original talks, was
called in by Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and his Irish
counterpart, Bertie Ahern, after marathon talks the two prime
ministers conducted in April and again in July failed to budge the
parties from their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The hard bargaining of the Mitchell review settled on a formula
under which the Ulster Unionist leader, David Trimble, would say he
was now willing to let Sinn Fein into a government if the IRA
stated its intention to establish formal contact with the
disarmament panel, which is headed by a retired Canadian general,
John de Chastelain.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble made that promise Tuesday morning, and Sinn Finn
followed with a supportive companion statement hours later. The
stage was set for Wednesday's message from the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's willingness to settle for less than a real turnover of
weapons was a major concession, after months of declarations that
he would never abandon his party's ``no guns, no government''
stance.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is to submit his final report and to return to the
United States on Thursday, and the success of the deal he brokered
now rides on Trimble's ability to persuade the many disaffected
Ulster Unionists to give up the party's prior disarmament demand
and support him in agreeing to work with their longtime Sinn Fein
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has apparently developed a working relationship with
Gerry Adams, the president of Sinn Fein, and he will be challenged
to convince party members that they can depend upon the word of
Adams, long a reviled figure in their circles. The 850-strong
Ulster Unionist party council is to gather in Belfast on Nov. 27 to
decide whether or not to back Trimble.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fresh momentum for approval, Trimble is risking his
position as the head of the party. He got a preview on Wednesday
night of what he faces from Jeffrey Donaldson, an Ulster Unionist
member of the British parliament who has his own designs on the
party leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson condemned the IRA statement, saying, ``There is no
timetable, no declaration that the so-called war is over, also no
guarantee that decommissioning will ever happen.'' He concluded,
``It doesn't give anything like the commitments that unionists need
to see.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Five other Ulster Unionist members of parliament put out a
statement urging party colleagues to recognize that accepting the
guerrillas' pledge and letting Sinn Fein into the government
``effectively removes the lines between democracy and terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ian Paisley, head of the hardline Ulster Democrats and
a fierce opponent of the entire peace accord, told the House of
Commons, ``There is no place in any government connected with the
United Kingdom for armed terrorists, no matter who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   If Trimble succeeds in swaying his party, the first days of
December will see the nomination of the Cabinet members to run the
Northern Ireland assembly and the passage of legislation in the
British House of Commons to transfer home rule from London to
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   The first weapons turnover would occur the end of January, with
a goal of meeting the peace accord's May deadline for full
disarmament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
