<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-OLDPLANE18-COX     11-17 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-OLDPLANE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A reunion with a cabin in the sky
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Birdie Bomar was a stewardess on the maiden voyage of
``Ship 41,'' Delta Air Lines' first DC-3 to carry passengers in
1940. The trip was from Atlanta to Fort Worth, Texas, with four
stops along the way.
</P>
<P>
   She also rode along when Delta retired the last of its fleet of
DC-3s in 1958. And she was back at Hartsfield International Airport
on Wednesday to be among the 21 people who rode along as Ship 41
carried its first passengers since a complete nose-to-tail
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just as excited as I was in 1940 _ a nervous wreck trying
to get ready to go,'' Bomar said before takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen Delta mechanics, dressed in khaki uniforms like those
worn in 1940, were excited, too, snapping photos of the results of
their seven-year, 16,000-hour labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a heck of an undertaking,'' said Bill Tinsley of
Senoia, Ga., who began working on the project even before the
once-dilapidated plane was brought back from the airfield in Puerto
Rico where it was found. ``I didn't know if it would ever get to
this.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of retired Delta employees convinced then-President Ron
Allen to pursue finding and restoring one of the company's original
DC-3s, planes that once were the workhorses of the airlines. Once
it was located, Delta swapped another DC-3 and cash for Ship 41.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the restoration was done on a volunteer basis by active
and retired Delta employees. Some got paid near the end.
</P>
<P>
   Project coordinator Robert Coakley, who has worked on the
plane's sheet metal and other parts since March 1996, simply said,
``It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gerken worked on the electrical systems and cockpit
instruments. ``We've had a lot of good times,'' Gerken said. ``It's
quite a good feeling to see it fly. I'm glad it's finally over, but
I'm also sorry it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's ceremonies, Delta CEO Leo Mullin and Bomar
arrived on the tarmac in a red 1940 Ford as the Woodward Academy
band played period tunes. Mullin escorted Bomar to the plane and
watched as she cut the giant red ribbon wrapped around the
fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin described the gleaming silver plane as ``magnificent in
every way.'' He raised a toast of nonalcoholic champagne, turned to
Ship 41 and said ``Welcome home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ship 41'' comes from the last two digits in the plane's
original registration number, 28341.
</P>
<P>
   Bomar said she was relieved to learn that the pilot would be
Billy Mercure, an old family friend. In the 1940s, when DC-3s ruled
the skies, Bomar flew on Ship 41 with Mercure's father-in-law, Dana
Jones, at the controls. Jones' wife, Paige, was a Delta stewardess.
The Joneses' grandson _ Mercure's son Adam _ is Delta's first
third-generation pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm particular about who I fly with,'' Bomar said.
</P>
<P>
   Bomar, on touch-down after a one-hour flight, had nothing but
praise for the plane and its pilot. ``The plane wasn't this nice
when it was new,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
