<HEADER>
A3046 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-SLEEPY-HALLOW-RE     11-17 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SLEEPY-HALLOW-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON`S `HOLLOW' A HAUNTINGLY EFFECTIVE VISION OF FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  3.5 stars  
(Eds: Not for use before Friday, Nov. 5) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sheer, creepy beauty of Tim Burton's ``Sleepy Hollow'' more
than compensates for a certain narrative thinness. Gothic and
primeval, dark and cold yet rich in earthy detail, this horror
movie vision lifts the genre to a new aesthetic high.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been done to Washington Irving's venerable ``Legend of
Sleepy Hollow'' this time around. All that's left from the original
story is its 1790s setting in upstate New York, the headless ghost
of a Hessian mercenary and a romantic triangle between prissy
newcomer Ichabod Crane, the lovely young Katrina Van Tassel and
local roughneck Brom Bones.
</P>
<P>
   But that's about it. The film's script, credited to Andrew Kevin
Walker (``Seven'') and polished without credit by ``Shakespeare in
Love's'' Tom Stoppard, traffics in murder mystery and witchcraft,
and the body count _ make that the decapitated body count _ is, as
you'd expect from a Burton horror film, off the charts. There's a
revenge theme, a burning windmill, a scrappy orphan, flashbacks to
Ichabod's magical/horrible childhood (complete with iron maiden), a
Tree of the Dead ... the changes, like the names of demons, are
legion, and prevent predictability of a certain kind. But the film
does play out in a differently rote manner, as a puzzle of
attrition common to many modern-day supernatural thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   Helping move things along agreeably, though, is Johnny Depp's
funny yet fundamentally dramatic portrayal of Ichabod. The
character in this version is a police detective from New York City
who arrives at the Hudson Valley township with a case full of
painful-looking, early-American forensics equipment and a
progressive's superior attitude. The former prove useless and the
latter is tattered by encounters with the Headless Horseman that
usually leave Ichabod in an unconscious swoon and his unlucky
companions dismembered.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't the vengeful wraith slash the life out of the fey
city boy when he has numerous chances to do so? The devil knows
that most of the residents of Sleepy Hollow wouldn't mind getting
rid of the cowardly but nosey sleuth, who's unearthing an
embarrassing conspiracy among the town fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Another question: What does the luscious little Katrina
(Christina Ricci in blond curls and pushup corsets), with her
unconvincing innocence and sweet little book of spells, really have
in mind for Crane? Or, for that matter, what is her mysterious
stepmother (Miranda Richardson) actually up to?
</P>
<P>
   A fine supporting cast of mostly older, mostly British gargoyles
(Michael Gambon, Jeffrey Jones, Ian McDiarmid, Michael Gough,
Christopher Lee, an unbilled Martin Landau) provide extra
wigged-and-powdered glower. Christopher Walken is frighteningly
effective as the headed version of the murderous Hessian, while Ray
Park (``The Phantom Menace's'' Darth Maul) lends his strong and
graceful acrobatic skill to the sword-swinging ghost.
</P>
<P>
   But the real act here was performed by production designer Rick
Heinrichs, costume designer Colleen Atwood and director of
photography Emmanuel Lubezki (with a little reshoot help from the
great Conrad Hall of ``American Beauty'' renown). They and the army
of artisans who gave their concepts shape have created a complete
universe, dank with fetid and fecund imagination.
</P>
<P>
   From an old crone's rank and cluttered keep to a grime-dusted
country morgue, from a haunted covered bridge to a stately home so
hopelessly benighted that even a lively harvest celebration there
can turn wakelike and dreary in an instant, ``Sleepy Hollow''
presents an ever-unfolding nightscape of dread. In many ways, it's
the eccentric Burton's most straightforward, least-idiosyncratic
genre exercise to date. But it may also be his most thoroughly
realized expression of bone-chilling artistry.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The film: &LR;  ``Sleepy Hollow'' (R; violence, sex). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Johnny Depp, Christina Ricci, Miranda Richardson,
Michael Gambon, Casper Van Dien, Jeffrey Jones, Christopher
Walken. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR; !off! Directed by Tim Burton. Written by Andrew
Kevin Walker and Kevin Yagher, based on Washington Irving's story
``The Legend of Sleepy Hollow.'' Produced by Scott Rudin and Adam
Schroeder. Released by Paramount Pictures. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 40 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  Citywide &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3.5 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3048 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-BISHOPS-TEACHERS-ART-     11-17 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-TEACHERS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS WANT TO PASS MUSTER ON THEOLOGIANS AT CATHOLIC
UNIVERSITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NTY13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's Catholic bishops voted overwhelmingly
Wednesday to require theology professors at Catholic colleges and
universities to obtain certification from their bishops declaring
that what they teach is ``authentic Catholic doctrine.''
</P>
<P>
   The requirement that theologians obtain a ``mandatum,'' or
mandate, emerged at the meeting of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops as the most controversial element in a broad
statement about what the relations should be between the church and
America's more than 230 Catholic institutions of higher education.
The document, which has been under discussion for nearly a decade
and has undergone two major revisions, states that Catholic
colleges and universities are fully autonomous and enjoy academic
freedom, but that their presidents should be Catholics, and,
ideally, so should a majority of the trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Although supporters of the document said they believed it would
not be unnecessarily intrusive, it appears likely to generate
tension at many Catholic universities, which enroll about 670,000
students. Indeed, Archbishop Rembert G. Weakland of Milwaukee
warned that the document, if implemented, would be ``a pastoral
disaster for the church.''
</P>
<P>
   The document now goes to Rome for approval, which is expected,
given that it was revised to incorporate a more legalistic approach
to the relationship between bishops and universities, which the
Vatican had asked for in 1996, when it sent back an earlier
version.
</P>
<P>
   In its broadest sense, the document, titled ``Ex Corde
Ecclesiae'' (a Latin phrase meaning, ``From the Heart of the
Church'') represents the bishops' response to the secularizing
forces at American Catholic universities, which some conservative
critics say have moved away from their original mission.
</P>
<P>
   There have been tensions between some American bishops and some
Catholic universities in recent years. The disputes have often
arisen over the universities' decisions to host public figures
whose views diverge from essential Catholic teaching, especially on
the issue of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In the discussion that preceded the 233-31 vote approving the
document, some bishops pointed to the long-ago secularization of
Harvard, Yale and Princeton universities, all founded by
Protestants, as examples of the trend that they want to avoid
within their own universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps us focus more clearly on not losing our
Catholic identity,'' Bishop John J. Leibrecht, the Springfield,
Mo., prelate who headed the committee that drafted the document,
said in a press conference after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   One significant unanswered question is what criteria bishops
should use in granting (or revoking) theology professors' mandates.
And what does a bishop do if a theology professor declines to seek
a mandate, given that the document affirms that bishops have no
role in a university's internal affairs, which include hiring and
firing?
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear when Ex Corde Ecclesiae will take effect. Vatican
approval could take several months. The document's provisions would
then take effect one year later.
</P>
<P>
   But it could take even longer for the provision for the mandate
to take effect, since the bishops still have to decide on the
procedures that will govern that issue.
</P>
<P>
   The document has already generated controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is redefining the relationship of Catholic
universities and colleges to the church to say that theologians
must request a mandate from the bishop which, once given, can be
withdrawn,'' said the Rev. Thomas Rausch, chair of the theological
studies department at Loyola Marymount University, in Los Angeles.
``Many Catholic educators are worried that this will compromise the
academic integrity of the institutions and the freedom of inquiry
of those teaching theology.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Mahony, archbishop of Los Angeles, who spoke in
favor of the document in the debate Wednesday morning, sought to
put Catholic universities at ease. ``I would say to the presidents
of our Catholic colleges and universities, you have nothing to fear
from us,'' he said. ``On the contrary, this is a new moment of
collaboration'' between the church and its institutions of higher
learning, he added.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The document was also supported by Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua,
archbishop of Philadelphia; Cardinal Bernard Law, archbishop of
Boston, and Cardinal John O'Connor, archbishop of New York, who has
not attended the meeting, but sent a letter, which was read aloud.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Weakland of Milwaukee, long considered a moderate figure in
the church hierarchy, warned that the document, if passed, would
create distrust between theologians and bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Although he credited the bishops with having established a
``good spirit'' of dialogue with Catholic college and university
presidents, he said that a similar spirit had not been achieved
with theology professors. ``Probably the tension between hierarchy
and theologians now is the highest I have seen it,'' he said.
Catholic theologians, he said, are ``not just afraid of being at
the whims of individual bishops, but also the object of vigilante
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after the bishops' vote, Margaret A. Farley, a
Yale Divinity School theologian who is president of the
1,500-member Catholic Theological Society of America, said that
while some theologians would see the requirement for a mandate as
affirming theology's importance, most would worry that it would
lead to a breakdown in trust between bishops and theologians. ``As
such,'' she said, ``it may discourage young scholars from pursuing
theological degrees or from seeking teaching positions in Catholic
colleges and universities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Catholics United for the Faith, a conservative group based
in Steubenville, Ohio, voiced support for the document Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To ensure that the teachings of the church are faithfully and
fruitfully taught, we need the oversight of our God-given
shepherds. Therefore, it is necessary that the role of Catholic
universities be subject to the authorities of the church,'' the
group said in a statement after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   And in the press conference after the vote, Leibrecht took pains
to emphasize that the bishops did not want to take the role of
disciplinarians of Catholic theologians. ``The bishop is not
involved in the internal affairs of the institution,'' he said.
``If a particular theologian does not have a mandatum, it's up to
the university to decide what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, the Rev. Joseph A. O'Hare, president
of Fordham University in New York, said much of the document's
effect depends on how it will be implemented by the bishops within
their individual dioceses. But he said the obligation to seek a
mandate lies with theologians, not with their universities. ``It's
really not a legal obligation of the institution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Curran, a priest who now teaches at Southern Methodist
University in Dallas, predicted that for many Catholic colleges and
universities, the new measure will have relatively little practical
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never going to go into effect unless and until the
universities put this in their bylaws,'' said Curran who was
dismissed from his job as a professor of moral theology at Catholic
University in 1986 after the Vatican criticized him as being
unsuitable. ``And the vast majority will not do this because their
trustees are mostly lay people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
