<HEADLINE>
WHEN RAIN DOES NOT FALL IN SPAIN, THE FARMERS MARCH TO PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID _ Spanish farmers often stage noisy demonstrations to
demand state subsidies, but 4,000 growers who marched in Madrid
last week behind a nervous brown camel and six men dressed as
bedouins sought something more basic: water.
</P>
<P>
   They came close enough to the prime minister's palace that
scores of riot police officers were summoned. No scuffles were
reported but the protesters derided what they termed the
government's inattention to yet another severe drought.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining of ruined crops and the burden of seeking bank loans
to cover their losses, the farmers, from Andalusia, vowed to
continue their protests if the government does not build dams and
pipelines to ensure a steady flow of water. The problem involves
southern Europe from Portugal to Greece, and arid climates and
unstable water supplies are getting more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be a plan in the European Union to transfer
water from the wet northern countries to the dry south,'' said
Antonio Torres, leader of the Guadalquivir Platform, an unlikely
coalition of conservative farmers and leftist unions that convened
the protest (which, incidentally, took place in pelting rain).
</P>
<P>
   But Torres would be satisfied if water were at least transferred
within Spain, where the rainy mountainous north provides little of
its water to the parched south.
</P>
<P>
   A devastating drought from 1992 to 1995 caused water shortages
for 12 million Spaniards, a third of the population, and farmers
suffered big losses. But the heavy rains in 1996 seemingly washed
away the subject until this year, which the National Institute of
Meteorology has listed as one of the driest this century.
</P>
<P>
   The government says it is trying to solve the problem and is
building 33 dams to add to the existing 1,100.
</P>
<P>
   In a peace-making gesture at last week's protest, an aide to
Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar emerged from the palace compound to
receive a printed statement from the 26 leaders of the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the end of 1995,'' the statement said, ``we have asked
for a solution to the problem of water shortages and in these four
years absolutely nothing has been invested'' by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The protest leaders said $3 billion would be needed to solve the
problem in the next few years, triple the government's proposed
budget for next year for water management.
</P>
<P>
   ``To compete in the market, we need stable production,'' said
Miguel Lopez, secretary general of the Farmers and Ranchers
Organization in Andalusia. ``We lose crops and jobs in every
drought.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said his family, which has an 86-acre cotton and sugar-beet
farm, has had to borrow $63,000, more than ever before, because of
drought.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers are particularly angry at what they see as the
government's foot-dragging, like the years of debate on the
national water plan, which has been postponed in part because many
southern growers have modernized their irrigation. Farmers pay
about $100 an acre annually for irrigation water and would be
willing, Lopez said, to help pay for dams and pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   The last big water protest in Spain was in 1995, near the end of
the previous drought, when 25,000 farmers converged on the
government water board in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   The protest in Madrid last week was smaller, but it was among
the few to bring the water issue to the capital. Torres said the
Guadalquivir Platform, named for the river through Seville, would
invite farmers in other drought areas to join if more protests are
held. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
