<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AIRCRASH-PILOT-875&AMP;AD     11-17 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-PILOT-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTAIR PILOT BECOMES CENTER OF CRASH INVESTIGATION, BUT HE HAS
DEFENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With AIRCRASH-RDP, moving in `w' news file) 
(th) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ His young child's illness has prompted
speculation that he may have been distraught. To some, his sending
of money and gifts home ahead of him seemed loaded with meaning. He
was also facing retirement, although it is unclear whether he was
looking forward to it or dreading it.
</P>
<P>
   Thus has begun the effort to understand Gameel el-Batouty, the
Egyptian pilot who, after decades of solid work and numerous
personal successes, is now the man investigators suspect
intentionally brought down EgyptAir 990, killing himself and all
216 others on board.
</P>
<P>
   His defenders, for their part, offer their own facts and
interpretations: He was a religious man who recently had gone to
Mecca, they say, and suicide would be unthinkable. He had bought a
villa here and did not have money problems. He had celebrated his
son's graduation from the police academy over the summer, and, at
the party, had danced for the first time in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Once investigators disclosed that they believed Batouty was the
pilot who initiated the fatal actions in the cockpit of the Boeing
767, it was inevitable that every aspect of the pilot's life would
be mined for significance _ to bolster or disprove the theory.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, in a measure of the intensity of the scrutiny,
his family, besieged by reporters, had guards posted outside the
house in a bid to fend off the debate over Batouty's role in the
doomed airliner.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to examine Batouty's life will probably not soon end.
Barring an abrupt reversal by investigators, more questions will
come soon _ by the authorities, by reporters, by people in his own
country.
</P>
<P>
   All will be trying to grapple with what seems inexplicable:
what, if anything, might have driven a 59-year-old man, a veteran
commercial pilot, to seize the controls of a 767 laden with
passengers and point its nose toward the sea?
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo on Wednesday, many people were insisting that something
like this could not have happened, including two of Batouty's sons,
who spoke to a few reporters permitted inside the family's
apartment in the Cairo suburb of Heliopolis, one of three family
homes in the Egyptian capital. A third son's remarks were heavily
quoted Wednesday in the Arabic-language press.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have anything to push him to this,'' one son, Karim,
20, told The Associated Press, portraying his father as a devoted
father and a financially secure man who would never have committed
suicide, much less taken the lives of others.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir officials have said that Batouty, a reserve pilot on
the flight, was sitting in the cockpit during takeoff, in one of
two observer's seats behind the pilot and the co-pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour into the flight, American investigators have
said, Batouty apparently replaced the co-pilot and then took
control of the plane when the pilot left the cockpit. He then
apparently set in motion the chain of events that doomed the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators have identified Batouty as the crew member who
uttered a short Arabic expression moments before the plane's
autopilot was disconnected, and they suspect that Batouty was the
one who took that step.
</P>
<P>
   But no American official has yet offered a theory as to what
might have driven Batouty to take such a step, and the few facts
that have emerged since he became the focus of the investigation
remain ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives said Batouty had persuaded a colleague to
carry gifts and cash home to Cairo ahead of him, instead of
carrying them himself on Flight 990. But they denied reports that
he had sent home his life savings, and said that in all cases the
amounts involved were relatively insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   They also insisted that Batouty did not have any life insurance,
and they rejected any suggestion that Batouty's gift-giving was a
sign that he was not planning to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pocket money,'' Mohammed el-Batouty, 22, the police
academy graduate, said of what he described as a $300 gift from his
father. ``He always sent me money with his colleagues because I was
home only one day a week, and he didn't like to leave my pocket
money with anyone.'' Another gift, a wool sweater, was sent ahead
with a colleague so that Batouty could save space in his own
luggage, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Batouty has also said that his father had telephoned
asking that someone meet him at Cairo Airport upon his return. The
reason, Mohammed Batouty said, was that his father was carrying as
baggage a set of car tires purchased for his son in the United
States, and would need a car to get them home.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and associates said they saw no signs of stress or
unease in Batouty's demeanor in the days and weeks before the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledged that Batouty, who held the rank of co-pilot,
was frustrated not to have been promoted to the full rank and
higher salary of captain. But they characterized him as a man who
was comfortably preparing for a more homebound life as he
approached March and his 60th birthday, the age at which EgyptAir
pilots must retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would a man like Batouty commit suicide?'' asked Walid
Murad, an EgyptAir pilot who, along with Batouty, traveled to the
Muslim holy city of Mecca last winter on a religious pilgrimage
known as the hajj.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another member of that group, Murad said, was Ahmed el-Habashy,
the veteran pilot who was the captain of EgyptAir 990 and with whom
investigators have theorized Batouty struggled for control of the
plane during its plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining EgyptAir in 1987, Batouty had spent most of his
career training Air Force and civil pilots; later, as a commercial
aviator, with the rank of co-pilot, he flew thousands of hours
carrying passengers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The records of the Egyptian pilots are honorable,'' Murad
said. ``Committing suicide is not a trait that Egyptians and
Muslims are known for.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Batouty held a party in honor of Mohammed's graduation
from a police academy. More recently, family members said, he had
thrown himself into supervising the work on a villa outside Cairo
to which the family planned to move after his retirement, according
to reports carried in the Egyptian press.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty had five children, including the youngest, a 10-year-old
daughter, Aya, who suffers from lupus, an immune disorder. On some
of his trips to the United States, associates say, he brought his
daughter with him for medical treatment at the University of
Southern California at Los Angeles Medical Center, a possible
indication of the seriousness of her condition.
</P>
<P>
   At the family apartment, reporters said, a framed photograph of
the stocky, dark-haired Batouty hung on one wall of the small
living room, opposite a photograph of the young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Though Batouty was plainly concerned about his daughter's
health, his wife, Umaima, was quoted Wednesday in the Egyptian
newspaper Al Gomurhia as saying that her husband had telephoned
from the United States during his final trip to say he had learned
that his daughter's illness could be remedied.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of his colleagues, Batouty had apparently not made
plans for a new career after his mandatory retirement.
</P>
<P>
   His associates insisted that he had received several job offers,
but was simply looking forward to time off.
</P>
<P>
   The friends and associates of Batouty also said they believed
that American investigators had given too much significance to the
cryptic utterance that the pilot apparently uttered in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase, ``Tawakilt ala Allah,'' can mean ``I put my faith in
God,'' or ``I entrust myself to God,'' and is used commonly by many
Muslims even as they undertake routine tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of other religions say, `Jesus Christ' or `Oh My God,'
and that does not mean they are preparing to kill people,'' said
another EgyptAir pilot, Ali Murad, who is not related to Walid
Murad. ``Why wouldn't it be the same with us?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3057 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-JOURNALISM-ART-2     11-17 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-JOURNALISM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AL GORE, JOURNALISM PROCEEDED POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT26 _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ It was not uncommon in the 1970s for the
children of celebrities to walk among the grizzled,
bourbon-swilling veterans in the newsroom of The Nashville
Tennessean, this city's once-muckraking morning newspaper. Bobby
Kennedy's son, David, and Arthur Schlesinger's son, Andrew, passed
through briefly, as did Judge John Sirica's son, Jack, and Henry
Aaron's daughter, Gaile.
</P>
<P>
   So it raised few eyebrows in September 1971 when the latest
$95-a-week greenhorn, a shaggy-haired 23-year-old named Albert A.
Gore Jr., was assigned one of the heavy metal desks in the front of
the office, where city editors kept an eye on their most
inexperienced charges. Here comes another one, the old guys
muttered. This time it was the son and namesake of Tennessee's
recently deposed U.S. senator, presumably looking to pad his resume
before following his father into politics.
</P>
<P>
   But to their surprise, Gore stayed for nearly five years and
became a skilled investigative reporter before eventually resigning
to run for Congress in 1976. If anything, Gore convinced his
colleagues that he was committed to journalism as his life's work,
and many were caught off guard when he left.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sutherland, a reporter at the time and now The
Tennessean's editor, recalled the day that several reporters
huddled mischievously to plot Gore's political ascent, culminating
with a presidential campaign in 2008. ``When Al found out, he
chastised us very seriously, no tongue in cheek,'' Sutherland said.
``He said, `If it gets out that I'm doing this as a stepping stone
it will undermine my credibility. I'm here as a reporter.' He
wasn't kidding around.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he runs for president some eight years earlier than his
colleagues had projected, Vice President Al Gore is anxious to
remind voters that he had a life before politics. In competing
against his only Democratic rival, Bill Bradley (basketball star),
and Republicans like John McCain (prisoner of war) and George W.
Bush (oil patch entrepreneur), Gore is turning to his now distant
career in journalism to provide a sheen of authenticity to an
otherwise uninterrupted political biography.
</P>
<P>
   He now regularly mentions his newspapering endeavors in campaign
speeches. ``I was a journalist for seven years,'' Gore said at a
recent forum in New Hampshire, referring collectively to his time
at The Tennessean as well as his days as an Army reporter and as a
copy boy at The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my editors not to assign me to any political stories,
but after a couple of years I was promoted to cover City Hall,''
Gore continued, ``and I saw how people became heroes in the
community by rolling up their sleeves and trying to make things
better, and I was drawn toward that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of Gore's nearly 400 bylined articles for The
Tennessean described an annual Hillbilly Day festival, which ``had
it all,'' he said in his lead sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Gore's articles were straightforward accounts of local
crimes or Metro Council debates on matters like rezonings and water
rates. He was known more for his industriousness and his difficulty
in meeting deadlines than for the grace of his writing.
</P>
<P>
   But the serious young reporter showed a compassionate eye with
early articles about a pregnant, 13-year-old runaway and a
Christmas Day spent in juvenile detention. And many of Gore's
pieces also displayed a dry, impish wit. When writing about a rabid
fox attack at a nudist colony, he said that doctors ``declined to
say where the victims had been bitten.''
</P>
<P>
   His account of a Burger King hamburger-eating contest reported
that hopes of a record-breaking performance were dashed ``when one
of the contestants regurgitated his first three Whoppers on the
table and dampened the morale of his competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore may have been drawn to politics by the community spirit he
now remembers seeing at City Hall. But he also have seen the petty
corruption that many government reporters eventually encounter, and
his inability to stifle it with his pen seems to have played just
as significant a role in his change of careers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Gore wrote a series of articles about council members
suspected of soliciting bribes in exchange for their support on
zoning measures. To produce his most sensational article, Gore and
The Tennessean's publisher, John L. Seigenthaler, cooperated with
the district attorney in devising an undercover operation that
seemed to catch Councilman Morris B. Haddox in the act of taking a
$300 payoff. Gore and three Tennessean photographers were watching
from a nearby office as Haddox, a pharmacist, took the money on a
downtown street from a local developer who was wearing a concealed
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed an ironclad case. But at the trial, Haddox's lawyer
argued that the freshman councilman had been entrapped by the
newspaper. A first jury deadlocked, and a second trial ended in an
acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, Gore used the word ``surprised'' to
describe his reaction to the verdicts. But former colleagues said
he was devastated.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Warnecke Jr., who was among Gore's closest friends on
The Tennessean's staff, said Gore had been heavily invested in the
Haddox story and was so nervous about the investigation that he hid
documents at Warnecke's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took it as a failure,'' Warnecke said of the verdicts. ``He
was so down and depressed. He had everything on this guy, and yet
this guy got off. I think it destroyed his feelings about justice,
and that was one of the things he liked about being a
newspaperman.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Gore had enrolled in law school at Vanderbilt; he
said in the interview that he wanted to try to understand the legal
system that had freed Morris Haddox. Gore said his goal was to
become a legal reporter.
</P>
<P>
   He also began writing editorials for The Tennessean, moving
eagerly, according to Warnecke, into the anonymity provided by
unsigned opinion columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just wanted to get his name off the front page,''
Warnecke said. ``He didn't want to do another investigation that
would blow up in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore put it this way: ``I thought that I did my best as a
journalist, but I thought that my best as a journalist had not
achieved some of the results that I thought were best. I felt that
whatever gifts I have might better be pursued in another
profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Gore could graduate from law school, Rep. Joe L. Evins
surprised voters in Tennessee's Fourth Congressional District by
announcing that he would retire after 30 years in office. Gore,
then 28, immediately announced his candidacy. It was not a move he
had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, only a month earlier he had tried
unsuccessfully to borrow enough money to buy his hometown weekly,
The Carthage Courier. Among his options, Gore said, was using the
newspaper ``to maybe build a base for a potential involvement in
politics 10 years down the road or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's journalistic career began as a Harvard undergraduate in
1967, when he spent two summer months as an ``office boy'' for The
New York Times. He received ``outstanding'' reviews for his work,
which included late-night forays to newsrooms around Manhattan to
swap the first editions of The Times for those of its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Gore found himself in Vietnam, having
enlisted in the Army despite his antiwar views, at least partly to
take an issue away from his father's political opponents. Gore said
he was assigned to become an Army reporter, attached to the
headquarters company of the 20th Engineers Brigade because
induction officials noticed that he had worked at The Times and
because he scored well on the entrance tests. He said he received
no special preference as a senator's son for the non-combat post.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Gore's five-month tour in Vietnam was spent writing
fill-in-the-blank news releases about soldiers' promotions and
decorations. But he also made occasional trips into the field to
write stories for Army publications about engineering feats like
the construction of new airstrips. He sent one article, a
reconstruction of a firefight near the Cambodian border, to his
wife, Tipper, a part-time photographer at The Tennessean. She, in
turn, passed it along to Seigenthaler, who printed the article and
then offered Gore a job as soon as he returned home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had absolutely no earthly idea what else I was going to
do,'' he said, ``and so I accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was disillusioned with politics because of Vietnam
and his father's 1970 defeat, and was wary of the potential
conflicts for someone with his name, so he avoided covering
politics for several years. When he did begin reporting on local
government, embracing the aggressive new style of post-Watergate
journalism, his subjects often chafed at seeing the byline of their
former senator's son on critical articles. Several Metro Council
members berated him after he questioned the size of their
delegation and their use of expense money on a trip to a conference
in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was offensive to have this little snot running around with
his poison pen,'' said Joe L. Crockett, a former councilman who
recalled that Gore's penchant for sandals and jeans clashed with
the council's starchy dress code. ``And it was not just that it was
Al Gore, but that it was Senator Gore's son. A lot of these people
had busted their butts for his old man.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Gore's political career has created some awkward
moments for his former colleagues at The Tennessean. The paper has
consistently supported him on its editorial pages, and it employed
his youngest daughter, Sarah, as an intern two summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland, the editor, wrote an apologetic column last August
after it was disclosed that he had granted an interview to the Gore
campaign for use in a fund-raising videotape. And after Gore
disclosed in his 1988 presidential campaign that he had smoked
marijuana, Seigenthaler assigned two reporters to ask dozens of
Tennessean staff members if they had ever witnessed such activity.
``I wasn't happy,'' said one of the reporters, Larry Daughtrey, who
received brusque ``no comments'' from several colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Gore's national campaign headquarters sits only a
few miles from The Tennessean, and between the two buildings is
Morris Haddox's pharmacy. After being voted out of office after
Gore's investigation, Haddox is now back on the Metro Council, and
he has placed three blue ``Gore 2000'' placards in his storefront
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``His qualifications outweigh anything that happened between
us,'' Haddox said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's views of his former quarry seem to have changed. ``He is
an innocent man, because he was not proven guilty,'' Gore said,
adding that he believes in redemption. ``I'm really moved by the
spirit that he brings to the relationship,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
