<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 18
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-JAPAN-DISCRIM-NYT (moved on Sunday, Nov. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Nov. 14,
about discrimination against foreigners in Japan misstated the size
of the award to a Brazilian woman who sued a jewelry store that
refused to serve her. It was $14,000, not $47,000.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incompletely to the university where
an American, Cynthia Worthington, says treatment of Japanese and
foreign faculty members is unequal. It is Kumamoto Prefectural
University, not Kumamoto University.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AIRCRASH-SUICIDE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Nov. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Nov. 16,
about intentional air crashes in history misstated the name of the
line involved and the number of deaths in a 1994 crash of a
commuter plane. The line was Royal Air Maroc, not Air Morocco, and
the deaths numbered 44, not 51. The article also misidentified the
crew member responsible for a 1982 crash in Tokyo Bay. He was the
pilot, not the co-pilot.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-LEONID-METEORS-NYT (moved on Monday, Nov. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Nov. 15,
about the Leonid meteor shower misstated the name of an engineer at
the Aerospace Corporation, which advises the Defense Department and
companies on ways to protect spacecraft from meteors. He is Glenn
E. Peterson, not Glenn D. Anderson.
</P>
</TEXT>
