<HEADER>
A3060 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-ART-2TAK     11-17 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPT CRITICIZES U.S. OFFICIALS FOR SUSPECTING CREW MEMBER IN AIR
CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AIRCRASH-PILOTS, moved in `i' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS and PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Egyptian government Wednesday escalated its
condemnation of U.S. officials investigating the EgyptAir crash,
saying that, by focusing suspicion on a backup pilot, they were
rushing to judgment about the cause. Egypt's principal spokesman
said that a statement attributed to a relief pilot in the cockpit
was being misinterpreted and did not show that he was about to
commit suicide by sending the plane into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism came as a federal official said that aviation
investigators were unsure of the significance of the utterance, in
Arabic, by the relief pilot as captured on the cockpit voice
recorder in the seconds before the Boeing 767 crashed into the sea,
killing all 217 on board.
</P>
<P>
   The chief spokesman for the Egyptian government, Nabil Osman,
said in a telephone interview in Cairo that the words that
investigators believe had been uttered by the relief pilot, Gameel
el-Batouty, was a Muslim prayer ``said in a time of crisis when a
person is facing a difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this prayer would never be said in terms of suicide,''
Osman said. ``It's definitely not to be said by someone who is
going to commit suicide, because suicide is against Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. investigators said Wednesday that despite confusion
about the Arabic phrase, they are still persuaded by information
from the voice and data recorders recovered from the ocean floor
that Batouty may have tried to crash the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said that they believed the cockpit's voice
recorders provided evidence that it was Batouty uttering an Arabic
expression that has been translated as ``I put my trust in God.''
</P>
<P>
   At Egypt's request, the U.S. government has delayed a decision
to label the inquiry a criminal investigation and to turn it over
to the FBI. James Hall, the chairman of the National Transportation
Safety Board, said that more study of the cockpit voice recorder
and data recorder was needed. The crash, U.S. officials said, was a
devastating blow to Egyptian pride. In addition, accusations that
an unstable Egyptian crew member caused it could have a serious
impact on tourism in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The swift agreement by the United States to delay a criminal
investigation reflects the exceptionally close relationship between
Washington and Cairo on a variety of issues, including the Middle
East peace process and counterrorism.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other senior Clinton
administration officials have telephoned their Egyptian
counterparts this week to assure them of close consultation between
Washington and Cairo as the investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB said that a group of experts, including representatives
from Boeing, which built the plane, Pratt &AMP; Whitney, which
manufactured the engines, the Federal Aviation Administration, the
FBI and the Egyptian government would begin work Thursday on a
transcript from the cockpit voice recorder.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Mamdouh Heshman, the head of the civil aviation section of
the Egyptian ministry of transport, and Capt. Mohsne el-Missiri,
the investigator in charge for Egyptair, are among the Egyptians
already in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Transcripts tell whether sounds and speech were picked up by the
microphone of the captain or the first officer, or one in the
middle, called the cockpit area mike. They also try to define
sounds, including alarms going off and levers or switches being
moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group expects to work through the weekend and will attempt
to complete this transcript next week,'' the board said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators said Wednesday that a new interpretation
of the Arabic utterance could have some bearing on their initial
theory as to what happened to bring down Egyptair Flight 990.
</P>
<P>
   But some of those investigators emphasized that the
interpretation of the utterance was not the only factor that had
led them to theorize that Batouty, a 59-year-old veteran of
EgyptAir who was serving as a relief pilot for the flight, might
have tried to crash the plane.
</P>
<P>
   According to that hypothesis, after the co-pilot left the
cockpit, the pilot, Capt. Ahmed el-Habashy, left, leaving Batouty
alone in control of the aircraft. Batouty then uttered the phrase,
``Tawakilt ala Allah,'' and someone turned off the autopilot.
Habashy then returned to the cockpit and remarked that something
was wrong and needed to be fixed. Seconds later, the plane began a
deep descent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investigators said that their initial theory _ that one
pilot was trying to drive the plane into the sea and the other was
trying to save the jet by pulling the nose up _ was influenced by
the absence so far of any evidence of mechanical failure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, safety investigators said that Wednesday they had
confirmed from the flight data recorder that an elevator on the
tail _ a kind of flap, controlled from the co-pilot's seat _ was in
the ``nose-down'' angle while the other elevator controlled from
the pilot's seat was in a ``nose-up'' position. The two elevators
are normally aligned.
</P>
<P>
   Senior law-enforcement officials said Wednesday night that while
their theory that Batouty intentionally caused the crash was
plausible and consistent with the evidence, they have not found any
reason why he would have committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Cairo's indignation and anger over the theory that one of its
pilots could have been responsible for the crash comes against a
background in which Egyptians and others in the Muslim world
believe that Westerners can be insufficiently sensitive to the
subtleties of Islam and too eager to attribute deadly events to
Islamic extremism.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CATHOLIC-BISHOPS-HNS &LR;      11-17 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-BISHOPS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS CALL FOR STRICTER CHURCH CONTROL OVER CATHOLIC COLLEGES 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: See optional trims) 
 
By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a ground-breaking decision, Roman Catholic
bishops voted Wednesday for stricter church control over America's
235 Catholic colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   The prelates, representing dioceses across the 61 million-member
American church, voted 223-31 for the new strictures, which now go
to the Vatican for approval. A two-thirds majority was needed for
passage.
</P>
<P>
   The move means local bishops must approve theologians _ granting
them a ``mandatum'' to teach _ for the first time since 1789 when
Georgetown University in Washington, the nation's first Catholic
college, was founded. The guidelines also require that ``to the
extent possible'' the majority of university boards of trustees
should be committed Catholics, college presidents should be
Catholic and non-Catholic professors must be ``respectful of the
Catholic faith tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines, granting the ``mandatum'' _ essentially a
commission to teach in the name of the church _ is the
responsibility of the local bishop. In theory, if a conservative
bishop wanted to get rid of a theologian at a Catholic college, he
now could.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility and other vagaries concern Catholic university
presidents and some Catholic theologians who lobbied to delay
passage of the new guidelines. They fear the strictures will
curtail academic freedom, undercut reputations of prestigious
schools and prevent them from receiving government funding. Others
fear the new guidelines open the door to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The board of the 1,500-member Catholic Theological Society of
America issued a statement expressing its disappointment that the
bishops did not respond to appeals for further dialogue, saying
efforts ``to juridically control the work of theologians'' are
``potentially damaging to the best work of theology.''
</P>
<P>
   Several bishops raised similar objections Wednesday with
Archbishop Rembert G. Weakland of Milwaukee, calling the guidelines
a ``pastoral disaster'' that could put theologians at the mercy of
``vigilante groups.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to be Big Brother and give all the solutions to
everything? I don't think we want to,'' Bishop John G. Vlazny of
Winona, Minn., said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reaction was mixed among Catholic theologians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth in advertising demands that those who teach Catholic
theology at a Catholic university should be scrupulously faithful
to Church teaching,'' said the Rev. Michael Miller, president of
Houston's University of St. Thomas. ``I'm for it. I would probably
have preferred a little more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholic theological society president Margaret Farley of Yale
Divinity School in New Haven, Conn., said her organization is
disturbed that the criteria for granting the ``mandatums'' are too
vague. ``We have no assurance that it (the criteria) would be
applied consistently from diocese-to-diocese,'' Farley said noting
theologians object to being put a legalistic relationship with
bishops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Catholic colleges and universities affected by the
legislation enroll about 670,000 students. Conservative church
people worry some Catholic schools are too secularized. In the
United States, Catholic schools have wrangled with the church over
issues, including abortion, gay rights and theology.
</P>
<P>
   Such tensions erupted into a faculty member's dismissal in 1986.
That year, the Rev. Charles Curran, who now teaches at Southern
Methodist University in Dallas, was told he could no longer teach
at Washington's Catholic University because of his views on
homosexuality, contraception and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   The great divide between Catholic colleges and the institutional
church dates back decades and springs in part from the history of
church-affiliated institutions in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Many American universities, including Princeton University in New
Jersey and Yale University in Connecticut, were founded by
churches. But most linked to mainline Protestants have severed
those ties this century. So have several Southern Baptist schools,
including Baylor University in Texas and Wake Forest University in
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As drafted, it appears the new Catholic guidelines do not
specify which professors of theology will have to obtain
``mandatums.'' But in an earlier draft, such certifications would
have been needed by theologians teaching Bible, dogmatic theology,
moral theology, pastoral theology, canon law, liturgy and church
history at Catholic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines allow a one-year grace period, following approval
from Rome, before they go into effect. A process for continuing
dialogue between the bishops and Catholic theologians is not
included but is assumed, several bishops said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the committee drafting the guidelines, Bishop
John Leibrecht of Springfield, Mo., said local application will
vary depending upon applicable state and federal laws and needs
peculiar to a particular Catholic school, which range from
research-oriented universities to community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The current discussion dates to 1983 when the requirement for
the mandatum first became an issue after being included in the
worldwide church's code of canon law in 1993. In 1990, Pope John
Paul II issued a decree titled ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae,'' directed to
Catholic universities around the world and meaning ``from the heart
of the church.'' Each nation's bishops had to apply it. The U.S.
bishops in 1996 issued a looser policy, which Catholic colleges
supported, but it was rejected by the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of this new document will remain unclear until Rome
acts, the U.S. bishops implement it, and it faces a court
challenge, said Lawrence Cunningham who teaches theology at the
University of Notre Dame in South Bend, Ind. ``Right now, it's
almost like a bill in conference committee,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
