<HEADER>
A3062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-ART-2NDT     11-17 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Islamic extremism.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prominent scholars of Egypt and U.S. diplomats who have served
in Cairo say they are concerned that U.S. investigators have been
too quick to rule out catastrophic mechanical failure as the cause
of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are holes in this story that puzzle me,'' said Frank
Wisner, , who was U.S. ambassador to Cairo from 1986 to 1990.
``Egypt has one of the lowest suicide rates in the world. They are
not a suicidal people.'' He said that the utterance attributed to
the pilot is commonly used by all Egyptians in everyday settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egyptian expressions are constantly interposed with
communications to the almighty _ when you sit down to eat food,
when you move, you are constantly using the almight's name,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Shibley Telhami, who holds the Anwar Sadat chair for
peace and development at the University of Maryland, said the
Egyptian reaction was based on a heightened sensitivity that
Americans' first instinct in such an event was to think of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a case where the immediate instinct was to portray
whatever statement was made in the cockpit as a prayer and it was
immediately tied to the fear people have in the west of militant
Islam,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said that another factor was that the Egyptian
government has found itself battling Islamic extremists and feels
it has been largely successful in doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Mamoun Fandy of Georgetown University's Center for
Contemporary Arab Studies said Wednesday that the Egyptian
government is very proud of its efforts to combat terrorism and
``especially proud of its security procedures on EgyptAir which is
the national carrier.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even as U.S. and Egyptian investigators struggled to sort out
the cause of the crash, American lawyers who specialize in aviation
disasters said that they were planning lawsuits against EgyptAir.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Kreindler, a New York lawyer who has represented the
families of victims in several major jet crashes, said Wednesday
that he had already been retained by the family of one of the
EgyptAir victims and that he expected to represent several others
in lawsuits against the Egyptian carrier.
</P>
<P>
   He said that under international aviation agreements, it would
matter little if the plane had been brought down by a suicidal
pilot or a mechanical error in terms of EgyptAir's liability.
</P>
<P>
   Under international treaties, an airline is responsible for the
crash of one of its planes unless it can prove that it took ``all
necessary measures'' to avoid the crash, a legal hurdle that has
proved difficult if not impossible for airlines to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Kreindler said EgyptAir would certainly not meet the standard if
the cause of the crash was a pilot suicide. ``EgyptAir employed
that pilot, they had the opportunity to train him and test him,''
he said. ``The argument is not going to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he suspected that any effort by EgyptAir to point
investigators away from a conclusion of pilot suicide had nothing
to do with the airline's fear of legal liability. ``It's more of a
matter of honor and disgrace for them,'' he said.
</P>
