A3066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MINOR-SMOKEOUT18-COX     11-17 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-SMOKEOUT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From hard-core to no more _ a former smoker sometimes feels
regret
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It will happen tonight at a jazz bar or
a birthday party or a lonely city stoop. Someone, somewhere, will
bum a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   And she'll smoke just that one.
</P>
<P>
   She'll mooch it from a regular ol' smoker, a sheepish person
with darkened fingers who always smells slightly of nicotine, and
then she'll lean back and relish the heady buzz. She'll enjoy every
last second of that stinking thing, then stub it out like a pro.
And come tomorrow, when the sun comes up, she'll get out of bed and
go about the day, never giving a second thought to cellophane
wrapping and misplaced Bic lighters and smoking sections and
midnight jaunts to the corner store.
</P>
<P>
   I hate these people.
</P>
<P>
   For 23 years, I wanted to smoke like that, the occasional
smoker, the person who smoked one day and not the next. But I
couldn't. I would get up in the morning and fix the coffee in the
kitchen and have my first cigarette before 8 on the back porch. I
would smoke on the way to work and again when I got there and then
again at 9:45. I'd have a cigarette before lunch and another one
after. I'd smoke when I was sick to my stomach and when I had a
headache and when I had the flu. Smoking defined me and no one _
and I mean no one _ ever imagined I could quit.
</P>
<P>
   I was always the hard-core smoker of the bunch, the one who
could, and would, light up the morning after a particularly
decadent night. But eventually, I got tired of the headaches and
the cough and dullness in my chest. And I did it. I've done nothing
spectacular with the money I've saved. I've yet to lose the weight.
But it's been 589 days since I've had a cigarette. Not that I'm
counting.
</P>
<P>
   I have survived all the things I imagined I could not: car
trips, hurricanes, family crises, newspaper deadlines, writer's
block, loud children, late-night telephone talks and one or more
decent beer buzzes. I have slipped just once _ a previously
undisclosed three-puff indiscretion at a Bob Dylan concert. It
tasted divine.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 47 million smokers in this country, and
my husband happens to be among them. This is not to lecture him.
Lectures do no good. This is not an attempt to blindside him with
my inspiration. His own will come with time. This is just to say
that I am a regular person who lived for 23 years with a regular
addiction. Then on April 6, 1998, my dear friend's 40th birthday, I
woke up with a determined plan to leave the cigarettes behind. I
chewed sugar-free gum until I was nauseous and ate little carrots
by the bags. I barked at my husband. I held my son. My emotions
were wacky and my insides itched and my feet would not be still so
I could sleep. And those were the good days.
</P>
<P>
   People sometimes ask me if I'm glad I quit and, really, it's
inexplicable. Every morning, I wake up happy that I do not smoke.
The remainder of the day is a little more complicated. The other
morning I saw a young mother smoking a cigarette in her car, a baby
in the back seat. She was holding her cigarette hand out the open
car window and fanning away her exhaled smoke. It was early _ say 7
a.m. _ and the morning sun had turned the light inside her car into
a smoky haze. And watching her made me half sick to my stomach. Not
the child or the mother or the right or the wrong. Just the thought
of smoking. Then the next day I smelled someone's cigarette on the
smoking porch at work, and my mouth literally watered.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, enough time has passed for me to have met people who
never knew me as a smoker. I find this incredibly odd. It's like
people not knowing I'm married or a mother or a writer, all of
which are givens in my life. Of course I smoked. I lived some of
the most interesting years of my life tethered to ashtrays and
matches and after-dinner disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes and I drove across the country together. We cried on
the phone with friends. We sat alone and wrote bad poetry and
celebrated births and mourned deaths. I patterned my days by my
next cigarette break and made many, many friends at smoking
outposts here and there and everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   So, you're darn right I don't like occasional smokers, those
disciplined folks who have managed to inhale the euphoria but not
the addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
