<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SMOKEOUT18-COX     11-17 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKEOUT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    America's long romance with tobacco
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today is a special day for those last-of-a-dying-breed
loyalists to the century's most successful consumer product.
Cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   It is the 23rd Great American Smokeout.
</P>
<P>
   The Great American Smokeout and Earth Day. For a
quarter-century, these days of subdued protest and quiet reflection
have tried their symbolic best to halt the conflagrations that
threaten our most precious natural resources: our planet and
ourselves. But fires still denude the rain forests, and cigarette
smoke still blackens lungs.
</P>
<P>
   More acres of jungle than ever _ and more lungs than ever.
</P>
<P>
   More teen-age lungs. More Chinese, Cambodian, Thai, Kenyan and
Brazilian lungs. Up to 90 percent of grown men's lungs in some
developing countries. More women's lungs. As many American lungs as
in 1990, according to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, which means younger Americans are picking up where
older, dead Americans, left off.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 6 billion pairs of lungs on the planet today, almost as
many are smoke-filled as there were humans on the planet 100 years
ago: 1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlboro Man has roamed the range worldwide with great
success. He has lassoed smokers by the hundreds of millions _
billions, counting the dead ones.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he, not Bill Gates or Henry Ford or Dr. Jonas Salk, should
be the American Man of the Century.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the day to contemplate all of this. And, if you smoke,
it's the day to give quitting a chance. The rest of the country
will contemplate with you, offer support if you go cold turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Some things to contemplate: At the turn of this century there
were no cars, no airplanes, no computers, and no mass-produced,
mass-marketed products such as razors, cosmetics, Wheaties, Beanie
Babies or cigarettes. Then came Ford, the Wright brothers, IBM's
Thomas Watson, Walt Disney.
</P>
<P>
   And tobacco's Buck Duke, a Southern planter known for his
ruthless deal-making _ the old grandad of the modern cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   You could argue which American consumer product _ cars, TV,
computers, cigarettes _ is the most successful of the century, but
you can't argue which is the most controversial.
</P>
<P>
   PROFITABLE BONSACK MACHINE
</P>
<P>
   Duke didn't see controversy at the turn of the century when he
beheld a contraption called the Bonsack machine. It could roll 200
cigarettes per minute. Buck Duke saw profits.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy is now a $200 billion-per-year industry. It employs
hundreds of thousands, pays dividends to millions of stockholders.
And it kills its customers.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy with historic hindsight to discount Duke's vision. A
cigarette's most active ingredient, nicotine, is addictive. Even
cigarette companies say as much now. Once America lit up, it stayed
lit up. But Duke knew nothing of nicotine. He saw market potential.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Watson didn't have as clear a vision with his products:
``I see a potential worldwide market for maybe five computers,''
said Watson, in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   And the automobile was not destined to be a mass-market product.
An English newspaper said at the turn of the century that the
automobile was going nowhere ``because there are not enough
chauffeurs to sustain large sales of automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke saw potential from the get-go, and he went after it in the
best tradition of American get-go-ism.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE 'EM IF YOU GOT 'EM
</P>
<P>
   This has been called the American Century. We extended our reach
worldwide. We brought peace, democracy, Mickey Mouse, Babe Ruth and
TV to the four corners of the world. And Buck Duke brought
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   On the homefront, the U.S. government gave cigarettes to
returning doughboys and GIs, sent smokes directly to VA hospitals.
Smoke 'em if you got 'em, said the drill instructors. Doctors
recommend Lucky Strikes, said the advertisements. The government
gave fat subsidies to tobacco growers, gave the tobacco industry
the deal of a lifetime: For the entire century, tobacco was the
only consumer product not regulated and tested by the government
for its effects on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   It is considered neither food nor drug. It is King Tobacco, the
leaf that made America, immortalized in song, made fashionable by
Bogey and Bacall, nurtured by field hands under summer sun,
protected by generations of senators and congressmen and
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you're in Washington, D.C., look upward at the
columns that line many of the corridors within the U.S. Capitol
building. Look at the fancy, scrolling stonework atop the columns.
Look again. Those are tobacco leafs. King Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   NICOTINE DELIVERY SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   Nicotine is King Tobacco's illegitimate stepchild. Nicotine is
why office workers will take the elevator 40 floors down, step
outside into sub-freezing temperatures and light up. The American
Cancer Society says nicotine reaches the brain within eight seconds
of inhaling a cigarette. It's both a stimulant and a depressant. It
is a drug. It lends clarity to thought, focuses mental energy. It
is not necessarily a bad drug, but the delivery system _ a
cigarette _ also delivers carbon monoxide, noxious tars, lead,
arsenic and a host of nasty and benign chemicals, more than 100 per
puff.
</P>
<P>
   But still they _ we _ light up. Smokers' stories are different
pages from the same book: I love the taste. I love my coffee and
cigarette. I knew the risks but just couldn't quit. I'm on oxygen
24-7 and my emphysema will kill me, but I still miss the things.
</P>
<P>
   And the denial jokes, the black humor: I mean, what are you
gonna do after a romantic interlude, slap a patch on your arm?
Different pages, same book. The book of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   By the grim numbers
</P>
<P>
   You need a computer to do tobacco by the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   _ By the year 2025, more than 500 million people worldwide will
die from cigarettes, according to former U.S. Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop.
</P>
<P>
   _ That's a Vietnam War of American casualties per day, a Titanic
every 27 minutes for 27 years, says Koop.
</P>
<P>
   _ The yearly worldwide medical, cleaning, fire damage and lost
work-time costs of smoking cannot be calculated. More than a
trillion dollars is probably in the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cigarette companies will pay at least $300 billion in legal
settlements to state governments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cigarette smokers will actually pay the settlements through
increased prices.
</P>
<P>
   How will it all end? Not today, Smokeout or no.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe schoolchildren will someday have to learn about another
Hundred Years War. The first, children, took place long ago between
England and France. The second took place in the 20th century, the
Tobacco War, some call it. Nobody won.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
