<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3070 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MODERN-MUSEUM-ART-2TA     11-17 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERN-MUSEUM-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART EVERY WHICH WAY BUT STRAIGHT AHEAD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the old days, you turned left at Cezanne's
``Bather'' and proceeded, one gallery after another, until you hit
Pollock, Pop and Minimalism, and that, pretty much, was that.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art, a primary author of the First Book of
Modernism, laid down this history in neatly organized movements
with the high points and patriarchs all clearly indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The narrative had an almost biblical authority and
inevitability. God created Picasso, who created ``Les Demoiselles
d'Avignon,'' from which all else descended as from Adam's rib.
French Impressionism and Post-Impressionism, that is, the
groundbreaking paintings of Cezanne, Monet, Seurat, van Gogh and
Gauguin were Old Testament, the prophets of the coming Light.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Modern Starts: People, Places and Things,'' you can say
goodbye to all that, at least for the moment. The show completes
its floor-by-floor unveiling Sunday, with the opening of the
``Things'' section. For starters, there is no clear beginning: you
can go left or right, start at either end. You get to choose, and
to a remarkable and sometimes frustrating degree, you get to make
it up as you go along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Starts'' is the first of three enormous shows with
which the Modern is fanning the siecle, as it were, while also
examining its unparalleled collection and the way it has
historically been shaped and presented. Each is being organized by
an interdepartmental team (itself highly unusual for the Modern),
will fill the entire museum and will be up for several months.
(``Places'' and ``Things'' are on view through March 14, ``People''
through Feb. 1.)
</P>
<P>
   With some additions fore and aft, ``Modern Starts'' concentrates
on 1880-1920 (the second part, opening in March, looks at
1920-1960; the third, which arrives next fall, at 1960-2000). Its
organizing team, headed by John Elderfield, chief curator-at-large,
and Peter Reed, the curator of the department of design and
architecture, decided to abandon the familiar narrative, or any
narrative at all, and let art history take the hindmost.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it is all here, it turns out to be a doozy of a show:
unwieldy, confusing, amazingly ugly in spots, jarringly arbitrary
in others, repetitive in still others and appallingly misogynist
throughout (there's barely a female artist in sight).
</P>
<P>
   Yet it tries, in some places valiantly, to buck the museum's
oppressive tradition, to suggest that a big exhibition can be a
series of speculative what-ifs and curatorial feints in this and
that direction and to send the mind ricocheting among thoughts
about history, visual culture and the challenges and
responsibilities of the curator's craft. As one might expect, it is
also chock-full of great art.
</P>
<P>
   The curatorial team has approached the show's four-decade span
not in terms of styles, periods or chronology but by subject.
People, places and things are, more or less, the figure, landscape
and still life, the three pillars of academic tradition that became
the launching pads of modern art. Each of these headings has been
subdivided into several smaller exhibitions, some as large as four
galleries (and frequently overlong), or into clusters of works.
</P>
<P>
   The individual shows are clearly demarcated in ``People,'' which
has seven, and ``Places,'' with six; ``Things,'' organized on the
open plan, has four or five loosely defined groups of objects and
artworks.
</P>
<P>
   Within this structure, the exhibition presents what might be
called a sweeping but episodic view of the inexorable drift toward
the modern that began in Europe in the middle of the 19th century.
It is conveyed by fragments of different shapes, sizes and essences
_ historical, formal, technological, psychological.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Places,'' a big section called ``Rise of the Modern World''
traces its subject in photography, encapsulating the early growth
of the medium in the process. Another big chunk of ``Places''
reverts to the Modern's beloved core narrative _ the evolution from
Impressionism to Cubism _ recounting the tale exclusively in French
landscape painting, which the museum owns in abundance and has
never exhibited on its own.
</P>
<P>
   In ``People,'' one sees signs of what might be called modern
consciousness in one of the galleries subtitled ``Composing With
the Figure,'' where images and sculptures of heads and faces reign
supreme. Back in ``Places,'' one senses opposition to modernization
in a small section titled ``Landscape as Retreat: From Gauguin to
Nolde,'' which contains etchings and woodblock prints of isolated
houses and figures by Gauguin, Munch and the German Expressionists.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary art puts in an occasional appearance. Installation
pieces on the walls of the garden hall galleries give each section
a bit of visual fanfare more or less in tune with its contents: a
big white-on-black wall drawing by Sol LeWitt for ``People''; a
wall surrealistically covered with clumps of artificial flowers,
the work of Maria Fernanda Cardoso, for ``Places''; and, making the
most sense, ``Objects, Ready or Not,'' by the British artist
Michael Craig-Martin, a billboardlike tract of images that depicts
some of the objects included in ``Things'' in hot colors and cool
black outlines.
</P>
<P>
   These isolated cameos make more sense than the persistent
leakage into other time slots throughout the show. ``Posed and
Unposed: Encounters With the Camera'' in ``People'' contains 44
photographs, 25 of which date from after 1930, while many of the
photographs throughout ``People'' and ``Places'' are from before
1880.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things'' starts off with a ravishing series of advertising
posters that like Pop Art, isolate single objects on fields of
solid color. Three are the work of the German designer Lucian
Bernhard; three are by his follower the Swiss designer Niklaus
Stoecklin and date from the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   There are some wonderfully focused moments: a small gallery in
``People'' devoted to the prints of the Mexican artist Jose
Guadalupe Posada and the Belgian James Ensor, two artists from
different worlds, unknown to each other, who worked the same
satiric vein at the same time in remarkably similar ways; another
features the furniture of Hector Guimard, whose sweeping, curling
lines helped ignite French Art Nouveau.
</P>
<P>
   And there are also moments when the exhibition just grinds to a
halt, like a pedestrian patch of ``People'' called ``Actors,
Dancers, Bathers.'' By the fourth gallery of this section, where
Matisse's ``Dance'' is flanked by four of Cezanne's ``Bathers''
etchings, a Picasso ballerina and whatnot, you might as well be
back at the old Modern again.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, at times you may wish you were, partaking of its
clarity and showmanship. The ``Demoiselles,'' for example, looked
better under the ancien regime, in splendid isolation on its own
wall, as if it were the genesis point of modernism, which it is,
according to the gospel. Here, its brusque forms are displayed
between Matisse's great streamlined ``Piano Lesson,'' and Picabia's
bulging, polymorphous ``I See Again in Memory My Dear Udnie,'' a
group distinguished by shared pinks and discordant notions of
abstracting the human form.
</P>
<P>
   But here ``Demoiselles'' looks like what it is _ a great
painting, not a cataclysmic event; this simply achieved
diminishment is an interesting lesson in itself.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some sections might as well be titled ``Curators Just Want to
Have Fun.'' The lush if overly homogenous exegesis on French
landscape painting is followed by a spacious, wildly disparate
gallery vaguely titled ``Seasons and Moments.'' Here the art simply
leapfrogs from Monet to Alfred Stieglitz to Cy Twombly to Bill
Viola.
</P>
<P>
   Four Kandinskys are seen in a templelike folly that turns out to
be a re-creation of the New York apartment foyer for which they
were commissioned. And in a particularly sophomoric touch,
Brancusi's ``Newborn,'' a golden, globelike orb, has been placed in
front of Miro's ``Birth of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere you can almost hear a professorial voice in the
background saying, ``Next slide, please.'' This occurs most
blatantly in the ``Unreal City'' section of ``Places,'' perhaps one
of the ugliest groupings of outstanding paintings ever to grace a
major New York museum: a jangling progression of canvases by
Matisse, Mondrian, Delaunay, Leger, Feininger, Severini and most
frequently de Chirico.
</P>
<P>
   It's a formalist relay race. Each painting has one thing (and
usually only one) in common with each of its neighbors. For
example, a Delaunay shares a tower form with a de Chirico on its
left and a passage of fractured, aqua-colored light with a
Feininger on its right. The Feininger in turn shares a row of
arches with another de Chirico to its right. This de Chirico
centers on a statue, as does the Matisse to its right. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   A large map, chart and text panel reveal an underlying
geographical logic: all the paintings were painted in Paris during
World War I, where, the text contends, their abstracting tendencies
were partly a reaction to the war's bewildering destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the artists often lived within a stone's throw of
one another, as the map demonstrates. This information, easily an
MA dissertation, makes somewhat more palpable than before our
notion of Paris before 1920 as a hotbed of invention carried out by
vastly different sensibilities, but I'm not sure it justifies the
visual mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   And occasionally there are groupings that should immediately be
absorbed into the next installation of the permanent collection.
One is found among the same-subject-different-style mismatchings of
the ``Composing the Figure'' section in ``People'' (Gary Hill and
Boccioni?).
</P>
<P>
   It is a gallery that seems to focus on the penchant among
turn-of-the-century artists, including Signac, van Gogh, Klimt and
Schiele, to depict people not just in front of, but embedded
within, richly patterned or painted surfaces. These paintings
essentially reflect the encroachment of abstraction, of
art-for-art's-sake upon representation.
</P>
<P>
   But on the gallery's final wall, another arrangement suggests
quite the opposite: the encroachment of photography on
representational painting, as evinced by portraits that include
Carjat's portrait of Baudelaire, Cameron's of Tennyson, Nadar's of
Georges Sand and Degas' of Rodin sitting next to Mallarme. Adding
to the exchange is the fact that the photographs assume the
conventions of older, more traditional forms of portraiture than
the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   If the main strength of ``Modern Starts'' is refutation of
linearity in favor of multiple ``partial'' narratives, as
Elderfield calls them, its weakness is that it doesn't go nearly
far enough with this or its other concerns. It still radiates an
oppressive Francophilia, reflected in the ubiquity of works by
Picasso, Cezanne and Matisse, the constant references to Paris and
the absence of much painting by anyone else _ Americans, Germans,
British.
</P>
<P>
   This may be an unavoidable reflection of the Modern's
collection, but the attempt to temper it could have been more
strenuous. Even ``Things,'' where the show lives up to its mission
most successfully, can't get by without four Cezanne still lifes
and several works by Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the stunning refusal of this show to allow women
even a ``partial'' presence except as artistic subjects. Of the
dozen or so women represented in the show, only half actually lived
and worked during the period it covers, and excepting the designer
Eileen Gray and the Surrealist Meret Oppenheim, whose fur-lined
teacup is included in ``Things,'' they are all photographers.
</P>
<P>
   (In addition, more recent photographers, like Diane Arbus, Tina
Barney, Dorothea Lange and Helen Levitt, are included in the
``Posed and Unposed'' section.) This is less a step than a free
fall backward, a purge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things,'' isolated on the ground floor, forms an inadvertent
coda to the exhibition. It is the first place where you can see
more forest than trees, which highlights what is lacking in the
galleries upstairs. For one thing, it is beautifully installed in a
way that allows different objects in various media to play off one
another.
</P>
<P>
   For another, the media are in fact various: only in this final
section have objects of design and graphic design been allowed to
mingle freely with paintings, drawings, prints, sculptures and
photographs. One is able to watch objects move through various
states, from two to three dimensions, from art to advertising to
nonart.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Gray's classic black lacquered screen, a piece of highly
finished functional art, plays off Brancusi's ``Endless Column,'' a
work of nonfunctional, ruggedly handmade art, and Duchamp's ``Fresh
Widow,'' a French window with blackened panes that has been
appropriated as art.
</P>
<P>
   Here, where the show comes to life, one sees the missed
opportunities. It's unfortunate that furniture, which is
essentially figurative, hasn't been allowed to animate the
proceedings of ``People,'' or that artifacts like the concrete
reliefs retrieved from Frank Lloyd Wright's Midway Gardens, or the
big handsome section of Louis Sullivan's ornate wrought-iron facade
for the Gage Building aren't able to join Guimard in ``Places.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this exhibition opens a very big, very important
door but, for the most part, declines to step through it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
