<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-LADN &LR;      11-17 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CULINARY TRIP THROUGH THE LAST 100 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Package includes MILLENNIUM-YEAR-BY-YEAR and 4 takes of
recipies MILLENNIUM-RECIPES) 
By CAROL BIDWELL AND NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the 20th century began, cooking was hard work. There were few
things to make a housewife's life easier, and virtually everything
had to be made from scratch. Even families with modest incomes had
paid ``help'' in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Many housewives counted themselves lucky if they had running
water (yes, a pump counted) inside the house. If not, water had to
be drawn from a well. Wood had to be carried, and a fire had to be
made in the stove.
</P>
<P>
   The cow had to be milked. Coffee was ``boiled up'' in a pot on
the stove, often with a eggshell thrown in for clarity. Biscuits
had to be baked, meat and eggs fried, gravy made, jars of homemade
jam brought from the pantry.
</P>
<P>
   All this and it was only 6 a.m. And there were two more meals to
prepare that same day.
</P>
<P>
   Women's work in the early 1900s was generally in the home, and
much of it was spent growing and preparing food _ and, of course,
cleaning up afterward. Housewives were ready for new advances that
made their lives easier.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, times were prosperous despite _ or perhaps in part
because of _ Prohibition, which drove even the law-abiding to drink
as sweet cocktails masked the taste of bathtub gin. Chinese
restaurants provided a bit of exotica. For ladies, tearooms became
popular, as did gelatin salads, the fruit-filled Lady Baltimore
cake, devil's food cake and pineapple upside-down cake. At the end
of the decade, with the stock market crash, financial havoc was
created on many fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rough financial times in the '30s, Americans loved to
socialize and found affordable ways to do it. Sunday night suppers,
tea parties and one-dish meals made entertaining inexpensive.
Gadgets such as the new electric toaster, waffle iron, percolator
and electric mixer made it fun, too.
</P>
<P>
   There were new things to cook, too: It was in this era that
zucchini and broccoli first became widely available in the United
States. Ruth Wakefield changed American snacking forever when she
chopped up chocolate and mixed it into cookie batter, creating the
first chocolate-chip cookies, which she named Toll House Cookies
after the New England inn she and her husband ran.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking methods became standardized, and assorted cookbooks
began to appear. With the opening of Route 66 between Chicago and
Los Angeles, highway eateries thrived. So did food companies, which
introduced a wealth of new products.
</P>
<P>
   In the '40s _ with the best of American food sent overseas to
soldiers and sailors doing the fighting _ those left at home had to
make do with what was left. Meat, coffee, sugar, butter, cheese and
canned goods were rationed _ if they were available at all. So
housewives _ who might have spent their days working in a defense
plant _ planted victory gardens to provide for their families.
</P>
<P>
   Basic American home cooking was the food of the day. Only the
very rich still had servants. Patriotic housewives saved bacon fat
to use in cakes and made their own jams, jellies and pickles. With
commodities scarce, entertaining was often coffee and dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Housewives also benefited from some foods produced for GIs _
dehydrated soups, dried potatoes, canned biscuits, pudding mixes,
margarine and vegetable oils. After the war, GIs brought home a new
taste for exotic food, especially pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed in the food realm. Frozen and pre-made foods
became available _ and supermarkets made shopping easier. A
prosperous future with an abundance of food _ including gourmet and
convenience foods, plus new and more exotic restaurants _ was on
the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, with World War II and the Korean War over, GI Joe
was home, his wife was back in the kitchen, and that kitchen was
often in the suburbs, where new houses were being built with
fabulous kitchens, patios and barbecues. Beef _ long before any of
us knew about cholesterol _ went on those barbecues. Add a baked
potato, a salad and garlic bread, and you had a meal as American as
apple pie. That's not to say suburbia wasn't a breeding ground for
gourmet cooks, though: Beef Stroganoff and baked Alaska were tops
on any gourmet's list of dishes to perfect.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Swanson was marketing TV dinners, complete
frozen meals the family could eat while watching television. Other
convenience and frozen foods also came into their own. Fast-food
chains got their start and boomed.
</P>
<P>
   The psychedelic '60s were a mishmash of food trends, from fast
food to spa food, from blender gazpacho to fondue, from soul food
to luaus. To really put on the dog, cooks dished up veal Orloff,
beef Wellington, rumaki and more. With the affluence, prosperity
and jet travel of the era, foreign foods became more familiar and
accessible. Ethnic restaurants appeared in ever-increasing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s, known by many as the ``me'' decade, was a time of
singles bars, mood rings, pet rocks, Earth shoes and disco, a time
when even the food had strange names, like Screaming Yellow
Zonkers, Fluffernutters and Harvey Wallbangers. Eventually, though,
dinner parties, cooking classes, nouvelle cuisine, regional
cuisine, the food processor and such trendy foods as goat cheese,
farm-fresh greens, chocolate truffles and specialty produce became
all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Crock-Pots (electric slow cookers) had moved into the kitchen,
along with bundt pans and granola. And cooks were turning out
zucchini and carrot cakes slathered with cream cheese frosting
along with crepes and quiche. Restaurant favorites were fettuccini
Alfredo, main dish salads, salad bars, ranch dressing and Kahlua.
</P>
<P>
   Americans had had enough of spa food and itty-bitty portions in
the '80s. They wanted comfort food like Mom used to make. Meatloaf
was king again, along with fried chicken, mashed potatoes (although
cooks added garlic) and pizza.
</P>
<P>
   America's power elite and baby boomers had become foodies,
wheeling and dealing over power lunches at high-priced restaurants
and becoming awed by star chefs who became celebrities at a time
when status and style were all-important.
</P>
<P>
   Grazing _ eating a bit of this and a bit of that throughout the
day _ was the ``in'' thing, and so were Cajun and Southwest
cuisine. Salsa replaced ketchup as the favorite condiment. Cooks
could find kiwi, mangoes, mesclun, free-range chickens, goat cheese
and creme fraiche in markets. Pesto was a new favorite, along with
risotto, croissants and muffins. Cholesterol-lowering oat bran made
up for all that comfort. In the home kitchen, heat-and-eat
convenience foods _ with no cooking required _ were popular.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe as a backlash to all that comfort food, in the '90s
Americans became obsessed with fat _ how much in food items and
dishes and how to reduce intake _ along with nutrition, health and
fitness. Supermarkets began devoting more shelf space to nonfat and
low-fat cookies, sour cream, cream cheese, ice cream and products
containing a new low-fat fat named Olestra as manufacturers rushed
to get in on the fat-free, reduced-fat product craze. Some were
good and found a permanent place on the shelves; others were so
poor and disappointing that they disappeared quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, obesity rates soared. Other consumers were into luxury
and quality (super-premium ice creams, fine wines and cheeses, for
instance). Biscotti in an array of flavors became popular. And
bread machines, turning out custom loaves with little effort,
became the rage for home cooks. Foods that were once only available
at ethnic markets were now available in supermarkets. And now it
was possible to order groceries, talk with other cooks and find
recipes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As you look back over the last century in food, reminisce with
this sampling of some of the most popular recipes. Depending on
your age, you may recall having eaten _ or cooked _ some of them. &QL; 
___
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson
(Clarkson Potter; $35); ``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren
(Macmillan; $25); ``Better Homes &AMP; Gardens' 75 Years of All-Time
Favorites'' (Better Homes &AMP; Gardens Books; $29.95); ``America Eats
Out'' (William Morrow &AMP; Co.; $25); ``Back of the Box Gourmet''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster; $12.95); Bon Appetit magazine, September 1999;
and ``On the Town in New York'' (Routledge; $30). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3073 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-COPELAND-2000-3TAKES-     11-17 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPELAND-2000-3TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPELAND, CHAMPION OF THE AMERICAN SOUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aaron Copland, who died in 1990, must have winced a bit when,
late in life, he found himself proclaimed America's greatest
composer.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, for all his self-effacing collegiality, he was
gratified. And the assessment was deserved. Other American
composers have loomed large in this century and produced impressive
catalogs. Elliott Carter's music is more ingenious than Copland's.
Roger Sessions' works are rightly respected for their structural
rigor, impressive density and seriousness of purpose. And the
flinty Charles Ives is by far America's most original composer.
</P>
<P>
   But in its freshness, consistency, auditory acuteness, rhythmic
vigor, spare harmonic beauty and authenticity, Copland's music is
the finest body of work an American has produced. It has certainly
touched the widest range of people, from jaded professional
musicians to the common man Copland saluted in his famous
orchestral fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is the matter of that pesky qualifier, that adjective
of nationality: greatest ``American'' composer. Doesn't it smack of
the Eurocentric snobbery Copland fought against all his life?
</P>
<P>
   If it bothered Copland, he had no one to blame but himself, for
no composer strove more consciously to be American. Born in a
tenement two floors above the dry goods store his Lithuanian Jewish
father ran in Brooklyn, Copland never lived far from New York and
never felt comfortable in any other country, with the possible
exception of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The few years he spent in his early 20s studying with Nadia
Boulanger in Paris and traveling through Germany were for him the
equivalent of the college education he never got. It was important
to absorb what was going on in contemporary music, and Paris was
then the center of it. But he returned from Europe more strongly
resolved than ever to stay home and work to foster among his
colleagues a distinctively American voice for new music.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadway, jazz and pop song composers of America in the
early 20th century had found such a voice. Those working in the
classical tradition, Copland felt, were still beholden to European
models. Composers had to turn to their own heritage for inspiration
and source materials, Copland believed. Russian music had a
distinctive sound and tradition, as did French, German and Spanish
music. Why not American music?
</P>
<P>
   Dissenters, including some colleagues Copland was trying to
rally to the cause, argued that this goal was self-limiting and
pointless. In a 1926 letter, the intellectually formidable
Sessions, an avowed internationalist, upbraided Copland for
``wasting precious energy'' on anything ``so vague and dubious as
the `future of American music.'''
</P>
<P>
   Copland's friendly rival Virgil Thomson, wary of all
compositional schools, thought that writing American music was a
no-brainer. ``Just be an American,'' he said, ``and write any kind
of music you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sessions' warnings and Thomson's kidding, Copland
managed to fashion a musical voice that has been accepted ever
since as quintessentially American. All any composer need do to
evoke America is to imitate Copland: the jazzy polyrhythms and
asymmetrical meters; the lean textures; the angular melodies; the
spiky, percussive orchestrations; the sonorities with intervals as
wide open as the plains; the unpatronizing use of folk tunes and
cowboy songs; the sturdy modal harmonies that suggest hymns played
on harmoniums in countless frontier churches.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the image of Copland as Musical Americana obscures the range
of his achievement, which holds up to any international standard.
His popular acclaim rests on a handful of works that get performed
too often for their own good. The best thing about the New York
Philharmonic's Completely Copland festival, a three-week
retrospective that began on Saturday with a Young People's Concert
conducted by Bobby McFerrin and really gets going on Wednesday
evening with a concert conducted by Kurt Masur, is the opportunity
it provides to hear the full scope of Copland's work.
</P>
<P>
   Next Nov. 14 is the 100th anniversary of Copland's birth, and it
is being observed with some 200 events internationally over the
year, a project called Copland 2000 and spearheaded by the
composer's vigilant and eternally grateful publishing house, Boosey
&AMP; Hawkes.
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic's offering is the largest component of the
celebration. Virtually all of Copland's orchestral works, as well
as music for film, dance and opera, will be performed in six
different programs led by five conductors. In addition, 10 prelude
concerts will present performances of chamber music, piano works,
choral pieces and songs, with commentary from lecturers and
panelists.
</P>
<P>
   The series offers a roster of thorny, seldom-heard works that
may startle many concertgoers who think they know Copland. How
often does one get to hear ``Connotations'' for orchestra, the
beautifully severe 12-tone work that Copland wrote for the 1962
inaugural concert of Philharmonic Hall (now Avery Fisher Hall),
which was conducted by Leonard Bernstein, the composer's most
ardent disciple. Even the Philharmonic has presented the work only
twice since its premiere, most recently in 1989, again with
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In one prelude concert the Sextet for Clarinet, Piano and String
Quartet will be performed. This is actually a 1937 arrangement of
Copland's Short Symphony (1933), an orchestral work renowned for
its difficulties: relentless syncopations, crisscrossing rhythms
and almost constantly changing meters. Stravinsky wrote few pieces
stronger than this sextet. Yet it seldom turns up in chamber music
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Another inexplicable rarity is the Piano Fantasy, which the
pianist Michael Boriskin will perform in the festival. Completed in
1957 after several years of labor, this is a monumental, gritty,
technically arduous half-hour composition, freely adapted from
12-tone techniques and true to its name. It holds up to any
20th-century piano piece, by Schoenberg, Messiaen or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Here the use of dissonance is bracing in a way that somehow
seems, well, American. There is no sense of European angst about
it. Rather, the astringent harmonies are ecstatic, energizing. It's
as if Copland were saying: ``Just listen to that dissonance. Isn't
it wonderful?'' The Fantasy is inexorable yet elusive in design,
like an adventure trip with ``few familiar landmarks,'' in the
words of the composer Arthur Berger.
</P>
<P>
   In many years of concertgoing I have come across only one
performance of the piece, during a Copland tribute presented by the
ensemble Boston Musica Viva at Jordan Hall in 1979. Copland, who
was present, had not heard the Fantasy performed for some time, he
said, and was awe-struck by the playing of the pianist, Randall
Hodgkinson. ``It's like you're reading my mind,'' Copland, clearly
moved, told the pianist.
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic programs draw from all periods of Copland's
work, which are more diverse than is generally realized, especially
the period during the 1920s when Copland, trying to shake up his
language and make it American, borrowed from jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporating jazz into his symphonic music ``signified a
defiant badge of contemporary urban America,'' Howard Pollack
writes in his new biography, ``Aaron Copland: The Life and Work of
an Uncommon Man.'' Thomson later referred to Copland's venture into
jazz as his friend's ``one wild oat.''
</P>
<P>
   Though witty, the remark is a bit unfair. Works like the Piano
Concerto and ``Music for the Theater,'' which will be performed by
the Philharmonic, are raucous, rude and vibrant.
</P>
<P>
   Copland eventually felt he had come to a dead end. Jazz was too
powerful; it resisted getting dressed up for the concert hall.
Copland's jazz works started sounding like stiff, self-conscious
imitations of the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s he simplified his harmonic language. But by the
1950s he was already experimenting with 12-tone music. Pollack, in
his book, convincingly challenges an existing assumption, that
Copland, following Stravinsky's example, started writing 12-tone
music out of a fear of being considered obsolete by younger
composers.
</P>
<P>
   Copland was always curious about new developments. By this time
he felt that his harmonic language was becoming stale. Why did he
turn to dodecaphonic techniques, Bernstein once asked him?
``Because I need more chords,'' Copland replied. ``I've run out of
chords.''
</P>
<P>
   That Copland's music was so stylistically diverse would seem to
complicate the question of its American character. Isn't it futile
to specify what makes his music, or any music, American? What makes
German music German? Copland's bare, widely spaced modal harmonies
may conjure up the spacious American plains. But Palestrina wrote
similar chords in 16th-century Italy. Sturdy, simple hymns may
evoke plain-spoken American pioneers. But Martin Luther's chorale
tunes are just as simple and sturdy.
</P>
<P>
   There is a disarming quality in all of Copland's music that
comes from its shifting moods, by turns joyful and ecstatic,
brusque and riotous, pensive and reserved. Somehow, the shifts
never seem tortured or neurotic; rather, just two sides of the same
identity, expressed clearly, without apology or fuss. But is this
American?
</P>
<P>
   Surely, that quality comes more from Copland's personality than
from any general character trait of the American people. For a
homosexual man coming of age in the America of the 1910s, Copland
was remarkably well adjusted. He accepted his difference, and the
resultant isolation, with inner calm and little self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he cultivated privacy. In public he was avuncular and
discreet about his personal life. With friends he was open and
easy. But the public reserve, the public face, was always there,
not least in his music.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable document movingly captures Copland's sense of
reserve as it relates to his music and illuminates the question of
his Americanness. In 1974 he conducted the chamber ensemble version
of ``Appalachian Spring'' for a Columbia recording. Included with
that album was a six-inch bonus record of excerpts from the
rehearsal session, and it is a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
