<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-LADN, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 YEARS OF RECIPES
</HEADLINE>
 4 takes  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Package includes MILLENNIUM-MAIN and
MILLENNIUM-YEAR-BY-YEAR) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you look back over the last 100 years in American food, take
a stroll down memory lane with this sampling of some of the most
popular recipes. You may have indulged in some of them.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRENCH DRESSING &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons cold water &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon unflavored gelatin &QL; 
2 tablespoons vinegar &QL; 
1 teaspoon onion juice (extracted by grating onion) &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
Pepper &QL; 
8 drops Worcestershire sauce &QL; 
1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Pour cold water in a bowl and sprinkle gelatin on top of water;
add vinegar. Place bowl over boiling water and stir until gelatin
is dissolved. Add seasonings and cool (but do not allow to
thicken).
</P>
<P>
   Pour into a bottle, add oil, and shake until well-blended. Use
other seasonings as desired.
</P>
<P>
   This dressing will remain in emulsion, but do not refrigerate or
it will acquire a jellylike consistency. Makes 3/4 cup.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Knox Gelatin Desserts, Salads, Candies and Frozen
Dishes,'' published 1933.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MIDDLE AMERICAN CHILI CON CARNE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons bacon drippings OR vegetable oil &QL; 
1 pound ground beef &QL; 
2 onions, chopped &QL; 
2 cloves garlic, minced &QL; 
2 cups canned tomatoes, chopped &QL; 
3 cups kidney beans, rinsed if canned &QL; 
3 tablespoons chili powder &QL; 
1 tablespoon corn meal &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
3 tablespoons water &QL; 
1 teaspoon dried crumbled oregano
</P>
<P>
   In a deep, heavy pan, heat drippings, then add ground beef and
onions and cook over medium heat until beef is brown and onions are
soft. Pour off excess fat. Add garlic to pan and cook over low heat
a few minutes. Stir in tomatoes and beans and cook 10 to 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix together chili powder, corn meal and salt.
Stir in water to make a thick paste. Stir chili paste into beef
mixture. Stir in crumbled oregano. Cook over low heat, stirring
occasionally, 1 hour. Adjust seasonings, adding salt, oregano,
garlic or chili powder to taste. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   (If chili is held overnight, check seasonings at serving time,
because heat of chili powder seems to dissipate on standing.) Makes
8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren, Macmillan
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLASSIC FLAMING BAKED ALASKA &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 half-gallon brick ice cream, any flavor, soft enough to cut but
not dripping &QL; 
1 (12- to 16-ounce) pound cake, about 7x4x2 inches &QL; 
4 egg whites, at room temperature &QL; 
Pinch salt &QL; 
1/2 cup powdered sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons high-proof rum OR flammable liqueur of choice
</P>
<P>
   Cut ice cream to exact dimension of cake. (There will be some
ice cream left over.) Cut cake in half horizontally and place
ice-cream brick in center, making a giant ice-cream sandwich. Put
sandwich on an ovenproof platter and cover lightly. Place in
freezer long enough to refreeze ice cream until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, preheat oven to 450 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg whites and salt until frothy, and gradually beat in
powdered sugar until whites are thick and glossy. Remove frozen
brick of ice cream and cake from freezer, and cover with egg
whites, whirling them festively.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 4 to 6 minutes, or until meringue is lightly browned. Watch
carefully to avoid burning meringue.
</P>
<P>
   Heat liqueur in small saucepan. As soon as baked Alaska is
removed from oven, carefully light hot liqueur with match until it
is flaming and immediately pour over meringue. Blow out flames when
meringue begins to singe if flames do not die out before. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``American Gourmet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TACO DIP &QL; 
1 (17-ounce) can refried beans (use hot and spicy beans if
desired) &QL; 
Bottled taco sauce &QL; 
Guacamole Dip &QL; 
1 pint dairy sour cream &QL; 
1 (1 1/2-ounce) package taco seasoning mix &QL; 
2 to 3 cups shredded Cheddar cheese &QL; 
4 green onions, chopped &QL; 
3 tomatoes, chopped &QL; 
1 (2.2-ounce) can sliced ripe olives, drained &QL; 
Tortillas chips
</P>
<P>
   Mix refried beans and 1/4 cup taco sauce. Spread bean mixture in
bottom of a 10-inch fluted quiche dish or pie plate. Top with
Guacamole Dip, spreading evenly. Mix together sour cream and taco
seasoning mix. Spread carefully over guacamole. Sprinkle with
cheese, green onions, tomatoes and ripe olives. Refrigerate until
serving time.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, stand tortillas chips up around sides of
serving dish. Serve with additional tortilla chips. Makes 8 to 10
servings.
</P>
<P>
   GUACAMOLE DIP: Mash together 2 to 3 ripe avocados, peeled and
seeded. Mix in 2 tablespoons lemon juice; 2 tomatoes, chopped; 3 to
4 tablespoons diced green chiles; dash Tabasco sauce; add garlic
salt and seasoned salt to taste. Adjust seasonings as desired.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KRAFT MUSIC HALL APPETIZER CLAM DIP
</P>
<P>
   When the recipe for clam dip first appeared on the Kraft Music
Hall television show in the early '50s, New York City sold out of
canned clams within 24 hours. The mania for clam dip continued
through the '60s (by then, premade clam dip could be found in the
refrigerator section of the supermarket).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 garlic clove, cut in half &QL; 
1 (8-ounce) can minced clams, drained and 1/4 of liquid reserved &QL; 
1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, softened &QL; 
2 teaspoons lemon juice &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons Worcestershire sauce &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
Dash pepper
</P>
<P>
   Rub a mixing bowl with garlic halves. Combine all remaining
ingredients, mixing until well blended. Chill.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with chips, crackers or raw vegetables as dippers. Makes 1
2/3 cups dip.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren, Macmillan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
STRAWBERRIES ROMANOFF
</P>
<P>
   This version of the popular dessert combines features of many
American recipes of the '40s and '50s. Use the orange juice mixture
drained from the berries in a punch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 quarts fresh strawberries, rinsed and hulled &QL; 
Powdered sugar to taste &QL; 
2 cups fresh-squeezed orange juice &QL; 
1/3 cup plus 1/4 cup curacao, Cointreau OR Grand Marnier liqueur &QL; 
1 pint vanilla ice cream &QL; 
1 cup whipping cream, whipped until stiff peaks form
</P>
<P>
   Put strawberries in a large nonreactive bowl and add powdered
sugar. Pour orange juice and 1/3 cup liqueur over berries; soak 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Drain berries of most of liquid and place berries in a chilled
serving bowl. Work 1/4 cup liqueur into ice cream (liqueur will
soften ice cream considerably).
</P>
<P>
   Fold whipped cream into ice cream and serve mixture over
strawberries. Serve immediately. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHICKEN DIVAN CONTINENTAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds or no, a gal's best friend can be a can of soup,''
said the October 1952, American Home, and this 1950s recipe _ ready
in 15 minutes _ proves it. Serve it over rice for a complete meal _
the soup makes a terrific sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1 (10-ounce) package frozen broccoli, cooked according to package
directions &QL; 
2 (10 3/4-ounce) cans condensed cream of mushroom soup, undiluted &QL; 
1/2 cup milk &QL; 
1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce &QL; 
1/4 cup grated Parmesan cheese &QL; 
1 (6-ounce) can chicken OR 1 1/4 cups sliced cooked chicken
</P>
<P>
   Arrange broccoli in a shallow 2-quart baking dish. Combine soup,
milk and Worcestershire sauce. Pour 1/2 of soup mixture over
broccoli. Sprinkle with 1/2 of cheese. Top with chicken, remaining
soup mixture and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   In preheated broiler, broil about 10 minutes or until heated
through and lightly browned. Makes 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUICHE LORRAINE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
6 slices bacon, chopped &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped onion &QL; 
1 1/2 cups (6 ounces) shredded Swiss cheese &QL; 
1 unbaked 9-inch deep-dish pastry shell &QL; 
1 1/2 cups (12-ounce can) evaporated milk &QL; 
3 large eggs, well beaten &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon ground black pepper &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Cook bacon in a large skillet over medium heat. When bacon
starts to turn brown, add onion.
</P>
<P>
   Cook until bacon is crisp; drain. Sprinkle cheese in bottom of
pastry shell. Top with bacon mixture. Combine evaporated milk,
eggs, salt, pepper and nutmeg in a small bowl until blended. Pour
into pastry shell.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 30 to 35 minutes or until a
knife inserted halfway between center and edge comes out clean.
Cool 5 minutes on a wire rack before serving. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHISKEY (OR RUM) CAKE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAKE: &QL; 
1 (18 1/4-ounce) package yellow cake mix &QL; 
1 (4-ounce) package INSTANT vanilla pudding and pie filling mix &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
1/2 cup vegetable oil &QL; 
1 cup milk &QL; 
1/4 cup rye whiskey OR dark rum &QL; 
1 cup chopped pecans OR walnuts, dusted with flour &QL; 
GLAZE: &QL; 
1/3 cup butter &QL; 
3/4 cup sugar &QL; 
1/4 cup water &QL; 
1/4 cup rye whiskey OR dark rum
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour a 12-cup bundt pan.
</P>
<P>
   For Cake, combine all cake ingredients except nuts and beat with
a mixer on medium speed 5 minutes. Stir in nuts. Pour batter into
prepared pan.
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven until cake pulls away slightly
from edges of pan and a toothpick inserted in center of cake comes
out clean, about 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While cake is baking, make glaze.
</P>
<P>
   For Glaze, in a small saucepan over low heat, melt butter, then
stir in sugar, water and whiskey. Boil 5 minutes, stirring
constantly. Remove from heat and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cake from oven and immediately pour 1/2 of glaze over
cake. Leave cake in pan 25 minutes. Remove from pan and pour
remaining glaze over. Makes 20 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren, Macmillan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
