<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 1st add  
UNDATED: ... by Sylvia Lovegren, Macmillan. DEVILED HAM DIP
<TEXT>
<P>
   I remember my mother serving this dip at her book club in the
late 1940s. In fact, it was my job to pass the dips and chips. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 (4 1/2-ounce) can deviled ham &QL; 
1 (3-ounce) package cream cheese, at room temperature &QL; 
2 tablespoons minced yellow onion &QL; 
1 tablespoon Dijon mustard &QL; 
1 tablespoon India relish, pickle relish OR chutney &QL; 
1/2 cup dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients until smooth. Cover and refrigerate several
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Before serving, let stand at room temperature 30 to 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mound in a small serving bowl and surround with potato or corn
chips, crackers, cherry tomatoes or bite-size chunks of carrot,
celery, zucchini, broccoli and cauliflower. Makes about 1 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson,
Clarkson Potter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
STROGANOFF CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   A '70s and '80s party pleaser that I dug out of my personal
recipe file. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds lean ground beef chuck &QL; 
1 large yellow onion, coarsely chopped &QL; 
l clove garlic, minced &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon dried leaf marjoram, crumbled &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon dried leaf thyme, crumbled &QL; 
1 (8-ounce) can tomato sauce &QL; 
1 cup cream-style cottage cheese &QL; 
1/2 of an 8-ounce package cream cheese, diced &QL; 
1/2 pound medium egg noodles, cooked and drained by package
directions &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt OR to taste &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon black pepper OR to taste &QL; 
1/2 cup coarsely shredded sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   Coat a 2 1/2- to 3-quart casserole with nonstick cooking spray
and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Stir-fry beef, onion and garlic in a very large, heavy, nonstick
skillet over moderate heat, breaking up clumps, until meat is
uniformly brown, about 5 minutes. Stir in marjoram and thyme and
cook, stirring often, 3 to 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mix in tomato sauce, cottage cheese, cream cheese, noodles, salt
and pepper. Taste for salt and pepper and adjust as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Turn into casserole, scatter Cheddar evenly on top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven, uncovered, until browned and
bubbly, 25 to 30 minutes. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson,
Clarkson Potter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PORCUPINE MEAT BALLS
</P>
<P>
   The sort of easy, novelty recipe that appealed to cooks in the
'30s appears to have been developed during World War I as a way to
stretch meat. In ``Conservation Recipes'' (1918), compiled by the
Mobilized Women's Organizations of Berkeley and published by the
Berkeley Unit, Council of Defense Women's Committee, there is
something called Rice Meat Balls, a clear forerunner of the recipe
here, which is adapted from ``My Better Homes and Gardens Cook
Book'' (1939). The 1918 version plumps up a pound of round steak
with 1 cup crumbs and 3/4 cup rice. The Better Homes recipe
specifies beef neck, shank or plate ground to order _ not readily
available today. Ground chuck has been substituted. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds ground beef chuck &QL; 
1/2 cup uncooked converted rice &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon black pepper &QL; 
1 tablespoon minced yellow onion &QL; 
1 (10 1/2-ounce) can condensed tomato soup &QL; 
1 soup can water
</P>
<P>
   Using hands, mix beef, rice, salt, pepper and onion well and
shape into 1-inch balls.
</P>
<P>
   Mix tomato soup and water in a medium heavy skillet and bring to
simmering over moderate heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add meatballs, adjust heat so mixture bubbles very gently, cover
and simmer 1 hour. Serve accompanied by a crisp green salad. Makes
6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson,
Clarkson Potter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CALIFORNIA DIP
</P>
<P>
   This may not be ``the mother of all dips,'' but it is surely
America's most beloved. The Lipton Company, whose dry onion soup
mix is the basis of California Dip, doesn't claim to have invented
it. That distinction belongs to an anonymous California cook, who
blended sour cream with the soup mix back in 1954 _ two years after
it hit the market. Beginning in 1958, Lipton included the recipe on
every box of Lipton Recipe Secrets Onion Soup Mix. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 envelope dry onion soup mix &QL; 
2 cups dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Mix ingredients and serve with potato chips, crackers or
bite-size chunks of raw vegetables _ celery, carrots, broccoli or
cauliflower. Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson,
Clarkson Potter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FROZEN FRUIT SALAD
</P>
<P>
   This salad is from ``The Charlotte Cookbook'' published in 1971
by the Junior League of Charlotte, North Carolina. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 (3-ounce) package cream cheese &QL; 
1 tablespoon plus 1 cup whipping cream &QL; 
1/3 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
1 tablespoon lemon juice &QL; 
Dash salt &QL; 
1 cup canned pineapple, drained &QL; 
1 cup orange sections, drained &QL; 
1 cup Royal Ann cherries, drained OR green seedless grapes &QL; 
1/2 cup maraschino cherries, drained &QL; 
3 tablespoons sugar &QL; 
1 cup miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Blend softened cream cheese, 1 tablespoon cream and mayonnaise.
Add lemon juice and salt. Add fruit, which has been cut in small
pieces. (Any fruit may be substituted.)
</P>
<P>
   Whip remaining 1 cup whipping cream, folding in sugar. Fold
whipped cream, marshmallows and fruit mixture together. Pour into
refrigerator trays or a square pan and freeze until firm. Makes 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TACO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   This salad arrived with the Tex-Mex fast-food franchise, which
began to pepper the country in the '60s. This recipe for Taco Salad
is adapted from the May 1968 issue of Sunset. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 pound lean ground beef &QL; 
1/4 cup finely chopped yellow onion &QL; 
2 teaspoons chili powder &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1 (8-ounce) can tomato sauce &QL; 
1 medium head iceberg lettuce, shredded &QL; 
1/3 cup shredded Cheddar cheese &QL; 
2 medium tomatoes, peeled, cored and cut into wedges &QL; 
1 medium avocado, pitted, peeled and sliced (optional) &QL; 
1 1/2 to 2 cups corn chips OR tortilla chips
</P>
<P>
   Crumble beef into a a large nonstick skillet. Add onion and
stir-fry over moderate heat until beef is no longer pink, 6 to 8
minutes. Mix in chili powder, salt and tomato sauce. Bring to a
simmer and keep hot.
</P>
<P>
   Divide lettuce among 4 dinner plates. Top with hot beef mixture
and sprinkle with cheese. Divide tomato wedges, avocado slices and
corn chips among 4 plates, arranging as artfully as possible. Serve
at once. Makes 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson,
Clarkson Potter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
