<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-SOFT-MONEY-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER SAYS IT IS ENDING `SOFT MONEY' GIFTS TO PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Time Warner announced on Wednesday that it would no
longer make unregulated donations to political parties, saying such
``soft money'' contributions distort the electoral process and
sully the givers.
</P>
<P>
   The company joins a handful of other corporations in swearing
off contributions to the parties, but advocates of campaign finance
reform said it was too early to declare the unilateral actions a
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, which owns Cable News Network, Warner Bros. and
Time magazine, among other properties, has given roughly $1 million
to the Republican and Democratic parties in each of the last two
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald M. Levin, the chairman at Time Warner, said much of the
soft money has been used for misleading and negative advertising
that cheapens the nation's political dialogue. Levin said the
company would use the money instead to beef up coverage of politics
and to sponsor electronic town meetings to educate the voters
better.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to employees, Levin and Richard D. Parsons, the
company's president, said the company would halt its corporate
giving to the parties but would continue to operate a political
action committee using voluntary contributions from employees to
make donations to individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The memo referred to the company's ``special responsibility'' to
provide full and fair coverage of politics, an acknowledgment that
many in the newsgathering side of the company were uncomfortable
with the parent corporation's political largess.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is analogous at other major television companies
that are owned by conglomerates with broad interests and big
political budgets. General Electric, which owns NBC and the Walt
Disney Co., which owns ABC, are substantial contributors to parties
and candidates. Viacom, the parent of CBS, gives virtually no money
to the parties but its political action committee contributes
sizable sums to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of campaign reform applauded the Time Warner
announcement, but other corporations, unions and wealthy
individuals showed no sign of following the company's lead. Time
Warner has not been among the biggest corporate soft-money givers _
it ranked 46th in 1997-98 with $471,000 and 48th in the current
cycle, at $155,000 so far this year. In 1997-98, Disney ranked 8th
overall among corporate soft-money donors, General Electric ranked
29th and Viacom 434th, according to FEC Info, an independent group
that tracks campaign expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they've done is courageous and we hope it will be
a good model for other companies around the country to follow,''
said Charles Kolb, president of the Committee for Economic
Development, a group of business executives who favor the
elimination of soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Kolb said that General Motors, Monsanto Co. and Allied Signal
announced a year ago that they would no longer make soft-money
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the current system identify soft money as one of
its chief evils. Corporations, unions and wealthy citizens gave
$190 million to the two major parties in soft money in the 1998
campaign and have donated $60 million already this year, according
to FEC Info.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the soft money is used to pay for so-called issue
advertisements that purportedly do not advocate the election of an
individual candidate. Critics say the ads are merely a means of
circumventing spending limits imposed on candidates but not on the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   A Time Warner official said the announcement followed a yearlong
review of the company's political activities and did not come in
response to a particular event.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just a profound trend that we grew uncomfortable
with,'' the official said. But he added that the company would not
seek refunds of the $80,000 it has already given the Democrats and
the $75,000 it has donated to Republicans this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, a campaign finance research group, said the Time Warner
announcement could embolden other companies.
</P>
<P>
   And it could be a sign of what Makinson called donor fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have been hit up and hit up and hit up and the
election is still a year away,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
