<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3088 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-INQUEST18-COX     11-17 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-INQUEST18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Official reopens inquest into Davidian's death
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Justice of the Peace David Pareya said Wednesday
that he will reopen the inquest into the death of Michael
Schroeder, killed by agents with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms on the day of the 1993 raid on Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Pareya said a recent review of the file showed the case to be
pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the cause of death,'' Pareya said. ``The purpose of
this proceeding will be to close out the case and make a
determination on the manner of the death.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder _ who was married to Kathryn Schroeder, a Branch
Davidian who became a key government witness in the 1994 criminal
trial of 11 Davidians _ was not at Mount Carmel on the morning of
Feb. 28, 1993, when ATF agents tried to arrest the late David
Koresh. Four ATF agents and five Davidians died in the resulting
shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, ATF agents shot and killed Schroeder when he, Bob
Kendrick and Norman Allison tried to sneak into Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Kendrick escaped and Allison was arrested at the scene. An
autopsy showed that Schroeder was shot numerous times in the head,
shoulder and thigh. ATF agents reported that Schroeder fired first
at them. He reportedly was carrying a loaded Glock 9 mm
semiautomatic pistol and two ammunition magazines. Four days passed
before Schroeder's body was recovered because FBI officials, then
in charge of the scene, claimed the body could not be removed
safely because it was in the line of sight of Davidian sentries
manning the tower at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Pareya viewed Schroeder's body before it was removed. ATF agents
in a barn behind Mount Carmel showed Pareya several bullet holes
that they said were caused by Schroeder firing at them. They
reported shooting Schroeder while he was in a ravine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them if that was the case, I needed to know who shot
him,'' Pareya said. ``I asked several times for that information.
Like a lot of other things I asked for during that time, I never
got an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Pareya said he's hoping the information will be in a Texas
Rangers' report on the shooting that he finally received last week.
He has not yet reviewed the report, Pareya said.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Pareya was only given the Rangers' preliminary
report on Schroeder's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional information was to follow,'' Pareya said.
``Unfortunately, it was never submitted to me for the final
disposition of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   A resurgence of interest in the Branch Davidian case _ driven by
a wrongful death lawsuit set for May _ led to numerous requests for
information on file in his office, Pareya said. In reviewing the
voluminous file, he noted that Schroeder's case was not closed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was awaiting information from various agencies that had
investigated the death,'' Pareya said. ``Frankly, that information
is more easily obtained now. To a certain extent, I've been able to
take advantage of the timing. People are giving out information
that wasn't made public before.''
</P>
<P>
   Pareya has not set a date for the inquest or determined what
form it will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do a private inquest, which is what we normally do,''
Pareya said. ``If witnesses need to be called, I will have to go
into another phase. There would need to be a court reporter at that
point, and we would go into a more formal mode. Until I delve into
this more, see what (evidence) I have on hand, I don't know what
procedure I will set up.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's mother, Sandra Connizzo, has tried for years to
learn the circumstances surrounding her son's death.
</P>
<P>
   She's suspicious of the government's official explanation of
Schroeder's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they finally did pick up the body, the Rangers marked
things,'' Connizzo said. ``The FBI was telling them, 'Koresh is
threatening us. Hurry up. Let's get going.' I find that kind of
hard to believe. I'd like to hear the tape with that threat on it.
Then the FBI wouldn't let the Rangers on the site for another 10
days, until the rain had washed everything away. I'm sorry, but I
find that incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's report on Mount Carmel states that the
FBI's Jeffrey Jamar initially let the Rangers recover Schroeder's
body and perform a limited crime scene analysis. But when the
Rangers later asked permission to complete the crime scene search
by casting footprints and gathering other evidence, the report
concluded that ``Jamar refused to allow the request, and did not
allow them back onto the crime scene for ten days. By then, rain
had severely eroded the footprints they hoped to process.''
</P>
<P>
   Connizzo also wonders what happened to the felt cap worn by
Schroeder when he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the body arrived at the coroner's office, his hat was
missing,'' Connizzo said. ``Mike McNulty told me that he saw
Michael's hat and a stun gun in a bag labeled M. Schroeder.''
</P>
<P>
   McNulty, who helped produce the Oscar-nominated film, ``Waco:
Rules of Engagement,'' toured the Davidian evidence locker in
Austin last spring before U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr.
of Waco took custody of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hat worn by Schroeder was not tested, the autopsy
on Schroeder done by the Tarrant County Medical Examiner's Office
showed no signs of soot deposition, powder tattooing or a muzzle
imprint _ any of which would indicate a shooting at close range.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder is not the only Davidian whose cause of death is not
listed.
</P>
<P>
   However, authorities often did not have enough body parts in the
other cases to determine how the individual died. Pareya and three
other local justices were given the formidable job of sorting
through bodies mutilated by fire and the collapse of Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Besides trying to determine a cause of death, local JPs
struggled to identify the mingled remains of the Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us two years, through DNA testing and numerous
requests for information, to close out the majority of cases,''
Pareya said. ``It was a very difficult process to go through. I
would often be here at my office late at night calling foreign
countries trying to contact family members about pauper funerals. A
lot was going on. It was mind-boggling to a certain extent.''
</P>
<P>
   Pareya said his decision to officially close out the Schroeder
inquest isn't related to the renewed questioning of the
government's explanation of the events at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unfinished business that needs to be taken care of,''
Pareya said. ``I have to do it. It's what I was elected to do. It's
my duty. What is going on now will not play a role in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
