<SLUG> BC-R-BERKELEY-THANKSGIVING-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEZ ALICE WATERS, A REHEARSAL FOR THANKSGIVING
</HEADLINE>
  
 Resending to delete art note; there are NO photos with the story,
which moved Tuesday.) (Eds: 3rd take contains recipes. ) 
(nk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ The house is unremarkable, a modest gray
Craftsman bungalow on a shady side street a few blocks from the
University of California.
</P>
<P>
   You know, though, that a serious cook lives there the minute you
walk into the spacious, modern kitchen. Not that the room gleams
with marble and stainless steel like a designer's fantasy, or that
it's packed with gimmicks and gadgets, or that everything matches.
Utility is the hallmark here. A bright yellow La Cornue range
stands along one wall, and a big rectangular copper sink catches
the eye, but at heart, this is a kitchen made for cooking, not
looking.
</P>
<P>
   One Tuesday morning in early November, it was dressed for
autumn. Branches of red and orange and mottled yellow leaves filled
a handsome purple glass vase, along with blowsy Cafe au Lait
dahlias and yellow English Garden roses.
</P>
<P>
   The mistress of the house had laid out big bowls of pomegranates
and persimmons, walnuts and chestnuts, Ida Rose apples and Adriatic
figs and crab apples. Quinces, too, that someone had filched from
an old tree on a vacant lot nearby. A stalk of brussels sprouts lay
on the table, and a cabbage, a Platonic ideal of a cabbage, its
outer leaves unfurled into a sort of halo, sat on a metal stand.
</P>
<P>
   Food as still life, fit for a 17th-century Dutch master.
</P>
<P>
   An oak fire, lighted at 7 o'clock, had produced a fine bed of
coals beneath the plump hen turkey that was revolving on a stout
spit. Alice Waters (for it was she, in a long striped apron and
black chef's clogs) was rehearsing for Thanksgiving 1999, reaching
into the kitchen fireplace with a long branch of rosemary to baste
the browning bird with warm olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Why a rosemary branch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Ms. Waters replied. ``It's pretty, and it works
well, and it adds a bit of flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time I turned up to watch, along with my wife, Betsey,
two of Ms. Waters' longtime colleagues at Chez Panisse, the
influential Berkeley restaurant she has run since 1971, had joined
her. They were trimming vegetables with the short, sure strokes of
the professional that make amateurs like me so jealous. Both of
them _ Jean-Pierre Moulle, a bearded, soft-spoken native of the
Charente region in southwestern France, and Fritz Streiff, a
Harvard man who wears Philip Johnson glasses _ have helped her to
establish the restaurant's worldwide reputation for extraordinarily
fresh, organically grown raw materials, cooked simply and superbly
in a hybrid Italo-Franco-Californian style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first real day of fall,'' Moulle said. In the
backyard garden, pomelos and Meyer lemons still hung from the
trees, and exactly four raspberries fought against time on a bush
near the guest cottage, but there was a nip in the air that the
bright sunshine could not quite dispel.
</P>
<P>
   As they worked, the three cooks chatted about the provenance of
the ingredients that would go into Ms. Waters' Thanksgiving feast.
The unusually fine-leaved escarole and the fabulously peppery
watercress for the salad had been grown by Bob Cannard in the
Valley of the Moon in Sonoma County, northwest of Berkeley. The
sourdough bread had come, of course, from the Acme Bakery just a
few blocks away, one of the cluster of establishments that have
flourished here since the food revolution began 30-odd years ago.
The vegetables had come from various farmers' markets, and the
cranberries for the upside-down cake baked by the restaurant's
pastry chef, Charlene Reis, from the Ladybug Cooperative in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have, would have, should have made the cake, if I'd
had the time,'' volunteered Ms. Waters, an intense, pale-skinned
woman who was once a Montessori teacher. ``It's easy enough for
even me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The cranberries really slayed me. You have to be a bit of a
maniac to conceive of organic cranberries, let alone find them, and
Ms. Waters pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you go to extremes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has gone so far as to hire a forager, Alan Tangren, who
searches not only for wild nettles and the like in back yards, but
also for unlikely suppliers like the Ladybug Co-Op.
</P>
<P>
   What about the turkey? I asked.
</P>
<P>
   Blank looks. Eager to give credit to all her suppliers, as she
always does on Chez Panisse's menus, Ms. Waters made an urgent
telephone call to the restaurant. It turned out that Ms. Turkey, a
13-pounder, had been raised on the Diestel Ranch, a small farm on
the outskirts of Sonora, a town not far from Yosemite National
Park. The bird had grown up, Ms. Waters emphasized, not in a cage,
but free to roam, eating grass and other vegetation innocent of
pesticides, herbicides and artificial fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
   Using a method she developed several years ago, Ms. Waters
soaked the turkey for 72 hours in a well-seasoned brine before
cooking it. Doing so, she said, helps keep the bird moist, and when
we tucked into it later, it was a juicy revelation. Even the
thinnest slices of white meat held together without crumbling,
which is more than you can say for most of the turkeys I have
cooked (or eaten) in the last few centuries. The marination also
added subtle overtones of herby, spicy flavor to a bird that, let's
face it, can taste bland as blancmange.
</P>
<P>
   The turkey was stuffed with a mixture of bread, herbs and wild
mushrooms, chiefly golden chanterelles. Chanterelle stems, a few
chestnuts, poultry stock and the turkey giblets went into a silky
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works perfectly in an oven,'' Ms. Waters said, ``but I'd
rather cook over a fire when I can. I have a fascination with fires
_ the flavors, the aromas, the primal quality of the process. I'm a
rotisseuse at heart. Some people can make sauces. They're
comfortable at the stove, but this is me, here, in front of the
flames, roasting.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Moulle, a keen hunter, suggested that the brining method would
be especially well suited to wild turkey, which is even more prone
to desiccation during conventional cooking than domesticated birds.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, Moulle and his wife, Denise, and a dozen or so
others assemble for Thanksgiving with Ms. Waters at the house of
Jay and Pam Heminway, her longtime friends, which is set amidst
mountain vineyards in the Chiles Valley, northwest of the Napa. But
the Moulles will miss this year's celebration. It will take place a
continent away, at the Heminways' house in Watch Hill, R.I., so
that Ms. Waters can be with her daughter, Fanny, 16, who is
attending the Mountain School at Vershire, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the change of venue, Ms. Waters said, would
be East Coast oysters, which she prefers to those of the West
Coast. Some other ingredients, she said, she would take with her
from Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving has always been a big deal for Ms. Waters, and it
has always involved a big crowd. Growing up in Chatham, N.J., she
recalled, ``that was the one time of the year when my parents had a
big party'' _ the one time they put all the leaves in the table and
asked 15 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the year, my mother never made real desserts, like
pumpkin pie,'' she said. ``The rest of the year it was fruit
cups.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Always friends' wines on holidays,'' Ms. Waters said as we
started our early Thanksgiving meal with a cool glass of Chateau La
Louviere 1990, a white Bordeaux made by Mrs. Moulle's father, Andre
Lurton. Later on, with the turkey, we _ the cooks, Mrs. Moulle and
the two of us _ drank a bottle of the Heminways' lean Red and Green
Vineyards zinfandel 1998, rather reminiscent of Tuscany, and
Lurton's Chateau Dauzac 1985, a fifth-growth Margaux. A bottle of
Dauzac 1978 materialized with the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody went to the table for the first course. In the European
manner, it was the most luxurious part of the meal. We stood around
or sat on kitchen stools to nibble on four kinds of oysters,
freshly opened and set atop a mound of shaved ice and seaweed _
Wellfleets from Cape Cod and Kumamotos, Hog Islands and
thumbnail-size Olympias from the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   With those came pork sausages, purposely made with little
seasoning other than a bit of white wine, so their blandness would
contrast with the coppery, briny taste of the oysters. The
combination is traditional not only in France but also in
Tidewater, Va., as my wife reminded me.
</P>
<P>
   Then came slices of a terrine of foie gras, made by Moulle from
Sonoma County duck livers and served on slices of sourdough toast
hot from a grill in the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   And then came bagna cauda, an Italian dip for raw vegetables
that is also served in Provence. It is made from olive oil, garlic
and anchovies pounded in a mortar, and the anchovies, packed in
salt in Sicily in a big round can, provided the morning's only
crisis, however transitory.
</P>
<P>
   Cans are uncommon denizens of Ms. Waters' kitchen, and Streiff,
one of Ms. Waters' collaborators on the new ``Chez Panisse Cafe
Cookbook'' (HarperCollins, $34), could not for the life of him find
an opener. Neither could Moulle. But Ms. Waters rummaged around on
a shelf and came up with one, an ancient lever-action model, rusty
but serviceable.
</P>
<P>
   The vegetable plate that accompanied the bagna cauda won the
prize, everyone agreed, for sheer good looks _ purple radishes,
deep red and light green radicchio, scarlet strips of bell pepper,
brilliant orange carrot curls, and paler celery, turnips and
artichoke hearts. The sauce tasted even better, I thought, sopped
up with a chunk of an Acme Bakery baguette.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours, the turkey was done, its ivory skin now
richly dappled.
</P>
<P>
   While it rested for a few minutes, the three cooks applied the
finishing touches to the vegetables, taking care, as they had all
day, to drop small scraps into a plastic pail for composting and
bigger leftovers into a basket, to be taken to the restaurant for
use in the stockpot.
</P>
<P>
   The striking thing about the whole meal was the absence of sugar
and cream, which are omnipresent in many Thanksgiving dinners. Even
the cranberry cake was tart-sweet, unlike pecan or pumpkin pie.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sweet potatoes, Ms. Waters served a puree of potatoes
and parsnips, boiled separately, then mashed together with a little
milk and very little butter. The other vegetable, braised fennel,
was prepared in an equally straightforward, equally satisfying way:
the fennel bulbs, cut into pieces, were stewed in a little water
and olive oil, and the feathery tops, chopped, were stirred in at
the last minute as a flavor-booster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like desserts with a little bit of a tart edge,'' she said.
``Richness is not what it's about. Cream overwhelms the taste of
vegetables, so I like to cook them in olive oil, the way the
Italians do, braising and stewing to bring out the vegetables' own
flavor. This isn't a health issue. It's a flavor issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The oval table in front of the kitchen fireplace table was set
in a minute or two with big, utilitarian napkins, sturdy cutlery,
pretty Deruta plates and a pair of well-worn brass candlesticks. A
food stylist might not have approved, but we eager eaters thought
it looked just right.
</P>
<P>
   Streiff popped a new disk of Vivaldi songs by Cecilia Bartoli
onto the stereo, and we went to work on our meal. The soprano's
swooping vocal line prompted talk of opera at Salzburg, the
director Peter Sellers, the Telluride Film Festival in Colorado,
the Adelaide festival in Australia and, somehow, eating in Naples.
</P>
<P>
   By then we had reached the salad, a great pile of airy greens on
each diner's plate, the dressing light but garlicky.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese _ a whole-milk Vacherin from the Jura, whose peak
season happily coincides with Thanksgiving _ came with music from
the Russian soprano Edita Gruberova. Last, the cake _ slim little
pieces, not much room left _ and glasses of tea made from spearmint
from the garden.
</P>
<P>
   None of us could have asked for a more delicious or more
celebratory holiday meal, and I got up from the table, I must
confess, feeling a great deal less laden than I usually do on the
final Thursday in November.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BRINE-CURED ROAST TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Alice Waters
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4 hours and 15 minutes, plus 72 hours for brining  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   } cup plus 2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   } cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup diced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 leek, white and light green parts only, cleaned and diced
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 star anise
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 12- to 14-pound naturally fed, free-range turkey
</P>
<P>
   Wild Mushroom Stuffing (see recipe) or other stuffing
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil or butter
</P>
<P>
   Fresh rosemary branches, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. In 16-quart or larger stockpot, bring 2 gallons water to a
boil. Add salt and sugar, and stir until completely dissolved. Turn
off heat, and add carrot, onion, celery and leek. Add bay leaves,
peppercorns, coriander, red pepper, fennel seeds, star anise and
thyme. Refrigerate until cold.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove giblets from turkey. Cover and refrigerate liver if
using in stuffing. Discard remaining giblets or reserve for another
use. Add turkey to stockpot. If necessary, weight it with a plate
so that it stays below the brine's surface. Refrigerate for 72
hours, then remove from brine and allow to come to room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Loosely fill the turkey at both
ends with stuffing, and truss as you would a chicken.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place turkey in a large roasting pan, and roast until it
starts to brown, about 25 minutes. Reduce oven setting to 350
degrees, and roast for 12 minutes more per pound, until internal
temperature at deepest part of the leg reaches 130 degrees. (Total
roasting time will be about 3 hours.) Baste frequently with olive
oil or butter and pan juices, using rosemary branches as a brush if
desired. If the bird begins to darken too much, cover it loosely
with a piece of foil. Before serving, remove turkey from oven and
leave covered with foil. Allow it to rest for 20 minutes before
carving and spooning the stuffing into a serving dish. Yield: 15
servings.
</P>
<P>
   WILD MUSHROOM STUFFING
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound chanterelles
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, peeled and finely diced
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   \ pound smoked bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 turkey or chicken liver, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 day-old baguette, crust removed, to make 4 cups cubed
</P>
<P>
   3 cups milk, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 lightly beaten egg, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   1. Clean mushrooms and cut them in half crosswise. In a large
skillet over medium heat, melt 2 tablespoons butter, and add
shallots and \ of the garlic. Saute until softened, about 2
minutes. Add mushrooms, and season with salt and pepper to taste.
Saute until mushrooms are softened, about 8 minutes. Chop coarsely,
and transfer to a large mixing bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. In the same skillet, melt remaining butter. Add the onions
and the remaining garlic. Saute until softened, about 3 minutes.
Season with salt and pepper to taste, and add to the bowl of
mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   3. Return skillet to medium heat, and add bacon. Cook until
crisp, then remove bacon (discard or save for another purpose),
saving fat. Add diced liver to pan, and saute over medium heat
until browned, about 2 minutes. Drain well, season with salt and
pepper to taste, and add to mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a large mixing bowl, combine bread cubes and enough milk
to saturate them. Drain bread, squeezing gently. Add to mushrooms,
and mix gently. Add herbs and mix again. If desired, add egg to
bind stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: Enough for a 12 to 14 pound turkey.
</P>
<P>
   PARSNIP AND POTATO PUREE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   10 all-purpose potatoes, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   8 medium parsnips, peeled and cut into equal-size chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 quart milk
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, or as desired
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place potatoes in large saucepan and cover with cold water.
Bring to a boil over high heat, then reduce to a simmer and cook
until very tender, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, place parsnips in a medium saucepan and cover with
a mixture of half water and half milk. Bring to a boil, reduce
heat, and simmer until tender, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Drain potatoes and parsnips well, and immediately combine in
the large saucepan. In a small saucepan, heat about 1 cup milk
until warm. Mash potatoes and parsnips together until smooth,
thinning to taste with warm milk. Season with butter, salt, and
pepper to taste. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   STEWED FENNEL
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 large fennel bulbs including feathery fronds on top (or
substitute \ cup chervil leaves for the fronds)
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fennel seed, finely ground in a spice grinder or
with a mortar and pestle
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   1. Clean and trim fennel bulbs, cutting off fronds. Wash and
finely chop fronds, and set aside. Cut bulbs into eighths, and
place in a medium saucepan. Add olive oil and 1{ cups water.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cover pan and bring to a boil over high heat, then
immediately reduce heat to medium. Stir fennel, cover, and stew for
5 minutes. Add chopped fennel fronds, ground fennel seed, red
pepper flakes, and salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir mixture, and raise heat to medium-high. Cook, covered,
until liquid has nearly evaporated and fennel is thoroughly cooked
and soft, about 10 more minutes. (If necessary, simmer uncovered
for a few minutes to reduce liquid.) Remove pan from heat and add
lemon juice. Toss to mix well. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
