<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-YEAR-BY-YEAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 YEARS OF AMERICAN FOOD TIMELINE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Package includes MILLENNIUM-MAIN and 4 takes of recipes
MILLENNIUM-RECIPES) 
By CAROL BIDWELL AND NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy, have we come a long way where food's concerned in the last
100 years _ and it's been a delicious and fun-filled journey. At
the outset of the 20th century, getting meals on the table was hard
work. There were no refrigerators, toasters, or gas or electric
ranges. Gadgets and appliances like stand mixers, blenders and food
processors were nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Buying groceries was a time-consuming effort, offering consumers
little choice. Canned, frozen and convenience foods gradually began
to appear. New types of eateries _ including the cafeteria, soda
fountain and fast-food establishments _ offered quicker, more
accessible and less expensive options for eating out.
</P>
<P>
   Self-service grocery stores and giant supermarkets were born.
And the culinary scene exploded with new foods, restaurants and
more.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that Americans greeted each new advance _ from
the introduction of packaged cake and pudding mixes to microwave
ovens and bread machines _ with great enthusiasm?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a listing of some of the products, gadgets and (we've
come to believe) necessities that have helped make our lives in the
kitchen easier over the past century. Some may take you down memory
lane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1900 _ Hershey manufactures a milk chocolate bar. Wesson oil
debuts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1901 _ Instant coffee is invented. ``The Settlement Cookbook'' by
Lizzie Black Kander published.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1902 _ Fannie Farmer opens her cooking school in Boston. Karo syrup
goes on sale. The Pepsi-Cola Co. is founded. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1903 _ A San Pedro, Calif., packer puts tuna fish in cans for the
first time. Milton Hershey builds a chocolate factory in Derry
Church, Pa., which will be renamed Hershey in 1906. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1904 _ The St. Louis World's Fair in St. Louis, Mo., introduces
hamburgers and hot dogs on rolls, ice cream in waffle cones,
popcorn and peanut butter. French's mustard is introduced.
Campbell's introduces canned pork and beans. Tea merchant Thomas
Sullivan invents tea bags. Dr Pepper debuts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1905 _ America's first pizzeria opens in New York's Little Italy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1906 _ Kellogg's Corn Flakes hit market shelves. U.S. Pure Food and
Drug Act passes. The hot fudge sundae is created at C.C. Brown's
ice cream parlor in Hollywood. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1907 _ Hershey's Kisses introduced. Minnesota Valley Canning Co. in
Le Sueur packs peas and corn in cans. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1908 _ Post Toasties cornflakes are introduced. The first cafeteria
opens in Los Angeles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1909 _ Quaker sells puffed rice cereal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1910 _ Hydrox Biscuit Bon Bons hit store shelves, later known as
Hydrox cookies. The first homes are marketed with built-in kitchen
cabinets. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1911 _ William Gebhardt markets the first canned chili and tamales.
Crisco is introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1912 _ First self-service grocery stores open in California. Life
Savers candy appears. Nabisco introduces Oreo Cream Sandwiches to
compete with Hydrox Bon Bons. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1914 _ First electric refrigerator introduced for commercial use.
Reuben sandwich created at Reuben's Restaurant in New York City. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1915 _ Corning introduces Pyrex. Processed cheese introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1916 _ Piggy-Wiggly opens in Memphis, Tenn., and becomes the first
supermarket chain. Fortune cookie invented. Nathan's hot dog stand
opened at Coney Island, N.Y. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1918 _ Canned tomato sauce is introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1919 _ KitchenAid introduces the first stand mixer for the home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1920 _ Prohibition begins. Home winemaking takes off. Candy lovers
could buy Oh Henry! and Baby Ruth. Wonder bread introduced. La Choy
Food Products started in Detroit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1921 _ Stainless steel flatware introduced. First White Castle
burger stand opens in Wichita, Kan. Eskimo Pie is introduced.
Quaker markets quick-cooking oats. Betty Crocker, a figurehead, is
created by the company that would later become General Mills.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1923 _ Milky Way candy bar introduced, along with Reese's Peanut
Butter Cups, Yoo-Hoo chocolate drink, and Welch's grape jelly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1924 _ Tijuana restaurateur Caesar Cardini invents the Caesar
Salad. The Popsicle is patented. Wheaties introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1925 _ The paper napkin and Mr. Goodbar are introduced. The Brown
Derby restaurant opens in Los Angeles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1926 _ Toastmaster automatic toaster first available for home use.
Brown Derby owner Bob Cobb creates the Cobb Salad to use up
leftovers. Hormel cans its first hams. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1927_ Kool-Aid is first sold. Milk is homogenized. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1928 _ Butterfinger candy bars, Peter Pan Peanut Butter and Rice
Krispies cereal introduced. Kraft makes Velveeta cheese available.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1929 _ Coin-operated vending machine patented. 7-Up goes on sale.
Gerber's debuts canned baby food. Oscar Mayer Wieners introduced.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1930 _ First presliced bread is sold. Jiffy biscuit mix, Twinkies
packaged cakes and Snickers candy bars debut. Birdseye introduces
frozen food. Better Homes &AMP; Gardens produces its first cookbook.
Electric stoves appear. Ruth Wakefield invents the chocolate chip
cookie at her historic Toll House Inn in Massachusetts.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1931 _ Bisquick biscuit mix introduced. ``The Joy of Cooking'' by
Erma Rombauer first published.  &QL; 
1932 _ Campbell's introduces canned tomato soup.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1933 _ Eighteenth Amendment _ Prohibition _ repealed. Ernest and
Julio Gallo go into wine business and start the E. and J. Gallo
winery in Modesto, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1934 _ The Ritz Cracker is introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1935 _ Pepperidge Farm bread is introduced. Pan Am serves the first
hot in-flight meals. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1936 _ Commercially baked Girl Scout cookies go on sale for 25
cents a box. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1937 _ Spam is introduced. Waring Blendor marketed as bartender's
tool. Kraft Macaroni &AMP; Cheese Dinner rolls out on supermarket
shelves. First shopping carts in use.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1938 _ Victor Bergeron opens the first Trader Vic's restaurant in
Oakland, Calif. featuring Polynesian food and potent rum drinks.
Teflon is discovered. Revere Ware with copper bottoms introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1939 _ Nestle Toll House Morsels become available. U.S. Department
of Agriculture introduces first food stamp program to feed the
needy. First Dairy Queen opens in Joliet, Ill.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1940 _ Dick and Mac McDonald open the first McDonald's in San
Bernardino, Calif. James Beard's first cookbook, ``Hors d'Oeuvres
and Canapes,'' appears. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1941 _ Gourmet magazine debuts. M&AMP;Ms candies introduced. General
Electric introduces the garbage disposal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1942 _ Food rationing begins. Dannon yogurt debuts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1943 _ First deep-dish pizza created at Pizzeria Uno in Chicago.
Recommended Daily Allowances of various nutrients first published. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1944 _ Chiquita bananas are marketed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1945 _ Food rationing ends for all items except sugar. Earl W.
Tupper invents resealable food containers. Cheerios shows up on
store shelves. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1946 _ Frozen french fries and orange juice are introduced, along
with instant mashed potatoes. The Culinary Institute of America
opens in Connecticut and later moves to New York. James Beard hosts
``I Love to Eat,'' America's first television cooking show. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1947 _ Reynolds Metal Co. markets aluminum foil to the public.
Raytheon introduces the Radarange, though the first microwave oven
isn't marketed to the public until the late '50s. Reddi-Whip, the
first major aerosol food product, debuts. Betty Crocker and
Pillsbury launch the first cake mixes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1948 _ Nestle introduces instant tea.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1949 _ First Sara Lee cheesecake sold. First Pillsbury Bake-Off
Contest is staged in the ballroom at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in
New York; grand prize was $50,000. KitchenAid develops the first
electric dishwasher. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1950 _ First Jack-in-the-Box opens in San Diego, and Dunkin' Donuts
opens in Quincy, Mass. Minute Rice is introduced, along with Kraft
presliced cheese, Rice Chex, Sugar Pops and Wheat Chex cereals.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1951 _ Glen Bell opens the first Taco Bell in San Bernardino,
Calif. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1952 _ Col. Harlan Sanders sells the first Kentucky Fried Chicken
franchise. Lipton markets dry onion soup mix and California Dip is
born. Dow introduces Saran Wrap. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1953 _ First refrigerated bread dough marketed. Eggo frozen waffles
introduced, along with Cheez Whiz. Presto develops the electric
skillet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1954 _ Swanson introduces the TV dinner. Butterball debuts the
first self-basting frozen turkey.The first Burger King opens in
Miami. M&AMP;Ms peanut candies appear. Nonfat dry milk is introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1956 _ The electric can opener is invented. The U.S. Department of
Agriculture formulates the four basic food groups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1957 _ Pam cooking spray patent issued. Sweet 'n Low debuts.
Williams-Sonoma opens in San Francisco. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1958 _ The Delaney Clause, added to the Pure Food and Drug Act,
bans the addition of any carcinogen to food. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1959 _ Haagen-Dazs is introduced, along with Rice-a-Roni and Jif
Peanut Butter, Cocoa Krispies, Cocoa Puffs and Corn Chex cereals.
The Four Seasons restaurant opens in New York. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1960 _ Peg Bracken's ``I Hate to Cook Book'' is published. Aluminum
cans first used for food and drinks. Salton's electric Hotray
becomes the appliance rage. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1961 _ ``Mastering the Art of French Cooking,'' by Julia Child,
Simone Beck and Louisette Bertholle is published. Ray Kroc buys
McDonald's, initiates many innovations, and the establishment is on
the way to becoming a leader in the fast-food business. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1962 _ The pop-top can debuts along with frozen pie crust. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1963 _ ``The French Chef'' with Julia Child hits the air on WGBH-TV
in Cambridge and is syndicated to 60 other cities. Weight Watchers
is founded. General Electric develops the self-cleaning oven. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1964 _ Buffalo Chicken Wings invented at the Anchor Bar in Buffalo,
N.Y. Pop-Tarts, nachos and Carnation Instant Breakfast are
introduced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1965 _ Cool Whip and Shake 'n' Bake debut. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1966 _ Catholics are permitted to eat meat on Fridays. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1967 _ Compact microwave ovens introduced. Gatorade appears on
store shelves, along with Lawry's Taco Seasoning. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1969 _ Whirlpool unveils the first home trash compactor. Pringles
potato chips debut. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1970 _ New on store shelves: Hamburger Helper, Orville
Redenbacher's Gourmet Popping Corn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1971 _ Alice Waters opens Chez Panisse restaurant in Berkeley,
pioneering California cuisine. The first Starbucks opens in
Seattle. Rival trademarks the Crock-Pot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1972 _ Sicilian-born Piero Selvaggio opens Valentino in Santa
Monica. Frozen yogurt is introduced. Mr. Coffee debuts along with
Snapple fruit juices. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1973 _ The Cuisinart Food Processor is introduced. The U.S. Food
and Drug Administration implements the first food package labeling
regulations. Universal Product Codes begin to appear on food
packages.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1974 _ The first supermarket scanners are installed. Miller
introduces Miller Lite, the first light beer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1975 _ ``The Doubleday Cookbook'' is published, complete with
calorie counts for the first time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1977 _ Dean &AMP; DeLuca and the Silver Palate specialty-food stores
open in New York City. Debbie Fields opens the first Mrs. Fields
cookie shop. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1978 _ Food &AMP; Wine and Cuisine magazines debut. Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice
cream premieres in Vermont. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1979 _ First Zagat Restaurant Survey appears in New York. Paul
Prudhomme opens K-Paul Louisiana Kitchen in New Orleans and the
cajun craze takes off. Michael's restaurant opens in Santa Monica.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1980 _ Tofu appears in U.S. supermarkets along with Fruit
Roll-Ups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1981 _ FDA approves aspartame as an artificial sweetener.
Stouffer's introduces Lean Cuisine dinners and entrees. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1982 _ Chef Wolfgang Puck opens Spago on Sunset Boulevard in West
Hollywood with an open kitchen offering sophisticated cuisine and
service in a casual setting. Actor Paul Newman founds Newman's Own
food company. Scramblers (egg substitute) become available for
cholesterol-watchers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1984 _ Hidden Valley introduces ranch dressing in packets. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1985 _ Americans are outraged when Coca-Cola changes its
99-year-old formula and the company brings back Classic Coke. Union
Square Cafe opens in New York. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1987 _ Cooking Light magazine debuts. Nestle introduces Alpine
White, America's first white chocolate bar. Matsuhisa in Beverly
Hills opens.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1988 _ Boboli pizza crusts make assembling a homemade pizza easy
work. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1990 _ FDA issues new Dietary Guidelines for Americans and adopts
the Food Guide Pyramid, doing away with the four food groups in
favor of a pyramid-shaped eating plan that emphasizes grains and
vegetables and limits meat and fats. Jamba Juice bars open in
California. Eating Well magazine debuts.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1993 _ The Food Network, the first 24-hour food TV channel, debuts.
SnackWells introduces low-fat cookies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1995 _ Pillsbury increases the Bake-Off grand prize to $1 million.
DiGiorno Rising Crust pizza debuts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1996 _ Betty Crocker has a new face, a composite of 75 women. The
FDA approves Procter &AMP; Gamble's Olestra fat substitute for use in
snack foods. Lay's introduces baked potato chips. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1997 _ The FDA approves irradiation of meat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1998 _ Jell-O, celebrating its 101st year on store shelves, opens
the Jell-O Museum in Rochester, N.Y. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1999 _ Sales of premium champagnes soar as Americans prepare to
toast the new millennium. &QL; 
___
</P>
