<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore wedges stump issues into Atlanta visit
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It wasn't an official campaign speech, but Vice
President Al Gore hit all his key themes anyway in a brief stop in
Atlanta on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription coverage for the elderly on Medicare. Health care
insurance for all U.S. children. A woman's right to choose
abortion. More teachers for more schools. Stronger penalties for
hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 5,000 international delegates to the United Jewish
Communities General Assembly meeting at the Atlanta Civic Center
applauded Gore's positions on those issues almost as strongly as
they did his unwavering support for Israel and the ``hopeful but
fragile'' Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's 35-minute address to the gathering was part of his vice
presidential duties, and he never once mentioned former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley, his rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination who was in town for a Georgia fund-raiser and a meeting
with Jewish leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's speech _ apart from a laugh-evoking top four list of
Jewish country-western songs _ was one that could have fit on
almost any stump in America.
</P>
<P>
   Laced with biographical sketches stressing his family's emphasis
on education and commitment to civil rights, Gore reached out to
Jewish leaders, underscoring that their values are very similar to
his.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to fight to enhance penalties for hate crimes, a key
issue for Jewish groups, and said the Senate ought to reconsider
and ratify the nuclear test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish leaders, like those gathered in Atlanta to try to unite
Jews throughout the world, can help push those policies, Gore said.
``I see things happening in our country right now that make me
believe this gathering can have a decisive voice in embodying our
values in our laws.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
