<HEADER>
A3103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-OIL-PRICES-ART-6     11-17 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-OIL-PRICES-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUDE OIL CLOSES ABOVE $25, THE HIGHEST LEVEL IN 3 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of oil Wednesday topped $26 a barrel, the highest
level in almost three years. If it climbs just a few more pennies,
it will be the highest since the Persian Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of other important commodities _ from copper and
lumber to tin and hogs _ are also rising. In fact, commodity prices
are now on track to show their first combined gain since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after a sharp three-year decline that helped keep
inflation in check, the increases do not present an inflationary
threat yet, in part because commodities _ other than oil _ are a
small component in the Consumer Price Index. In addition, the
rising cost of industrial metals, like copper and tin, have been
somewhat offset by falling prices for agricultural products, like
soybeans and wheat.
</P>
<P>
   But oil, especially in the form of gasoline, is helping push
consumer prices modestly higher. For the 12 months through October,
the Consumer Price Index is up 2.6 percent. If oil prices had held
steady, the index would be up 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that energy is up a ton,'' said Robert J.
Barbera, chief economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. in Rye Brook, N.Y. But
because the market rally has not pushed consumer prices markedly
higher, people are comfortable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors and Wall Street analysts are focusing less on the
total index and more on the core inflation rate, which excludes
food and all energy costs. In the last year, the core rate has
risen 2.1 percent, compared with a climb of 2.4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The direction of commodity prices depends heavily on OPEC's
actions, the rebound of the world economy and the weather. But
William Byers, director of futures research at Bear Stearns &AMP; Co.,
predicted that ``this rise in commodity prices is probably going to
flatten out.''
</P>
<P>
   A cutback in oil production that OPEC members agreed to in March
has been the major reason for rising prices. So far this year, the
price of the near-term futures contract traded on the New York
Mercantile Exchange has jumped 120.7 percent to $26.60 a barrel.
That is just two cents below the recent high of $26.62 on Jan. 8,
1997. And if that high-water mark is breached, oil will be at its
highest since it began falling from $32 a barrel in January 1991,
just after the American and allied success in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the rally stopped with oil just short of $25 a
barrel, and the price slipped to $20.90. But the rise has resumed
in recent weeks as confidence has grown that members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would extend their
production cuts beyond March 2000, the end of their one-year pact.
</P>
<P>
   Several OPEC members said this week that there was already an
agreement to extend the production cuts beyond March. But oil
ministers from Saudia Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico, who met
Wednesday, asked only for a commitment to the planned production
cuts through March. They did not commit to an extension.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the rally was a report by the American Petroleum
Institute after the close of the market on Tuesday. It showed that
inventories dropped 2.49 million barrels last week to 308.97
million, a bigger drop than expected, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rothman, the senior energy analyst at Merrill Lynch who
has attended OPEC meetings since 1986, suggested in a note to
clients on Monday that OPEC may have changed its thinking about
``what's too high an oil price.'' The threshold is now near $30,
instead of $25, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But OPEC does not want the price to stay at $30, he said,
reiterating his forecast of a price decline later next year.
Economists at Merrill Lynch said that the higher oil price would
not have a significant impact on either economic growth or
inflation, he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Along with crude oil, gasoline and heating oil have led the rise
in commodity futures prices this year. The price for the near-term
unleaded gasoline contract traded on the New York Mercantile
Exchange is up 105.6 percent to 73.40 cents a gallon this year. The
price of heating oil has jumped 102.1 percent to 68.73 cents a
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The rising prices of industrial metals is a sign that the
economies that suffered during the global financial crisis that
began in July 1997 are turning around. If prices continue to rise,
they will spur economic growth in the countries that rely heavily
on the sale of commodities. Asia's potential is enormous. South
Korea, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines and Thailand, where the
economic pains were greatest, accounted for about a quarter of the
growth in demand for copper from 1992 through 1996 before the
crisis began, according to the International Monetary Fund. Metals
are also being bolstered by an economic turnaround in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the gains in those prices are small compared with those in
energy. The near-term copper future, traded on the Commodity
Exchange, is up 18 percent this year to 78.30 cents a pound. Last
year the price of copper fell 13.7 percent. The Journal of Commerce
index of industrial commodities, which includes oil, tin, copper,
lead, rubber, hides and other products, has climbed 6.2 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural prices continue to be weak overall. Hog prices are
up sharply, with pork belly futures up 73.7 percent. But that is
from lows last year that forced some farmers to shoot their pigs in
the pen rather than bring them to market. And some grains are off
sharply. Soybean prices are down 29.3 percent, while wheat is down
11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that industrial metals are the only place where you
can extrapolate a trend for higher prices,'' said Byers of Bear
Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Barbera of Hoenig &AMP; Co. said he did not expect Federal Reserve
policy makers to worry about a modest rise there as long as it was
driven by growth in the rest of the world while the American
economy slowed down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
