<HEADER>
A3104 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-TURKEY-HOW-TO-LADN 2takes &LR;    11-17 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-HOW-TO-LADN, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING ON THE BIRD
</HEADLINE>
 2 takes  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: note 3-column chart below ...) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's your turn to host the Thanksgiving feast this year, and
that means orchestrating the meal and cooking the turkey. Don't
panic. While the big bird can appear intimidating _ especially if
you're a novice _ it's really not difficult. Once you learn the
ABCs, you'll find it as easy as 1-2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Food experts and professionals have varying opinions and
theories about the the best way to roast the bird. Some favor
breast side up, others breast side down. And some cooks even
recommend turning the turkey during roasting, which can be awkward
and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   While some cooks like to stuff the bird (it wouldn't be a
traditional Thanksgiving without the stuffing cooked inside the
turkey), for safety reasons food professionals don't. The same goes
for basting _ some favor doing it often during roasting (which
really isn't necessary as it doesn't penetrate the skin much) while
other cooks just oil the skin, shove the turkey in the oven and
forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook authors vary on temperature preferences. Some prefer
low, slow-cooking. Others like hot, high temperatures for roasting
the bird. And the middle-of-the-roaders like combinations thereof.
But the experts at the United States Department of Agriculture's
Meat and Poultry Hotline and the Butterball Turkey Talk-Line
recommend a steady 325 degrees F for safety's sake and optimum
results.
</P>
<P>
   Without fail, every holiday finds someone whose frozen turkey
still hasn't fully thawed or someone panicked about doing things
just right, said Diane Van, supervisor of the USDA's hotline.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just want to make cooking the turkey complicated,''
said Jean Schnelle, director of the Illinois-based Butterball
Turkey Talk-Line, which has 48 home economists on staff this year
to answer the 200,000 consumer calls usually received this month
and next.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot to do with traditions, expectations and standards
people set for themselves,'' Schnelle said. ``You have memories of
past Thanksgivings, and they all seemed wonderful and perfect. And
if it's your turn to host Thanksgiving, you want to meet those
standards and expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she emphasized, the fuss over cooking the picture-perfect
turkey is really much ado about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing about cooking the turkey is that you
don't perceive it as such a major hassle. Relax! Cooking the turkey
is the easiest part of the Thanksgiving dinner,'' Schnelle said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Butterball hotline started in 1981, most callers wanted
help to achieve the perfectly moist, nicely golden brown turkey.
Today, food safety questions top the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not used to thawing out something so big _ and it
always takes longer than anyone expects,'' said Schnelle, noting
that the company has expanded thawing time recommendations because
complaints kept growing. ``Our observation is that glass shelves in
new refrigerators are slowing down the thawing _ due to less
circulation. Also, a full refrigerator is less effective in thawing
quickly as there is less air circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   An 18-pound bird takes at least four days to thaw in the fridge.
And it can be completely thawed up to a day or two ahead of
roasting, which means you could put a frozen turkey in the fridge
up to six days ahead of roasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkeys do not take as long to cook as people perceive they do
_ and that's a major mistake people also make,'' added Schnelle.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a run-down of answers to common questions tackled on both
the USDA's and Butterball's hot lines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PRELIMINARIES
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should I buy a fresh turkey or a frozen turkey?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although opinions vary regarding this matter, there is no
significant difference in quality between a fresh and a frozen
turkey, according to Van at the USDA hot line. Mostly, the choice
depends on when you plan to shop (last minute or several days in
advance) and if you have sufficient space to store and thaw a
frozen turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long can a fresh turkey be stored in a home refrigerator?
</P>
<P>
   A: No longer than two days. Some fresh turkeys are labeled with
pull dates, so check the label on the turkey when you buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I estimate how big a turkey I'll need to feed the
crowd I'm serving?
</P>
<P>
   A: Figure on 1 to 1 1/2 pounds of turkey per person _ more if
you have hearty eaters or desire leftovers. If you know that more
guests will prefer dark meat than white, consider buying extra
parts and roasting in a separate pan. Be sure your oven is large
enough for the size turkey you'll be buying. In some instances, it
may be best to buy two smaller birds and roast them side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should I buy a hen or a tom?
</P>
<P>
   A: The sex designation of hen (female up to 16 pounds) and tom
(male larger than 16 pounds) is optional on the label and is an
indication of size rather than tenderness. There is no significant
quality difference, said Van.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there anything I should look for on the label when I buy a
turkey?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Look for the inspection mark that lets you know the
turkey has been inspected by USDA's Food Safety and Inspection
Service for wholesomeness and accurate labeling. Also look for a
USDA grade symbol; most are marketed grade A today.
</P>
<P>
   A turkey label marked ``fresh'' means it has been stored at a
temperature no lower than 26 degree F. A ``frozen'' label indicates
the turkey must be stored at 0 degrees F or below. ``Basted'' or
``self-basted'' means the turkey has been injected with a solution
(3 to 8 percent allowed) containing edible fat, broth, stock, or
water, plus spices and other approved substances. ``Natural'' means
the turkey contains no artificial flavors, colors, chemical
preservatives, etc. and is minimally processed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've had a turkey in my freezer for nine months. Is it OK to
use?
</P>
<P>
   A: At 0 degrees F or below, a frozen turkey will keep for up to
one year without appreciable loss of quality and flavor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THAWING
</P>
<P>
   Q: How should I thaw the turkey?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are three options.
</P>
<P>
   In the refrigerator, place the wrapped frozen turkey on a tray
or in a pan lined with paper towels (to catch moisture that
accumulates as it thaws), allowing 24 hours for every 5 pounds of
turkey. A 12-pound turkey, for example, would take two to two and a
half days to thaw. The thawed turkey can remain in the refrigerator
up to two days prior to cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Using cold water is another thawing method. It's faster than
refrigerator thawing, but requires more attention. Place wrapped
turkey (if there are any leaks in packaging, place in a clean
plastic food bag and secure) in a sink of cold tap water, changing
water the every 30 minutes. Allow about 30 minutes per pound of
turkey for complete thawing. A 12-pound turkey, in this case, would
take about six hours to thaw.
</P>
<P>
   It's feasible to thaw a turkey of 12 pounds or less in the
microwave oven on the defrost cycle, turning often. However, it's
necessary to cook the turkey, unstuffed, immediately after thawing,
either in the microwave or a conventional oven because some areas
of the turkey may become warm and begin to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My friend thaws her frozen turkey on the counter at room
temperature? Is it safe?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. NEVER thaw a turkey at room temperature or in warm water.
Bacteria multiply rapidly at room temperature and in the hours it
takes for a turkey to thaw, the surface bacteria could multiply to
dangerous levels. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROASTING
</P>
<P>
   Q: Once thawed, how do I prepare the turkey for roasting?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unwrap the turkey and remove giblets and neck piece from the
cavities. Rinse turkey inside and out with cold water; drain well.
Pat dry with paper towels. (Stuff turkey at this point, if
desired.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the easiest way to roast the turkey?
</P>
<P>
   A: Place the turkey breast side up on a rack in a shallow
roasting pan, 2 to 2 1/2 inches deep. Do not add water. Brush
lightly with vegetable oil (or melted butter).
</P>
<P>
   Truss the bird, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Cover turkey loosely with foil, leaving a little space between
bird and foil and pressing foil over drumsticks either the first or
last (it doesn't matter) 1 to 1 1/2 hours of roasting time.
</P>
<P>
   Roast in a preheated 325 degree F oven according to the chart,
until the inner thigh reaches 180 degrees F on a meat thermometer,
the center and all parts of the stuffing reach 165 degrees F and
the breast is 170 degrees F. Both the USDA and Butterball emphasize
the necessity of using a meat thermometer for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   When done, remove from oven and allow the turkey to stand 20
minutes before you remove the stuffing or begin carving. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3106 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-TURKEY-HOW-TO-LADN 1stadd &LR;    11-17 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-HOW-TO-LADN, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 1st add  UNDATED: ... stuffing or begin carving. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How long will it take to roast a turkey?
</P>
<P>
   A: Roast the bird using these times provided by the USDA. The
times are approximate. Variations in ovens, pan sizes and
materials, and the temperature of the turkey at beginning of
roasting affect roasting time. Therefore, begin checking for
doneness about an hour prior to the end of the recommended roasting
time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TURKEY ROASTING GUIDE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WEIGHT IN POUNDS ... COOKING TIME STUFFED IN HOURS ... COOKING TIME
UNSTUFFED IN HOURS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
4 to 6 ... 1 1/2 to 2 1/4 ... not applicable (whole breast) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
6 to 8 ... 2 3/4 to 3 ... 3 to 3 1/2 (whole breast) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
8 to 12 ... 2 1/4 to 3 1/4 ... 3 to 3 1/2 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
12 to 14 ... 3 to 3 3/4 ... 3 1/2 to 4 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
14 to 18 ... 3 3/4 to 4 1/4 ... 4 to 4 1/4 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
18 to 20 ... 4 1/4 to 4 1/2 ... 4 1/4 to 4 3/4 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
20 to 24 ... 4 1/2 to 5 ... 4 3/4 to 5 1/4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I cook the turkey partway through one day and finish it
the next?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. You should never partially roast a stuffed or unstuffed
turkey one day and complete roasting the next. Interrupted cooking
increases the possibility of bacterial growth.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My friend says her mother has always cooked the turkey in a
200 degree F oven overnight. Is it safe?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Overnight cooking at a low temperature isn't a safe
method for cooking turkey. According to the USDA hotline, it is not
safe to cook any meat or poultry at a temperature lower than 325
degrees F. At 200 degrees F, meat remains in the ``danger zone''
(between 40 degrees and 140 degrees F), where bacteria multiply
rapidly and can form toxins.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can a turkey be prepared any way other than roasting?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can grill it, smoke it, microwave it, or deep-fry it, but
the turkey should not be stuffed. Deep-frying is a trendy way to
cook a turkey these days, but it requires special equipment and can
be messy and dangerous. For more information on these and other
cooking methods, see the USDA Web site, www.fsis.usda.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's Thanksgiving Day and I forgot to thaw the turkey. What
can I do?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can start cooking the unwrapped frozen (unstuffed) turkey
in a preheated 325-degree F oven, but you'll need to add 50 percent
more cooking time to the original times on the chart. Also once the
turkey is thawed enough, you'll need to very carefully (without
burning yourself) remove the giblets and neck piece from the turkey
cavities. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
STUFFING
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm debating _ should I stuff the turkey or not?
</P>
<P>
   A: Food safety professionals advise against stuffing the turkey
and recommend baking the stuffing separately in a casserole dish _
it's the safest way. But it's your call. An unstuffed turkey takes
less time to cook than one that is stuffed.
</P>
<P>
   If you desire a stuffed turkey, the stuffing should be placed in
the cavities at the last minute just before the turkey goes into
the oven.
</P>
<P>
   If you opt to bake the stuffing separately, place in a greased
dish, cover with foil and bake 1 hour (the last hour the turkey
roasts) at 325 degrees F. Remove foil the last 30 minutes of baking
time to allow the top to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I plan to stuff the turkey. How do I do it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mix stuffing just before it goes into the turkey. Never stuff
a turkey in advance. Allow 3/4 cup of stuffing for each pound of
ready-to-eat turkey. Bake any extra stuffing separately.
</P>
<P>
   The wet and dry ingredients can be prepared and cooked ahead of
time and chilled separately. Combine and mix them just before
placing inside a turkey or a casserole.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the stuffing in the turkey, close the neck and body
cavities by folding the neck skin over the back and fastening with
a skewer, trussing pins, clean string or toothpicks; then twist the
wing tips under the back of the turkey to rest against the neck
skin. Close the body cavity with skewers or by tucking ends of legs
under a band of skin at the tail, or into metal ``hock-locks,'' if
provided. You can also close the opening by tying the legs together
with a clean string. Allow for extra cooking time, because a
stuffed turkey takes longer to cook than an unstuffed one. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOOD SAFETY
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just discovered I cooked the turkey with the package of
giblets still inside the cavity. Are the turkey and giblets safe to
eat?
</P>
<P>
   A: If giblets were paper wrapped and left in the cavity during
roasting, even though this is not recommended, the turkey is
probably safe to eat. However, the giblets should be discarded,
noted USDA's Van. Both the turkey and giblets should be discarded
if the packaging containing the giblets were in plastic and had
been altered or melted during cooking because harmful chemicals
from the packaging may have penetrated the surrounding meat.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long is it safe to keep cooked turkey leftovers at room
temperature?
</P>
<P>
   A: Within two hours of removing the turkey from the oven,
refrigerate or freeze the leftovers separately _ the turkey,
stuffing and gravy. Cut the turkey into smaller pieces (leg, wing,
half breast) or remove the meat from the bones to speed cooling in
the fridge. Refrigerated turkey should be used within two to three
days. Frozen cooked turkey should be used within two months.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am fixing turkey for the office party this year. How should
I serve it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's probably simpler and safer to serve it cold. Cook the
turkey at home, slice and refrigerate in a shallow container for
transporting to the party. Keep the meat refrigerated until serving
time. Throw away any leftovers that have been left out more than
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I plan to bake some pumpkin pies for Thanksgiving Day two
days in advance. Can I leave them on the counter or do I need to
refrigerate them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Foods made with eggs and milk such as pumpkin or custard pies
and cheesecake must first be safely baked to at least 160 degrees
F. After baking, cool up to two hours at room temperature and then
refrigerate. Eggs and milk have high protein and moisture content
and when these baked products are left at room temperature,
conditions are ripe for bacteria to multiply. Other holiday cakes,
cookies or breads with a perishable filling or frosting (such as
cream cheese or whipped cream) should also be kept refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What food safety tips should I follow in preparing the
Thanksgiving meal?
</P>
<P>
   A: To reduce the risks of foodborne illness, keep hot foods hot
and cold foods cold. Don't leave perishable foods at room
temperature for more than two hours on the big day. Two hours is
considered the bacteria danger zone in which harmful bacteria can
grow rapidly in temperatures between 40 degrees F and 140 degrees
F.
</P>
<P>
   Also wash your hands with soap and hot water before and after
handling any food. To prevent cross contamination, use two cutting
boards, one for meat and one for other foods. Wash utensils with
soap and hot water after using. And use paper towels, not
dishcloths, to clean up any spilled meat juices and to dry the
turkey after rinsing. &QL; 
____
</P>
<P>
   If you run into turkey problems this holiday season, call the
USDA Meat and Poultry Hotline at (800) 535-4555 or the Butterball
Turkey Talk-Line at (800) 323-4848. Both will have operators
available Thanksgiving Day. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
