u a BC-FLA-ELECTRIC-CHAIR-AR     11-17 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ELECTRIC-CHAIR-ART-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA'S MESSY EXECUTIONS PUT ELECTRIC CHAIR ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ala., Ga., Neb.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In Florida, say opponents of the death penalty, there is
something worse than death. There is death in the state's electric
chair.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Lee Davis, a 300-pound triple murderer known as ``Tiny,''
was electrocuted at Florida State Prison in Starke last July.
Photographs of his execution, posted on the Internet by the Florida
Supreme Court at the request of one of its judges who is opposed to
the electric chair, show in graphic detail what happened as the
switch was thrown.
</P>
<P>
   His body reared back against the chair's restraints, giving
witnesses a grotesque glimpse under a black hood designed to hide
the faces of the condemned. His round, moon face contorted grossly,
the flesh seeming to knot, and colored a vivid purple. Blood poured
from his nose, ran down the wide leather strap that covered his
mouth and soaked his white shirt.
</P>
<P>
   After the power was turned off, Davis, who had killed a pregnant
woman and her two young daughters in 1983, was still alive.
Witnesses said his chest rose and fell about 10 times before he
went still.
</P>
<P>
   State prison officials and Gov. Jeb Bush say the chair
functioned properly. Bush called what happened to Davis a
``nosebleed,'' insignificant when viewed alongside his crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the photographs, the latest evidence that this state has
trouble humanely putting to death its condemned inmates, have
whipped up renewed passion in an old debate that could signal the
end of the electric chair in Florida and perhaps the rest of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis execution was not the first to raise questions in
Florida about the humaneness of electrocution. In 1990 and 1997,
inmates caught fire in the chair as they were being put to death.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, long the subject of dark humor in the state, has
become the focus of talk shows and political rallies as far away as
Madrid, and may be considered in a special legislative session
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed interest has put Bush on the defensive and has
emboldened the forces opposing the death penalty. There is even
some evidence that residents of Florida, long supporters of using
the electric chair, are having a change of heart. A recent poll
showed that more than half the state's registered voters thought it
might be time for a new means of execution.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate rages, all executions in Florida are on hold. The
U.S. Supreme Court, considering the appeal of another condemned
killer in Florida, agreed in October, for the first time in more
than a century, to consider whether the electric chair is cruel and
unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush contends that the chair is humane, but is considering a
special session of the Legislature in January to discuss a change
to lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the death penalty, in Florida and around the
nation, have called the state's use of the chair barbarism. They
have also accused Bush and other state officials who defend it of
using such spectacles to deter crime and to prove they are tough on
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on the death penalty say more is at stake here than
whether Florida continues to use the chair or changes to lethal
injection, as other states have done. In 34 of the 38 states that
have death-penalty laws, lethal injection is either the only method
or a choice given to the condemned.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a humane alternative to hanging and the firing
squad, electrocution is now seen by many people in Florida as the
preferred way of exacting justice for a much different reason:
because it poses the possibility of pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A method that was once defended because it was supposed to be
humane is now being mostly defended by a state because of its
inhumanity,'' said Carol Steiker, a law professor and associate
dean at Harvard Law School. ``It's been turned on its legal head.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three other states _ Alabama, Georgia and Nebraska _ use
the electric chair exclusively. Some legal experts say the Supreme
Court case out of Florida could be the beginning of the end for all
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will bring an end to all electrocutions in the
United States,'' said Stephen Bright, a lawyer who works with death
row inmates and is the director of the Southern Center for Human
Rights, in Atlanta.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Bush told reporters he thought the Supreme Court would
dismiss the debate over Davis' execution as ``an argument over a
nosebleed of a criminal who savagely murdered a pregnant woman and
her two young daughters _ and who was successful in delaying his
own execution 16 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statewide poll conducted by The St. Petersburg Times and
The Miami Herald, 58 percent of the people asked said they
supported a state law to switch from the electric chair to lethal
injection.
</P>
<P>
   That has not swayed Bush, said Lucia Ross, his press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is in the process of considering other options
that include lethal injection,'' Ms. Ross said. ``That does not
diminish his feelings about the constitutionality of the chair.
It's legal, it works and we fully support it. We believe it is a
quick and humane way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's legal advisers have said he will consider lethal
injection if his insistence on use of the chair has the effect of
delaying executions.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's intervention stems from an appeal by Anthony
Braden Bryan, who was convicted of kidnapping and killing a man in
the Florida Panhandle. Oral arguments in that case are expected to
begin in February.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
