<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-FIRES18-COX     11-17 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-FIRES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Georgia fires nearly contained
 &HT;    By Rick Badie
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A fire that crept along a North Georgia mountain ridge
Wednesday feasted on wilderness that succumbed with a snap, crackle
and pop. A 20-man crew of Puerto Rican firefighters watched the
blaze, just in case it raced across a gravel road into a thicket of
white pine, dogwood and sweet gum trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have corralled it, not contained it,'' said Sid Hall,
leader of the crew helping to fight a 1,450-acre fire near Pigeon
Roost Mountain, north of Cleveland. ``It's between the roads and
creeks right now, and we have a good chance of keeping it there.''
</P>
<P>
   An interagency effort to stop several fires that since Saturday
have scorched 4,400 acres of mountain wilderness gained ground. The
total number of fires increased to eight, but two of them _ Pigeon
Roost and Turkey Stamp in Lumpkin County _ were burning themselves
out. Favorable winds, coupled with natural and man-made barriers,
aided in keeping the fires from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural boundaries and containment lines we are putting in
are beginning to pay off,'' Alan Polk, spokesman for the U.S.
Forest Service, said Wednesday. ``We're starting to put a circle
around the fires, and a big factor has been the wind. But you never
know what the weather is going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   About 200 firefighters battling fires in Gilmer, Lumpkin and
other mountain counties used rakes, hoes and leaf blowers to clear
natural paths and build 4-foot lanes to starve the flames. Another
100 firefighters from the west who were to arrive Wednesday will be
in the field today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one of two fires that have consumed 1,800 acres in
Gilmer County has been contained; the other fire that was heading
toward the southeast was doused with water by helicopter. Three
smaller fires in Rabun, White and Chattooga counties were
contained.
</P>
<P>
   Today, firefighters may start their own fires to control
burning. Those fires, called ``backburns'' would be set to burn
toward the fires they want to put out, said Hall, the crew leader
from Saguache, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both fires would sit and smolder a little bit, but they
wouldn't be a threat,'' said Hall, as soot and smoke bellowed from
a ridge near Pigeon Roost. ``What we don't want to happen is a tree
to fall across the road and ignite a new area.''
</P>
<P>
   If it does, firefighters including Rey Lorenzo of Puerto Rico
stand ready. Since becoming a firefighter in 1992, Lorenzo has
worked natural disasters in Florida and Texas. It's his first trip
to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have family that we leave behind, but we are here to
protect the people,'' said Lorenzo, 30. ``But for us, it's a matter
of pride to be here. We are called in because we are trained for
this kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-ELECTRIC-CHAIR-AR     11-17 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ELECTRIC-CHAIR-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MIAMI: in February.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bryan's lawyers persuaded the Supreme Court to review his case
and stay executions in Florida by citing the history of the
electric chair in this state.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, smoke and flames leaped from the face mask of Pedro
Medina, a convicted murderer. In 1990, flames shot three feet high
from behind the head of another condemned killer, Jesse Tafero.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, we just can't seem to pull the switch and get
people to die instantly,'' said Walter Campbell, a Democratic state
senator from Coral Springs, near Fort Lauderdale, who favors the
death penalty but is tired of the embarrassments caused by the
electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors working for the state have always contended that death
in the chair is fast and painless, despite burns and other evidence
to the contrary. And a majority of the Florida Supreme Court has
repeatedly held that the chair is not a cruel and unusual form of
punishment, and the court did so again this year by a vote of 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   But in a dissent, Justice Leander Shaw wrote, ``Execution by
electrocution, with its attendant smoke and flames and blood and
screams, is a spectacle whose time has passed.''
</P>
<P>
   He requested that the pictures of Davis' electrocution be posted
on the Internet. The state Supreme Court complied, as a way to let
the public see exactly what went on, said Jane Bentley, a
spokeswoman for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four states that use the chair exclusively _ seven others
give the condemned inmate a choice between the chair or lethal
injection _ none has Florida's reputation for messy executions.
</P>
<P>
   While talk shows here have lampooned the chair, opponents of the
death penalty see Florida's use of it as macabre.
</P>
<P>
   The executioner is not a state employee, but a private citizen
who is paid $150 per electrocution to pull the switch. Condemned
inmates are granted a last meal, but only if it costs $20 or less.
Then, once strapped in the chair, the inmate fears not only death,
but agony, said death penalty lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the poster child for ugly executions,'' said Bruce Rogow,
a lawyer and professor at Nova Southeastern University, who was
Tafero's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client's scalp caught on fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The wooden chair that caused flames in the executions of Tafero
and Medina was built in 1923, by inmates, and was so rickety by the
time the obese Davis was executed that state prison officials
replaced it with a sturdier one. But they used the old chair's
electrical system.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials said that Davis had been taking blood-thinning
medication, which can increase bleeding. He did not suffer, state
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with the chair,'' said C.J. Drake, the
state prisons spokesman. ``But it was a profuse nosebleed. He was
wearing a white shirt, which made it a lot more noticeable.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tafero's execution, the flames were attributed to a faulty
sponge _ wet and used to transfer electricity _ in the headpiece.
In Medina's execution, prison officials wet the sponge improperly.
</P>
<P>
   The botched executions have backfired on state officials who
want to speed the process of carrying out the death sentence. The
problems have been fodder for lawyers trying to win stays for many
of the 372 inmates on death row, creating logjams in the appellate
courts. More than half have been there 10 years or more, and some
for 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it's done is delayed and delayed,'' Campbell said. ``The
real victims are the victims' families.''
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted many state officials to propose the switch to
lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most Floridians that support capital punishment don't
see a difference,'' said Ron Klein, a Democratic state senator from
Boca Raton. ``I mean, dead is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has said that many Floridians, like himself, do not see
the chair as cruel. Interviews with the friends and families of
murdered people bear witness to that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, George Pfeil, a reserve deputy in Seminole County, near
Orlando, was on his way home when he stopped in at a pharmacy in
Longwood to pick up a prescription for his sick wife. He walked in
on a robbery and was shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``George did not deserve to die like he did,'' said Capt. Al
Sanchez, who had worked beside Deputy Pfeil.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy's killer, Terry Sims, has been on death row for 20
years and was scheduled to die last week, until the Supreme Court
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez not only wants him to die, he wants him to die in the
chair. ``Lethal injection is too humane for these guys,'' he said.
``I think they ought to suffer a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Florida voters overwhelmingly approved an amendment
placing the death penalty in the state constitution and allowing
any method permitted by the U.S. Supreme Court, including the
chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people think that these people deserve this
type of punishment,'' said Bright of the Southern Center for Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the photos of Davis' execution convinced many people that
the chair was, if not cruel, at least an embarrassment. The photos
even provoked one international incident.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, hundreds of protesters gathered outside the U.S.
Embassy in Madrid as the Florida Supreme Court heard an appeal by a
death row inmate and Spanish citizen, Joaquin Martinez. He shot and
stabbed to death a young woman and man in Tampa in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters paraded in front of the embassy chanting
``assassins'' and ``beasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Some state officials say Florida could have avoided such
unwelcome attention if it had been more competent in
electrocutions.
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty experts, like Ms. Steiker at Harvard, say there is
no solid proof that executions _ no matter how carried out _ deter
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The people on death row acted out of passion or depravity, death
penalty lawyers say, and few stopped in the course of their murders
to ponder the repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think about the chair or having a needle stuck in
their arm,'' Rogow said. ``Does it prevent the next guy from
committing murder? No.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, he said, that state executions are revenge killings,
and messy executions are sweeter revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Pfeil was this really nice guy,'' Sanchez said of the
reserve deputy's death. ``Decent guys, killed by less-than-decent
people. They deserve everything that's coming to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
