<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-MARKETPLACE-ART     11-17 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: U.S. INVESTORS SALIVATE OVER CHINESE STOCKS AFTER
PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it depends which side of the Pacific you're on.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since China and the United States signed a deal that
may lead to Chinese admission into the World Trade Organization,
the Chinese stock market has made small gains, with indexes of
mainland stocks up about 1 percent. Hong Kong stocks did better,
with the leading index of such shares up 3.6 percent since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the relatively small number of Chinese stocks traded
on major U.S. stock markets have risen sharply. In some cases they
have gone absolutely berserk. Suddenly, any stock with China in its
name seems to have willing buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest gains have gone to stocks that previously had been
of little interest to American investors. By contrast, China
Telecom (Hong Kong), which provides cellular telephone services in
China and has been an institutional favorite in America, rose on
Monday and Tuesday but fell $5.9375, to $86.5625, Wednesday, and is
up just 2 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
   But such languid performance is more than offset by other stocks
that have skyrocketed. A list of nine stocks _ all traded on the
New York Stock Exchange or Nasdaq and all with the word ``China''
in their names _ shows increases of at least 60 percent for six of
the nine since Friday. Investors who put an equal amount of money
into each of the stocks on Friday _ the last trading day before the
WTO agreement was announced _ would have more than quadrupled their
money by Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing move came in the shares of China Prosperity
International Holdings, a company that does property renovations in
China _ but that has also been talking about doing something
related to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   China Prosperity was once something of a hot stock, moving as
high as $37 a share in Nasdaq trading in 1996 _ adjusted for a
later reverse split. But it had fallen out of investors' favor, and
by Monday was trading at $1 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Tuesday, the stock leaped to $11.06, trading as high as
$14, and volume rose to 521,100 shares, or more than had traded in
the previous year. That however, was just the prelude. Wednesday
volume totaled 4.4 million shares, or more than the total volume in
this country since the company went public in 1995. The price
leaped as high as $80, then began to slide before ending at
$32.0625.
</P>
<P>
   There was no announcement from the company, but the same could
not be said for another suddenly high flyer. China Resources
Development, a distributor of natural rubber, reported that its
losses were growing. It added that it had no explanation for the
stock's movement in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   That stock jumped $19 to $25 a share in Nasdaq trading
Wednesday, on volume of 906,800 shares. That volume is nearly twice
the total number of shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Another amazing performance was turned in by Dransfield China
Paper Corp., which rarely trades on Nasdaq. During October, there
were only two days when shares in the company, which distributes
paper products and is building pulp mills in China, were traded.
The price then was $1 a share. It fell to 43.75 cents on Monday,
and then did not trade Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, with anything named China looking hot, 1.3
million shares were traded _ more than triple the total volume
traded since the company was listed on Nasdaq in 1997 _ and the
price rose as high as $29 before closing at $11.125.
</P>
<P>
   China.com, a company based in Hong Kong that provides a portal
for Chinese users of the Internet, leaped from $58 on Friday to a
close of $105 Wednesday, trading as high as $137. It had gone
public, at $20 a share, in July.
</P>
<P>
   Even China Tire, a company that makes car and truck tires, got
in on the action. Since Friday, it is up 77 percent, to $10.625.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to explain such moves based on expectations of
what will happen if China is successful in entering the World Trade
Organization, something that could yet be derailed by congressional
opposition. Changes in the Chinese economy will arrive over a
period of years, and the opening of the economy to competition from
foreign companies may damage some Chinese businesses even as others
are helped.
</P>
<P>
   But there seems to have been little in the way of such analysis
regarding many of the stocks that were moving Wednesday. Instead,
Internet chat rooms were full of comments about how certain stocks
were sure to keep moving because there were relatively few shares
available for trading. Traders were chasing performance, and in the
process they were creating it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
