<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BRUCE SMITH'S NEVER-ENDING STRUGGLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Ian Rafferty was doing just fine until Tuesday. He was living the
anonymous life of a free-agent rookie lineman trying to make it in
the NFL. Rafferty, an offensive tackle from North Carolina State,
was waived in September by the Tennessee Titans and then signed to
the Titans' practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the 23-year-old rookie received an SOS call from
the New York Jets, who got right to the point. They were playing
Buffalo on Sunday. Jason Fabini, the starting right tackle and the
backup at left tackle, is out for the season; Jumbo Elliott, the
starting left tackle, has a bad back and may not be able to play.
And the Jets need a left tackle, because they will going up against
Bruce Smith, Buffalo's future Hall of Fame, rookie-devouring
defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Rafferty found himself in New York before 9 a.m. Wednesday, at
the Jets' complex by 9:30 and up to his ears in the team's fat
playbook shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of their very slim playoff hopes, the Jets have to
hope that Rafferty won't have to play against Smith, that Jumbo
Elliott is healthy enough to get on the field, that Ray Lucas,
Monday night's star quarterback against the New England Patriots,
won't suffer the same fate Boomer Esiason suffered in 1995 when
Smith roared in from the left, past the rookie tackle Everett
McIver and knocked Esiason cold.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets can't afford any more losses, not in personnel, and not
in games. At 3-6, the team has the slimmest of chances for a
miraculous playoff run and absolutely no margin of error; Bruce
Smith is the error the Jets cannot afford to let happen.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Wednesday that he was fully expecting to line up
against his old adversary, Elliott, on Sunday. He said he was
equally sure that if Rafferty has to play, he'll get plenty of
help. ``They tend to give players who don't have a great deal of
experience or are very young a lot of help through slide
protection, or leaving a back or tight end back there to help,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, for the next 72 hours, Ian Rafferty will sit in
front of a screen and watch hours of Bruce Smith footage. Then, on
Sunday, the rookie may discover, as rookies always discover, that
the qualities that make players like Smith great don't show up on
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, everyone, I guess, thinks I'm a great athlete,''
Smith said. ``I'm a gifted athlete who works hard during the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what the film doesn't show is how much I put into
preparing myself to play a ball game _ working out year-round, 365
days a year, as opposed to six months out of the year. Studying in
the classroom, just putting in that extra time by myself to make
sure I'm fully prepared. My eating habits _ making sure I stayed
the same weight the last 13 years. Those are little things you
can't see on film.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a stellar season for Smith, but a difficult year,
too. His 78-year-old father has emphysema, heart problems and other
ailments. He lost a favorite aunt on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying my best to stay focused,'' Smith said. ``My father
tells me to stay focused and pray and do the things that are
necessary to keep me strong.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the biggest difference between the 36-year-old Smith
and the 23-year-old Rafferty isn't size or strength, speed or
quickness. The difference is an ocean of experience, of highs and
lows, of disappointments and travails that Smith has overcome and
Rafferty has yet to face. Smith has known rivers; they have
strengthened his resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been reading a book, and one of the concepts the book
focuses on is struggle,'' Smith said. ``That's what I tend to think
about certain points of my career _ it's been a struggle. But
through struggle I was able to gain a lot of knowledge, dignity,
respect. Struggle builds character. I'm still in the struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, so are the Jets. ``They're a dangerous team.''
Smith said. ``I saw their game against New England. We thought it
would have been a good game, but we didn't realize they were going
to go out and be able to win commandingly as they did.''
</P>
<P>
   For the young Ian Rafferty, who is trying to make it in the
National Football League, the battles are defined by each week's
game. For the veteran Bruce Smith, who has been to four Super Bowls
and known only defeat, battles are framed by far-reaching goals. He
signed a six-year, $28.2 million deal in 1997, but that was merely
a mark of success, not success in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggle to get better, I struggle to make my teammates
better, I struggle to try to help this team win,'' Smith said.
``It's a struggle to teach some of these younger players how to
play this game of football, how to study. It's always going to be a
struggle, until I win a championship or retire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
