<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-TV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The mall channel: Turner to target shoppers
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now television will follow you to the mall and urge
you to buy more stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting will create a new channel, based on a
smorgasbord of its programming, to air exclusively in Lenox,
Phipps, Mall of Georgia and the other malls of the Simon Property
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The as yet unnamed channel will use Turner Broadcasting shows
and characters to promote products and encourage shopping.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the effort will help Turner Broadcasting not only
launch channels but also expand into new product lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to touch our viewers in all aspects of their lives,''
said Steven J. Heyer, Turner Broadcasting's president and chief
operating officer. ``We're trying to create loyalty that extends
beyond our channels.''
</P>
<P>
   What the channel will look like and how it will appear in the
malls has yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   One thing it won't be is weighty. ``This channel doesn't lend
itself to two-hour movies,'' Heyer said. ``We're talking about
shorter, crisper clips.'' Programming will be based on the content
of Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting's 18 cable TV channels.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting is no stranger to specialized repacking of
its programming. Its Airport Channel pumps reconfigured versions of
CNN material into airports worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting executives hope to begin airing the mall
channel, which will run 24 hours a day, by late next year.
</P>
<P>
   The channel is part of a multimedia alliance between Turner
Broadcasting and Simon to put interactive kiosks in 256 malls
nationwide that will offer Web access and family entertainment.
Simon owns or has a stake in eight malls in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Heyer declined to reveal the level of investment in the new
partnership, other than to say it would be relatively minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The effort will require setting up a new division, to be based
in Atlanta and New York. Most of the programming will be done in
Atlanta, while sales and marketing efforts will be directed from
New York. A general manager will be hired for the channel, and will
work out of both cities.
</P>
<P>
   The new mall channel is part of a larger effort. Turner wants to
establish the names of its 18 channels, which include CNN, TNT and
the Cartoon Network, as brands recognized beyond the television.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting couldn't ask for a bigger opportunity to
extend its brand recognition. Indianapolis-based Simon Property's
malls serve 100 million shoppers. It has locations in the nation's
top 20 markets.
</P>
<P>
   For Simon, the deal is a way to distinguish its properties in
the highly competitive and crowded world of mall shopping.
``Creating this new multimedia platform is a significant
competitive advantage for both of our companies,'' said chief
executive David Simon.
</P>
<P>
   The company will draw on the vast library of Turner Broadcasting
and of its parent, Time Warner. Original programming also will be
developed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
