<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3123 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f BC-AMWEST-AZR &LR;      11-17 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCELED FLIGHTS ANGERS AMWEST PASSENGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - America West, already plagued by delays, has canceled
more than 400 flights the past two weeks, stalling more than 50,000
passengers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Close to half of those cancella tions occurred Nov. 10-14, when
America West was forced to take three Boeing 757 aircraft out of
service until required maintenance was performed, company spokesman
Steve Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration officials would not grant
America West a short-term extension on the maintenance overhaul,
and that forced the airline to park the planes until the work could
be completed, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials in Phoenix would not comment on the America West
maintenance issues or cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the scrubbed flights, America West continues to
turn in the industry's worst on-time record, according to figures
com piled through September and released Wednesday, Nov. 17, by the
U.S. Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   America West canceled about 40 flights per day during the worst
stretch of its problems, Nov. 10-14. The airline has about 650
flights per day, and about three-fourths of those originate or end
up in Phoenix. So, Valley travelers were hurt the most by the
cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Southwest Airlines, by comparison, has about 2,500 flights
per day and averaged fewer than 25 canceled flights during the past
20 days, according to spokeswoman Carol Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   The series of cancellations this month at America West, roughly
double the normal rate, and the carrier's ongoing problems with
delays have angered travelers. The problems also raise questions
about the Tempe-based carrier's operations heading into the holiday
travel crush next week.
</P>
<P>
   But America West returned the 757 aircraft to service and does
not anticipate any similar problems next week, according to
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be back at full strength for the holidays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   America West would not say how much each canceled flight costs
the airline.
</P>
<P>
   The company is initiating changes in maintenance operations that
are taking longer than expected to implement, but it expects to
improve its reliability over the next few months, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be too late for some passengers, who have had their
fill of cancellations and delays.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Arnold of Scottsdale and his family were among those caught
by America West's recent problems.
</P>
<P>
   His wife's flight to San Francisco on Nov. 10 had an hourlong
weather delay. His flight to San Francisco on Saturday with his two
children, ages 2 and 3, was canceled and a substitute flight to San
Jose was delayed about 90 minutes, Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   While standing in line during the delay, Arnold said, he talked
to other America West passengers, and it seemed the airline was
having problems all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was truly wondering if Amer ica West was going out of busi
ness,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   The return trip from San Fran cisco with his wife and children
on Tuesday was supposed to leave about 2:30 p.m. but didn't depart
until about 5 p.m. The Arnolds were given meal vouchers and allowed
to make a three-minute long-distance call for their troubles, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to fly somebody else when I can,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance problems, which force cancellations or delays, have
been an issue at America West for several years. The airline was
fined $5 million by the FAA in July 1998 over maintenance and
safety viola tions.
</P>
<P>
   Half of that fine was waived in July by FAA officials in
Washington despite objections from Phoenix inspectors who argued
that the airline had not fully complied with an agreement to
resolve it's mainte nance problems.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also had an in-flight accident that injured four
flight attendants on Sept. 20 when a pilot quickly changed course.
A National Transportation Safety Board investi gator indicated the
pilot was react ing to a faulty ground proximity warning system
that America West knew about but had been unable to fix.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 12 months, America West has been last in on-time
performance of the 10 major air lines, with just under seven out of
10 flights arriving within 15 min utes of their scheduled arrival
time.
</P>
<P>
   Canceled flights do not count against a carrier's on-time
perform ance, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry leader, Southwest, completed 80 percent of its
flights on time over the past year, accord ing to the Department of
Transpor tation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. airlines have been plagued this year by delays and cancella
tions, creating an uproar among passengers and igniting calls for
greater government oversight. The airlines, meanwhile, blame some
of the flight problems on the over loaded air traffic control
system.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the complaints from passengers keep rolling in. In
Sep tember, federal transportation offi cials received 2,732
passenger complaints about U.S. airlines, more than triple the rate
from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Figures released Wednesday by the Department of Transportation
also show that America West com pleted just 65.8 percent of its
flights on time in September, compared with No. 1 TWA at 89.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the America West spokesman, said that some of the
delays in September were due to weather problems in Phoenix and
hurricanes on the East Coast, and that the air traffic control
problems also accounted for delays. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at (602) 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
