<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3126 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-DEBT-ARRESTS     11-17 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-DEBT-ARRESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFAULTERS ARE ARRESTED IN PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ The military government, making good on
threats to jail people who have defaulted on millions of dollars in
bank loans, began arresting some of the nation's wealthiest
citizens Wednesday, including senior executives, politicians and a
retired air marshal.
</P>
<P>
   Under a law enacted overnight, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, who came
to power in a coup on Oct. 12, has set up a National Accountability
Bureau with the power to place willful defaulters behind bars for
14 years. Convicted offenders also face the seizure of assets.
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning, hours after a heavily publicized deadline
to pay up on bad loans, authorities began a national sweep. Among
21 influential people taken into custody were Anwar Saifullah Khan
and Nawaz Khokhar, both ministers in Benazir Bhutto's government
from 1995 to 1997, and Islamuddin Sheikh, briefly a minister under
the recently ousted government of Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   A televised bulletin also said Ms. Bhutto and Sharif were wanted
on charges of corruption. Ms. Bhutto, who lives in London, already
faces a five-year term on an earlier conviction. Sharif has been
held in a secret location since he was pushed from power.
</P>
<P>
   Saifur Rehman, a high-profile politician who ran Sharif's own
anti-corruption campaign, and Shahbaz Sharif, former chief minister
of Punjab, have also been named in the defaults. They, too, have
been in detention since the coup.
</P>
<P>
   These people ``have committed a crime against this nation,
against this country,'' Interior Minister Moinudeen Haider, a
retired general, said. ``Obviously, we have to be tough with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Toughness is what Musharraf has in mind, asserting that the
eventual return to democracy has to be preceded by a war on
corruption. Banks are owed $4.2 billion in unpaid loans, much of
which is thought to be cash borrowed with little or no collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Defaulters had 30 days to make good on the loans. Few did so,
though the number is now expected to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people are talking, and they are agreeing to submit what
they have taken from the national wealth,'' Finance Minister
Shaukat Aziz said at a news conference. ``No one will be spared.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers, asked to supply lists of defaulters, have been asked to
make distinctions between willful defaulters and those whose debts
have resulted from business reversals.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, special courts will be convened for the
corruption cases. The proceedings are not to last beyond 30 days.
One appeal would be permitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
