<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AND PRESIDENT AGREE IN PRINCIPLE ON BUDGET CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and Republican leaders in Congress
agreed in principle on Wednesday to an across-the-board spending
cut to seal a deal on the overdue federal budget, then argued
fiercely over how to impose it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, all sides said a deal was imminent. Rep. C.W. Bill
Young, R-Fla., who is chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, said his party expected the dispute to be settled within
hours and the final spending bill to be filed in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Their dispute was ``like when you go to buy a house, and you've
agreed on the price, and all that's left is a disagreement over the
color of the trim on the tool shed,'' said Robert Stevenson, a
senior aide to Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M. the chairman of the
Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The across-the-board cut would be about .33 percent of the $610
billion budget for federal agencies, and would yield about $1.3
billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement threatened to undo the final budget deal, even
though both sides had said earlier on Wednesday that an accord was
only hours away. Also potentially standing in the way of a final
agreement is another dispute over federal price rules for dairy
farms, an issue so crucial that the combatants are threatening to
shut down the Senate, block any final budget bill and keep Congress
in session well into December.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., in an effort to protect his state's
23,000 dairy farmers from legislation favoring milk producers in
the Northeast, has placed a formal hold on the final spending
package. The budget cannot pass, and Congress cannot adjourn, until
Kohl lifts it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to take the dairy out of the appropriations
package,'' said the Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
``It's got to come out. It will blow it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, the White House budget director, said the dairy
dispute was so dire that it ``raises a real risk of a government
shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that problem, a budget agreement is still one handshake
away.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans want nearly $7 billion in spending cuts and
savings from the White House. That would allow the Republicans to
say that their spending bills will not dip into Social Security
surpluses, a political point they have made daily, since spring,
but still have not formally fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   The money would ``help them fill the hole they created'' with
new programs they wanted, along with new spending that the White
House fought for and won, Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   The argument over an across-the-board cut is a fine-print feud
over who controls the budget-cutting scalpel _ high-level
administration officials, as the Democrats want, or mid-level
budget officers at federal agencies, as Republicans want _ and
whether certain programs can be protected.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides described this as an issue of flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Lew said: ``It still matters how it's done. If it goes
across-the- board cut with no flexibility, that would lead to very
foolish results.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said Democrats demanded that the cuts should be ``a
targeted reduction,'' under the control of the president and his
aides, and focused on specific programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking semantics,'' said the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott, R-Miss. ``If it exempts personnel, whatever, you could
then call that some sort of targeted savings. O.K., I'm all right
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted on cutting all federal programs more or
less equally. They would let budget officials at each agency wield
the knife. They could protect individual programs from any cut.
Other programs could be cut by up to 5 percent, but no more.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM(
</P>
<P>
   The day's war or words began when the speaker of the House,
Dennis Hastert, said President Clinton had agreed to an
across-the-board cut of 0.38 percent in the budget, which is now 47
days overdue.
</P>
<P>
   It dragged on all day.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was seeking every last new dollar it could
extract from Congress before shaking hands, including $100 million
for a program for disabled workers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House brought nearly $7 billion to the bargaining
table on Wednesday, enough to cover the Republican's demands
without an across-the-board cut, Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   About half that sum would come in a onetime transfer from the
Federal Reserve's portfolio of government securities _ a
bookkeeping device, since the money belongs to the government
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The rest would come from delaying government paychecks for
military personnel and many civilian employees for about 48 hours,
until just after Oct. 1, 2000, _ the start of the next fiscal year.
This accounting maneuver, a variation on a theme first proposed by
the Republicans, would not actually save money, but simply shift
about $3.2 billion into next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Clinton vetoed a 0.97 percent across-the-board
cut that Congress passed, almost exclusively with Republican votes,
calling it a ``blind'' and ``mindless'' exercise. To make such a
cut seem sensible to Democrats, the White House insisted more
``flexibility'' to protect some programs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But evening came with no agreement. Lew and the White House
chief of staff, John Podesta, left the Senate, and the Republicans
began writing the final version of the spending bills by
themselves, talking with the White House by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Several Senate Republicans called the cut largely symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small gesture,'' said Lott. ``Both sides get all caught
up in symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how small, an across-the-board cut was a matter of
principle for the party's conservatives in the House, who on
Wednesday wore big buttons on their lapels saying they had
``stopped the raid on Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   This stance, the Democrats insisted, was pure political
sloganeering.
</P>
<P>
   ``This symbolism is important to the Republican side,'' said
Lew.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important to two Democratic senators are demands for
favors for their home states.
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia is threatening to filibuster the
final spending bills to protect his state's coal miners from a
federal court ruling barring the dumping of wastes into valley
streams. Byrd has drafted last-minute legislation that would stop
the court ruling from taking effect for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which first supported Bryd's effort on behalf
of his state, then opposed it and said it would veto any bill
containing it, appeared to be taking a noncommital stance on the
issue on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Kohl and the dairy dispute, which is holding up
the process of writing the final budget bill that will wrap 5 of
the year's 13 spending measures into one package.
</P>
<P>
   The dairy problem dismays most members of Congress. When the
House majority leader, Dick Armey, R-Texas, began talking about it
on the House floor, members began to moo.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the House approved a measure that lets a system
keeping the price of milk in New England artificially high to
remain in place for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has formally placed a hold on every piece of legislation
pending in the Senate, including the budget bill, to stop that
measure from becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw politics _ that's what originated it, and that's what
keeps in going,'' Kohl said in an interview on Wednesday. He
promised to ``do everything I can'' to keep the cartel from being
extended.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a provision of a 1996 farm bill that allowed the
formation of a cartel, called the Northeast Dairy Compact, which
puts a floor on the price of milk in the six New England states.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is to keep milk from Midwestern dairies out of New
England. Politicians from New England say this prevents hundreds if
not thousands of dairy farmers in their states from going under.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl calls it an attack on Wisconsin's 23,000 dairy farmers, and
a program ``diametrically opposed to everything this country stands
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Authority for the cartel expired Sept. 30, at the end of the
last fiscal year, although a judge's order has kept the pricing
mechanism in place temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the House voted, 285 to 140, to extend the system.
Midwesterners mounted a filibuster against the measure in the
Senate. A 53-47 vote to cut off debate indicated that a majority
favored the cartel.
</P>
<P>
   With those votes in mind, Hastert and Lott agreed this week to
attach a two-year extension of the cartel to one of the final
must-pass spending bills. The measure would also prevent the
secretary of agriculture from imposing a new national milk-pricing
system that would benefit dairies in the Midwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
