<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT-PACKARD RESULTS BEAT FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After warning last month of an earnings
shortfall, Hewlett-Packard Co. reported results Wednesday that beat
analysts' revised estimates by two cents, not including charges
related to the spinoff of Agilent Technologies, its test and
measurement business.
</P>
<P>
   Carleton S. Fiorina, who joined Hewlett-Packard in July as
president and chief executive, said she was setting a goal for the
year of 12 percent to 15 percent growth in revenue and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Hewlett-Packard said it had raised the price and the
number of shares of Agilent it intends to offer to the public.
Agilent, based in Palo Alto, Calif., now plans to sell a 15 percent
stake, or 65 million shares. The shares will be sold in an initial
public offering for $30, which would give the company a market
value of $13.4 billion. Last month, the company said it planned to
sell 57 million shares at $22. The revised deal would raise $1.95
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard announced its results after the close of the
market. Its shares closed at $77.4375, up $1.3125, on the New York
Stock Exchange, but still down 35 percent from their 52-week high
of $118.43. Analysts said Hewlett-Packard shares were likely to
move up now that investors could focus on future growth rather than
this quarter's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations had been talked down, annihilated, dashed,
but now we see Carly charging employees with a growth rate of 12 to
15 percent,'' said Laura Conigliaro, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co. ``Of course they have to make those numbers, but Carly's a
smart person. She knows how Wall Street works. She's not setting
these high numbers for herself to get a done-day jolt. She has to
think there is reality behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   For its fourth quarter, which ended Oct. 31, Hewlett-Packard
reported earnings of $760 million, or 73 cents a diluted share, up
7 percent from the comparable period a year ago; revenue rose 10
percent, to $11.36 billion. The quarter's earnings reflect
spinoff-related costs of 2 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Without those charges, Hewlett-Packard had earnings of 75 cents
a diluted share. Analysts had expected Hewlett-Packard to earn 73
cents, according to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the reduced expectations, it looks like a solid quarter,
but there's still work to be done,'' said Steven Milunovich, an
analyst with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revenues up 10 percent looks like what they were talking about
early in the quarter,'' before warning on Oct. 1 that earnings
would fall short, he said. ``Strong printer sales certainly had
something to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Ms. Fiorina said that after
warning analysts to expect a weaker quarter she had challenged
Hewlett-Packard employees to produce a strong October and they had
risen to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are capable of far more than our prior achievements would
indicate,'' she said. ``We need to set our goals high and stretch
to achieve them.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, at the Comdex computer trade show in Las
Vegas, Ms. Fiorina announced a $200 million global brand campaign
and a new logo to reflect what she called ``the new H.P.'' The new
logo uses the initials, without spelling out the company name, and
promotes the word invent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a company founded by inventors, fueled by invention and
adept at reinventing ourselves,'' she said Wednesday. ``But as we
look in the mirror we know we have been squandering the H.P.
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard now reports earnings on a continuing operations
basis, separating the contribution of the business units that will
be spun off as Agilent.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Agilent reported revenue of $2.4 billion, an
increase of 23 percent over the same period last year. Net earnings
for the quarter were $146 million compared to a net loss of $51
million for the same quarter in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, including the Agilent contribution,
Hewlett-Packard reported earnings of $3.49 billion, or $3.34 a
diluted share, up 19 percent from fiscal 1998. Revenue rose 7
percent, to $42.37 billion, from $39.42 billion in the prior year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
