<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-1STLEDE18-COX     11-17 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-1STLEDE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Revises last 2 grafs.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Winning Jewish voters a key test for Democrats
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia is not destined to be decisive in the battle
between Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, so
Wednesday afforded a rare opportunity to see both Democratic
presidential candidates in town on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Although they gave different sorts of presentations, both Gore
and Bradley spoke to the United Jewish Communities' first General
Assembly in the United States _ an interesting setting in which to
consider how the Democratic rivals stand.
</P>
<P>
   While Jewish voters may not play quite as central a role for
Democratic strategists as they have in the past, they are still
important to the party, not least because their sentiments are one
barometer of a much larger demographic. Many people in the
electorate, like these Jewish voters, are traditionally Democratic
but increasingly independent, more suburban and affluent than their
parents but more nervous about their identity. Winning over these
voters will be decisive in the struggle for the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the Jewish group may be unfamiliar, because it is
itself the product of an identity crisis over the past few years.
The UJC is a combination of three older organizations, brought
together under the leadership of Canadian businessman Charles
Bronfman. It may not have been entirely accidental that the Maple
Leaf was displayed between the United States and Israeli flags at
Wednesday's convocation.
</P>
<P>
   On matters such as relations with Israel and hate crimes
legislation the two candidates can make competitive claims, but the
campaign for these voters' affections revolves at this stage around
broad matters of style _ not only personal style but what that says
about where each candidate wants to lead the party.
</P>
<P>
   Keenly aware of the kinds of changes that have been necessary
within their religious and charitable community, these Democrats
may be looking at the two contenders with an eye to which can take
on a similar task in the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   As a former Knicks hero and New Jersey senator, Bradley has a
natural appeal for many Jews from the Northeast, but Gore has had
the vice presidency in which to prove himself a ``strong and
unyielding supporter,'' as he put it Wednesday, of the country's
``unshakable'' relationship with Israel. The Tennessee native even
had a list of supposed Jewish country song hits, including ``I've
Got My Foot on the Glass, Now Where Are You,'' and ``The Second
Time She Said Shalom I Knew She Meant Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told his audience he had ``so many friends in this group,''
he could walk up one aisle and down the other saying hello to them.
He went to some lengths to make a personal connection, taking
microphone in hand _ which created temporary havoc with the sound
system _ and walking in front of the podium to tell the inspiring
story of his mother, an early feminist, and his father, a crusader
for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   It was much the same schtick he would have done with retirees in
New Hampshire, but it was striking to see so open a courtship in
front of the larger group Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spoke Wednesday night in a smaller but very crowded
room. He talked about the country's need for ``a particular kind of
leader in the world today,'' and told of his leadership in standing
down the Saudis over increasing the strategic oil reserve.
</P>
<P>
   His audience listened carefully, as they had to Gore. Many of
these Democrats seemed undecided still, as the race enters a more
feverish phase.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
