<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. PLANS TO CRACK DOWN ON IRS AGENT MISDEEDS
</P>
<P>
   Urged by Congress to get tough on abuse of taxpayers, a new team
of Treasury agents plans a sharp increase in investigations of IRS
employees for misconduct. Indeed, the number of cases expected to
be opened against IRS employees will soon nearly equal the number
of cases of suspected of tax crimes. The IRS goal has stirred
worries even within the inspector general's own staff that
investigators are being forced to search for far more misdeeds than
may exist.
</P>
<P>
   SCRAMBLE FOR TECHNOLOGY WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the booming technology-based economy, companies'
long-standing scramble for qualified technical workers has taken on
an air of desperation. A severe shortage of engineers who design
hardware and software and create Web pages has led companies and
their recruiters to try all sorts of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ETHICS INQUIRY SOUGHT FOR RUBIN
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of consumer and community groups has called for a
government ethics investigation into former Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin's decision to accept employment from Citigroup, the
financial services conglomerate, contending the move presents an
``undeniable appearance of impropriety.'' Rubin said that his
decision to join Citigroup was entirely unrelated to anything he
worked on while in government.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY STAYING OUT OF PHONE BID
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from recent past reactions in Germany, political
leaders have not tried to intervene as Vodafone Airtouch of Britain
attempts the biggest hostile takeover ever _ a $100-plus billion
bid for Mannesmann, the telecommunications giant.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's board, scheduled to meet Thursday, will consider
paying as much as $125 billion in its hostile bid for Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS SLIDE ON INFLATION WORRY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks stumbled as oil prices neared three-year highs,
rekindling inflation fears. The Dow Jones industrial average closed
down 49.24 points, to 10,883.09. The Nasdaq composite index ended
with a loss of 26.13 points, at 3,269.39. The Standard and Poor's
500-stock index slipped 9.36 points, to 1,410.71, after setting a
record on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices fell for the second consecutive session as the
yield on the 30-year issue rose to 6.13 percent from 6.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BT ALEX. BROWN SETTLES SEC CASE
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said that BT Alex. Brown,
now a part of Deutsche Bank, had agreed to pay $15.3 million to
settle allegations that the brokerage firm defrauded the federal
government and the state of Pennsylvania in municipal bond
transactions in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT PROFIT BEATS ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   After warning last month of an earnings shortfall,
Hewlett-Packard posted results that beat analysts' revised
estimates. Carleton S. Fiorina, who joined Hewlett-Packard in July
as president and chief executive, said she was setting a goal for
the year of 12 percent to 15 percent growth in revenue and
earnings. Before the results were announced, shares of
Hewlett-Packard closed at $78, up $1.875.
</P>
<P>
   NTT CONFIRMS JOB CUTS OF 21,000
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, one of the world's largest phone
companies, confirmed that it planned to eliminate 21,000 jobs and
sharply curtail investment over the next three years to enhance its
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   NBC IN BROAD NEWS-SHARING DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Subsidiaries of NBC News, MSNBC and the Washington Post Company
have entered into a broad news-sharing arrangement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
