NYT-11-17-99 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3139 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      11-17 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY SAY, `AMEN' REVEREND! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Again, America is angry and confused and, again, it's
our fault.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem isn't that newspapers and TV broadcasts are filled
with bad news, but that reporters don't recognize good news when it
hap pens, as it did Tuesday, Nov. 17, when the Rev. Jesse Jackson
got himself arrested in Decatur, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has spent most of the past few weeks in Decatur. He said
after being released from the slammer, ``It's an honor to be
arrested for a righteous cause.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in America when ``righteous cause'' meant
eliminating large-scale discrimination, segrega tion and
disfranchisement.
</P>
<P>
   A ``righteous cause'' was marching through Jackson, Miss., after
crimi nal thugs murdered activist Medgar Evers.
</P>
<P>
   A ``righteous cause'' was the Civil Rights Act, the Voting
Rights Act, the establishment of the Equal Em ployment Opportunity
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the final days of the millennium, ``righteous cause''
means defending a handful of punks who got into a fight at a high
school football game.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this is reported as bad news, when clearly it
isn't. &QL; 
ARM-IN-ARM &QL; 
Jesse Jackson, who walked arm-in-arm with the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr., now walks arm-in-arm with the parents of boys expelled
for participating in a near riot during an athletic contest between
the Eisen hower Panthers and the MacArthur Generals.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower won, by the way, 25-18.
</P>
<P>
   The game was in late September.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many days afterward, the local school board decided to
expel for two years seven African-Ameri can youngsters involved in
the fight ing. One of the students withdrew from school during
expulsion hear ings. Three face criminal charges in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Students and parents complained. The local representative of
Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH organization an nounced he was going on a
hunger strike _ sort of the way Dick Gregory used to go on hunger
strikes to protest war and police brutality. Only, not.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the governor of Illinois got involved. Then, Rev. Jackson
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The school board reduced the pun ishment to one year, giving the
students the option to attend an alternative school in the
meantime. But Jackson said each of the boys' cases should be
considered indi vidually. There was a stalemate, after which
Jackson decided to get ar rested.
</P>
<P>
   The local paper in Decatur reported how things got ugly Tuesday,
Nov. 17, as Jackson approached a police line blocking the entrance
to Eisen hower High School.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't protesters causing trouble, though, it was the
lunging, pushing, bumping horde of reporters and camera operators.
</P>
<P>
   The ``sea of media representatives . . . caused the biggest
scenes and nearly knocked over a woman in a wheelchair'' wrote the
Decatur Her ald &AMP; Review. SPILLING A FEW DROPS All the usual
suspects were there. Newspapers. Radio. CNN. The net works. All of
them in Decatur, Ill., to report on a famous man and some kids who
behaved badly at a football game.
</P>
<P>
   After noting the attention Jackson received, former Ku Klux
Klansman David Duke announced he might go to Decatur to lead some
type of counterprotest.
</P>
<P>
   This entire episode may be bad news to the nice people of
Decatur, but for the rest of us it couldn't be better.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the worst problem facing our country, if this is the
top of the to-do list for America's foremost social reformer, then
these really are the best of times.
</P>
<P>
   That's the story.
</P>
<P>
   We're no longer arguing over whether the glass is half-full or
half-empty.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about a cup filled to the brim while a guy in
Decatur complains about a few drops spilling over the edge.
</P>
<P>
   During his ordeal in Illinois, Jackson has spent time with
worshipers at the Church of the Living God, praying for a
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   If, at the same time, one or two of the faithful paused to thank
the Almighty for presently going easy on us, I'd like to add this:
</P>
<P>
   Amen. E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
