<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STRIPCLUB-INDICTMENTS     11-17 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIPCLUB-INDICTMENTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta strip club hit with indictments
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Gold Club, a prominent Atlanta nude dance club, is
a den of prostitution that overbills its patrons, provides free sex
to celebrities, bribes Atlanta police officers and buys protection
from the Gambino organized crime family, federal prosecutors said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A 97-page racketeering indictment charges that the Gold Club's
owner, Steven Kaplan, intimidated his competitors by using his
Mafia ties and corrupted two Atlanta police officers in return for
special favors.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment by a federal grand jury also provides details of
numerous sex acts allegedly performed by Gold Club dancers.
According to prosecutors, Gold Club dancers performed lesbian sex
acts and prostitution for club patrons and celebrities, including
professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment contends the club paid dancers $1,000 to go to a
Charleston, S.C., hotel, where they staged a sex show and had sex
with members of an unnamed professional basketball team. The club
also sent them on sex trips to a Buckhead hotel and to Las Vegas
and Miami, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the grand jury indicted the Gold Club, Kaplan and 15
other people _ including club managers, dancers, one current and
one former Atlanta police officer and two Delta Air Lines
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities did not attempt to shut down or take
immediate control of the club. The government will attempt such a
move if it wins a criminal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's lawyers said they ``vigorously deny the allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gold Club is licensed by the city of Atlanta and has
always operated in strict compliance with the law,'' said a
statement issued by attorneys Benjamin Brafman of New York and
Steve Sadow of Atlanta. The lawyers predicted ``complete
vindication'' for Kaplan and his co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The city will allow the club to continue operating.
``Indictments are accusations, and it would be premature to revoke
their license at this point,'' said City Hall spokeswoman Zee
Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bush, the FBI's assistant special agent in charge, said,
``This is one step taken by law enforcement to eradicate the
influence of organized crime. It should also serve notice to
Georgians that organized crime is far-reaching and not limited to
cities historically associated with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, who took control of the club in 1994, is accused of
having long-standing ties to the Gambino crime family, once run by
John Gotti. In the 1980s and early 1990s, Kaplan operated clubs in
Boca Raton, Fla., and New York, where he ``refined and perfected''
his criminal activity and then brought it to Atlanta, the
indictment said. He is said to own homes in Atlanta and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accuses Kaplan and other club officials of
skimming millions of dollars in cash from club operations in order
to evade taxes and pay the Gambino family for protection.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing faded blue jeans and tennis shoes, Kaplan, 40, entered a
plea of not guilty Wednesday in federal magistrate court in
downtown Atlanta. He was released after posting a $2 million bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adult entertainment world is built on fantasy and so is
this indictment,'' said Atlanta lawyer Bruce Harvey, who represents
a dancer charged in the indictment. ``We look forward to getting
into the reality of the facts when we get into the courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's client, Jacklyn Bush, also known as ``Diva,'' and
another dancer, Jana Pelnis, known as ``Frederique,'' pleaded not
guilty to charges of prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Atlanta police Officer John
Redlinger provided protection and fixed traffic tickets for club
officials. In return, Redlinger accepted cash, food and drinks,
free use of the club's limousine and free tickets to Disney World,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Reginald Burney, another officer, notified the Gold Club when it
was about to be inspected, the indictment said. Burney, who is no
longer an Atlanta policeman, allegedly received sex and
complimentary food and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard defended her department.
``In this instance, we believe these were individual police
officers who made individual choices to tarnish their badges,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Club is popular with conventioneers, and women often
promote it by standing outside the Georgia World Congress Center
handing out free admission passes. Four golden lion statues greet
patrons at the club's front entrance. Inside, a large room with
couches and chairs is surrounded by private anterooms where naked
women dance for tips.
</P>
<P>
   Regular patrons paid for sex, the indictment said. One customer,
described only as ``G.H.,'' was charged more than $107,000 on his
credit card for prostitution and other illegal sexual favors over
six months ending in February, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Richard Deane declined to name the celebrities or
athletes who allegedly received sex.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities and athletes were ``enticed, invited and routinely
cajoled to visit the Gold Club,'' Deane said. ``...This enhanced
the reputation of the Gold Club and helped pull in other
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Most air trips made by Gold Club officials and dancers were on
Delta Air Lines. According to the indictment, two Delta ticket
managers _ Lawrence Wooten in Atlanta and Aaron Maker in New York _
arranged for club officials to receive reduced rates in exchange
for free drinks, food and other unspecified favors, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has suspended Wooten and Maker, company spokesman John
Kennedy said. The two men defrauded Delta of more than $50,000 in
airline fares, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment draws on a history of Kaplan's alleged
involvement with organized crime. Since the 1980s, Kaplan has owned
nightclubs that made payments to the Gambino family for
``protection,'' according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the indictment said, a member of the Bonanno
organized crime family tried to gain a foothold in Kaplan's
businesses in Boca Raton. Kaplan obtained help from the Gambino
family in ``removing'' an unnamed Bonanno associate from running
Club Boca's food concessions, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Kaplan and his associates have skimmed cash from his
business operations, including the Gold Club, and funneled it to
the Gambino family, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Art Leach, who is heading the
prosecution, said organized crime families expect payoffs to keep
other crime syndicates from pressuring club operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is protection in the truest sense of the word,'' Leach
said. ``If you don't go along, anything can happen, including
physical damage.'' Staff writers Scott Thurston, Ron Martz, Joshua
B. Good and Julie Hairston contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
