<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-MARTIN18-COX     11-17 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MARTIN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last race, then surgery for Martin
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Martin will run under the green flag at Sunday's
NAPA 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway. The next day, the Winston Cup
driver will go under the knife.
</P>
<P>
   Martin will have back surgery on Monday in New Smyrna Beach,
Fla. He ``chickened out'' of the operation at the last minute a
year ago but has no escape plan this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go through with it,'' Martin said Wednesday in
Marietta, Ga. ``I've decided this is what I have to do to improve
the quality of my life. So I'm going to do it and finally get it
over with.''
</P>
<P>
   The back problems have hindered one of stock-car racing's
greatest drivers over the past few years _ even though Martin
insists that the discomfort does not affect his driving.
</P>
<P>
   Martin will finish third in the Winston Cup points standings,
but it is difficult to ignore his apparent discomfort at the track.
Sometimes, he walks awkwardly to take the pressure off his back.
After wrecking at Daytona in July, the crew members of Ford No. 2
had to carry and place Martin into the car for several ensuing
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my back (problems) have had any impact on my
racing,'' Martin said. ``I think it has made it harder for me to
smile. And sometimes I didn't sign autographs when I normally might
have. That's about all.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has been bothered by back problems since the age of 18,
but the pain has intensified over the past several seasons.
Martin's frustrations peaked this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm half a man,'' Martin said at Rockingham. ``I
can't even pick up a chair or move it. Or pick up my son or bend
over and get something. There are so many things that I am limited
to doing, and, on top of that, I have knee limitations. With those
things, man, I feel useless. I feel like I have to get out of the
race car and get on the couch.'' Doctors diagnosed Martin last year
with a bulging disc. He was set to have surgery to slice off some
of the disc. During tests, however, Martin was discovered to be
suffering instead from a pair of degenerating discs in his lower
back.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has two separate discs that slide in the opposite
direction and irritate nerves when he bends his back. The new
course of direction was to graft bone from Martin's existing
vertebrae and fuse the two discstogether.
</P>
<P>
   When Martin heard about fusion suddenly being involved with the
procedure, he abruptly canceled the operation.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Martin fully understands how the surgery will work
and is mentally prepared to cope with it. He will check himself in
at 6:30 a.m. on Monday at Bert Fish Medical Center of New Smyrna
Beach, Fla. The operation will be performed by orthopedic surgeon
Charles Kollmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is anxious about it,'' team owner Jack Roush said.
``Whenever you have your back operated on, there is always a
question to the outcome. Mark could wind up with more pain, the
same pain or less pain than he has now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things are acceptable: the same pain or less pain. If it
does either, then Mark will be all right for a while. If it
worsens, it may affect how he can drive a race car. Mark was not
inclined to come back and make the judgment (to have surgery) until
he was nearing a threshold where the amount of pain was distractive
to a point that it might shorten his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's season-ending race, Martin said he will devour a
hearty breakfast. Then he won't be able to eat again until after
the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we don't have rain during the race,'' Martin said.
``That would be my luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin will remain in the hospital for at least five days.
Afterward, he will rest at his home for six to eight weeks. He
plans to attend the Winston Cup awards banquet in New York on Dec.
3, but he will have another driver test his car at Daytona in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be able to do a lot for the next two
months,'' Martin said. ``I'm going to be lying on my back on the
couch. I have to make sure that I have plenty of batteries for the
remote control.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've got a `Sanford &AMP; Son' video that I haven't watched.
My son (Matt) has some `Good Times' shows taped that he wants me to
see. I also need to do some studying for my airline-transport pilot
license.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different for me, because I'm a real active
person. I'm sure I'm not going to be happy for a while, but this is
something I need to do so I'll have a good enough body to live a
rich, full life.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MARK MARTIN FILE
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: NASCAR driver.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 40.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife Arlene and five children.
</P>
<P>
   Home: Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Background: Has finished in top five of the Winston Cup points
standings for each of the past seven years. He already has locked
up the No. 3 spot for this season. Martin will undergo back surgery
the day after Sunday's NAPA 500, to correct degenerating discs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
