<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changes for Pontiac in offing
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Winston Cup is considering changes for the Pontiac
Grand Prix, but nothing will happen at the season-ending NAPA 500
on Sunday at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no rule changes for Atlanta,'' said Kevin
Triplett, NASCAR director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nelson, the organization's Winston Cup Series director,
said last weekend that adjustments are likely in store for the
Pontiacs next season. Pontiac swept the poles and victories in each
of the past two races.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet and Ford drivers have been complaining that Pontiacs
have an unfair advantage with extra rear spoilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear us complaining when (Fords and Chevys) win
races, do you?'' said Tony Stewart, who drives the No. 20 Pontiac.
``If it's that big of deal, put one body on all (the cars).''
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER GORDON
</P>
<P>
   Jeff and Robby Gordon are no relation, but both will be
competing in Winston Cup next season. Robby announced Wednesday
that he is leaving CART to return to NASCAR. He drove in 22 Winston
Cup races for Team Sabco in 1996-97 before being released because
of personality conflicts with car owner Felix Sabates.
</P>
<P>
   Team Gordon, headed by the 30-year old driving veteran and
co-owners Mike Held and John Menard, is in the process of moving
its Southern California-based operations to the Charlotte, N.C.,
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't begin to tell you how excited I am to be returning to
NASCAR country, and I do plan to stay here this time,'' Robby said.
``This brings us back to the most popular racing series in the
world, and we're committed to being here for the long haul. In this
day and age, if you're in the business of racing, you better be
racing NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN: TITLE CONTENDER
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin won't win the Winston Cup championship this year,
but there is another family member on the brink of racing title.
Matt Martin, 7, has a slim points lead heading into Friday's season
finale of the junior novice division of the Mid-Florida Quarter
Midget Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is what he will want to do for a living
some day, and I'm not sure if this is what I want him to do, but he
is having fun and that is what's important,'' said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Matt's car travels at about 40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Extra laps
</P>
<P>
   AMS said Wednesday that approximately 12,000 reserved tickets in
the East Turn and Weaver Grandstands are available for Sunday's
race.... The purse for the NAPA 500 has increased from $2,578,392
to $2,845,192 _ the richest event in AMS's 40-year history....
Morgan Shepherd to will attempt the No. 5 Pontiac for Sunday's
event. Shepherd has three of his four career wins at AMS....
Stewart called Joe Gibbs Racing teammate Bobby Labonte to apologize
for their incident in the Pennzoil 400. Stewart bumped Labonte on
lap 249 to take the lead and eventually win the race.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
