<HEADLINE>
KNOWLEDGE GAP ON VOUCHERS AND CHARTER SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ariz., Wis., Ohio) (jt) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study suggests that a majority of Americans have little or
no understanding of what a publicly financed school voucher is, or
what distinguishes a charter school from other public schools _
even in Milwaukee, Cleveland and Arizona, which were among the
earliest places to experiment with such options.
</P>
<P>
   In a response that the authors of the study highlight as
alarmingly typical, one woman suggested that a voucher was a chit
that could be redeemed for a school uniform.
</P>
<P>
   A voucher is indeed a chit, but one that, at least as defined in
Cleveland and Milwaukee, enables some students to attend parochial
or other private schools at public expense.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, nearly 1,700 charter schools have opened in 28
states; they are largely exempt from union contracts and other
regulations that govern most other public schools, but must
demonstrate specific progress within a designated period of time or
risk being closed.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the study, which was made public on Tuesday,
interviewed more than 1,200 adults selected randomly across the
country, as well as 208 parents in those communities that
participate in voucher or charter experiments. The study, which was
conducted by Public Agenda, a nonpartisan educational organization,
has a margin of sampling error of 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The authors maintain that public officials, educators and
journalists have largely failed to educate the public on the merits
or distinguishing characteristics of such academic alternatives.
Deborah Wadsworth, the executive director of Public Agenda, said
the study showed that ``even the community leaders themselves have
a limited grasp of the essentials of this debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found, for example, that 63 percent of those
interviewed reported knowing ``very little'' or ``nothing'' about
vouchers. Even in communities that have voucher programs, that
figure was 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The general public reported knowing even less about charter
schools, with 81 percent of those interviewed saying they knew
little or nothing about such schools. In communities with charter
schools, the figure was 52 percent.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
