<HEADLINE>
NO BAD FEELINGS THIS TIME AS DAVENPORT TOPS MAURESMO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was back to basics Wednesday night at the Chase
Championships: Lindsay Davenport and Amelie Mauresmo kept things
impersonal in their opening-round match at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   They put aside their checkered past, that awkward Australian
Open moment when the disgruntled Davenport reacted to her semifinal
surrender to the then 29th-ranked Frenchwoman by accusing her of
hitting the ball like a person of a different gender; a person of
the wrong gender to be performing on the WTA Tour. A person whose
avowed lesbianism also gained her the label of ``half a man'' from
top-ranked Martina Hingis, who merrily and mercilessly throttled
Mauresmo in the Australian final.
</P>
<P>
   That particular fence was never properly mended, but Mauresmo
made her peace with Davenport, who quickly sent her a note of
apology and publicly praised Mauresmo's rippling one-handed
backhand and rippling musculature as a strength and a weapon, not a
curiosity. By the time the hard-hitting duo hit the court Wednesday
night, their rivalry was evenly proportioned at 2-2, and the
second-seeded Davenport made it clear she didn't take this opponent
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   After an ineffectual opening set in which Mauresmo surged to a
3-0 lead and Davenport, hobbled by a sore left thigh, seemed
disinclined to play catch-up until Mauresmo was serving for the set
at 5-1. The 1999 Wimbledon champion upped the ante and inflicted a
3-6, 6-3, 6-2 reversal of fortune on her challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Daveport said she was injured Sunday in Philadelphia, where she
won the Advanta Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sore, but what can you do?'' Davenport said. ``It's the
end of the year; I'm not dying, but it's tough to play. The more I
played, the more I got used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing can't-miss tennis in the early stages of the first
set, Mauresmo proceeded to play all-miss tennis in the next two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could have won this one,'' said Mauresmo, whose
actions did not back up her mental meanderings. ``On this surface,
you know, you miss, you make a winner. It's up and down all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was all downhill for Mauresmo after the opening set.
</P>
<P>
   Mauresmo had so much trouble winning that set once Davenport
bestirred herself from her early trance that she bungled four set
points, the fourth with a double fault, before sealing the set, a
hint of fallibility to come. Davenport roared through the middle
set, and in the third, she amassed a 4-0 lead before Mauresmo
collected her weapons and began to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   The morning match, watched by 2,000 customers, not all of them
paying, and contested between two best friends, produced an upset:
17th-ranked Anke Huber, a 1995 Chase finalist who barely squeaked
into this year's event, ousted ninth-seeded Julie Halard-Decugis,
6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Huber, the maid of honor at Halard's wedding to her coach,
Arnaud Decugis, attributed her success against her friend to her
serve, which yielded six aces and was unbreakable Wednesday. The
two had a 3-3 record in previous encounters, but Huber confused
Halard-Decugis by mixing things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I changed a little bit my game,'' the German said. ``I think
she just never knew where I was serving to. It was just a very good
day; not every day is like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Huber said she needed to have a banner day in her quarterfinal
against Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Lindsay, I lost the last, I don't know, five, six,
seven times,'' Huber said. ``But now it doesn't matter. I'll try to
do my best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played eight weeks in a row, but I'm still alive and I'm
trying,'' said Huber, who reached a career-high fourth in the
rankings five years ago but has battled recurring injuries in the
interim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
