<SLUG> BC-BBN-HUMMER-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hats off to `Larry'
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They sang it out from the press boxes of the National
League in a strong and unified voice Wednesday. ``Lahr-Ree,
Lahr-Ree, Lahr-Ree'' came the chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wayne Jones, Chipper to those not from New York, took his
first MVP award in the same way he took out the regular-season
Mets. He dominated, collecting 29 of 32 first-place Baseball
Writers votes. This landslide went uphill, carrying Jones along to
his place atop Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Just 391 days ago, the Braves' third baseman appeared in these
pages beneath headlines that read ``Tarnished Golden Boy'' and
``Another Fallen Idol Disappoints.'' They dealt with his
confessions of adultery and fathering a son out of wedlock. Not the
recommended preparation for a Most Valuable Season, but Jones
somehow kept the personal embarrassment in its own little box for
the bulk of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This was an award for dealing with it as much as it was an award
for turning on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just being able to separate the two (the broken
marriage and the soaring career),'' Jones said. ``There were times
in my career when I couldn't, and it had an effect on the way I
played the game. I can remember one time in Philadelphia going into
Bobby's office and apologizing to him for how bad I was playing,
thinking I owed him an explanation. It goes back to my immediate
family and the handful of close friends that I have, being able to
have them act almost as therapists to help me deal with things.
Then rededicating myself to my workouts and my career.''
</P>
<P>
   The favorite son of Atlanta baseball would follow the path cut
by his own Braves model, Dale Murphy. Of course, on certain levels,
Jones never can measure up. As strictly a player, the parallels are
there. He got his first MVP at 27, Murphy at 26. And no one would
be shocked if Jones defended the title, just like Murph. Even
without Don Baylor here to hold his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Once Jones stumbled, he went immediately to work to spackle his
image. The repair job has been remarkable. From heel to Most
Valuable Player in 13 short months. Short of entering a monastery,
this award was the next best fix. His was the performance of a man
trying to make it right the only way he knows how.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out and put a good product on the field and you let
everybody know that you are genuinely apologetic for what happened,
stand up for it like a man, people respect you a lot more for it,''
he said. ``The best way to make people forget about something bad
that happened is to go out, play as hard as you can, put up career
numbers and let them know you haven't changed as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   The morality play aside, Jones has been an MVP in waiting.
Credit him for cultivating an undeniable talent. Once he added a
little pop from the right side, Jones became positively
frightening. Opponents couldn't walk him quickly enough. He got
more free passes in a season than Kato Kaelin has in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the kind of talent that will be quite expensive to keep
beyond the one year left on his contract. When he says, ``I was
born an Atlanta Brave and would like to stay one as long as
possible,'' write it down. He'll not repeat it much during
negotiating sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Jones' arrival as MVP was immaculate. It applied a
little spit-shine to the image and uplifted the man himself. ``A
wonderful year, all around,'' he can even say now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
