<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rider to play off the bench
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Isaiah Rider returned Wednesday to the Hawks as the
team's sixth man, after a one-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   And Rider, who is unhappy with the assignment, and the team will
have to co-exist for the remaining 74 games, because Hawks
management says it plans no changes. Coach Lenny Wilkens told Rider
that his role would be like that of high-scoring guard Fred Brown
on the coach's 1979 NBA championship team in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred Brown affected the outcome of games in so many ways
(that) to strictly describe him only as a shooter is inaccurate,''
Wilkens said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach also said that Rider's role off the bench is not
permanent. ``It doesn't mean he will never be a starter,'' Wilkens
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rider, however, thinks that the sixth-man role might cast him in
the one-dimensional role of a shooter. ``It's not about starting,''
said Rider, who has started three games this season. But he went on
to question why ``a coach of Lenny's caliber would not want a
player with my talent to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider played well off the bench against Milwaukee and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks do not dispute Rider's talent. They say they
understand that he wants to play 40 minutes a game and lead the
team in scoring and passing while helping them win a lot of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the same things,'' team president Stan Kasten said.
</P>
<P>
   No trade is in the offing, the Hawks say. ``We've had some very
preliminary talks with some teams, but I can't tell you anything is
going to happen,'' general manager Pete Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said that Rider did not ask for a trade after being
suspended for Tuesday's game against Charlotte. However, he said
that Rider had asked earlier to be traded. ``He changes his mind,''
the general manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Rider reiterated Wednesday that he does not want to be on a
``rebuilding team at this stage of my career.'' But last week he
said he would accept a trade to a bad team so he ``can be the
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said he has no regrets over the deal that brought Rider
and Jim Jackson here from Portland, in exchange for All-Star Steve
Smith and Ed Gray, who is out of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do this for one season. We did it so that we would
be players in the free-agent market over the next few years,''
Babcock said. ``That goal has not changed. In fact, we're more
committed than ever to bringing in a superstar, and making that
deal was the only way we could hope to accomplish that goal over
the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten said he and Babcock agreed on the trade. ``We had our
eyes wide open,'' Kasten said. ``This wasn't Pete's deal, not by a
long shot. One man doesn't make those kinds of decisions in our
organization (Turner Sports). One man doesn't make baseball trades,
and one man doesn't make basketball deals. For that reason, the
Hawks will not eat Rider's $5.4million contract simply to be rid of
him. It would create problems with the salary cap and enormous
expenses in paying off a player while getting nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   However, it does not mean that Rider might not be suspended
without pay for extend periods, ultimately for an entire season, if
the Hawks had cause.
</P>
<P>
   Rider has been late for virtually every bus ride, every practice
and every game this season. He was suspended for skipping practice
Monday to take care of personal business involving his cars.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is ``unfortunate and regrettable'' Kasten said,
``but only from the standpoint of how it's turning out. It was a
gamble, and at this point that gamble was a failure, (but) we're
not close to giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we had our eyes open. It was a one-year contract. We also
got Jim Jackson, and we drafted Dion Glover and if the worst that
happens is that it hurts us for one year, weigh that against the
risk of Smitty getting old with four years on his contract.... You
have to take risks in sports. I'm convinced of that. History tells
us that. And that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
