<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aggregate score sends England past Scotland
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lionhearts held on against the Bravehearts.
</P>
<P>
   England's 2-0 win over Scotland in the first leg of the Euro
2000 playoffs on Saturday was just enough for the Lionhearts to
defeat the Bravehearts _ as the tabloids love to call them _ in the
ballyhooed ``Battle of Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   Just barely enough.
</P>
<P>
   A header in the 38th minute by Everton striker Don Hutchison at
Wembley in Wednesday's finale gave the Scots hope of repeating
their famous victory in London in 1977. But that's all they could
manage, despite winning 1-0. England advances to next summer's
finals in The Netherlands and Belgium on a 2-1 aggregate score.
</P>
<P>
   The English hero in Glasgow was Manchester United midfielder
Paul Scholes, whose disciplinary record with both club and country
lately has been notorious. He scored twice in the first half as
England overcame its mediocrity under coach Kevin Keegan.
</P>
<P>
   But improving enough to make a good impression next summer is
another thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic of Ireland, injury- and suspension-riddled, was
eliminated after a scoreless draw with Turkey in Istanbul. The
teams were 1-1 on aggregate, but the Turks advance because their
score came as an away goal on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia got a 74th-minute goal from Miran Pavlin to earn a 1-1
draw with the Ukraine in Minsk and advance on a 3-2 aggregate. Each
country was seeking its first European Championships berth since
gaining independence after the fall of the Iron Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark had little to fear from Israel after winning the first
leg 5-0 but still rolled to a 3-0 win in Copenhagen for good
measure and an 8-0 aggregate. The only negative was the 17th-minute
removal of goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel, who has been hampered by
injury this season for Sporting Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: FOUR PLAYOFF SPOTS LEFT
</P>
<P>
   Four of Mexico's powerhouses have secured spots in the Torneo
Invierno playoffs that begin Wednesday. But Guadalajara's hopes
rest on a win Sunday against lowly Santos (1 p.m., Univision) in
the last game of the regular season. Chivas blew a chance to
qualify last week against city rivals UAG Tecos, which got goals in
the 81st minute from Zdenko Muf and in the 89th minute from
Sebastian Abreu for a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Toluca, Cruz Azul, America and Atlas already are in. In Group 1,
UAG and UNAM Pumas are battling it out against Atlante and Celaya,
respectively. Morelia, Puebla and Celaya have chances in Group 2.
Morelia has the upper hand, closing out against eliminated Leon (1
p.m., Telemundo). Group 3 is more complicated. Necaxa leads
Guadalajara and Pachuca but needs a win over America. Pachuca meets
reigning Torneo Verano champion Toluca.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS: FAVORITES ON ROAD
</P>
<P>
   After taking a deep breath, the 16 teams remaining in the
European Champions league begin the second round of group play on
Tuesday, with most of the favored clubs starting out on the road.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Barcelona travels to Hertha Berlin and defending
champion Manchester United heads to Italy to play Fiorentina. Serie
A leaders Lazio meet Olympique Marseille in the southern French
city on Wednesday (2:30 p.m., ESPN2). Real Madrid will have a new
manager as it opens at Dynamo Kyiv. Bayern Munich is banged up and
has a tricky contest in Trondheim against Norwegian champion
Rosenborg.
</P>
<P>
   The other matchups are Porto at Sparta Prague, Girondins de
Bordeaux at Valencia and Feyenoord at Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: TOSHACK SACKED
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid president Lorenzo Sanz said he fired embattled
manager John Toshack on Wednesday for publicly deriding his players
in the Spanish press. But the Welshman's fate in the
pressure-cooker job probably was sealed when the club got off to a
poor start. Toshack, first sacked by Real Madrid in 1990, got the
ax despite qualifying for the second round of the Champions League
and getting a thrilling 3-2 win last week over Primera Division
leaders Rayo Vallecano. Afterward, Toshack lashed out at the play
of third-string goalkeeper Albano Bizarri, who has been erratic all
season. Toshack, signed to a 16-month contract in February, has no
regrets about his criticisms: ``It's more likely for pigs to fly
over Bernabeu Stadium than for me to take back what I said.''
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: INNOCENTI SUSPENDED
</P>
<P>
   Bari defender Duccio Innocenti might have thought he got away
with crushing the cheekbone of Perugia's Renato Olive during a Nov.
6 Serie A match, but video doesn't lie. Innocenti wasn't carded for
the offense, which took place far away from the ball, but the
league issued a four-match suspension after seeing a replay. It's
the third such action taken against a Serie A player this season.
Olive said he might file a lawsuit. GERMANY: BASLER GETS NEW CLUB
</P>
<P>
   The close proximity of Oktoberfest and Munich's night life got
Bayern Munich midfielder Mario Basler into so much trouble that he
was forced to find a new club. On Tuesday, he signed with
Kaiserslautern, which is near Germany's Mosel River wine country.
He was brought on at the behest of manager Otto Rehhagel, for whom
he played at Werder Bremen, which won two Bundesliga titles in the
mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PALERMO INJURED
</P>
<P>
   Boca Juniors striker Martin Palermo scored the 100th goal of his
career in a 2-1 victory Sunday over Colon, but a freak injury later
in the game could put him out of action for as long as nine months.
Palermo, who is set to join Lazio after the Apertura season ends in
December, tore knee ligaments falling off balance after being hit
in the leg with a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
