<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; VOICECHAT  &LR;  _ First, people used chat rooms to type instant
messages to one another. Now, they're going a step beyond and
talking to each other out loud in real time. Hundreds of thousands
of people have downloaded software to participate in `voice chat.`
Instead of merely typing messages back and forth, people are
talking into their computers and hearing the spoken responses of
others from around the world. A slew of Bay Area companies are
developing the technology to enable voice chat and users say they
love the service. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
