 _ SF CHRON  
 Activists Seek Revised State Lending Rules for Banks  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Two leading California activist groups yesterday urged state
lawmakers to tighten community lending rules for banks, filling a
gap created by a recent weakening of the federal Community
Reinvestment Act.
<P>
   In testimony at a San Francisco hearing of the Assembly Banking
and Finance Committee, Robert Gnaizda, policy director of the
Greenlining Institute, and Alan Fisher, executive director of the
California Reinvestment Committee, called for legislation to
stiffen reporting requirements on bank lending in low-income
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an opportunity for the state to step in and pass a
disclosure law,'' Gnaizda said in an interview. Data could be used
to rate bank performance and eventually allow California to set
minimum community lending standards for any institution that does
business with the state, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   There are now federal, but no state, requirements for banks to
report how much credit they extend in low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Assemblyman Louis Papan, D-Millbrae,
said Sacramento lawmakers may consider such legislation during
sometime in  &LR; the current session.
</P>
<P>
   Introduction of a state community lending bill ``is a
possibility,'' Papan said. ``What we're thinking of is to provide
standard reporting on community reinvestment.''
</P>
<P>
   The reporting provisions would affect only state-licensed banks
_ mostly smaller institutions _ and would be designed to supplement
similar rules regulating banks with federal charters, such as Bank
of America and Wells Fargo, Papan said.
</P>
<P>
   The push for state reporting rules follows final approval
earlier this month of a landmark federal banking bill that includes
provisions easing community lending standards. standard. &LR;   &LR; Under
the new law, federal regulators now review the lending records of
small banks once every four or five years, instead of the previous
schedule of exams every year or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great deal of concern about small banks,'' said the
CRC's Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Since passage of the Community Reinvestment Act almost three
decades ago, banks have made hundreds of billions of dollars of
mortgages, small-business loans and other credits in low-income
neighborhoods they once avoided. By the 1990s, multibillion-dollar
community loan pledges had become a routine part of large bank
merger announcements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
