<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3170 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     11-17 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Imagine Starts Maximum Digital Revolution 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Imagine Media, a Brisbane tech publishing company, plans to launch
five magazines next year.
<P>
   Galvanized by the success of its Business 2.0 magazine, which in
little more than a year has grown into a profitable, fat New
Economy monthly, Imagine is looking to expand into more
consumer-oriented mags.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which made its name with gamer mags and MacAddict
for Macintosh computer users, plans publications devoted to digital
photography, the online music revolution, electronic gadgets and
movies. It does have a geeky offering in the works as well: Maximum
Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine plans to hire 150 people, bringing its U.S. employment
to more than 400. The company is about ready to burst beyond its
Brisbane office space, where most of those people work, and is
looking for new space.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Paris, where he had gone for a
company board of directors meeting, Imagine chief executive Chris
Anderson gushed about the success of Business 2.0 and the prospects
for the year ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine has kind of snuck in under a lot of people's radar,''
Anderson said. He noted that its parent company, the Future Network
PLC, went public on the London Stock Exchange in June and has
doubled in value since then. ``Because it took place in London, no
one really heard about it,'' he said. But it gave the company ``the
resources and motivation to go for a big growth spurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the success of Business 2.0, which will
have a guaranteed subscriber base of 210,000 readers and ad pages
nearly tripling this month to 207 pages, gave Imagine new
credibility with media buyers and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what's happened this year, morale is sky-high,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the first half of 2000 will see the launch of
Maximum Linux, Digital Foto and the music magazine, to be called
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   As a magazine covering the hot open-source Linux software,
Maximum Linux is almost a no-brainer; the company put out a
``one-shot publication this autumn, and the thing blew out the
doors,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution will face a more competitive landscape, but Anderson
said it, too, is a natural. Business 2.0 covers the way the
Internet changes all business; the same thing is happening in
music, he said. The new mag will ``reflect the way people find,
listen to and buy music,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Revolution will give out a CD with songs on it,
much the way Imagine's gamer mags give out CDs with game promos?
``There's an insightful question which I can't answer,'' Anderson
said, chuckling. ``Done right, that would have huge consumer
appeal. I don't want to say anything else about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital Foto will give tips on buying and using digital cameras.
Anderson was tight-lipped about the other ventures, which are due
out in the latter part of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much about these subjects _ Linux, music, photography
_ is covered on the Web, but Anderson is a big believer in print.
He doesn't even have the domain names sewn up for Revolution or
Digital Foto, although he does have online partnerships in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he doesn't own www.imagine.com, either, and he seems
to be doing all right in tech publishing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INDEPENDENTS DAY: &QL; 
The Northern California Independent Booksellers Association likes
to take on the corporate titans of the publishing industry and was
therefore heartened to see Chronicle Books this week remain in the
hands of local ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Nion McEvoy, a member of the family that owns Chronicle
Publishing Co., bought Chronicle Books from his relatives for an
undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled it's him and not Bertelsmann from Germany,'' said
Hut Landon, the association's executive director and the owner of
Landon Books in Mill Valley. ``I was glad it was sold to a local
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Roxane Farmanfarmaian, West Coast editor of Publishers Weekly,
agreed. ``It's unusual, in this era of conglomeration, to have a
publishing company become an independent. There are pitfalls, but
there are also opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Books is ``flourishing,'' she said, and has a strong
distribution program, selling the books from other presses, which
should give it an edge. ``In this dog-eat-dog world of bookselling
these days, it's very tough to be a small publisher in the face of
Bertelsmann and Penguin, to stand out and make yourself heard.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the experience of Harper San Francisco was ``a classic
case of what Chronicle didn't want to get into, becoming the
California outpost of a New York publisher.'' She was alluding to
Harper Collins management, which revamped the business and laid off
workers in the early 1990s. When that effort failed, Harper San
Francisco returned to its roots as a spiritual publisher, and it is
successful, albeit smaller than it once was, she said.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy could face pressure, as he'll need to pay back the loans
that enabled him to buy Chronicle Books. But ``it could have gone
to someone who knew nothing about books,'' Landon said. ``Big
conglomerates don't care about books. Their heart isn't in it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOOD TIMES ON THESTREET &QL; 
I thought the New York Times did a pretty good job with business
coverage, but I guess the Gray Lady needs to call in some relief.
This week, it launched a newsroom in a joint venture with
TheStreet.com, with six reporters and a Times assistant business
editor producing content to run on the Web sites of both TheStreet
and the Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Times was already an investor in TheStreet, and the new
newsroom will further lend the newspaper's prestige to the upstart
Internet financial news organization.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet also plans to announce that it has hired Jonathan
Krim, former assistant managing editor of the San Jose Mercury
News, to be its new  &LR; executive editor. That post has been vacant
since early this year, when Jamie Heller became editor of strategic
ventures for the company _ endeavors like the joint New York Times
newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Krim started looking when the Merc brought back
Susan Goldberg, a former Merc editor who spent 10 years at USA
Today, to be managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the CEO gone, the stock price down and talk buzzing
about lower revenues amid bulk subscription discounts, TheStreet's
Editor in Chief Dave Kansas said things are looking up. His spin:
The company has $130 million cash in the bank, a new CEO, new blood
like Krim, and the New York Times deal. ``Things are going pretty
well,'' he said. ``Call me Pollyanna.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW MONEY FOR MARKETWATCH &QL; 
Meanwhile, MarketWatch.com, TheStreet's San Francisco rival in
financial news, has a new corporate backer: the Financial Times of
London. The peach-colored broadsheet reported an $800 million
merger this week with Data Broadcasting Corp., which owns a 32
percent stake in MarketWatch.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, MarketWatch said CEO Larry Kramer would take on the
title of chairman, relinquishing the role of president to Philip D.
Hotchkiss, founder and CEO of BigCharts.com, a company that
MarketWatch acquired last June.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KRAMER VS. CRAMER REDUX &QL; 
I just happened to like reading MarketWatch's coverage of its rival
TheStreet.com's appointment of a new CEO. The November 7 story
about Thomas Clarke succeeding Kevin English, who resigned, quoted
a former CBS New Media exec as saying that it's a ``real problem''
when senior management leaves so soon after a company goes public.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, MarketWatch is closely allied with CBS New Media, as
a Web property in which CBS Corp. holds a 32 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The article also included this parenthetical clarification about
TheStreet co-founders and board members James Cramer and Martin
Peretz: ``Cramer said a report by CBS.MarketWatch.com that Peretz
and he are no longer talking to one another was untrue. `Marty and
I talk three times a day, every day. We reconciled five months ago,
and I toasted him at his 60th (birthday),' Cramer said in a note to
MarketWatch.com this weekend. `We work closely together.'
CBS.MarketWatch.com apologizes for the error.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, the final knife: Although TheStreet has been a
forceful advocate for opening up company conference calls to
investors _ it was TheStreet's Adam Lashinsky who scored a big
scoop by weaseling his way into a Webvan conference call, garnering
information that forced the company to delay its IPO _ MarketWatch
noted that the company doesn't necessarily practice what it
preaches. In talking to investors about the CEO succession, the
article noted, ``The media company on Friday closed off its
conference call to reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
