<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-ADS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Kia Dismisses S.F. Ad Agency as Too Small  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Kia Motors America yesterday dismissed San Francisco's Goldberg
Moser O'Neill after six years as its advertising agency, saying it
was too small to handle the South Korean automaker's growing U.S.
business.
<P>
   The Kia account this year comprised $75 million of GMO's $550
million in media billings.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Goldberg, GMO's chief executive, said his agency will start
looking for a new auto account immediately. He denied that GMO's
size was the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think this is more of a financial issue,'' Goldberg
said. ``Their business is going up, but our fees are going down.''
The two companies argued over their 1999 contract for 18 months and
just signed it last week, Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kia sales are 61 percent above last year, so the decision to
terminate GMO was not a result of slow sales or bad creative,''
said Dick Macedo, Kia's executive vice president, marketing, in a
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be launching three new models in the next 12 months,''
Macedo said. ``Unfortunately, GMO is unable to support our needs _
and our dealers' needs _ during this incredible growth period for
Kia.''
</P>
<P>
   Kia is negotiating with a new agency, the release said. Kia
executives could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   One source speculated that the Kia account could go to Bates
USA, the ad shop used by Hyundai Motors, which bought Kia in a
bankruptcy court auction last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles office of DDB Needham also has a foot in the
door since Kia has hired that agency for special projects.
</P>
<P>
   GMO's other accounts include Cisco Systems and K.B. Toys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
