<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SCHWAB </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Schwab Has New Investing Tool for IPOs  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
IPO road shows _ in which soon-to-be-public companies make their
pitch to big-bucks institutional investors _ are finally going to
be open to individual investors as well.
<P>
   Well, the richer ones anyway.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Charles Schwab Corp. has received a green light
from the Securities and Exchange Commission to broadcast road show
proceedings via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Because the SEC's approval came in the form of a ``no-action
letter,'' which sets a regulatory standard that applies to all
market players, other online brokers theoretically could air road
shows for initial public offerings as well.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that Schwab specifically asked for permission to
make road show information available to its ``Signature Gold''
clients _ those with at least $500,000 in assets at the brokerage _
as well as for its fee-based investment advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Less-well-heeled Schwab investors will remain barred from road
shows, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   the time being.  &LR; ``Ideally, over time, we'd like to expand it,''
said Greg Gable, a spokesman for the company.
</P>
<P>
   As for rival brokerages, it's unclear whether the SEC's letter
would confine their own road show activities only to investors with
half a million bucks worth of assets.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Merrill Lynch in New York said the brokerage is
interested in this matter but declined to comment further.
Representatives of E-Trade Group and Ameritrade Holding Corp. could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of access to IPO road shows has been a bone of contention
among many individual investors. They resent that institutional
investors are given inside information about a company's prospects
before the initial share offering.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, that information is significantly more detailed
than what is generally available to the public via a company's
prospectus or SEC filings.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, institutional investors and a small number of
``accredited'' individual investors _ the ones with oodles of cash
_ can log on to a handful of Internet services providing real-time
and taped road show presentations.
</P>
<P>
   While Schwab's Signature Gold clients have considerably more
market exposure than most individual investors, they are still well
below the asset threshold of the typical ``accredited'' investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant change,'' Schwab's Gable said. ``It's a
step toward the democratization of what had been a closed market.''
</P>
<P>
   While the road show access would be Internet-based, he stressed
that this is not intended as a way to compel more customers to
become online traders.
</P>
<P>
   Gable said a number of Schwab clients have asked for access to
IPO road shows because they felt ``left out'' of high-flying share
offerings. It's not uncommon for an Internet company's IPO to post
spectacular short-term gains.
</P>
<P>
   Also this week, Schwab said it is joining with Ameritrade and TD
Waterhouse Group to form an online investment bank. The goal is to
secure a greater number of IPO shares from Wall Street
underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Grodsky, director of research at Grodsky Associates in
New Jersey, said providing more access to IPOs will help Schwab
retain wealthier clients in the face of increased competition from
full-service brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them an extra something that they didn't have
before,'' Grodsky said. ``It's a clear plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Gable said Schwab's impression of the SEC's letter is that
regulatory authorities want to proceed slowly in granting more
individuals access to road shows. He said the SEC likely wants to
see how the Signature Gold clients respond before allowing greater
access.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
