<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MVP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong finish closes deal
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The can't-miss kid just hit the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones, 27, welcomed himself to the prime of his career
with an MVP season, something that was confirmed on Wednesday when
he won the National League Most Valuable Player award in a
landslide. The 156 points that separated him from runner-up Jeff
Bagwell was the third-highest margin of victory this decade behind
Bagwell in 1994 and Sammy Sosa last season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was voted first on 29 of the 32 ballots by the Baseball
Writers Association of America, second on two and third on one for
a total of 432 points. Bagwell, who received one first-place vote
and 20 seconds, was second overall with 276 points and Matt
Williams was third with 269 points. They were the only players
chosen on all 32 ballots, two from each NL city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tickled pink that he won,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said
from the Cayman Islands, where he is vacationing. ``He absolutely
deserves it. He was extremely important to our pennant race this
season. I can't think of a better player to win the award.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Jones became the front-runner during the
first Mets series in September, when he hit four home runs to spoil
New York's division title hopes, but Jones prefers to think of the
last two months of the season as the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game we played the last two months was a playoff game,''
Jones said. ``You're running on pure adrenaline. To go out for the
last two months when every pitch, every swing, every out, every
inning is big, you'll be surprised what you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   What he did was hit a career-high .319 and a career-high 45 home
runs, score 116 runs, drive in 111 runs and steal 25 bases. He
finished in the top 10 in the league in 10 major offensive
categories to help the Braves to their eighth division title this
decade. But it really shouldn't have been that much of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jones signed with the Braves in 1990 as the first overall
pick in the draft, he has always played under the highest
expectations, and he has yet to disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a perfectionist,'' Jones said. ``I hate when I make an
error. I can't stand striking out. I hate the hundreds of ground
balls I hit to second base. I don't want to get thrown out
stealing. If we're in a dire situation and I don't come through,
that bugs me for days until I get the chance to do it again. Nobody
is going to put any more pressure on me than myself. That's what
keeps me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has had his eye on winning this award since he was a
child. ``I grew up watching Dale Murphy,'' Jones said, flashing his
famous boyish grin. ``Dale was the man. I saw him win back-to-back
MVPs in '82 and '83. I thought how great it would be to be standing
in his shoes one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   And like Murphy, Jones wants to stick around Atlanta for a
while, though it'll cost the Braves to make it happen. Jones is
entering the final year of his current contract _ the Braves
exercised their option to pay him $4 million this year. After
signing a relatively modest contract in 1996 _ worth $12 million
over five years _ Jones will command that kind of money annually
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic that I can stay as a Brave,'' Jones said.
``I was born an Atlanta Brave. I would like to stay here as long as
possible. I like to think (general manager) John Schuerholz and I
have a good rapport and the lines of communication are open. I'm
sure we'll be on the phone with each other pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in his interests and our interests to (re-sign Jones),''
Schuerholz said. ``The lines of communication have been
established. We're hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
