<HEADER>
A3175 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VOICECHAT-VOICECHAT_S     11-17 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICECHAT-VOICECHAT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New voice technology lets people `chat' out loud _ online  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
When Billie Lemmerman starts to feel lonely, the 74-year-old widow
boots up her computer and heads to a chat room on the Internet for
some conversation.
<P>
   But instead of just typing a message and waiting for a written
response, the Stockton resident is actually chatting _ using her
voice to talk in real-time with others online.
</P>
<P>
   Online ``chat'' is evolving from a crude, written form of
communication to a multimedia experience, allowing users to hold
oral conversations via the Internet with friends, relatives,
strangers and business associates.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmerman, like millions of other Net users, is using a
technology called voice chat _ turning the computer into a giant
speakerphone that lets her talk with others around the globe at no
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is gaining popularity as major Web portals like
Excite, Yahoo and AltaVista incorporate it into their existing chat
features. And businesses looking for cheaper ways to communicate
with customers, vendors and employees also are beginning to use
voice chat instead of plain old e-mail or even the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people like about voice chat is that it adds personality
to the whole interaction process,'' said Paul Matteucci, president
of HearMe.com  &LR;   &LR; of Mountain View, which provides voice-chat
technology. ``It's like the difference between using the telephone
and writing a letter. Hearing a voice conveys emotion and
personality. That's particularly important when it comes to
strangers coming together in a community site.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, instead of guessing whether Jester182 was flirting with
you, chat room users can hear the subtle inflections that help
people gauge the context of a conversation. And unlike picking up a
telephone, the service is free and allows lots of people to
participate. Although you can talk to large numbers of people
through telephone voice-conferencing, it's expensive, cumbersome
and primarily used by businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Voice chat works by downloading special  &LR; software off the Web
onto your computer's hard drive. With speakers and a microphone,
users can hold a conversation with one or hundreds of people on the
Web. Or they can opt just to type text messages and listen to
others in the room. Like regular chat, there is some latency &LR; 
 &LR; delay so that not everybody talks at once.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VOICECHA (43424 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The software is available on major portal sites such as Yahoo,
Excite and AltaVista, as well as from www.hearme.com and
www.lipstream.com _ two of the companies that developed the
technology and supply it to portals and other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Once the software is downloaded, users can participate in
one-on-one conversations or head to a karaoke room to sing en masse
with dozens of other voice chatters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have more and more computers that are coming
equipped with microphones and speakers, voice chat is a natural
outgrowth of traditional chat rooms,'' said Larry Gerbrandt, an
analyst with Paul Kagan Associates in Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an obvious limitation to chat rooms, and that is how
fast you can type.'' With voice, people are limited only by how
fast they can speak, Gerbrandt said.
</P>
<P>
   For those who like to chat, the technology may seem a smidgen
too personal. After all, one of the things chat room users seem to
like most is the anonymity that it provides. On the Web, a chat
room user can be anybody they want _ a teenager, a Southern
debutante, an Englishman. But once voice is incorporated, fooling
others into thinking you're from the French Riviera may be a bit
trickier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, companies providing voice chat say that after a while,
most people want to take the chat experience a step beyond written
words. Voice chat is the bridge between traditional chat and
picking up the telephone and calling somebody, said Matteucci of
HearMe.
</P>
<P>
   For people like Lemmerman, hearing a voice _ even if it's a
stranger's _ is crucial at times when she's feeling lonely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started using voice chat because I'm old and I get lonesome
and to hear a voice is nice,'' she said. Lemmerman, who visits chat
rooms for people over 50, said that last week she met a man from
her hometown in England and had a 10-minute conversation with him.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Ike DeLorenzo, use it for business. DeLorenzo's San
Francisco Web engineering firm, Parlez Communications, uses voice
chat to communicate with employees in Montreal and Europe, as well
as with customers.
</P>
<P>
   The firm likes to hold virtual meetings, where staff can meet
online and share files, look at charts and discuss details
simultaneously. They do this through a company called WebX, which
recently added voice chat as a service. San Jose's WebX offers a
Web site, www.webex.com, that allows businesses to share
applications and documents online.
</P>
<P>
   Before voice chat, ``the weak link was the fact that we could
communicate a lot of code design and schematics with our people
working in Montreal and overseas, but then we had to pick up the
telephone to communicate with them while we were online,''
DeLorenzo said.
</P>
<P>
   With voice chat, DeLorenzo said, ``I don't have to keep track of
everyone's number or who's going to originate the conference call.
I just start the meeting, everybody talks over the computer, and my
office phone line stays free.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the company's phone bills have dropped dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The portals that offer the service say it's one of the most
popular features, with thousands of people downloading the software
from Yahoo, AltaVista and Excite.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Park, senior producer for Yahoo, said the portal added
voice chat as a logical extension of regular chat. The company also
is letting users record and send voice e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if you're a telecommuter logged in from home, you can
send the boss a voice message instead of having to disconnect and
get on the phone, which means you can stay online,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been extremely valuable for people who have long-distance
relationships or who know a lot of people in different countries.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a valuable tool for people like Arizona resident
George Buys, a blind man who uses voice chat to communicate with
others and who is starting his own online business using the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Buys, who lost his sight 13 years ago, has created an online
community where people can communicate via voice chat. At
www.audio-tips.com, people who are blind can talk with others who
have lost their sight and learn how to function without the use of
their eyes, Buys said. Having voice chat enables people who are
blind to feel as if they are a part of the online community instead
of feeling left out, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voice chat makes blind computer users more powerful,'' Buys
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
