<HEADLINE>
ETHICS INQUIRY URGED ON FORMER TREASURY SECRETARY'S NEW JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A coalition of consumer and community groups has
called for a government ethics investigation into former Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin's decision to accept employment from
Citigroup, the financial services conglomerate, contending the move
presents an ``undeniable appearance of impropriety.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which submitted a letter to the Office of government
Ethics Wednesday calling for the investigation, criticized what it
referred to as ``turnstile behavior'' by the former secretary, who
held a leadership post at the Wall Street firm Goldman, Sachs
before joining the Clinton administration in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In his role at Citigroup, announced late last month, Rubin
became one of three members of an expanded ``office of the
chairman.'' He resigned his post as treasury secretary four months
before joining Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Robert Rubin to move from his Treasury job to the highest
echelon at Citigroup in less than four months raises significant
ethical and public policy questions,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said Wednesday that his decision to take a job at
Citigroup was entirely unrelated to anything he worked on while in
government. ``During the time I was Treasury secretary, my sole
concern was to produce the best possible public policy,'' he said.
``I could not have cared less how anyone in the industry reacted to
my position or my views.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was signed by leaders of the Center for Community
Change, the Association of Community Organization for Reform Now,
the Greenlining Institute, New York Public Interest Research Group
as well as consumer advocate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said that the circumstances of Rubin's move to
Citigroup should be investigated, in part, because the move
coincides with the passage of congressional legislation repealing
Glass-Steagall, the 1930s-era law that divided banks from other
kinds of financial services companies. The repeal of the law was a
high priority for Citigroup, which faced the possibility of having
to divest its insurance underwriting subsidiary if the legislation
was not repealed.
</P>
<P>
   As Treasury secretary, Rubin was involved in pushing for
modernization of laws governing the financial services industry. He
left office before the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act, which restricted
banks' freedom to merge with or compete with nonbanking businesses,
was replaced with new legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
