<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-HURRICANE-LENNY-1118-     11-17 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-LENNY-1118-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POWERFUL, LATE-SEASON LENNY POUNDS EASTERN CARIBBEAN
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: This story will have to be updated with 11 p.m. EDT
coordinates from National Hurricane Center.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ A powerful late-season surprise packing
winds of 150 mph, Hurricane Lenny lashed the eastern Caribbean
Wednesday, uprooting trees, tearing off roofs and downing power
lines as it made a near direct-hit on St. Croix in the U.S. Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny brushed past Puerto Rico on a rare west-to-east course and
seemed likely to go down as one of the most powerful November
hurricanes on record. The storm flirted with reaching Category 5,
the most powerful level on the scale of hurricane strength, and was
expected to leave extreme damage in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m. EDT, Lenny's center was located at latitude 17.7 north
and longitude 64.1 west, or about 70 miles southeast of the Dutch
island of St. Maartens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very serious storm,'' U.S. Virgin Islands Gov.
Charles Turnbull told the island chain's 97,000 residents in a
radio broadcast as the storm bore down. ``The winds are becoming
severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenny's well-defined eye passed within 35 miles of St. Croix,
where roofs were ripped away and boats tossed ashore in
Frederiksted on the island's western tip. There were reports of
roads blocked by debris and flooding over much of the hilly,
20-mile-long island, as Lenny dropped 10 or more inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``My yard is completely flooded out, the telephone lines are
whistling and the rain is beating against the house,'' said Anthony
Lewis of Frederiksted.
</P>
<P>
   There were no initial reports of fatalities among St. Croix's
55,000 residents, who saw nearly 90 percent of their buildings
damaged by Hurricane Hugo in 1989. The U.S. islands also suffered
multi-billion-dollar damage at the hands of Hurricane Marilyn in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny seemed likely to add to the toll.
</P>
<P>
   But even as it approached the Virgin Islands, Lenny was blamed
for the drownings of two fishermen off the coast of Colombia, where
heavy rains and waves kicked up by the storm pounded the coast and
reportedly left hundreds of people homeless. A St. Maartens man was
killed when his garden wall collapsed on him hours before Lenny's
arrival Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rico, one man was killed when he fell while trying to
board up his windows. But this island of 3.8 million residents
seemed to escape the worst, experiencing only tropical-storm force
winds and heavy rains as the storm kept to the south. There were
reports of flooding and blocked roads along the island's south
coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got very lucky,'' said Carlos Alvarado, 34, a postman who
lives near San Juan. ``There was a lot of rain and some wind, but
nothing like we've seen in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   San Juan's airport re-opened late Wednesday and the city's
bustling tourist district hummed with activity.
</P>
<P>
   But Puerto Rico's residents took the storm seriously, boarding
up homes and stripping grocery stores of emergency supplies. Last
year, Hurricane Georges blasted across the island, causing
extensive damage and leaving 500 people dead throughout the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   On Vieques, a tiny island off Puerto Rico's east coast,
protestors who have been occupying a U.S. Navy bombing range since
May reportedly took shelter from the storm in an old tank used by
the military for target practice. The protestors want the U.S.
military to end its war games on the island.
</P>
<P>
   But Lenny's most potent winds were aimed at the U.S. Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Turnbull declared a state of emergency and deployed the
National Guard. Tourists packed airline counters, hoping to escape
the islands of St. Thomas, St. Croix and St. John, which are
normally beginning to fill up this time of year with winter
snowbirds. Many were left stranded as airlines cancelled flights
and airports were closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through (Tuesday) night the police were busy helping
evacuate a number of individuals who sought assistance after their
mobile homes and homes in low-lying areas became threatened by
flood waters,'' said St. Croix police chief Novell Francis.
</P>
<P>
   In Frederiksted, waves smashed a sea wall, tore up a wooden pier
and damaged a large concrete pier that serves cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   One tourist who ventured out into the storm got stranded on a
rock near a resort as surging waves surrounded him. Divers rescued
him after a terrifying hour.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the Caribbean, huge surf wreaked havoc while
Lenny was still more than 100 miles away, sweeping away four
houses, damaging roads and flooding the business district on
Grenada, according to media reports. A small group of people
suffered fractures and other injuries when waves swept over a pier
on St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Lenny emerged from a swirl of stormy weather over the central
Caribbean on Monday, quickly blossoming from a disorganized squall
into a hurricane. It pelted Jamaica, Haiti and the Dominican
Republic with heavy rains, then picked up speed and strength.
</P>
<P>
   But its direction of movement was the biggest surprise. On
Puerto Rico, residents dubbed the storm ``El Zurdo,'' or ``Lefty''
because of its unusual course.
</P>
<P>
   Most Atlantic hurricanes approach the Caribbean islands from the
south or east, and savvy residents have learned to build towns,
ports and homes on the protected north and west sides of their
islands. Lenny's approach from the west meant huge waves and
damaging winds would torment the heavily populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's strength, course and late-season arrival ``is
unheard of,'' Puerto Rican meteorologist John Toohey said on radio
station WOSC-AM. ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime event.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane warnings were posted for French St. Martin, Dutch St.
Maarten, Anguilla, St. Kitts, Nevis, Montserrat, Antigua, Barbuda,
St. Barthelemy, St. Eustatius, Saba, Puerto Rico and the U.S. and
British Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny also disrupted the efforts of Tori Munden, a Kentucky
lawyer attempting to become the first American _ and woman _ to row
solo across the Atlantic. Munden began her journey in September in
the Canary Islands off Africa and was only 400 miles from her
destination, Guadeloupe, when Lenny's waves reportedly began
hampering her progress.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
