<SLUG> BC-NTT-CUTBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NTT PLANS TO CUT 21,000 JOBS IN EFFORT TO BE MORE NIMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, one of the world's
largest phone companies, officially confirmed Wednesday that it
planned to eliminate 21,000 jobs and sharply curtail investment
over the next three years in an effort to enhance its
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement had been expected; unions representing NTT
employees leaked word of the plans a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the cutback is a strong sign that measures
undertaken by many Japanese businesses to become more efficient are
pressuring even the most stalwart companies to change.
</P>
<P>
   NTT was once the government-owned monopoly for domestic
telephone services. Now, smaller competitors like DDI and Japan
Telecom as well as foreign companies like Cable and Wireless and
British Telecom are pressing NTT to cut costs and change its ways.
</P>
<P>
   The company was recently forced to cut the price of a flat-rate
Internet access service to roughly $75 a month at current exchange
rates, almost half the price it had originally intended to charge.
</P>
<P>
   Others have plans to charge even less. SpeedNet, a joint venture
of Tokyo Electric Power and Microsoft, is hoping to offer consumers
a $48 monthly Internet access service, and Sony is moving to offer
wireless Internet access service in big cities.
</P>
<P>
   NTT's job cuts will be done Japanese style, through attrition,
hiring freezes and what is known as shukko, or pushing excess
workers onto affiliates. NTT, which has 224,000 employees
throughout its affiliates and subsidiaries, said it would send
employees only to growing affiliates, like the NTT Mobile
Communications Network and NTT Data.
</P>
<P>
   Junichiro Miyazu, the president of NTT, made it clear that the
company had no intention of adopting Western-style tactics in job
elimination. ``Sales at NTT East and West are falling, but we will
keep people there who we hired when we were making money from the
telephone business,'' he said, referring to the two entities under
the NTT umbrella that provide local fixed-line service.
</P>
<P>
   The company's plans to cut capital spending by 900 billion yen,
about $8.5 billion at current exchange rates, underscored the
economy's heavy dependence on government spending. Last week, the
government announced an $18 billion economic stimulus package, but
if companies like NTT continue to keep a lid on spending, it may
have to come up with a similar size package sometime next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
