<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS &LR;      11-17 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AGREES TO CUT AS SIDES INCH CLOSER TO FINAL BUDGET DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton agreed Wednesday to 0.38 percent
across-the-board cut in federal spending as White House and
Republican negotiators put the finishing touches on a final budget
deal after nearly seven weeks of talks.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiators on both sides cited some confusion over how the
cuts would be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   There were also signs that disputes among senators over dairy
pricing policy could delay a Senate vote on a final bill aimed at
settling remaining budget issues for the 2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, House and Senate Republican leaders instructed
their staffs to draw up one large omnibus spending bill, based on a
tentative deal, totaling nearly $390 billion and covering seven
government departments in hopes of pushing it to a vote in the
House on Thursday and in the Senate by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will read that bill to ensure that Republicans kept
commitments they made to the president, especially on teachers,
police officers, the environment,'' White House spokesman Jake
Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some confusion over the final details of negotiations,
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said he was ready to
vote for the negotiated budget package based on what he had seen
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole, I think it is a favorable agreement if we can
get the final details done,'' Gephardt told reporters, adding that
he would insist that the cuts be carefully targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also hailed the tentative deal as a winner, claiming
that the across-the-board cut of less than four-tenths of a percent
would keep Congress from dipping into the Social Security Trust
Fund to help pay for increased spending in some government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to have an across-the-board (cut) to show our
absolute determination not to dip into the Social Security Trust
Fund,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already signed into law eight of the 13 annual
appropriations bills needed to keep the government running. But the
five remaining bills have been tied up in negotiations since the
start of the 2000 fiscal year Oct. 1, and Congress has had to pass
a series of five temporary spending measures to keep most
government offices open.
</P>
<P>
   The last of those stopgap measures expired at midnight
Wednesday, and Congress was forced to approve a sixth one to
prevent a government shutdown. But that measure runs only through
midnight Thursday, so in all likelihood a seventh stopgap measure
will have to be passed Thursday to enable Congress to complete its
work on the budget and adjourn for the year.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to wrap up a final budget agreement, Clinton agreed
in an early morning phone call Wednesday with House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., to accept a 0.38 percent across-the-board cut in
spending. The cut, which Republicans will use to bolster their
claim that they did all they could to avoid using Social Security
money to pay for spending in other areas, will amount to $1.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials said Clinton insisted in his talk with
Hastert that the Democrats would have to accept the cut as well,
and that he would have to be given ``very flexible use'' of his
authority to make sure that the reductions don't hurt vital
government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were still trying to figure out how to ``target''
the cuts Wednesday night so they would be acceptable to Clinton and
Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico Sen. Pete Domenici, one of the key negotiators, said
Republicans had agreed to provide some flexibility in how the cuts
are administered. He also said that no department would be allowed
to trim more than 5 percent from any one program as
the-across-the-board reduction is implemented. In addition, he said
negotiators had agreed that no military or civil service personnel
would lose their jobs as a result of the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   If the cuts are included in the final bill, it would be a
political victory of sorts for Republicans, mainly because Clinton
_ only two weeks ago _ vetoed a bill containing a 1 percent
across-the-board proposal. He called the cut ``mindless'' and
``excessive'' at the time and vowed to oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   The across-the-board cut is just one of several tools that will
apparently be used to pay for about $6.5 billion in additional
spending next year that Clinton and the Republicans agreed to in
their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to find more savings, the two sides also agreed to
delay a payday for the military and some civil service personnel
scheduled for Sept. 30 next year until Oct. 1. The move would
technically push the payday into the 2001 fiscal year, resulting in
a savings in 2000 spending of more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   To cover the cost of the rest of the new spending, the
negotiators agreed to transfer money from a Federal Reserve's
foreign currency account to the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the last-minute haggling over how to implement the cuts,
Gephardt said a final bill would honor the commitments made by
Clinton and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president got his priorities and we got our
priorities of (more money for hiring) police (and) teachers. We got
rid of the (anti-regulatory) environmental riders. We got some good
provisions on foreign affairs that we think are important, like
paying our U.N. dues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if a final bill does pass the House today, it could
still get bogged down in the Senate, where senators have threatened
to filibuster a final spending package if it does not include a
provision changing the way milk prices are set.
</P>
<P>
   That issues is likely to be debated when the bill reaches the
Senate floor. But in the end, it is not likely to be included as
part of the final 2000 spending package.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
