<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT TO SUE POWER PLANTS, CITING SMOG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ky., Ohio, Va., WVa.)  (js) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following similar moves by New York and federal officials,
Connecticut's attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, said Wednesday
that he intends to sue 16 coal-burning power plants in five states
to force them to reduce pollution believed to cause smog and acid
rain in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is the latest in a flurry of recent legal
actions by state and federal law enforcement officials to reduce
air pollution from smokestacks in the Midwest that, according to
federal studies, is carried by wind currents into the highly
polluted New York region and on to New England. Two months ago, New
York's attorney general, Eliot L. Spitzer, sent letters to the same
coal-burning power plants that Connecticut has focused on _ in
Indiana, Kentucky, Ohio, Virginia and West Virginia _ notifying
them of his intent to sue them in federal court for violating
emissions standards stipulated in the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 3, in what federal officials called one of the largest
enforcement actions in the nation's history, the Justice Department
announced legal and administrative proceedings against 32
coal-fired power plants in 10 states in the Midwest and the South.
The legal actions are intended to force power companies to abide by
provisions of the Clean Air Act that require upgrades of older
coal-fired plants to include new pollution controls that reduce
emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide, compounds that
cause smog and acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other suits brought or pending against the power
plants, Connecticut's claims the power plants have failed to
accompany the upgrades of their turbines and boilers with the
expensive new pollution-cutting equipment required by law,
Blumenthal said. As a result of the upgrades, the largest plants he
intends to sue have increased their coal consumption by 50 percent
to 75 percent in the last two or three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Blumenthal said his office would work
closely with Spitzer's to mount a case against the power companies.
``We'll be using a lot of the same documentation and research,''
Blumenthal said. ``My hope is that there will be other states that
will join us. The added weight of an increasing number of states
may force these plants to do the right thing and obey the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's suits will be filed in federal courts in each of
the five states where the power plants operate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Wooley, counsel to the Clean Air Task Force, said the
attorneys general will need to demonstrate how the plants' upgrades
caused an increase in pollutants not attributable to other, routine
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the coal-fired plants Wednesday accused
Connecticut of ``piling on'' to the Midwest plants' legal battles
instead of focusing on reducing its home-grown pollution. ``We have
an awfully hard time trying to understand where Connecticut is
coming from with this kind of litigation,'' said David M. Flannery,
a lawyer for the Midwest Ozone Group.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the Justice Department joined the legal fray earlier
this month, Flannery added, ``It makes it especially curious that
Connecticut thinks it has to step in and pursue this.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, who linked the eastward-drifting air pollution from
the plants to water quality problems in the Long Island Sound and
to asthma rates in Connecticut, said his suit was necessary to
protect the state's citizens and resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
