<SLUG> BC-MCDONALD'S-DIVIDEND-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McDONALD'S TO CONVERT ITS DIVIDENDS  
 (bl)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   McDonald's, a company that grew rich by selling 15-cent
hamburgers, is tired of sending small change to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-food chain announced Wednesday that it would pay its
final quarterly dividend, 4.875 cents a share, on Dec. 15. It will
convert to an annual dividend beginning in December 2000, with the
amount to be decided by the board then.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all American companies that pay dividends do so
quarterly, as McDonald's has done until now. But it is following
the lead of Walt Disney, another company that has many shareholders
with just a few shares; Disney shifted to annual dividends a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's has about 900,000 shareholders who own 1.3 billion
shares. Even with most shareholders keeping their shares in
brokerage accounts, to which dividend payments are transferred
electronically, and others using its dividend reinvestment plan,
McDonald's still issues about 110,000 dividend checks each time it
makes a payment.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Ebling, a McDonald's spokesman, said that just over half
of those checks are issued to shareholders with 20 or fewer shares,
meaning the quarterly check is for less than $1. The company's
announcement said that it would save an undisclosed amount of money
in processing costs and that shareholders ``will no longer be
inconvenienced with handling dividend checks for very small
amounts.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, in an attempt to reduce the number of small
shareholders, McDonald's offered to repurchase shares from owners
who had fewer than 50 shares. Few of the small owners took the
company up on the offer, and Ebling said the company had no plans
to repeat it. ``We are very happy to have small shareholders,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both McDonald's and Disney are companies well known to children,
and many of the small shareholdings reflect gifts of a small number
of shares to children by parents or grandparents hoping to interest
them in investing.
</P>
<P>
   That interest may have been increased by the fact that both
companies have excellent long-term records. But Disney's record has
slipped this year _ presumably not because of its changed dividend
policy _ and its share price is down 12 percent in 1999. If the
price does not rally, it will be the first down year for the stock
since 1993. Shares in McDonald's fell 6.25 cents, to $46.125
Wednesday, but are still up 20.1 percent in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
