<SLUG> BC-BKC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN ENTERS CRITICAL SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Wayne Morgan's Long Beach State 49ers had
just cruised to a 41-point win in an exhibition game against a team
even less challenging than the Washington Generals, and you readily
can understand why the 49ers are the preseason picks to win the Big
West.
</P>
<P>
   They displayed all the requisite ingredients needed for such an
achievement: speed, quickness, enthusiasm, teamwork, accurate
shooting, strong rebounding, deft passing and athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   It is a team that seems to have everything, but it also has
Wayne Morgan as its head coach. And, as Morgan enters his fourth
season with the 49ers, it's not known for sure if he's a good
coach, a bad coach, a mediocre coach, or a coach somewhere among
these variants.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line with Morgan during his 36-46 Long Beach
incumbency is that none of his teams has had a winning season and
each of them has had agonizing periods of underachieving and
disorientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you we're going to have a winning season, barring
some sort of natural catastrophe,'' promised Morgan moments after
his team had posted its 117-76 win over something called the Global
All Stars Tuesday night at the Pyramid. ``This is definitely the
best team I've had since I've been here. We have good depth. We
have a group of players on the same page determined to win ... ''
</P>
<P>
   So, as the 49ers get set to open their season Saturday afternoon
at Pepperdine, optimism blooms brightly for a change around
Morgan's program that has surpassed its quota of bleak moments.
</P>
<P>
   His two starting forwards, Antrone Lee and the heralded junior
college transfer, James Williams, both are exceptional leapers who
can score from all angles, with Williams having the potential to be
a dominant performer.
</P>
<P>
   His center, Mate Milisa, is sound fundamentally and can drop in
three pointers, as he did on two occasions against Global.
</P>
<P>
   His off-guard, Ramel (Rock) Lloyd, is a natural scorer who is
particularly effective in the open court and now seems to be
playing with more discipline.
</P>
<P>
   His starting point guard, Charles O'Neal, missed the Global
exhibition because of influenza, but his two sharp-passing backups,
Ron Johnson and Keith Felton, ran the 49ers' offense expertly and
collected 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
   His top three reserves, Grant Stone, who can rebound, Brad
Smith, who can shoot three pointers, and D'Cean Bryant, who can do
a little of everything, all played admirably against Global.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers should
</P>
<P>
   win the undernourished Big West, and Wayne Morgan should
</P>
<P>
   , finally, silence the growing legion of community critics that
has become hopelessly restless from the prolonged losing of his
teams that has seriously impacted home attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to have a positive, winning season,'' says Bill
Shumard, the 49ers' athletic director who came thisclose (cq)
</P>
<P>
   to firing Morgan last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I've seen so far,'' says Dr. Robert Maxson, the
Long Beach State president credited with saving Morgan's job.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's no certainty the 49ers will cover themselves with
glory this winter, and no one is under more pressure to succeed
than Morgan, in the fourth year of a five year contract that he
might not be allowed to finish if his team disappoints again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the 49ers have had three straight losing years, do
you consider this the most challenging season of your coaching
career?'' I asked Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole career at Long Beach has been challenging,'' he
replied tersely.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly has been and we're not just talking about the 46
losses that nearly included an awfully embarrassing one last season
against, of all schools, Cal State Dominguez Hills.
</P>
<P>
   In Wayne Morgan's defense, he inherited a few players from the
former regime who weren't exactly model citizens and caused serious
team discord.
</P>
<P>
   His teams also have been bedeviled by untimely injuries, but
even Morgan now concedes there are no more excuses to be offered.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are with the exception of O'Neal at peak health and
Morgan personally recruited all the players on his roster, with the
exception of the fifth-year senior Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Morgan, like all coaches, doesn't put much credence
into preseason polls, especially in the one that has his team
favored to win the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not shoo-ins,'' he said. ``New Mexico State has everyone
coming back from last year's team. We have nothing yet to
celebrate. Let's face it, we've had three straight losing seasons,
and we still have to prove ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident we will turn it around this season. We have the
players I want. It's a good group that seems to want to win. What I
like about these players is that they come to practice to learn and
to get better, not just to survive. I'm excited about this season.
Very excited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
