<HEADLINE>
TROJANS, BRUINS ON DISPLAY FOR RECRUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Officially, it will be USC's turn on Saturday to
play recruiting host to most of the top prep football seniors in
Southern California. But don't think it will just be the Trojans
trying to impress the recruits when they play host to UCLA at the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said, ``all the good
players in Southern California will be at the game. Sure, they all
say they are there to see USC (which provides the tickets). But
they will be there to take a look at both teams to help in their
decision. There's a huge amount at stake for our program.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Toledo, who put together two consecutive national Top 10
recruiting classes, knows very well what a ninth consecutive
victory over his team's chief rival would do to help sway a
prospect to Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is all about this rivalry in football,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are several of California's top players that still have
both USC and UCLA on their list. And many of them are expected to
attend Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A small list of that group could include Harvard-Westlake tight
end Alex Holmes (6-4, 280), San Diego Mira Mesa quarterback-tight
end-defensive end Teyo Johnson (6-6, 242) and linebacker Amon
Gordon (6-3, 265), Newport Harbor offensive lineman Blair Jones
(6-7, 244), Dominguez offensive lineman Brandon Lockheart (6-6,
330) and safety Kevin Burnett (6-2, 220), Sherman Oaks Notre Dame
defensive lineman Travis Johnson (6-4, 265), Temescal Canyon
defensive lineman Nathan Goodson (6-4, 250), Mater Dei safety Matt
Grootegoed (6-0, 200) and St. Paul cornerback Mike Holloway (6-3,
190).
</P>
<P>
   A player whom both schools wanted but has already made up his
mind is Valencia running back Manuel White. The 6-foot-2, 220-pound
bruising tailback said earlier this week that he plans on becoming
a Bruin.
</P>
<P>
   USC appears to be close to adding a pair of junior college
players to its list of commitments. Orange Coast College fullback
Jimmie Banks (6-1, 250) and Palomar College cornerback Chris Cash
(5-11, 180) are reportedly close to committing to the Trojans, but
neither will be at the USC-UCLA contest because they have games of
their own to play.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bruins score big
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend was equally important for UCLA as the Bruins
welcomed several key recruits to watch the upset win over
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors included receiver Ronnie Rodamer (6-4, 190) of
Morgantown, W.Va. and defensive tackle Stevie Lee (6-4, 260) and
safety Phillip Geiggar (6-2, 190) of nationally top ranked
Shreveport (La.) Evangel Christian. Rodamer has UCLA and Tennessee
as his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento Christian running back Albert Hollis, who committed
to UCLA early but has since wavered, was also at the game as were
Grootegoed, Holmes, Travis Johnson and Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   __ Devil of a time
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State picked up its seventh commitment when Canyon
Springs offensive lineman Chad Rosson (6-7, 260) announced he
intends on becoming a Sun Devil. Rosson, who was high school
teammates with ASU freshman linebacker Solomon Bates, also
considered Oregon, Oregon State and Washington State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
