<HEADLINE>
BT ALEX. BROWN AGREES TO PAY $15.3 MILLION IN BOND CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said Wednesday that BT
Alex. Brown Inc. had agreed to pay $15.3 million to settle
allegations that the brokerage firm defrauded the federal
government and the state of Pennsylvania in municipal bond
transactions in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is the largest yet won by federal officials, who
have been investigating accusations that several Wall Street firms
engaged in ``yield burning,'' or profiting heavily by vastly
inflating the prices of government securities.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its investigation, the SEC also charged six people,
including the former head of public finance at BT Alex. Brown and a
key adviser to the former state treasurer of Pennsylvania, and
three other companies with participating in the alleged scheme,
which SEC officials said included influence peddling and
undisclosed financial arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   In resolving its case, BT Alex. Brown, now a unit of Deutsche
Bank, also reached an agreement with the Internal Revenue Service
and the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York, both
of which had been investigating the case. The firm said it neither
acknowledged nor denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the case, the SEC filed a securities fraud complaint
against Patrick H. McCarthy III for his role in two bond offerings
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said that although he was not a state employee, McCarthy
used his influence as a fund-raiser and key adviser to the former
state treasurer, Catherine Baker Knoll, to influence state
decisions and steer business to Alex. Brown on the condition that
the brokerage firm agree to split its fees with the state's
financial adviser, Arthurs Lestrange &AMP; Co., a Pittsburgh brokerage
firm. The SEC said that McCarthy then arranged to have a consultant
to the financial adviser make a payment to his law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC does not contend that either Alex. Brown or the
financial adviser were aware of the payments to McCarthy's law
firm. But the agency said McCarthy failed to disclose the
compensation that his law firm received to the state of
Pennsylvania. No state officials were charged with wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, a prominent Pennsylvania lawyer, could not be reached
for comment Wednesday. But his lawyer issued a statement on his
behalf that read, ``Rather than face years of litigation and
attendant legal fees, my family and I decided to move on with our
lives.'' McCarthy agreed to pay a civil penalty of $100,000; his
law firm repaid $172,000 to Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the SEC also reached settlements totaling more
than $500,000 with several former employees of Alex. Brown; two
consulting firms, HDI Inc. and JMS Associates Inc.; and Arthurs
Lestrange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
