<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRL-SCOUTS-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL SCOUTS SETTLE BIAS CLAIM OF GIRL WITH HIV 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Girl Scouts settled a human rights complaint this week that
accused them of excluding a 9-year-old girl from at least five
troops in upstate New York because she was infected with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS. The Scouts admitted no wrongdoing but
agreed not to bar girls like her in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint was believed to be the first claiming that a Girl
Scout or Boy Scout organization discriminated against a person with
the human immunodeficiency virus.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides Wednesday would not discuss the case or
indicate whether a monetary settlement was involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Legal Action Center of New York City had filed the complaint
last March with the state Division of Human Rights on behalf of
Quashawn Donovan, now a fourth grader, who lives in Queensbury, a
rural town about 50 miles north of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondack Council of the Girl Scouts and the Girl Scouts of
the United States of America were named in the complaint, which
alleged violations of the state's human rights law. Neither the
council nor the national organization admitted that any unlawful
discrimination had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother, Dianne Donovan, said in a statement released
Wednesday that the Adirondack Council would revise its policy to
ensure that volunteers understand that girls may not be denied
admission to a troop or discriminated against because of their HIV
status. The council also has set up a comprehensive education
program for troop leaders and staff members regarding HIV
transmission, universal precautions and the organization's
nondiscrimination policy, Mrs. Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Donovan expressed pleasure that the ``matter was resolved
amicably.'' The complaint arose after troop leaders rescinded an
invitation to allow Quashawn to join a troop last November after
they learned that the girl was HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
   The troop's co-leader told the girl's mother that the troop was
full, the complaint said, but the leader later admitted that she
and her co-leader feared that other Scouts would leave the troop
out of fear that they could contract the virus from Quashawn.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of several other troops refused to admit Quashawn
because of similar fears, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   The national Girl Scouts organization had been accused in the
complaint of failing to take the necessary action to halt the
discrimination. The organization will continue to investigate
complaints of alleged HIV discrimination and to take appropriate
action, Mrs. Donovan's statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
