<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VODAFONE'S BOARD TO DEBATE AN OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The board of Vodafone Airtouch PLC is scheduled to meet
Thursday to weigh paying as much as $125 billion in a takeover of
German rival Mannesmann AG, executives close to the British company
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That amount, equivalent to 240 euros ($249.84) a share, would be
the largest unsolicited bid ever, eclipsing the record $106.4
billion Vodafone offered Sunday, which Mannesmann rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Vodafone stressed that it would not decide
on a final bid price until the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone chief executive Christopher Gent pledged Tuesday to
press ahead with an offer and warned that his company, the world's
largest mobile phone operator, would make a hostile bid if
Mannesmann resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone is expected to bring its bid to Mannesmann's board on
Friday, according to executives close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone also hired Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to advise on
its bid after its main adviser, Goldman, Sachs, stepped aside.
Mannesmann has contended Goldman betrayed confidential information,
obtained in earlier dealings, to Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann is also considering going to court to have the
Vodafone bid thrown out because of the Goldman allegation,
executives close to Mannesmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann shares fell 5.3 percent Wednesday, to 196.65 euros
($204.71).
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Vodafone rose 1.9 percent Wednesday to 277 pence
($4.50) in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
