<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAFONE-GERMANY-NYT &LR;      11-17 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANS, USED TO CONSENSUS, SEEM UNFAZED BY PHONE WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Two years ago, Krupp ignited a political
firestorm in Germany by attempting a hostile takeover of its rival
in the steel industry, Thyssen AG.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now, as Vodafone Airtouch of Britain contemplates the
biggest hostile takeover of all time, a $100-billion-lus bid for
Mannesmann AG, the reaction here is far different.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders have not tried to intervene. Germany's biggest
banks and insurers, which have a long tradition of rescuing
troubled companies, have largely been passive.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who blocked a steel merger several
years ago when he was the state premier of Lower Saxony, indicated
this week that Mannesmann must fend for itself. ``Whoever wants to
buy a British company, like Mannesmann with Orange, can't say
`We're allowed and they are not,''' Schroeder said this week.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, hostile takeovers still run against a deeply
ingrained habit in Germany of seeking consensus _ one that has
created a clubby, often impenetrable web of cross-links among
banks, industrial conglomerates and sometimes even government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   And the Vodafone bid has aroused alarm in some quarters.
Hans-Peter Stihl, president of the German Chamber of Industry and
Commerce, has repeatedly assailed an unwanted bid as nothing more
than a shortsighted attempt to break up one of Germany's most
successful companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a major departure from German business leaders' hostility to
regulation, Stihl has proposed that the government prohibit
``destructive takeovers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is not whether the takeover is hostile or
friendly,'' said Axel Koblitz, who oversees the association's work
on antitrust issues. ``The issue here is the breakup of a very
successful and healthy company. That's what gives us concern.''
</P>
<P>
   But in corporate Europe of the last year or two, those views
have been the exception. Europeans have seen hostile takeovers of
Telecom Italia SpA, the French oil company Elf Aquitaine and the
financial services company Paribas.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, German companies have become among the world's
most acquisitive. Daimler-Benz bought Chrysler Corp.; Deutsche Bank
bought Bankers Trust; the chemical and pharmaceutical company
Hoechst merged with Rhone-Poulenc of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no longer in the situation that we were in a few years
ago,'' said Norbert Walter, chief economist of Deutsche Bank.
``Within the country and within Europe, events like this have
become familiar. People recognize that an unwanted takeover is a
form of negotiation _ a different form of negotiation, but one that
can also be orderly.''
</P>
<P>
   That is an enormous change. When the Krupp steel group attempted
a hostile takeover of Thyssen in 1997, labor unions and politicians
from steel-making regions assailed the effort as ``casino
capitalism.'' Helmut Kohl, who was the the chancellor, telephoned
the head of Deutsche Bank, which was financing Krupp's offer, and
told him to engineer a friendly compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many executives and deal makers now view the Krupp battle
as a watershed. As events worked out, Krupp and Thyssen negotiated
a friendly merger of just their steel operations and then later
merged their other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In Vodafone's takeover plan, the most contentious issue, at
least so far, is not the presumed hostile nature but rather the
expected price.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich Hocker, president of Germany's biggest advocacy group for
small investors, has fiercely criticized the anticipated Vodafone
offer for its size.
</P>
<P>
   Hocker is furious that Stihl and the chamber proposed government
prohibitions on ``destructive takeovers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is horrifying that our own Stihl is demanding that our
lawmakers put up legal restrictions,'' he said. ``It cannot be the
government's job to protect badly run companies from competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann has thus far not sought political protection. ``We
have made it clear we don't like hostile offers,'' a spokesman,
Manfred Soehnlein, said. ``But we are not asking for government
restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   German newspapers have greeted the Vodafone battle as evidence
that German corporations are opening up to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The takeover attack from Britain could be a test case for
Germany,'' the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung suggested in an
editorial this week. ``It will show whether Germany remains the
closed industrial club it has been up until now or whether it has
opened up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, a company like Mannesmann might have sought
protection with its longtime financier, Deutsche Bank. The bank has
held a significant stake in Mannesmann for years, as well as in
many of Germany's other conglomerates, and it has frequently used
its position to foil deals it disliked.
</P>
<P>
   But Deutsche Bank has made no move to raise its stake in
Mannesmann or even to assert an opinion about the Vodafone offer.
``We are treating this just the way any other shareholder would,''
said bank spokesman Detlev Rahmsdorf.
</P>
<P>
   For institutional investors in Germany, the only real issue is
price. Mannesmann's shares are widely distributed, with more than
half in the hands of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   A German fund manager said he would not be interested in selling
unless the British company raised the price to at least 250 euros a
share, or around $130 billion in all. Mannesmann shares closed
Wednesday at 196.65 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Vodafone's offer is expected to be entirely in stock
rather than cash, he said, Vodafone will have to pay a very high
premium over Mannesmann's current market price to be credible.
</P>
<P>
   Walter, chief economist at Deutsche Bank, said the possibility
of hostile bids is now a fact of life for German corporations,
especially those with international aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be a global player,'' he said, ``it is obvious
that those who hold shares have to be able to make up their own
minds after they've been informed. The only practical alternative
is to invite government interference, and inviting government
interference would make more problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
