<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIF. CONGRESSIONAL VICTORY; TIMING LOUISIANA'S CAUCUS; SUPPORT
FOR MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORY PROVES SWEET, BUT IS NOT SIGNIFICANT
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic victory in Tuesday's special election in
California's 42nd Congressional District appears to hold few
significant clues about what to expect in House races in Election
2000. But it is nevertheless a sweet victory for Democrats since it
means that the district, centered on San Bernardino, just east of
Los Angeles, remains under Democratic control and the Republican
margin of control in the House stays at just five seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate, state Sen. Joe Baca of Rialto, won
comfortably, taking 52 percent of the vote, compared with 44
percent for his Republican opponent, Elia Pirozzi, a lawyer and
mortgage broker from Rancho Cucamonga.
</P>
<P>
   National Democratic leaders hailed the Baca victory as a
harbinger for next year's elections. National Republican leaders
insisted that Pirozzi had exceeded expectations and therefore House
Republicans were sure to keep their majority in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But non-partisan political experts see no great national
implications in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a contest in a Democratic-leaning district and though
Republicans had some openings, it easily stayed Democratic, which
is about the size of it all,'' said Stuart Rothenberg, editor of
The Rothenberg Political Report, an independent publication
distributed mainly to political professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The election was called after Rep. George E. Brown Jr., the
hard-left Democrat who had held the seat for 27 years, died in
July. Republican challengers had made several good runs at him in
recent years and party leaders were hopeful, initially, that in the
special election their candidate might finally prevail.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates the Republican leaders most diligently
recruited turned down the request to run, apparently figuring that
the district, although it had seemed for a while to be trending
conservative and away from Brown, was remaining solidly,
working-class Democratic, especially as more and more Hispanics
moved in. In the end, disappointed party leaders found themselves
backing a retread candidate, Pirozzi, a solid conservative who only
a year earlier had been beaten by Brown in the congressman's last
run.
</P>
<P>
   Baca is more conservative than was Brown, whose unyielding
liberalism almost cost him several re-election races. So unable to
effectively play the liberalism card against Baca, Pirozzi rested
his hopes on a big Republican turnout and a prayer that the
Democratic vote, badly split in the earlier primary, would remain
split.
</P>
<P>
   Pirozzi got a pretty good turnout. But the Democratic vote came
together enough to give Baca a comfortable win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever the Republicans put up in the district next year
probably shouldn't expect things to be any easier,'' said
Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   FIGHT GETS TOUGHER ON LOUISIANA CAUCUS
</P>
<P>
   The fight over whether Louisiana should jump nine days ahead of
Iowa and hold the nation's first presidential caucuses next year on
Jan. 15 is no longer just a war of words between Gov. Mike Foster
and Mike Francis, the chairman of the state's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Now Foster, also a Republican, is pushing to get a majority of
the 213-member Republican State Central Committee, the top party
policy group, to sign a petition demanding that Francis scrap his
plan to have Louisiana go first. The governor argues that none of
the major Republican candidates will risk angering Iowa voters by
going to Louisiana and thus the Louisiana caucuses will be an
embarrassing political disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is scheduled to consider the issue on Dec. ll. So
far, 85 of the required 107 committee members have signed the
petition.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ENCOURAGEMENT FOR MCCAIN'S RACE
</P>
<P>
   More good polling news in New Hampshire for surging Sen. John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a poll there had the Arizona Republican almost in a
dead heat with the other top Republican contender, Governor George
W. Bush of Texas. Now comes another poll, this one by the polling
institute at Quinnipiac College in Hamden, Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   First the institute matched the Democratic contenders, Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, and found them in a
dead heat. Then it threw McCain into the mix _ and found that he
could beat either of them, Gore by 19 points and Bradley by 7
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
