<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-NEWS-SHARING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING MEDIA COMPANIES FORMING JOINT WEB VENTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unusually broad news-sharing arrangement is bringing together
some of the nation's leading media companies in a venture to share
news reports on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The venture includes the nation's leading broadcaster, the most
popular news site on the Web, one of the country's most prominent
newspapers, the No. 2 weekly newsmagazine and an all-news cable
channel.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made by major subsidiaries of NBC News,
MSNBC and The Washington Post Co. and represented one of the most
significant developments in media alliances in response to the
challenge of attracting audiences in the narrowcasting era of cable
TV and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Their companies' World Wide Web outlets will receive daily lists
of planned articles from the partners and have access to the final
news reports. Wednesday, a Washington Post report on traveller's
reluctance to fly on New Year's Eve was on MSNBC.com.
</P>
<P>
   Many details remain unsettled. But the executives of the news
organizations said Wednesday that the journalism of The Washington
Post, NBC News, Newsweek and MSNBC will be available on both
MSNBC.com, Washingtonpost.com and a planned new site,
Newsweek.MSNBC.com. Some exclusive reports will be held back until
after they have been published or broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NBC's local owned-and-operated station in
Washington, WRC-TV, will share its news reports with the Post on
their respective online outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue from the collaborative ventures would be
shared, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   And in the upcoming election year, NBC, MSNBC and MSNBC.com can
supplement their coverage with reports from the Washington Post's
respected corps of political reporters. MSNBC and MSNBC.com are
joint ventures of NBC, a unit of General Electric, and Microsoft.
The Washington Post owns Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolzien, a media analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.,
who for many years was a producer with NBC News, said Wednesday
that the effort to aggregate high-quality journalism on a Web site
could quickly broaden that site's audience _ and its appeal to
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got, both with the Web but also with TV and cable,
is a recognition that depth of content, depth of proprietary
content, counts,'' he said. ``As you move into an
advertiser-supported Internet, `your' site needs to have more
proprietary content than `mine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Collaborative reporting among some of the news organizations
have also been discussed, executives on a conference call said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be discussions about shared presentations of news
between NBC and The Washington Post,'' said the Post's executive
editor, Leonard Downie Jr. ``We have no idea what form it will
take. This is new territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance between the news outlets of NBC and the Post
company is one of many arrangements that have made competing news
organizations into partners. Some arrangements have supplemented
earlier alliances and others have superceded them. For instance,
now that Washington Post and Newsweek reporters will be appearing
on Brian Williams' MSNBC news broadcast, reporters from The New
York Times will not.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's agreement leaves intact the broader pre-existing
partnership between Dow Jones, the Wall Street Journal's parent,
and CNBC, the financial news cable channel owned by NBC. The Wall
Street Journal's reporters regularly contribute material to CNBC.
In return, Dow Jones is paid a licensing fee and shares in the
advertising revenue. Articles from the Journal are also posted on
the MSNBC.com site.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times has been exploring ventures with other news
outlets, like ABC, which is owned by the Walt Disney Co. ``We've
talked to them about a whole range of things, including a limited
collaboration on campaign coverage and some cooperation in
television and Internet news,'' said Bill Keller, the managing
editor of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all at the talking stage at this point,'' he added. ``We
haven't signed any formal agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of the Web, alliances are the rule, as media giants
seek partners to help them compete in myriad online niches. This
week, Pearson plc, the parent company of The Financial Times,
announced it would take a stake in one of the major owners of the
financial news Web site Marketwatch.com. That site is also partly
owned by CBS, and its journalists appear on some CBS news programs.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times also holds a 6.3 percent stake in
Thestreet.com, another financial news site. Several reporters
working out of thestreet.com's offices in the financial district
file reports throughout the day to both The New York Times on the
Web and Thestreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the news organizations in the alliance announced
Wednesday will retain editorial control over its publications or
news broadcasts. Editors at the Web sites receiving material from
partner newsrooms, however, cannot edit the material without
consultation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
