<SLUG> BC-PLAYDOG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYBOY, IN CHICAGO, TO SUE PLAYDOG, ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playboy says it can take a joke, but not trademark infringement,
so lawyers for the magazine have threatened to sue the Milltown,
N.J., man who started a Web site called Playdog.com that features
pictures of dogs wearing nothing but their fur.
</P>
<P>
   With an editor named ``Spot Hephner'' and a Playdog of the
Month, the site's inspiration is obvious. This month's playdog is
Daisy (her turn-ons include drooling and sleeping; her turnoffs
include mailmen). Readers are invited to send in pictures of their
dogs. The site is not recommended for cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is dog nudity,'' the site warns, it is
``appropriate for viewers of all ages,'' with the possible
exception of cats. ``If you're looking for dirty pictures, you're
barking up the wrong tree.''
</P>
<P>
   But apparently somebody did get confused, after receiving e-mail
from Playdog.com, and asked Playboy if there was any connection,
said Angela DePaul, a spokeswoman for Playboy Enterprises in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, Playboy's legal department began writing to
Steve Sackman, the 37-year-old Milltown bartender who started the
site in September 1998 to attract subscribers to a print magazine
for dog owners that he plans to begin publishing in February. He
said Wednesday he was shocked that Playboy had paid him any mind at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely different market,'' he said. ``The only
similarity is the word `play.' I have dogs, they have women. I'm
not calling their models playdogs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Playboy is demanding that he alter his logo's typeface,
which is similar to Playboy's, to avoid the impression that there
is any connection with the magazine. The company also objects to
his use of the logo on dog dishes and other products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the humor,'' Ms. DePaul said, ``but it's the
idea that if you let one individual infringe on the brand, because
it's online, the brand can become diluted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
