<SLUG> BC-IRA-STATEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA TO DISCUSS HANDING OVER WEAPONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ In what could signal the end of its long war to end
British control of Northern Ireland, the Irish Republican Army said
Wednesday that it would discuss handing over weapons as soon as a
power-sharing government, including its political allies, was
formed.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's four-paragraph statement, signed by its fictional
messenger, P. O'Neill, did not promise to turn in weapons. But a
concession was widely seen from the IRA, which had hitherto refused
to countenance even a token gesture on weapons. The statement said
the IRA would talk to the international commission overseeing the
disarming of paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the IRA equate the turning in of weapons to surrender,
something the IRA insists it will not do. But the leadership of
Sinn Fein, the IRA's political allies, has convinced IRA leaders
that their goal of a united Ireland will come about sooner through
democratic politics than armed insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   The statement Wednesday was the first public confirmation that
the IRA's ruling Army Council accepts that arms decommissioning is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was also the latest in a series of steps to break
the impasse that has stalled the peace process for 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Ulster Unionist leader, David Trimble, said that
in exchange for an IRA pledge to send a representative to the arms
commission, his party was willing to drop its demand that IRA
weapons be turned in before forming a power-sharing government with
Catholic republicans. That government will include two members of
Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence of events that is supposed to lead to a break in
the impasse has been scripted by George Mitchell, the former US
senator from Maine who brokered the 1998 Good Friday Agreement, and
who has spent the past 10 weeks trying to save it from collapse.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement called for the creation of political institutions
aimed at transforming the conflict over whether Northern Ireland
should remain part of the United Kingdom, or merge with the
Republic of Ireland. The idea is to change the debate from violent
to political exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The process stalled 17 months ago. Then, the unionists said they
would not sit in government with Sinn Fein until the IRA began
disarming. The republicans countered that nothing in the agreement
linked creation of the government to decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two months of patient coaxing by Mitchell,
however, Trimble indicated on Monday that he was willing to risk
his leadership by seeking his party's backing for the compromise
that drops the party's ``no guns, no government'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   If Trimble gets approval from a meeting of the 800-member party
council, tentatively set for Nov. 27, the local government could be
formed within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Sinn Fein leader, Gerry Adams, said that Irish
republicans, who for two centuries have considered it their duty to
use force to seek an independent and united Ireland, accept that
the decommissioning of IRA weapons ``is an essential part of the
peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams also gave his most explicit repudiation of violence,
including a condemnation of vigilante beatings and shootings, which
both the IRA and loyalists routinely use to police the
neighborhoods they control.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, the IRA made no reference to the beatings
Adams deplored, but said it backed the Sinn Fein leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who like Trimble has a hard task of persuading hardliners
in his party to accept the accord, Wednesday praised the IRA for
its ``courage, discipline and patience.''
</P>
<P>
   But the man whom Adams ousted as the leader of Sinn Fein more
than a decade ago, Ruairi O Bradaigh, said a new generation would
rise and take over the ``armed struggle'' that the IRA was giving
up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-MATCHUP1-LADN-(SL     11-17 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MATCHUP1-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANTASY BOWL I
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ J.J. Stokes one-on-one against Ronnie Lott . . .
Jonathan Ogden blocking Chip Banks . . . Chris Claiborne tackling
Freeman McNeil . . . Junior Seau blitzing Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the possibilities. Imagine the prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I want to be the ticket vendor for that game,'' said UCLA
assistant Bob Field. ``That would really be something.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagination meets newsprint in the Daily News' two-part mythical
matchup between the greatest players from UCLA and USC. Today, the
Bruins offense faces a USC defense so good that Dennis Thurman and
Willie McGinest didn't make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's offense isn't bad, either. Quarterback Gary Beban, the
school's only Heisman Trophy winner, didn't make it. Neither did
left tackle Kris Farris, an Outland Trophy winner, or tailback
Gaston Green, the school's career rushing leader.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the matchup might seem one-sided. The Bruins have no
Heisman Trophy tailbacks, and tight end Tim Wrightman and receiver
Dick Wallen probably would struggle against USC's defensive backs
(Lott, Mark Carrier, Dennis Smith and Tim McDonald.)
</P>
<P>
   Even UCLA's offensive line, however accomplished, might lack the
overall size and speed to repel Gary Jeter, Tim Ryan and a Trojans
linebacking corps for the ages: Seau, Claiborne, Banks and Richard
Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a long list of great Trojan players,'' former UCLA
assistant coach Jerry Long said. ``Some of those guys were giants.
But you look back and there are some incredible UCLA victories
against the monsters from USC.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have a chance, if only for one reason: Their offense
is stocked with players who made their names with legendary
performances against USC. Size and speed are nice, but there's
nothing more important than playmaking ability in the
pressure-filled city series.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Trojans fans which UCLA quarterback they'd least like to
face, and it probably wouldn't be Beban or John Sciarra or Bob
Waterfield or even Troy Aikman. It'd be McNown. He was to USC what
Rodney Peete was to the Bruins in the late '80s _ a nemesis
nonpareil.
</P>
<P>
   McNown beat the Trojans four times and invariably made the
game-winning plays.
</P>
<P>
   As a true freshman in 1995, his last-minute, third-down sprint
preserved UCLA's possession and enabled the Bruins to run out the
clock. In 1996, McNown passed for 356 yards, scored three
touchdowns and directed the greatest comeback in school history.
(The Bruins trailed 38-21 with 6 minutes left, then won in
double-overtime.) In 1997, McNown passed for three touchdowns in a
seven-point win.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for Stokes, whose three-touchdown, 263-yard
masterpiece in 1992 helped the Bruins to a 38-37 victory. (UCLA
trailed by 14 points in the fourth quarter.)
</P>
<P>
   McNeil, too, saved his best for the Trojans. The Bruins could
have five Ogdens blocking in the mythical matchup and they'd still
struggle to run outside on Seau and Banks. But McNeil, at 210
pounds, was strong enough to run between the tackles, thereby
negating USC's speed. What's more, McNeil has the playmaking skills
to match Stokes and McNown, as the 1980 USC-UCLA game proved.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with an injured hip that necessitated extra padding,
McNeil had 111 yards running and 74 receiving. His last play was
best: With two minutes remaining and the Bruins trailing by three,
Jay Schroeder's sideline pass to McNeil was deflected by USC
cornerback (and current NFL coach) Jeff Fisher. McNeil made an
acrobatic catch, then raced 35 yards for the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-17 victory snapped USC's four-year mastery of the Bruins.
It was also coach Terry Donahue's first win over the Trojans after
several narrow defeats in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play, that win, was huge for the program,'' Field said.
``It was a real breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the stuff of legends. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UCLA'S ALL-TIME OFFENSE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUARTERBACK  &QL; 
Cade McNown 6-1 210 1995-98
</P>
<P>
   __ Accolades: All-American. Third in 1998 Heisman Trophy voting.
</P>
<P>
   __ Comment: His four wins over USC are three more than Gary
Beban and four more than Troy Aikman. Owns five school records.
Playmaker without peer.
</P>
