r a BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-1STLD-     11-17 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-1STLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURORS BEGIN DELIBERATING IN TEXAS MAN'S DRAGGING DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Updates 2nd graf with jury retiring for the night) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The 1998 torture slaying of a disabled black man
``already has been avenged'' by guilty verdicts against two other
white men, and justice would be served if jurors acquit Shawn Allen
Berry, his attorney told an all-white jury as he closed his case
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in the capital murder trial began deliberating shortly
after noon, and requested numerous transcripts, Berry's
blood-stained clothing and other evidence, leading prosecutors to
predict there would not be a quick verdict. Shortly before 10 p.m.,
the jury retired for the night.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of seven women and five men have a choice of finding
Berry, 24, guilty of capital murder, guilty of murder or not
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   An alternate juror, released from duty before deliberations
began, said he would have voted for a capital murder verdict.
George Coleman of nearby Buna said that both Berry and his fiancee,
ex-beauty queen Christy Marcontell, lacked credibility on the
witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Berry admitted giving James Byrd Jr., 49, a ride on June 7,
1998, during a night of beer drinking and cruising for girls, and
that he initially lied about his actions.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted Tuesday that he did not kill the disabled
African-American. After an initial attempt to help Byrd, Berry said
he stood by, paralyzed by fear, as John William King Jr. and
Russell Lawrence Brewer beat Byrd, chained him behind Berry's
pickup and then dragged him to death along a bumpy rural road.
</P>
<P>
   King, 25, and Brewer, 32, who belonged to the same white
supremacist gang in prison, were sentenced to death earlier this
year. Unlike them, Berry had no racist affiliations. Numerous
defense witnesses, including three African-Americans, said he was
not hateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Byrd Jr.'s murder has been avenged,'' defense attorney
Joseph Columbus ``Lum'' Hawthorn said in a closing statement. ``The
two people who killed James Byrd Jr. were tried, convicted and
sentenced to death. ... Justice has been served.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Berry knew his childhood friend Bill King had come back
from prison a racist, Berry viewed him as a boastful blowhard who
never had followed through on threats, Hawthorn said. And neither
King nor Brewer had shown any violent tendencies, he said,
explaining why his client would invite a black man into his truck
with two avowed white supremacists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason for Shawn Berry to believe that Bill King
was anything other than a bag of wind,'' the attorney said.
``Nobody took Bill King seriously, not until this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray insisted that Berry not only
gave Byrd a ride but was driving when the black man was dragged to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he picked up James Byrd, he knew it was wrong,'' Gray
said. ``It went from drinking beer and picking up girls to some
other kind of fun. ... Whoever had his hand on the wheel was having
fun. ... He was just as active as the other two. Really, he's more
active than the other two.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the trial, Gray suggested that King was starting a hate
group in Jasper and that Byrd's slaying was an initiation rite,
possibly for Berry. During the trial, Gray said Berry was not a
racist, but a young man out for a deadly form of thrill-seeking on
June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three people who participated, and that man was the
worst of the bunch on that particular night,'' Assistant District
Attorney Pat Hardy said. ``Because as sick as their beliefs were,
at least King and Brewer believed in something. Shawn Berry did all
of this for nothing but the fun of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Motive aside, the prosecution hammered away at Berry, citing his
own statements, acknowledged lies and evidence collected in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Shawn Berry's truck, Shawn Berry's chain,'' Gray said.
``It was Shawn Berry that made the decision to pick James Byrd up.
Shawn Berry made the decision to drive out to a remote area. Shawn
Berry has got blood on his boots, he's got blood on his pants, and
he's got blood on his shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Bill King had one drop on his sandal.
Russell Brewer had one drop on his tennis shoes,` the district
attorney said. ``Shawn Berry has got more blood on him than any one
of the three.''
</P>
<P>
   But the defense suggested that Berry got blood on his clothes by
accident while he and King sprayed down the pickup and logging
chain at a carwash the afternoon after the dragging death.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, a cinema manager, showed little emotion throughout the
six-day trial. And although he said he was sorry he did not
intervene more effectively to stop the slaying, he made no
expression of regret for Byrd's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, his 23-year-old fiancee, a former Miss Newton
County, sat next to him. His biological father, whom he hadn't met
until just before the trial, flew in from Ohio and sat in the first
row with other friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Byrd sat on the other side of the courtroom.
Several of Byrd's sisters said they considered Berry at least as
culpable as King and Brewer because he picked up their brother
knowing that King and Brewer were Ku Klux Klansmen.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
