<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: NEW BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   On the day that Sergio Vieira de Mello, the U.N. administrator
for East Timor, arrived in Dili to begin preparing the territory
for independence, an East Timorese leader in exile, Jose Ramos
Horta, announced that he and Jose Alexandre Gusmao, who is expected
to be East Timor's first president, would go to Jakarta on Nov. 30
to ``begin the process of building a relationship with Indonesia.''
Ramos Horta was speaking at the United Nations after receiving an
award from the Hague Appeal for Peace organization.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PARLIAMENT'S AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would propose legislation intended to
save the legal system money and time by eliminating the right of
defendants in many criminal cases to trial by jury. The measure,
which would apply to defendants accused of crimes like theft and
assault, whose cases would be heard by a judge, was one of 28 bills
presented at the state opening of Parliament. Lawyers denounced the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: 2ND TRIAL IN BASQUE DEATHS
</P>
<P>
   A second trial will start on Dec. 13 to investigate accusations
that the former Socialist government carried out a covert campaign
in which 27 suspected Basque terrorists died. The new trial, for
the murder of two Basques in 1983, will have seven defendants,
including a former senior Interior Ministry official, Rafael Vera.
Vera was convicted last year in the first trial, for the 1983
kidnapping of a suspected Basque separatist. He served more than
three months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS: U.N. ENVOY SWORN IN
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. representative, swore in a new
U.S. envoy assigned the full-time job of negotiating with other
nations to meet the conditions Congress has placed on the payment
of U.S. assessments to the organization. Donald Hays was promoted
in a ceremony attended by representatives from around the world.
Holbrooke, who asked the envoys for their help in meeting
congressional demands, said the United States and the United
Nations were ``on the edge of a new relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: MENEM INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   Vice president-elect Carlos Alvarez announced that he would lead
an examination into the assets of the departing president, Carlos
Saul Menem, as the beginning of a possible corruption
investigation. Menem has valued his assets at $2.5 million, and
says he is not guilty of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: INDIANS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Uwa Indians have occupied an area they say is part of their
ancestral homeland but which the government awarded to a U.S.
company as an oil drilling test site. Occidental Petroleum Corp.
won exploration rights to the 800-square-mile area just outside the
Uwas' legally recognized reservation after a seven-year legal
battle, but the 5,000-member tribe is demanding the government
cancel the contract and Occidental abandon the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
