<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SCOUR SHELTERS FOR MAN WHO HIT WOMAN WITH BRICK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas) (With NY-BRICK-VICTIM) 
(rk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police detectives fanned out to homeless shelters and
soup kitchens in Manhattan Wednesday in search of a man who hit a
woman with a brick in an unprovoked attack on a busy midtown street
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The attacker, who is believed to be homeless, struck the woman,
Nicole Barrett, in the back of the head with a brick as she waited
to cross the street at East 42nd Street and Madison Avenue about 3
p.m. Tuesday. As detectives searched more than a dozen shelters for
the man Wednesday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner
Howard Safir met with the victim's parents and later held a news
conference in which they sought to allay mounting fears about the
random nature of this and other recent attacks in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett, 27, a native of a small town in Texas who moved to
New York a year ago, remained in critical condition Wednesday at
Bellevue Hospital Center with a skull fracture and brain swelling.
Investigators said she probably did not see her attacker, whom the
police described as a black man, in his 40s, between 5 feet 6 and 5
feet 7 inches tall, with short hair. They said the man was wearing
dirty blue jeans and a black nylon jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that after being hit by the brick, which was
either thrown or smashed against her head, Ms. Barrett, who was
returning to work after running an errand, fell to her knees and
landed face first on the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said Ms. Barrett, a graduate of a community college in
Texas, was on her last day of work in a temporary job Tuesday and
was to begin a new full-time job this week. She was also
considering going back to school to study interior design.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday morning, police detectives began searching for a
homeless man who was believed to be mentally ill and had frequently
been seen in the area where the attacked occurred. The police also
canvassed construction sites nearby, in a search for clues about
where the brick may have come from. But by Wednesday night, the
police had made no arrests or other significant headway in the
case, officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The assault of Ms. Barrett added to the list of capricious
crimes in which unsuspecting victims were attacked in the past
year, including the killing of a Manhattan woman, Kendra Webdale,
and the maiming of a Bronx man, Edgar Rivera, both of whom were
pushed in front of subway trains by assailants they had not
previously known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
