</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-VICTIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK SHATTERS YOUNG LIFE AS IT WAS COMING TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (With NY-BRICK-ATTACK) 
(rk) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Things had been going Nicole Barrett's way since she
moved from East Texas to New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   She had found a steady boyfriend, was soon to have a steady job,
and was lining up a new apartment in Queens. With her life coming
neatly together, she was planning a Thanksgiving trip back home
next week, when she was to introduce her boyfriend to her circle of
family and friends in Athens, the small town where she grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, that introductory trip happened in reverse, as Ms.
Barrett's parents flew to New York to visit their daughter in the
neurosurgical intensive care unit at Bellevue Hospital Center in
Manhattan. Ms. Barrett was the victim of what the police called a
random attack on Tuesday in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   A man, apparently without motive or provocation, approached her
from behind and struck her in the head with a large brick, sending
her sprawling to the pavement near the corner of 42nd Street and
Madison Avenue. She received a head wound so large that one of the
first people to rush to her after she fell said he thought she had
been hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   A vigil was under way at the bedside of Ms. Barrett, 27, who was
listed in critical condition and under sedation after two
operations to relieve the pressure on her brain caused by the
ravages of a skull fracture. ``It could be very grim,'' said one
Bellevue staff member. ``It may be so severe that nothing
consequential can happen'' to repair it.
</P>
<P>
   As the police search continued, friends of Ms. Barrett's
provided a description of a young woman who was eager to get to New
York and strike out on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, after a relationship with a Texas man ended, Ms.
Barrett traveled to New York to join a friend, Stacey McGlaun, who
had accepted a job as a physical therapist, friends of the family
said. Ms. Barrett and Ms. McGlaun have been friends since
elementary school, and attended college together at Trinity Valley
Community College in Athens and at Southwest Texas State University
in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, shortly after arriving, Ms. Barrett wrote a
letter to Debbie Baker, a friend from Texas and the current head of
the community college drill team, saying that she had taken the
opportunity to move on after her breakup and was optimistic about
her prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Bobby had moved away, I thought: `What the hell. Why
not?''' Ms. Barrett wrote. ``So I made a spur of the moment
decision and within three weeks I quit my job, sold my car, packed
up and moved to the Big Apple. It's been a huge move, but it's been
fun so far. Kind of crazy though.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after arriving, Ms. Barrett and Ms. McGlaun met two men
at Le Bar Bat, on West 57th Street, and began double dating, said
one of the men. The relationships went well. The four moved in
together in a small second-floor apartment on a quiet lane in
Maspeth, Queens, where they kept mostly to themselves, neighbors
said.
</P>
<P>
   For a while Ms. Barrett had been a temp worker, working out of
the Taylor Grey employment agency. A company statement called her
``a kind person and a hard worker.'' But that stint was over, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   She was due to start a new job this week and Kelly Herriage, a
longtime friend, said she was considering returning to school to
study interior design. She was also planning to move with her
boyfriend this month to an apartment of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herriage, speaking from Texas, said Ms. Barrett had embraced
city life, and though she was wary of the possibility of danger,
she never harped on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She mentioned that it was kind of scary at night on the
subways, but she never really mentioned she feared anything,'' she
said. ``I feared it, but it's because I'm not there. I'd worry
about her because she was there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
