<SLUG> BC-CHAPPAQUA-TSHIRTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
T-SHIRT CASE NOW INVOLVES SECRET SERVICE AS CHAPPAQUA GROUP IS
WARNED AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ A week ago, White House lawyers ordered a
college scholarship group here to stop selling T-shirts bearing the
presidential seal, warning that the seal's misuse was a crime
punishable by up to six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Secret Service says the unauthorized use of its name on
the shirts violates yet another federal law. And once again, future
neighbors of the president and first lady have found themselves
threatened with jail.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, two Secret Service agents knocked on Robert M.
Bernstein's door and warned him that his group, the Horace Greeley
Educational Fund, must not even give away the T-shirts, which bear
the words ``Secret Service, Chappaqua Bureau, Presidential
Detail.'' Using the service's name without authorization is a crime
punishable by up to a year in jail, they told him.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, a salesman, is not accustomed to receiving mail from
the White House and visits from the Secret Service. ``When they
came to the door, and he flashed his badge, it was sort of
surreal,'' he said. ``It was like something out of a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service has not yet decided whether to confiscate the
T-shirts. Last week, a White House spokesman said that as long as
the fund did not sell the shirts or manufacture more, it could give
away the shirts that had already been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to work with them,'' said James Mackin, a spokesman
for the Secret Service. ``Our concerns are not just the use of our
name but also security issues. We wouldn't want people to assume
that someone wearing one of the shirts was an agent of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackin said lawyers for the service were discussing how to
preserve the integrity of the Secret Service name ``without being
too heavy-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   The forbidden T-shirts were first sold in September, shortly
after President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, announced they
planned to buy a house in Chappaqua, in preparation for Mrs.
Clinton's expected bid for the U.S. Senate from New York. Profits
from the $15 shirts went to the scholarship fund for needy
graduates of Chappaqua High School.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts sold out immediately. The fund ordered 36 dozen more
and was quickly selling them out when the letter from the White
House arrived. In the flurry of media attention that followed, the
shirts became a hot commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, people have pledged hundreds of dollars to the fund,
hoping to get shirts. One man sent in a $1,000 check, asking for
four T-shirts in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a waiting list of 300 people now,'' said Wendy S.
Nolan, a real estate agent who came up with the fund-raising idea.
``They are a collectors' item now. They are a piece of history.
Everywhere I go, people ask me if I can get them one.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that she got up to eight calls a day from people
seeking shirts but that she did not know how to respond to the
requests. The shirts are safely locked up while Bernstein waits for
word from the Secret Service about whether he can give the shirts
away without risking imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they would just tell us, one way or the other,'' Ms.
Nolan said. ``If they end up saying no, you just hope that people
with a conscience will say, `Keep the money, it's good for the
foundation.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
