<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEHOW, BRUINS WILL TRY TO TOE THE LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pushed to the brink by injuries and frustration,
UCLA's offensive line responded with its best game of the season
last week against Washington. But can the Bruins, who have lost
three starters in the last two weeks and are down to their
fourth-string center, do it again?
</P>
<P>
   Running consistently and protecting rookie quarterback Ryan
McCann are essential to defeating USC for the ninth consecutive
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington game gave us a real boost emotionally,'' guard
Brian Polak said. ``We're actually enjoying it. The last few weeks,
I've been joking about the situation. It helps me keep my sanity.''
</P>
<P>
   The key this week, as it was against Washington, is
aggressiveness. The Bruins play better with an edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``With young guys, you have to learn the speed and learn the
offense and how to play, and the last thing to come is
aggressiveness,'' line coach Mark Webber said.
</P>
<P>
   __ In relief: Freshman tackle Blake Worley (sprained knee) is
expected to play but won't start. The other reserves Saturday will
be scout-team players Ed Anderson, Doug Cummings and Tyson Clayton.
Cummings and Clayton are walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tight end Bryan Fletcher (235 pounds) is taking a
crash course on playing tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to know what to do,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``I told
him it's like tight end, except one step closer to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   __ How bad? The Bruins have so many injuries that for the first
time in Toledo's tenure, there's no season-ending scout-team
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my coaching career, never ever have I gone through a
season like this,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cummings, Anderson and Clayton are practicing with the
starters, there's only one offensive lineman on the scout-team
offensive line: freshman Shane Lehmann. The other linemen are
defensive players: Asi Faoa and Mat and David Ball.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stat of the day: USC has not defeated UCLA in the Coliseum
since 1987, when Rodney Peete beat Troy Aikman. The teams tied
10-10 in 1989 when UCLA's Alfredo Velasco missed a game-winning
field goal. The Bruins won in the Coliseum in '91, '93, '95 and 97.
</P>
<P>
   USC is a seven-point favorite Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruiting update: The Bruins have stopped recruiting Albert
Hollis, a top tailback prospect from Sacramento. Despite committing
to UCLA over the summer, he visited Georgia and has scheduled trips
to Notre Dame, Nebraska and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia running back Manuel White, who committed to UCLA
earlier this week, replaces Hollis as the Bruins' 10th commitment.
They have approximately seven slots remaining. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
