r f BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      11-17 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACHING ACROSS THE GENERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Trillions of dollars of wealth will pass from
generation to generation in the next decade. Much of it is tied up
in family-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever seen or been in families ripped apart by
inheritance squabbles can appreciate the monstrous challenge when a
company's assets are part of a family estate.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, asset-transfer plans are made before the older
generation's deaths. That's the only way to avoid steep tax
consequences. But therein lies the rub: By their very
entrepreneurial nature, those who built businesses are typically
reluctant to let go.
</P>
<P>
   Relinquishing financial control means relinquishing power. Few
who have built a business from scratch, or shepherded a family firm
through decades of ups and downs, say goodbye easily.
</P>
<P>
   Such transfers are exacerbated by sibling rivalry and questions
of fairness and equality (which are not the same things) when
accumulated wealth is divvied up among offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that there's a growth industry in providing
wealth-transfer advice for family-owned enterprises. The names of
such fast-blooming advisory firms tell the story. Just a few blocks
apart from each other in Overland Park, Kan., for example, are the
Legacy Financial Group and Legasus Group.
</P>
<P>
   Despite similar names, they are separate organizations. Each has
grown and thrives in different niches hewn from the need to
transfer control of family-owned companies from one generation to
the next.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the Legacy Financial Group was the Patrick
Murphy Agency, a life insurance sales group affiliated with
Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. Murphy had the vision,
though, to build the agency into a diversified financial consulting
group that specializes in family-business succession, drawing from
the expertise of 40 financial professionals and about 35 support
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Legasus Group, once planning advisers for small and
midsize businesses, has evolved into a consulting organization that
specializes in the organizational and emotional parts of
family-firm successions.
</P>
<P>
   The two organizations are meeting the market need that has
fueled the Family Firm Institute since its founding 13 years ago.
The Boston-based membership organization says between 80 and 90
percent of all businesses in North America are family-owned.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking just mom-and-pops here. According to the
institute, 30 percent to 35 percent of all Fortune 500 companies
are family-owned. This is big money.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Garton, director of business development at Legacy, says
family-firm counselors have to be part psychologist, part diplomat
and complete financial wizard.
</P>
<P>
   It takes broad-based talent to meld the wishes of a family
firm's chief executive officer _ usually the father and//or founder
_ with those of the ``chief emotional officer'' _ who typically is,
you guessed it, the wife and mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
