<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MCI-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT AND MCI STRESS CONSUMER ADVANTAGES IN FILING MERGER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Sprint Corp. and MCI WorldCom Inc. filed with the
Federal Communications Commission on Wednesday for approval of
their $129 billion merger and put a pro-consumer spin on a deal
that many business and consumer advocates are urging regulators to
block.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference after the filing, the companies portrayed
the merger as the union of two ``dragon slayers, price slashers and
innovators'' and the best hope for creating a company that can
compete with cable and local-telephone powerhouses such as AT&AMP;T,
Bell Atlantic and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for the merger, said MCI general counsel Michael
Salsbury, is ``to create a dramatically more effective competitor
... that will take on the entrenched monopolies in the United
States and around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives downplayed the widespread concern that the new
company could control long-distance prices, despite the fact that
the deal would leave 80 percent of the market controlled by AT&AMP;T
and the new WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they painted a picture of a market filled with hundreds
of aggressive, if smaller, long-distance rivals and a market facing
upheaval with the imminent entry of the regional Bells.
</P>
<P>
   Salsbury said that with the rapid growth of long-distance
capacity in fiber networks built by such upstarts as Qwest
Communications, ``there are no shortages that somebody could
exploit to drive up prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the companies will urge phone and antitrust regulators
to ignore the historical distinction between local and
long-distance calling, which they say is rapidly eroding.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to judge the merger's effects, they said, is to
look one or two years into the future. By that point, they said,
the regional Bells will have added long-distance service to their
local and Internet offerings. AT&AMP;T will be providing local,
long-distance and Internet service over cable lines. And consumers
will be buying integrated bundles of all the services from one
provider, with all-distance, flat-rate pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear and read a lot about this merger being the merger of
the No. 2 and 3 long-distance carriers,'' Salsbury said. ``We don't
look at the market that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we see it, it's really the merger of the Nos. 4 and 7
providers in the domestic telecommunications market. AT&AMP;T, SBC and
Bell Atlantic are all bigger today. ... We would be the No. 4
player in a post-merger world. We view this as a way to get big
enough to fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   Salsbury said the combined company would benefit from economies
of scale, the scope of its combined services, and $15 billion in
operating and capital expenditure savings over four years, which
could be passed to customers in the form of lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies stressed the strategic sense of the merger.
Sprint owns local telephone assets in rural areas, and MCI owns
local facilities in 100 urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint owns America's fastest-growing wireless company, Sprint
PCS. MCI is a big player in the paging industry through its Skytel
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are investing heavily to roll out broadband
services. In the past year, the companies have snapped up companies
owning fixed wireless licenses, radio spectrum that can be used to
provide high-speed Internet and voice services through a 9-inch
antenna mounted on a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Separately, we don't have sufficient mass to develop that into
a broadband access vehicle,'' Salsbury said. ``Together, we reach
about 60 percent of households. That does become very attractive,
with sufficient scale and reach, to be an attractive alternative''
to high-speed Internet services offered by cable and local
telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   J. Richard Devlin, Sprint's general counsel, suggested that the
combined company might consider shedding some Internet assets to
allay antitrust concerns. But he said any further divestitures,
such as parts of the companies' long-distance business, would be
``unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies hope to complete their merger by mid-2000. There
is no time limit on the FCC process, but the agency has been under
congressional pressure to speed up its reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC will open up the proposed merger for a public comment
period of 30 to 60 days and then take replies from the companies.
At that point, the FCC is free to act, but it also could go into
additional proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and MCI said they expected the review to move much more
quickly than did the review of SBC's purchase of Ameritech, which
took 15 months because that merger involved the combination of
local monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this deal is expected to undergo scrutiny. The
Justice Department has already asked for more information from the
companies, indicating that it will be conducting a full-blown
antitrust review.
</P>
<P>
   Just after the companies announced their plan to merge, William
Kennard, the FCC chairman, said they would bear ``a heavy burden to
show how consumers will be better off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
