A3393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     11-17 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SENATOR HAGEL'S DECEPTIVE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Nov. 18:
</P>
<P>
   In the welter of unfinished business left behind by Congress
this year, campaign finance legislation again stands out.
Nevertheless, progress has been achieved. The House passed a reform
measure in the summer, and 55 senators backed some form of ``soft
money'' ban promoted by Sens. John McCain and Russell Feingold.
Less noticed but also significant, five more Republican senators
now say some controls on soft money are needed. Congress can build
on these gains next year.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential election year is not usually productive
legislatively, but cleaning up the election fund-raising system
could prove an exception to that rule. A sign of the turning tide
came yesterday with the announcement by Time Warner, one of the
biggest corporate donors, that it would no longer make soft-money
contributions to the political parties. With its action, Time
Warner joins a growing number of companies that are in open
rebellion against traditional fund-raising. Through groups like the
Committee for Economic Development, that rebellion has spread
despite heavy-handed warnings from Sen. Mitch McConnell, a leading
defender of soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain has gained in the polls by supporting a
campaign finance overhaul and has promised to bring up his bill
again next year. This growing support for limits on
special-interest money has produced a new danger, however. Sen.
Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, an articulate critic of current
fund-raising practices, has proposed an alternative bill to control
soft money. His bill has gained some adherents, but it is fatally
flawed. The danger lies in this measure's serving as an excuse for
not passing genuine improvements in the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   The objective of reformers, embodied by the McCain-Feingold
bill, has been to outlaw soft money _ the unlimited contributions
by corporations, unions and rich donors to political parties that
circumvent the tight limits on donations to the candidates
themselves. Hagel argues that an outright ban on soft money is
extreme. He wants to cap such donations to parties at $60,000 a
year, raise the ceilings on regular donations to individual
candidates from $1,000 to $3,000, and allow an individual aggregate
of $75,000 a year to parties for all races.
</P>
<P>
   These ceilings are unacceptably high. They would not end the
corrupt soft-money system so much as legitimize it. The $60,000
annual cap would actually be $120,000 for each two-year cycle,
translating into $240,000 for a couple, along with $300,000 for
each couple for direct donations to candidates. The caps would be a
step backward, legalizing donations from corporations (outlawed in
1907) and from unions (outlawed in 1947). Another loophole in
Hagel's bill would allow unlimited donations to state parties for
use in federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   In defending his bill, Hagel argues that the McCain-Feingold
measure, with its complete soft-money ban, is dead in the Senate.
He says he is only trying to find a middle ground. But this is no
middle ground. It is a surrender to the corrupt status quo. The
tipoff is that McConnell, the Senate Republicans' chief
fund-raiser, has praised Hagel's bill and announced hearings on it
for next year. Surely no more hearings are needed on this issue.
McConnell is simply trying to use hearings as an excuse to
forestall stronger legislation.
</P>
<P>
   What is actually going on is that pressure is building on
wavering Republicans to break the filibuster engineered by
McConnell and Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, to thwart the
majority support in the Senate for the McCain-Feingold bill. That
pressure has led George Voinovich and Mike DeWine of Ohio, along
with Spencer Abraham of Michigan and Craig Thomas of Wyoming, to
back Hagel's bill, apparently hoping that their constituents will
be fooled. Their anxiety is at least encouraging. Hagel can now
perform a service by acknowledging the flaws in his own bill and
bringing it closer to serious reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2334EST &QL; 
