A3396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TEACHER-OF-THE-YEA     11-17 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-OF-THE-YEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER WHOSE FIELD TRIPS ARE AN ART IS HONORED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARCHMONT, N.Y., Nov. 16 _ Donald S. Tedesco had been teaching
for only about four years when he almost gave up on it. Frustrated
by the conventional classroom, its stodgy textbooks and
sit-at-your-desk formality, he had decided to resign, but an
assistant superintendent in the Mamaroneck School District here
challenged him to find a better way to teach _ and then gave him
the freedom and the budget to try his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   For 29 years now, through shifting school board policies, a
variety of administrators and a changing school culture, Tedesco
has continued his experimental program, known as Actionville. And
on Sunday, his untiring effort won national recognition at Disney's
American Teacher Awards ceremony in Hollywood, where Tedesco was
named the Outstanding General Elementary Teacher in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our inception it has not been easy,'' said Tedesco, who
returned to class Wednesday after five days of celebrity treatment
in California. ``When you do something different, there are always
obstacles. At times, keeping Actionville going has been like rowing
up Niagara Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Actionville program, Tedesco has sidestepped textbooks
and focused instead on direct experience _ supplemented by
newspapers, magazines and, more recently, the Internet. Every week,
his 50 students at the Hommocks Middle School, who study all their
academic subjects through the program, go on a field trip. And
parent participation, in everything from helping create projects to
leading required dinner table conversation, is mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of parents who didn't want their kids in the
program, because it's really intense parent participation,'' said
Nancy Miller, a book editor, whose son Benno Kling is a graduate of
the program. ``It wasn't easy for me _ I had a job, a younger child
and a baby _ but I wouldn't have missed it. It made you so involved
in your child's life.''
</P>
<P>
   The students, a mix of fifth and sixth graders chosen by a
districtwide lottery, learn by solving problems and creating
projects, Tedesco said. Each year, for instance, students have to
write a novel as part of their English requirement. For social
studies, this year's class is redesigning the exhibits at the
Thomas Paine National Museum in New Rochelle to make the displays
more user-friendly _ and getting a good dose of American history in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents and teachers in the Mamaroneck schools worry that
the Actionville program takes more than its share of school
resources and draws the best students away from the district's
other programs. But Ann R. Tannen, the district's director of
public information, said that was not the case. ``Alternative
programs by their nature cost more,'' she said. ``It's not as much
as people on the street seem to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Actionville costs about $15,000 more than a traditional program
of its size, for staff, supplies and trips, but spread out over 50
students, the cost is small, Ms. Tannen said. ``Is there jealousy
from teachers?'' she said. ``It's human nature. If not jealousy,
wistfulness. People thinking, `If I had that extra little whatever,
I could do more, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   For winning the Disney award, Tedesco and his school will each
receive $2,500. The overall Outstanding Teacher of the Year Award
went to Teri Lindner, a high school special education teacher from
State College, Pa. She and her school district won a total of
$60,000.
</P>
<P>
   They were chosen from a large field: 75,000 teachers were
nominated, 15,000 of those filled out Disney's extensive
application form, and 39 were chosen as finalists and invited to
Los Angeles, where 12 were chosen as winners in various categories.
The awards program was held Sunday night and broadcast Monday on
the Disney Channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
