<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-REFUNDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK JOINS IRS PROGRAM THAT MAY TRIM COST OF FASTEST REFUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Taxpayers who want their refunds really
quickly in the upcoming filing season may get a price break for the
fastest possible delivery, H&AMP;R Block Inc. said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Block, which operates the nation's largest tax preparation
network, announced it was joining a growing number of tax services
participating in a one-year Internal Revenue Service pilot program
designed to double-check refund claims from taxpayers who file
electronic returns.
</P>
<P>
   The new program, Debt Indicator, is part of an effort by the
federal government to make sure taxpayers aren't delinquent on back
taxes, student loans, child support and certain other kinds of debt
before it issues refunds.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan also will provide Block and other tax services the
most solid assurance they've had since 1995 that taxpayers will get
the refunds they claim.
</P>
<P>
   These assurances are what companies rely on to make short-term
loans that put refunds in taxpayers' hands in days rather than
weeks. Tax services and the lenders with which they work currently
run their own special forms of credit checks to judge whether full
refunds will be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS program will likely result in substantially lower fees
for this service,'' said Frank L. Salizzoni, Block's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Debt Indicator program, the IRS checks incoming
returns for suspicious claims or to see if money for debts might be
withheld from a refund. Then the IRS sends its findings to Block or
other participating preparers to relay to clients.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say the program represents a significant
advancement in fighting potential tax fraud. Preparers such as
Block say the arrangement also is a potentially important tool for
delivering fast refunds more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, it takes the IRS about six to eight weeks to send
refunds to taxpayers who file paper returns and about one to three
weeks for those who file electronically. Tax services cut this time
to about two or three days by offering taxpayers what are known as
refund anticipation loans.
</P>
<P>
   Tax services offering these loans will calculate the refunds and
help arrange for taxpayers to get that money _ minus a fee of
usually about $60 on an average-size refund _ from a bank instead
of the government. The bank is repaid three weeks later when it
receives the full refund that otherwise would have gone to the
taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   Block said about 5.5 million of its customers took advantage of
these loans to get their refunds as quickly as possible during the
1994 filing season, the last in which the IRS provided assurances
directly to lenders that refunds would be sent.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS stopped offering those earlier notifications in 1995
because electronic assurances were being sent to lenders faster
than refund amounts could be verified.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the number of customers dropped below 3 million, and
loan costs to those remaining clients rose sharply when lenders
switched to their own screening programs, Block said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3402 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-FBCCOL-LADN-(SLAN     11-17 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FBCCOL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURRIER STIRS UP QB CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the rivalry 99.9 percent of the nation will focus on,
except for the sliver of the country interested in two 4-6 teams
playing each other at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Florida-Florida State probably features the two best teams in
the nation, and wouldn't you know that ornery Steve Spurrier is in
his finest form as the game approaches. He benched starting
quarterback Doug Johnson for last week's victory over South
Carolina and used Jesse Palmer, who had not played since the second
game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't exactly seem like the best way to go into the biggest
game of the year, but Spurrier jumped on reporters who dared ask
which quarterback would start against the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to do whatever gives us the best chance to beat
FSU,'' he said. ``Quit trying to figure it out for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier has grown increasingly frustrated with Johnson in
recent weeks as Florida's high-powered offense sputtered. Two weeks
ago against Vanderbilt, the Gators had to hold off the Commodores
in the final seconds of a 13-6 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Although they weren't threatened in the second half at South
Carolina, a 20-3 win over a winless team is nothing to brag about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look overly impressive in our games right now,''
Spurrier said. ``We played as hard as we could both halves. That's
what we are. We aren't as mighty as people like to think we are,
but we keep winning somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   A quarterback change might seem like drastic approach to take in
mid-November, but Spurrier-watchers know he's always had a quick
trigger with the position and it's hard to argue with his track
record.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer completed just 15 of 33 passes for 161 yards, one
touchdown and one interception against South Carolina. Johnson, who
had started 15 straight games, did not play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me too long to get into a groove,'' Palmer said.
``It's been about a year since I started. I have worked in
practice, but you've got to go out and execute on the field. We had
a lot of guys open and I was making the right decisions, I just
wasn't getting them the football.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tallahassee, Florida State Bobby Bowden is in high spirits,
even if he does have to go to The Swamp. He remembers winning there
in 1993 during the Seminoles' national championship season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we're going in there in as good a circumstance as
we can go in,'' he said. ``You still have to go down there and do
it and the odds of playing in that stadium are not big and yet the
year we won the national championship, we did it. You wonder if
those are signs.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, '93 was the last time the visiting team won in
this series.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bad team: If nothing else, the Iowa football team
inconsistent. Consistently bad.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes rank 102nd or worse in six statistical categories
nationally, last in 10 Big Ten categories and are 1-9 overall, 0-7
in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the factors is we aren't the most experienced group,''
Iowa first-year coach Kirk Ferentz said. ``The other, obviously, is
we're playing in a league right now that's extremely strong from
top to bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he including Indiana and Northwestern in that statement?
</P>
<P>
   __ What a streak: As Wisconsin tailback Ron Dayne and his
teammates celebrated Dayne becoming the NCAA's all-time rushing
leader, a streaker with a red wig came out of the far end zone and
ran the length of the field into the waiting arms of security at
Camp Randall Stadium. Along the way he paused at about the 20-yard
line and did the Heisman pose.
</P>
<P>
   __ Date with destiny: The last three Louisiana State head
coaches _ Mike Archer, Curley Hallman and Gerry DiNardo _ all saw
their terms come to an end Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   __ Redemption: Arkansas quarterback Clint Stoerner spent a year
living down his fumble that opened the door for Tennessee's
improbable win over the Razorbacks a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Stoerner's brother gave him a gag gift for Christmas
_ afootball with a handle glued on it. One day when Stoerner and
his girlfriend were passing oranges in the grocery, a couple of
guys starting saying, ``Oh, he dropped it. He dropped it!''
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner won't hear any more stories now that the Razorbacks
upset Tennessee last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rivalry 101: South Carolina coach Lou Holtz has been teaching
his players about the history of the Gamecocks' rivalry with
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   It must beat worrying about their winless season.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Holtz will test his players on the knowledge of the
series, who won the first game, when it was played and who has won
by the most lopsided score.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things I didn't know about the history of the
Gamecocks, '' senior tight end Trevon Matthews told The State
(S.C.) newspaper. ``There's so much I never knew, like back then a
touchdown was worth fourpoints. . . . That's something I'm glad he
taught us.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rooting for the enemy: Washington State players are
disappointed that Washington lost to UCLA on the eve of the Apple
Cup, which makes the game slightly less important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty upset that Washington couldn't beat UCLA,'' said
senior safety Torry Hollimon, whose brother played at Washington
before an acrimonious transfer in the spring of 1997. ``It takes a
little something out of the Apple Cup. We wanted to be the ones to
knock them out of the Rose Bowl.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
