<HEADER>
A3419 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JASPER-TRIAL-1STLDWRI     11-17 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE OF 3RD JASPER DEFENDANT NOW IN JURY'S HANDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note language in 25th graf. Story has been updated.) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Jurors deliberated for more than eight hours
Wednesday but could not reach a verdict in the capital murder case
of Shawn Berry, the last of three white men to be tried in last
year's gruesome dragging death of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m. CDT State District Judge Joe Bob Golden sent the jury
to a local motel. He ordered them back to the Jasper County
Courthouse on Thursday to continue deliberations. The all-white
jury of seven women and five men is trying to decide whether Berry
is guilty of capital murder, murder or whether he was not
responsible for the death of James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister Betty Boatner said she was prepared for whatever
the jury would say. Even if Berry is acquitted, he eventually will
have to answer to God, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a higher court to go to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 24, admitted during his trial that he invited Byrd _ 49
years old, disabled and inebriated the night of June 7, 1998 _ into
his truck with two white supremacists, Bill King and Russell Brewer
Jr. Berry drove the three of them to the East Texas woods where
Byrd was beaten, chained and dragged to his death.
</P>
<P>
   Berry denied participating in the crime. He said it was King,
25, and Brewer, 32, who attacked Byrd, and that he was too
frightened to intervene because King had threatened to kill him
too. Berry said he had no idea what King and Brewer planned to do
when they picked up Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   Alternate juror George Coleman, who was released from the jury
when deliberations began about 12:30 p.m., said he didn't believe
Berry's story. Had he remained on the jury, Coleman said he would
have voted to convict Berry and sentence him to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a big lie,'' said Coleman, a 26-year-old construction
worker from Buna.
</P>
<P>
   While being questioned during jury selection, Coleman admitted
knowing a member of the Ku Klux Klan. Berry wouldn't have lived
with King, a Klansman, if he didn't hold similar racist views,
Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman also said he didn't believe Berry stood idly by while
Byrd was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes more than two people to hold somebody down and put
chains on his feet,'' Coleman said. ``To me, he had more to do with
it than the others did.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, a theater manager in the racially mixed community of
Jasper, was not known to be a racist. But prosecutors contended
Berry knew King and Brewer were. Both King and Brewer had been
incarcerated and both joined the Confederate Knights of America, a
small racist prison gang. The arms of both men are covered with
racist tattoos and they talked of starting a race war. During
Berry's trial, jurors saw photographs of King and Brewer's tattoos,
including one on King's arm depicting the lynching of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   Berry also had to know King and Brewer were up to no good when
they stopped to pick up Byrd, a divorced father of three, as he
walked along Martin Luther King Boulevard on his way home.
</P>
<P>
   The men drove Byrd to a clearing in the woods, beat and kicked
him and then dragged behind Berry's pickup for more than three
miles. A pathologist testified that for at least two of those
miles, Byrd was conscious and fighting desperately to keep his head
off the pavement. Byrd ground his elbows to the bone in the futile
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's agony ended when his body slammed into a concrete culvert
and he was decapitated. His head, right shoulder and arm were found
in a ditch the next morning. The rest of his body lay about a mile
away, just outside a rural black cemetery on Huff Creek Road.
</P>
<P>
   The crime shocked Jasper residents and prompted armed black
activists and the Ku Klux Klan to march on the community.
</P>
<P>
   The jury contemplated Berry's case behind closed doors for five
straight hours before breaking for dinner. After an hour, the jury
returned to the courthouse and continued discussing the case until
Golden sent them to the motel.
</P>
<P>
   The juries in the King and Brewer trials did not take nearly as
long to return verdicts. In King's trial last February, a Jasper
jury with one black member convicted him after only 2 1/2 hours. A
Bryan jury in September convicted Brewer in four.
</P>
<P>
   If Berry is convicted of capital murder, which would mean he
both kidnapped and killed Byrd, he would face life in prison or
join his co-defendants on death row. If the jury convicted him of
the lesser charge of murder, Berry could get five years to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In a 45-minute closing argument, defense attorney Joseph C.
``Lum'' Hawthorn insisted that Berry had no idea that King was
violent. Hawthorn asked the jury to have the courage to acquit
Berry, just as three blacks and one biracial woman braved public
criticism to take the stand in Berry's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Byrd Jr.'s murder has been avenged,'' Hawthorn said.
``The two people who killed James Byrd Jr. have been tried,
convicted and sentenced to death. Justice has been served.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors countered Hawthorn's argument by telling jurors
Berry assaulted his child's mother, Christie Marcontell. On at
least two occasions, Marcontell gave statements to police, saying
Berry hit her, choked her and threatened to throw her off a
balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Pat Hardy told jurors Berry was just
as responsible for Byrd's killing as King and Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three people involved in this ... and that man was
the worst of the bunch,'' he said, pointing at Berry. ``As sick as
their beliefs were, King and Brewer, at least they believed in
something. Shawn Berry did all of this for nothing but the fun of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Berry claimed he had no idea why white
supremacists would offer a black man a ride until he heard King
say, ``Let's kill this nigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors disputed that account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn Berry knew exactly what was going on,'' Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray: ``It was
Shawn Berry's truck, Shawn Berry's chain. It was Shawn Berry (who)
made the decision to pick James Byrd up. Shawn Berry made the
decision to drive out into a remote area. Shawn Berry has got more
blood on him than any one of the three, and it was Shawn Berry
driving that truck.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the killing, Berry admitted he went to a local
carwash and helped King clean the pickup and the 24-foot logging
chain used to drag Byrd. Berry later led police to a shallow hole
outside a friend's trailer home, where he said King and Brewer hid
the chain. The defense claimed any blood found on Berry's clothes
was splatter from the water used to wash the chain.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the Byrd family waited pensively for the jury to
reach its decision Wednesday, Byrd's oldest daughter, Francis Renee
Mullins, gave birth to Byrd's second grandchild at a hospital near
her home in Hawaii. The baby will be nicknamed ``Son,'' which was
James Byrd Jr.'s nickname, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
