<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3420 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-STOWERS-INSTITUTE-KAN     11-17 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOWERS-INSTITUTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS SEE INSTITUTE AS CATALYST FOR INCREASED RESEARCH
INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH and ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As the $200 million Stowers Institute for
Medical Research takes shape, area leaders are looking to it as the
catalyst to turn Kansas City into one of the nation's top 10
biomedical research and development sites.
</P>
<P>
   The institute marks a milestone Thursday as it moves into its
new administrative office and introduces the first three scientists
it is bringing to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   When the institute begins scientific work about a year from now,
it will do biomedical research that could result in better ways to
treat cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to help improve the quality of everyone's life,
while making this area of the country known as one of the best
places in the world for biomedical research,'' said James E.
Stowers Jr., the mutual fund executive who founded the institute
with his wife, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, city leaders hope that the Stowers Institute will pump
new life into the area's scientific, educational and economic
spheres.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a task force has recommended that the area
raise $300 million for community-wide research and development over
10 years. Meeting that goal may be viewed as the city's answer to
recent losses of corporate and organizational headquarters, task
force members say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This effort will produce a sense of pride and control over our
destiny in the Kansas City area,'' said John M. Edgar, co-chairman
of the Life Sciences Task Force. ``This is a community undertaking,
which is located here and is not susceptible to being acquired and
taken from this area.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the task force is to boost the level of research and
development in the Kansas City area, now about $100 million a year,
to $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Noffsinger, executive director of the University of
Kansas Medical Center Research Institute, predicted that if Kansas
City was successful in becoming a biomedical research center, it
would create the kind of economic impetus in the next decade that
Sprint Corp. provided in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pull this off the way it's going now, there will be an
economic turnaround,'' he said. ``It's (biomedical research) a huge
new growth area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stowers Institute alone is expected to be a welcome addition
to the city's economic arsenal. The projected value of building and
equipping the office building and the first 230,000 square feet of
research space is about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   The complex, which is being built on the site of the old Menorah
Medical Center at 49th Street and Rockhill Road, will have enough
room to grow into 530,000 square feet of research space.
</P>
<P>
   Stowers research is focusing on some of the most fundamental
questions in the life sciences: how the genes that carry the
blueprint of every living organism work together to produce and
maintain life, and to cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   This knowledge is considered essential to understanding many
illnesses, including cancer, diabetes, heart disease and autoimmune
disorders, that have challenged medical science.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stowers research can be expected to produce many
technological spin-offs, the institute will not develop new drugs
or medical treatments. Nor will it treat sick people.
</P>
<P>
   Stowers plans to sell rights to its discoveries to businesses,
yielding hundreds of millions of dollars to swell the institute's
endowment, Stowers officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Stowers intends the discoveries to be commercially developed
locally, with the researchers themselves sharing in the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Stowers Institute endowment now stands at $340 million and
is expected to grow to billions of dollars in the coming decades.
Nonetheless, institute officials say they will need to engage in
fund raising once scientific work begins, in order to operate at an
optimum level.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was announced in September 1994, the Stowers Institute
has generated a hopeful buzz among area leaders searching for the
next economic bandwagon. The local economy is strong, but the
possible loss of the Sprint headquarters and other losses have made
Kansas Citians hunger for an economic ticket into the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Several area civic and business leaders see life sciences
research as that ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we put our strengths together, we then reach a point where
we really start to have a critical amount of R and D going on that
would spin off enough ideas to attract enough companies to have a
significant economic impact on the region,'' said James Spigarelli,
executive vice president and chief operating officer of the Midwest
Research Institute. Spigarelli has played a key role on the life
sciences task force.
</P>
<P>
   The task force was formed by the Kansas City Area Development
Council and the Civic Council of Greater Kansas City. The $300
million that it has recommended be raised for research and
development would come from sources such as government, foundations
and private funders and would act as a catalyst for additional
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The task force said such an endeavor made sense in light of the
Stowers plans and ongoing work at entities such as Midwest Research
Institute, St. Luke's Hospital, Children's Mercy Hospital, the
University of Kansas Medical Center, the University of
Missouri-Kansas City School of Medicine, Quintiles Transnational
Corp. and Bayer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that if this strategy is successfully implemented,
Kansas City can be among the top 10 regions in the country for
expenditures in life sciences research, at $500 million a year,''
Edgar said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael F. Morrissey, the other co-chairman of the task force,
said a business plan on how to accomplish the goals of the task
force would be developed by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The goals of the Kansas City group mirror the thinking of
national experts.
</P>
<P>
   The Milken Institute, a nonpartisan economics think tank in
Santa Monica, Calif., reported in July that Kansas City ranked 29th
among the 315 metropolitan areas Milken studied in terms of the
percentage of the nation's high-tech output it produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research centers and institutions are undisputedly the most
important factor in incubating high-tech industries,'' the Milken
report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-AIRCRASH-NYT &LR;      11-17 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIRCRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INVESTIGATING THE CRASH OF EGYPTAIR 990 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Nov. 18:
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash of EgyptAir Flight 990 remains a mystery.
Information from voice and flight data recorders raised suspicions
that a relief pilot, Gameel el-Batouty, deliberately sent the
Boeing 767 plunging into the ocean. But Egypt's government has
strongly protested the view that Batouty's recorded words suggest a
prayer before a suicidal act rather than a response to a problem in
the cockpit. Given differing cultural interpretations of his words
and the fact that much of the wreckage has not been recovered, it
is too early to draw conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, it is appropriate for the National
Transportation Safety Board, the lead investigator, to retain
jurisdiction for now rather than transfer the matter to the FBI,
which will take over if there is evidence that the disaster was the
result of a criminal act. It is also prudent for the NTSB to allow
Egyptian authorities to help analyze the words of the crew. That is
not just a diplomatic courtesy. Egyptian experts are in the best
position to grasp the import of the words spoken.
</P>
<P>
   In the voice recording, Batouty is heard uttering a common
Arabic expression that can mean ``I put my trust in God.'' Egyptian
officials insist that the words are said in response to danger
rather than as a prelude to suicide. About the time of that
comment, someone shut off the automatic pilot and the plane went
into a a dive from 33,000 feet to less than 17,000 feet. The
microphones also picked up the voice of the captain, Ahmed
el-Habashy, who may have briefly left the cockpit and then
returned, saying in Arabic, ``What's going on?'' Investigators also
say that during the rapid descent, the two flaps on the tail moved
in opposite directions, suggesting to American investigators that
two pilots were fighting for control of the plane as one of them
struggled to crash it.
</P>
<P>
   James Hall, the safety board's chairman, says that so far
investigators have found no sign of a mechanical malfunction or a
weather condition that could have caused the accident. But they
have not yet retrieved the remains of the cockpit, which may
provide more clues.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB and the FBI have thus far avoided the bureaucratic
infighting that plagued the investigation of the crash of Trans
World Airlines Flight 800. In that case, the FBI took an early and
visible role. But by leaning toward a terrorism theory, critics
say, the FBI came into conflict with safety board investigators who
favored a theory of mechanical failure. In this new case, the
tension centers on a complex mix of safety concerns, national pride
and genuine puzzlement over a mystifying crash.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's cautious response on Tuesday was the correct one.
The FBI has an important role to play, but the NTSB should remain
in the lead until the Egyptians have had a chance to contribute
their judgments and until it seems clear that mechanical failures
cannot explain the disaster. Then the FBI would appropriately take
charge without ambiguity or bureaucratic conflict. The possibility
of a suicide crash of Flight 990 is a frightening scenario. But
since nothing can reclaim the lost lives, a careful, collaborative
inquiry is the proper course for the time being.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
