<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DESEGREGATION CASE ENDS, BUT ACCREDITATION STRUGGLE
CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple on Wednesday
dismissed the 22-year-old Kansas City school-desegregation lawsuit
and refused to block a state decision to strip the district of
accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple ruled that despite many remaining problems, the district
has done all that it can to eliminate segregation and should be
freed from court control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sole question in this case is whether the (district) is
currently providing an equal education to its students, regardless
of their race,'' Whipple wrote in a 42-page order. ``The court must
answer this question in the affirmative.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple's decision to end the long-running case stunned many.
Most had not expected a decision on whether the district should be
freed from the case until after a court hearing sometime next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic day for the Kansas City, Missouri, School
District,'' Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr. said. ``Clearly, the
court believes that this administration is focused on the things
that need to be done to raise student academic achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in more than 20 years, we control our own
destiny,'' Demps continued. ``This community has been given back
the responsibility for educating its children. Our success, or our
failure, will rest squarely on our shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   But Demps didn't agree with Whipple's refusal to block the state
Board of Education's decision to declare the district unaccredited,
effective May 1, for failing to meet any of 11 Missouri performance
standards. District officials had argued that the loss of state
accreditation would make it impossible to meet court-ordered goals
to improve academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Demps said the state's action heightens the uncertainty and
anxiety for parents and students and will make it harder to attract
and retain high-quality staff.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple said his decision on accreditation stemmed from his
confidence that the state's standards mesh well with the court's
desegregation goals. He also argued that the state Department of
Elementary and Secondary Education might be better positioned than
the federal court to help the district implement the needed
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   District officials said they were still considering measures to
stop the state action.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Delaney, an attorney for the district, said Demps likely
will ask the state board to reconsider its accreditation decision,
or at least to postpone it until after graduation to reassure high
school seniors that their status won't be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   If the state board won't reconsider, Delaney said, the district
plans to challenge the accreditation action in state court. Delaney
said the district doesn't question the state's standards, but it
disputes the way the state measures the district's performance
against those standards.
</P>
<P>
   Should efforts to challenge the accreditation decision fail, the
district would have two years to improve performance or face the
possibility of a state takeover. Ultimately, the district could be
dissolved and its students attached to new or existing districts.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Education Commissioner Robert Bartman said he was
pleased with Whipple's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful now we can spend the energy being eaten up by this
litigation on raising student performance in the Kansas City School
District,'' Bartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Benson II, attorney for the plaintiff schoolchildren,
said he disagreed that the district had done everything it could to
improve academic achievement. He said Whipple also failed to allow
the plaintiff schoolchildren to present evidence or legal arguments
before dismissing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he would not commit to an appeal, saying, ``We are genuinely
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the decision may be constitutionally insufficient,
educationally, the judge's argument merits careful consideration,''
Benson said. ``The court's argument that (the state department) is
finally, after 40 years of neglecting urban education, better
positioned to improve teaching and learning may be correct.''
</P>
<P>
   The landmark decision, should... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
