<SLUG> BC-MALL-STYLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BATTLE FOR SHOPPERS, MALLS EMPHASIZE SENSE OF PLACE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Ohio)  (rk) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH, N.J. _ If F.T.D. and the Tupi Indians of Brazil
joined forces to build a massive shopping center in the bleak,
industrial strip between Newark Airport and the hulking marine
docks here, it might look something like the Jersey Gardens Outlet
Mall.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-foot wall of ivy cascades near the neon signs in the food
court. Topiary gardens hang in steel-mesh cages high above the
entrances to stores like Neiman Marcus and the Gap. In the
Rainforest Cafe, customers sit under plastic banana leaves dining
on Mayan Meatloaf and Primal Steak to a safari soundtrack complete
with braying elephants, apocalyptic thunderstorms and the
percussive beating of digitally mastered conga drums.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the lengths that retailers in the mall-choked New York
region are driven to these days to attract shoppers. In New York,
New Jersey and Connecticut, where 324 malls offer more than 81
billion square feet of merchandising space, the message is clear:
You gotta have a gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   So when Jersey Gardens opened last month, it placed itself in
competition with the region's outlet champion, a mall that wants to
evoke a homey Main Street appeal, Woodbury Common Premium Outlets
in Central Valley, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises a question: Restraint or razzmatazz? Which
do the shoppers prefer?
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, developers at both centers prefer their own mall.
Jersey Gardens, which is owned by Glimcher Realty Trust of
Columbus, Ohio, says its blend of theme-park architecture, retail
shops and entertainment (restaurants, game arcades and a 22-screen
cineplex opening in the spring) is the future of shopping malls.
Woodbury Common, on the other hand, is content to rely on its
stable of blue-blood outlet tenants and its bucolic setting at the
foot of the Catskill Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spend the entire day and enjoy everything we have to offer,
that's what we want our customers to do,'' said Crystal Stell,
Jersey Gardens' marketing director. ``We're about finding a nice
pair of jeans at a good price. But we're also about having lunch,
seeing a movie and spending time with your family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Rothstein, vice president for marketing at Woodbury
Common, which is owned by Chelsea GCA Realty Inc. of Roseland,
N.J., said shoppers at her mall ``don't get that sense of crazy,
frenetic mall life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have what we believe is the finest outlet shopping
anywhere,'' Ms. Rothstein said. ``But even if you live 15 minutes
away, you still feel like you're on vacation when you come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Physically, the two malls could not be more different. Jersey
Gardens is a carefully sculptured indoor idyll of Shinto arches,
leafy arbors and silent, glass-caged waterfalls. Surrounded by
sylvan slopes, Woodbury Common is an outdoor place, a collection of
white-washed clapboard buildings designed to resemble a quaint
Colonial town.
</P>
<P>
   The shoppers at Woodbury Common typically dress up to shop:
black-clad Manhattanites cooing at the Prada window and Japanese
tourists in Chanel snap pictures of the Gucci store. At Jersey
Gardens, the attitude is come as you are: carpenters in nylon union
jackets, elderly couples in matching cardigans, a few Wall Street
types playing hooky from work and die-hard mall rats in baggy
pants.
</P>
<P>
   Both malls place equal emphasis on customer service (shuttle
buses to and from New York, free pagers, help with dinner
reservations). Both are deluged with customers (10 million people a
year visit Woodbury Common; more than 100,000 visited Jersey
Gardens on its opening day, Oct. 21). And both are so busy that the
state police in both states have to direct traffic on the weekends
at the highway exits near their parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their similarities, the two have little to fear from
each other, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jersey Gardens is looking for the crossover shopper, someone
who will go see a movie or eat at the Rainforest Cafe then think,
`Hey, I need a pair of socks,''' said Malachy Kavanaugh, a
spokesman for the International Council of Shopping Centers.
``Woodbury Common is more of a true outlet mall, positioned 30 to
40 miles from its competition. Their customer makes a conscious
effort to go there and shop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
