A3427 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DESEGREGATION-LAWSUIT     11-17 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESEGREGATION-LAWSUIT-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DESEGREGATION CASE ENDS, BUT ACCREDITATION STRUGGLE
CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...and learning may be correct.''
</P>
<P>
   The landmark decision, should it stand, would end what is
considered the most costly and ambitious desegregation remedy in
the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $2 billion was spent constructing or renovating nearly 80
buildings, improving teacher salaries, cutting class sizes and
introducing magnet programs designed to lure white suburban
students into the district.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the district abandoned many of the magnet
themes and returned to a system where the majority of students
attend neighborhood schools. Ironically, the number of racially
isolated schools _ those with more than 90 percent minority
populations _ has increased in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the desegregation efforts also failed to improve
student performance. Whipple's ruling comes at a time when the
district has floundered educationally.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple said part of the lack of progress might stem from ``too
many chefs in the (district's) kitchen,'' a revolving door of
administrators and an overly political board.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought the court's continued involvement was more
likely to impede Demps' progress.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple said the court's involvement has meant that too often,
educational policy differences that would normally be resolved by
the elected school board become mired in costly litigation. He also
said the court had become a convenient scapegoat and a shield for
the board against accepting responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``These byproducts of court oversight suggest that retention of
judicial control may be more disruptive than beneficial to the
(district),'' Whipple wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Whipple said the district had made significant progress
in recent years, including budget cuts, school closings and
progress toward eliminating the academic achievement gap between
black and white students.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that the district appears to have recently surmounted
the lack of administrative talent to carry out many of the needed
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple also ordered that his court-appointed Desegregation
Monitoring Committee remain in place until March 27, 2000, to
advise the district.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring committee Chairman John Murphy had recommended
against the loss of accreditation, but said he was optimistic about
the district under Demps' leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``l feel confident, given appropriate support from the community
and Board of Education, Ben can take the school district in a
positive direction and implement the plans that have been designed
and put the school system back on its feet,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers' union President Judy Morgan said that she and her
members were stunned and pleased by the judge's ruling to end the
desegregation case. They had expected the district would have to
participate in a hearing, projected to cost nearly $1 million in
legal fees, to get out from under court control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think it's good,'' she said. ``Our union went on
record....We felt the court had become an impediment, and there
were too many layers of bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morgan, who has been in the district for 29 years, said she
could not vouch for the assertion that the district has emerged
better than it was when the desegregation lawsuit was filed in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a period when things were better. But I
don't think they are now,'' she said. ``There's a lot of low morale
among staff....There's not much respect for the teachers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
