<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT COULD USE A TOLEDO TRANSFUSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The poll had to take its toll on Paul Hackett's
camp. So what if the demographics were small as a Whitman's Sampler
and less diverse? When 76 percent of Daily Trojan respondents say
you ought to throw in the towel, it's tough to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Hackett has spent the past few weeks picking at
pretexts like they were candies, searching for the most palatable
to obscure this season's bitter taste. Like George W. Bush, he's
trying to win over a constituency as spoiled and stubborn and rich
as the Republican right.
</P>
<P>
   Like Al Gore, he has a boss fighting public-image problems of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bill Bradley, he's often caught saying what he means
instead of what sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has huddled with a group of image-makers dubbed ``The
Crystal Group'' and is becoming a clear threat to Gore for the 2000
Democratic presidential nomination. Perhaps that's what Hackett
needs to close the gap with his primary nemesis, Bob Toledo: an
image makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: Toledo, the fourth-year head coach of crosstown
rival UCLA, comes across as cashmere to Hackett's burlap.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo is glib and warm. He is a natural-born schmoozer in
college football's cocktail-party climate. He is more
self-deprecating than defensive, more prone to public outbursts of
analysis than anger.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo jumps up and down on the sidelines and throws his arms in
the air and does almost as much cheerleading as the song girls.
People gravitate toward him for the same reason they do the
overstuffed chair in the living room; he looks snug.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett comes across as just plain smug.
</P>
<P>
   He's hard to read, what with his tinted glasses and impassive
expression. Pacing the sidelines on Saturdays, he exudes all the
warmth of freezer burn. The Trojans' second-year head coach is the
marble table in the living room, so austere people think twice
about putting a drink on it, much less their stocking feet.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a 21-game winning streak goes a long way toward
establishing good will in our fair city. However, UCLA's
resplendent run the previous two seasons doesn't alone explain why
Toledo and Hackett both can awkwardly juggle their quarterbacks and
jiggle their seniors this fall and only Hackett gets raked over the
coals for it.
</P>
<P>
   If L.A. is slower to censure Toledo, it's partly because he is
as familiar to us as the friendly neighbor down the street. He
makes himself so accessible, we feel like we know him. He comes
across as one of us _ not anyone above us _ and so we're inclined
to ignore his blemishes as sure as we do our own.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett moved into Mr. Toledo's neighborhood and set the wrong
tone from the start. As the Bruins were piling one win on top of
another, Hackett lauded Oregon for having the best offense in the
conference and warned that the unbeaten Bruins were in for a bear
of a battle against Miami hours after Miami had been pummeled by
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   It mattered little that he turned out to be right about the
Hurricanes, who upended the Bruins' national-title hopes last
December. Hackett came off sounding petty, not unlike the neighbor
who disparages the guy's garden down the street after the guy's
roses have been named best on the block.
</P>
<P>
   We'll say this for Hackett: He seems to be learning from his
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, he roundly praised Toledo and his staff for
finding a way to win a tough game last week against Washington with
a back-up quarterback (a fourth-stringer, actually), ``something I
didn't do a good job of (after starting quarterback Carson Palmer
was lost for the season with a collarbone injury against Oregon in
Week 3). That's the criticism I have of me,'' Hackett said,
liberally applying salt to his open wound.
</P>
<P>
   After the Stanford loss in week seven, Hackett lashed out at
this reporter for pointing out the public perception was he wasn't
taking much responsibility for his team's sloppy play. Since then,
Hackett has blamed himself for everything but the white lines on
the Coliseum turf being drawn crooked.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the image makeover already is under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developing a (positive) public image is important to me,''
Hackett said. ``Being honest and out-front is a big part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   So long as it's done in a glib, gallant way. Dour and defensive
won't get him very far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone was telling me about John McKay and how after he
started 11-11 here, it changed his personality,'' Hackett said.
``He became glib, learned to give short answers. It can get too
painful laying yourself out there every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett understood that even before the injuries and losses
started mounting this year. In his first head-coaching stint, at
Pittsburgh, ``I put my feelings out there every week and it
backfired,'' said Hackett, who was fired after three seasons. ``I
got angry very quickly. The point is, I'm not going to let myself
get angry in my second year of developing this program.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley faces didn't go out of vogue with the 1970s. David
Gibson, a senior safety at USC, can see that, having watched the
way people react to Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see his stony face and they don't know exactly what's
going on in his head,'' Gibson said. ``So they invent Paul Hackett
(in their own minds).'' All the more reason for Hackett to follow
Bradley's lead and subtly reinvent himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-17-99 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991117.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-17 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
