u e BC-SOTHEBY'S-ART-AUCTION     11-17 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY'S-ART-AUCTION-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AUCTION RECORDS IN CONTEMPORARY ART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Greece)  (See also ART-AUCTION) 
(js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices soared at Sotheby's sale of contemporary art
Wednesday night, when works by blue-chip artists like Marcel
Duchamp and Mark Rothko, Alexander Calder and Sam Francis sold for
more than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The sale totaled $56.2 million, $10 million more than its high
estimate. Of the 68 works offered, 63 found buyers. Nine records
were set.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's runaway success felt far more solid than Christie's
smaller sale of contemporary art on Tuesday night. Sotheby's
defines contemporary art as dating from 1945 to the present, so its
offerings were a classic mixture of artists. Christie's puts art
from 1945 to 1970 in its 20th-century sale; its contemporary-art
auction on Tuesday night featured artists working in the last 30
years. Christie's sale, which brought $13.2 million, was an almost
frightening feeding frenzy that set records for 18 artists,
including Jeff Koons and Damien Hirst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sotheby's sale had a little more quality,'' said Francis
Bowes, a San Francisco collector. ``There sure is a lot of money
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Work after work brought flurries of bidding, but most of the
biggest spenders were bidding by telephone. A majority of the works
came from some of America's most distinguished collectors, among
them S.I. Newhouse Jr., David Whitney, Barbara and Richard Lane,
Harry and Linda Macklowe, and Donald Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Four bidders were desperate to buy a 1952 Rothko, ``No. 15,'' in
bright yellow and red. Estimated at $4 million to $6 million, it
finally sold to an anonymous telephone bidder for $11 million after
a bloody battle. It became the star of the evening and set a record
for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Another bidding war ensued over a 1959 Cy Twombly, ``Untitled,''
one of the artist's abstract works with cloudlike forms and sweeps
of red. In the end, it was down to Larry Gagosian, the Manhattan
dealer, against a telephone bidder. The painting finally sold for
$4 million, almost twice its high estimate of $2.2 million, to the
telephone bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Some works were considered so rare and special that no one
flinched when they sailed right past their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was ``Brazilian Fish,'' a 1947 hanging fish mobile
by Alexander Calder. One of about a dozen he produced in the 1940s
and '50s, it is made of sheet metal, painted wire, wire rods,
broken pottery and glass. Five bidders went crazy for it, and it
finally sold to yet another unidentified telephone bidder for $3.9
million, more than three times its high estimate of $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   One bidder who was proud of his purchase was Dimitri
Daskalopolos, an Athens-based collector. He bought Duchamp's famous
urinal ``Fountain,'' an image that was barred from the 1917 New
York Armory show but prominently displayed on the cover of
Wednesday night's sale's catalog. Sotheby's was selling the fifth
in an edition of eight fabricated under Duchamp's supervision in
1964. Estimated at $1 million to $1.5 million, it sold to
Daskalopolos for $1.7 million. After the sale, he told Sotheby's
officials he had bought it because ``for me, it represents the
origins of contemporary art.''
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some prices were so high that they surprised even Sotheby's
experts. When Roy Lichtenstein's ``Still Life With Sculpture,'' a
1974 painting being sold by Newhouse, came on the block, two
bidders refused to give up. The painting eventually sold to Lucy
Mitchell-Innes, a dealer who formerly headed Sotheby's contemporary
art department worldwide, for $2.7 million, nearly four times its
high estimate of $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse was also selling a Brice Marden ink-and-gouache drawing
from the artist's famous ``Cold Mountain'' series. The work, a mass
of black and white spiral shapes, was estimated at $150,000 to
$200,000. Seven bidders tried to buy it before it ended up selling
to a telephone bidder for $629,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flag,'' a 1959 Jasper Johns drawing on notebook paper being
sold by Peter Brant, the newsprint manufacturer and collector, was
estimated at $800,000 to $1.2 million. Several people had fallen in
love with the work, which went to Simon de Pury, the Geneva dealer,
for $1.7 million, a record for a work on paper by the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Another record was set Wednesday night for Sam Francis. His
``Toward Disappearance 1,'' a 1958 abstract painting with strong
blues throughout the canvas, was estimated at $1.5 million to $2
million but sold for $3.4 million to Andrew Fabrikant, who runs the
Richard Gray Gallery in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Lucian Freud's ``Evening in the Studio'' (1993), estimated at
$2.5 million to $3.5 million, sold to an unidentified bidder for
$2.4 million. A triple portrait, it shows Nicola Bateman, the
former wife of Leigh Bowery, Freud's model, sitting in a chair,
working on a rich piece of embroidery, while a naked woman lies
asleep on the floor on the bottom half of the painting and the
artist's dog sleeps on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Warhol's work has been commanding high prices this season,
and Wednesday night was no exception. Warhol's ``Liz,'' a 1963
portrait of Elizabeth Taylor estimated at $1.5 million to $2
million, went to a telephone bidder for $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was very focused, rational bidding tonight,'' said the
auctioneer, Tobias Meyer, head of Sotheby's contemporary art
department worldwide. ``It was a high-quality sale with
high-quality results.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
